<SLUG> BC-ROY-ROGERTOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR'S TIES TO L.A. SUBURB STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ s soon as she heard about Roy Rogers' death,
Virginia Watson started planning to showcase his life and work in
Chatsworth, a community in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The curator of the Chatsworth Museum on Shadow Oak Drive, Watson
knows much about the years the ``King of the Cowboys'' spent here
and how he used the area often to film movies and television shows,
particularly on the Iverson Ranch in the Santa Susana Pass.
</P>
<P>
   But while most fans knew only Rogers the legend, Watson knew
Rogers and his wife and co-star Dale Evans as real community-caring
folk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never stuck up. They always invited the kids up to
their home. They had a big playroom and billiard room,'' said
Watson, a longtime Chatsworth resident. ``Their home was a
gathering spot, which was unusual for movie stars.''
</P>
<P>
   All around town, people reminisced Monday about the good, family
folks they remembered or heard about. They recalled Rogers' last
public appearance here, at the opening for the Chatsworth Metrolink
train depot in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Up on Trigger Street, named after the cowboy's famous palomino,
Roy Rogers' former ranch home is now surrounded by newer, lavish
houses developed after he sold off his ranch.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy lives on in the neighborhood, however. A block over
from his ranch house _ where actor Val Kilmer was later raised _
people live on Trigger Place and Dale Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch him when I was this tall,'' said real estate
broker Michael Harris, swinging an open palm at his hip. ``He was
always the good guy. He always wore a white hat.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood is studded with views that look like scenes
from his western movies and television shows, shot here from 1935
to 1963.
</P>
<P>
   A fan who identified himself only as Bernie lives next door to
Roger's former ranch. And he swears he has a piece of the actor's
landscape right out back, by the blue, mosaic-tile underground
pool.
</P>
<P>
   It's a massive boulder shaped slightly like an ancient hand ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a scene where someone was standing on top. When I
first saw it, it flashed right back to me,'' Bernie said, though he
couldn't recall which of Rogers' 90-some movies the boulder
appeared in.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents moved in well after the Rogers family moved out
and the area has changed plenty since. Roy Rogers played golf and
started a gun club on what has now become parkland and
condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still plenty of Old West-style quaintness.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the hill, a small sign posted at the front of
the Oakwood Memorial Park reads, ``Caution: Rattlesnake season.''
Homes for sale come with signs that read, ``Horses Okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking the hills in town feels like stepping into a scene from
one of Rogers' singing cowboy westerns. The breeze sends the
wildflowers and tall grass tucked between jumbles of buff-color
boulders rippling against a bright, blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say they cherish hearing coyotes and peacocks at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Mininberg, 60, lives across the street from the
original Roy Rogers home. She watched his films since she was 6,
growing up in Long Island, N.Y. She moved to Trigger Street 12
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have lived here while he was here,'' she
said with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, at the Chatsworth Museum, first met Rogers and Evans in
the 1940s. Their daughters were friends at Sutter Junior High.
</P>
<P>
   Watson remembers fondly the times when Rogers' daughter Linda
worked as a soda jerk at the ice cream parlor Watson owned with her
husband. It sat next to the local post office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale would come in and read her mail,'' Watson said. ``I
remember him. He was so funny. He always blew the paper off his
straw.''
</P>
<P>
   But something changed for the couple after another of their
daughters, Debbie, was killed in a bus crash. Not long after, they
left town for good.
</P>
<P>
   Before Rogers and Evans retired in 1976 to Victorville, the
couple donated the last $1,000 in the little girl's bank account to
help save and move Chatsworth's historic Pioneer Church, which the
family had attended for years. Watson was in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
