<SLUG> BC-RUN-DOCTOR-RUNNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A DOCTOR, A RACE BETWEEN TWO CLOCKS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the term used by medical people, Dr. Kim Griffin
is an intensivist. For the last five years she has spent 11 or 12
hours a day, five days a week as the assistant director of the
cardiac-thoracic intensive care unit at Mount Sinai Hospital on
Manhattan's Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   When the day is done, and before it begins, she is the other Kim
Griffin, the one who runs to work from her Upper West Side
apartment through Central Park, then runs home, sometimes sneaking
in an extra six-mile loop.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends she may race, not in the middle of the pack but up
front, as befits a former national champion who leads a double life
as doctor and runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like two people,'' Griffin said in an interview
last week, ``but sometimes I think I am. I have one role, and an
hour later I have another. I like that. It keeps me refreshed
because I'm doing a different thing. Then I go home and have
another life with my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine is 4 and Caroline is 3. And while their mother is
working, a baby-sitter or their father, Patrick, a freelance
computer specialist, keeps tabs on them.
</P>
<P>
   Given her limitations, Griffin has done unbelievably well. Last
November, in her first marathon, she was the 19th woman (and the
second American women) to finish in the New York City Marathon. Her
time was 2 hours 50 minutes 25 seconds, and if an Achilles' tendon
had not tightened at 20 miles, she might have run 10 minutes
faster.
</P>
<P>
   In May, in the first of the year's Chase Corporate Challenges,
she beat the 5,911 other female finishers over the course of three
and a half miles in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   In June, she beat 6,000 women in the 10-kilometer Avon Mini
Marathon in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, she will run in the third and last Corporate
Challenge of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That race in May was my first since the marathon,'' she said.
``I ran at a pace of a 5:40 mile almost from memory. The week after
my whole body revolted.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she feels better and is eager to race. At age 36, she is the
picture of fitness: 5 feet 6 inches, 115 pounds, with bright brown
eyes and a sense of adventure that keeps her running ambitions
high.
</P>
<P>
   Those ambitions were high in 1982, when, as Kim Schnurpfeil, a
Stanford junior from Burlingame, Calif., she won the national
collegiate and U.S. 10,000-meter titles. In time, medical school
and hospital duties became a greater priority. She accepted that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I train enough to run at a high level,'' Griffin
said. ``My goal was always to be the best. I always believed I
could run on the international level. I consider myself still a
good athlete, but I don't sit around and say if I did this or that,
I could win the New York City Marathon. There are too many things
going on in my life. I enjoy running, and I do what I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me still wants improvement. I would like to run a
marathon in 2:40, but I'm not going to go crazy. Your kids are very
important. I do take some time away from them because I run. And
when you're a doctor and you're at work, you might think about
other things, but your job is your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get up at 10 minutes before six in the morning, take
my time, drink a cup of coffee, wait for the bus and go to work.
Now I get up 10 minutes earlier, run from 6 to 6:30 through Central
Park from home to the hospital and take an extra loop. I shower at
the hospital and I'm ready to work at 7 o'clock with a workout
behind me. After work, I run home.
</P>
<P>
   ``On weekends, the kids like to sleep late, so I run early and
get home as they get up. And I have the whole day with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin trains about 40 miles a week. She hopes to get that up
to 70 or 80 miles a week before the New York City Marathon in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' she said, ``it all seems too much. But the way I
use running, it helps me deal with stress. It kind of relaxes you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to avoid telling myself that I have to win races. I have
to remind myself I'm doing this for fun. If your accomplishments
meet your expectations, you're on the right track. There are a lot
of things I could be doing better. I have to accept that I do what
I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin accepts that because she sees what her routine does for
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in better shape,'' she said, ``I have more energy.
The benefits of exercise are great. I want to stay healthy. I could
do more academic things, but I'm not sure if I did I could be that
much better a person. Putting the running in makes you more
efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   But if she could train like full-time distance runners, with 150
or so miles a week plus speed work and weight training, how good
could she be? Griffin smiled at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wondered what it would be like if I trained harder and
competed at the highest level,'' she said. ``I kind of wish I could
do that, but I can't. I think I would go crazy. I'm not cut out for
that. My mind needs to be more active than just run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like I'm trying out for Miss America,
but I've been fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get satisfaction taking care of other people and in some
ways contributing to the world.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
