<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SEES UNLIMITED-RIDE METROCARD AS A WORKADAY SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first workday that they were on sale, the new
transit passes that offer unlimited rides on the city's subways and
buses on Monday caused long lines at some token booths and minor
confusion throughout the system. But over all, transit officials
said, the new passes were a success.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Metropolitan Transportation Authority said the
cards, which were introduced on Saturday and cost $17 for 7 days of
unlimited rides and $63 for 30 days, continued to sell very
briskly, though they did not have any firm sales figures. ``The
closest you could come to a number is saying that we've probably
sold in the tens of thousands of passes,'' said Christopher Boylan,
a deputy executive director of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the Union Street station in Park Slope, Brooklyn, and at the
86th Street station on the Lexington Avenue line on the East Side
of Manhattan, among others, rush-hour lines at the token booths
extended up the stairs, which regular riders said was unusual even
for a Monday, when many commuters typically replenish their
Metrocards. But at many other stations, including several on
Manhattan's Upper West Side and at the Atlantic Avenue station in
downtown Brooklyn, lines were about normal.
</P>
<P>
   At the 42nd Street station underneath the Port Authority Bus
Terminal, the line moved slowly Monday morning, in large part
because of the unfamiliarity of the new passes.
</P>
<P>
   Some riders were puzzled to find that the new passes looked
identical to the pay-per-ride Metrocards. ``I expected something
different,'' Sharon Allen, 38, of Crown Heights, Brooklyn, said at
the Atlantic Avenue station. ``I don't know quite what, but just
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances, the new passes and the pay-per-ride
Metrocards are not interchangeable. Another token clerk at the 42nd
Street station said several riders were disappointed when told they
could not take their existing pay-per-ride Metrocard and simply add
enough value to it to turn it into an unlimited pass.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the bugs in the system were made more annoying by a
feature that makes it impossible to use the pass twice within 18
minutes, an electronic barrier to keep people from swiping other
passengers through at no extra charge. Last week, the City Council
released a study showing that many Metrocard users who were unable
to swipe their cards at one turnstile and moved to a different
turnstile found that they had been charged two fares. The
unlimited-ride passes were supposed to eliminate that problem
because they do not charge per ride.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Albert, chairman of the Transit Riders Council, a
watchdog group, said that if a pass holder swiped at a defective
turnstile, ``it won't deduct a trip, but it will lock you out of
the system for 18 minutes while you watch trains go by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
