<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-NYT &LR;      07-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-NYT </SLUG>
  
 GRIFFEY OUTDUELS McGUIRE IN HOME RUN DERBY  
(sw) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When the All-Stars come out to shine Tuesday night, the
nation will get a look at the mighty home run swings of Mark
McGwire and Ken Griffey, who squared off in Monday night's home run
derby, with McGwire falling out in the first round with only four
home runs and Griffey winning the whole thing with 19 before a
record Coors Field crowd of 51,231.
</P>
<P>
   That will be enticing enough for most baseball fans. But
interestingly, what will not be on display when the starting
lineups are introduced at sold-out Coors Field is an overabundance
of New York Yankees, the team that has tied the major league record
for the most victories after 81 games, with 61.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the American League Manager Mike Hargrove of the
Cleveland Indians chose the left-hander David Wells as the American
League's starting pitcher on Monday did the Yankees crack the
starting nine. Wells, 11-2 and author of the only perfect game and
no-hitter of the season, will face Greg Maddux, the Atlanta Braves'
Cy Young regular who is quietly dazzling as always with a 12-2 mark
and a 1.54 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's selection of the starting pitchers, and the traditional
announcement of the starting lineups, were newsworthy, of course,
but they were clearly overshadowed by the hoopla surrounding this
evening's All-Star home run derby, with McGwire and Griffey as the
centerpieces in jam-packed Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The home run derby itself is not new, but it was a highly
anticipated event this year because of the three-way assault that
McGwire, Griffey and Sammy Sosa have launched on Roger Maris'
single-season home run record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa took himself out of the derby, and Tuesday's game, with
a sore shoulder and Griffey at first had declined to participate in
the derby, citing weariness from having had to play a game on
Sunday night. But after Griffey heard boos from the fans during
Monday's batting practice, he changed his mind. When the five derby
participants from each league were introduced on Monday evening,
there was Griffey, cap on backward, ready to take his swings.
</P>
<P>
   Why did he change his mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to get booed,'' he said. ``This is not a time to
get booed, at an All-Star Game. If they want to see me in the home
run competition, that's four million reasons why I did it.'' The
reference to four million had to do with the number of votes
Griffey drew as the top vote-getter in the balloting for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The derby does not count, of course _ and Juan Gonzalez and Greg
Vaughn, like Sosa, also declined to participate _ but Griffey did
everything he could to justify all those votes. After hitting eight
home runs in each of the first two rounds on Monday night, Griffey
then edged Jim Thome of Cleveland, 3-2, in the third and final
round.
</P>
<P>
   As for McGwire, who leads Griffey 37 home runs to 35 in games
that count, there was a ``sorry, everybody,'' for the crowd after
he went out, disappointingly, in the first round. But McGwire did
hit the longest shot in the derby _ a 510-feet blast to center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the ball middle in, and the pitches were middle away,''
McGwire said afterward by way of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, there were no Yankees in the home run derby, but
there will at least be three Yankees on the bench when the game
gets under way on Tuesday night. After the fans voted, Hargrove
added several Yankees _ third baseman Scott Brosius, right fielder
Paul O'Neill and shortstop Derek Jeter _ as reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Also picked by Hargrove but unable to attend was center fielder
Bernie Williams, the league's leading hitter, who is currently on
the disabled list. Of the Yankees eventually selected only Jeter
finished second in voting at his position, but he trailed Seattle's
Alex Rodriguez by nearly a million votes.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, the manager left to fill out the roster, was not
initially thinking about the Yankees on Monday. Not when he was
busy explaining why he selected his own shortstop, Omar Vizquel,
over Boston's Nomar Garciaparra or why he hesitated before turning
center field over to the Gold Glover Griffey and moving his own
center fielder, Kenny Lofton, to left.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the absence of pinstriped starters from the Bronx finally
struck home with Hargrove during a day of interviews, contests and
starry-eyed hyperbole on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I surprised? I guess maybe a little bit,'' said Hargrove,
``because the Yankees have maybe the best following around the
country, if not the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think instead of it being a knock against the Yankees,
and the players, I think it is a big compliment in how well
rounded, how well balanced, their team is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
