<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KWAN-LADN     07-07 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KWAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S LOVE AFFAIR WITH KWAN CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sometimes well-wishers will approach, says
Michelle Kwan, and simply burst into tears before they can get a
word out.
</P>
<P>
   And an usual phenomenon continues: Wizened adults still have
much more difficulty dealing with Kwan's unrealized hopes at the
1998 Winter Olympics than does this diminutive figure skater. She
turns 18 today, but her maturity and sportsmanship have so belied
her years that she's become something of a marvel in the sports
world.
</P>
<P>
   And out of it. Imagine two American skaters finishing 1-2 at an
Olympics and the silver medalist emerging as the more popular of
the two. Unthinkable. And yet that seems to be reality to date.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Lipinski, who won the gold in Nagano, Japan, gushed and
giggled, turned pro at age 15, and was about as embraceable as a
lottery winner.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, the prohibitive favorite going into the Games, held her
head high, spoke graciously and made not a single excuse _ although
she would have been fully warranted to cite at least two. Since
then, a wave of public and corporate appreciation has cascaded over
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, if anything, she came out of Nagano and was held in
higher regard by people,'' said Kwan's manager, Shep Goldberg,
``because I think they found out a lot more about what kind of
person she is and how she does handle adversity and her outlook on
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, everyone knew of her as a skater, but I think this
certainly humanized her.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who has been cheered warmly on an exhibition skating tour
that will make three stops in Southern California in the next few
days, seems grateful for her heightened popularity in the aftermath
of Nagano. But it's clear her reaction to the silver-medal finish
emanated from her core and wasn't some carefully calculated
response to elicit approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part of my upbringing,'' Kwan said recently over lunch
at an airport hotel, her mother at her elbow. ``What my parents
taught me was to do my best. And whether you win or lose, respect
the sport. Life has no guarantees. As a general rule, treat others
as you would like to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   As for refusing to wallow in the despair of an unfulfilled
dream, Kwan said, ``I think it really does speak for itself. It's,
`OK, let's do something else. Let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And on she has gone. There is the current tour, Champions on
Ice, which stops at the Long Beach Arena on Thursday, the Anaheim
Pond on Friday and the Sports Arena on Sunday. Later this summer,
she will participate in the Goodwill Games in Long Island and also
complete her independent studies and graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who has won two world championships and two national
titles, announced shortly after the Olympics she would continue to
compete as an amateur (although relaxed rules enable her to pull
down a healthy living in exhibitions), and aim, at least for now,
for a return to the Olympics in 2002 at Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Her commercial opportunities have also exploded, such that she
appears to be in more demand than Lipinski. There is a deal with
Disney for a series of televised specials, some product
endorsements and, according to Goldberg, discussions under way on
unspecified movie projects.
</P>
<P>
   She's also having fun. Kwan, who dropped out of school in
Torrance in the eighth grade so as to devote her full energies to
competitive skating, seems to be making up for lost teen time.
</P>
<P>
   While throwing a nervous glance toward her mother, she tells of
the time on tour recently when the skaters were careening down
infamous Lombard Street in San Francisco in a car driven by bronze
medalist Philippe Candeloro of France. There was also the
whitewater rafting excursion in Boise, Idaho, and the seaplane tour
of the wilds of Alaska. After this lunch, she was positively giddy
about the prospect of driving her car _ clear to LAX, a distance of
about a mile.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan has also toured Harvard and is weighing the prospect of
balancing college with her heavy skating schedule. ``I'm taking
things slowly because I want to make the right decision,'' she
said. ``It's important to pursue education. If I can stall it for a
year or two, fine, but I want to be the same age as everyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet, however, she will be a triple-toe leap ahead of
her contemporaries when it comes to poise and perspective.
</P>
<P>
   What happened at Nagano, strangely, was entirely if unwittingly
set up by Kwan herself. By delivering a dazzling, unprecedented
performance at the U.S. championships in Philadelphia just one
month before the Olympics _ getting perfect 6.0 scores on 15 of 18
marks _ she set a personal standard that proved improbably high.
When she dipped just slightly below that standard at Nagano while
Lipinski spun like an airborne top, the result was second place.
</P>
<P>
   The judges appeared to deem the performance just short of Kwan's
level. And, well... ``For me, it was a little short, too,'' said
Kwan. ``Just a hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My best performance ever was Philadelphia.'' Her eyes brighten
to a sparkle. ``I'll always remember that one.... Usually, you're
like, `(Sigh), Oh, it's over.' This time, it was, `Oh, I don't want
it ever to end.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Estella, interjects: ``Michelle got a card from a
lady that saw one of the shows in San Francisco. She said, `I'm 90
years old. I can't remember my name sometimes. But I'll always
remember the performance you did in Philadelphia. I'm looking for
the next one, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was to be no duplication of the performance at the
Olympics. Kwan never said a word about it until weeks after the
Games. But she was bothered throughout the competition by a stress
fracture in her left foot, a problem that had plagued her on and
off for months (and put her in a cast at the end of '97).
</P>
<P>
   She also had cause at least to question the judging, but she
didn't. The international skating community has been vowing for
some time it would not reward acrobatic jumping at the expense of
the balletic beauty of the sport. But in the '98 Games, this proved
to be lip service. Kwan presented her trademark artistry in her
free skate, but, as usual, produced no jump more daring than a
triple-double. Lipinski, landing five triple-triples, won over six
of the nine judges.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this, Kwan smiled impishly and said, ``Well, I've
already planned that I'm going to do a (quadruple jump).''
</P>
<P>
   She laughed, then turned serious: ``I don't want to be lacking
of something. I don't want the judges to have an excuse to put me
where they want to put me. That's why you have to improve. You have
to keep on improving. I think I can improve my technical side. I
can do those triple-triples....
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very subjective sport. There are a lot of opinions and
no facts, because there's no timer, there's no (measuring) how high
you can jump. Maybe one judge is looking for triple-triples,
another one is appreciating the grace and artistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started skating, I knew it was like this and I didn't
mind. And I still don't mind. You have to be a well-rounded
skater.''
</P>
<P>
   No complaints. No excuses. No cries of injustice. Just an
acknowledgement of the conditions, a determination to give the
judges everything they might require. And, all the while, a sincere
expression of pride in the silver medal, the winning of which was
no small feat.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder they cheer so enthusiastically for Michelle Kwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
