u S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     07-07 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY DOES RIGHT THING IN RESPONSE TO COORS BOO-BIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sheesh. The way people were starting to act, it looked
as if Ken Griffey Jr. ranked somewhere between Attila the Hun and
Seinfeld's resident persona non grata, Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those loud boos you heard wafting over the Rockies and
Cascades Monday afternoon were for Griffey _ before he did the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   When baseball's most popular player stepped into the batters box
for a pre-All-Star Game workout, baseball fans at Coors Field let
Griffey have it, big-time.
</P>
<P>
   See, Griffey said he was going to skip the crown jewel of the
All-Star Game festivities _ the home run derby _ and suddenly he's
the worst thing that ever happened to the youth of America since
Ronald Reagan's regime deemed ketchup a school lunch vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, bad for your health. Griffey, bad for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   No one cheered, either, when Griffey reached into the stands and
personally handed his double-dipped, black lacquered Louisville
Slugger to one very amazed and happy boy.
</P>
<P>
   It's true there's a thin line between love and hate. Sports
stars and sports fans seem to live out this basic human truth in
wildly dramatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   And Griffey, for all his growing up so gifted and so squarely in
the glaring spotlight, does not seem to mind straddling that
precarious line, even when he knows everything he says and does is
magnified times 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Griffey spent his All-Star Game confounding baseball
fans and observers by clamoring for more respect _ odd mostly
because there is no other baseball star more universally held in
awe.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Griffey undertook another quirky experiment in
group psychology. For a month, up until minutes before the home run
derby, Griffey steadfastly denied he would take part.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Griffey was holding a protest against Players' Union
representative Gene Orza, who all but insulted Griffey at the last
All-Star Game. Secondly, Griffey is frustrated with the baseball
schedule-makers, who have the Mariners traveling 70,000 miles in
six months with only three days off at home all season, with too
many day games that follow night games and other schedule grinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called a spoiled brat, a punk and everything else,
and I don't think I deserve it,'' Griffey said yesterday, launching
a defense of his no-derby stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to do one thing and I become a villain,'' said
the American League's reigning MVP and the leading All-Star
vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   Well, even Griffey _ maybe especially Griffey _ understands
baseball does not need any villains. That's ultimately why he
undecided to skip the derby, which meant that Griffey _ who also
straddles the line between tradition and new-generation baseball
like no other major leaguer today _ ultimately does the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   When they announced his participation just as the derby was
about to get started, Griffey drew the adulation of the Coors Field
crowd. From boos to cheers, just like that. That's the paper-thin
line of sports passion. Love and hate, so close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be booed. This is not a time to be booed, not
at the All-Star Game. If the fans wanted me to try, there's four
million reason why I should. I did it for them,'' Griffey said
after winning the whole darn thing, as Mark McGwire and Jim Thome
went for distance and Griffey just tried to do his best.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the pressure is on the game's biggest stars to
deliver the goods, to keep the love flowing. And it's a good
pressure, mostly. From Cub rookie Kerry Woods' 20 strikeouts in a
single game to Juan Gonzalez's 101-pre-All-Star RBI assault on Hack
Wilson's record to Sammy Sosa's record 20 dingers in the month of
June, the players are eating up the opportunities to take on
history, maybe even to make history.
</P>
<P>
   By all measure here in the rare air of Denver, baseball has to
understand it has gotten a huge break.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after baseball's ugly strike, the unsavory image of
union boss Donald Fehr and commissioner Bud Selig is about all the
villain baseball can sustain. The image of that ugly standoff grows
ever distant, especially now that Selig is calling 1998 a
``renaissance'' season as attendance and interest are again
flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   And with Griffey's 35 homers so far this season and McGwire's 37
and Sosa's 33, there is no lack of punch and box-office draw to the
game formerly known as the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   That's ultimately why Griffey had to relent and join in the home
run derby. Maybe the boos made him think twice. Maybe he always
intended to participate. Maybe the words of Hall of Famers Frank
Robinson and Joe Morgan worked on him.
</P>
<P>
   While he has a knack for confounding behavior, Griffey
understands as clearly as anyone that in the big picture there is
still so much baseball must do to reach out and grow and evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Griffey lamented the fact that rocket-throwing Woods
was left off the National League roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all he's done this year, he deserves to be here,''
Griffey said. ``I didn't say I wanted to face him, but he should be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Griffey thinks the All-Star rosters should be
expanded, to give more deserving players a chance. And, as always,
Griffey is adamant that baseball should do more to market the
players and the game to appeal to a new generation of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Is baseball on its way back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Griffey said. ``I think it is. I think the things
going on, with McGwire and Woods and David Wells' no-hitter and
Sammy, these are things we need. Hopefully, it's something we can
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Like baseball itself, sometimes Griffey's path and rationale are
a little convoluted. Ultimately, we have come to learn, he does the
right thing, homers and all.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
