<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STARS READY FOR TAKEOFF TUESDAY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With this being the year of the home run in the major
leagues, you couldn't find a more suitable location than Coors
Field for the game's most powerful sluggers to put on a show.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs are hit here more often than any other big-league
stadium, giving Tuesday night's 69th All-Star Game the potential of
becoming the highest scoring Midsummer Classic in history.
</P>
<P>
   The record is 20 runs, scored on July 13, 1954, in Cleveland,
when the AL won, 11-9. But the air is thinner here. The muscles are
bigger. And the timing is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the homers flying out of the yard, it's kind of weird
that we're in home run heaven,'' San Diego Padres outfielder Tony
Gwynn said during Monday's National League workout. ``If you're a
home run hitter, you've got to love playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to be a home run hitter to think long-ball.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariner shortstop Omar Vizquel walked into the visiting
clubhouse Monday, holding a video camera and dreaming of reaching
the seats for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't hit one yet, but I can't think of a better place to
do it,'' the first-time All-Star said. ``I've never played a game
here, but I hear that the ball travels pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   And often.
</P>
<P>
   Through June 30, there were 856 home runs hit here since Coors
Field opened for the 1995 season. That is 105 more than teams have
hit at the Kingdome over the same span.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was the hitting coach (for the Rockies) for two years
and he always told me you don't have to swing very hard for the
ball to go out here,'' Ken Griffey Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   According to scientists, a ball hit 400 feet at sea level will
travel 440 feet in Denver's mile-high altitude. One of Mark
McGwire's best bolts Tuesdat night might wind up in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about managing his first game at Coors Field, AL
manager Mike Hargrove said, ``You get a dart board and darts and
start firing them at the wall. Anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed for a year in Colorado Springs so I'm a little bit
familiar with how well the balls travels in this part of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   So does National League starter Greg Maddux of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to compare pitching in Coors Field to anywhere else,
Maddux said, ``Well, I mean, obviously, you know, your slider
doesn't slide as much and your curves don't curve as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can still pitch here, as long as you keep the ball
down.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, the AL starting pitcher and the Yankees'
perfect-game star, said he isn't intimidated by the ballpark,
McGwire or anything else for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a challenge and I enjoy challenges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the odds favor a hitter's game.
</P>
<P>
   Wells is 11-2 with a 3.75 ERA. He joked that his principal
strategy Tuesday night will be to duck. ``I have a vision of a
high-scoring game, but hopefully not when I'm in there.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four players on the teams who have hit at least 30
homers this season: McGwire (37), Griffey (35), Sammy Sosa (33) and
Greg Vaughn (30). Sosa, however, won't play because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who like their games on the 12-10 side have come to the
right place. Coors Field led all major-league parks in runs per
game, homers per at-bat and batting average from 1995-97, according
to Stats Inc. That's not only a reflection of Denver's mile-high
air. Since the ball carries so well and outfielders play so deep,
there's more room for singles to fall in front of them and doubles
to reach the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   A well-pitched, tightly played game _ which is unlikely _ could
go a long way toward dispelling Coors Field's image as a launching
pad. When Chicago Cubs first baseman Mark Grace christened the park
``Williamsport'' _ in reference to the Little League World Series
site in Pennsylvania _ it wasn't because of the ambience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best park in the National League to hit in, for
sure,'' said Rockies outfielder Dante Bichette. ``But I think the
reputation is a little bit exaggerated. Hopefully everybody will
see a well-played game and it won't add to the park's mystique _ or
whatever you want to call it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
