<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-HOMER-SPI &LR;      07-07 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOMER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOS LIGHT GRIFFEY'S FIRE IN HOME RUN DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ken Griffey Jr. insisted for more than a month that the
All-Star Home Run Derby would have to go on without him. No way, no
thanks, no chance of changing his mind.
</P>
<P>
   A loud crowd at Coors Field on Monday changed it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to get booed. I don't think anybody does,'' the
Mariner center fielder said after not only competing in the derby
but winning it. ``This is not a time to get booed, the All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, you know, if they want to see me in the home run
competition, the fans, that's the reason why I did it. For them.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey was the overwhelmingly least-favorite All-Star
introduced during Monday's American League workout. He stepped into
the batting cage and the fans let him know they weren't happy about
him refusing to compete in what has become the glamor event of the
Mid-Summer Classic.
</P>
<P>
   American League home run leader vs. National League home run
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey versus Mark McGwire, man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   Although McGwire, of the St. Louis Cardinals, hit the longest
home run _ 510 feet _ Griffey hit the most, beating Cleveland
Indians first baseman Jim Thome in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Each slugger had five outs in the finals. Thome, batting first,
hit two into the seats. Griffey, cap turned backwards, stepped in
and sent three batting practice pitches into the bleachers with two
outs to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew two wasn't going to be enough to beat Junior,'' Thome
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same fans who booed Griffey, stood and cheered him.
</P>
<P>
   As Griffey talked to the media at his locker, Hall of Famer Joe
Morgan stuck his head through the gathering and said, ``I'm proud
of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so much for winning a second derby title, but competing.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, an ESPN baseball analyst, had spoken to Griffey in
Arlington, Texas, Sunday night and reminded him that he was the
most popular player in the game _ as evidenced by his major
league-leading 4 million All-Star votes.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, Hall of Famer Frank Robinson talked to Griffey about
half an hour before the derby started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to the guys with those types of numbers and
credentials,'' Griffey said. ``You know, you don't know everything.
This is my 10th year in the big leagues and I'm still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   After the boos and batting practice, several of Griffey's AL
All-Star teammates offered encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the boos are the reason he changed his mind,'' said
Mariner shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who hit five homers and failed to
get to the second round. ``And as only Junior can do, he put on a
show.''
</P>
<P>
   The five AL participants already had been selected by the time
Griffey changed his mind. Damion Easley of the Tigers; Rafael
Palmeiro of the Orioles; Rodriguez, Thome and Darin Erstad of the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad and Griffey talked. Erstad watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ended up making the final decision,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   He stood on the dugout steps holding a bat. After local favorite
Vinny Castilla, the Rockies' only All-Star was introduced, Griffey
stepped down and then walked up the dugout steps to be introduced
to a mixture of cheers and boos.
</P>
<P>
   The cheers grew louder as Griffey pounded eight batting practice
pitches into the seats, guaranteeing him a spot in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   The major league's leading home run hitter with 37 settled for
four homers in the first round. ``I'm sorry, everybody,'' he told
the capacity crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to see how far Mark could hit the ball,'' Griffey
said. ``They will remember the one (510 feet) he hit more than the
number of homers I hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Griffey said he was glad he changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to win, but it was fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
