<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO VOTES FOR MCGUIRE TO HIT 62 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, re-editing throughout) (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The numbers change, but for a day or two or sometimes
an at-bat or two, each number is part of their name. The names and
numbers now are Mark McGwire 37, Ken Griffey Jr. 35, Sammy Sosa 33.
</P>
<P>
   For most home run hitters, any of those numbers is a good
season. But as McGwire, Griffey and Sosa gathered for Tuesday
night's All-Star Game, each has a realistic chance to surpass the
name and number that defines home run history for one season: Roger
Maris 61.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire needs only 25 more to break the record, Griffey only 27,
Sosa only 29.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sosa, the Cubs' 29-year-old right fielder, was asked on
Monday which had the best opportunity to break Maris' record, he
never hesitated even with Griffey sitting next to him in the Coors
Field interview room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my money on Mark McGwire,'' Sosa said. ``Griffey, I
know you my boy, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey laughed. Sosa continued in his Dominican-accented
English, saying: ``We have another second half to go. Who knows? I
might be the one, Griffey might be the one, or Mark.'' But with a
smile, Griffey agreed that McGwire had the best chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bigger,'' the Mariners' center fielder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that Griffey swing, that's something that's natural,''
Sosa said. ``He don't try to hit a home run, just an easy swing,
make contact. Myself, I'm crazy. I'm swinging the bat all the way.
If I'm not swinging the bat hard, I think I'm cheating myself.
Mark, he is so big, he swing so easy. I don't think he go out there
trying to swing hard to hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   This was before the home run derby that Griffey, who changed his
mind about competing after being booed, won with a total of 19 over
three rounds. Although McGwire hit only four, he hit the longest, a
510-foot moon shot to center. Sosa was scratched with a sore
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just enjoy it,'' McGwire had said earlier of the home run
derby. ``Why guys are backing out, I'm sure they all have their own
reasons, but I enjoy it. It's something I do. It's something that
I've accepted that I am.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit 58 last season, including 24 after being traded to
the Cardinals from Oakland on July 31. He hit 52 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly,'' the 6-foot-5-inch 250-pound first baseman
said, ``some of the longer ones I've hit, I didn't realize they
were going that far because a lot of people say, `What's the
feeling?' Actually there's really no feeling at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when the ball meets the bat that it's left the ball
park. My swing is nice and easy, short and compact. It's really
effortless. Because of that, there's really not that hard feeling
that I think some players have. It's a nice, easy thing.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire minimized the theory that his back problems threaten his
chance to hit 62, if not 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take away 1993 and 1994 where I missed all those games,
I've basically averaged 150 games a year,'' he said, alluding to
the heel ailment that put him on the disabled list. ``Everybody
gets injured in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play six months of the year. No other sport does that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play through the hottest time of the year. I've had a bad
back since 1989. It's something I have to deal with. I swing a bat
probably 100,000 times a year.''
</P>
<P>
   But he believes that missing all those games in 1993 and 1994
made him a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time since I was a Little Leaguer that I had
to sit on the bench and watch a game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time that I really started watching pitchers
pitch to hitters. I started watching tapes on how they pitched me.
I started watching hitters, how they approached other pitchers.
When I came back, I started adapting that to my game.''
</P>
<P>
   And almost every day now, McGwire sees himself linked to Babe
Ruth, who hit 60 homers in 1927, and Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that when I was a kid and all I wanted to do was
pitch, it wasn't until my sophomore year in college that I turned
into a hitter, never knowing if I'd get a chance to go to the big
leagues,'' he said, alluding to the University of Southern
California. ``The next thing you now, they're talking about my name
along with Babe Ruth, Roger Maris, Mickey Mantle. It's
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's that Mark McGwire hits baseballs over walls. Maybe, in
one season, like nobody else ever has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
