<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3088 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-PREVIEW-A     07-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM HEARTS, COLD SHOULDERS FOR 2 PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It happens every July, Major League Baseball charges
into its summer blockbuster with a rush. Baseball's All-Star Game
has become the game's mid-season showcase event.
</P>
<P>
   For the 69th time, the American and National Leagues will get
together to decide which is the dominant league. The usual story
lines are all in place _ the game's great sluggers facing the best
of today's pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is so much more to this year's event. Coors Field is
awash with two of the most compelling stories of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, there's Atlanta shortstop Walt Weiss, whose
three-year-old son, Brody, appears to have successfully fought off
a potentially lethal strand of E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, there's New York Mets pitcher Rick Reed, who
has become the first replacement player to reach the game's
pinnacle, at least on an individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Both Weiss and Reed are All-Stars for the first time in their
careers. Both have interesting subplots that stem from
circumstances away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   In Reed's case, it was almost painful to watch the way most of
his NL All-Star teammates ostracized him before, during and after
Monday's workout. In Weiss' case, there is universal support for
his son and family.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every player became emotional when discussing what the
Weisses have gone through since Brody contracted the virus while
playing in contaminated pool water at an Atlanta theme park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked up to him today and said, `Look, I've never really
met you, but my family has said prayers for you,' '' Yankees
outfielder Paul O'Neill said. ``I know he has a lot of faith, and I
think that's helped him tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Atlanta teammate Javier Lopez: ``You see his face and how
happy he is, but that's not because he's at the All-Star Game. It's
because his son is better. It affected all of us. He's been
amazing. He's never lost faith, which is the biggest thing he's
shown all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Before signing with the Braves last winter, Weiss played three
seasons for the Colorado Rockies, where owner Jerry McMorris found
a special place in his heart for the slick-fielding shortstop, who
is almost universally considered one of the most decent humans in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   McMorris was so overcome with joy from Brody's release from an
Atlanta-area hospital last week that he sent his private jet to
Georgia to pick up the Weiss family. Doctors did not want Brody to
fly commercially until his immune system had a chance to strengthen
itself further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I couldn't thank him (McMorris) enough,'' said
Weiss, who still makes his off-season home in the Denver suburb of
Aurora. ``It shows it was more than a player-management
relationship when I was here. The way people have reached out to us
is beyond belief. It just blows me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody will attend the All-Star Game tonight and sit inside
McMorris' private box. Weiss will always remember his first
All-Star Game. But not because he finally made it after 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outpouring of support has been nothing short of amazing,''
Weiss said. ``You wouldn't believe the stacks of cards, letters and
stuffed animals we've received, most of them from Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Weiss story apparently will have a happy ending, it's
uncertain which way Reed's will wind up. One thing was certain from
Monday's workout: The resentment toward players who crossed
baseball's picket line back in the spring of 1995 still exists.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the NL clubhouse, Reed made his way to his
cubicle, dressed and started up on a crossword puzzle. Only a
handful of NL All-Stars said anything to Reed, who mostly sat
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say less than half have said anything to me,'' Reed
said. ``Crossing the picket line was something I felt I had to do.
Looking back at it, I would never have done it now. But it's too
late for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time. It really was. I guess I stepped on some
toes. I was pacing in my room before coming here today. It wasn't
that tough walking into the clubhouse. It was much tougher getting
on the bus with all the players on it.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Atlanta's four-time Cy Young Award winner, Greg
Maddux, walked up to Reed and asked him to sign a baseball signed
by the other NL All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' Maddux said. ``And, congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   It was simple, yet it meant so much to Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the very first time we've ever talked,'' Reed said.
``That makes it all worth while.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hard feelings were obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a guy crosses a picket line in baseball, that's just the
way it is,'' said Colorado Manager Don Baylor. ``Maybe in time that
might change. But I'd say it's a slim maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Home Run Derby, when the NL players stood on the
first base dugout rail, Reed was down at the end, flanked by a pair
of Rockies' grounds crew workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on it,'' said Philadelphia's Curt
Schilling. ``It's the All-Star Game. I'm here to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others seemed more willing to welcome Reed back into good
graces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he feels uncomfortable,'' San Diego's Tony Gwynn
said. ``But what's done is done. I went up and congratulated him.
He's a big part of why the Mets are succeeding. He's earned his way
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mark McGwire: ``That's long in the past. It was too long
ago to continue dwelling on it.''
</P>
<P>
   One game, two vastly different sides of baseball sharing the
All-Star stage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
