</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL </SLUG>
 STAR MARLINS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ex-Marlins dominate pre-game discussion
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ It was just like old times.
</P>
<P>
   On a couch in the National League clubhouse, Moises Alou, Devon
White and Gary Sheffield _ all integral parts of the Florida
Marlins' title run last season _ were reunited with former manager
Jim Leyland.
</P>
<P>
   They rekindled World Series memories. Mostly, though, they
caught up on a hectic last few months that saw a near complete
dismantling of the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   A few lockers away, a couple more ex-teammates _ Kevin Brown and
Robb Nen _ answered questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Marlins were together again, if only for a few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Five players.
</P>
<P>
   Five different uniforms. And that's just part of the story. In
all, 16 members of the 1997 World Series champions are with 10
different teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they wanted to defend,'' Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn
said. ''Look at the number of ex-Marlins in here. They would have
had a pretty good chance of doing that because they had a quality
club. ``That's done. They're all spread out.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the former Marlins, no player has contributed more to his
team's success than Alou, whom the Astros acquired last November.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series magic has yet to wear off for Alou, whose 20
home runs and 73 RBIs earned him a third All-Star selection. None
of it comes as a shock to his former coaches and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big-game player. He wants to be there in the big
game,'' Marlins coach Bruce Kimm said. ``He wants to go out there
every day and if he doesn't beat you with his bat, he'll beat you
with the glove. He's an all-around player. He's definitely one of
the best players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the occasion, he'll rise to it. In a big game, if you
had to have somebody at the plate, I'll take him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He meant a lot to us,'' said Nen, now the Giants' closer. ``He
had a great year and he's doing the same thing this year for the
Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 of the World Series, Alou delivered a three-run homer
in the sixth inning and later added an RBI single as the Marlins
beat Cleveland 8-7. Alou hit .321 with three homers, nine RBIs and
six runs in the seven-game triumph over the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Mike Hargrove, manager of the AL All-Star team, had
an idea of what to expect from Alou before last year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going into that he had a reputation as a big-game
player,'' Hargrove said. ``He did nothing to dispel that. We knew
in the World Series he was going to be a big out for us, that we
didn't need to let him beat us. For the most part we were able to
succeed with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much you can do and eventually a hitter like
that is going to step up and burn you.''
</P>
<P>
   What has made Alou even better, some players say, is his
insertion into a lineup of heavy hitters, similar to when he was
with the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing is that he didn't have to shoulder
the load by himself,'' Gwynn said. ``They had good players to begin
with. All he is is another piece to the puzzle, just like some of
these other guys are with other clubs. He has made them a much
better ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of his former teammates on the NL All-Star
squad:
</P>
<P>
   Brown is 10-3 with a 2.67 ERA for the NL West-leading San Diego
Padres, including a 7-0 mark in his last eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   Nen, a first-time All-Star, is tied for the league lead with 25
saves for the Giants, who lead the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers have struggled but Sheffield has been
impressive since being traded in the blockbuster deal for Mike
Piazza in May. He is batting .327 with eight home runs and 32 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   White is arguably the best player for the expansion Arizona
Diamondbacks, owners of the worst record in the major leagues. The
three-time All-Star is hitting .292 with 13 homers and 49 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Edgar Renteria is the only member of the 1997 Marlins
still playing in Florida. He will appear in his first All-Star Game
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland said there was no conspiracy to reunite his old players.
They will play tonight because of their accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there was no plan behind it (the selections),''
Leyland said. ``It just tells you what an outstanding baseball team
we had last year. I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
