<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-BICKLEY-     07-07 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER FOR THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER - There is no ambiguity over the crack of a bat, no
ambivalence when a ball sails into the street.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone understands force. Everyone is intoxicated by power.
And no one can turn away when records start quivering in fear.
</P>
<P>
   They said baseball was past its time, no longer hip, an
antiquated sport that couldn't possibly appeal to a generation
weaned on Michael Jordan and the X Games. But here you are, touched
by the sluggers, romanced by the most awe-inspiring moment in
sports:
</P>
<P>
   The home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most difficult thing to do in sports today,'' Mark
McGwire said. ``To hit a round ball with a round bat squarely, to
get it to go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Stars will take the field today, but the reason for
baseball's renaissance was on display Monday, a few rounds of
missile-launching pinball that served as a microcosm for the first
half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN hyped the event like the Super Bowl, knowing that last
year's Home Run Derby produced a 5.7 rating, higher than any of its
programming outside the NFL. Ken Griffey Jr., who spent the
afternoon explaining why he wouldn't partake in the contest, came
to his senses and realized the importance of the moment. And when
McGwire failed to make the cut, the biggest freak of them all
apologized to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   This was a meaningless exhibition, but it was wonderfully
symbolic, for there is giddy apprehension just around the corner.
Soon, the chase will get serious. And if Roger Maris is snuffed out
after 37 years on the throne, baseball will dominate the landscape
in a way few thought possible at the start of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has accepted the firestorm of attention and is
threatening to make a mockery of the record. Although strangely
indifferent, Griffey can spend the rest of the season swinging for
the fences. And the attention-craving Sammy Sosa is just the type
to enjoy the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to be on television everyday, but if they ask, I
will be there,'' Sosa said. ``You have to be strong mentally to do
it, and right now, I think I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the climate is perfect. When Maris bopped 61
homers in 1961, he lost clumps of hair and developed a rash on his
face. The sentiment was against him, and the commissioner felt it
necessary to attach an asterisk to his feat, noting the schedule
had been lengthened by eight games since Babe Ruth smashed 60.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you don't care if the pitching is diluted, if the ball is
juiced or if creatine is turning the game into batting practice.
You want to see history, even if it means abandoning all loyalty
when the candidates come to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I want to go like this,'' said McGwire, motioning
like a quarterback requesting silence. ``The guy on the mound is
trying his best to get me out. He throws one or two balls and the
stands are booing. It's another thing that has been so overwhelming
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, it is wonderful for the game that the men chasing
Maris represent different ethnic backgrounds. And all three have
unique opportunities: Sosa has Wrigley Field. Griffey has the
perfect swing. And if McGwire stays healthy, he could do the record
justice, besting it in fewer than 154 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until my sophomore year in college that I turned
into a hitter, never knowing I'd ever get a chance to go to the big
leagues,'' McGwire said. ``The next thing you know, they're taking
about my name along with Babe Ruth, Maris, Mantle. It's
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the homestretch is beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my money on Mark McGwire,'' Sosa said, turning
sheepishly toward his friend. ``Griffey, I know you're my boy, but
. . . ''
</P>
<P>
   So they said the game was too long, too slow, a rocking chair in
the high-tech den of athletics. But now you're watching the
rocket's red glare, the bombs bursting in air, and suddenly,
baseball is hot.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time in a long time, definitely cool. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
