<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HNS &LR;      07-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL </SLUG>
 STAR-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Griffey takes Home Run Derby
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ The rarefied air of Coors Field, a defenseless batting
practice pitcher and an oversized redhead named Mark McGwire didn't
appear to be a very good combination for anyone else hoping to win
Monday's Home Run Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your upsets.
</P>
<P>
   In the year of the home run, the man who has done more for the
cause than anyone else was just ordinary. McGwire, who hit 37
homers in the first half of the season and is on pace to set a
single-season record with 70, pumped just four out of Coors Field
during Monday's contest _ and was eliminated after the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd at Coors Field must have felt like the
Griswalds in National Lampoon's Vacation after the family drove
across country to visit an amusement park that was closed for
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   There might as well have been an ``out of order'' sign hanging
around McGwire's neck as he sat near the dugout and watched Jim
Thome and last-minute entry Ken Griffey Jr. battle for the award he
was supposed to win.
</P>
<P>
   This was the most anticipated Home Run Derby since the event was
added, and no one had to tell McGwire who the fans expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, everyone,'' McGwire said during an on-field interview
that could be heard over the public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   The Coors Field gathering owed Griffey an apology after the
long-ball display he treated them to.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who won the event for the third time, was booed when he
accepted his award as the top vote-getter in fan balloting. The
fans were disappointed because Griffey had announced he wouldn't
participate in the Home Run Derby. The negative reaction lit a fire
under Griffey and spurred him to 19 homers in the three-round
competition.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Thome 3-2 in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good after batting practice, so I decided I would go
ahead and do it,'' said Griffey, who received 4,202,803 All-Star
votes. ``I don't like to get booed. I figured there were about 4
million reasons I should do it, and I'm glad I did. It was a lot of
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was (once) the hitting coach (with the Rockies), and he
said, `Just go out there and swing the bat. Don't try to do too
much, because if you hit it, it will go out'''
</P>
<P>
   Although McGwire has said he feels like a ``caged lion'' because
of the attention his daily batting-practice sessions draw, he
actually seemed to be looking forward to Monday's contest. But he
wasn't pleased with the pitch location from the BP pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the ball middle and in, and most of the pitches he
threw me were middle and away,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitchers usually take center stage on the day
before the All-Star Game, but David Wells and Greg Maddux took a
back seat to the homer hubbub on Monday. Both are hoping the
attention shifts from home runs to quality pitching tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the fans get to see a high-scoring game with some home
runs, but hopefully not when I'm on the mound,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was an easy choice for AL manager Mike Hargrove. The
Yankees lefthander has an 11-2 record and pitched a perfect game
against Minnesota on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   His mound opponent, Maddux, is the closest thing to pitching
perfection in the modern era. Maddux, who is 12-2 with a 1.54 ERA
for the Braves, will appear in his seventh All-Star Game and make
his third start.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games are always so much fun,'' he said. ``They're great
to play in; it's almost like spring training because there's no
pressure at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maddux has not pitched well in All-Star play, posting a 4.26
ERA, and Coors Field is not exactly the place to reverse one's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has his own share of horror stories from Coors, dating to
his days with the Cincinnati Reds. When asked what it would take to
be successful tonight, Wells' answer was quick and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luck,'' he said. ``You have to hope for luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the best pitchers from both leagues are assembled, it
seems unlikely they will be able to work enough magic to keep the
score low. But whether it's a 1-0 game or a 10-9 game, Hargrove
believes it will be enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you bring this much talent together, it's
awe-inspiring,'' he said. ``I'm very appreciative just to be
associated with it because you never know if you'll get the chance
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most special events in baseball for
everyone involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
