<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-PEOPLE-CONFAB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTEST FOLKS CONQUER BIG ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At just over 4 feet tall, entertainer Michael
Gogin prefers not to be called a dwarf or a little person but a
short-statured person.
</P>
<P>
   An actor now on screen in ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas,''
Gogin has been married for 18 years to a woman who is 5 feet 2.
</P>
<P>
   But the height difference between Gogin and his wife, Darla, was
never much of an impediment. Winning the acceptance of her mother,
Helen, was the biggest obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people realize that in a relationship, there is no
height,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1,500 people from around the world who are attending the
Little People of America's 1998 National Conference at the Warner
Center Marriott Hotel this week, issues surrounding height,
disability laws, parenting and orthopedic concerns are hot topics.
</P>
<P>
   In Gogin's case, his mother-in-law knew his history, including
his first 19 years spent in and out of hospitals because of
orthopedic problems. She didn't think he could offer her daughter a
good life, both because of his stature and because he was trying to
make a living as an actor and a musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just told me that she was unhappy and wished her daughter
would not be involved with me,'' said Gogin, whose trademark is a
braided ponytail falling more than halfway down his back. ``Even
after we married, she tried to split us up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very hurtful,'' Darla Gogin said. ``She was civil for
most of our relationship, though she made it clear she wanted us to
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   She kept that attitude for almost 18 years but began to come
around as she saw how her son-in-law interacted with the three sons
born to Darla and him. The first, Matt, now 16, was born with the
same dwarfism as his father.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Gogin's mother-in-law sat him down and told him:
``You're a good father.'' And she promised to provide a new house
for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like you're apologizing to me for all the years
before,'' Gogin said he told her _ and she agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Christmas, she actually said I love you,'' Gogin recalled,
still proud he won her over.
</P>
<P>
   When she died in 1996, she left the Gogins more than enough
money for a home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gogins' story is hardly unique, according to others
attending this week's conference for people 4 feet 10 and shorter,
along with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Monique Hamilton and her fiance, Stuart Davis, also experienced
opposition to their relationship when they began dating seriously
five years ago, after they developed a cross-country friendship
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She is 3 feet 8 inches tall, and he is 5 feet 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family had a very difficult time accepting me,'' said
Hamilton, 26, who uses a wheelchair or crutches because of a spinal
injury nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Active her entire life with the Little People of America, she
said animosity from the average-size person's family is common when
one marries a very short person.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' family wasn't opposed to her relationship with him solely
because she is short, she said. ``They wanted him to have a family
with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton doesn't want children because she feels she wouldn't be
able to care for them, which would force Davis to do all the work,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Southern California native, Hamilton moved to Davis' home
state of South Carolina to live with him about four years ago. Two
years ago they moved to California and now live in Lake Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with his family has gotten better, said
Hamilton. Meeting her face to face helped change their minds about
her and her stature, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they felt it wasn't such a difference after all.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
