<HEADLINE>
USC RECRUIT TRIES TO GET CHARGES REDUCED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The status of USC football recruit Windrell Hayes
remains in doubt, but the highly touted wide receiver is attempting
to reduce felony charges to improve his chances of being eligible
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes is facing three felony counts: suspicion of writing bad
checks for merchandise, conspiracy and burglary. He was arrested in
Northern California May 22 with two other men and has pleaded
innocent to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   There is a possibility Hayes could plead guilty to one of the
felonies and make full restitution to the victims. Then the crime
would be reduced to a misdemeanor, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   However, police investigators have determined that Hayes
personally wrote about $6,000 in bad checks. Another $10,000 in bad
checks were written. But police cannot determine who wrote those
checks, according to Lodi deputy district attorney Scott Fichtner.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office has informed Hayes that he must
make restitution for the entire $16,000 for any possibility of the
charges being reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always said what he wants is a misdemeanor,'' Fichtner
said. ``It's yet to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes chances of attending USC would be greatly enhanced if he
could get the charges reduced.
</P>
<P>
   USC football coach Paul Hackett is on vacation and could not be
reached for comment. But Hackett has said he is still waiting for
all the facts to emerge before commenting.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, 6-feet, 200 pounds, is considered one of USC's impact
recruits. He started two years at San Jose State, leading the
Spartans in receiving both seasons. In 1996, Hayes was named
All-Western Athletic Conference second team after catching 58
passes for 848 yards and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   __ Controversial tutor off football: Janice Henry, the
controversial tutor/supervisor who was a key figure in two
investigations of academic impropriety in the past three years,
will no longer assist football players
</P>
<P>
   Henry will primarily focus on assisting basketball players next
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
