<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FANS MAKE ANNUAL TICKET TREK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Longtime Dallas Cowboys fan  &UR; Juan Marquez knew
what would happen if he didn't arrive at the Cardinals' Tempe
training facility early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The best seats for the Nov. 15 game between the Cowboys and
Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   That's always the way it is when the Cardinals put single-game
tickets on sale: Cowboys fans show up before the doors open to
stand in line for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were brisk Monday, but plenty of tickets are available for
all games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm late,'' Marquez said after buying tickets. ``I meant to
get here earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquez has been a Cowboys fan since the 1970s and lets everyone
in the Valley know it. The license plate on the back of his van
says, ``Da Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   He's glad the team fired Coach  &UR; Barry Switzer after last year's
6-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only positive thing that happened to them last
season,'' Marquez said. ``They had the most talent in the league
last year. They should have been in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also follows the Cardinals on a casual basis and is
expecting them to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've shown so many (good) signs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Cowboys fan,  &UR; Jorge Kimzin, also missed the Monday
morning crush for tickets but stood in line later.
</P>
<P>
   He said he goes to a few Cardinals games each year, almost
always seeing the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't go last year (in September) because it was too
hot,'' he said. ``There's no way I'm going to sit out there in that
heat.''
</P>
<P>
   He also is glad the Cowboys have replaced Switzer with
first-year Coach
 &UR; Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took too long for them to make a change,'' he said. ``They
should have gotten rid of him a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He also doesn't expect the Cardinals to go 4-12 again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think they will be better,'' he said. ``I think
the draft picks will make a difference. The key is protecting  &UR; Jake
( &UR; Plummer, quarterback). You have to protect Jake if you want to go
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Single-game tickets also are available at ETM ticket machines at
selected Safeway stores or at www.etm.com via the Internet and by
phone at 888-386-8497. &QL;  &QL; 
In demand &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State defensive tackle  &UR; Jamal Williams, considered the
top player available in Thursday's supplemental draft, visited the
Cardinals on Monday. He also took a physical examination.
</P>
<P>
   Williams became available for the draft when academic problems
forced him to withdraw from school.
</P>
<P>
   The national scouting group listed Williams, 6 feet 2, 300
pounds, as a top-20 player in next year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams consider Williams a possible first-round pick in the
supplemental draft, but it is unlikely the Cardinals would take him
in an early round because of their strength at that position.
</P>
<P>
   They are more likely to choose Navy offensive tackle  &UR; Mike Wahle
in a later round. Wahle, 6-5, 302 pounds, visited Tempe earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Any team that picks a player in the supplemental draft will lose
its corresponding pick in the 1999 regular draft. &QL;  &QL; 
Winners &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals rookies who attended last week's NFL symposium in
Denver came away with the overall first prize.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies were graded on categories such as attentiveness,
promptness and interaction with others.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals rookies were awarded gold watches for
winning, first-round draft pick  &UR; Andre Wadsworth spoke for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys better get used to this,'' Wadsworth told the rookies
on the other teams. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
