<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-LEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR TASTE LEAVES LEE CRAVING MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It wasn't quite the same as driving in the winning run
to win the Big Show, but Travis Lee will take it.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie first baseman for the Diamondbacks teamed with former
Kansas City Royals star George Brett and country singer Tim McGraw
to win the MCI All-Star Hitting Challenge on Monday as a lead-in to
tonight's 69th All-Star Game at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The purple-jerseyed trio defeated the green-clad team of Oakland
Athletics rookie outfielder Ben Grieve, actor Kevin Costner and
former slugger Dave Kingman, 370-210.
</P>
<P>
   Players were awarded points on the basis of where they hit the
ball in various ``zones.'' Ground ball hits did not count, and the
final swing of each round was double the points.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's team and Grieve's team had the highest point totals of the
four teams in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The other teams were made up of Chicago White Sox rookie Magglio
Ordonez, actor Jonathan Silverman and former star outfielder Andre
Dawson; and Colorado Rockies rookie first baseman Todd Helton,
Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway and former Milwaukee Brewers
star and Paradise Valley resident Robin Yount.
</P>
<P>
   Lee hit only one home run in the first round, scoring 230 points
on eight swings, but came back in the second round to hit three,
good for 180 points on five swings. He took home a small glass
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of the pitches were a little low, and in a normal
situation during a game, I probably would have gone the opposite
way,'' the left-handed-hitting Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was enjoyable for Lee, ``because I got to hit
with George and meet Tim and Kevin Costner. They seem like
down-to-earth, everyday guys. George is kind of funny. He still has
that competitive spirit and was getting us pumped up for the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   How could it have been more enjoyable?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was out there (with the National League All-Stars)
taking batting practice for real. I'm just a fan right now,'' said
Lee, who flew back to Phoenix on Monday night for a little rest
before the season resumes Friday against Cincinnati at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had a solid first half for the Diamondbacks, hitting .284
with 47 RBIs and a team-leading 17 home runs. It shouldn't be long
before he is an All-Star for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him play twice this summer,'' said Brett, who with
brother Bobby owns the Diamondbacks' High Desert affiliate of the
Class A California League.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter,'' Brett said. ``He's going to be one of
those hitters who can hit over .300 consistently in the major
leagues _ hit 15, 20, 25 home runs, driving in 100 runs. There's no
doubt in my mind that he has that capability.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
