<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AFTER THE BOOS, GRIFFEY HOMERS FOR THE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The idea that fans would boo Junior would have been
unthinkable before Monday. He was everybody's darling, this
happy-go-lucky kid who always wore a smile, enjoyed himself daily,
joked with people and appeared unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday the Coors Field fans booed Ken Griffey Jr. They
followed immediately by lustily cheering Mark McGwire. The two
All-Stars were on the field receiving awards as the top
vote-getters in their respective leagues, but the fans' starkly
contrasting receptions for them had to do with the home run contest
that would follow an hour or so later.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was enthusiastically participating in the contest that
has become, in some ways, more popular than the game itself.
Griffey had declined to participate. Politely, but he had declined.
</P>
<P>
   So had some of the other top home run hitters of the home
run-dominated 1998 season. Sammy Sosa had excused himself because
of soreness behind his left shoulder _ he missed the Chicago Cubs'
game on Sunday because of it _ but others, such as Juan Gonzalez
and Greg Vaughn, like Griffey, had said no. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This one said he was always sore after the contest and needed a
few days to recover. That one said the contest would mess up his
swing because he wasn't a home run hitter. The focus, though, was
on Griffey, whose 35 home runs are second to McGwire's 37 in the
pursuit of Roger Maris' home run record.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure was on Griffey, too, in the form of the boos that
cascaded into his psyche. At the last minute he changed his mind,
competed in the contest and won it. ``I usually get booed on the
road,'' he said after the contest, ``but in this situation, an
All-Star game, I really didn't like it. They felt they wanted me in
the home run competition so I did it. This is not a time to get
booed, at an All-Star game.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who has been generally viewed as baseball's most
popular player, had talked throughout the day as if he planned to
skip the contest. And he meant it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I flew seven hours to get to a press conference at 9
o'clock,'' he said at a news conference before batting practice,
explaining his decision. ``The home run contest didn't start until
4 o'clock. By 4 o'clock I was worn out. So I said this year I just
can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At yet an earlier news conference, Griffey was asked whether he
preferred playing center field, his position, or left in Tuesday
night's game. ``It doesn't matter where I play,'' he said. ``It's
for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, he was asked later as he sat at his locker, don't you
think the fans want to see you compete with McGwire and the others
in the home run contest? ``That's a little different,'' he said.
``They voted for me to play the game. They didn't ask me to do the
home run competition.''
</P>
<P>
   If fans voted for players to compete in the home run contest, of
course, Griffey would be a big winner there, too. He acknowledged
as much after the contest. ``If they want to see me in the home run
competition,'' he said, ``that's four million reasons why I did it.
For them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the boos, he said, that changed his stance. The record
Coors Field crowd of 51,231 made a difference. So did Frank
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   On the scene as a representative of the commissioner's office,
the Hall of Famer spoke with Griffey half an hour after batting
practice. Robinson told Junior that if he wanted to stick to his
decision not to compete, that was all right, but. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to guys with those type of numbers, those
credentials,'' Griffey said. ``You don't know everything. This is
my 10th year in the big leagues and I'm still learning. If a guy
with those type of numbers relates something to me that's positive,
I've got to listen to him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Griffey had said that he didn't think it was fair of fans or
anyone else to criticize him for his position, but, fair or not,
the Coors Field fans didn't stop with their initial boos. Every
time Griffey stepped into the cage during batting practice, they
booed him. They had cheered McGwire every time he batted and
cheered again when he hit a batting practice pitch into the seats
or to some other distant part of the park.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was asked to explain his outlook on the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it started in '92 when I accepted that I was a home
run hitter in the game,'' he said. ``It was the first year that I
really enjoyed hitting in a home run contest. It turns out it's
probably the most fun thing to do in the All-Star Game. I enjoy it.
Why guys are backing out, I'm sure they all have their own reasons,
but I enjoy it. It's something I do. It's something I've accepted
that I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, a players association official said three weeks ago
that Griffey said he would compete even as he was continuing to say
publicly that he would not. But it took the fans' reaction to
induce the public Griffey to keep the private Griffey's word.
</P>
</TEXT>
