u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-FREEDOM-DRIVE-NY     07-07 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-FREEDOM-DRIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL PROFILING PROTESTED IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUMBULL, Conn. _ Saying the police have often stopped motorists
based on their race, the president of the state chapter of the
NAACP led a ``freedom drive'' protest from Bridgeport to
neighboring Trumbull on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as racial profiling, recently gained
attention in Trumbull after officers said a 1993 memo by Police
Chief Theodore Ambrosini included coded references to racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosini has denied that his department practices racial
profiling, but he has also said he sees nothing wrong with being
aware of ``strangers'' who drive through Trumbull, where blacks
make up about 2 percent of the 32,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The memo said, ``Not only is it our obligation to enforce the
motor vehicle laws, but in doing so, we are provided with a profile
of our community and those who travel within its boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Vann, president of the state and greater New Haven
chapters of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, criticized the 68-member, all-white Trumbull Police
Department at a forum on Monday at Messiah Baptist Church in
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're calling us liars when they deny that profiling exists,
and we won't tolerate it any longer,'' Vann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is black and has driven a car knows all too well
that this is something that continues to happen all across this
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Alvin Penn, a Bridgeport Democrat, told those
gathered at the rally that the Trumbull police stopped him in 1996
and asked him if he knew which town he was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a humiliating and debilitating experience,'' Penn said,
``and we must put an end to allowing people with authority and a
badge being able to stop you, detain you and pull you from your car
under the guise of making a traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a paramount issue that is gaining attention on a state
and national level. But I'm angry, very angry, that this is still
permitted to take place in America in 1998.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
