A3104 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     07-07 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TOOK DETOUR TO TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels had high hopes to start the
season.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they had re-signed Ken Hill and acquired free-agent
Jack McDowell for the starting rotation; had catcher Todd Greene
and second baseman Randy Velarde coming back from injuries, and had
the best young outfield in baseball in Garret Anderson, Jim Edmonds
and Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Well, things didn't go the way they were planned.
</P>
<P>
   Hill and McDowell are on the disabled list, as well as another
starter, Allen Watson. Greene never made it back from the DL and
Velarde has played in two games, with no return in sight. Also, the
outfield hasn't had Salmon since April 22, when he suffered a
partial tear of a ligament in his left foot. He's been limited to
serving as the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   When May ended, the Angels were 27-26 and 5{ games behind Texas
in the American League West and in desperate need of some frontline
pitching to just stay in the AL West race. And they got it, just
not from where they expected it.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Jarrod Washburn was brought up from Triple-A
Vancouver, Omar Olivares was moved into the starting rotation and
Steve Sparks came off the scrap heap to provide the needed shot in
the arm. Washburn, a 23-year-old rookie; Sparks, a 32-year-old
knuckleballer; and Olivares, who turned 31 Monday, have combined
for a 12-5 record and a 3.61 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would have told me in May we'd be in first place at the
All-Star break,'' Collins said, ``I would have laughed at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins might be not be laughing, but he can certainly afford a
smile. The Angels went 22-6 in June, winning more games in any
month in the club's history. At the All-Star break, the team is in
first place with a 49-37 record, 1{ games ahead of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround came suddenly. The Angels had gone 12-15 in May
and seemed to be struggling to keep their heads above water. The
Angels point to a couple games that sparked their resurgence:
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; May 31 at Minnesota. The Angels trailed 5-0 after
four innings but came back to win 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; June 2 at Kansas City. The Angels and Royals
fought several times during a 7-5 Angels win. The fights resulted
in the suspension of manager Terry Collins for eight games during a
crucial part of the schedule. Five players were also suspended.
</P>
<P>
   While the pitching of Washburn, Sparks and Olivares has been
crucial, so too has the steadiness of other players.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also have gotten a typical Chuck Finley (8-4, 3.16
ERA), and enough offense to make any game interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad plays in today's All-Star Game and has been the
Angels' best hitter (.313, 18 homers, 59 RBI). Anderson has gotten
hot after a slow start to post good numbers (.302, 10 homers, 40
RBI).
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds continues to play Gold Glove-caliber center field and is
hitting well (.304, 15 homers, 50 RBI). Despite his injury, Salmon
is a threat at the plate (.265, 15 homers, 43 RBI). Cecil Fielder,
signed to be the DH, has instead filled in at first base and played
well. He's also second on the team with 58 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina's biggest asset to the team is his
defense, and his .313 average is a bonus. Rookie Justin Baughman
has become the club's second baseman and is the team's fastest
player.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have gotten solid work out of the bullpen, none more
so than Troy Percival, who joins Erstad at the All-Star game with a
major-league-leading 25 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things went wrong in the first half,'' general manager
Bill Bavasi said, referring to the injuries. ``But some guys played
pretty well, too. Whether it's injuries or performance, there's a
ledger. It goes well or it doesn't. There are going to be injuries
and guys that don't play well. You've got to hope the other guys
pick them up.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels overcame their first-half problems, they say
they'll need better luck and the same type of performance in the
second half to reach the playoffs for the first time in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose any more pitchers,'' Collins said. ``And we need
guys to do what we expect them to do. This game in the second half
is won by the big guys. And we have some good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Angels went into the break with a season-worst
five-game losing streak, they feel good about their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the big picture,'' DiSarcina said. ``We've
played above everybody's expectations despite all the injuries. If
you sit back and look at the big picture, you have to be proud of
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been in this position before, as recently as
1995, before failing late in the season. But the players who were
there in '95 say they learned from their failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have got to stay mentally strong,'' Percival said.
``We're not the most talented team in baseball, we're not even the
most talented team in the AL West. But we're definitely the
toughest and most resilient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
