A3144 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABALONE-EXTINCTION-SF     07-07 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABALONE-EXTINCTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE ABALONE POISED ON BRINK OF EXTINCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By GLEN MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A once-abundant California mollusk appears
headed the way of the dinosaur, earning the unenviable distinction
of being the only marine invertebrate to face extinction through
human activity.
</P>
<P>
   A planned effort by marine scientists to take white abalone and
induce them to spawn in captivity may be the last chance to save
the species.
</P>
<P>
   White abalone were once plentiful off the coast of Southern
California. Of the eight species of California abalone, the white
abalone lived at the greatest depths _ between 80 and 300 feet.
They were so deep, in fact, that they weren't discovered until
1940. Throughout the 1950s and 1960s, the inhospitableness of their
preferred habitat prevented divers from harvesting them.
</P>
<P>
   But both diving equipment and skills progressed significantly by
the 1970s, allowing commercial divers to exploit white abalone
beds.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a ready market for the tasty marine snails. At
eight inches long, they are somewhat smaller than red abalone, the
most commonly consumed abalone species. But whites are particularly
succulent and are far more tender than reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need to be pounded like reds before they're
cooked,'' said Konstantin Karpov, a senior biologist with the
California Department of Fish and Game's Noyo Marine Laboratory in
Fort Bragg. ``They were considered a truly gourmet species, and
they brought top dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, it seemed that white abalone were as limitless as
buffalo were during the early 19th century. In many areas, the
plump gastropods exceeded densities of one per square yard.
</P>
<P>
   But white abalone resembled the buffalo in more than numbers.
They also shared a similar fate. Like the buffalo, the abalone were
relentlessly hunted until their populations plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell it all. The annual white abalone catch peaked
in 1972 at 65 metric tons. It then fell to less than one metric ton
in 1979. The catch stayed flat until 1995, when the California
Department of Fish and Game banned the harvest of white abalone
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that white abalone will soon be listed as an
endangered species, but that's probably too little, too late,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, we began conducting surveys to determine the state of
the (white abalone) resource,'' said Fish and Game biologist Pete
Haaker, the state's lead scientist on the white abalone problem.
``It was very discouraging. We surveyed 3.06 hectares (about 6.5
acres) of prime white abalone habitat and found only three live
abalone and 119 empty shells. Before that area was exploited, we
would have found about 12,000 abalone.''
</P>
<P>
   While those findings indicate that white abalone are not yet
extinct, the end could come fairly soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply isn't enough density to allow the animals to
successfully reproduce,'' said Haaker, explaining that abalone and
other mollusks propagate by releasing sperm and ova into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, biologists thought that white abalone
would endure because their harvest was subjected to size
restrictions _ divers legally could take only large specimens.
</P>
<P>
   But because white abalone had never been exploited before the
1970s, most were mature, and hence of legal size, when commercial
diving got under way. Vast beds were wiped out before scientists
realized what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, the concept of extinction (through overharvesting)
was foreign to marine fisheries managers,'' said Karpov. ``We used
to think in terms of a surplus population that could be safely
removed, because it would be replaced through the reproduction of
the remaining animals. What we didn't know is that there is a
critical density of animals that you can't fall below, or the
entire population collapses.''
</P>
<P>
   Haaker said that abalone reproduction is a tricky affair in the
best of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a matter of successful spawning,'' he said.
``Abalone are free-swimming when young, and they later settle out
(on rocks). If water conditions aren't optimum, they don't settle
successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many years when water temperatures and currents aren't
ideal, said Haaker, and thus few young abalone are produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the big flaws in earlier abalone management
policies,'' Haaker said. ``It was assumed they reproduced
successfully every year. Now we know they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   A pending diving project may be the white abalone's last hope,
Haaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go down in submersibles (small submarines), mark any
abalone we can find with buoys, then send divers down to recover
them,'' Haaker said. ``We'll probably use special chemicals to
anesthetize and relax the animals so they won't be injured when we
take them off the rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   These last surviving specimens will be taken to a laboratory,
where biologists hope they can be induced to spawn, although white
abalone have not been propagated under artificial conditions, as
red abalone have.
</P>
<P>
   If young abalone are eventually obtained, they can be used to
reseed depopulated habitat, Haaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Haaker said there could be remnant colonies of white abalone in
the ocean off Mexico, but American biologists haven't been able to
secure approval from the Mexican government to conduct a search.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican authorities have made it clear they aren't
interested,'' he said. ``They're still looking at white abalone as
a resource to be exploited, while we're looking at them as an
endangered species to be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the white abalone's fate has not been lost
on biologists, said Karpov.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be too late for the whites, but we're applying what
we've learned to the management of other (abalone) species,'' he
said. ``One important lesson is that abalone stocks are extremely
vulnerable to cumulative impacts _ excessive harvesting combined
with disease and sea otter depredation, for example. Suddenly you
find that the populations have dropped below the point where they
can sustain themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Biologists will need all their acumen, and some luck, to make
sure other abalone species don't follow whites into oblivion.
Black, pink and green abalone also have experienced catastrophic
declines in recent years, and extinction is a definite possibility
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been hit by withering disease, which is caused by a
microorganism that thrives during warm water conditions like El
Nino,'' said Karpov. ``The blacks and greens are particularly
vulnerable. We're very concerned about them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
