<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME TIME TO CONVERT TO A ROTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 47 and have just changed careers and will be in school
until late 1999. I will be working part time _ and maybe less.
Would this be a good time to convert my $50,000 IRA to a Roth? It
consists of $2,000 in Vanguard Specialized Health Care fund and the
rest in Vanguard Wellington. I expect my annual income will be less
than $20,000 a year until I graduate. Upon eventually retiring, I
doubt that my income will be enormous, since my career change is
into the nursing field.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're in a low tax bracket now and will be in a low tax
bracket when you retire, it will make no difference whether you
convert.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I like the idea for several reasons. One is that things
may work out better than you think in retirement. Another is that a
Roth IRA is a lot more flexible than a traditional one, most
notably because owners face no mandatory withdrawal schedules. And
finally, there's the big wild card, which is the question of
whether tax rates in 18 years or so will be similar to today's
rates; if it turns out that they are higher, the conversion will,
in retrospect, seem a very wise move.
</P>
<P>
   But you cannot withdraw the money from the IRAs to pay the taxes
without facing penalties, so you will have to come up with the
money to pay the taxes on the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   If it were stretched out over four years, this could amount to
as little as about $1,800 a year (I'm making some guesses about
your earnings and tax situation here), and that figure is getting
close to 10 percent of your expected total income.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My fiancee and I are planning to buy a house and start a
small family. We have about $80,000 in various growth mutual fund
accounts intended for a down payment. She claims a single-family
house has better resale value than a condo. Is that true? We've
looked at a property listed at $150,000. Our combined income is
$50,000. Is it wise to put the entire $80,000 down? We don't have
any debts and have about $5,000 in checking and savings accounts.
Should we go with a fixed-rate or an adjustable-rate mortgage?
</P>
<P>
   D.C., Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not an expert on real estate, but it seems the general
consensus is that the market for single-family homes is far
stronger than for condos. Further, as the market gets weaker, the
variance in strength between the two tends to become broader. So
all things being equal, I would favor your fiancee's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of making a large down payment are twofold: One,
of course, is the larger the down payment, the smaller the monthly
payments. The other is that you can usually get a better mortgage
rate with a large down payment.
</P>
<P>
   However small, a mortgage will cut into your income stream at
least for a few years, and will increase your expenses for many,
many years. So your current emergency savings, representing 10
percent of your annual income, should be boosted _ at least doubled
and better quadrupled. This would leave you with $65,000 for a down
payment, enough to command a favorable rate.
</P>
<P>
   I favor fixed-rate mortgages, because you can do your financial
planning without worrying that higher rates might increase your
biggest single expense. With the pressures of starting a family,
operating (at least for a time) with a reduced income stream, and
facing the expenses of children, this is not something you want to
worry about.
</P>
<P>
   One final thing, since it seems you are thinking of making your
purchase fairly quickly: Immediately move that $80,000 into money
market funds. Now that you've made your plans, this has become
short-term money, and it should be invested conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
