<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unloved, unhealthy child adopted into the hearts of new parents
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The drive from the orphanage was long
and quiet. She looked out the window. He prayed. Or maybe it was
the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, just to keep their wandering imaginations
in check, they would ask a question of Galina, their translator,
and she would answer, her words and expressions soft and melodious.
And it seemed to new parents Jim and Connie Brown that their whole
world might very well be spinning in a very disorienting slow
motion.
</P>
<P>
   They drove through the country, two-lane roads in the northwest
part of Siberia, away from the old wooden cottages where
who-knows-what had occurred. Away, away, away, as the child in
their arms, the stinking child with the deformed face, screamed and
cried and squirmed.
</P>
<P>
   And while this was the day they'd been wanting, indeed, waiting
for, the one thing they could not do was bring themselves to look
too long at the boy who was now their son.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown hadn't quite known what to expect when they'd agreed
to adopt this unloved child from an orphanage on the northern
fringe of Siberia. At first he was horrified at the idea.
</P>
<P>
   For heaven's sake, they were first-time parents. They wanted a
pink newborn who smelled of baby powder. They wanted someone
healthy, someone who might grow up to look just like one of them!
And now, here they were, a world away from home, driving through
forest after forest of tall trees, thinking about the truth that
faced them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that they told us could be wrong was,'' Jim Brown
says now.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, for it was a five-hour drive back to the
town of Tyumen, Connie Brown would force herself to look at the
little boy born to an unmarried Russian woman. And she supposed he
was beautiful if you could work your eyes past the dirty, gray cast
on his leg and the lone decaying brown tooth and the gnarled
opening, a hole, really, where his upper lip should have been. But
that was part of the reason the Browns has agreed to take in this
child. He had been born with a cleft palate.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Connie had been.
</P>
<P>
   And, so, there were brief moments when Connie was able to
convince herself that maybe this wasn't going to be so bad. Maybe
this was going to be OK, maybe this child was just unloved, not
profoundly mentally retarded. The dear little thing would open his
mouth and out would come the only sound this boy had ever made:
</P>
<P>
   A long, throaty, guttural moan that sounded more animal than
human.
</P>
<P>
   And Connie Brown would turn toward the window so she could watch
the clouds whir by.
</P>
<P>
   After they married in 1984, they half-heartedly tried to start a
family, with no success. Then in 1991 _ after several miscarriages
and several failed trips to the fertility specialist _ they
realized it would probably have to be adoption.
</P>
<P>
   So they contacted an agency, scraped together the money and
filled out their application. She quit her job (long story, but it
was taking her away from the adoption paperwork) and they began The
Long Wait.
</P>
<P>
   All along, the Browns, who met in 1983, figured they'd get a
newborn baby. But on a weekday morning in September 1994, the woman
from the adoption agency called.
</P>
<P>
   We have a child, she said. Connie Brown listened with just a
hint of hope.
</P>
<P>
   He's about 2 years old. So much for cute newborn clothes from
the Gap, thought Connie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He has a cleft palate. Now that's weird, thought Brown, who
herself was born with a bilateral cleft palate and had gone through
dozens of facial surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   He's in Russia, the adoption worker said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was then that Connie Brown called her husband, who of
course had the presence of mind _ or was it just plain old common
sense? _ to say what his wife should have said all along.
</P>
<P>
   Are you nuts?
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, they were.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months and about $30,000 later, Connie and Jim Brown were
leaving the village of Tobol'sk with a boy they named Judah
wriggling in Jim Brown's arms.
</P>
<P>
   When the new family got back to the room they were using in
Tyumen, Connie and Jim Brown had their first good look at their
son.
</P>
<P>
   His head was scabbed with sores that wept down both sides of his
face, from scurvy, they believed, and one of his eyes had gone
crossed from lack of visual stimulation. Even though he was nearly
4 years old, he wore 0-6-month-size shoes and was the size of an
11-month-old baby. The entire right bottom half of his body was
encased in a plaster cast. Judah had broken his right leg about a
month or so before the Browns came to get him.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Connie did when they got back to the room was
fetch her manicure scissors and start cutting. Jim held the child;
she snipped. She snipped and snipped and snipped that hard, dirty,
smelly plaster away until her fingers bled. But, finally, the cast
fell away. And what they saw turned their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   The plaster had been wrapped around Judah's skin so tightly, it
had cut off circulation to his lower body. His genitals were
swollen and blue. His skin was gray, his joints swollen from
rickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first time I really looked at him, Judah was
laying in Jim's arms on the bed. And he was doing this orphan
thing, rocking back and forth, which is not to be described,''
Connie says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just stood there, in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns had been told that Judah, born Anatoli Zhigalov, was
probably about 2 years old; it turned out he was 3 years, 7 months
old when they picked him up May 13, 1995. But he weighed little
more than 22 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Judah could not walk and he could not crawl. But he could sit
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all he ever did, was sit up in his crib,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns believed at first that their son was profoundly
retarded. But slowly _ slowly _ a healthy mind began to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   It was, says Connie Brown, ``the journey of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the things the Browns will never, ever forget about
those early days. They were living in Miami then, but they now live
in West Palm Beach where Jim, 34, works for Wackenhut security.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, even the open outdoors was strange and baffling.
Judah would try to wipe the wind from his cheeks. ``Imagine,'' says
Connie Brown now.
</P>
<P>
   The steady hum of the refrigerator freaked him out. So did the
ring of the telephone and the voices coming from the television.
Judah had been born into an impoverished life, yes. And because of
his facial deformities, he had been deprived of what little love,
food and comfort were available in the Siberian orphanage. But it
was the only home he'd ever known.
</P>
<P>
   He had never seen himself in the mirror, never seen his gnarled
mouth. And when Connie showed him, he looked at his face, then he
looked away. Then he looked at his face, then he looked away.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Connie showed the little boy the inside of the roof of
her mouth, which is still deformed like his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhhh,'' he shrieked, the light bulb going off in his head.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all this, Jim and Connie Brown, deeply devoted
people who believe they were led to Judah by God, also saw in Judah
the very thing the adoption service had told them about.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something inside his eyes that told us there was
somebody in there,'' Connie says.
</P>
<P>
   They just had to find him.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Judah.
</P>
<P>
   He is 6 years old and weighs 46 pounds. He loves to swim, ride a
bike and play with Chopper Dave, the little Army man who's about
the size of a giant bottle of Tylenol and keeps getting lost, then
getting found, then getting lost. Well, you've got the picture.
</P>
<P>
   This was not an easy journey. In those early days, Connie's arms
ached from holding Judah tight as he fought off the comfort of her
love. He did not call her Mother for a year and a half. He's had
three surgeries, all by the same surgeon in Miami who did Connie's
facial surgeries all those years ago. And what a job on Judah.
There's barely a seam.
</P>
<P>
   So proud is Connie Brown about her son that she'll readily tell
you how smart he is: He can read, write, add, subtract, color,
paint, draw, tie his shoes, tell time, fold his clothes, clean his
room _ and sing like an angel.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. The happy ending. The happy boy with the
happy parents. They laugh and sing and pray and pass the time of
day like the most blissful of families.
</P>
<P>
   Except, not too long ago, Connie, 45, made a phone call to the
adoption agency. ``I have always thought that Judah should have
siblings,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, the agency has two children.
</P>
<P>
   Each has a cleft palate. Each is dirty and sick and smelly. Each
is near death at an orphanage in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Browns are undaunted by these truths.
</P>
<P>
   They want to bring these children home. They want to teach them
how to love and laugh. They want to teach them about the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor's Real Life column appears in the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
