<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Tools: Compressed archive files need a ZIP to get going
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every so often someone asks me what to do with a ZIP
file, that is, a file with a .ZIP extension.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sure sign that people are still buying their first
computers without any prior experience, because ZIP files have been
with us about as long as modems, and the current popularity of the
Internet has made them even more prominent.
</P>
<P>
   A ZIP file is an archive file, often consisting of several
different files that have been compressed and packed into a single
file with the .ZIP extension.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of archiving is to make large files into smaller
ones. This can be done for storage purposes, but it is most
commonly done for transmission of binary files over telephone
lines. The amount of space saved depends on the type of files. Text
files are rarely zipped. Graphic files such as .JPG, .GIF, .EPS,
and so forth, are already compressed and little if anything is
gained by zipping them.
</P>
<P>
   There are an amazing number of ZIP programs commercially
available now; ZipMagic from Mijenix is a good one. WinZip is a
common shareware program.
</P>
<P>
   The original programs, and the programs whose code is included
in all these latter-day commercial programs, are PKZIP.EXE and its
counterpart, PKUNZIP.EXE. They were marketed as shareware by PKWARE
Inc. in 1989. Nowadays, as far as I can tell, it's considered
freeware unless you plan to use it commercially. PKZIP, which makes
the ZIP file, and PKUNZIP, which extracts the original files from
it, can be found just about anywhere on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, relatively primitive programs, still stuck in
DOS command line mode, and they take more effort to use than most
folks are willing to put forth. If you have downloaded a .ZIP file,
for instance, and along with it procured PKUNZIP.EXE, you want to
put them both in the same directory to avoid a real hassle. If all
you wish to do is extract the binary files from the archive, you
open a DOS window, go to the proper directory and first type the
name of the program, i.e., PKUNZIP. Then type a space and the name
of the archive file, which might be, for instance, ARCHIV.ZIP.
</P>
<P>
   The program will then pull out all the compacted files into the
same directory. It will do a lot more things, and to find out about
them, you simply type the name of the program without giving it a
file to take apart. It will show a fairly comprehensive list of
switches and commands.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you're going to do a lot of this and you aren't
comfortable typing commands in a DOS window, you might as well get
one of the commercial archiving programs. They all use PKWARE's
basic programs _ WINZIP even requires that PKUNZIP.EXE be available
for some operations _ but they make it easy and intuitive to use
the fancy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers, i.e., those who have been messing with computers for
more than 10 years, will recall that PKWARE once had competition.
Its main adversary was LHARC, made by Haruyasu Yoshizaki and first
distributed in 1988. Its files had the extension .LHZ or LHC.
</P>
<P>
   It had the original advantage of being able to make a
self-extracting file, in other words, an archive file with an .EXE
extension that could be unarchived simply by executing it. That's
now possible with the other programs that unzip files. You still
see LHARC used on program distribution disks occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is more than almost anyone would want to know
about ZIP files and archivers in general, but if I don't explain
things in some detail, I run almost no chance of making a mistake,
thus disappointing many readers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
