<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GRASSHOPPERS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hungry grasshoppers chew up Central Texas
 &HT;    By Jodi Wetuski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Backyard gardens and farmers' fields all over
Central Texas are falling victim to a bumper crop of grasshoppers,
whose tiny jaws are chewing through plants, grasses and even tough
tree bark at a hungry pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In isolated areas in the county, it's a severe situation,''
said Doug Andrews, McLennan County, Texas extension agent. ``I've
gotten many, many calls about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In normal years, a certain type of fungus limits the grasshopper
population by killing a good portion of the eggs, Andrews said. But
this year's dry weather kept that fungus from growing, allowing the
eggs to hatch unchecked, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a swarm of bugs who are not too picky about what
they eat, devouring everything from front-yard flowers to cotton to
peaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll eat grasses, shrubs, leaves,'' Andrews said. ``In some
cases they're even eating the bark off trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hansen, a farmer who lives halfway between Lorena and
Chilton, said he's got a few grasshoppers in his soybeans, but the
drought killed off much of that crop anyway, so he doesn't
anticipate many bug-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said the farmers who have the most difficulties with
grasshoppers are those who have pasture land near their crops. The
insects will come out of the dry grass looking for something to
eat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said he's heard stories from other farmers about
grasshoppers eating the bit of green plant that connects ears of
corn to the stalk, causing the corn to fall to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like anything that's green,'' he said. ``If it's green
they eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials fear the worst is yet to come _ for this season
and for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   John Cooper, a Denton County extension agent, said grasshopper
season won't peak this year for another two weeks. That's when each
square yard of land is expected to be host to about 80 of the
insects, far more than in an average year.
</P>
<P>
   And Kerry Bryan, a plant health director for the U.S. Department
of Agriculture, said more adults hopping around now means more eggs
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Each adult female can lay anywhere from 200 to 400 eggs from now
until early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said the grasshopper explosion has been on a roll for
about three years _ with each year getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's building up to what we had in 1984 _ when we had
thousands and thousands of acres of range land that was being
attacked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During that year, Congress appropriated money for one of the
biggest spray campaigns in grasshopper history.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Bryan said, grasshopper outbreaks have not been as
damaging so lawmakers have stopped funding such domestic
agriculture programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any big outbreaks after '84, '85, '86,'' Bryan
said. ``They thought we weren't using the money.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's time again to deal with the droves of gnawing pests,
Bryan said, before they become an economic danger.
</P>
<P>
   County extension agents said it will be difficult to gauge how
much damage grasshoppers have done on crops because drought losses
have been so severe _ in the billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   As for what can be done about grasshopper infestations, the
answer is, simply, not much. There are several chemical
insecticides approved for homes and gardens. Or people can simply
wait the insects out.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said grasshopper invasions of this magnitude usually
happen every 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cycle,'' he said. ``I don't think it's related to El
Nino or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jodi Wetuski is a staff writer for the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
