<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: As mom scales new heights, son worries
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON A MOUNTAINTOP SIX MILES FROM A PAVED ROAD, N.C. _ ``From the
front porch there'll be a 140-degree view of at least five mountain
ranges and that's with clouds,'' I babble into the cell phone.
``I'm six miles up a gravel road from the nearest pavement, and
there are bears. Isn't that great?''
</P>
<P>
   My son, back in the flatlands of Columbus, Ohio, is not
committing himself to an answer. His silence is ominous, but I'm
too excited to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a mountain cabin with a screened porch on the front
and some bears out back has been my dream for longer than I can
remember. The other is losing weight while gorging on disgusting
quantities of Breyer's butter pecan.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he speaks. ``When I talked with you
</P>
<P>
   day-before-yesterday, you were at home, which, if I may remind
you, is 90 miles north of me, and you had no plans. Now you're
calling from the top of some mountain?'' He sounds a little distant
and a whole lot confused. ``Mom,'' he says rather sternly reminding
me of the way I must have sounded to him when he was small, ``where
are you? Exactly?'' I consult the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``In North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother!'' He's getting serious. It's time to shape up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of in the northwest corner,'' I tell him, then, ``gotta
go
</P>
<P>
   now because the man who owns the top of the mountain wants to
show us a stream out back. I'll call you later.'' I push the cell
phone's ``End'' button and shove it into my back pocket, declaring
myself ready for the trek.
</P>
<P>
   A cool drizzle has drifted onto the mountainside. I turn up my
</P>
<P>
   shirt collar to divert the rain that's trickling down my neck.
Then I
</P>
<P>
   look around. Over there, I'm thinking, that's where the
fireplace will be and all around it will be glass. I picture myself
in front of a
</P>
<P>
   warming fire, all scrunched down in a big chair, watching the
mist slide over the mountains. There'll be coffee on the stove,
cats on the hearth, and peace in my world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch your step here, it's getting a little slick.'' The
warning
</P>
<P>
   brings me back to reality. I should have worn boots. I should
have worn a poncho. Heck, I don't even own a poncho. What do I know
about mountain living?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, here I am, 3,000 feet up the side of a mountain,
</P>
<P>
   slogging through the woods with my Lake Erie-level lungs
protesting the whole way ... and I'm all wet. I hear my friend ask
about wells and septic systems. The answer doesn't interest me. I'm
busy locating things.
</P>
<P>
   The sleeping loft will be up there, I'm thinking as I gaze into
</P>
<P>
   the tops of some lanky pines. Just above the kitchen, facing the
</P>
<P>
   fireplace. I picture myself lying in bed, watching the fire burn
itself
</P>
<P>
   out for the night and then, in the early morning's grayness,
</P>
<P>
   rediscovering the neighboring mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
   That's my dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``...wouldn't want to clear anything more than what's absolutely
necessary,'' I hear my friend say, ``just enough for a view.'' The
man with the mountain agrees. I listen long enough to learn
there'll be a laundry, a garage, and a workshop on the basement
level. That's OK by me. Never did like the idea of living in a
cellar.
</P>
<P>
   But I have other things to think about. I picture a deep bathtub
next to a wall of windows, an island cooktop facing the fireplace;
a hammock on the screened porch; and of course, guest quarters for
kids and grandkids. I can see it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``...and I know you'll love it here.'' It's later that night,
and
</P>
<P>
   true to my word, I have called my son back and am bringing him
up to speed on my day. He, meanwhile, is filling me in on his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put a lot of thought into this today,'' he states in some
</P>
<P>
   newly acquired ponderous voice, ``and I'm concerned. What if you
get sick? What if you get snowed in? What if you run the Bronco off
the road?'' I say it's sweet of him to care but he'll have to skip
the worrying part because I'm going to do it anyway. He sounds
confused _ probably because his weighty tone has failed to
intimidate me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, Babe,'' I explain, ``I'm fearless, and as long as I'm
</P>
<P>
   capable of remembering you as a little boy with poopy pants,
I'll be in charge of my life. I appreciate it, but I'll let you
know when I need help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he agrees, almost too quickly. Then he zings one in on
me. ``Mom, there's no garbage pick-up on mountain tops. Have you
thought about that?''
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
