<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Charge of `Eurocentrism' misses the point about
classical music
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It will disappoint some people to learn that Fats
Waller played Bach.
</P>
<P>
   The great jazz pianist played Bach when he was alone and wanted
to reach, through music, a higher realm of understanding.
</P>
<P>
   This would not surprise Gov. Zell Miller. It is only his critics
who would have trouble explaining it. There have always been
ignoramuses for whom classical music was culturally defined. But
now we find out it is racial as well, something suited to this race
but toxic to that one. Maybe it's in the melanin.
</P>
<P>
   When the governor proposed giving families of Georgia newborns a
classical music recording, he could have anticipated the gibing of
Rush Limbaugh and Jay Leno, know-nothings whose chief function is
to provide wit for the witless. What must have caught him off guard
was being accused of racism.
</P>
<P>
   You never know what land mines await your unwary step. The more
innocent the gesture, the more hurtful its rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   But free-floating hatred is indiscriminate, smearing anyone
within range. Even, sometimes, those whom the hateful would exalt.
Thus when Richard Kenyada of Lithonia wrote a letter to the
Constitution accusing Miller of ``Eurocentrism,'' he did a
disservice to a musician who would disavow him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put (Duke) Ellington up against Mozart any day,'' Kenyada
wrote. ``Once again, black children will be force-fed a European
standard of excellence. It's taken hundreds of years for
African-Americans to overcome the indoctrination of the European
standard of beauty. Just when Americans appear to be on the brink
of accepting diversity, here we go again with another racial
cleansing in the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again is right. It's more racism and more
``Eurocentrism,'' force-fed in the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   It would be uncharitable to take this gentleman seriously,
except that he is representative of a view pandered to at every
turn. Another letter writer, taking issue not only with Miller but
also with Einstein and Galileo, saw no benefit to an early exposure
to classical music. ``My musical tastes have not changed as my
income has increased over the years,'' wrote Yuseff Shabazz of
College Park. ``I was not particularly fond of classical music
before, and I am not fond of it now. Income does not determine
musical taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Income? Miller said nothing about income. He simply said _ as
many others before him have said _ that the brain picks up sound
patterns in its earliest development, even in the womb, and that
the more complex, more sophisticated those patterns, the more
neural connections are made in the brain's circuitry.
</P>
<P>
   It's long been known that learning mathematics, especially, can
be facilitated by the kind of circuit building that listening to
classical music provides. As Miller said, ``Einstein knew it.
Galileo knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Richard Kenyada doesn't, what can one say? But there is
nothing ``Eurocentric'' about it. At a minimum, Kenyada needs to
define that word. And after that he needs to get right with Duke
Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say something like that is insulting to Ellington because
he had the highest regard for classical music,'' says Matt Schudel,
a writer and jazz critic for the Fort Lauderdale (Fla.)
Sun-Sentinel. ``He himself composed classical pieces.'' For what
it's worth, Schudel considers Ellington perhaps the greatest
composer America has produced. He was also a man of strong racial
feelings, but one who never let himself be made into a spokesman
for his race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rose above that,'' Schudel says. ``In his autobiography,
`Music Is My Mistress,' he said, `My people are people who like
music. My people are people all over the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   And neither was Ellington an exception among the great jazz
musicians, so many of whom were black. ``Fats Waller loved to play
J.S. Bach on the piano when he was at home,'' Schudel says. ``And
Art Tatum, who is considered the greatest jazz pianist, worked
classical motifs into his music. Wynton Marsalis is as much a
classical musician as a jazz musician. Miles Davis attended the
Juilliard School of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not only the jazz musicians, but musicians of any artistic
aspiration. Consider the pianist Andre Watts. Or Marian Anderson
and Leontyne Price. ``And,'' Schudel says, ``look at Paul Robeson,
for God's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   If they, too, were ``Euro-centric,'' then we all are. Or we
should wish we were.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube is a lifestyle columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
