<SLUG> BC-TECHREPORT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recording CDs adds twist with audio option
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philips suggests that you dig out those old records, pile up
your compact discs and make yourself the customized sets of music
that you've always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Philips also suggests that a good way to do this is by
purchasing the company's CDR870, the second in the company's line
of CD recorders, which lets consumers make digital recordings from
CDs, vinyl long-playing records and even live music.
</P>
<P>
   The recording of CDs got its start, of course, as a way to
compile huge piles of data that you either couldn't store in your
computer, needed to transfer to another computer or just plumb
wanted to protect from a computer crash. With the Philips machine
and others like it, the whole notion of recording your own CDs
seems to be making a leap into the world of consumer audio.
</P>
<P>
   The recording of straight data continues, but the software has
improved dramatically, making it much easier to record music _ from
digital or analog LPs. In fact, CD recorder drives will probably
soon be built-in features for personal computers. The external
drives are now selling for as little as $300.
</P>
<P>
   The technology now permits, not just customized copying, but the
ability to cut unwanted noise on the original. The Philips machine,
while twice as expensive as the external drive, is built for use as
a music recorder that will be part of the user's stereo system. The
suggested retail price for CDR870 is $649, but an alert observer of
national mail-order houses might find it listed for under $600.
</P>
<P>
   The Philips works with either the CD-R discs that can only be
recorded once or the much more expensive CD-RW format, the
rewriteable discs that can be re-recorded more than 1,000 times.
</P>
<P>
   Recording industry executives snarl if you mention the idea of
passing along the copies at a profit. However, they sigh and
acknowledge that they will accept consumer use of copying
techniques for personal use. But how much work do you want to do to
make a copy? The devices and software are still ``as much labor as
love,'' according to The New York Times. ``The user may need to
spend three or four times as much time as the length of the music
being recorded to make a successful CD. And that does not take into
account planning and learning time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can let someone else make the darned CD. There
are services like Custom Revolutions (http://www.customdisc.com)
that will make a CD for you from their own catalog. The drawback to
that is that their catalog may not match your tastes quite as much
as those hundreds of old records gathering dust in your basement.
</P>
<P>
   Truth and drudgery
</P>
<P>
   It's been a bad time for print.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, print journalists might have self-righteously
turned up their noses at the likes of Matt Drudge, author of the
Drudge Report, which has become one of the Internet's hottest
sites. After Drudge ran several problematic stories about the
Clinton White House, the cheerleaders of print might have sniffed
that rumor-mongering was a poor substitute for real journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But then came June and July. The New Republic admitted that a
writer made up scads of things, including companies he was writing
about. The Boston Globe fired an acclaimed columnist for making up
quotes and the people who supposedly said them. Then last week, The
Cincinnati Enquirer canned a reporter after announcing that he had
stolen voice mail messages that were used in an investigative
series on Chiquita.
</P>
<P>
   We seem to have proven that print is fallible. What about the
Net?
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the big picture, the first issue of Brill's Content
has a voluminous story about press coverage of the Monica Lewinsky
matter. That piece, written by Stephen Brill, is bitterly critical
of print, Net and broadcast, slamming everyone from Drudge to Sam
Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   But tucked away in that same issue of Brill's Content is author
and near-ubiquitous Net guru Esther Dyson. She says the Net is all
about the end of ``the official story,'' the take on events that
was once controlled by authorities in Warsaw, Wall Street and
Washington. ``The guys who talk back to the advertisements, the
dissidents, the disgruntled employees and whistle-blowers, the
cranks and the truth-tellers _ all have found their medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson suggests neither glorification nor vilification of the
Net. Instead, she says that people should exercise their own
quality control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as consumers now expect labels and other information on
the goods they buy, they need to start looking for the same kind of
disclosure on their information,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   No, she doesn't want an official government certification, a
stamp on information. The responsibility lies elsewhere, she says.
``Yes, there is an information market for the truth. But it will
work only if we have educated citizens, demanding disclosure and
able to judge for themselves what is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
