<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN GENERAL MOTORS WORKERS START TO FEEL SQUEEZE OF U.S.
STRIKE
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server by the Austin American-Statesman.
 &HT;    EDs: Silao is about 200 miles northwest of Mexico City.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILAO, Mexico _ People in this obscure town in Mexico are
discovering that the fickle global economy can give, yet suddenly
take away.
</P>
<P>
   The month-long strike of General Motors Corp. workers in the
United States has rolled into Silao, a city of 30,000 in Guanajuato
state that is home to cowboys, corn and vegetable fields -- as well
as a sprawling GM truck-production factory that's become a company
showcase in just six years.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of striking American workers, GM has big
plans for expanding this plant about 200 miles northwest of Mexico
City, along with other GM facilities in Mexico that churn out
pickups, Suburbans, trendy sport-utility vehicles and other autos
mostly for the American market.
</P>
<P>
   But right now a lack of parts from the United States has
rendered the Silao plant of some 2,500 workers mostly idle, and the
quiet that blankets the normally bustling factory signals an
uncertain future for these workers and Mexico's booming auto
industry, considered a key ingredient to the country's economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard something about how workers in the United States
are upset because labor is cheaper here,'' said GM worker Pablo
Lopez Perez, wearing his official ``GM-Mexico'' sports shirt while
hanging around Silao's town square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think there's work enough for everyone,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, there's little work on either side of
the border for GM workers.
</P>
<P>
   A strike that started on June 4 in Flint, Mich., over
subcontracting disputes and other grievances has had a chain
reaction far beyond the two plants involved. More than 161,000 GM
workers across North America are now idled due to lack of work,
some drawing salaries, others not.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Silao's work force has been idled. Plants in
Toluca, near Mexico City, and at a large facility in Coahuila state
near the U.S. border are also facing cutbacks in production.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest hit of the GM plants are many of the 53
auto-parts factories run by Delphi Automotive, a GM subsidiary.
These factories, which produce for other companies as well, have
mushroomed in northern Mexico recently courtesy of Mexico's
domestic investment reforms and the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
   This growth has made GM and Delphi Mexico's largest private
employers, with more than 84,000 employees combined.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Delphi workers are on mandatory summer vacation now. But
before vacations kicked in, Delphi was forced to idle 29,905 of its
72,000 employees. Many still are receiving full salaries that are
sometimes less than $10 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lopez Perez, who makes about $13 a day plus medical
care and housing subsidies, was told to go home along with most of
the other GM workers in Silao. He is receiving 50 percent of his
pay, and worried about how long he and his family of four can last.
</P>
<P>
   So is Silao's mayor, Luis Gerardo Baldovinos, who says the
municipality of Silao is losing 25 to 30 percent of its sales
revenues now because so many workers are laid off and have less
money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Guanajuato state could lose 10 to 15 percent of its sales
revenues, Baldovinos added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't get better, we're going to have to go to the
United States to look for work, even without papers,'' the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't mince words when it came to assessing the GM strike,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hunger for work here,'' Baldovinos said. ``I think
the unions in the United States are very peculiar. They are abusing
the kindness of American policies and making too many demands . . .
I hope that those gentlemen, with all due respect, with stop being
lazy and get back to work so the rest of us can get back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   These are fighting words to American auto workers, who fear a
continuous bleeding of jobs into Mexico, where labor costs are a
fraction what they are in the United States. The United Auto
Workers union has also accused GM of failing to invest in U.S.
factories to keep them sufficiently competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jaime Herrera, who follows the auto industry for
LatinSource of Mexico City, says U.S. auto workers have reason to
be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   GM, he said, has plans to pour 20 percent of a $5 billion
worldwide expansion plan for the next few years into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokesman Joe Jacuzzi said that because GM needs to protect
its competitive edge, he couldn't comment on the company's specific
plans for growth anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Herrera said GM is not alone in its aggressive stance.
Nissan is expanding in Mexico, along with Ford, Volkswagen and
other foreign companies who are taking advantage of the benefits of
NAFTA and Mexico's cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   GM, Delphi and other foreign companies are at the heart of
Mexico's explosion in auto manufacturing, whose output leaped by 30
percent in 1997 to generate more than one-fifth, or $20 billion, of
Mexico's exports.
</P>
<P>
   The GM strike in the United States hasn't stalled business'
optimism for continued growth in Mexico's auto industry. But it has
certainly applied some brakes to newly prosperous communities like
Silao.
</P>
<P>
   Store owners in the town are starting to grumble about fewer
customers. And at least one restaurant, La Bonita, which used to
serve mostly GM workers waiting for company buses, decided it was
more profitable to simply close its doors and wait to see what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
