<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-REBUKE (San Francisco) _ The body that disciplines state
judges has charged Justice J. Anthony Kline of San Francisco with
misconduct in an extraordinary attack that has alarmed the legal
community and raised questions about free speech in the courts.
Kline's alleged offense: flatly contradicting the state Supreme
Court in a written opinion. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-RIGHTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The 150th anniversary of the
Women's Rights Convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y.. will be marked
with four days of events, beginning with a speech on July 16, by
Hillary Rodham Clinton. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-INFLUENCES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The actions and
support of many women in the suffrage and reform movements read
throughout the Northeast like the roots of an ever-strengthening
tree. Here are a few of those influences: If Seneca Falls was a
cradle of reform in 1848, it could be said that an Iroquois hand
was rocking the cradle. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ There's been lots of talk about
investment scams over the Internet. Now there's a new frontier _
bogus bank sites on the Web. Bank regulators have begun surfing the
Net looking for fraudulent Internet bank sites. They're especially
concerned about ones that are likely to be confused with the sites
of legitimate banks that have opened up in cyberspace. By PAMELA
YIP.
</P>
<P>
   RENEWABLE-ENERGY (San Francisco) _ Renewable energy sources were
promoted in two announcements by electrical energy retailers
competing in the state's recently deregulated market. Green
Mountain Energy Resources is selling rooftop solar electric
systems. Enron Energy Services said it has agreed to supply
renewable energy to Patagonia Inc.''s 14 California facilities. By
GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
