named Leonard Slye who was born in Cincinnati but grew up in
Marietta, Ohio. The fact that he was a fellow Ohioan was not lost
on me. Even as a 6-year-old member-in-good-standing of the Roy
Rogers Club, Columbus chapter, I felt we had a special bond. By
CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ After plodding through a
couple of clunkers, it was a real joy to read four terrific books
in a row. First out of the gate is Thomas Perry's outstanding ``The
Face-Changers'' (Random House, $24, 372 pages). By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-COYOTE-REVIEW (Houston) _ Despite a slow start and a few
lapses here and there, actor Peter Coyote's ``Sleeping Where I
Fall'' (Counterpoint, $26) tells of what he saw in the '60s with
skill, honesty and, perhaps most remarkably, a passion only
slightly diminished by the years that have passed since he first
toyed with the thought that the world could be changed for the
better. By MITCHELL J. SHIELDS
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTER-BANKS-SURF (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ As a transplanted
California surfer, I needed to find some East Coast waves. Like,
right here on the Outer Banks of North Carolina. By REX BABIN.
</P>
<P>
   OUTER-BANKS-TOURISM (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ Things to do on Cape
Hatteras when you're not surfing: Shipwrecks and pirates: The Outer
Banks, also known as ``The Graveyard of the Atlantic,'' like a
cemetery, with hundreds of ships that have been buried over several
hundred years along the Banks. By REX BABIN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RESPITE-CARE (Albany, N.Y.) _ An estimated 7 million unpaid
caregivers nationwide find a boon in respite programs. They provide
short-term stays for ailing loved ones and some needed time off for
their families. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LOCKOUT (Albany, N.Y.) _ The longer the NBA lockout lasts,
the better. The players and owners will feel the pain of labor
dispute before fans do. The players and owners should stay in
hiding until they settle their greedy differences. By then, they
might even be able to find somebody who still cares. By STEVE
CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The news coverage of embattled
Florida homeowners and firefighters has been missing those phrases
you hear whenever California burns, shakes or slides: ``Living in a
land of illusions.'' ``Denying ecological reality.'' ``Why do
people live there?'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y) _ Arguments about whether to
educate the children of immigrants in their own language in
America's public schools are an aspect of a glaring reality that is
shaping the future of the country. By HARRY M. ROSENFELD.
</P>
