<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3475 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-07 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILINGUAL EDUCATION MUST FOCUS ON ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY M. ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Arguments about whether to educate the children
of immigrants in their own language in America's public schools are
an aspect of a glaring reality that is shaping the future of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   California, the state with the greatest number of immigrants,
may have voted recently to scale back bilingual instruction to one
year, but the fact remains that 1 in 10 of everyone in this country
was not born here, a trend that is expected to hold at least steady
in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, bilingual education is merely a part of the larger
issue of how best to absorb the multitude of newcomers, which in
this decade will exceed the numbers that entered this country
during this century's first 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the largest group of immigrants in our own time comes
from Latin America, with substantial numbers from Asia and the
Caribbean, and comparatively fewer from Europe, the primary source
of the earlier immigrations.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, the reason for their coming is to improve the
quality of their lives, just as the reason for their being welcomed
is that they power the nation's economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, bilingual instruction was adopted by the
educational establishment. It made sense, on the face of it.
Anything that would help turn the children of immigrants into
English-speakers would facilitate their becoming, in due course,
fully participating citizens of this nation.
</P>
<P>
   But what appeared to be happening, to those critics of
bilingualism who were not merely expressing traditional nativist
reaction to the newcomers, was that instead of helping the kids to
learn English quickly, too many bilingual programs were focusing on
providing continuing, open-ended instruction in the native tongues.
</P>
<P>
   What the nonideological critics saw happening was the de facto
establishment of schooling in a foreign language (usually Spanish)
underwritten by the American taxpayer. Hispanic parents in large
numbers also began to object because they saw that their kids, far
from learning the English they were supposed to in these bilingual
programs, were coming out of school unequipped with the language
skills needed for them to make it in America.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the distortion of what essentially is a practical
idea is that an administrative bureaucracy had found a good thing
in bilingualism and wanted to expand it with ever more bountiful
government stipends. Moreover, with the growth of identity
politics, it was a way to have public money to help sustain the
ethnic separateness of the immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   It was my good luck to arrive in the United States as an
immigrant boy nearly 60 years ago. At the time, there was no
thought of bilingual instruction. Within four months after stepping
off the gangplank, equipped only with the English I had managed to
scrounge up on the playground, I found myself as a 10-year-old in
the second grade. It was the only time in my life I was the tallest
boy in the class.
</P>
<P>
   Attentive teachers monitored my progress and moved me up as my
English improved. I never totally caught up and graduated from high
school as an 18-year-old, when most of my classmates were a year
younger.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, and cognizant of the presumption of arguing
from personal experience to a general principle, it is clear that
kids up to a certain age are capable of learning English quickly by
themselves. But there should be no objection to a program, of short
duration, that would help accelerate the learning.
</P>
<P>
   Bilingual education, however, would appear to be more essential
for older kids, upon whom scholastic demands fall heavily.
Bilingual education would seem to be a practical way to help them
keep up with their schoolwork as they gain English proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But the stress in bilingual education should be on the learning
of English, so the students could become totally integrated with
their peers. Such education deserves public support and
understanding. The beneficiaries are not only the people who
thereby are helped to live and work in their new country; it helps
just as much the country, which benefits from their coming into the
linguistic mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   But these programs need constant monitoring to make sure they
are not misused to become the means by which immigrant children are
effectively isolated for the sake of enhancing ethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the business of government. Rather, that is for the
immigrant families to do for themselves, through whatever community
groups they wish to establish and fund.
</P>
<P>
   The great motto of this successful republic, built from the
ground up by the sweat labor of generations of immigrants, is ``E
pluribus unum'' _ one out of many.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry M. Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times
Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
