<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TIMES EVERYWHERE BUT CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Almost half a million acres of Florida have
burned in the last week, and the news coverage of embattled
homeowners and firefighters has been very familiar to Californians.
We feel a gut sympathy for Floridians in peril.
</P>
<P>
   One thing has been missing, though. I'm still waiting to hear
those phrases you hear whenever California burns, shakes or slides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in a land of illusions.'' ``Denying ecological
reality.'' ``Why do people live there?''
</P>
<P>
   Those phrases all apply to people living in developments in the
Florida woods, but when disaster hits them, the media and ordinary
folk refrain from lectures, smirks and comparisons to Biblical
plagues.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend puts it, ``When it happens somewhere else, it's hard
times. When it happens in California, we're getting our just
deserts.''
</P>
<P>
   As is so often pointed out, this state is largely just desert,
and we shouldn't be living here _ or at least not so many of us.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is largely swamp turned into subdivisions by greed, air
conditioning, bulldozers and chemicals. People _ or at least so
many of them _ shouldn't be living there either.
</P>
<P>
   But when Florida burns or is blown away by hurricanes, you won't
hear anyone say Floridians brought it on themselves, the way
Californians deserve fire, earthquakes and mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, swamps burn. It's part of nature, especially when
nature gives Florida the dry end of El Nino, another phenomenon
seen as part of God's wrath on California.
</P>
<P>
   California occupies a special, overdeveloped place in the
national imagination. Florida, for most Americans, is a great place
to visit a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   When Malibu, Calif., burns, it's a vision of celebrity hell.
When Mims, Fla., burns, it's just another disaster story.
</P>
<P>
   Here's wishing all of those good people luck with their
insurance companies _ the real plague upon all of us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is America, and people have been shot over poker hands,
sheep grazing and gang signs, but over a Tweety Bird?
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, eight people were shot and wounded at
the Alameda County (Calif.) Fair because of an argument over who
got the last giant stuffed Tweety Bird at a carnival booth.
</P>
<P>
   You can see how the Tweety Bird shootings would come down. He or
she is a damned cute big-headed yellow descendant of dinosaurs. In
the argument over Tweety someone got disrespected, punches were
thrown and a gun was drawn. What's the point of carrying a gun if
you don't draw it? And then use it?
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain logic to random acts of American violence, as
any middle-class American who has ever felt road rage will attest.
Dumb leads to dumber and misdemeanors lead to felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Funny what a difference an ocean makes. Anyone who has fought
for a lane in a car has to admit he can understand why people get
shot over a Tweety Bird. But despite our Klan history, very few
people in this country understand why men in Belfast get dressed up
and march through someone else's neighborhood to tick them off and
cause riots.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just because they've been doing it for centuries. And they
wear bowler hats, too, and sashes showing their allegiance to the
British crown, which would like nothing better than to keep them
from marching and burning their neighbors' churches.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes non-random violence is stranger than Tweety Bird
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
