<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT: WHO CARES? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the end, only three things of substance
separate man and woman from beast:
</P>
<P>
   _ An ability to bathe without an over-reliance on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   _ A full appreciation for the way the Spice Girls, Kenny G,
Sinbad, Bobcat Goldthwaite, Howie Mandel, Urkel and Gallagher make
the world a better place to live.
</P>
<P>
   _ A need for a rooting interest in the outcome of sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
   A crocodile doesn't care if it's the slob with the ``I'm With
Stupid'' T-shirt or the slug with the ``Mama'' tattoo who jumps
into the river for a swim. A crocodile just wants somebody hit and
take the plunge. People _ being at the top of the evolutionary
scale, perhaps because they invented the scale _ need to make
emotional connections.
</P>
<P>
   People need to root for or against somebody. People need to
stand for or against something. People need to love or hate, for
better or worse, for good reasons or bad. On blessed occasions,
along comes somebody like Howard Cosell for people to unashamedly
love or hate.
</P>
<P>
   Passions run particularly high when it comes to matters of
national loyalty, like in the Olympics or the World Cup.
(Americans, for their part, appear to be above great partisanship
when it comes to the World Cup. This might have something to do
with the fact that it's easier to find a sportswriter who doesn't
have mustard stains on his shirt than it is an American who knows
what sport the World Cup involves. As far as most American men are
concerned, the World Cup is the greatest hope yet of ensuring that
they will never become falsettos against their will.)
</P>
<P>
   The point is, people aren't going to get involved in something
unless they have a reason _ whimsical as it may be _ to care. One
way or another. It can be for as simple a reason as hating a team's
uniforms (See: the heretofore dignified Los Angeles Dodgers, who
have fallen under the evil influence of Fox and now wear slow-pitch
softball blue jerseys).
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when the resistible force meets the contemptible
object? What happens when the National Basketball Association
owners and players draw a line in the sand that could eliminate a
sizable chunk of next season? What happens when greedy owners and
equally greedy players try to pass on their labor pains to
long-suffering fans?
</P>
<P>
   The owners began what has the makings of a long, bitter dispute
last week by locking their doors to the players. Under the terms of
a lockout, teams cannot have contact with players, conduct contract
negotiations or run summer camps. Players cannot use team
facilities. Oh, and players don't get paid.
</P>
<P>
   Though three years remain in the current labor agreement, the
owners are within their rights to shut down operations. A clause in
the current labor agreement allows owners to re-open discussions if
more than 51.8 percent of the league's basketball-related income
goes to player salaries. Players took in 57 percent of that income
this past season, with no end to the escalation in sight. Even
Hollywood is smarter about the way it does business.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Titanic'' had been made with 57 percent of the money going
to the cast, James Cameron would have had to do the filming on the
S.S. Minnow. At the center of the NBA labor dispute is the Larry
Bird exception to the salary cap. Life is too short to get immersed
in the minutiae of the Bird exception. Suffice to say, the Bird
exception allows teams to re-sign their free agents without regard
to the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Bird exception, 24 of 29 teams exceeded the NBA
salary cap of $26.9 million. The Bulls managed to sign Michael
Jordan to a $33.1 million contract last season when they were
already over the salary cap. Kevin Garnett and _ gulp _ Alonzo
Mourning became $100 million players.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, in other words, see the salary cap as a dunce cap.
Still, it's hard to feel anything but contempt for the owners when
Jerry Reinsdorf _ one of the hard-liners during the baseball strike
that wiped out the 1994 World Series _ is among their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   For an idea of how NBA owners do business, consider the New York
Knicks. Despite the lockout, the Knicks are demanding full payment
up front for 1998-98 season tickets. That would be the same Knicks
ownership that has raised ticket prices for courtside seats from
$500 apiece to $1,350 in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a players' union that serves as apologist and enabler
for the likes of Latrell Sprewell, Isaiah Rider and Chris Webber
inspires anything but contempt. The union stance is that owners
don't have to pay the exorbitant player salaries. Right. All a team
has to do is make a stand, and fans will understand. And if the
owners all agreed to hold the line on salaries, especially those of
free agents, they'd get taken to court for collusion faster than
you can say Donald Fehr.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't good for the league when Garnett can turn up his nose
at a $103 million offer from the Minnesota Timberwolves when he
hasn't even been in the league three years. Garnett eventually
deigned to stay with the Timberwolves for $121 million over six
years, then said it wasn't about the money.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, the players only seem interested in being business
partners with the owners when it comes to reaping the benefits.
When it comes to doing something that is in the best interest of
the league as a whole, they say it's the owners' problem. ``We're
strong,'' said Knicks center Patrick Ewing, now the president of
the Players Association. ``We believe in what we're doing. We're
fighting for our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing speaks, you can hardly even see the lips of agent
David Falk move. Ewing spent the first decade of his career
collecting his money, doing nothing off the court to promote the
league. And then, when the prospect of the $18 million balloon
payments began drying up, he turns into Samuel Gompers.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing soaring faster than NBA ticket prices is the
mediocrity of the product.
</P>
<P>
   I say the longer the lockout lasts, the better. I say the
players and owners will feel the pain of labor dispute before fans
do. I say the players and owners should stay in hiding until they
settle their greedy differences. By then, they might even be able
to find somebody who still cares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
