<SLUG> BC-RESPITE-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESPITE STAYS CAN OFFER BREAK FOR LOVED ONES AND THEIR CAREGIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A month shy of 101 years, Augusta Boyd needs some
looking after. A nursing home is out of the question, said Dennis
Tillman, her godson. He and his girlfriend would rather take care
of Boyd at their home.
</P>
<P>
   But they need a break sometimes. So recently, the truck driver
took Boyd to the Ann Lee Home for a respite stay during his
weeklong vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She showed me a lot of love in raising me, and I'm just
showing my love in return,'' Tillman, 38, said of his decision to
care for Boyd at home. ``That's what being a family is all about _
taking care of your own, not putting them in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But respite care comes in handy. I don't know how I would do
it all without it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tillman and an estimated 7 million other unpaid caregivers
nationwide, respite programs are a boon. They provide short-term
stays for ailing loved ones and some needed time off for their
families.
</P>
<P>
   As the vacation season heats up, beds for respite care are in
greatest demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to let the caregiver get some time away,'' said
Marty Haase, executive director of the Caregivers Respite Program
of Catholic Charities in Albany. ``They'll get into the role of
caring for their loved ones and forget about caring for themselves.
The caregivers can get seriously ill, and then you've got two
people who need medical attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But just like making a reservation for a room at a popular
hotel, Haase said, ``You've got to get it before it gets booked.''
</P>
<P>
   With more people living longer, the fastest-growing age group
nationally is 85 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Respite care is not just for people who live with the elderly.
Those who look after disabled relatives need that break, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the Center for the Disabled in Albany, the overnight respite
program is booked through August, said Joseph M. MacBeth, director
of the special education program. The center has 10 respite beds on
weekends for people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The program is funded with an annual state grant, which has
remained at $215,000 for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could double that, we could run 20 beds _ there's a
really high need,'' he said. ``There's not a lot of respite options
out there, and some families don't know it exists at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Caring for loved ones at home costs far less than nursing
facilities, which makes respite programs even more attractive.
Regular respite care can be as low as $50 per day. If medical care
is required, respite costs may run as high as $200 a day. Some
programs accept Medicaid. Compared to nursing homes and live-in
nursing care _ which can charge $60,000 a year _ respite can be a
real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers recommend that caregivers take advantage of
respite care even when they're not going out of town. Barbara
Wazny, a referral specialist with Senior Services of Albany, said
sometimes a single day off really makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of hard work and dedication _ it really builds
on you,'' Wazny said. ``People don't realize how important it is to
take a day off, or take a vacation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
