<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTH-FACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH FACE GAINS STAKE IN ITALIAN COMPANY, PLANS MOVE TO COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The North Face Inc., the sportswear company that
has made a name for itself selling serious mountaineering gear, has
acquired the majority stake in an Italian outdoor footwear company
and is moving the bulk of its headquarters to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the purchase, San Leandro, Calif.-based North Face
agreed to pay $6.6 million plus 20 percent in interest immediately
and another 31 percent over the next two to five years to gain a 51
percent share of La Sportiva S.r.L. of Ziano de Fiemme, Italy. To
obtain the company's U.S. distribution rights, North Face will
spend $3 million for independently owned La Sportiva, USA, the
Italian company's American spinoff, based in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   North Face said it will maintain its financial operations in San
Leandro, but move the rest of the business to Carbondale, Colo., to
save money.
</P>
<P>
   While the move and the newly purchased company both have
Colorado connections, North Face and analysts say they are
unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcements by North Face were the latest in a series
of changes for the 33-year-old company, which in May named James
Fifield chief executive, replacing William Simon, who is now
serving as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Fifield) came in and said he was going to shake things up
and he's done that,'' said Shawn Milne, a research analyst for
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco. ``There's an opportunity for
North Face to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Milne approved of the acquisition of La Sportiva, which makes
specialized, high-end footwear for such activities as rock climbing
and mountaineering. ``These are very technical products that would
have taken North Face several years to develop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The timing also appears to coincide nicely with the announcement
in June of North Face's own brand of running foot gear. North Face
will start shipping its brand-name footwear in the fall and will
co-brand the La Sportiva label, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   North Face, which moved to San Leandro from Berkeley in 1995,
will shift its marketing, research and top executives to Colorado
next month.
</P>
<P>
   James Reilly, the company's chief operating officer, said 70
employees would move from San Leandro to a leased property in
Carbondale in August, where added staff will bring the total number
of employees to 90 or 95. Carbondale is about a half-hour drive
from Aspen, where Fifield owns a house.
</P>
<P>
   About 175 employees will remain in San Leandro, even after the
company builds a new corporate headquarters on 36 acres it is
negotiating to buy in Carbondale. The newly built headquarters is
expected to open by late 1999 or the spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Face is making important strategic decisions in order to
grow our business and reduce costs,'' Fifield said in a statement
Monday. ``Our current corporate facility cannot accommodate our
future growth plans and attract talented executives in a
cost-effective manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction to Colorado is the mountainous terrain, which
is expected to be a testing ground for the company's equipment.
Nike Inc.'s ACG (All Conditions Gear) product line and
Adidas-Salomon AG have product testing centers in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   North Face stock trades on the Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1227EDT &QL; 
