<SLUG> BC-RENEWABLE-ENERGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER COMPANIES OFFERING ALTERNATIVE ENERGY IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two energy retailers competing in California's
recently deregulated electricity market have announced they will
provide solar and other renewable energy sources for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Green Mountain Energy Resources said Monday it had begun sales
of rooftop solar electric systems for homeowners. The photovoltaic
(PV) cells, producing electricity directly from the sun, will allow
customers to produce from 20 percent to 50 percent of their own
electricity, according to South Burlington, Vt.-based Green
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   And Enron Energy Services, a subsidiary of Houston-based energy
provider Enron Corp. said Monday it would provide renewable energy
for Patagonia Inc., the Ventura, Calif.-based outdoor clothing
company.
</P>
<P>
   Green Mountain entered into an agreement with Applied Power
Corp., based in Olympia, Wash., to design and install rooftop
systems, the two companies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The PV systems cost from $4,750 to $7,450, depending upon
installation costs. However, rebates are available through the
California Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, California permits ``net metering,'' which provides
that electricity generated by homeowners can be sold at retail rate
back to a utility and becomes an earned credit on an electricity
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue that while the initial cost for a PV
system is expensive, it can pay for itself over time. Moreover,
Julie Blunden, who directs marketing efforts in California for
Green Mountain, said consumers have demonstrated a willingness to
pay premiums for renewable sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price is not the only factor customers consider. Our
lowest-priced power product is our least popular,'' she said.
``People want to buy cleaner electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Patagonia, meanwhile, becomes one of the first businesses in
California to commit to 100 percent wind energy.
</P>
<P>
   Enron plans to construct a 16-megawatt wind-power facility near
Palm Springs. Until the plant is complete in early 1999, Enron
Energy Services will supply all of Patagonia's electricity needs _
approximately one million kilowatt hours annually _ from a mix of
renewable sources in California. Once the new plant begins
commercial operations, Patagonia's power will be provided by Enron
Wind Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
