<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERI     07-07 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR GREAT BOOKS FOR A THRILLING READ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After plodding through a couple of clunkers, it was a real joy
to read four terrific books in a row.
</P>
<P>
   First out of the gate is Thomas Perry's outstanding ``The
Face-Changers'' (Random House, $24, 372 pages).
</P>
<P>
   For years, Jane Whitefield, a member of the Seneca tribe, has
been a guide who has helped people in trouble disappear. But
following her wedding to Dr. Carey McKinnon, she has promised to
retire from her very dangerous career.
</P>
<P>
   Whitefield settles into married life. Then, one night, McKinnon
asks her to come to the hospital and introduces her to his surgical
mentor, Dr. Richard Dahlman, who has been wounded trying to resist
arrest for the alleged murder of his partner. McKinnon believes
Dahlman is innocent and asks Whitefield to help Dahlman escape the
police and guide him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   But as Whitefield and Dahlman flee the hospital, Whitefield
spots two men who can only be professional assassins. And now
Whitefield knows their flight will not only be from the police but
also the assassins and the people who hired them.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlman's story is simple. In his 60s, he pretty much quit
performing operations to concentrate on pure research. He set up a
clinic with a female colleague. To finance Dahlman's work, his
partner, Dr. Sarah Hoffman, accepts an offer of $500,000 to give a
man a new face. After his release from the clinic, three of the
clinic's staff take new jobs in different parts of the country.
Then Hoffman is murdered and Dahlman gets framed. Eventually,
Whitefield learns that the other clinic staffers all died under
mysterious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Whitefield moves Dahlman across the country, always just
a few steps ahead of the hit squad and the FBI. And the only way to
ensure Dahlman's safety is to create a new identity for him and
find a place to stash him while she tracks down the man with the
new face and finds out who he hired to erase his past and all the
people who knew of his plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   To her horror, she will learn that the ``face-changers'' are
using her name and identity to ``destroy lives, not save them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Whitefield, Perry has created one of the smartest and most
engaging female characters in the thriller genre. His plot, as
always, is truly creative and will keep you guessing. The only
thing the reader knows for sure is that somehow Whitefield will
eventually win out. Perry just keeps getting better with each new
Whitefield saga.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Point of Origin.'' By Patricia Cornwell. G.P. Putnam's Sons.
$25.95. 356 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell's ninth forensic thriller featuring Dr. Kay Scarpetta,
Virginia's chief medical examiner, is the best yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's been five years since psychopathic killer Carrie Grethen
was incarcerated in a psychiatric center. Suddenly, Scarpetta gets
a rambling note from Carrie, who indicates she is not done with
causing mayhem for Scarpetta and those she loves _ her niece Lucy,
Carrie's former lover; and Scarpetta's lover, Benton Wesley, former
head of the FBI's profiling unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to leave for a week's vacation with Wesley, Scarpetta and
Richmond Police Capt. Peter Marino are summoned to a horrible fire
scene by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. The fire
destroyed the rural estate of media tycoon Kenneth Sparkes.
Nineteen horses died in the stable fire, and Scarpetta and the ATF
team fear a body found in the destroyed house might be Sparkes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Scarpetta's autopsy finds the victim was a woman who
had been mutilated. Meanwhile, the FBI calls Wesley in as a
consultant when Carrie escapes from the psychiatric center.
Everyone knows that Scarpetta, Wesley and Lucy are all in grave
danger. At the same time, more mutilated bodies are found at fire
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point of Origin'' moves with breathtaking, tension-building
pace. Cornwell instills more raw emotion in her well-developed
characters than in her previous works. And her villains are as
heinous as any that Stephen King has created. This thriller is
worth every penny of its $25.95 price.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Full Dress Gray.'' By Lucian Truscott. William Morrow &AMP; Co.
$25. 400 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott's military thrillers always ring true, and ``Full Dress
Gray'' is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Cadet Ry Slaight caused a scandal at West
Point when he proved that a fellow cadet had been murdered by his
gay lover.
</P>
<P>
   Now Slaight is back at West Point, having been promoted to
lieutenant general and named the academy's superintendent. The day
after Labor Day, the full cadet corps passes in review to welcome
Slaight. Four cadets pass out in the heat, and one, 1st-Class Cadet
Dorothy Hamner, dies. The autopsy is inconclusive on the cause of
death, but it does reveal that Hamner had sex with multiple
partners the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The many-pronged investigation must uncover whether it was a
gang rape or a cadet orgy. Slaight locks horns with Brig. Gen. Jack
Gibson, the commandant of cadets, who is having an affair with
another officer's wife and has joined forces with a powerful
senator who wants to close down West Point.
</P>
<P>
   Slaight's daughter, Jacey, was Hamner's company commander.
Slowly she learns about the party Hamner attended the night before
she died, who was at the party, and eventually she is convinced
that Hamner was murdered. All the male cadets at the party are
members of West Point's Honor Committee, and Jacey's probe points
to their misusing their power. Eventually, she is kidnapped and
severely beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Slaight's mandate is to bring Hamner's murderer or murderers to
justice and save the academy and his daughter from powerful forces
within and without the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott, who attended West Point, has created some very
complex, honorable characters, along with some really awful human
beings. The plot is realistic enough to be on tomorrow's front
page. The dialogue is believable and up to date, while the pace
moves briskly. Once again, Truscott delivers a first-rate thriller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sisterhood of Spies _ The Women of the OSS.'' By Elizabeth P.
McIntosh. Naval Institute Press. $29.95. 256 pages.
</P>
<P>
   This is a wonderful addition to any World War II collection.
</P>
<P>
   Little has been written on the women who worked for the Office
of Strategic Services, the predecessor to the Central Intelligence
Agency. The author, who joined the OSS in 1943 and worked in Burma
and China, thankfully has righted that omission.
</P>
<P>
   Some were spies, like the elegant Virginia Hall. Before she
joined the OSS, she worked for the British Special Operations
Executive. Twice Hall, known as The Limping Lady, set up spy
networks in occupied France, and eventually her cover was blown.
The Gestapo so feared Hall that they issued this order: ``The lady
who limps is one of the most dangerous Allied agents in France. We
must find and destroy her.''
</P>
<P>
   When she switched to the OSS in 1944, her handlers were fearful
of sending her back to France, but twice she parachuted into France
and worked with the Resistance in getting downed Allied aviators to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Others had less glamorous but equally important jobs _
cryptographers, cartographers, analysts, recruiters of double
agents, propaganda experts and so on. Some were famous, like the
actress Marlene Dietrich. Others, like Julia Child, would become
famous in other careers after the war. All were courageous. Most
survived, but some did not.
</P>
<P>
   When McIntosh writes about individuals, the book sings.
``Sisterhood of Spies'' is a belated, but welcome, tribute to the
women who worked for Maj. Gen. William ``Wild Bill'' Donovan's OSS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
