<SLUG> BC-APSEN'S-SUMMER-FESTIVITIES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN ASPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JAMES BROOKE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Coloradans sometimes feel they need a visa to visit Aspen. But,
behind the intimidating buzz of celebrities and high prices, Aspen
is a magical town where the beauty of the Elk Mountains combines
with an ever more stimulating cultural life.
 &HT;    Long known for winter sports, Aspen now reports its highest
hotel occupancies in August. Highlighting its increasingly cerebral
image, a survey by the Aspen Chamber Resort Association of last
summer's visitors found that half came for cultural events and only
one-fifth for outdoor recreation.
 &HT;    The survey also found that the average household income of
visitors was $131,000. But with almost two hotel beds (9,200) for
each of its 5,600 residents, it is possible to manage a stay on a
moderate budget.
 &HT;    A key to enjoying Aspen, an eminently walkable town, is to leave
your car behind. Parking is rare and expensive. Visitors who arrive
by air can take a van to town _ free from Aspen's airport, or $81
from Denver's airport, four hours away. Visitors arriving by car
can park free at the Aspen airport and take the 15-minute bus ride
into town.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    The largest cultural draw of the summer is the Aspen Music
Festival, a miniature Tanglewood that draws as many as 1,700 people
to concerts under a blue-and-white tent set up across from Harris
Concert Hall, with seating inside and, free, on the lawn.
 &HT;    The festival began June 18 with the Starling Chamber Orchestra
performing Britten and Puccini, and will finish Aug. 16 with a
Prokofiev performance by the Aspen Festival Orchestra conducted by
James DePriest. Tickets are $8 to $50. Information: (970) 925-3254.
Tickets: (970) 925-9042.
 &HT;    Saturday afternoons until Aug. 15 there is a free festival
concert atop Aspen Mountain. Gondola tickets, $18, are required.
 &HT;    In July and early August, the students of the festival's school
also perform at the Wheeler Opera House, a beautifully restored
1889 building. This season's offerings include Mark-Anthony
Turnage's ``Greek'' (July 23 and 25) and Carlisle Floyd's
``Susannah'' (Aug. 4, 5, 7 and 8). Tickets, $17 (for ``Greek''),
$24 and $48; (970) 925-9042.
 &HT;    The opera house has also inherited events from Dance Aspen,
which went bankrupt last winter. A series of engagements July 22
through Aug. 15 features the Paul Taylor Dance Company, Les Ballets
Jazz de Montreal, the Parsons Dance Company and Ballet West.
Tickets are $15 to $48 from (970) 920-5770.
 &HT;    Aspen Theater in the Park will offer a full summer season in its
white tent in Rio Grande Park. The season, June 28 to Aug. 29,
rotates ``Forever Plaid'' by Stuart Ross, Neil Simon's ``Jake's
Women,'' ``The Nerd'' by Larry Shue and a children's show, ``The
Magician's Nephew.'' Tickets, $25 and $30 ($7 for ``Magician'') are
sold through the Wheeler, (970) 920-5770.
 &HT;    This week, Snowmass, Aspen's modern sister city, holds Janus
Jazz Aspen at Snowmass, a distinguished small festival, in its town
park, with tent and lawn seating for 5,500. Appearing Thursday to
Sunday is a lineup including Wynton Marsalis, the Headhunters with
Herbie Hancock, B.B. King, and Earth, Wind and Fire. Tickets: $20
to $100 from the Wheeler, (970) 920-5770.
 &HT;    The Aspen Institute, the nonprofit educational organization,
offers free lectures at 6:30 p.m. on Tuesdays in July and August at
Paepcke Auditorium on its campus. Speakers include the playwright
Wendy Wasserstein, July 28, and Murray Gell-Man, Nobel Prize winner
in physics, Aug. 18; (970) 925-7010.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    In Aspen, the mountains are accessible to all _ on an easygoing
gondola ride to the 11,212-foot-high summit of Aspen Mountain, a
moderately challenging bicycle ride down a secluded path, or a
crashing raft ride down the Roaring Fork River.
 &HT;    On busy summer weekends, the Silver Queen Gondola carries 2,000
people a day to the summit. It runs daily 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. At the
top, there are free, 45-minute guided nature walks daily, on the
hour from 11 a.m. to 3 p.m., until Sept. 7.
 &HT;    The Sundeck restaurant is open for lunch every day, and for
dinner on Monday (Mexican) and Wednesday (barbecue), when the
gondola runs till 7:30. Gondola prices range from free for children
6 and under to $18 for adults on weekends. Dinner and gondola
combination is $8 to $25. For information, call (800) 525-6200.
 &HT;    Bicycle paths abound in Aspen. My family and I rented bikes at
Aspen Velo, one of at least nine bicycle renters in town. We rode
down a riverfront path to Woody Creek Tavern, about six and a half
miles one way. A four-hour rental is $22, helmet included; (888)
925-1495.
 &HT;    Hiking is another popular activity. A favorite route is the
two-mile Maroon Lake Scenic Trail, which is accessible by bus from
the Rubey Park transportation center in town. Information: Aspen
Chamber of Commerce, (970) 925-1940.
 &HT;    Rafting on the area's rivers is a fast-growing recreation sport.
Among the rafting companies in the area are Inland Drifters, (970)
963-7438, which charges $45 a person a half day or $75 for a full
day, and runs class 1 through class 4 rapids (6 is the most
difficult), and Blazing Adventures, (800) 282-7238, which charges
$65 to $78 for class 1 through 5.
 &HT;    Children enjoy exploring Ashcroft, a semirestored ghost town on
Castle Creek Road, 30 minutes from downtown. The Aspen Historical
Society gives free tours at 11 a.m., 1 and 3 p.m. every day but
Monday.
 &HT;    On rainy days, tours of Aspen's two silver mines, Smuggler and
Compromise, offer instructive insights into the city's origins (but
children must be 5 or older).
 &HT;    At Smuggler, visitors walk a quarter-mile into a mountain that,
in 1894, provided the world's largest silver nugget: 1,840 pounds.
Admission is $20, $15 ages 5 to 12. The Compromise tour, offered
only on Saturday after July 11, involves a Jeep ride to the mine,
then a rail ride into Aspen mountain. Fee: $30 and $20.
Reservations required: (970) 925-2049.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Among Aspen's several luxury hotels, two Victorian red-brick
standouts are on Main Street, the Jerome at 330 East Main, and the
Sardy House at 128 East Main.
 &HT;    Built in 1889, at the height of the silver boom, the Jerome
boasted the first elevator west of the Mississippi. Painstakingly
restored a decade ago, this central Aspen landmark is one of 16
city buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
 &HT;    With a fire in the parlor fireplace, elk heads on walls and
cherry wood throughout, a visitor feels like a silver baron. For a
night in one of its 93 hotel rooms, the Jerome's nightly charges
vary in the summer from $295 to as much as $1,190, for a suite;
(800) 331-7213, fax (970) 925-2784.
 &HT;    Two blocks down Main Street, half-hidden by towering pines,
stands another Victorian gem, Sardy House. This quiet hotel of 20
well-appointed rooms has a small heated swimming pool in the
garden. Summer room rates, including breakfast, vary from $180 to
$440; (970) 920-2525.
 &HT;    For a resortlike setting in town, the Aspen Institute has 98
guest rooms and suites on its 40-acre riverfront campus on the west
end of town. Guests can use the institute's six tennis courts,
gymnasium and outdoor lap pool, and have golf privileges at the
Snowmass Lodge and Club. Summer room rates are $195 to $395; (970)
925-4240.
 &HT;    Budget: The Limelite Lodge at 228 East Cooper Ave., was the
cradle of the 1950's folk group The Limeliters when it was a
nightclub. Now, it is a family-oriented hotel, with 72 rooms, some
with kitchens, starting at $98 in summer; (970) 925-3025.
 &HT;    The Boomerang Lodge at 500 West Hopkins Avenue has 34 sun-filled
units, each with a private balcony or terrace offering a view of
Shadow Mountain. Rooms in summer start at $131, including
Continental breakfast; (970) 925-3416.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Aspen's nearly 100 restaurants have spruced up their summer
menus and honed their service in anticipation of the Food and Wine
Magazine Classic, taking place this weekend. Among them is Pinons,
105 South Mill St., where entrees include sauteed Colorado pheasant
breast and elk tenderloin. Dinner for two, with wine, is about
$120; (970) 920-2021.
 &HT;    The Little Nell, in the hotel of the same name, at 675 East
Durant Ave. is a personal favorite. In the elegant dining room or
sunny courtyard, diners enjoy mustard crusted trout or
honey-soy-seared salmon. Dinner for two with wine is around $150;
Hours: 7 a.m. to 10 p.m.; (970) 920-6330.
 &HT;    Outdoor dining with a view of Aspen Mountain can also be found
down the block, at Ajax Tavern, 685 East Durant. On a terrace near
the ski area's gondola as well in the dining room, diners can eat
local foods like free range chicken and Colorado lamb. Dinner for
two with wine costs about $100. Lunch and dinner served; (970)
920-9333.
 &HT;    A midpriced standout is Campo di Fiori, 205 South Mill St., an
earthy grotto with well-prepared Northern Italian dishes, a strong
Italian wine list and rapid-fire service. Try the arugula salad and
the risotto giardinera (asparagus, tomato, spinach and bell
peppers). Open for dinner daily. Dinner for two with wine costs
about $80; (970) 920-7717.
 &HT;    On the second floor of a bookstore at 221 East Main, Explore
Bistro offers vegetarian meals _ breakfast, lunch and dinner _ on a
sundeck or inside. Dinner for two with a drink is about $40; (970)
925-5338.
 &HT;    La Cocina, 308 East Hopkins Ave., a local hangout with
Southwestern cuisine, draws everyone from ski lift operators to
Hollywood types. Margaritas, blue corn tortillas and chocolate
velvet, a mousselike cake, add up to about $35 for two; (970)
925-9714.
 &HT;    Woody Creek Tavern is a timeless joint held together with
cigarette smoke, country music and old wallpaper five miles out of
town, in Woody Creek. The burger of local Limousin beef goes for
$6.95 and the chicken fajitas are $8.95. No credit cards. Don't ask
for espresso; (970) 923-4585.
 NIGHT LIFE  
 &HT;    After serving surprisingly good cabaret food, the waiters and
waitresses at the Crystal Palace, 300 East Hyman Ave., transform
themselves into a hilarious satirical revue.
 &HT;    During their annual spring break, they undoubtedly wore pencils
to the nub reworking fresh material supplied from our nation's
capital. Dinner and one-hour show are offered Thursday through
Saturday for $49.50 a person. For reservations, call (970)
925-1455.
 &HT;     (James Brooke is chief of the Denver bureau of The New York
Times.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 James Brooke  
