<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELLENIC-COLLEGE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELLENIC-COLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLENIC COLLEGE GETS ACCREDITATION WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two educational bodies that accredit Hellenic College and
Holy Cross Greek Orthodox School of Theology have warned the
institution that it could face probation if the Greek Orthodox
Church fails to guarantee its academic autonomy, including freedom
in personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In two pointed letters to the school, the New England
Association of Schools and Colleges and the Association of
Theological Schools expressed serious concern over the way the
Brookline, Mass. school's president and three veteran professors
were fired last year.
</P>
<P>
   The church's national leader allegedly had the four priests
fired because they refused to cover up an incident of alleged
sexual misconduct by a seminarian at the theology school, sources
said. Their firings last July have sparked heated controversy and
calls for the resignation of Archbishop Spyridon, the embattled
leader of the nation's 2 million Greek Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   Both educational associations have given the flagship
educational institution of the Greek Orthodox Church in America
several months to come up with a governing structure that
safeguards it from interference by church authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hellenic College, a four-year liberal arts college, and Holy
Cross, a seminary that trains Greek Orthodox priests, enrolled a
total of about 180 students last year.
</P>
<P>
   If the school does not come up with a satisfactory plan, the
accrediting associations said they will consider placing it on
probation, the first step toward loss of accreditation. Such a step
would deal a major blow to the school's reputation and could make
it difficult to attract students.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Spyridon, who also holds the title of chairman of the board of
trustees of the school, tried to downplay the seriousness of the
warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to report that the accreditation will not be
affected in any adverse way by the actions of either body,'' he
said in a press release issued late last month by the Greek
Orthodox Archdiocese of America.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Theological Schools, in a recent letter to
Greek Orthodox Church leaders, said it was formally placing Holy
Cross on ``warning'' until January.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate letter, the New England Association of Schools and
Colleges told church leaders it was delaying action on a motion to
ask the school to ``show cause why it should not be placed on
probation.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Association delayed taking any punitive action
because church and school leaders showed a strong willingness to
correct problems at the school, the association's letter said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the letter said, ``Failure to effectively respond to
our concerns will lead to an adverse action.''
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon and other archdiocesan officials have repeatedly stated
that the firings at the school had nothing to do with the sexual
misconduct case. They said the personnel decisions were an attempt
to resolve long-running personal feuds among faculty and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Some Greek Orthodox activists sympathetic to Spyridon say that
many conservative Greek Orthodox fear that Hellenic College has
become too secular and has lost some of its religious and ethnic
identity. They say the archbishop is trying to respond to these
fears.
</P>
<P>
   The school receives funding from and is part of the national
Greek archdiocese. Many Greek-Americans have long hoped that
Hellenic College could break free of its Greek Orthodox ties and
like other institutions with religious and ethnic roots, such as
Notre Dame and Brandeis, evolve into a more secular academic
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon's detractors say that the potential threat to the
accreditation is another example of the archbishop's poor
leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archdiocese has issued a press release making this look
like a slap on the wrist, but as a college administrator I can tell
you that the actions taken by the accrediting agencies amount to
much more,'' said Thomas Lelon, executive director of Greek
Orthodox American Leaders, a church dissident group, and vice
president and dean of academic affairs at Nichols College in
Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, many American colleges and universities would
overhaul administrations for placing their accreditation in
jeopardy,'' added Lelon, whose group, made up of influential
Greek-Americans, is trying to force Spyridon to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues raised by the accrediting associations were the
difficulty of reconciling the role of church authorities with the
American practice of separating church and state in education, and
the proper role of priests as faculty and administrators, as well
as academic freedom, and faculty rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand we have an institution of higher learning
expected to function more or less like any other institution,''
said Charles Cook, director of the New England Association of
Schools and Colleges. ``On the other hand it's part of a church.
The issue is one of balance and that's what we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lelon, a former president of Hellenic College, recalled how
difficult it was for the school to obtain its accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``After overcoming all the challenges ... it becomes
professionally embarrassing to have the administration called on
the carpet to defend why probation should not be imposed,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
