<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING A DRUG WORK ITS WONDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Farragher, at 75, has always been vigorous to a fault. He
wants to cut his own grass, shovel his own sidewalk, and trim the
trees he planted years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of his large family, he also sometimes
likes to act as his own doctor, applying liniment for aches or
popping off-the-shelf pills for pain, insisting he knows what works
and what doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his generation, Farragher is suspicious of medical
claims about miracle treatments and wonder drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That suspicion dissipated last month.
</P>
<P>
   My father suffered a massive stroke on June 25. But within hours
of receiving a relatively new drug _ a drug that specialists say
could spare thousands of Americans each year from death and
disability _ I watched him move an arm that had been paralyzed and
see from an eye that had been blinded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stroke is the number three killer in this country, and we just
recently developed the first treatment that's been proven effective
for it,'' said Dr. John Marler, a neurologist with the National
Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the enormous potential for reducing the toll of death
and disability, however, only an estimated 5 percent of stroke
patients who might benefit are being treated with the drug, a
genetically-engineered clot-buster called TPA that must be
adminstered within three hours in order to work. One major reason
is the inability of many Americans to recognize the symptoms of
stroke _ dizziness, numbness, headaches, slurred speech, vision
problems or shortness of breath. Another is that many hospitals and
physicians have been slow to offer the treatment, which can cause
devastating harm if given to the wrong type of stroke patient.
</P>
<P>
   TPA, for tissue plasminogen activator, can re-establish blood
flow to the brain and cut the risk of stroke damage. It is widely
used to treat heart attack victims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; James Farragher, the neurologist said, was the beneficiary not
only of that new treatment, but of meeting the chief criterion for
its use: He got to the hospital soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   My father is a retired mailman who still works part-time at a
market in Clinton, Mass., collecting grocery carts and small-town
gossip in the parking lot. Eleven days ago, after his morning at
work, he was spreading insecticide in the front yard when his
oldest grandchild, 15, noticed him slumped over.
</P>
<P>
   Even to the untrained eye, it was clear he had had a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter flagged down a passing police cruiser, his wife
called 911, and within a half hour, he was in Clinton Hospital's
emergency room, where his treatment began.
</P>
<P>
   As I drove from work down the Mass Pike and up Interstate 495, I
steeled myself for the worst. When I walked up to his hospital bed
I was, briefly, relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Tom,'' he said. ``Did you read about Barnicle's dog
today? Pretty good.'' He was conscious. He recognized me. I had
counted on neither.
</P>
<P>
   But it was &UR;  &LR; quickly &UR;  &LR; obvious that he had been badly damaged. The
left side of his face was frozen. His speech was terribly slurred.
His left arm sat withered by his side and responded to no stimulus.
He could move his left leg, but it was clearly weakened by the
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   He had become one of about 700,000 Americans this year who will
suffer a stroke, the sudden interruption of blood flow in the
brain. One-third of them will die. Only heart disease and cancer
kill more Americans each year.
</P>
<P>
   Eight out of every 10 strokes are caused by a clot in the blood
vessels that halts flow to the brain. That's the kind of stroke my
father had. And it's the kind of stroke that's treatable by TPA,
which was approved by the Food and Drug Administration for
treatment of strokes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After a CT scan determined that my father's stroke was caused by
a clot, and not a hemorrhage _ &UR;  &LR; which TPA can worsen with
disastrous results &UR;  &LR; _ the emergency room physician, Dr. Robert
Stine, said he was a candidate for the treatment. There was, we
were told, a 3 percent chance it could hurt him; a 97 percent
chance it would be ineffective or cause improvement.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, TPA must be given within three hours after the
stroke occurs. My father's, as near as we could tell, had occurred
at about 1:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to get the drug,'' the family told Stine. And
he &UR;  &LR; began receiving the drug at about 4:15 p.m., barely within the
three-hour limit.
</P>
<P>
   As the clot-dissolving drug dripped into his bloodstream at the
same hospital where his nine children were born, the family kept
vigil in the hallway outside.
</P>
<P>
   His primary-care physician arrived with sobering news. The
stroke was massive. Death was a possibility. My mother called a
Catholic priest to administer what used to be called the Last
Rites, and now &UR;  &LR; is known as the Sacrament of the Sick.
</P>
<P>
   I began thinking of my father's future in terms of wheelchair
ramps and nursing homes _ a future far from his vigorous life.
</P>
<P>
   As we gathered around his bed an hour later, the last of the TPA
just entering his system, my father had what the doctors call an
``on-the-table response.'' Without prompting, he suddenly raised
his left arm over his head. His left eye, cloudy all afternoon,
began to brighten. His speech was slightly better. A nurse asked
him to squeeze her hand. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have been really conservative about using TPA,''
said Marler. ``But there is a wonderful opportunity here that just
doesn't exist for other major diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroke specialists say that public understanding is critical if
TPA is to become a more common treatment. Allowing for tests that
must be done after a stroke victim gets to the hospital, patients
must recognize what is happening and call for help within about 90
minutes after symptoms occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your father was lucky that he went to a hospital where the
physician was organized enough to do this,'' said Marler, a federal
stroke researcher. ``What I think is going to make the difference
is when patients begin to ask, `Does my hospital have this
treatment?' And then, of course, they've got to get to the
emergency room rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Hospital, a small community hospital, is affiliated with
the &UR;  &LR; University of Massachusetts Memorial Health Care in nearby
Worcester, Mass., a level-one trauma center. Strokes have been
aggressively treated there for two decades, and physicians from its
emergency department teach doctors around the country how to use
TPA to treat strokes.
</P>
<P>
   James Farragher was only the second person to receive TPA at
Clinton Hospital, and one of only 14 patients in the UMass Memorial
system, which encompasses seven hospitals, to have met the
treatment criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Majaz Moonis, who oversees stroke treatment at the UMass
center, said the drug carries with it an increased risk of
hemorrhage. But patients who get it are 30 percent more likely to
be ultimately free of the effects of stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to increase the public's awareness about this,''
Moonis said. ``We're trying to make people think of a stroke as a
brain attack, just like a heart attack, and not to wait and see,
but to get to the hospital quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   My father, transferred to UMass medical center an hour after he
received TPA, is now in a nearby rehabilitation center, where more
improvement is expected.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen of the 80 hospitals in Massachusetts have recently
committed themselves to establishing stroke teams to provide prompt
stroke diagnosis and treatment. The Massachusetts Hospital
Association said the treatment is available at many others.
</P>
<P>
   A neurologist who treated my father said TPA saved him from
about 80 percent of the effects of the stroke that he otherwise
would have incurred, such as partial paralysis. He remains somewhat
weak, and his speech is a little slurred.
</P>
<P>
   But he can walk and talk and read and eat. And he will go home
to a family that believes in miracles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
