First law school
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The Noblest Study: The Legacy of America's First School of
Law'' has opened at the Litchfield (Connecticut) Historical
Society. The state-of-the-art exhibit tells of Tapping Reeve's
school, which began in his living room and soon moved to its own
building. In doing so, the exhibit illustrates students'
experiences of travel, study, entertainment, and courtship. The
first student was Aaron Burr, Reeve's brother-in-law, and soon
included future leaders of the country, including Vice President
John C. Calhoun, educator Horace Mann, and Supreme Court justices.
The exhibit, Tapping Reeve House, and Law School are all near the
Litchfield Green, one of the most picturesque in New England. For
information, call the historical society at 860-567-4501.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
