<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IMPORTANCE OF LOOKING GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm so honored! I'm in the New Yorker's summer fiction issue!
No, no, I didn't write anything. Just open the front cover. You see
the words: POLO RALPH LAUREN, and the photo of the dashing young
man in the adirondack chair. No, no, that's not me _ are you
kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Lift open the flap _ it's one of those ads that spread over
three pages. There we are! How generous it was of Mr. Lauren to
invite me to join the photo session. Run your eyes over the family
portrait in front of the beach house. Such a beautiful crew: women
of full lips and full bosom, men of broad forehead and narrow eyes
_ all with finely chiseled features, rich tans, confident smiles,
teeth as blond as the hair. Everyone is so at ease, so casual yet
sophisticated: white summer suits and ties, and no socks anywhere
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Do you see me? I'm not exactly male model material, especially
for a Polo ad. It must have something to do with my monster
schnozzle and too-thick glasses, receding hairline, and porky legs.
And I do have this old-fashioned penchant for wearing socks with my
shoes. But there I am _ the one with the underconfident half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I do stand out. And for that reason I commend Mr. Lauren
for including me. It is my curse to bear a most unpreppy look. But
does that mean I can't wear Polo clothes? Does that mean I can't
spend lots of money on Mr. Lauren's designs? Lauren is no dummy. He
knows I too can wear his clothes and look, well, just fine. And so
there I am.
</P>
<P>
   In no short time I felt just like one of the Polo family. I felt
and looked beautiful, and feeling and looking beautiful, I
therefore was beautiful, inside and out, untouched by the travails
of life. Just like the family. Look into those perfect faces. Can
anyone who looks like that have a care in the world? Of course not.
When you're pretty your troubles can only be small and easily
brushed under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, see the schoolboy with the tousled hair, v-neck
sweater, navy blazer, white trousers, and loosely knotted tie. He's
under house arrest. He shot six classmates at his exclusive private
school. But feast your eyes on him _ he looks great!
</P>
<P>
   See the dapper fellow seated cross-legged on the porch with the
adorable little girl riding on his shoulders. A fetching portrait
of father and daughter. He's so handsome in his khaki suit and
white turtle neck, and she's so cute in her navy dress with gold
stripes. You'd never suspect that daddy kidnapped his baby girl
years ago. Poor little thing has no idea what her mother looks
like. But what's the big deal? No kidnapper ever looked so grand!
</P>
<P>
   See the dad and son in front of the house, both sinking their
toes into the grass, white pant cuffs rolled above the ankles. The
son is draping an arm over dad's shoulder; dad is clutching a small
black-and-white-faced dog. When the ancestral beauty has been
passed down along the generations so flawlessly, who cares that the
son has just smashed up the Jag while high on PCP.
</P>
<P>
   I know what that dear fellow Ralph Lauren meant for me to learn.
Join the Polo family _ buy a shirt, some trousers, whatever _ and
my every hardship will crumble into dust. He wanted me to feel it,
and to tell you: All that really matters is to look great _ and to
look like them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(AT)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
