<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-07 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCHOOLS RISK RESEGREGATION WITH `NEW' PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If Boston school officials forget or ignore the past, they are
destined to repeat it _ and that may be the city's future if it
adopts any of the proposed alternatives to the current student
assignment plan.
</P>
<P>
   Court-ordered desegregation came to Boston _ with ensuing
violence _ in 1974 after the federal judiciary ruled that the
school system was under official racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, after relative calm replaced the intense
and often bitter racial turmoil that nearly engulfed Boston, a new
student assignment plan to replace the court-ordered desgregation
plan and its massive busing of students was approved in 1989 by
then-Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn, the School Committee and the
state education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, called ``controlled choice,'' was designed by Harvard
University sociology professor Charles Willie and Michael Alves, a
desegregation planner at Brown University. It proved to be a
positive alternative to the court-ordered plan because it gave
parents a wider choice of schools for their children, and it
virtually eliminated ``forced busing'' of students to assigned
schools under the court order.
</P>
<P>
   And the new plan kept the school system from relapsing into
segregation which, as Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. warned, would
have prompted the return of federal court control over the schools.
Yet, nine years later, Schools Superintendent Thomas Payzant and
other officals are considering replacing a proven school assignment
plan with one of three alternatives that are so flawed that, as
Willie and Alves point out, they could return Boston to the
terrible days of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   One option that Payzant is considering is the cluster plan that
would limite parents' choices of elementary and middle schools but
would ensure that students can attend schools closer to their
homes. A second option called a circle plan would allow parents to
choose from 10 schools nearest their homes.
</P>
<P>
   As Alves noted, these two plans would limit parental choice to a
handful of schools within mostly residentially segregated sections
of the city. The plans also give no assurance that the schools
within those contained areas would be of good quality or would
provide enough seating. Willie and Alves view both plans as
virtually guaranteeing a return to the segregated school days that
brought in busing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Another plan that Payzant is considering involves assigning
students to schools without regard to race. Students would be
assigned to schools by choice or by lottery. Under this plan, the
city would retain its system of three large zones, with parents
allowed to pick schools in any of the zones. Students also would
have a priority of attending a school in their immediate
neighborhood over students who want to be transported from other
parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   As Alves points out, this plan appears similar to the notorious
``freedom of choice'' and ``open enrollment'' plans that in reality
were schemes to keep the school system segregated, as many school
officials and parents preferred. ``These plans largely gave
African-American parents false choices, since they had no
reasonable expectation of getting their child admitted to a school
in a predominantly white neighborhood,'' Alves said. This was among
the reasons why the US Supreme Court in 1986 rejected these plans.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to be fueling these alternatives to the current
school assignment plan are deliberately raised false perceptions
that Boston is still under some some form of court-ordered
desegregation that continues to require ``forced busing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such perceptions are not only misleading, but dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Anyone familiar with the original ``controlled choice'' plan
and the three plans currently being floated must wonder what the
real motivation is behind these efforts. All three could bring
racial segregation back to Boston's schools and, as proven by the
courts, could damage the futures of thousands of children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The fact is, despite some remarks to the contrary, the
current ``controlled choice'' student assignment plan in Boston
already achieves what Payzant and others suggest is what the three
alternative plans could achieve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As Willie explained, a 1994 study of the ``controlled choice''
plan in Boston, commissioned by the mayor office and the Private
Industry Council provided the following data: 80 percent of
Boston's parents are satisfied with the student assignment process;
72 percent do not wish to have their children mandatorily assigned
to neighborhood schools; 55 percent of the parents choose schools
for educational reasons; and only 20 percent choose schools because
of their location.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 90 percent of students who currently wish to attend
neighborhood schools are accommodated in such schools.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the much-publicized perception that forced busing still
exists, the controlled choice plan actually has all but eliminated
it. In its place is a transportation system that takes students but
largely to schools of their choice. When a critic of the current
plan says a new plan will ``end busing,'' the only busing that will
be ended will be the transportation that students need to take to
go to the school of theirs, and their parents', choice. That would
be akin to ``ending busing'' for students attending the prestigious
Boston Latin school who need it to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Boston considers replacing ``controlled
choice,'' more than a dozen cities across the United States are
still embracing the plan because it brings two important
ingredients _ equality and diversity _ to the school systems. As
for eliminating ``race'' considerations, the controlled choice plan
has already reached that goal. Controlled choice is based on
parental choice, not racial choice.
</P>
<P>
   While some critics of controlled choice argue that a new plan is
needed to improve the quality of the city's schools, controlled
choice has a built-in process for that to happen. Some 30 schools
under the current plan are overenrolled each year, reflecting the
fact that parents know a quality school when they see one. All the
city has to do is to replicate these schools, and the overall
quality of the school system will be vastly improved.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than return to a school system that fits the needs of
some politicians who want to declare a victory over an illusory
``forced busing'' program, the school hierachy ought to maintain
the plan that already fits the educational needs of the city's
children. And that plan is ``controlled choice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
