<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-07 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, DOUBT CAST ON THE LINDA TRIPP `TALKING POINTS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Steven Brill now has company.
</P>
<P>
   To last month's examination of the press's uncritical handling
of suspect material in the initial stages of Kenneth Starr's Monica
Lewinsky investigation, the names of Skip Fox and John F.X. Gillis
now need to be added as the de-constructors of one of the case's
most important, purported pieces of ``evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the infamous ``talking points'' that Lewinsky's
manipulative, self-inflating friend, Linda Tripp, claims the former
White House intern gave her during a car ride home last Jan. 14,
and which Tripp claims to have then immediately passed on to the
independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   To that official version, thanks to Fox and Gillis, one question
now cries out for an answer and an investigiation: what talking
points?
</P>
<P>
   Fox is an English professor at the University of Southwestern
Louisiana, and Gillis is a doctoral candidate assistant. In a
serious of three, astonishingly detailed analyses available via the
Internet, they have dealt seriously with some important information
that the Scandalrama Press, competing mindlessly for anti-Clinton
morcels, has essentially ignored. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   _There are significantly different versions of these so-called
talking points, depending on which media outlet claiming possession
of them (they find at least seven) one happens to study.
</P>
<P>
   The best example is a single sentence of recommended Tripp-talk:
``You have never observed the president behaving inappropriately
with anybody.'' It is missing from two outlets' copies but is
present in five others. In addition, one version from US News's
on-line text uses paragraphs completely out of the order in which
they appear in the other versions.
</P>
<P>
   _The differences, not explainable as either typographical or
transcription error, undermine (to put it mildly) any assertion
that there was a simple transmission of a single version of a
document as an attempted subornation of perjury from Lewinsky to
Tripp and then to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   And in their textual analysis, Fox and Gillis don't just note
the widely observed changes in style and content _ from lawyer-like
to quasi-political strategy in preparation for deposition by Paula
Jones to personal asides to second- and first-person versions of
affidavit drafts. They also make a case for multiple authorship,
including by Tripp herself.
</P>
<P>
   _The content of the various versions of the talking points does
not support an assertion that Lewinsky was trying to get Tripp to
``lie'' about what she saw and heard from Kathleen Willey, the
woman who has claimed with diminishing credibility that President
Clinton virtually assaulted her four years ago. Instead, it
supports a skeptical view of Willey that Tripp has always asserted
in public comments and contains ``beliefs'' that by definition
cannot be perjurious.
</P>
<P>
   _The published versions of the material contain information that
available evidence indicates Lewinsky or even the White House could
not have known, above all that Tripp had been dealing with Paula
Jones's attorneys virtually from the moment of her subpoena in that
case on Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The best example here is an almost offhand observation in the
text, obviously for the benefit of Jones's lawyers: ``By the way,
remember how I said there was someone else that I knew about. Well
she turned out to be a huge liar ...'' The authors note that for
Lewinsky to have tried to put those words in Tripp's mouth she
would have to know that Tripp was dealing with them, for which
there is no known evidence. However, they do note that the
adjective ``huge'' is a Tripp favorite in previously published
audiotape transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   _In that one instance, a casual insertion of a gratuitous
comment more than suggests that instead of being a single document,
the talking points are more plausibly an e-mail compilation that
may have existed on more than one computer. That is especially
valid, given the comment's final, throwaway line, ``Well, at least
that gets me out of another scandal I know about.'' And from more
than one computer, more than one source could have given the
differing versions of the document to different media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   _It's also at least interesting that the only reference to
Tripp's first attorney is with his first name, Kirby (Behr), while
Clinton attorney Bob Bennett is mentioned by surname.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief reference to the Fox-Gillis work in this
week's Village Voice and, more important, a Web site
(www.ucs.usl.edu/jfg0701/essays/tripp.html).
</P>
<P>
   There are three documents there, and the reading is heavy. But
it's worth it, as well as truly disturbing about the handling in
the press of ``evidence'' that is very clearly not what it seems or
has been purported to represent. So what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
