<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIABILITY-GUNS-BOS &LR;      07-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIABILITY-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIABILITY REFORM MAY COME AT COST TO ANTIGUN LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under a bill with the bland name of ``product
liability reform,'' victims of gun violence could find it much
harder to sue gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens may lose much of their ability to bring unrestricted
lawsuits against the gun industry for selling to a felon or a
minor, for marketing weapons with criminal appeal, or for making
dangerous or defective guns that cause accidental harm or death,
legal analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   They also predict the measure could damage recent efforts by
big-city mayors and gun-control advocates to draft lawsuits that
hold the gun industry _ like the tobacco industry _ responsible for
the public health and safety costs associated with their products.
</P>
<P>
   These potential consequences have received little attention,
while the overall bill has won bipartisan support and a nod from
the White House. Supporters say the legislation balances the goal
of protecting businesses from vexing, sometimes frivolous
product-liability litigation with the need of consumers to have
recourse in the courts when they are harmed by defective or unsafe
products.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for action in the Senate this week, the legislation
would require consumers to show that companies acted with
``conscious, flagrant indifference'' to safety, and would make it
more difficult for consumers to win their lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   For small businesses, the bill would limit jury awards for
punitive damages to $250,000. The White House wanted this provision
because small companies have fewer economic resources to draw from,
and need additional protection.
</P>
<P>
   But the provision also means that thousands of gun dealers and
potentially dozens of small manufacturers of guns, particularly
those in California's so-called ``Ring of Fire'' where Saturday
Night Specials are produced, would be protected from the kinds of
million-dollar judgments that have been awarded victims harmed by
firearms produced or marketed negligently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to remove the threat of such lawsuits?'' asked Carl
T. Bogus, a professor at Roger Williams University School of Law in
Bristol, R.I., and an expert on product liability. ``Some of the
most notorious gun manufacturers are in fact small businesses who
promiscuously sell cheap guns. It makes no sense whatever to grant
these people a safe harbor from damages that would be reasonable in
view of willful and egregious conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The product liability legislation is a compromise negotiated by
the White House, Senator Slade Gorton, Republican of Washington,
and Senator Jay Rockefeller, Democrat of West Virginia, after years
of wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-consumer groups and some legal scholars say the bill, which
would change 50 years of common law, stamps on the rights of
individuals to sue corporations, and interferes with the jury's
privilege to punish a company for negligent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, pro-business groups, including the gun lobby,
hail the bill as a long-awaited reprieve from runaway lawsuits that
hamper commerce and even put people out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a major component of our legislative wish list,''
said Bob Ricker of the American Shooting Sports Council, which
represents firearms manufacturers, retailers, and distributors.
``The tort system has handcuffed our economy. It is ludicrous to
think that a lawyer can experiment with any legal theory in the
courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricker said the bill should ``swing the pendulum'' away from
courtroom fights.
</P>
<P>
   Bogus warned the bill will give the gun industry incentive to
play ``corporate shell games'' and spin off their businesses into
small enterprises that qualify for the exception to avoid liability
in court.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, at least a dozen firearm manufacturers appear to be
small enough to qualify for the small-business exception, according
to a study by the Violence Policy Center, a Washington gun-control
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our point is that you can make a lot of guns that have a real
impact on the market and do it with few people, very cheaply,''
said Kristen Rand, federal policy director for the nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Products like cars and drugs are regulated, guns are not,''
she added. ``The courts are the only thing that function as
regulation, and without them, you are giving the gun industry carte
blanche. ... People don't realize they are giving up their rights.
It's that basic.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and the American Shooting Sports
Council have been working with a large coalition of business groups
called the Product Liability Advisory Committee pushing for tort
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The council also used support of the reforms as a litmus test
for endorsing congressional candidates in its rating system during
the 1996 elections. The NRA also made an election issue out of tort
reform, condemning Clinton for his veto of an earlier version of
the bill in a ``resolution'' to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA did not reply to requests for comment. According to
articles in Guns &AMP; Ammo magazine, the NRA views the proliferation
of lawsuits against manufacturers and distributors as ``a back-door
way to ban guns,'' and tort reform as a way to fend off such
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley and Philadelphia Mayor Edward G.
Rendell have proposed suing firearms manufacturers and distributors
for the costs associated with gun violence in much the same way
that states have gone after the tobacco industry in court.
Gun-control groups, as well as groups of victims, are also suing
the firearms industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ricker does not believe the product-liability bill will impede
these efforts. ``The reason for our support is not special
treatment for our industry, it is because the bill is good for
business and therefore, good for the firearms industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators, including Democrats Dianne Feinstein of
California and Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, want to ensure that
the gun industry remains liable for defective or dangerous
products, and they have drafted an amendment that would exempt it
from the bill's provisions. The tobacco industry already has been
excluded. Debate on the amendment is expected to be heated and the
vote close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
