<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MINERS-BOS &LR;      07-07 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MINERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINERS SEETHE OVER THEIR FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VORKUTA, Russia _ The skeletons of Stalin's gulag still ring
this barren arctic city. Crumbling prison walls and abandoned
wooden crosses in the tundra are stark reminders of the thousands
of slave laborers who built Vorkuta and founded the coal mines that
surround it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the miners of Vorkuta have something else to remind them of
their unfortunate forefathers: their own jobs. For something
resembling slavery has returned to this city of 180,000, located on
a bleak tundra plain at the foot of the Polar Urals, 1,250 miles
northeast of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   For the worst thing about being a miner in Russia's Far North is
not that people were never intended to build cities in this place,
where it snows despite round-the-clock daylight in summer and where
winter is six months of frigid night. The worst thing is not that
there is no place to go, and that the only jobs are in the mines,
where abysmal safety standards and outdated equipment cause an
average of two fatal accidents each week.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing is the feeling the miners have _ that while they
go months without pay, the mines are making their bosses incredibly
rich. And that is making the miners of Vorkuta angry.
</P>
<P>
   In May, they took the city's mayor and the directors of the main
mining company hostage for 10 days. For the past two weeks, 200
Vorkuta miners have picketed the federal government building in
Moscow, where they bang their plastic helmets on the pavement.
Their demand is no longer that the government pay off some $56
million in back wages. They now say they will not be happy until
President Boris N. Yeltsin resigns.
</P>
<P>
   That should sound a warning to Yeltsin, who rode to power on the
wave of protest that began with miners' strikes in Vorkuta in 1989
and spread across the great Kuzbass mining region of Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, miners across the country are planning a reprise of their
protest in May, when they blocked critical train routes, crippling
Russia's supply lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as million-strong meetings raised Yeltsin to power in
1991, we now hope to show with million-strong meetings that the
people are frankly tired of him,'' Alexander Sergeyev, head of the
Independent Miners' Union, said last month.
</P>
<P>
   But in Vorkuta, the possibility of new nationwide protests is
greeted with tempered enthusiasm. When miners in Inta, a city 100
miles southwest of here, sat on the rails in protest last May, it
was Vorkuta that stopped receiving food and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we strike, it hits us in our own pockets,'' said Yevgeny
Shumeiko, deputy head of the Vorkuta miners' union.
</P>
<P>
   Miners in the rest of Russia can survive when they strike,
thanks to the garden plots that produce as much as 50 percent of
Russia's produce. But in the permafrost around Vorkuta, nothing
grows except lichen and low bushes. Even the polar aspens brought
to enliven Vorkuta's barren streets have trouble surviving.
Potatoes, the Russian dietary staple, are out of the question here.
</P>
<P>
   In a dingy hallway at the Severny mine, Shumeiko displayed the
humble rations that miners can buy for a dollar each: a hardboiled
egg, some stale bread and old sausage. With no money and no other
way to get food, miners charge up to 10 such rations a day against
their salaries and take them home to their families. For the
average miner, that means as much as half of his monthly salary of
about $400 goes toward purchasing rations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slaves of Rome lived better. At least they were properly
fed,'' said Ravin, a worker at the Severny mine near Vorkuta, who
reluctantly gave only his first name.
</P>
<P>
   Ravin produced a slip of paper that details how much he is owed
_ over $6,000 in wages and benefits. The pay stub shows that income
taxes have been deducted each month, even on money Ravin did not
receive. His conclusion is that the mine got the money. It just
never made it to him.
</P>
<P>
   He waved at the tundra, its bleak monotony broken only by the
mountains on the horizon and a ring of distant smokestacks,
billowing sulfurous yellow smoke into the artic air.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``This place is one big prison camp, and we are the
prisoners,'' Ravin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ravin and other Vorkuta miners sense that their directors, and
senior union leaders, are getting rich while holding back payments
to workers. The head of the miners' union in Severny has opened an
expensive supermarket. (``We'd like to know how he did it, if his
salary is as late as ours,'' said Ravin.)
</P>
<P>
   The wealthiest businessman in Vorkuta is the son of the mining
conglomerate's former director. Miners at Severny say they are
forced to work Sundays, producing coal that does not show up in any
of the mine's accounts. They suspect this coal is being sold at cut
rates for cash, which the directors pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know where the coal goes. We only know that the
bosses' salaries are never late,'' said a miner who asked that his
name not be used. ``You could put them all in jail right now, if
only anyone had the will to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when money does arrive, getting it is another problem.
Payroll accountants gladly pay the miners their salaries, for a fee
of 10 percent of the paycheck, according to Alexandra Kuzina,
editor of the local daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's humiliating to have to beg for your own money,''
commented Severny miner Zhenya Zheredetsky. ``You earned it, and
yet you have to drag it out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It used to mean something to be a miner in Vorkuta. Although
political prisoners built the place, in the 1960s and 1970s people
flocked to Vorkuta, lured by the comparably high salaries and
lucrative benefits offered by the Soviet government, and spurred on
by the ``More Coal to the Motherland'' slogan still prominently
displayed in Vorkuta's central square.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1991 Soviet breakup, however, the Kremlin has been
trying to improve efficiency in Russia's massive and unsafe mines.
Subsidies to coal mines were slashed in 1994. A new slogan appeared
over Vorkuta: ``More Coal with Fewer Workers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the miners have nowhere to go. Without cash, they have no
way to move south. Federal programs to move them have failed thus
far, partly because funds intended for relocation and retraining
programs were used to pay wage arrears.
</P>
<P>
   As with most of Russia's ailing large enterprises, there is no
consensus on who is responsible. Vyacheslav Davydov, the spokesman
of the state-owned conglomerate that runs the mines, says the
government causes the wage problem by failing to pay its bills on
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the money we get, we put towards paying people,'' Davydov
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov, the government's point
man on the mining problem, counters that the problem is corrupt and
inefficient management.
</P>
<P>
   Probably directors and the Kremlin share the guilt for overdue
wages for all large Russian firms, mines included. Unwilling to pay
the social cost of mass unemployment, Moscow has been slow to push
bankruptcy laws against companies that cannot pay their debts to
their workers. Instead, the government has granted subsidies to
firms that are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't get paid when the people who are supposed to pay
them can get away with not paying them,'' said Rory MacFarquar, an
economist at the Russian-European Center for Economic Reforms in
Moscow. ``If it turns out that you can get a larger subsidy from
the government when you run up wage arrears, you will run up wage
arrears.''
</P>
<P>
   While the state and the managers try to work out who is at
fault, the miners are losing patience. Two weeks ago, a miner at
Severny hanged himself in the shaft. A woman who is owed $6,000
threatened to throw herself into the shaft of the Komsomolsky mine
unless she was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Shumeiko, the union leader, rushed to the mine to talk the
director into paying her at least something, and the woman did not
jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this keeps up, we won't be able to stop the people from
rising up,'' Shumeiko said.
</P>
<P>
   Shumeiko said he would like to get to the bottom of what really
happens to the money. But he has more immediate concerns, such as
dealing with the safety of the mines' aging, outdated equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Recently a miner was killed as he tried to repair a huge machine
that bores a tunnel into the earth, spitting out huge blocks of
coal at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for their often tragic consequences, safety
standards in the mines would be laughable. For example, to detect
dangerous methane deposits that can cause a blast like the one in
January that killed 26 miners, workers at Severny rely on rats. If
there are rats in the mine, there is no methane. No rats, and the
area is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that the rats are attracted by the rations the
miners bring with them. And since most miners have stopped eating
in the pits, instead bringing their rations home, fewer rats
descend into the shafts, making it harder to detect the methane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the rats know,'' said Vorkuta miner Nikolai Avkhimenko,
``to get out of this place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
