<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROY-ROGERS-APPRECIATI     07-07 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROY-ROGERS-APPRECIATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY TRAILS, ROY ROGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Rogers was really a guy named Leonard Slye who was born in
Cincinnati but grew up in Marietta, Ohio. The fact that he was a
fellow Ohioan was not lost on me. Even as a 6-year-old
member-in-good-standing of the Roy Rogers Club, Columbus chapter, I
felt we had a special bond.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard that Roy Rogers had died Monday, at age 86, it was
like saying goodbye to a piece of my childhood. Closing a chapter
of innocence, I suppose, where the good guys really did wear the
white hats and ride in on stallions so golden and heroic, you
almost had to wear sunglasses to watch them canter across the
silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   Roy was handsome. His eyes tilted up like a Tatar tribesman with
a Cherokee ancestor. He was whippet-slim and moved like a dancer,
which is pretty hard to do in high-heeled cowboy boots equipped
with jingling spurs. He had the requisite six-gun and was really
good with his fists. His pal was a bearded old codger named Gabby
who complained a lot in a high, gruff voice, which Roy took so
good-naturedly; Gabby drove Nellybelle the Jeep, and Roy's love
interest, Dale, rode her own dun-colored Palomino mare named
Buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   I never wanted to be Dale. No, sir. She was real cute and all
with her tightly curled coif, white cowboy hat, sunny disposition
and smile, and those nifty skirts with the buckskin fringe. But she
was just an accessory, and quite incidental to the movies' plots,
which got recycled every outing.
</P>
<P>
   When you were a girlchild of my vintage, pre-Barbie, you focused
on one of two things: You either wanted to be a ballerina or own a
horse. My Aunt Ruby's caretaker had taken me over a low jump on the
front of his saddle on a huge bay gelding when I was 4. So the
choice was a no-brainer. I went horse crazy. And absolutely crazy
over the Stetson-wearing guys who rode them.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a first-grader, my mother started giving me 30 cents
every Saturday to go to the Roy Rogers movies at the Drexel Theater
on Main Street, right next door to my school. I would walk the six
blocks down Sheridan Avenue, which was the first street in our
little community, on the wrong side of the Main Street and almost
not even Bexley, Ohio, at all. The popular kids lived between Main
and Broad. I lived in what my Jewish mother called ``erev (almost)
Bexley,'' but before I understood what snobbism, Spaulding shoes,
cashmere sweaters, box-pleated skirts and boyfriends with letter
sweaters were all about, I was in love with Roy.
</P>
<P>
   So Mama, in her wisdom, allowed me my fantasy. She never tried
to talk me out of wanting to be this studly cowboy who was on the
side of right. She dutifully counted out the quarter and the nickel
each Saturday and sent me and my friend Debbie on our way to the
11:30 a.m. show. The money was divvied up thusly: 15 cents for the
movie, 10 cents for popcorn and five cents for a Sugar Daddy, which
lasted a long time and was responsible for pulling out a couple of
front teeth before it was time for them to go.
</P>
<P>
   We'd file into the Drexel Theater, an Art Deco leftover. Cool
terrazzo tile on the floor, worn maroon seats and the smell of
freshly popped popcorn mingled with bathroom deodorizer are the
sense memories I can still summon up today. We showed our numbered
membership cards, and before the entertainments started, there was
always a drawing. I won a Roy Rogers lunch box once, a Dale lasso
another time. Who knows what they're worth on the collectors'
market now?
</P>
<P>
   Then the lights would dim and the show would start. We'd have a
Tom and Jerry cartoon, then a Buck Rogers or Boston Blackie serial.
And then finally, the Roy Rogers cowboy movie, with sweating horses
galloping into impossible terrain or through arroyos (all the
better for them evil sidewinders to bushwhack our hero) or over the
sagebrushed desert. There was nothing Roy did that wasn't perfect,
legal and up-front. He was never wily or underhanded.
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't hide his face behind a mask. He wasn't chunky like
the Other Guy, Gene Artery, we called him. He had a whiskey tenor
and when he sang with the Sons of the Pioneers, it was pure
heaven-on-a-stick.
</P>
<P>
   I still know the words to ``Blue Shadows on the Trail'' and
``Riders in the Sky.'' My parents realized that I could sing when
they bought me an album of Roy's songs and heard me singing along
with the music on my old Victrola.
</P>
<P>
   Roy married Dale. They adopted a passel of inter-racial kids and
became good and high-profile Christians. They lost a child and Dale
wrote a book about it. I admired what they were able to do. I hated
it when Roy stuffed Trigger. Some wag I know figures somebody will
stuff Roy, too. And I outgrew wanting to be a cowboy. I fixated on
Brenda Starr and became her instead.
</P>
<P>
   So now he's gone and that part of my childhood is finally over.
Happy Trails, my friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
