<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOOMSDAY-REALITY-BOS &LR;      07-07 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOMSDAY-REALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING THE LAWS OF NATURE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earth-bound asteroids and comets seem to have an uncanny knack
for aiming straight at the world's major cities _ especially New
York _ and laying them flat, just as surely as tornadoes always
seem to aim for trailer parks.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the case in most of the movies ever made about
the Earth being battered from above, including this summer's big
duo _ ``Deep Impact'' and ``Armageddon'' _ blockbusters
(literally). But although the Big Apple is reduced to applesauce in
both of them, at least ``Deep Impact'' does it in a way that makes
scientific sense.
</P>
<P>
   That affinity for cities is cinematically understandable; after
all, watching the Chrysler building or the Statue of Liberty come
crumbling down is a lot more visually exciting than watching an
impact on a wheatfield in Kansas or some sand dunes in the Sahara.
But it's just one of many quibbles and questions that scientists
have raised about the latest rage in disaster flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, most astronomers seem somewhat mollified by their
expectation that, that despite the usual slew of inaccuracies, the
release of ``Armageddon'' last week, following that of ``Deep
Impact'' in May will, if nothing else, greatly raise the public's
awareness of the real risk our planet faces from an impact someday.
And overall, they say ``Deep Impact'' comes a whole lot closer than
any movie before or since to getting the scientific facts of
impacts right _ although that may not be saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less inaccurate than the others,'' said Dan Green,
assistant director of the real-life central clearinghouse in
Cambridge, where all discoveries of asteroids and comets are first
sent. ``That's not saying much, but I would say that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Other astronomers have been more positive. David Morrison, head
of space research at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Ames Research Center in California, said that
``one can always nitpick the science, but in my opinion there is
not one serious error in this film _ nothing that damages its basic
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison especially praises the way ``Deep Impact'' portrays the
effects of the impact, in particular the tsunami (what people often
call a tidal wave) that actually flattens New York in that film,
rather than the impacting object itself. As recent computer
simulations at the Los Alamos National Laboratory have shown, an
impact anywhere in the North Atlantic really would innundate New
York, Washington, and most of the East Coast, rushing many miles
inland with a wall of water that could tower thousands of feet high
in some places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie was at least 100 times better than `Asteroid,'''
last year's TV miniseries about an impact that homes in on Dallas,
said Clark Chapman, an astronomer at the Southwest Research
Institute in Boulder, Colo., who specializes in the study of
asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon,'' on the other hand, gets uniformly bad reviews
from the scientists _ even those who haven't seen it yet; they say
it's clear just from basic descriptions that most of its basic
premises are flat-out impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely impossible,'' says Green of the movie's central
storyline: That an asteroid the size of Texas is discovered on a
collision course with Earth, just 18 days before the expected
impact. ``There's only one object in the solar system known to be
that size,'' the asteroid Ceres _ an object so bright and
unmistakable that it was discovered way back in 1801, before the
advent of powerful telescopes. ``Anything that kind of size would
be too bright to miss.'' And Ceres never comes within tens of
millions of miles of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers were also a bit harsh in their criticism of the way
``Armageddon'' depicts a series of smaller objects, apparently
thrown into a collision course by the huge asteroid, that come
crashing to Earth sporadically whenever there's a lull in the
action in the weeks before the Big One is due. And, of course,
these precursor impacts head straight for the cities of New York
(where the tiny objects seem to come flying in from all sides; in a
a true meteor shower, everything comes from a single direction) and
Paris (which gets flattened by one big object in one of the film's
few realistic scenes).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nuts,'' said Chapman. `'It doesn't make scientific
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Both films took the rather unusual step (by Hollywood standards)
of hiring technical consultants for the rocket sequences, in which
astronauts head out to intercept the doomsday rocks and nuke them
to bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' had the full cooperation of NASA itself, and did
some filimg at the Kennedy Space Center; in fact, the movie's
premiere was held at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you'd know it from the movie. The rockets it uses to
intercept the incoming asteroid hundreds of thousands of miles out
in space look exactly like the space shuttle, whose ceiling is
about 300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Impact'' also uses shuttle-like rockets to intercept the
speeding comet, but at least those craft are clearly much larger
and quite different from the familiar shuttle. The script gets
around the problem of deep-space travel by describing them as new
nuclear-powered rockets that were secretly assembled in orbit.
Astronomers say keeping something like that secret would be
impossible _ the vehicles are described as larger than the Mir
space station, which is so bright that it can easily be spotted
passing overhead on clear nights, unmistakably visible to the naked
eye. But the rocket science makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking as a former NASA rocket scientist,'' engineer Keith
Cowing wrote recently in an Internet newsletter, ``the technology
(in ``Deep Impact'') is portrayed quite realistically, the
celestial scenery is done very well, and the cataclysmic effects of
a cometary impact are masterfully realized.'' He added that ``given
Hollywood's chronic habit of violating the laws of physics, this
movie is a rather notable exception.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because, unlike ``Armageddon,'' the makers of
``Deep Impact'' also hired several consultants to help them get it
right on the nature of comets and the effects of an impact, and the
initial script was written by screenwriter Bruce Joel Rubin, who
had extensive interviews with researchers and sat through days of
scholarly meetings about the latest research on the asteroid
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Rubin was fired early-on in the film's
production. And the movie-makers didn't always heed some of the
consultants it paid to advise them, including the highly-respected
husband-and-wife team of comet and asteroid specialists Carolyn and
the late Eugene Shoemaker. So though it's much better than most,
``Deep Impact'' still has its lapses.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the comet is said to have been discovered about
two years before the predicted impact, by amateur astronomers at a
star party. That's reasonable _ many comets are found by amateurs,
and Thomas Bopp of Hale-Bopp fame made his discovery at a star
party in Arizona. The problem is, the film places the comet next to
the Big Dipper stars Alcor and Mizar, and it appears much brighter
than those bright naked-eye stars. Then, it's mysteriously lost
from view and its existence is suppressed by the government for
another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break!'' said Green in an interview last week. It
would be impossible to suppress that kind of phenomenon in a
wide-open field like astronomy _ an object so bright that anyone
could see it just by looking up. And another thing: To have been
that bright so long before impact _ and thus, so far away from
Earth _ it ``would have to be about the size of Texas,'' Green
said. And no known comet has been much bigger than Dallas, much
less Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of Chapman, who was reached by telephone last
week at an international meeting of authorities on asteroid
impacts, that's not the film's biggest problem. He says its
portrayal of the comet's being blown to smithereens shortly before
it would have walloped the world is dead wrong. Blowing it apart so
close to Earth, he said, would instead make things worse. We would
be pummeled by comet fragments delivering the same, cumulative
amount of destructive energy as the whole thing. Every living thing
would be incinerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere on Earth would have been like the inside of a hot
oven'' Chapman said, and yet nuking the comet to pieces is supposed
to have saved the planet. ``To me, that's the biggest error in
`Deep Impact.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it could have been a lot worse. Many things were changed
as a result of the filmmakers' consultation with specialists.
Carolyn Shoemaker wryly commented recently that at least they took
out a scene that included a nude astronomer: ``I always thought
astronomy was one of the coldest professions, and envisioned
frostbite at the least!''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even as the films frequently skirted and even
flouted the laws of Nature, they helped in a visually powerful way
to get across to the public what deeply troubles astronomers and
other scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, maybe in a million years, maybe in a week, the
people of Earth will face a real doomsday scenario: A real comet or
an asteroid will be detected on a collision course with our planet.
</P>
<P>
   A mere handful of astronomers is trying to hunt down and monitor
all the objects in space that have the potential to strike Earth,
but they are operating on a fraction of the budget that the makers
of ``Deep Impact'' and ``Armageddon'' had to work with.
</P>
<P>
   A major search program called Spaceguard, advocated by a NASA
study, never came to pass, and the only search of the Southern
Hemisphere's skies was cancelled recently for lack of money. Even
the most ambitious search effort anyone has ever proposed, which
would find virtually all of the potential threats within a decade,
would cost far less than either of the impact movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week's gross from `Deep Impact' would be enough to
implement the Spaceguard Survey,'' Morrison noted wistfully. That
gross was $41.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that film may ultimately make a difference, he said. ``It
may do more to alert the public to the impact hazard than anything
in the past. And its images may even keep you up at night wondering
if we are doing enough to protect our planet against this threat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
