<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT2-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO BATTLE HEATING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nasty fight over the business practices of health maintenance
organizations, a big part of the scene around Washington for
months, is going national, demonstrating that while it is
definitely nasty, it is also very important.
</P>
<P>
   As Exhibit A, the wide-open campaign to succeed Representative
Joe Kennedy in Massachusetts' 8th Congressional District more than
qualifies, as witness an effort by the state's powerful HMO lobby
to muscle one of businessman Chris Gabrieli's TV ads off the air.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the classically dumb move failed. Showing commendable
focus for a rookie pol, Gabrieli not only didn't pull his ad, he
made a show of putting a new, tougher one up; but the politics of
this incident is just the tip of a much more interesting iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Down in Washington, the power of the topic of HMOs has been
amply demonstrated _ most recently by the decision of Newt
Gingrich's Republican leadership to join the movement to reform the
cost-shaving behemoths by offering an outline of what it is
prepared to support in the way of codified patients' and doctors'
rights. You can knock Gingrich for only going so far, or you can
agree with him; but the important point is that the GOP move
validates the reform push and provides a solid basis for bipartisan
legislating.
</P>
<P>
   In the HMO and insurance business, the reponse was almost
immediate _ a quick round of attack ads (initially targeted at the
home districts of ranking Republicans on health care issues) and
the prospect of much more. Borrowing strategy from the tobacco
racket's successful changing of the subject last month (from health
to taxes and big government), the HMOs' marketers took the victim
route, portraying the business as a pinata that politicians were
swinging away at. Unable to refute the ocean of evidence about
profit-driven denials of care and restrictions on physicians, the
industry has resorted to cynically claiming that this is all just
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Up in Boston in late June, Gabrieli's campaign aligned him with
the HMO reformers on TV, following earlier New Democrat
communications on education. For 30 seconds his opposition was
registered to all forms of restrictions on what doctors in a plan
can tell their patients (generically known as gag rules), as was
his support for the making of medical decisions solely by doctors
as opposed to those evil accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly rough stuff, but it produced a diatribe from the state
lobby _ the Massachusetts Association of HMOs _ in the form of a
letter pushing him to pull the add, with copies to the three
Boston-area network affiliates. The letter focused narrowly on a
denial that any plan literally prevents a doctor from disclosing
treatment options or other information to a patient, noting there
are no such plans in the state, and that the association supported
a state law two years ago that prohibits them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic, nondenial denial. As Gabrieli noted in his
reponse, most HMOs have been found to use a number of techniques to
keep providers in line. Some use contracts that bind them to
pledges not to say anything to patients that could undermine
confidence in the health plan, a nice, open-ended sword to hold
over someone's head; others can drop physicians and others from the
all-important provider list without providing a reason.
</P>
<P>
   When we talked, Gabrieli emphasized the much broader context of
his views on health care _ as businessman, think tank chairman (the
relentlessly innovative MassINC), and now as congressional
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He believes in universal insurance coverage, though
realistically via incremental change and with a mixture of private
and public organizations. He favors maintaining the
employment-based nature of health insurance, but favors more
choices for participating workers, citing the federal employees'
much-praised system from which all members of Congress benefit. And
he thinks the government should help consumers by developing
standards for quality care and putting out information about the
quality of individual health plans.
</P>
<P>
   In short, because Gabrieli is committed to an open system that
is based on choice, he is strongly committed to the ``thoughtful
regulation'' of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   There will be those who grumble and more about Gabrieli's wealth
and his TV ads, but recent history shows that money is only a
handicap for the vapid and/or the negative.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrieli's real challenge as a candidate who didn't come up in
the system is to get his ideas from the TV set to the kitchen
table, in terms directly relevant to the working families in his
very urban district.
</P>
<P>
   The state's foolish, overbearing HMOs have given him a rare
chance not available to the other candidates, and he has taken
skillful advantage of it so far.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
