<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' &LR;  by Rick Bass (Houghton Mifflin,
$25). A fiercely beautiful first novel about oil, men, and western
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Meditations from a Movable Chair''  &LR; by Andre Dubus (Knopf,
$23). Muscular but sensitive essays, enlivened by Dubus's
storytelling prowess.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Freedomland'' &LR;  by Richard Price (Broadway Books, $25).
Cinematic story of a white mother's fabricated tale about a black
carjacker, and the horrific consequences for a divided city.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Final Vinyl Days'' &LR;  by Jill McCorkle (Algonquin, $18.95).
Stories of small-town Southern folk, trying to hold their lives
together.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Inn at Lake Devine''  &LR; by Elinor Lipman (Random House,
$23.95). A poignant novel of memory, prejudice, and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``In the Night Season'' &LR;  by Richard Bausch (HarperFlamingo,
$24). On the surface, a crime novel; underneath, a work of
literature.
</P>
</TEXT>
