<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
!! ``Armageddon''  Bruce Willis and his gang trying to destroy a
Texas-sized asteroid before it destroys us. Big, noisy, stupid and
shameless _ but Billy Bob Thornton, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler, Will
Patton, Peter Stormare, and Steve Buscemi almost persuade us we're
watching something that matters. That's more than can be said for
the amped-up directing style and special effects. (PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! &UR; 1/2 ``Buffalo 66''  &LR; A derivative film, but a nice try from De
Niro wannabe Vincent Gallo, the co-writer, director, and star. He
plays a loser just released from prison who kidnaps a young woman
to accompany him home to an uncaring mom and a raging dad.
Christina Ricci, who alternates between being too much for him to
handle and an uncritical projection of the compliant woman of his
dreams, is a big plus. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FU) &LR; !! &UR; 1/2 ``Henry Fool''  &LR; Hal Hartley's most ambitious film
yet, a parable about those who make gassy pronouncements about art
and those who are actually good at making it. The film can't
sustain its ambitions, but it at least makes you think as it
deploys the affectless lowlifes around a bleak patch of Queens in
which Samuel Beckett wouldn't dream of waiting for Godot. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! &UR; ``I Went Down''  &LR; Offbeat Irish gangster movie that succeeds
because everybody in it seems to be taking everything personally. A
quick-thinking amateur and a slow-thinking thug are sent from
Dublin to the provinces to extradite a crimelord's thieving crony.
Their troubles begin when they actually find their talkative,
slippery quarry. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! &UR; 1/2 ``Smoke Signals''  &LR; Beautifully written road movie about
a couple of American Indians who find themselves on a journey of
closure when they go from Idaho to Arizona to bring home the
remains of the father who abandoned one of them. In this movie _
written, directed, acted, and co-produced by Native Americans _
humor is used as a weapon against the imposition of second-class
citizenship by a cowboy culture, and there's plenty of it. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
