<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SEX-BOS &LR;      07-07 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REGION WHERE OUTER WORLD MEETS INNER DESIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SOUL OF SEX 
Cultivating Life as an Act of Love 
By Thomas Moore. HarperCollins. 307 pp. $25. 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Part monk, part psycho-therapist, part Pan, writer Thomas
Moore sets himself the task of reconciling the coarseness of
American culture with the resurgence of spirit. In his eighth book,
``The Soul of Sex,'' he plumbs the duality of body and soul, the
divide between the external world with its ``relentless pace of
time'' and the internal world of sweet desire.
</P>
<P>
   The soul has its own ambit, he believes, its sly life and its
undeniable will. In a season when the myth of Venus has been
preempted by images of that pouting cipher, Monica Lewinsky,
Moore's analysis is as welcome as a cool breeze in an overheated
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``By looking at the sexual myths we live out, and at our
spiritual attitudes,'' Moore writes at the outset of the book, ``we
will find the roots of our desires and the sources of our
satisfactions.''
</P>
<P>
   A monk for 12 years and a student of post-Jungian psychologist
James Hillman, Moore, author of the best-selling ``Care of the
Soul,'' seems perfectly poised to write about the ghosts, myths,
visions, body parts, and profane rituals that inhabit our sexual
imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   He begins from the premise that modern life is saturated with
sex. Why add to the groaning heap of literature, then? To answer,
he turns to Freud. ``He enunciated a principle I find useful: we
display outrageously and obsessively that which we do not fully
possess or have deeply at our disposal.'' In other words, the flags
of sexual liberation fly high because we have not found its heart,
or ours. Like gourmands addicted to junk food, Moore writes, we are
settling for quantity when what we want is small and real. The
potent god Eros has been debased and stripped of his allure, Moore
believes, cast out of heaven into the grimy realm of Internet sex
chats and newsstands with cellophane-wrapped magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hillman, Moore searches for mythical archetypes that have
deep symbolism. (In fact, Moore edited ``A Blue Fire,'' a book of
Hillman's writings published in 1989.) Moore also draws from Greek
and Roman myth, though his writing lacks the edge-walking thrill of
Hillman's. Moore draws from the American novel, film, and poetry,
as well: His parade of sexual archetypes includes figures like
Hester Prynne, Marilyn Monroe, and Old Coyote Woman.
</P>
<P>
   He strives for nothing less than a new ethic, one that blends
soul and spirit and pries loose the grip of prudish moralism. Moore
traces a pathway to tolerance. ``As we enter more deeply into the
soul of sex, we may be called upon to expand our ideas about what
sexuality is, allowing it to stand somewhat outside the range of
will and intention, allowing each other our private sexual
developments, all the while knowing that they are relevant to the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is a core ingredient for sexual freedom, and if Moore
had a political bent, he might have expanded his analysis to probe
individuality, rights, and responsibilities as they play out in a
social context. Instead, he retreats to myth, although his
metaphors are certainly powerful and the conclusion readily
available: Love and soul and spirit flourish in rooms of their own.
</P>
<P>
   As for sex itself, it is a ritual that demands the attentions,
ablutions, and adornments of a high priest. And as such, it can
deepen an individual encounter with the world. ``Giving ourselves
plenty of time, preparing a place, adorning our bodies, and
creating a spiritual milieu, an arena bigger than ourselves and our
`relationship,' might pull off the veils that have shrouded sex in
the shadows of biology and psychology during the recent modern
period. We can restore the mystery grasped so palpably by our
ancestors who built temples to eros in realization of our absolute
and unforgiving need for enchantment.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is less adept at dealing with the shadow side of sex. He
would have us believe that those lined up at ``adult'' magazine and
video racks are redeemed by their act of contemplation. Can the
sexual gaze ever come to rest without bringing distortions of
power? Does society's skittishness about pornography stem merely
from a history of prudishness? What about child pornography? Rape
fantasies? Moore never effectively dispatches these questions, and
skirts the intersection of pornography and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Although he notes that ``feminists have rightly complained about
the humiliation involved in the pornographic gaze,'' Moore implies
that it is because of a lack of expansiveness. ``It is not a
question of one being good and the other evil. Because of the
narrowness of our current vision, all we have of sexual imagery is
Persephone's dark side, the kind lacking altogether in innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   His solution? Limits born of tolerance and worn gently. And
recognition that the soul of sex takes on many guises, including
celibacy. Only a former monk could have the audacity to riff on
Jesus in a book about sex. Moore echoes the biblical command to
choose life, and suggests that limits allow the spirit to thrive.
Those limits should come not from convention and fear but from a
warm embrace, from the soul in sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of Jesus suggests a way of placing limits that
derives from joy and pleasure rather than fear and anxiety, limits
determined by a positive choice in life. Jesus seems to choose
joyful celibacy and then to tolerate the struggles of others to
establish their ways of being sexual and their ways of finding
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore calls for a return to the philosophy of Epicurus:
deepening simple intimacy and pleasure by honoring desire. Snapping
the leash will take courage, he implies, but it will allow us to
get on with the business of life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ellen Clegg is assistant managing editor in charge of the
Globe's regional weeklies.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
