<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTISTS-COLONY-ART-BO     07-07 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTS-COLONY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS AND CRAFT, SKOWHEGAN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MADISON, Maine _ Like any camper pining for the comforts of
home, Californian J.D. Beltran began her summer in the country by
personalizing her space. She painted her studio walls electric
blue, then built herself a keyboard stand and bookcase in the
woodworking shop down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran took her assigned job _ replenishing the campus's peanut
butter and jelly supply _ seriously, too. That and the mandate to
mingle as furiously as possible with the other 64 campers, most of
whom did not, unlike Beltran, leave a spouse behind when they left
their lofts in SoHo and Paris to spend nine weeks in rural Maine,
at the Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the immersion-exhaustion method,'' says Beltran, 38,
taking lunch in the lakeside dining hall while gazing out on the
peaceful waters of Lake Wesserunsett, a bit more than a week into
the season. ``There's a ton of socializing at first. It's good they
don't expect you to get much work done, because I've been averaging
four hours of sleep a night.''
</P>
<P>
   With no phones or televisions in the dorms, Beltran says, what
feels confining at first becomes liberating. Friends don't expect
you to return calls. Laundry gets ignored. Pick-up soccer games and
browsing in the library take the place of household chores.
</P>
<P>
   Says San Francisco painter Jennifer Mattson, who would otherwise
be working in an office this summer, ``It's rare to find a
community like this in the real world. Everyone here feels
displaced. No one worries about paying the rent or feeding the
cat.''
</P>
<P>
   In a region where summer colonies come in all shapes, sizes, and
flavors, from seaside writers' enclaves to woodsy religious orders,
Skowhegan is indeed a rare species: an established colony whose
membership changes every year.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1946 by a quartet of World War II veterans who
envisioned a seasonal think-tank run for artists by other artists,
and whose vision took shape on the grounds of a funky old Maine
chicken farm, the school, named after the nearby lumber town, has
survived fire, faddishness, in-fighting, and fiscal uncertainty to
claim a seat at the art world's head picnic table. Skowhegan, just
northwest of Waterville off Interstate 95, is the
anti-Provincetown: remote, unglitzy, devoid of galleries or
tourists. Yet in some circles of commerce, Skowhegan carries as
much name value as Sotheby's. Maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Alumni of the school include superstars Alex Katz,
Ellsworth Kelly, Robert Indiana, and Nancy Graves. Jack Levine and
Louise Nevelson taught here. So, in one fashion or another, have
Ben Shahn, Roy Lichtenstein, Frank Stella, Buckminster Fuller, Red
Grooms, Alice Neel, Claes Oldenburg, and Nan Goldin. Janine Antoni,
a resident faculty member this year, won a MacArthur grant last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding one's hubby goodbye for two months is a small price to
pay _ on top of the school's $5,200 tuition _ for a shot at joining
such an exclusive fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that. For about five minutes,'' Beltran, a
painter and video artist, says with a laugh. ``This is Skowhegan,
after all. An opportunity like this doesn't come along too often.
</P>
<P>
   For artists seeking admission to Skowhegan, as nearly 800 did
this year, portfolio counts for everything. Candidates are judged
on the originality of their work, not their college grades or
personalities. There are no preadmission interviews. Theoretically,
the class could be composed entirely of recluses and sociopaths. In
reality, the school almost forces artists out of their shells and
into a group dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Boroson, a student in 1989 who returned this summer as a
staff assistant, remembers locking himself in his sculpture studio
for the first two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' Boroson says, ``I was basically told to get out
of there and have some fun. Which I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun aside, those accepted to the program look to jump-start
their careers by exposing themselves to fresh ideas, new
surroundings, and rigorous critiques from established artists like
Antoni. The average age of this year's group is 28, with slightly
more men (36) than women (29) in residence. The typical resume
includes attendance at a top-flight arts school. The class of 1998
also continues a long tradition of multiculturalism at Skowhegan,
with a dozen countries and more than two dozen nationalities
represented.
</P>
<P>
   While a good deal of the colony's value rests in its built-in
impermanence, continuity and tradition are also important. The
300-acre campus looks much as it did in the 1950s and '60s, for
instance, with a smattering of new shed-style studios added over
the past decade. Cows and sheep still graze in the fields. At dusk,
loons call across the lake. The surrounding woods yield relics of
summers past: a dilapidated Picasso-esque treehouse; a
rubber-covered ``toadstool'' inspired by Lewis Carroll, perhaps.
Bits of magical realism hidden amid the moose tracks and
mosquitoes. Visitors, while not prohibited, aren't encouraged
either.
</P>
<P>
   Bernarda Shahn, a renowned artist and Ben Shahn's widow, has
maintained a summer home here since 1966. Now 95, she paints in her
studio every day, and until her late 80s seldom missed a Saturday
night barn dance or a visiting lecture. Styles come and go, Shahn
reflects, but the school's ``deliberately noninstitutional''
orientation helps preserve its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Says Shahn, ``Skowhegan is entirely different from any other art
school, where over time the students tend to become secondary.
Here, the students make the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the students, Shahn recalls, have been an 11-year old boy,
an artist who painted clumps of dirt, and a Swedish woman (actually
a faculty member) who decorated her body and swam across the lake,
nude, in a performance piece that startled unsuspecting sunbathers
on the far shore.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's group included a video artist who drove a car in a
local demolition derby and another who constructed a float for the &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Presque Isle Potato Festival parade. A third stole into downtown
Skowhegan one night and installed a highly unauthorized mural of
the Mike Tyson-Evander Holyfield fight (infamous for its ear-biting
episode) on a vacant storefront. The police called co-director Tom
Finkelpearl, who moved swiftly to have the offending mural removed.
</P>
<P>
   The artist ``was mad at me, but he got over it,'' says
Finkelpearl. ``Maintaining good community relations is important to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Student'' is actually a misnomer, Finkelpearl adds, since
apart from classes in fresco painting, Skowhegan offers no formal
instruction in anything. Attendees need not produce a coherent body
of work, either. Or any work at all, if they choose. Talking about
making art _ or not making art _ is as valuable as what takes place
in the studio, Finkelpearl suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do your work back in LA,'' he says. ``But you cannot
get this type of intensity anywhere else. By the end of the term,
though, people are really into what they're doing. You walk by the
studios at 2 in the morning and lights are blazing everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkelpearl, in his second full year at Skowhegan, is a low-key
CEO who pedals a mountain bike around campus wearing a Red Sox cap.
He seldom misses one of the three communal meals served daily (the
food, by the way, is excellent) and solicits constant feedback from
the group. One minute Finkelpearl is lending advice on where to buy
a keg for a weekend party. The next he's leading a discussion on
contemporary theory or public funding of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my jobs is to say yes to every artistic request,'' he
says, ``provided it's not setting fire to a dorm or something like
that. Fortunately, I don't have to do any fund-raising. We have a
New York office and a well-heeled board of trustees'' chaired by
Boston arts maven Ann Gund _ ``to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Skowhegan has seen hard times as well as good ones. In 1960,
fire gutted the original fresco barn, destroying dozens of works
and the school library. A proposal to open a Skowhegan West, in
California, was shot down. Finkelpearl says the school failed to
open one year, although he cannot remember when. Shahn recalls
``ferocious fights'' among the trustees, who help underwrite the
school's $1 million operating budget, and board of governors, a
group of artists that determines each year's participants and sets
what passes for the school's academic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Artists being artists, egotism and eccentricity are to be
expected _ even celebrated _ in a community like Skowhegan. Shahn
nevertheless credits Finkelpearl's predecessor, Barbara Lapcek, for
providing strong leadership when it was needed. In the '80s, says
Shahn, Lapcek helped neutralize a radical gay element that had some
wondering if the school would be shut down. In other years sexual
repression and racism have been the controversies.
</P>
<P>
   Says Finkelpearl, ``It feels like a new era here. The last of
the founders'' _ sculptor Sidney Simon _ ``died last year. The
current staff was not even born when the school was established.
Thanks to a booming economy, we're reasonably flush. A new era
means new opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rikki Wemega-Kwawu, 39, a painter from Ghana, Skowhegan
brought the opportunity to visit his first Western country. So far,
he says, ``it's been a wonderful interaction, like being in
paradise. We leave our doors unlocked 24 hours a day. I find this
very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   His only reservation, says Wemega-Kwawu, is walking to and from
his studio after dark. ``I don't like to because of the wildlife. I
do not know what is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He peers cautiously out the screen door of his hillside studio,
which is bathed in rich morning light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me,'' Wemega-Kwawu asks, ``are there bears around
here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
