<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ALEXIE-2TAKES-     07-07 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ALEXIE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXIE SENDS `SMOKE SIGNALS' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ Sitting in a stylishly sterile hotel cafe in this
tropical playpen, surrounded by bored tourists whose day in
paradise was just spat upon by a window-rattling thunderstorm,
Sherman Alexie is about as far away from home as he could get
without needing a passport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty wild place,'' deadpans Alexie, a tall man
with thick glasses and a searchlight grin who has seen no end of
wild places in the last six months. Author Alexie is a Native
American, of Spokane/Coeur d'Alene descent, whose film ``Smoke
Signals'' is the first feature-length film written, directed, and
co-produced by American Indians. It was a critical favorite at the
Sundance Film Festival and charmed audiences at the Nantucket Film
Festival, so lately Alexie has been a frequent flyer, usually far
from his Seattle home.
</P>
<P>
   As it begins its slow national rollout (opening Friday, July 3,
in several cities), ``Smoke Signals'' has been tagged as a prime
indie alternative to the usual summer slate of blockbusters. No
meteors follow the film's two main characters on their poignant
journey from Idaho to Arizona, and no lizards of any size prowl the
arid trailer park where Victor Joseph and his friend Thomas
Builds-the-Fire go to retrieve Joseph's father's ashes.
</P>
<P>
   In an animated interview over lunch recently, Alexie suggested
that ``Smoke Signals'' flows counter to the current Hollywood trend
not because it is so new, but because it is like so many other
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old-fashioned story. And I think that's just what's
been really appealing to people. They want a movie with a
beginning, middle, and an end,'' Alexie said, adding slyly, ``I
think we're tired of movies about good-looking white guys shooting
each other while saying clever things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Off the reservation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As ``Smoke Signals'' seeks to prove with its on-the-road scenes
of personal epiphanies, revelations can happen in the strangest
places. And like his characters, Alexie has traveled a long way
from the ``rez'' (the reservation) both physically and mentally.
That was made clearer than desert sky at the Nantucket Film
Festival. It was there, Alexie said, that he discovered the highly
autobiographical story's ability to touch an audience he never
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there would be a certain part of the audience that
would see it as quaint and think, `Oh how cute, Indians.' But in
the lobby after the screening, I was shaking hands with people and
this woman _ upper-class, Polo-wearing white woman, 50-something _
was crying. She came over to me and said, `That was a beautiful
movie. I haven't talked to my father in 12 years, and I'm going to
talk to him right now.' She walked over to the pay phone in the
lobby, dialed, and as I was standing there about 10 feet away, she
starts talking to her dad,'' Alexie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing just tore me apart in a lot of ways. It broke
apart all the stereotypes I had about a well-kept, 50-something
woman in Nantucket, the idea that their lives are perfect. My
provincial thought was obviously proven wrong at that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the film, Alexie prods the audience into examining
the flip side of prevailing ways in which Indians are misperceived.
In one wry, incisive moment, Thomas, the nerdy raconteur/con
artist, practices being more classicly stone-faced and inscrutable
in his story delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Four stories from Alexie's collection ``The Lone Ranger and
Tonto Fistfight in Heaven'' are at the heart of ``Smoke Signals.''
Possibly because it was pieced together from related but discrete
parts, the film often seems like a portrait drawn with deliberate
small strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie said he took pains not to allow the audience to fall into
the same ``Dances With Wolves'' syndrome lampooned in dialogue
between the hunky Victor and oddball Thomas, whose pairing is more
Felix-and-Oscar than Quixote-and-Sancho Panza. For the most part,
Alexie got what he wanted: altered expectations of both Indians and
of the way that most Americans see them, through the smudged lenses
of Hollywood. Alexie weaves enough false conjuring and overt cliche
about Indians into the story to leave mental cul-de-sacs for the
unwary. Still, several early reviews have proved that there's still
a long way to go before perceptions catch up to reality.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Thomas, a classic trickster who begs not to be taken
seriously. ``He comes from a long history of not only indigenous
trickster figures, but Western civilization figures,'' Alexie said.
``When he's telling his stories, they're so used to seeing a stoic
Indian storyteller standing up on a mountain that I'm not sure that
they're even listening to him. He's lying, telling jokes, making
fun of people, manipulating them. Certain people have missed the
point that he's really an unreliable narrator, telling lies and the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ironic thing is that these people prove our point, by
buying into the whole national consciousness about the way Indians
should be. Indians can be just as full of (expletive) as anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Life, art, and all that
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he washed down fragrant soba noodles with a cola, Alexie
explained that there is much of his life woven into the film.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up on the Spokane Indian reservation northwest of
Spokane, Wash., a river city near the Idaho state line. He was a
drinker, as were members of his family, and elements of the
indelible pain of alcoholism crystallized within his writing.
Alexie, 31, has penned eight volumes of poetry of varying length,
two novels, and the aforementioned short story collection, a body
of work that prompted Granta magazine in 1996 to select him as one
of the top 20 young American novelists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
