<P>
   Copy ETA: 10 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENDORSEMENT _ Another day, another Democrat. Republican
Gov. George W. Bush heads to Houston, home of former Mayor Bob
Lanier, a longtime Democrat, to pick up Lanier's endorsement.
(Herman, Austin American Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ Followup on Tuesday announcement that Ohio is the
third-worst state in the nation in letting low-income elderly know
they are eligible for federal assistance in paying for Medicare.
(Lamb, Dayton Daily News). 10.
</P>
<P>
   POLICESTUDY _ The Atlanta Police Department is heavily
criticized by the newest New Human Rights Watch report. The report
says Atlanta's police department has the weakest external review of
14 cities evaluated (including Detroit, Los Angeles and New
Orleans); the internal affairs division is cloaked in ``secrecy,''
biased, and discourages complaints by refusing to release any
information about cases; that police and the city attorney's office
don't release information and keep inadequate records; and that
Police Chief Beverly Harvard's responses were ``oblique.'' The
report from the 20-year-old non-profit organization monitoring
human rights in seventy countries worldwide is titled ``Shielded
from Justice: Police Brutality and Accountability in the United
States.'' (Longa, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GM-MEXICO _ SILAO, Mexico _ People in this small Mexican city
are discovering that the global economy gives and takes. With all
due respect, the mayor of Silao says, American General Motors
workers should stop being so demanding and ``lazy'' and get back to
work -- so that his people can also resume their jobs here. As a
result of the GM strike in the United States, most of the 2,500 GM
workers at a plant in Silao have been idled with only 50 percent
pay. Auto parts from the United States are no longer coming into
Mexico, and unfinished trucks are stacking up outside a sprawling
six-year-old factory here. Mexican workers, who are paid about $12
a day or less, are starting to get worried. Thousands of other
Mexicans who work for GM-owned Delphi auto parts plants scattered
across northern Mexico have also been idled with partial pay.
Striking American workers fear that GM wants to move even more
aggressively into Mexico, where labor is much cheaper. Analysts say
they're right. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ The ``Drug-Free America'' program
that President Clinton is launching in Atlanta this Thursday is a
nationwide series of public service announcements designed to warn
teenagers away from drugs. It is based on a pilot program
test-marketed in 12 cities, including Atlanta, that officials
called very successful. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NEW-DEMOCRATS _ WASHINGTON _ After a disastrous year recruiting
Southern Democrats to run for Congress, especially in Georgia, the
Democratic Party is looking to a handful of ``New Democrats'' from
North Carolina to Texas to lead the party back from near extinction
in the South. President Clinton will be in Atlanta on Thursday to
drum up some campaign cash for Senate hopeful Michael Coles, one of
the South's new crop of Democratic challengers hoping to topple
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   (Foskett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GROWTH _ BALTIMORE _ The National Governors Association holds a
national conference on the rapid expansion of suburbs and cities
into farmland and open space and releases a report on cities that
have had success in dealing with the problem. (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   INFOTAINMENT _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate Judiciary subcommittee
holds a hearing on he future of convergence and consolidation in
the entertainment and information industry. The heads of AT&AMP;T, ABC,
Sun Microsystems and Time Warner testify. (Joyce, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CITIES _ WASHINGTON _ The fiscal health of the nation's cities
is improving, but revenue collections are lagging behind the rate
of economic growth, the National League of Cities says in an annual
report. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Detailed information is being released on Austin and
Longview, Tex.; Elizabeth City, N.C., and Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
