<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ALEXIE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-07 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ALEXIE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MIAMI BEACH: ... American novelists.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' is based on a trip Alexie took with a friend
to get his father, except that in the course of writing, Alexie
substituted his own family for his friend's. ``That story is not
mine to tell,'' he said, cryptically, deflecting any further
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Joseph, the outgoing, tragic, force-of-nature father of
Victor, is ``a lot like my father, sort of an exaggerated cinematic
version,'' Alexie said. ``My father is at home, very much alive,
unlike Arnold.'' And unlike the lingering bitterness that haunts
Victor along his journey, Alexie said, ``My relationship with my
father has progressed to the point where I can say `I love you' and
`I'm mad at you' in the same sentence. I'd say that's a sign of
health.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's writing built bridges between himself and his father
despite causing some tension early in his career. ``At the
beginning, my family was really uncomfortable with my writing
because I was dealing so heavily with autobiographical material,
about our various dysfunctions and domestic riots, and also about
our intimate and tender moments.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed with the acclaim for his poetry (``The Business of
Fancydancing,'' published in 1992 and selected as a Notable Book of
the Year by The New York Times), his short story collection (a
citation winner for the 1994 PEN/Hemingway Award for First Best
Fiction), and his first novel, ``Reservation Blues,'' published in
1995. His family eventually realized that the attention Alexie's
work was bringing to Indian life would allow more people to
understand and connect with Indians ``on the rez and off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked the fact that so many people were identifying with
it. We didn't feel alone in our problems. We grew up in a
reservation. It's a tiny little community, so the idea of a
worldview is a luxury. My parents were worried about putting food
in the fridge. That was the daily struggle, feeding their kids.
They've seen that the stories help other people survive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A new wave?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's latest novel, ``Indian Killer,'' a dark tale about a
serial killer, is being developed as a feature film that Alexie
plans to direct beginning this fall. If ``Smoke Signals'' succeeds
in the meantime, it could set off a wave of young Native American
filmmakers and writers, in the way that Spike Lee and Robert
Rodriguez motivated African-Americans and Latinos to get behind the
camera (and money people to invest in them). It's likely that some
may be like Alexie, a lifelong film buff who planned to watch
movies from a reasonable seat-to-screen distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother and I would hitchhike from the reservation to
Spokane, about 45 miles, to sneak into movies. We'd go to drive-ins
and spend the whole evening dodging the employees, hiding in front
of cars, underneath cars. We were two cute little Indian kids, so
some people would invite us into their cars. We'd be sitting with
some strange white family watching movies, or we'd sit by one of
the speaker stands, in the dirt,'' Alexie said, putting down a
forkful of noodles and vegetables. ``Before I was married, before I
had a kid, I would wake up on a Saturday morning, get out the
newspaper, and circle the movies I wanted to see. I knew Spokane
well enough to drive from place to place to see four or five movies
in a day. I would see Jean-Claude Van Damme movies, art films _
everything. Then I would wake up the next morning and do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He never intended to write for films, or to be a writer of any
kind. He wanted to be a pediatrician. Childhood illness, as it has
many others, left him with an enduring fascination with doctors and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born hydrocephalic, so I had brain surgery when I was 6
months old and was really sick after that,'' Alexie said. ``I had
seizures, was medicated and essentially bedridden for most of the
first seven years of my life. You spend a lot of time in bed and
you think a lot. I imagined whole worlds, imaginary tribes around
me and whole lives for myself. That's really where the storytelling
started.''
</P>
<P>
   His fluidity with language helped him get a scholarship to
Washington State University _ but no tale, however mystical or
grand, was a talisman for what he would find in human anatomy
class. ``I kept fainting. I couldn't handle the smell of the
cadavers. It's not really a good bedside manner to fall into your
patients during surgery,'' Alexie laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a class to fill his schedule and in danger of losing his
scholarship, he found the only match for the open slot in his
schedule: a poetry-writing workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few classes, Alex Kuo, the professor, came up to me
and gave me an anthology of contemporary American Indian poetry. It
was a revelation. All this very specific cultural stuff that I'd
never seen written down. Then I read a line of poetry by a Piyute
Indian poet, Adrian Louis _ `I'm in the reservation of my mind' _
and for me it was like reading for the first time `Because I could
not stop for death, death kindly stopped for me' or `I sing the
body electric.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that I wanted to write, that I would spend my whole
life writing. No matter what else I had to do to make a living, I
would write. People talk about those moments happening _ I don't
think it happens much. It's more gradual, all of a sudden they wake
up and realize, `I love what I'm doing.' But for me it was a
sledgehammer to the heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
