<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROGERS-MEMORIES-BOS &LR;      07-07 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGERS-MEMORIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ROGERS, NATION'S YOUNG LEARNED TO SHOOT STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1990, driving from Las Vegas to Los Angeles, I
stopped with Dylan, my son, in Victorville, a nondescript des-ert
town in California, to see the Roy Rogers Museum, where Trigger,
the Wonder Horse, was stuffed and on display.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan didn't understand why I wanted to stop at a museum
dedicated to a guy who'd made his name selling fried chicken. I
explained to him that there was more to Roy Rogers than a
multimillion-dollar fast-food restaurant chain. When I was his age,
Roy Rogers was not only the King of the Cowboys, he was the king of
television.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the museum, under glass, were hundreds of items from Roy
Rogers's 87 motion pictures and seven-year television career. Most
of the relics would be insignificant to anyone who didn't spend
every Saturday morning in the early to mid-'50s in front of the
television set wearing a cowboy hat, a checkered shirt, a pair of
Fanner-50 cap pistols, and, if they were very lucky, boots with
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   In the days when television was literally and figuratively in
black and white and the available stations didn't hit double
figures, Roy Rogers was a touchstone for the nation's kids.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, Rogers, along with his wife, Dale Evans, and
sidekick, Pat Brady, made the world safer by capturing the bad
guys. And they did it without killing. The guns, when they did come
out, disarmed the villains. In the years the show ran _ from 1951
to 1957 _ not one drop of blood was ever spilled.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, a lot of the shows seem corny, simple-minded.
It's no wonder that, even given the plethora of cable outlets and
nostalgic television, ``The Roy Rogers Show'' is not in
syndication.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the narrator of one of his sagebrush colleagues used to
say, ``return with us now to those thrilling days of yesteryear''
because, in his time, Rogers may have influenced more children than
Dr. Spock.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many of today's so-called role models, Rogers stood
for something. He believed in doing the right thing. He believed in
standing up for the downtrodden and earning respect through
heroism. He believed in hard work and in an America where everyone
got a fair shot, because Rogers was a straight shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a boy, our parents taught us that hitting below the
belt was a cowardly thing,'' he once said. ``I don't believe this
kind of thing is `entertainment,' no matter how you look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers's philosophy seems quaint and naive in a era filled with
the hip, nasty cynicism of TV's ``South Park,'' where hitting below
the belt is the least of it. But Rogers gave those of us who used
to be kids a sense of ethics and obligation that seems so
unprofitable nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't stay long at the museum. Dylan was in a hurry because
he wanted to get to the set of his favorite show, ``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his family, Roy Rogers leaves millions of fans
whose lives were enriched by his. Happy trails to you, Roy. Until
we meet again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
