<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OZZY-BOS &LR;      07-07 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OZZY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN BEHIND THE OZZFEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine asking this question 25 years ago: Will Ozzy Osbourne
and/or his band Black Sabbath be alive _ to say nothing of working,
to say nothing of being idolized _ as the millennium beckons? Many
would have laughed it off. One of those would have been Osbourne.
``Believe me,'' says Osbourne, ``we did a good job of trying to
kill ourselves on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said to me, `Do you consider yourself a lucky guy?' I
said `I'm a hell of a lucky guy.' If my life was to end right now,
it's been one hell of a journey.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been lots of sex, drugs, rock 'n' roll _ and lots of
money made. The working-class son of a northern England family
lives in a sunny land and inhabits a tasteful manse.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy metal itself _ Osbourne's metier, a form of guitar-stoked,
oft-angry music that can be simultaneously reactionary and radical
_ has been pronounced dead ``ever since our first album,'' Osbourne
says. ``I'm here to tell you that it ain't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozzy Osbourne is the Iron Man, the godfather of heavy metal, the
now-sober icon to whom all young metal-ites turn for inspiration
and insight. And they're not the only ones seeking words of wisdom
from the 49-year-old singer-songwriter, the once and future leader
of Black Sabbath, the man whose name and legend sit atop the
multi-band bash that is Ozzfest '98, a cavalcade that comes to
Great Woods Tuesday and Thursday. Why, The New York Times
magazine &UR;  &LR; recently picked his brain for thoughts about guns and
rock. (Guns kill, rock rocks, said Osbourne, essentially, spiking
his thoughts with, as always, a few expletives the paper had to
delete.)
</P>
<P>
   All this respect going toward a man mainstream America once knew
as the crazy guy who bit into a live dove at a meeting with his
record company (he was drunk) and bit into a dead bat onstage (he
thought it was rubber).
</P>
<P>
   Ask someone who is part of the new metal breed about Osbourne.
Limp Bizkit singer Fred Durst says: ``I used to listen to him
nonstop back in the day. I used to listen to him back when I didn't
even know what a band was. He's a living legend. I can't believe he
called me up to be on the Ozzfest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevendust's drummer Morgan Rose: ``In my wildest dreams, I never
thought I'd play the same stage as Ozzy Osbourne. Ozzy did say to
me, though, `You never want to be a ... legend.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are those among the young who believe Osbourne's lost some
of the old fire _ that he's become pop-oriented and cuddly over
time _ but no one will spit at his early days with Sabbath (``War
Pigs,'' ``Iron Man,'' ``Paranoid,'' ``Fairies Wear Boots'') or
dance on his grave now. There is no grave. Literally or
figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Osbourne says he's working now to beat what he calls his last
addiction, tobacco. He's been on the patch. ``Toughest thing I've
ever had to do kick in my life,'' he growls. ``Worse than smack,
cocaine, crack, anything. I'm not all clear yet. It's too easy for
me to go out and buy a pack of cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Surprise hit
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first proper Ozzfest was last year, and it was the surprise
hit of the summer, averaging a higher ticket gross than any
multi-band tour, including Lilith Fair (which, for the entire tour,
had the highest gross). Ozzfest '98 should match its predecessor.
But it will be an endurance test for the fans. Two stages, 100 to
120 decibels of bone-crushing rock on a constant basis in summer
heat. On the main stage: Osbourne, Tool, Megadeth, Limp Bizkit,
Soulfly, Sevendust, and Coal Chamber. On the pit stage: Motorhead,
the Melvins, Life of Agony, System of a Down, Incubus, Monster
Voodoo Machine, the Snots, Kilgore, and Ultraspank.
</P>
<P>
   There are melody makers and there are melody shredders. Fast
thrashers and slow dirge-mongers. Angst-meisters and
party-heartiers. Grizzled old geezers and Young Turks. There will
be a bit of hard-edged, hip-hop-influenced metal and a bit of
art-rock metal. Lots of double-bass drum sets. The mosh pits should
be approached with elbowpads and kneepads. You'll hear about death
and destruction, drug addiction and exhilaration, war and peace,
Satan and his minions. You'll see one band emerge from a giant prop
toilet. Osbourne himself will have you happily singing along to
``Paranoid,'' a conspiracy theory every metalhead worth his salt
knew about before Mulder and Scully did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a few of the bands,'' says Osbourne about the tour
selections. ``Megadeth, Soulfly, Coal Chamber, Motorhead, the
Snots. What I want to do, especially on the second stage, is give
an unknown band a springboard, a band that wouldn't normally get
the opportunity to play in front of that many. I love passing the
torch to the next generation. It keeps me young at heart, in tune
with what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Osbourne, for one, isn't going to listen to the whole thing.
``Put it this way,'' he says. ``Even if it was an acoustic set _ if
you listened to one, two, three, four ... 15 bands, at the end of
the day you ain't gonna know what you listened to. But there's
variety there. It's not just music, though, it's for people who
like a carnival atmosphere, with sideshows. You can see the band
that you want, you don't have to leave the grounds, you can see
people getting tattooed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I do care about the welfare of the people.
I have kids of my own and if they were going to a rock concert of
any magnitude, I would be devastated if they got (messed) up on the
way home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
