<HEADLINE>
CULTURE, HISTORY _ AND CHICKEN WINGS! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's have a rousing cheer for Buffalo! And, yes, we do mean the
city in western New York. Oh, winters can be rough, but summers are
sunny and pleasant, and the city offers history and culture
aplenty. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _Presidents Millard Fillmore and Grover Cleveland were both from
Buffalo. Alas, another president, William McKinley, was
assassinated there in 1901, and Vice President Theodore Roosevelt
took the oath of office in Buffalo's Wilcox Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   _That mansion is now a National Historic Site. In addition, the
city has eight National Historic Landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   _The Albright-Knox art gallery features the work of Picasso, Van
Gogh, Warhol, Renoir, and many other celebrated artists.
</P>
<P>
   _Buffalo is the only city that boasts five homes designed by
master architect Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   _And let us never forget that Buffalo wings were created here,
at the Anchor Bar in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about the city's myriad attractions, call
800-BUFFALO.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  What is the only African country that has Spanish
as its official language? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Good advice: &LR;  A sign in a Japanese hotel room advised, ``Please to
bathe inside tub.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name:  &LR; The word ``hamburger'' is not derived from ``ham'' and
``burger'' but traces its roots to Hamburg, Germany, where people
used to eat a similar food called the ``Hamburg steak.''
Eventually, the Hamburg steak made its way to the United States,
where people shortened its name to ``hamburger.'' (With thanks to
Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass. On a separate topic, Schuster
tells us he was rooting for ``Bob'' to be the name of Canada's new
territory, but ``Nunavut'' was chosen instead.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``One would say that Elvis helped to make me what I am
today.'' _ Andrew Wilson, head of Boston Duck Tours, a successful
company that gives land-and-sea tours of Boston in renovated World
War II amphibious vehicles. Wilson says that during an odyssey
across America, he visited Elvis's Memphis, where he first saw one
of those vehicles, nicknamed Ducks, in action. With a lot of
stamina and perseverance, he got the needed permission from 29
(count 'em, 29!) government bodies to travel on Boston streets and
the Charles River. The result is one of the city's most popular
rides, with 16 brightly painted Ducks now quacking up tourists and
residents alike.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of amphibious tours:  &LR; Providence, R.I. now has
amphibious vehicles, too, but they're called Pirate Ships. Peter
Pan offers a 90-minute look at the city by land and sea, beginning
at Kennedy Plaza and Dorrance Street. For more information,
schedules, and fares, call 800-343-9999 or 401-751-8800.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag:  &LR; In response to our list of airports with fun activities,
Bill Emswiler of Walpole, Mass. writes, ``How could you leave out
the airport in Las Vegas? Where else can you lose 20 bucks playing
slots while waiting for your bags?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gaughan of Weston, Mass. notes that a joke a reader
forwarded to us about luggage traveling to several destinations is
most closely associated with Henny Youngman. But then aren't all
jokes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continuing our discussion about unusual aspects of Guinness
stout, Jim Nason of Norton, Mass. writes that a bartender in
Ireland once told him that ``you can always tell a good keg of
Guinness by the rings that are left in a glass. Every sip you take
leaves a ring. If it is (from) a poor keg, the rings wash down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Equatorial Guinea is the only African country
that has Spanish as its official language.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
