<HEADER>
A3650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIKING-SAIL-ART-BOS &LR;      07-07 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIKING-SAIL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKING CREW'S LIKING IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine days into the journey, W. Hodding Carter finds this
remarkable: He doesn't hate the boat yet.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and his nine-man crew have set sail once again on the
Snorri, a 54-foot wooden replica of a Viking ship, and are
attempting to re-create _ as authentically as possible _ the voyage
of Leif Ericsson.
</P>
<P>
   For Carter, a writer and adventurer from West Virginia and son
of former State Department spokesman Hodding Carter, the smooth
sailing so far has been a pleasure. During last year's maiden
voyage, a rudder broke while the Snorri was crossing the Davis
Strait from Greenland, and the crew was forced to abandon the
expedition. The boat was towed back to Greenland by the Canadian
Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Carter said. ``I kept fooling myself,
saying we can keep on going. We would have probably died.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carter, who says he has ``a big stubborn streak,'' decided
almost immediately to try again.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and his crew of would-be Norsemen left Nuuk, Greenland,
on June 28 and are en route to L'Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland _
the one confirmed Norse settlement in North America. The Snorri's
crew hopes to complete the 1,500-mile voyage in less than three
months, crossing the Davis Strait from Greenland to Baffin Island
and then south to Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   The Snorri, which carries crew from across New England, has no
cabin so the men sleep on deck, under tarps. &UR;  &LR; Named for the first
Viking child born in the New World, the Snorri was followed out of
port by a fleet of kayaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day was a very emotional one for me,'' said Carter. ``I
even cried a little. Tough Viking, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   The Snorri crew had a few days of sunny, warm weather to begin
the voyage. But as they sailed north along Greenland's coast, the
rains came. Over the weekend, the crew put ashore in the town of
Maniitsoq to stock up on provisions and dry out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just relentless rain,'' said crew member Doug Cabot of
Somerville by telephone from Greenland. ``After a while, it gets
just a little bit dull, a little bit depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cabot is eager to get on with the journey. He was on bow
watch when the Snorri had a close encounter with a humpback whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We passed within 10 yards of it. It did a big roll out of the
water right next to us ... spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Cabot said the crew is now engaged in ``a little bit of a
waiting game to figure &UR;  &LR; where to make the crossing'' of the Davis
Strait. That decision will be based on weather and ice conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Snorri is powered by a canvas sail and wooden oars. But the
boat is outfitted with some modern navigational aides _ radios, a
compass, and hand-held global positioning system unit, as well as a
laptop computer that can connect the Snorri to the rest of the
world via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The voyage's site on the World Wide Web
(www.beyond.landsend.com) recorded about 180,000 hits in the first
week of this year's voyage. The trip is being underwritten by
Land's End, the Wisconsin mail-order retailer, and Carter plans to
write a book.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's voyage, Carter remembers hating the Snorri,
hating the cold that made him think about chopping his hands off,
and questioning the whole idea of the voyage.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter has fallen back in love with the Maine-built Snorri,
whose rudder, as well as the crew's spirit, has been shored up.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are guys that are trying to pretend to be Vikings,''
Carter said of his crew. ``They don't know what a second thought
is. ... Last year we went into this last summer with our typical
sort of American impatience, and, as a group, we left it with a lot
more patience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snorri crew has 100 miles behind it and 1,400 ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on schedule, because we really have no schedule,''
Carter wrote. He said his crew was ``psyched. More positive than
last year even, and happy to be together again. No one has gotten
too stinky yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And, at this point in the journey, Carter still loves his boat.
``I think,'' he said, ``it has something to do with the Viking
clothes.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
