<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MOTORHEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTORHEAD: LEMMY AND TWO OR THREE GUYS WHO AREN'T LEMMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You don't see a lot of Ozzy,'' says Motorhead bassist-singer
Lemmy about what he expects to see backstage and out front at
Ozzfest. ``He just does what he does all day and comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   If Osbourne's the king of this tribe, is Lemmy, who has toured
before with Osbourne's Blizzard of Ozz, the dark prince?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he scoffs. ``I'm the jester, just the jester.'' Another
expat Brit living in LA, Lemmy used to play in the space-rock band
Hawkwind and formed Motorhead when he was kicked out _ as he was
from every other group he'd ever been in. After writing ``Kings of
Speed'' for Hawkwind, he was busted at the Canadian border for
possessing _ get ready _ speed. He formed Motorhead, a
razor-voiced, hot-rails-to-hell punk-metal machine, in part so he
wouldn't get kicked out again. He's been at this music thing for 34
years. Motorhead _ once best described as Lemmy and two or three
guys who aren't Lemmy _ are touring behind ``Snake Bite Love.''
Classic songs include ``Ace of Spades,'' ``1916,'' and ``Killed by
Death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The main secret of surviving,'' says Lemmy, ``is not stopping,
right? It's just what I want to do. I don't want to do nothing else
and I don't want to stop doing it, 'cause I'm enjoying it. Also, my
facial presentation doesn't lend itself to a lot of other jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmy and Motorhead are so well loved in the metal world, even
if they're a fringe band for many fans, that three years ago the
four guys in Metallica all dressed up as Lemmy (``bullet belts,
black shirts and trousers, shades and wigs on _ they looked more
like me than I did, but they had the tattoo on the wrong arm'') and
played his 50th-birthday bash. Iron Maiden and Marilyn Manson came.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmy figures the only reason people called Motorhead a metal,
not a punk, band back in 1976 was because they had long hair. He's
still not wholly comfortable with ``metal'' as a term for what he
does and reckons that both genres at their best are ``just
offshoots of the original rock 'n' roll, what Elvis or Eddie
Cochran would be doing if they were 18 now.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the expected metal onslaught of Ozzfest, he says of
Motorhead: ``We give 'em a break. You can't listen to that (stuff)
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   So, will Motorhead be a revelation to the unwashed and
uninitiated? ``Those who don't know us going in will know us going
out,'' barks Lemmy. ``We ain't an easy act to follow. We ain't no
day at the ... beach. We're the real thing. Without us, who would
people get to point at and blame? ... We're probably gonna get
bounced off the tour _ we always do for bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys in the Melvins _ an iconoclastic, tat-tered legend of a
band from the great Northwest, a trio once worshiped by Nirvana's
late Kurt Cobain _ share the second-stage-headlining honors with
Motorhead.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be there?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go to Ozzfest,'' says singer King Buzzo, speaking
as if he were a potential ticket buyer. ``Nothing to do with the
musical thing. ... I'm not 17, I'm 34, and there's no point to an
all-day circus freak show unless it involved actual circus
freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Melvins can entertain; the Melvins can aggravate. They can
move fast and ... very ... slow. The Melvins will mess with your
mind. ``I don't feel part of any musical scene and certainly not a
heavy-metal one,'' Buzzo says. ``We got involved basically 'cause
Tool wanted us to do it with them. ... I expect nothing from any
audience. I don't care what they think or do. But heavy metal, at
least, for all its trappings is `rebel' music, a little pointless
teenage rebellion. I do like Motorhead, but 85 percent of the bands
I haven't heard.''
</P>
<P>
   On the reflected glory from Nirvana, Buzzo says that ``99
percent of the people won't hear the connection and think we're a
stupid band. Nirvana were a big pop band. ... Hopefully, I can get
a good bird's-eye view of what the rest of these bands are doing
and do the polar opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger bands are, perhaps, not so ... prickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pretty strange band,'' explains Sevendust drummer
Morgan Rose, who describes his band as heavy spooky-core. ``When we
wrote the stuff, it was just for us, we were fans of Pantera and
Korn, but so out of the loop. We were worried we'd be too melodic
for the metal people and too heavy for the melodic people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevendust, which has been one of metal's top newcomers in the
past year or so, actually gets a bit of soul into its metal. Singer
Lajon Witherspoon, who listens to Sam Cooke and Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire,
can do more than just bark. He can croon. Sevendust ``stole'' him
from another band, and initially Witherspoon adopted a familar
metal rasp. Rose says, ``I told him, `Chill out and do what you
do.' And it's great. He's real versatile. Our chemistry is built by
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   The band has been on the road 15 straight months. Three of the
five members have lost long-term girlfriends. That's life. Their
time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna bring something you've never witnessed,'' says the
hype-minded Fred Durst of Limp Bizkit. ``No, not dancing girls.
We're coming straight from the sewer, man. We're coming out of a
gigantic 13-foot toilet! I don't think any band's ever come out of
a big ol' toilet. I'm gonna be standing in the middle, flushing
some of your favorite artists.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll also be bringing a hip-hop flavor to the proceedings.
``We're heavy and, sometimes, we're not heavy,'' Durst says.
``We're metal-influenced. A lot of people call us hip-hop
crossover, alterna-tive/metal, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   If people just know the Limp Bizkit name or maybe just heard a
tune, that's cool, says Durst. The Ozzfest is a proving ground but
not, Durst hopes, a competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's a big family thing,'' he says. ``This isn't
sports. Festivity means fun. I have no fears playing in front of
that crowd. You've gotta see us live. I think we'll gain a lot of
friends and fans.''
</P>
<P>
   And why, in 1998, three decades after its beginnings, does heavy
metal still matter?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our world today is really emotional,'' says Durst. ``And metal
music is really emotional. A lot of dynamics. A lot of anger. And a
lot of just being heavy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
