<HEADLINE>
SUMMER EVENTS ARE TITANIC AND TERRIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best things about summer is the variety of festivals
and happenings _ some titanic in scope _ to choose from. On now or
coming soon are the coolest sounds of jazz, celebrations of black
ships and sweet onions, wild thrills on Maine's rivers, and Titanic
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   If you can spare some time, head now to Montreal for the 19th
annual International Jazz Festival through July 12. And, if you
can't go now, pencil it in for next year, if you love jazz, this is
the place for it. Musicians from 15 countries are participating
this year in 400 concerts, and most sessions asre free. For
festival information, call 888-515-0515; for Montreal information,
call 800-MONTREAL.
</P>
<P>
   While many Americans have questioned President Clinton's China
trip, the Black Ships Festival in Rhode Island July 16-19 recalls a
period when Japan closed itself off from the rest of the world
except for limited trade between China and the Dutch. In 1854,
Commodore Matthew C. Perry of Newport negotiated a the Treaty of
Kanagawa between the United States and the Edo Period Shogunate,
which ended Japan's isolation and began Japanese-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the treaty, Americans with their kurofune or black
ships were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   It is these new relations that are being celebrated in Newport
with a marvelous series of events including a Festival of Drums
featuring Taiko drummers, tea ceremonies, kimono displays, Sumo
wresting demonstrations, children's events _ even Sumo workshops,
flower arranging, and many more happenings. For festival
information, call 401-846-2720.
</P>
<P>
   Maui onions are the main ingredient at the ninth annual Maui
Onion Festival July 31-Aug. 2. This Hawaiian food fest features
Maui's top chefs, free cooking classes, and entertainment. The
festival is being held at Whalers Village, the oceanfront shopping
center. For information, call 808-661-4567.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought that white-water rafting was just for the big
kids, think again. At Unicorn Rafting Expeditions in Maine, family
riverside camping trips are the fastest- growing expedition. Seems
guests from the '80s are now returning with their children. Also
new this year at Unicorn are ``Wild Women Rafting'' weekends just
for women and led by women guides. On July 15, Unicorn is opening a
new Penobscot Resort with both camping and lodging facilities. And,
if you're really into white-water thrills, ask about Generator Days
such as tomorrow's when the power company releases twice the amount
of water as usual to provide unbelieveable thrills. Call
800-864-2676.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 86 years since the Titanic went down in the cold
Atlantic, but the story of this disaster has never been hotter than
this year. In Boston, ``Titanic _ the Artifact Exhibition'' has
just opened at the World Trade Center and its well worth the $13.95
adult admission. To see some of the objects _ a vase, some jewelry,
a sheet of music, a porthole _ recovered from the wreck 2 1/2 miles
below the sea is a haunting experience and a technological wonder.
Driving home after viewing the exhibit, I couldn't get over that
from my exit on Route 2 to my home is also 2 1/2 miles _ to dive
that distance where the water pressure is 6,000 pounds per inch is
mind-bogling. The exhibit both shows respect for those who died
that night while displaying the triumphs of the technology of
exploring the oceans. For information, call 888-744-7998.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket stubs to the exhibit are also good for a discount on the
Museum of Science's showings of ``Titanica,'' a fascinating
documentary about the famed luxury liner being shown on the Mugar
Theater's five-story screen. The film includes photographs from
1912 as well as unbelievable shots of the ship as it lies on the
ocean floor today. For information, call 617-723-2500.
</P>
<P>
   At five Paramount parks _ Richmond, Va.; Cincinnati; Santa
Clara, Calif.; Charlotte, N.C.; and Toronto _ the magic of the film
``Titanic'' comes to life with a huge exhibit that includes a
collection of movie memorabilia, including props and costumes,
Rose's blue diamond necklace, Rose and Cal's stateroom, and the
Renault car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you buy a one week vacation in Rome from TNT Vacations,
you'll also get a free week in Athens. The total package, starting
at $1,299, includes air fare and accommodations. Travel agents have
details, or call TNT at 800-GO-TNT-GO.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Everyday Hero'' package is being offered firefighters,
police, and emergency medical technicians and their families by the
Holiday Inn Hotel &AMP; Suites Main Gate East in Kissimmee, Fla., Aug.
21-Dec. 25. The ``Everyday Heros'' package includes rates beginning
at $49 a room a night, a complimentary dinner with the purchase of
one at regular price, free child care and beeper rental, and
welcome gifts. For information, call 800-FON-KIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair is offering round-trip economy companion fares from
Boston and New York to Luxembourg for $525 for the first passenger
and $263 for the companion. The fares are valid for travel between
Aug. 15 and Oct. 31 and must be purchased by July 17. For more
information, call 800-223-5500.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for information on Britain? If you call the British
Tourist Authority's information service before the end of
September, you could win a free trip to England or free
sightseeing. All callers to 800-462-2748 are eligible to win the
trip on British Airways or free Great British Heritage passes good
for free or reduced entry to 500 castles, palaces and historic
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth annual ``Hidden Gardens Tour: A Cornish Ramble'' will
be hald July 11 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. The tour consists of seven
gardens in Cornish, N.H. Advance tickets are $15 and can be
obtained st Windsor House in Windsor, Vt., by calling 802-674-6752.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
