<HEADLINE>
HELPING MENTALLY ILL RETURN TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stricken with a psychiatric disorder that confined him to
society's margins, Bart Gottesdiener was certain he would never
resume his rightful place in the world, much less the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But 18 years after a bizarre compulsion caused him to drop out
of American University Law School, Gottesdiener credits a new
generation of psychotropic drugs and Boston University's Center for
Psychiatric Rehabilitation with helping him find a job and turn his
life around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've proven to myself that I can work at a reasonable job,''
said the 42-year-old Brookline, Mass. resident. ``I have a support
system now, and a home. I've come far, and it looks like the worst
is over.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every mentally ill person who puts the past behind him,
thousands more struggle to overcome symptoms that distort reality,
not to mention stereotypes that impede even the most valiant effort
to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning to work is terrifying for people with mental
illness,'' noted Larry Kohn, director of services at the Center for
Psychiatric Rehabilitation. ``There is still a tremendous amount of
stigma associated with psychiatric disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1979 by William Anthony, a psychiatric rehabilitation
professor, the center was the first in the country to attempt to
help the mentally ill reshape their lives. With the development in
1993 of Training for the Future, a computer training program, the
center expanded its offerings. But it still has the same goal: to
assist the mentally ill in using their new skills as a stepping
stone to the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to think bagging groceries or pumping gas would be
less stressful for people with mental disabilities,'' said Anthony,
the center's director. ``That was a crazy way to look at vocational
rehabilitation. Working in a job that was not interesting caused
people even more stress.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that in a society where the mentally ill are
often feared and sometimes shunned, the most difficult problem they
face is whether to disclose their past.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Considine, 26, of Holmdel, N.J., knows about such fears
firsthand. A vivacious woman whose rapid-fire speech and confident
ways contrast sharply with the person she used to be, Considine's
life was as frenzied as a roller-coaster ride eight years ago. She
went on binges, and then starved herself. She went without sleep,
and then couldn't get up at all.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the spring of 1990, Considine returned home from
college in even worse condition. &UR;  &LR; ``My parents thought I was on
drugs,'' she recalled. ``They took me to a psychiatrist and I was
diagnosed as having schizo affective disorder _ a mood and thought
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, Considine started hearing voices. She became
depressed and afraid. Voices were saying her parents hated her,
that she was going to die.
</P>
<P>
   Several new drugs relieved Considine's depression, stabilized
her moods, and put an end to the hallucinations, but there was a
void. She wanted a job, an apartment, a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Considine attends computer classes at the center, where
she is learning Microsoft Windows, Microsoft Word, and other
computer programs designed to prepare her for future employment.
Even so, there have been moments of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the workplace is the main issue to deal with,''
Considine said. ``When I worked part time, people would ask why I
wasn't working full time. When I worked at a department store, my
hands shook because of the drug I was on. The store manager called
me in and asked if I had epilepsy. I made up some story.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not tell the truth? ``I couldn't imagine finding a
sympathetic ear, or a reliable person to talk to,'' she said
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1993 after IBM donated 15 computers and technical
assistance, Training for the Future is the brainchild of Kohn. With
little more to go on but an idea, he raised $112,000 from Lotus
Development Corp., Gillette, Houghton Mifflin, Polaroid, and other
companies. A $50,000 donation from Boston University provided the
seed money for a computer laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn gave each student in the first 15-member class a $6,000
scholarship. Since then, 56 people have graduated and 75 percent
are employed at Boston firms.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Laura Davis, a 23-year-old purchasing assistant at
the New England Aquarium. The center's job developer, Rob Salafia,
met with Davis several times before she went on an interview, and
he placed her in internships designed to ease her into competitive
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Using role playing, he taught Davis, who suffers from
depression, what to ask during an interview, how to dress, and how
to develop good listening skills. Then he secured a job commitment
from Steve Wong, purchasing agent at the aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers want to know what to expect from the new employee.
How does the person handle stress, and what are their functional
limitations?'' said Salafia. ``Graduates want help with
transitions. So I act as their coach and counselor. My role is to
build trust on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a Boston Globe staff member. She can be
reached at The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107, or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
