<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINE WILL SKIP TRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once was enough for Sonny Hine.
</P>
<P>
   The irascible trainer of Skip Away took one trip to the West
Coast with his charge, the leading candidate to be Horse of the
Year, and watched him win the $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup June
28. But he's not going back, and the $1 million Pacific Classic at
Del Mar Aug. 15 is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I take him all the way back out to California again, I may
blow my chance to make the Woodward, Jockey Club Gold Cup, and,
maybe, even the Breeders' Cup,'' said Hine, who has Skip Away
stabled at Belmont Park. ``After seeing what the last trip to
California did to him, I'm no longer that high on the Pacific
Classic. I'd rather run on the East Coast than the West Coast. If
they want to win a championship (hello, trainer Bob Baffert and
Silver Charm), let them come through New York.''
</P>
<P>
   There was once a chance that the long-anticipated matchup
between handicap champion Skip Away and 3-year-old champion Silver
Charm would come in the Pacific Classic. But that confrontation was
already in jeopardy since Silver Charm is recovering from a fever
that negated a late decision by Baffert to take Skip Away on in the
Hollywood Gold Cup. Silver Charm is supposed to be on the shelf
until near the end of the month and whether Baffert can get enough
training into him to make the Pacific Classic is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Hine is now looking toward the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Park
Aug. 30 for Skip Away. However, there will have to be some major
changes in the Iselin if the big gray, who has won seven in a row
dating back to last year's Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont, is
going to compete. The Iselin is run at a mile and one-16th, short
by classic standards, and the now-retired Formal Gold simply
outsprinted Skip Away at that distance in last year's Iselin. Hine
wants the race lengthened to a 1 1/8 miles, and he wouldn't mind if
the purse, a modest $250,000 for a horse of Skip Away's quality,
was increased. ``If they don't change the distance, I'm not in,''
he said. ``They came to me, I didn't go to them. I think they
should do what they need to do to bring people in.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if Hine's wishes will be fulfilled. ``We'll do
everything we can to pull off what would be a major event,'' said
Monmouth vice president Bob Kulina. ``Obviously, the distance is a
question Sonny had. There's a lot of stuff we have to sleep on.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't work out with Monmouth, Hine will consider the
$400,000 Whitney Handicap at Saratoga Aug. 8. The Whitney is run at
1 1/8 miles and Skip Away finished third in it last year, behind
Will's Way, who is also retired, and Formal Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, Hine wants Skip Away to make the $500,000 Woodward
Stakes at Belmont Sept. 19, a 9-furlong race around one turn that
he lost to Formal Gold last year in what was his last defeat.
That's the spot where Skip Away may finally meet Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iselin would be fine as a prep for the Woodward,'' said
Hine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Trick' disappears
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick, who was named Horse of the Year as a 2-year-old
over Skip Away last year in a display of poor judgment by many
Eclipse Award voters, has not run since his sorry eighth-place
finish in the Kentucky Derby May 2. Favorite Trick, who is
basically a miler, was knocked out by the 10-furlong Run for the
Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bill Mott is considering bringing Favorite Trick back in
either the Dwyer Stakes at Belmont July 12 or the Long Branch
Stakes at Monmouth July 19. Both events are at a mile and one-16th.
``I prefer to run my horses in New York,'' said Mott. ``This is
where I am based, and I don't like to ship too often. But Favorite
Trick was slow coming back from the Kentucky Derby, and then he
bruised his foot and we lost some training with him. The Dwyer was
his goal but I'm going to have to see if he needs an extra week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Free' debut on tap
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House, who had a terrific 1997 season, is scheduled to make
his '98 bow in the $100,000 Bel Air Handicap, at a mile and
one-16th, at Hollywood Park Saturday. Free House has not raced
since bleeding profusely while finishing sixth as the 3-5 choice in
the Super Derby at Louisiana Downs Sept. 28. A powerful gray, Free
House attested to his readiness with a 5-furlong breeze in 1:003/5
under Chris McCarron at Hollywood Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Free House, a son of California sire Smokester, won $1,336,910
in purses last year, taking the San Felipe, the Santa Anita Derby
over Silver Charm, and the Swaps. He was third in the Kentucky
Derby, second in the Preakness, and then third again in the Belmont
Stakes. He was also third in the Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Girl' can get Tiara
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jersey Girl, a New Jersey-bred daughter of Belong to Me, can
become the ninth 3-year-old filly to sweep Belmont's Triple Tiara
if she can win the Coaching Club American Oaks July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by Ackerley Brothers Farm and trained by Todd Pletcher,
Jersey Girl took the 1-mile Acorn June 7, and then the 1 1/8-mile
Mother Goose June 27, in which she defeated Kentucky Oaks winner
Keeper Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-BOS &LR;      07-07 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS IS GOOD FOR MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Half the fun of watching Mark McGwire is the joy of
watching him swing. His muscles flex, then the swing is set in
motion. On contact, there is a crack, and the ball soars skyward in
a high arc. If he has hit it just right, it comes gently back to
earth among a sea of smiling faces in the stands. It is something
to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Exciting to everyone except McGwire himself. The longtime
American League slugger who now is in the employ of the St. Louis
Cardinals, wishes people would remember that he has no overriding
interest in home run chases or the surrounding hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is just a job. If the fans get a kick out of the way he
works, fine. But keep things in perspective if he gets close in the
chase of Roger Maris for the record for home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job,'' McGwire said recently in Cincinnati. ``I do it
every day. This is not a show. But I think it's good for the game
that fans are coming out to watch what I do, particularly in
batting practice. I don't do anything differently coming out for
work than I've done in the last 11 years. I have things to work
on.''
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke to a room full of media at Cinergy Field over the
weekend, he made sure to get across a simple message. Yes, his 37
home runs at the break suggest another 50-plus homer season and a
realistic chance to surpass Maris's mark of 61 in 1961. But don't
put the horse before the cart, at least until September. His total
tied Reggie Jackson (1969) for the highest total before the
All-Star Game. But remember, he's not the only slugger on the
block. Don't forget Ken Griffey of the Mariners and Sammy Sosa of
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very talented,'' said McGwire. ``Griffey has been
doing it for years. Sosa has been coming into his own for the last
several years. It's great. I love watching it. The only home run
any of us can look forward to is the next one. See me if somebody
has 50 and it's September.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did things this way in 12 years in the AL, and has
continued in the National League. He won't change, but that is not
a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is one of two cities in which he has not homered.
Each day of the recent series, he put on a show at batting
practice, once hitting one 452 feet into the third deck. He drew
extra fans, and helped sell a lot of hot dogs. But it didn't help
the Cardinals, as the Reds did not pitch to him, and won all three
games.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire got only one hit in six at-bats. He walked six times _
twice intentional. Saturday, with two out and the bases empty in a
4-4 game, he was walked by Reds manager Jack McKeon, who said he
only had done that to one other player, Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire knows he will have to deal with more of this down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing the game I love to play,'' he said. ``And when I
play, I know what to do. That's my domain. Players only have
control over what we can do to prepare ourselves for the game. We
don't know what we're going to do in the box. Realistically, we
understand we can't get a hit every day. You try to make
adjustments and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was born to bash. Even since his 49-home run season as a
rookie in 1987 at Oakland, he has been one of the game's premier
sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   But the NL crowds are not as familiar with McGwire, half
expecting the 6-foot-5-inch, 250-pounder to be a monster. They are
delighted to discover how intelligent, friendly, and unique he is.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had a lifetime .260 average at the start of the season,
with 387 home runs. He won a World Series ring in 1989. Tonight is
his 10th trip to an All-Star Game, his fifth as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   It's his job, his lifestyle, and he had no problems with taking
part in last night's home run derby, or signing autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says, ``Everything I've read recently is about
individuals. But this is a team sport. No one individual is going
to win a game for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I say, what Griffey says, and what Sosa says is the same
thing. The most important thing is winning. Sometimes people lose
track and put a lot of emphasis on the home run. I've never been
like that. It's still overwhelming for me and for those guys,
too.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Easier said than done
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, not a lot of people paid attention to McGwire, who
had a nice season for Oakland with a .284 average and 34 home runs.
In July, time was winding down on the final year of a five-year
contract. The A's had to make a move or lose him to free agency. So
McGwire was traded to St. Louis for pitchers T.J. Mathews, Eric
Ludwick, and Blake Stein.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit 24 home runs for St. Louis the rest of the way for a
total of 58, the most since Maris in '61. Coupled with the 52 he
hit in 1996, he joined Babe Ruth as the only men to have
back-to-back 50 home run seasons. How tough is that? Ask
Baltimore's Brady Anderson, who hit 50 in '96 and 18 the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire didn't have to return to St. Louis this year. It is a
big ballpark in which for years speed, not power, was a key
consideration. But in his brief tour on the Mississippi River,
McGwire had fun playing for the St. Louis fans and his longtime
manager in Oakland, Tony La Russa. The deep sense of tradition,
missing in Oakland, intrigued him. Thus McGwire signed a
three-year, $28.5 million contract in the offseason, with an option
that could boost it to $40 million. He has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' said McGwire. ``Certainly not just because it
looks easy. I prepare myself mentally, and use my mind as well as
my talent. Some of the physical stuff we go through that people
don't know about is incredible. I know my swing like the back of my
hand. I'll make the adjustments when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about the home run. But the home run does not
control the game. It's the players themselves. I've seen it. There
is so much pressure on Sosa, Griffey, and myself right now. Yeah,
it's a great thing. But the media is building it up like it's
supposed to be done. And yet, this is the toughest thing of all to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Reds drew 41,302 to see McGwire's first visit to
their stadium, one of only two where he has failed to homer (Turner
Field is the other). The game drew a walkup crowd of 9,338, the
Reds' most since 1974. McGwire walked twice and went 0 for 1. The
fans booed their own team when an intentional pass was issued. They
like McGwire and wanted to see him go deep. More curiosity seekers
showed up Saturday. Three walks. It was more of the same Sunday.
No, it isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do enjoying playing the game,'' said McGwire, ``but I've
never been a guy who liked to be singled out. The good Lord gave me
the ability to do certain things, and I have acccomplished some
things. But you won't find me talking about the home run record.
Nobody is close to it. The only thing we're close to is the next
home run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(September) is when somebody has a legtimate shot at it. Until
then, it's just speculation. Seems like every year I've played,
there has been somebody near or over 30. Everybody talks about it,
but let's be realistic.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Comfy surroundings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chances of the record falling aren't as dismal as McGwire
might want you believe. Despite its distant fences, Busch Stadium
is the site of 19 of his 37 homers this season. His teammates
admire him. His reunion with La Russa means he has a manager who is
as experienced with the pressures as he is, and he's also a friend.
He has had the benefits of Barry Weinberg, the Oakland trainer for
16 years, who has joined him in St. Louis. McGwire has only missed
one series (June 2-4 against the Dodgers) with back spasms, and
avoiding injury will be crucial in the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually goes out just once a year and then it is no
problem,'' said Weiner of McGwire's back. ``The key, of course, is
the hard work he does every day. You wouldn't believe how hard he
works. Mark takes good care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa says the McGwire of today is an even better player and
person than the one he was first introduced to in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better now, no matter where he is,'' said La Russa. ``He
keeps on improving. He's a little tougher putout, too. He's
swinging better. The big difference is in his thinking. His
concentration is locked in and he doesn't throw at-bats away. Day
after day. That's why he's going to be great under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis hitting instructor Dave Parker feels the same way. He
not only monitors McGwire's batting practice ``show'', but also the
media that might try to break his concentration. McGwire is no
longer complaining about being a ``caged animal'' during BP.
</P>
<P>
   Parker played with McGwire early in McGwire's Oakland career and
said, ``When you look at him now he's more compact. He's got a
shorter swing, and he's a lot stronger. He doesn't have to worry
about anybody bothering him, anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa says that no matter how things turn out, McGwire is the
right guy to make a run at the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he takes batting practice,'' says La Russa,``he's putting
a lot of pressure on himself. But you know he does it because he
knows people are here, he's a good guy, and he doesn't want to let
them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his pluses to our club is he gets the ball into the air
for distance. I don't want him chopping down, and we're not playing
hit-and-run. His ability is his team thing. He's not being selfish
to enlarge his zone. He'll take a walk just to get a rally going.
When you do that, it's team baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
