<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MOUNTIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE HEROES IN SCARLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ The Mountie was big. Seriously big.
</P>
<P>
   And full of hot air. If he were real, the 150-foot-high hot-air
balloon shaped like a Royal Canadian Mounted Police officer atop a
horse would weigh 450 tons.
</P>
<P>
   So when this odd apparition &UR;  &LR; made its debut at a festival
earlier this summer high above Canada's capital city, the cheers
from the crowd were thunderous.
</P>
<P>
   But then, nothing less spectacular would do for this occasion,
the 125th anniversary of the RCMP _ a police force with a cachet
that goes far beyond its official federal, provincial, and
municipal law-enforcement duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one thing to remember about us,'' says retired Deputy
Commissioner William Kelly, who joined the force in 1933. ``Other
police officers are known as cops. We're known as Mounties. And
there's one heck of a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly they've had their share of criticism and embarrassment
_ such as the night in Ottawa in 1995, when RCMP officers guarding
the official residence of Prime Minister Jean Chretien took a full
seven minutes to respond to a telephone call by Mme. Chretien that
a knife-wielding intruder was outside their bedroom door. (By the
time the Mounties got there, the prime minister had been forced to
arm himself with the only weapon he could get his hands on, the
Inuit soapstone sculpture near his bedside.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's probably no other Canadian institution so
glorified inside Canada and famous outside of it than the trusty
scarlet-coated Mounties with their lantern jaws and romantic
history of heroic deeds _ a history that dates to 1873 when the
force was formed to maintain order as settlers swept into the
western frontier. With their crimson coats, trusty steeds, and the
mission to ``always get their man,'' the Mounties have attained the
implausible status of pop culture icon. (Think of Dudley Do-Right,
Sergeant Preston of the Yukon, the musical Mountie chorus of
``Monty Python.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to get excited about Massachusetts state
troopers, but somehow the Mounties caught on,'' says Bernard A.
Drew, a writer and author of the 1990 book ``Lawmen in Scarlet: An
Annotated Guide to Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Print and
Performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had their scandals in recent years, but somehow they
clicked, whereas the national law body in India or Brazil never
did.''
</P>
<P>
   So all the stops are being pulled out this summer and fall for
the anniversary milestone, the so-called ``One-Two-Five.'' A
commemorative Mountie silver dollar has been issued.  &UR;  &LR; A Mountie
postage stamp will soon be released. A new RCMP history book, ``Red
Coats on the Prairies,'' has just been published. Even the RCMP's
antidrug campaign has gotten a facelift, featuring new bumper
stickers that depict a horse and say ``Say Neigh to Drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the elaborate Mountie festivities _ more than
500 public events through October, from community picnics to bike
rodeos. What the public will see is vintage RCMP: colorful,
patriotic, and loaded with pomp and ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Especially The Ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Musical Ride, as it's more properly known, is the Mounties'
piece de resistance. Among the last links with RCMP early history,
it is a 25-minute riding display performed by 32 Mounties in formal
RCMP dress (red tunic, Sam Brown belt, Stetson hat, and high brown
boots.)
</P>
<P>
   Developed from traditional cavalry drill movements, inspired by
British tradition, the first known riding display was given in
1876, ostensibly as a way for the officers to break up the monotony
of patrolling the plains in the dead of winter. In 1904, it became
a regular form of public entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Mounties take their show on the Canadian road from May
through October, plus some American stops and occasionally a
European tour. An estimated 1 million people annually flock to see
it. There is scarcely a child in Canada unfamiliar with the image
of a scarlet-coated Mountie on a black horse with a maple leaf
stenciled on its rump. The pageantry of the elaborate maneuvers,
many executed with medieval-looking lances and pennants, never
fails to wow the crowd _ and often the riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets me every single time we lower the flag,'' says
Katherine  &UR;  &LR; Simard, one of seven women riders in the equitation
unit. ``When I see those little faces (in the audience) beaming up
at me, I cry every time.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Mounties are scheduled to perform at three
American locations. (see below). ``But our main mandate is to show
for the Canadian public,'' says Corporal Bill Stewart, a horse
trainer with the Mounties for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Canada love it,'' says William Beahan, coauthor
of the new Mountie history book ``Red Coats on the Prairies.''
``It's a big boost to the community. I don't think Canada would
ever let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for this love affair is that the Mounties are
so deeply ensconced in Canadian culture. The children of Canada
even get to name the Mountie horses in an ongoing ``Name the Foal
Contest.'' (Approximately 15,000 entries pour in each year, with
names like ``Patrol'' and `Pulsar'' and ``Pichou.'') It doesn't
hurt, either, that the Mounties have a bit of the royal touch. Part
of the mounted unit's official function is providing mounted
escorts for Queen Elizabeth and other visiting dignitaries. ``We're
very close to the queen, horsewise,'' says Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the music is canned (the RCMP band was disbanded a
few years ago due to budget cutbacks) and the show is, by today's
standards, low-tech and even a little hokey: At a recent ``sunset
ceremony'' here, the horses and riders stood at attention while the
emcee led the crowd in a rousing rendition of ``Happy Birthday to
Us.''
</P>
<P>
   But this seems to matter not a whit to Canadians. ``I'm proud
it's not so glitzy,'' said one woman who saw the show and who asked
not to be identified, for fear of offending the Mounties. ``If the
Americans got their hands on it, it would be a Vegas revue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MUSICAL RIDE SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following is a partial schedule of RCMP Musical Ride locations
this summer and fall in Canada and the United States. Note: Many of
these dates are tentative. To confirm locations and times, call
613) 993-2621.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calgary, Alta. July 8,9,10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlottetown, PEI, Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   _ Halifax, NS, Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Woodstock, NB, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   _ Montreal, Quebec, Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ottawa, Ont. Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rutland, VT., Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Topsfield, MA (Topsfield Fair) Oct. 5,6,7,8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Woonsockett, RI (Autumn Fall Fair) Oct. 10,11,12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE MOUNTIES IN POPULAR CULTURE.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bernard A. Drew, author of ``Lawmen in Scarlet: An Annotated
Guide to Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Print and Performance,''
has calculated that the Mounties have made appearances in more than
500 works of fiction and 200 films.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Porky of the Mounties'': 1944 Porky Pig Dell comic book.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rose Marie'': 1936 movie starring Jeanette Macdonald and
Nelson Eddy, who played a Mountie assigned to arrest a fugitive who
had killed a Mountie. Songs include ``Indian Love Call.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Sergeant Preston of the Yukon'' series: A half-hour
radio show in the 1950s and later a television show about a Mounted
Police officer and his dog.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dudley Do-Right, a cartoon Mountie who was a contemporary of
Rocky and Bullwinkle on the ``Rocky and His Friends'' TV show.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Due South'': A syndicated TV comedy-drama about a Mountie
transplanted to the mean streets of Chicago. Includes lots of jokes
about the Canadian-American culture clash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
