<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUDUBON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDUBON LEGACY TAKES FLIGHT AT NEW BEDFORD ART MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE AUDUBON LEGACY 
At the New Bedford Museum of Art, 
680 Pleasant St., New Bedford, through July 19. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ Just entering its second year this summer,
the New Bedford Museum of Art continues to make a virtue of
necessities. It has no comprehensive core collection, it is run by
part-time paid staff and volunteers, and its most noticeable
architectural feature is a huge bank vault that dominates one end
of its downstairs gallery. Its single most important physical asset
is a complete Elephant Folio edition of John James Audubon's
``Birds of America,'' which technically belongs to the New Bedford
Public Library, across Pleasant Street from the museum, but which
the museum has undertaken to restore, preserve, and present. Local
citizens and corporations have donated at the rate of $1,000 per
image to bring the Audubon plates up to archival standards and put
them in elegant frames.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's first show (through July 19) relies on all the
museum's assets. Eighteen of the magnificent Audubons are on
display on the ground floor of the museum. A volunteer curator has
assembled a complementary show of commissioned work related to,
relying on, reflective of, the Audubon prints. And the bulk of the
commissioned works, gathered as ``The Audubon Legacy,'' are hung
inside the huge downstairs vault, the museum's signature space for
new and untraditional artworks.
</P>
<P>
   The real legacy of Audubon is difficult to describe. He was
hardly the greatest bird artist of his century, let alone all time
(whatever that means). His near-contemporary Edward Lear (better
known for light verse) was a defter draftsman and capable of
putting the birds in more lifelike positions. Aubudon's birds are
often beautiful, but less often are they posed in entirely
believable situations and postures. That said, his work completely
outclassed anything that came before him.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, focusing on Audubon's life, not just his art, is a
blessing for the 18 artists who accepted commissions to take
Audubon's legacy and create their own works. Audubon is an
excellent illustrator, but an artist coming after him is not
overwhelmed by Audubon's mastery. What really inspires in Audubon's
work is his persistence, his absolute faith in his own grand
vision, his insistence on perfection as he defined it.
</P>
<P>
   Audubon chose the Elephant Folio, with a single rectangular
sheet over a yard wide, because he could fit the largest American
bird on the format in life-size. This worked well for everything
but very long-necked birds, which had to be posed in contorted, if
theoretically possible, stances. His flamingo seems to have been
the prototype for Lewis Carroll's croquet set, where the birds were
unwillingly twisted into both mallets and wickets.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Backes, a landscape painter, curated the legacy show by an
inventive method, not in the usual tradition of wildlife art. She
visited New Bedford and Boston galleries, found artists whose work
she liked, regardless of subject matter or medium, and commissioned
them to work off, with, through, even around, the Audubon theme.
What she ended up with was not a show about birds (though there is
a bird, or part of a bird, in every work) but a show about
translating nature into art, or letting nature inform art.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most Audubon-like works is Roger Kizik's ``Perusing
Puffins,'' except that Kizik's quizzical bird (the puffin is an
inherently comical animal) isn't contemplating its mate or staring
at the ocean (Audubon's birds occasionally have rather unfocused
poses). Kizik's puffin is reading the first page of James Joyce's
``Ulysses,'' where stately, plump Buck Mulligan emerges from the
bath, about to shave blasphemously.
</P>
<P>
   A work inspired by the Audubon portrait of the passenger pigeon
(alive and thriving by the millions when he painted it) is
necessarily transformed by the bird's subsequent extinction. Diane
Horton's complex-media painting (oil alkyd/ &QC; 
wax on wood) has transferred the repeated image of the passenger
pigeon into a very manipulated surface that forces the bird to
recede into a limbo that can stand for, but not stridently comment
on, extinction. She does this with stenciled drawings on canvas
that are overpainted, rubbed out, redrawn, glazed, sanded down,
wiped, varnished again, and that end up both optically and
physically layered.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Bertoni, a sculptor, leapt at the chance for a
post-Audubon moment, since she has been fond of birds, and pileated
woodpeckers in particular, since childhood. The pileated is the one
that looks like, and in fact sounds like, the cartoon character of
Woody Woodpecker. The difference is that the real pileated is about
as serious a bird as one ever encounters. Her simple sculpture, of
found wood and paint, astonishes a viewer who enters the vault.
Even from a distance it is clearly an abstraction, and somehow it
still looks as though a real pileated woodpecker, or perhaps the
mummified remains of one, had found its way into the bank's most
protected space. In fact, one would do just as well, if not better,
using Bertoni's sculpture as a visual aid to identify a real
pileated woodpecker than if one had a copy of Audubon's plate of a
family of the things. Bertoni has got what British birders call the
``jizz'' of a bird, its visual and behavioral persona, exactly
right.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities for a show of Audubon legacies have hardly
been exhausted by this satisfying exhibition. There are a few
hundred more birds to use as inspiration, and it would also be
possible to assemble a show of artists working in the
representational manner of Audubon. He has his followers, and some
of them at least equal, if not surpass, the master. A show of
Audubons hung alongside paintings by the greatest bird artist of
the early 20th century, Louis Agassiz Fuertes of Cornell
University, would be a revelation. Fuertes's work is seldom seen
except as illustration plates, as in the two-volume, long-
out-of-print works ``Birds of Massachusetts'' and ``Birds of New
York.'' And there are dozens more artists painting birds with
Audubon's passion. As satisfying and enlightening as ``modern'' art
can be, a museum with a core of representational work could
consider celebrating those schools of painting and sculpture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
