<HEADLINE>
CAUTION NEEDED IN NET BANKING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theres's been lots of talk about investment scams over the
Internet. Now there's a new frontier _ bogus bank sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Bank regulators have begun surfing the Net looking for
fraudulent Internet bank sites. They're especially concerned about
ones that are likely to be confused with the sites of legitimate
banks that have opened up in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high-value target, so there's a lot of incentive for
people to duplicate,'' said Bill Carr, a partner at KPMG Peat
Marwick in Houston, who heads the firm's information risk
management practice for the Southwest region. ``You can pull in
funds from all over the U.S. and from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which insures bank
deposits, recently launched a ``Suspicious Internet Banking'' Web
site to help consumers detect potentially fraudulent banking
activity in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it hasn't been a big problem. FDIC officials said that
last year, regulators caught six fraudulent bank Web sites, none of
which was in Texas. One in the Southeast had collected $650,000 of
consumers' money.
</P>
<P>
   Texas hasn't experienced serious problems with fake bank sites,
but that is no guarantee you won't reach one from your PC at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could easily happen because the Internet is global,'' said
Catherine Ghiglieri, Texas banking commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for a hacker to duplicate someone else's Web site and
have it look legitimate, Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   Before doing business with a bank on the Internet, go to the
FDIC's Web site at www.fdic.gov.
</P>
<P>
   After clicking on ``Consumer News'' or ``Banking News,'' click
on ``Suspicious Internet Banking'' and go to the FDIC's
institutions search engine. There you will find instructions on how
to use the search tool.
</P>
<P>
   On the site, you can find out whether a bank is a legitimately
chartered, FDIC-insured institution and you also can report
suspicious bank Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're saying they're a bank and they're not a bank,
that's illegal,'' said David Barr, FDIC spokesman. ``If they're
indicating that they have FDIC insurance and they don't, that's
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDIC also posts on its home page Web sites found to be
fraudulent and special alerts on unauthorized banking operations in
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find them on the FDIC site, you also can check out
a bank on the Texas Department of Banking's Web site at
www.banking.state.tx.us/.
</P>
<P>
   Fraudulent entities also will try to disguise themselves through
subtle changes such as using a derivative of a legitimate bank's
name that's close enough to the real thing that you wouldn't notice
anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they may call themselves ``Citicorp N.A. (which
means it's a nationally chartered bank).'' The problem with that
name is that Citicorp is the name of the holding company. Citibank
is the name of its bank operation.
</P>
<P>
   Scam artists are often quicker than regulators and their lists.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they're not on a warning list, make sure they act like a
legitimate bank.
</P>
<P>
   One way to spot a questionable bank is how it pitches its
products to you. It's a red flag if the institution offers
abnormally low rates on loans or extraordinarily high interest
rates on deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking 6, 7 or 8 percent; we're talking 18, 19
percent interest rates,'' Barr said. ``A lot of them claim they do
this because their operating costs are lower. Granted, that is
true, but they're not that much lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Another warning sign is if the bank's Web location doesn't have
a direct address such as ``www.bank.com,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like `geocity.jonesborobank.com,''' he said.
``Usually, if it's a real bank, it would be
`www.jonesborobank.com.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pay close attention if the bank lists a post office box instead
of a street address. There's a reason why fraudulent operations do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, the cops don't have an office, a house or a building
to raid,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, just because a bank operates only on the Net
doesn't mean it's trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But understand that there are only about three pure Internet
banks out of the 10,800 FDIC-insured banks in the nation, Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that helps cautious consumers is that a bank must have
a charter to do business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
