<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTER-BANKS-SURF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA'S OUTER BANKS OFFER HAVEN FOR LAND-BOUND SURFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With OUTHER-BANKS-TOURISM.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REX BABIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. _ As the discussion rambled on, I began to
understand why superior surfboard shapers are so revered in the
surfing community. This was better than going to a Park Avenue
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear that we were talking less about templates and
outlines and rocker and volume of surfboards and more of making
peace with my life as a surfer from Albany, N.Y. Strange as that
sounds, it's possible to live in upstate New York and surf.
</P>
<P>
   Pouring out of me, like water out of a grommet's nose after a
morning session, was the story: How I was born and spent most of
the first 25 years in California (a stone's throw from the Pacific)
and much of that time surfing. How career choices led to the least
likely of surf towns. Having to adapt to not having an ocean in the
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   We reflected on the fact that while living in California, the
surfing was limited primarily to local breaks. Since leaving, it's
had to be more creative.
</P>
<P>
   Living in Albany has required traveling to surf spots. This is
not altogether a bad thing. In fact, I have found it liberating,
and a pleasure to be part of a fledgling group of upstate New
Yorkers who surf. Several of us have gathered at 5 a.m., loaded my
Jeep down with surfboards and have driven four hours to the coast,
usually New Hampshire or Rhode Island (the most direct, accessible
spots). Once there, we surf for six hours, only to turn around and
drive the four hours back to Albany.
</P>
<P>
   It is satisfying to help someone catch a wave for the first
time. Someone who will forever know the out-of-body sensation when
human energy becomes a part of some larger fundamental transfer of
energy. A wave is energy, after all. A worldly one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing, then, is simply employing the laws of physics,
exploiting and redirecting that energy through the use of floatable
devices.
</P>
<P>
   The sensation, described as a rush by surfers, comes as the
larger force overtakes the human effort and lifts the surfer up, as
if by the hand of God. The feeling is just as thrilling after 20
years of surfing as it was on that first memorable wave. There is a
look of pure, childlike joy on the faces of people who connect with
that pulse of energy for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Not having a local break also means adopting world famous breaks
as my own, scheduling vacation time around exotic surf
destinations: North Shore of Oahu; Puerto Escondido, Mexico; and
Pichelemu, Chile, among them.
</P>
<P>
   But one place stands as my Cape Hatteras on the Outer Banks of
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it sits on the Eastern Seaboard of the United States
and, therefore, just south of a most populous corridor, the
onslaught of ubiquitous development, and the misfortune of having
Jesse Helms as U.S. senator, it's possible to find there a slice of
the most pristine, flawless stretch of coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Hatteras is one of the continuous barrier islands that run
along the East Coast from Maine to Georgia. The narrow strands of
sand, dunes, and adapted vegetation, on the front line of hurricane
assaults, migrate steadily south with the winds, tides, and
currents. Slammed in the winter by nor'easters only to face
tropical storms and hurricanes' havoc in the late summer and fall,
the Banks' mercurial weather precipitated hundreds of shipwrecks
off its coast, earning it the nickname ``The Graveyard of the
Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   The legend goes that pirates walked horses with lanterns along
the beach to imitate ships at sea to lure unsuspecting vessels onto
the shallow shoals to plunder. ``Boilers,'' a popular surf break,
resulted from a sunken ship, its boiler still visible above the
waves like a bobbing tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   For years, because of harsh conditions, few lived out there.
Year-round populations are still small, with permanent communities
in Buxton, Frisco, and Hatteras on the widest, most protected parts
of Hatteras Island, and Okracoke, on the bayside of that island.
The few locals who are around are generally mellow, described by
professional surfer Shea Lopez in a surf magazine as ``the nicest
bunch of hicks you'll find.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not primitive, this is distinctly not Cape Cod, the
Hamptons, or Jersey Shore. Fleeing the overrun Nag's Head and Kitty
Hawk, cross the Oregon Inlet Bridge and enter the 12-mile stretch
of the Pea Island National Wildlife Preserve. This is the start of
Cape Hatteras National Seashore, which stretches the length of
Hatteras Island, and therefore one of several long chunks of
protected coastline nestled by dunes and marshes throughout
Hatteras.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to hike out over a windblown dune onto a stretch
of beach without another human in sight and look toward the ocean
and see the most perfectly shaped waves, glistening magically as
they peel down the shore, crackling in exultation.
</P>
</TEXT>
