<SLUG> BC-OUTER-BANKS-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO SEE AND DO AT CAPE HATTERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REX BABIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. _ Things to do on Cape Hatteras when you're
not surfing:
</P>
<P>
   Shipwrecks and pirates: The Outer Banks, also known as ``The
Graveyard of the Atlantic,'' feature hundreds of ships that have
been buried over several hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boilers,'' now a surf break, lies just off the Pea Island
seashore. A ship's boiler appears bobbing above the surf. It's
possible to snorkel in and around some of the wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Pea Island nature preserve: An inter-convergence zone of birds,
particularly during fall and spring migrations. It is a sometime
island, during the high tide or when an inlet opens.
</P>
<P>
   Chicamacomico Lifesaving Station: This is the highly respected,
all-black Coast Guard station. A guard, from the tiny cupola,
searches the sea for distress signals, and other guards risk their
lives in treacherous surf to recover ship crews.
</P>
<P>
   Water desalinization plant: It may be considered quirky
entertainment by some, but a tour of this high-tech, high-volume,
plant, processing brackish water from a deep aquifer, and which,
for better or for worse, makes all this tourism possible.
</P>
<P>
   Buxton Woods: A rare and ever-shrinking maritime forest. Take a
walk in the dark and steamy woods, alive with kingsnakes, deep
sand, standing pools of black water. There is horseback riding on
beach and through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Biking: Distances are long but it's very flat on Highway 12, the
only thoroughfare. Avoid Saturday-Sunday arrival and exodus of
vacationers and weekenders. For bike rentals, call Island Cycles,
Avon, 800-229-7810.
</P>
<P>
   Surf casting and clamming: Just like the great bird migration,
the waters off the Banks host a convergence of tropical and cold
water fish during spring and fall migrations.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins frolic, usually earlier than one wishes to rise during
vacation, but the sunrise and empty beach make the experience worth
the loss of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Take a flashlight and chase crabs on the beach at night (make
sure you rent a cottage without a television): The beach appears
iridescent in the light.
</P>
<P>
   Ferry to Okracoke Island: For miles of truly deserted beaches,
the village has been weathered to perfection over the years on a
protected harbor, with shops and restaurants, and artists in
residence.
</P>
<P>
   For food, try Billy's Fish House, offering fresh catch and
southern hush puppies.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Dare County Tourist Bureau 800-446-6262;
North Carolina Tourism, 800-VisitNC
</P>
<P>
   Major Property Rental Companies: All will send catalogs with
photos of properties. A variety of cottage sizes and prices. Some
cottages permit dogs to make your family vacation complete. Sun
Realty, 800-334-4745. Midgett Realty, 800-527-2903. Outer Beaches
Realty, 800-627-3150; Surf or Sound Realty, 800-237-1138; Cape
Escape, 800-996-2336.
</P>
<P>
   Camping: Cape Point at the Hatteras Lighthouse; Frisco Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
