<P>
   NY-BRUNCH (New York) _ When the weekend arrives and the city's
daytime motor shifts into idle, New York prepares to greet its
favorite meal. It is called brunch, and it is weird. A linguistic
and culinry hybrid, brunch is a breakfast that begins with a
cocktail. Or a lunch that's organized around a stack of buckwheat
pancakes. It's neither fish nor fowl nor good red herring, although
all three can wind up on the same plate. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-CARIBBEAN (Miami) _ On a blistering South Florida
afternoon whose heat approximates a restaurant kitchen's, Norman
Van Aken, dressed from chin to cuffs in his white chef's outfit,
looks refreshed and cool as he cuts a path through sweaty shoppers
inside the Palacio de los Jugos market. It looks less than regal,
but for Van Aken, the fresh fruits and vegetables shipped here
daily from the Caribbean, Latin America and other tropical lands
represent the raw material for dishes fit for gastronomic royalty.
Van Aken is the head chef and partner in Norman's in nearby Coral
Gables, which is widely considered the best restaurant in South
Florida. A pioneer in the Florida-Caribbean fusion cooking that he
calls New World cuisine, Van Aken is perhaps the best known of the
Miami chefs collectively called ``The Mango Gang.'' By Jon
Nordheimer.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ Nwes and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   ALLENDE-COOKING (Undated) _ The morning sun that flooded Isabel
Allende's kitchen was as innocent and unblemished as a perfect egg
yolk. It slid across the hand-painted ceramic tile counter, warmed
her back and made her dangling silver earrings sparkle. But the
56-year-old Chilean novelist was, for the moment, immune to the
poetry and the pleasure of the spring sun. Bent in her own shadow,
calibrating the flame under the omelet pan on her stove, Ms.
Allende, had surrendered to an atavistic ritual of the kind that
might have made a scene in one of her novels. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe
</P>
