<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BOTTLE OF WHISKEY; TWO SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The story in The Arizona Repubic might have left you
with the wrong impression because of the two guys who were quoted
making excuses _ one for the 20-year-old ex-con, the other for the
cop who shot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Dad, I'm going to have my little fling . . . and
then, that's it. It's time for me to get my life together,' '' the
dead man's father said..
</P>
<P>
   ``These are split-second decisions,'' answered the police
department spokesman. ``Everybody can play Monday night
quarterback, but you weren't there and you don't know how quick
things are escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men are wrong, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But for the right reason.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fairly simple one. While they disagree on just about
everything that happened last Saturday night at the Harbor Ridge
apartment complex on North 29th Street, they share one virtue:
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if the ex-con or the cop deserve it. Or even
need it. It's there. It was there when the call came into police
dispatch complaining about a couple of rowdy drunks roaming around
an apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Shover Jr. had been out of prison less than a week. He'd
been sent up on a probation violation and served six months. It
wasn't the first time he'd been locked away.
</P>
<P>
   Shover knew last week that getting drunk would be yet another
probation violation, but there he was, wobbling around with a
nearly full bottle of Jack Daniel's, raising hell.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Harold Jr. meant it when he told his father this was
to be his last ``little fling.'' It even could be his father
believed him, though I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   A father knows his son.
</P>
<P>
   If ``the little fling'' that got Shover sent back to prison six
months ago didn't work, nothing would. Except maybe a couple of
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The police say Shover was waving the bottle of whiskey over his
head as officers approached him. The department spokesman said the
drunk young man could have hit an officer on the head or grabbed an
officer's weapon.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that's true, but only if Phoenix police officers now
attend the academy of Barney Fife.
</P>
<P>
   A man from the apartment complex said he confronted Shover when
he saw him trying to get into a pickup truck that wasn't his.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swung at me twice (with the bottle) and missed both
times,'' the man said, ``and I never moved.''
</P>
<P>
   The police had everything in their favor. They outnumbered him.
They were sober. They were trained. They have stun guns, pepper
spray, beanbag weapons and night sticks. They had time.
</P>
<P>
   Shover had time, too.
</P>
<P>
   He had time to straighten out his life, but didn't. He had time
to play it smart for once, and not drink. He had time to surrender
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, one man got two bullets in the chest and the newspaper
got a song and dance sung in two-part disharmony.
</P>
<P>
   I have a rule at work and at home that has to do with being
critical of family or co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is: Don't.
</P>
<P>
   Not in front of outsiders, anyway. Inside the office or at home,
anything goes, but outside, you stick with your guys.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping that's what's going on here.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping that privately the family of Harold Shover Jr. is
almost as angry at him as they are with the police; that they're
ticked off he put himself in a position to get killed.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, at police headquarters _ where they're just getting
over a $5.3 million settlement for an unwarranted killing and now
face the possibility of another one _ I'm hoping word from the top
is, ``Never again.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty is good.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty is to be admired, especially in a world where it
sometimes seems as if anyone will sell out anybody for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   But a drunk getting shot dead?
</P>
<P>
   There's no excuse for that. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
