<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ALEXIE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERMAN ALEXIE MASKS HIS FEELINGS BUT NOT HIS PURPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behold the dazzling fancy dance of Sherman Alexie.
</P>
<P>
   Behold how a ridiculed outcast on the Spokane Indian Reservation
transforms himself into a lavishly praised literary author and film
writer.
</P>
<P>
   The fancy dance begins when Alexie survives brain surgery only
months after his birth, an operation doctors said the baby probably
would not live through _ or would emerge from severely retarded. A
Catholic priest is summoned to baptize the baby and also administer
last rites.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie survives frequent consignment to a hospital room where
the only escape is books _ he learns to read at age 3. He survives
government surplus food and surplus eyeglasses and years of
tauntings and beatings by other Indian boys who picked on their
frail and bookish classmate for being ``an apple'' (red outside,
white inside).
</P>
<P>
   Alexie also survives crushing poverty, alcoholic parents,
epileptic seizures until the age of 7 and the death of his beloved
older sister and her husband in a trailer fire after a night of
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   But watch Alexie rise: He decides to leave the reservation (the
``rez'') and enroll as a student at the nearby farm town of
Reardan, the only Indian in a tiny high school whose sports teams
are the Reardan Indians. He soars to high school heights _
president of the freshman class, member of the debate team that
went to the national championship in Kansas, president of Future
Farmers of America, captain of the basketball team, member of
National Honor Society.
</P>
<P>
   Observe Alexie fall: He scores scholarships to Gonzaga
University, arrives on campus and short-circuits from a terminal
case of frat-boy culture shock. He becomes a binge drunk and
college dropout after two years, drifts to Seattle and sinks so
subterranean that he works as graveyard sandwich slinger at a
Hoagie's Corner where a robbery at knife point becomes a wake-up
from the nightmare of his squandered potential.
</P>
<P>
   Then watch Alexie rise again: He retreats to the rez, transfers
to Washington State University, quits booze cold turkey on the day
after he ruined his girlfriend's birthday, then flowers as a
fledgling writer of poems, under cherished professor Alex Kuo, and
gives readings in a Pullman coffee shop before crowds that grow to
200.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, behold Alexie's fancy dance stretch across the country
and garner rave reviews and headline attention, including ``one of
the major lyric voices of our time'' (New York Times Book Review on
his first book), ``one of the 20 best American novelists under age
40'' (Granta Magazine), plus ``one of the 100 most creative people
in entertainment'' (Entertainment Weekly).
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is, at 31, becoming ``The Most Famous Indian in
America,'' but he cautions, ``The second you think you deserve it,
you get in trouble. I think that's when you become a raving
egomaniac instead of just an egomaniac. I'm arrogant enough as it
is; I don't need to encourage my own arrogance by thinking I
deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked hard and I'm reasonably talented. And working hard
has a lot to do with it. There are plenty of writers who are a lot
more talented than me, but there are very, very, very few who work
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two Sherman Alexie's, different and distinct from each
other, as is pointed out by the writer himself and his closest
compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Diane, says she can watch me at a dinner that's a mix
of friends and business associates,'' Alexie relates, ``and she can
see me switch persona in midsentence.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the public Alexie. Supremely confident, even cocky.
Never at a loss for words, quips or opinions. Mature way beyond his
years. A charismatic performer with a laser wit who delights in
confounding his mostly white audiences. He keeps them off guard
with his wisecracks about stereotypes that sound like some Indian
version of Richard Pryor or Eddie Murphy, and then shifts to his
``pissed-off Indian'' utterances that sound like a movement
militant time-tripped from the late 1960s. All this sarcasm and
irony comes with an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laughter is an effective political weapon,'' Alexie
emphasizes. `` ... Is that calculated on my part? Oh yeah, although
it's not a calculated thing for me to be funny. I am funny. But
that persona is on purpose. Nothing in my career is an accident.
The results _ you never know exactly what's going to happen. But
I've planned.''
</P>
<P>
   So Alexie strides on stage and just lets loose:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to answer a few of your questions before you ask them.
No. 1. I prefer Indian, not Native American. Native American is a
white guilt term. No. 2. No, I've never ridden a horse. No. 3. No,
I don't live in a tepee. No. 4. No, I don't know where you can get
Navajo rugs cheap. No. 5. Yes, some of my best friends are white.''
</P>
<P>
   But the uproarious laughter will die down later when Alexie
castigates white writers who write, in his view, badly and
presumptuously about Indian life. Or attacks whites who are smitten
with things Indian, from sweat lodges to vision quests to drumming
in the wilds.
</P>
<P>
   Or even skewers other successful men of color who marry white
women, something he might have done until he met and married Diane
Tomhave, the third love of his life and the first Indian, a woman
of Hidatsa/Ho Chunk/Potawatomi heritage. She has a master's degree
in theology and has worked as an academic adviser at the college
level.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the private Alexie. Quieter, even circumspect,
except about basketball. Loyal to friends and publishers who helped
him on the way up. Committed to being a role model for young
Indians, visiting dozens of reservations, teaching classes,
contributing money. Protective of his personal life, refusing to
allow his wife to be part of publicity, or their young son or their
home in the upscale, racially mixed neighborhood of Madrona.
</P>
<P>
   The real difference between the public Alexie and the private
Alexie is the degree of alienation and doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, who is of Spokane/Coeur d'Alene descent, is a bona fide
celebrity in his adopted home of Seattle, with its liberal
consciousness and its unabashed love of writers. The lanky
6-foot-2-inch figure with a mane of black hair is frequently
approached by strangers bearing compliments and was even recognized
recently when shopping for underwear (``Man, we never thought you'd
be shopping at Sears!'').
</P>
<P>
   The public Alexie helped create the attention, but the private
Alexie views his celebrity with uneasiness, although he disguises
that well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel isolated and alone here in Seattle,'' Alexie
admits. `` ... The comparison I always tell white people is to
imagine yourself in Compton, Calif. (a predominantly black city
south of Los Angeles) at midnight on a Friday and that's how I feel
all the time in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel threatened, physically threatened. But I feel
isolated and often nervous, highly aware of my body, my self. And
that's not only from being Indian. It's also part of being this
writer guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Tulee, a Yakama Indian, has known Alexie as a youth
(called Junior) on the Spokane Reservation, as a fellow student at
Washington State and in Seattle. Tulee has often reflected upon
what it takes for Alexie to inhabit such different personas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult,'' Tulee says. ``In public, people think
Sherman is performing and he is performing. But when we're just
ourselves and allowed to be ourselves, he is much more complex.
Sherman is enjoying his fame in a good way, but he is also aware of
how it kind of owns him. ... He does have to split things. He can
share some of his personal life with his audience, but he has to
put that in a different persona. If he mixed the two, then it would
be something he could never own. He has to keep something for
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Alexie, the author's mother, concurs: ``My son has
learned to wear many masks to cover up his feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is seldom happier than when he turns hermit and cranks
out pages of work. He even boldly concedes that Diane sometimes
comes second to his writing. But Alexie's prolific output across a
wide territory of writing springs at least partly from a single
emotion: fear.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Alexie is a workaholic writer on the run because he is
haunted by his past and afraid of what might be his future.
</P>
<P>
   His past on the reservation provided a wealth of stories for
Alexie's writing, but he paid dearly. The Alexie family barely
scraped by, with father Sherman Alexie Sr. working infrequently as
a laborer because of his medical problems; he came and went from
the family for a week or two with unpredictable irregularity.
Lillian Alexie earned a little from sewing quilts and working as a
clerk at the reservation trading post in Wellpinit.
</P>
<P>
   Both Alexies were bedeviled by alcohol, until Lillian Alexie
finally quit drinking in 1974 and went on to become a substance
abuse counselor with the tribe. The Alexie children _ Mary; Arnold;
Sherman Jr.; twin sisters, Kim and Arlene; James _ were often left
to their own devices, existing sometimes on what Sherman would
later describe as ``wish sandwiches, two slices of bread with only
wishes in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   His childhood prompts Alexie to reflect: ``Although I can look
back and recall all sorts of instances of happiness, the general
feeling is miserable. It was of being poor _ that's what did it. I
recall having to fight for every damn thing, having nothing of
privilege, so I could never take anything for granted. There was
never a moment when I could relax. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody in my ancestry who distinguished himself in
the way that I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That drive remains undiminished, even after Alexie has now done
so well for his family in Seattle and his family on the reservation
that potato chips, once a coveted treat immediately consumed upon
purchase, now sit around the Alexie home undisturbed for days. The
writer even jokes about how ``I have a mortgage, I have life
insurance, I have IRAs of three varieties, I have three lawyers,
I'm an inc. (FallsApart Productions Inc.)''
</P>
<P>
   Money may buy welcome comforts, but Alexie remains acutely aware
of mortality, how the average life expectancy of an Indian male in
America is just over 50 years _ no abstract statistic for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm constantly convinced I'm going to die in a car wreck, a
plane wreck, some automobile-locomotive thing,'' Alexie emphasizes.
``I get scared on Amtrak trains. ... There's too long a history of
our people dying young. I've seen too many of my friends die to not
be affected by it and to not be afraid of the same fate.''
</P>
<P>
   His writing, especially his poetry, sometimes seems to get
overshadowed by the media phenomenon of Sherman Alexie. He was
originally published by tiny Hanging Loose Press in Brooklyn, N.Y.,
with poems in its magazine, then with a 1992 collection of poems,
``The Business of Fancydancing,'' that set off the first chorus of
raves, including the New York Times Book Review's hosanna that
publisher Robert Hershon had to read twice to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's ``The Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven'' was
published by the Atlantic Monthly Press in 1993 after publisher
Morgan Entrekin had been tipped off about this ``new voice'' by
bookseller Michael Coy of Seattle. But Atlantic Monthly Press put
considerable money behind its new author of short stories,
dispatching him on the first of his grueling book tours across
America, a key element of Alexie's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherman's a trouper,'' Entrekin emphasizes. ``Sending him on
tour was the most effective way to promote him, especially when he
has such incredible presence. He works in person _ and if you've
got it, use it. Sherman understood why that's important from the
outset and he proved he would keep at it to the point of utter
exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Business of Fancydancing'' (16,000 copies in print) and
``The Lone Ranger and Tonto'' (114,000) went on to become Alexie's
most popular books of poetry and prose. Both show Alexie at his
most creative, with dazzling leaps of language and image and a
gut-punch combo of humor and pathos, plus a portrait of Indians as
resilient survivors who rely on humor and irony to get them through
too many tragedies. Alexie as a writer showed much the same skills
that he would later ascribe to baseball wizard Ozzie Smith _ ``a
Langston Hughes-of-the-diamond, bebop, improvisational jazzman
shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   So in ``The Business of Fancydancing,'' Alexie describes the
enlarged brain condition (hydrocephalus) that led to his perilous
surgery as an infant: ``My skull was expanding, pushing outward,
all the while changing my hearing and my vision, even changing the
shape of my teeth. I was born with dreams, lies, lust, all
impossibly large, filling my mind and spilling out onto the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer William Kittredge of Missoula, Mont., first met Alexie as
a WSU student and he included some of Alexie's early poems when he
edited ``The Viking Portable Western Reader,'' a 1997 anthology of
essential literature from the West.
</P>
<P>
   Kittredge considers Alexie to be ``a writer of great force and
great imaginative power who is developing at a great rate. ... He
gives us whites a sense of a subculture within our culture that we
seldom find out about. His work invites whites in, but also helps
Indians define themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most writers, Alexie is his own toughest critic. Reviewers
had been unanimous in praising Alexie until his 1996 novel,
``Indian Killer,'' a conventional thriller about a serial killer
scalping white men and terrorizing Seattle (what he calls ``a
cracked and perverted fairy tale'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian Killer'' was Alexie as artist-provocateur with a novel
about racial hatred intended to confound readers' expectations and
provoke outrage. But the criticism of Alexie remained muted,
perhaps because these are such hyper-sensitive times about race and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   As Alexie himself jokes, ``I was surprised there wasn't more
criticism, but you know good white liberals _ they love a good
beating from a brown guy. ... Maybe this is a little bit of
literary reparations. Never before in world history has an Indian
received a literary accolade based on his Indian-ness. So if that's
true, great.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie assesses his own work with the same shocking frankness he
uses on other targets: ``I'm overrated.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not Alexie playing at being humble. He recognizes that
his prodigious output (one story collection, two novels, four major
poetry collections, four small poetry limited editions) in just six
years contains work of uneven quality. When ``Reservation Blues''
was one of eight finalists for the richest prize in world
literature, Alexie said he was ``shocked'' because he would grade
his first novel with a C-.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Alexie takes great pride in his best work. He believes
his strongest talents are as a poet _ ``that's the way I think,
everything starts as a poem.'' But he quickly cites ``The Lone
Ranger and Tonto'' as ``the best work I've ever done ... the best
work I'll ever do, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is no elitist literary writer. He is an equal opportunity
consumer of American popular culture with rampant enthusiasms _
``The Brady Bunch,'' country legend Hank Williams, TV's Jane
Pauley, singer Tori Amos, bluesman Robert Johnson, Dungeons and
Dragons, horrormeister Stephen King, ``The Graduate,'' ``Midnight
Cowboy,'' ``Alien.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was probably inevitable that this lifelong movie lover
would leap at the chance to have his work translated to film.
``Smoke Signals,'' an engaging and bittersweet road movie directed
by fellow Indian Chris Eyre that opened nationally last weekend, is
Alexie's adaptation of several short stories from ``The Lone Ranger
and Tonto.'' He is scheduled to write and direct ``Indian Killer''
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Most writers are content to take the money and run with their
big dollars from Hollywood. But Alexie is intent on becoming a film
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in going unread and I'm not interested in
being unseen; art is public and the most public art form is the
movies,'' Alexie says. `` ... The thing is _ everything is going to
benefit everything else; a successful movie will make the books
sell a whole lot more copies and I'm quite aware of that. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You can affect people in larger ways with film not only in
terms of sheer numbers, but also in terms of emotional impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is not without his critics these days, even if literary
critics have treated him mostly with white gloves. He has risen too
high too fast and been too outspoken not to spawn some animosity
and jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that, Alexie recognizes, he brought on himself. The
public act may have worked a little too well, at least in cementing
certain perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm mean,'' Alexie relates. ``I think that's one
of the public perceptions of me _ meanness. And, you know, I've
created that. I've certainly worked at that, being the angry
Indian. `Indian Killer' was part of that whole mythos. It worked,
all right, but it's really kind of hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no smiles for anyone when Alexie canceled his reading
in January before a PEN/Faulkner audience in Washington, D.C., only
days beforehand. Never in the 15-year history of the prestigious
series had a writer decided not to appear and Alexie's no-show was
widely reported. And a group of Washington inner-city students were
stiffed by a writer whose work they had studied in advance of his
visit to their school.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie sent a $1,000 donation and an apology to the writer's
organization, but Janice Delaney, PEN/-Faulkner's director, was not
mollified: ``Sherman Alexie did not fulfill his obligation and
sending a donation did not fulfill it either, although I'm glad he
has a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie blames his cancellation on illness and exhaustion wrought
by his immersion in the Sundance Film Festival, a crucial event for
``Smoke Signals''' future: ``I had overextended myself _ I really
underestimated the effect that the Sundance Film Festival would
have on me. The people at PEN/Faulkner made a big public deal out
of it, trying to shame me, which was fine. It was my fault. I
admitted responsibility. ... I made mistakes, I'm not perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   A more lasting question about Alexie is whether all the early
and extravagant praise, plus all his diverse projects, will somehow
dilute his talent. Tom Robbins, the imaginative novelist from La
Conner, has seen that happen with other writers.
</P>
<P>
   As Robbins says, ``Alexie's first collection of stories was
witty and poignant, biting and soulful. The book attracted a lot of
praise, certainly well-deserved praise. But it was somewhat
unfortunate for Alexie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When writers that young are praised to that extent, they are
often crippled by it. The danger is that they become careless and
sloppy, not work hard enough, not bear down enough and continue to
grow as a writer. ... I'm not saying that has happened with Alexie.
I'm saying that's the danger and I hope he recognizes that and
finds a way to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is rushing across the country these days, from premieres
of ``Smoke Signals'' on both coasts to television appearances on
Charley Rose, CNN and Good Morning America. He is scheduled to be
one of eight people in a television dialogue on race with President
Bill Clinton tomorrow in Washington, D.C., that will be broadcast
on PBS with Jim Lehrer moderating (at 7 p.m. Thursday on KCTS/9 in
Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is weary, but gratified in his moment of his greatest
national fame, saying, ``No Indian has ever been offered these
kinds of opportunities _ I'm being offered multipicture deals with
Hollywood studios. ... I cannot let that go. My friendships suffer,
my family life suffers, I suffer. But there's some sense of larger
responsibility in it, and also a huge sense of ego. I am the first,
I like being the first, I want to be the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie has even come to accept the slights and hurts that once
rankled him, including the fact that he has never been asked to
read his work on the Spokane Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to hear the tribe's headliner have had to travel
the 50 miles to Spokane. But others in the tribe would not walk
across the street to hear Alexie, with the way this big city big
shot has exposed and profited from so many of their rez stories,
including his frequently told tale about the drunk who passed out
and drowned face down in a mud puddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my best not to antagonize those people who are
antagonistic toward me on the rez _ I don't need that grief and
they don't either,'' Alexie says. ``My literary career has not
changed my reservation's opinion of me. The people who loved me
when I was 7 love me now. The people who hated me then hate me now.
It would be the same if I was a successful carpenter or lawyer or
doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie knows he has what truly matters to him. He has sobriety,
what he considers the greatest accomplishment of his life. He has
his wife and he has his son, although that was once in grave doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In an eerie reprise of Alexie's own infancy, Joseph Alexie was
born with a serious medical problem that put him in intensive care
with a grim prognosis. There were weeks of great trial and tension
for the young family. Lillian Alexie worried her son might return
to drinking, but he did not.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Alexie survived and is now prospering, and his father is
loathe to see parallels to his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to be learned from it,'' Alexie says. ``If you
start looking for connections, you're going to blow your brains
out. It's a s----- coincidence, that's all. Besides, I'm Indian _
so there's no why me? I mean we get our ass kicked for hundreds of
years. Another slap across the face is not going to cause me to
start feeling sorry for myself. ... Besides, I've got cousins in
jail, and cousins dead and cousins dying of cirrhosis of the liver
at age 25. I've got it pretty damn good.''
</P>
<P>
   There are moments when Alexie will be watching television or
driving his beat-up car and it will hit him, a sudden flash of
satisfaction over what he's been able to accomplish so quickly.
Often, it will make him laugh out loud, a common Alexie response,
although his real feelings run deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``People listen _ that's all you can ask for,'' Alexie says.
``And through that, you hope you can change some people's opinions
and change the world a little, too. I mean, I'm going to be
remembered. I've made a difference in some way or other. One
hundred years from now, my work will still be in textbooks
somewhere, so I've got my tiny little bit of immortality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
