<HEADER>
A3752 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI &LR;      07-07 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON PASADENA FOR TV CRITICS MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The postcard-pretty grounds of California's
Ritz-Carlton Huntington Hotel evoke wispy visions of another time.
Tucked into a quiet corner of Pasadena _ eons away from such
look-at-me destinations as Laguna Beach or Santa Barbara _ the
elegantly understated surroundings hint at whispered intimacies
taking place far from the fadding crowd of LaLaLand.
</P>
<P>
   Except maybe for two weeks in January and three weeks in July.
That's when the L.A. limo brigade makes daily treks to Pasadena to
deliver an assortment of big names and bigger egos to a huddled
mass of TV writers yearning to breathe the latest on new television
programming to their devoted readers.
</P>
<P>
   The annual July version begins Wednesday and ends on the 26th _
a 19-day run of news conferences and luncheons designed to induce
homesickness while affording us ``access'' to the people we'll all
be complaining about in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ The granting of so much face time with the stars supports the
theory that critics tend to submit kinder, gentler copy when
they're personally acquainted with the people they write about.
Because of certain anatomical considerations, it's not possible to
get too close to Pamela Anderson, so if I ever say something nice
about ``V.I.P.,'' the latest in Anderson's body of work, please
ascribe it to something more than our, uh, eyes having met across a
crowded hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The former ``Baywatch'' lifeguard is among the big names being
trotted out today by the companies that syndicate ``first-run''
programs so local stations across the country can fill all the time
slots not occupied by network stuff.
</P>
<P>
   First-run syndication means original material, such as
``Pensacola: Wings of Gold'' or ``Xena: Warrior Princess,'' as
opposed to syndicated reruns of previously original network
programming such as ``Seinfeld'' or ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has bothered to watch ``The Adventures of Sinbad''
can tell you, first-run doesn't necessarily equal first-rate. The
budgets for syndicated shows are usually much lower than for
network series, and the cheesiness is often readily apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is still out on Anderson's ``V.I.P.'' Screening tapes
weren't available Another safe bet: ``V.I.P'' will be
fabric-challenged. I'll have more (or less) on Pamela tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   _ From two documentaries on the Cold War (a 24-hour marathon on
CNN, a more condensed version on The History Channel) to a remake
of ``Fantasy Island'' (Saturdays on ABC), the fall-TV lineup runs
the usual gamut.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't seen much of the cable fare yet, but some new network
shows that have made an early impression: ``Cupid'' and ``Sports
Night'' on ABC, ``Felicity'' on The WB, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' on NBC and
``Seven Days'' on UPN. More on all of these as I settle in for the
long pull at the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
