<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3849 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-REBUKE-HNS &LR;      07-07 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-REBUKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA JUDICIAL PANEL CRITICIZES APPELLATE JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The panel that disciplines California judges has
charged a Court of Appeal judge with misconduct in an extraordinary
attack that has alarmed the legal community and raised questions
about free speech in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Judicial Performance on Monday accused Justice
J. Anthony Kline of contradicting the state Supreme Court in a
written opinion. It was an unprecedented move that could lead to
Kline's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based commission said Kline had issued a
dissenting opinion Dec. 2, 1997, in a San Mateo County
landlord-tenant dispute centering on a point of law decided five
years earlier by the California Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Kline said he believed the state's highest court had been wrong
and that he couldn't follow its ruling ``as a matter of
conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   The specific issue involved what observers described as a matter
of legal philosophy: whether opponents in civil lawsuits may ignore
judgments of trial courts and reach financial settlements in
blatant disregard of those courts.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a ``stipulated reversal,'' this action was upheld in a
1992 state Supreme Court case, Neary vs. Regents of the University
of California. It has been upheld by no other court, including the
U.S. Supreme Court, which expressly rejected it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded letter to the commission March 13, Kline
laid out his position. The letter said stipulated reversals wrongly
permitted parties ``with the necessary economic means to purchase
the reversal of an adverse judgment'' and undermined the integrity
of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Such post-trial collaborations, he said, convert court judgments
``into a commodity that can be bought and sold.''
</P>
<P>
   He protested that the commission was trying to punish him for
``forthrightness and candor'' in his attempt to persuade the state
Supreme Court to reconsider the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the 11-member commission, a politically appointed body
composed mostly of non-lawyers named during the administration of
Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, said Kline had engaged in ``willful
misconduct ... that brings the judicial office into disrepute.''
</P>
<P>
   It said he had violated canons of the state Code of Judicial
Ethics barring actions that did not promote ``public confidence''
in the courts and requiring that a judge be ``faithful to the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the legal community condemned judicial
panel's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an outrage,'' said Stephen Barnett, professor of law at
the University of California at Berkeley. ``It shows the commission
doesn't know the difference between misconduct and an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed,'' said David Heilbron, former State Bar president.
``There's never been a charge like this pursued by the
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Former appeals judge and commission chairman John Racanelli said
he shared Kline's legal view and was ``surprised and distressed''
that the disciplinary panel would examine a written opinion
``through the lens of conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Kline, 59, declined to comment on the charges, but said he would
hire a lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      07-07 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BE SWEET &QL; 
 &UR; Roy Blount Jr. (Knopf, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Talk to any humorist, and you will hear the same refrain: In his
heart of hearts, he'll tell you, he is not funny. In his heart of
hearts, he's sad. Fans of Blount's intelligent, antic humor will
have to make some adjustments as they read this memoir, because
much of it deals with Blount's difficult relationship with his
mother, and the subsequent ``sefflo'' _ a humorist's shorthand for
self-loathing _ that is at the heart of his desire to make people
laugh. The passages in which Blount tells of his resentment toward
his mother and his lifelong inability to understand her are not
terribly convincing. They often sound like emotional baggage that a
56-year-old man should long since have put down. His book also has
a tendency to become disjointed as he rushes headlong out of a
particularly dark passage into a hilarious dissertation on, say,
meeting up with Daryl Hannah in a public restroom. What saves it is
Blount's superb comic sense _ when he's on, there's no one better _
and his affable persona, even when he's talking about ex-wives,
difficult childbirth and matricidal guilt. This is a book worth
reading, but not the book you expect it to be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; KYKUIT: THE ROCKEFELLER FAMILY HOME &QL; 
 &UR; Ann Rockefeller Roberts (Abbeville, $49.95)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Abbeville has been waiting in the wings, knowing how
prudent it would be to publish this coffee-table book on the heels
of Ron Chernow's ``Titan,'' a wonderful biography of John D.
Rockefeller Sr. that was released last month to glowing reviews.
Ann Rockefeller Roberts is the great-granddaughter of ``JDR,'' as
she calls him, and her daughter, Mary Louise Pierson, contributed
photographs of the estate as it is today. Construction of the house
was overseen by JDR's son, John D. Rockefeller Jr., on behalf of
his parents, and it was all he could do to coax his frugal father
through the shock of rising costs and the inadequacy of their
original estimates of the price of house and grounds. After years
of renovation (JDR and his wife were unhappy with the first
version), the house was finished in 1913, 20 years after JDR
purchased the land. A few minor details later _ JDR paid $700,000
to reroute the New York Central Railroad, which cut across the
estate _ it became the family home, including a farm that supplied
produce and spring water (JDR became so fond of the produce that it
was shipped to him wherever he went). This is an elegant look at
the house and its holdings _ artworks, outbuildings, gymnasium,
bowling alley and an ``automobile hall'' for the family cars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MEDITATIONS FROM A MOVABLE CHAIR &QL; 
 &UR; Andre Dubus (Knopf, $23)
</P>
<P>
   ``My imagination gave me a dual life: I lived in my body, and at
the same time lived a life no one could see,'' Dubus writes. ``All
my life, I have told myself stories, and have talked in my mind to
friends.'' This collection of essays begins on a somber note, but
not, as you might expect, with the story of why Dubus is in his
movable chair (12 years ago he was hit by a car, losing one leg and
the use of the other). Instead, he begins with the night when his
sister, Kathryn, was sexually assaulted by a stranger on the yard
behind her house while her daughter waited for her inside,
oblivious to what was happening. There is nothing overly dramatic
about this essay. These are, after all, meditations, and although
several deal with tragedy, they also share something strong and
life-affirming in the steady, trustworthy voice of Andre Dubus.
It's a wonderful sound, no less so when the stories it tells are
true. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FUN ALONG THE ROAD &QL; 
 &UR; John Margolies (Bulfinch, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   We have perused every tourist attraction in this book, and have
decided that we want to go to Hayward, Wis., to visit the National
Freshwater Fishing Hall of Fame, where there is a fiberglass muskie
that stands four and a half stories high, with an entrance on its
underbelly and a railing in its gaping mouth to keep you from
falling to your death on a trash can below. There are other fish
statues, too, all open-mouthed, larger than life and deeply ugly.
Margolies goes looking for this type of thing. We cannot tell you
what his motives are, except to sell books and make a record of the
endangered kitsch by the side of the road. His book is pricey, and
could be more informative. There's only a photo and one short
caption on that big muskie. It deserves more. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EXILES &QL; 
 &UR; Philip Caputo (Vintage, $13)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is this collection of three novellas by the
author of the Vietnam memoir ``A Rumor of War.'' The best is ``In
the Forest of the Laughing Elephant,'' a Conradian tale of men
pitted against nature in a far, exotic place. They are soldiers on
the edge of the action in the Vietnam War, and their leader, an
otherworldly man named Lincoln Coombs, forces them deeper and
deeper into the jungle in search of a tiger that has snatched one
of his men. As their quest becomes increasingly menacing, Coombs
becomes demented in his determination to find and kill the animal
that, unbeknown to the other men, has shamed him. Caputo's prose is
rich and assertive, but it never dominates the events that it
describes. Things (begin itals) happen (end itals) in these
stories, in the tradition of tales told on the edge of a campfire.
That's the best kind of fiction of all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
