<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONDHEIM-BOOK-AZR &LR;      07-07 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONDHEIM-BOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONDHEIM KNEW HIS CALLING EARLY ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Stephen Sondheim: A Life 
Meryle Secrest (Alfred A. Knopf, $30) 
 
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   God must love the American musical theater. At the moment of its
greatest decline, its greatest composer/lyricist arrived as
recompense.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sondheim was living the unremarkable life of a
10-year-old New York boy in 1940 when his father left his mother,
starting the chain of events that would lead to the scores for
``Company,'' ``Follies,'' ``A Little Night Music,'' ``Sweeney
Todd,'' ``Into the Woods,'' and the Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Sunday
in the Park With George,'' among many others.
</P>
<P>
   Left to raise her son alone, Foxy Sondheim botched the job,
turning her only child into a receptacle for her guilt, having him
mix drinks for all-night parties and even, on several occasions,
attempting thinly veiled seductions. Of course, little Stevie grew
up afraid of women and emotionally frigid.
</P>
<P>
   He also grew up around Oscar Hammerstein II, and that made all
the difference. The Pennsylvania farm where Hammerstein lived with
his family became a refuge for young Steve, who lived with his
mother nearby. The librettist/lyricist of ``Show Boat'' and
``Oklahoma!'' became a substitute father, a role model, and Steve
wanted to be just like him. ``If he had been an anthropologist, I
would've been an anthropologist,'' Sondheim has said elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the field that needed his singular talents. As
Meryle Secrest points out in her throughly researched and vividly
written biogra phy _ the first of the man most consider the world's
most important living composer for the stage _ Sondheim's life has
been fiercely devoted to his art, to the exclusion of every
possible distraction. Committed personal relationships have been
few and late-blooming. Disciplines irrelevant to a relatively
narrow artistic focus have been ignored. Composer Ned Rorem once
noted with a puzzled air that Sondheim has never mastered
orchestration or French, though he obviously has the intelligence
for both. The reason seems obvious: Broadway composers don't
orchestrate, and they don't write in French. Why spend energy that
could be used on more pertinent things, such as the next score?
</P>
<P>
   Excluded, too, has been any attempt at popularity for its own
sake. From the moment in 1945 when he wept openly at the opening
night of Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``Carousel,'' Sondheim has
viewed the musical as a form ripe with serious potential. He's
followed that vision even while the world has gone in the other
direction. Secrest quotes one Broadway professional as saying that,
to succeed today, musicals must have lots of special effects, a
simplistic book, and a rock-influenced pop score. It is not
surprising that Sondheim's musicals, ranging in subject matter from
the nature of art to the Westernization of Japan, and written in
styles influenced by an assortment of 20th-century Classical
composers (Ravel in ``Night Music,'' Britten in ``Sunday,'' etc.),
have overwhelmingly failed as financial ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim's ambition from the start was to write both music and
lyrics, and he showed extraordinary early promise in both areas.
After attending Williams College, where he was regarded as a fine
actor as well as musician, Sondheim studied with Milton Babbitt, an
avant-garde composer and disciple of Arnold Schoenberg. Babbitt was
a perfect fit because he harbored a secret life: that of a
frustrated Broadway songwriter. Sondheim, with ambitions to be a
tonal Broadway composer, became the unlikeliest artistic grandchild
of Schoenberg, the most feared name in early 20th-century
avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   But it was as lyricist only that Sondheim first broke through,
in two of the most successful musicals of the late 1950s: ``West
Side Story'' (music by Leonard Bernstein) and ``Gypsy'' (to Jule
Styne's music). Though 1962 brought his first music-and-lyrics
credit, ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum,'' it
would be decades before the general public thought of Sondheim as a
composer. (``Forum'' would also supply him with his main source of
income for many years.)
</P>
<P>
   Written with Sondheim's cooperation and rumored in advance to be
a ``tell-all'' biography, Secrest's book is pleasingly free of the
sort of detailed intimate information that is irrelevant to any
real discussion of art and artist, though it is often the stuff of
bestselling celebrity bios. She treats her subject's private life
openly but with respect, from his early suspicions of being
homosexual to his attempts at forging heterosexual relationships
(with Mary Rodgers, composer and daughter of Richard, and actress
Lee Remick, among others), his slow process of self-accommodation
beginning in the '70s, and the first time he fell in love _ at the
probably record-breaking age of 61.
</P>
<P>
   These and other personal matters, including Sondheim's famous
enthusiasm for games and his less well-known star-struck side (he
followed Bogart around the set of ``Beat the Devil''), are explored
with reference to their impact on Sondheim's work, which is the
real subject here. Generally, Secrest's observations make good
sense, such as her connection of ``The Ladies Who Lunch'' from
``Company'' to the personality of Sondheim's mother, and of
``Finishing the Hat'' from ``Sunday'' to Sondheim's own loneliness.
Once in a while, as when she tries to relate Sondheim's excitement
over a performance of ``Someone in a Tree'' from ``Pacific
Overtures'' to his childhood, the link can seem a tendentious
stretch. ``Tree'' is probably Sondheim's favorite song simply
because it is the most unusual song from a most unusual score.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim's musicals are testament to what the musical might have
been following the innovations of Rodgers and Hammerstein in the
1940s and the heyday of the musical in the 1950s. They still point
the way to a possible future. New operas, at least the ones seen by
this writer, are looking increasingly bleak. Opera turns 400 this
year; the modern musical is less than quarter that age. The lyric
stage might well profit by a shift from opera's emphasis on
vocal-display-as-expression to the emphasis on dramatic song in the
Sondheim musical. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1552EDT &QL; 
