<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-HNS &LR;      07-07 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEDS OF WOMEN'S MOVEMENT BEGAN IN UPSTATE NEW YORK VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENECA FALLS, N.Y. _ When Elizabeth Cady Stanton strode to the
speaker's podium at the first-ever woman's rights assembly, she was
surrounded by friends and fellow reformers among the 300 people who
packed the Wesleyan Chapel in Seneca Falls, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she was alone.
</P>
<P>
   Only Stanton was pushing to add voting rights for women to the
agenda. Quaker leader Lucretia Mott advised against it. Henry
Stanton left town when he learned what his wife was planning. Her
father questioned her sanity. Stanton was reaching beyond her
grasp. And hoping to ignite a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1848, elective franchise for women was considered sheer
lunacy. But Stanton had embodied a feminist perspective since
childhood. The death of her only brother at age 10 had crystallized
her inferior status. Near the casket in their large, dark parlor,
she climbed onto the knee of her pale and immovable father.
</P>
<P>
   ``At length he heaved a sigh and said: `Oh, my daughter, I wish
you were a boy!' Throwing my arms about his neck I replied, `I will
try to be all my brother was,' she would later recall.
</P>
<P>
   By 1848 Stanton was passionately provoked by inequities that
banned half the population from voting, holding public office,
attending college, preaching or expressing opinions at social
gatherings. In this ``tempest-tossed condition of mind'' she opted
to launch the first projectile in a battle that would take 72
years.
</P>
<P>
   The 150th anniversary of the Women's Rights Convention will be
marked with several days of upcoming events, including a speech
July 16 by Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the National Women's Hall of Fame will induct 21
people whose lives demonstrate how far women have come in politics,
the professions and family life.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton's journey to Seneca Falls started in Johnstown, 40 miles
west of Albany. The day she was born _ Nov. 12, 1815 _ her father,
Daniel Cady, was elected to Congress. As a girl she loved to dance
and sleigh. After the death of her brother Eleazar, she added, with
her own initiative, mathematics, Greek, economics and equestrian
feats.
</P>
<P>
   When her classmates went on to Union College in Schenectady,
Stanton was excluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vexation and mortification knew no bounds,'' she recalled
in her autobiography, ``Eighty Years &AMP; More'' (1898). She convinced
her father to send her to women's education pioneer Emma Willard's
female seminary in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   While the 1830s ``cult of true womanhood'' popularized in
magazines limited a woman's sphere to the home, family and church,
law school would have been more in keeping with Stanton's feisty
and argumentative character. As a young girl she watched a parade
of penniless female clients arrive at her father's law office door,
powerless over the state law that left husbands' estates to their
sons, not wives.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Elizabeth vowed to cut the cruel laws from her father's
legal books with a pair of scissors. Daniel Cady advised her to
lobby the state Legislature when she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus was the future object of my life foreshadowed,'' Stanton
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   From her abolitionist cousin Gerrit Smith, an 1848 presidential
candidate, to her Boston social contacts with abolitionists
Frederick Douglass and William Lloyd Garrison and writer Ralph
Waldo Emerson, she was encircled by radical thinkers. In 1840 she
married abolitionist Henry Stanton (she edited ``obey'' from the
traditional vows). They honeymooned in London at an anti-slavery
convention, traveling with Quaker abolitionists James Mott and his
wife, Lucretia Mott, founder of Philadelphia's Women's Anti-Slavery
Society in Philadelphia. When the male delegates banned female
delegate participation, Stanton and Mott were outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really pitiful to hear narrow-minded bigots, pretending
to be teachers and leaders of men, so cruelly remanding their own
mothers, with the rest of woman-kind, to absolute subjection to the
ordinary masculine type of humanity,'' Stanton later wrote. She and
Mott decided then to hold a women's rights convention back in the
States.
</P>
<P>
   It took eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The air was rife with reform sentiments by the time Mott and
Stanton met again in 1848 in Seneca Falls. Stanton had moved to the
mill village of about 4,000 people the year before with her husband
and three children.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, some dubbed upstate New York from Utica to
Rochester the ``burned-over district'' due to the flames of
religious revivalism sweeping the area. As they left New England to
follow industry and the Erie Canal, ``Yankee Yorkers'' _ Yankees
who moved west to New York _ dropped such old beliefs as
predestination for newer notions of individual freedom and
community responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical preachers exhorted their mainly female audiences to
convert others, from drunks to slave owners. The villages around
Rochester provided natural great hiding places for runaway slaves
headed to Canada as well as activist abolitionists like the
Hicksite Quakers who relocated from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The area also spawned such religious movements as Mormonism and
spiritualism.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this foundry of reform that Stanton forged her
feminist artillery. Often, she was alone with three children while
her husband traveled making abolitionist speeches. Her own
frustrations mixed with small-town life and the domestic abuse and
economic oppression she witnessed just across the Seneca River in
the crowded, smelly factory town populated by Irish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1848, Lucretia Mott came to town for a Quaker
convention. At a tea party at the Waterloo home of Jane Hunt,
Stanton, then 32, poured out ``the torrent of my long-accumulating
discontent'' to her friends: Hunt, Mott, Mary Ann M'Clintock, and
Mott's sister, Martha Coffin Wright. Her rant inspired them to call
the meeting at the Wesleyan Methodist Church in Seneca Falls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stanton died in 1902, 18 years before women got the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after the groundbreaking assembly at Seneca Falls,
Stanton remained the leading thinker in the women's movement. As
she raised seven children at her home in Seneca Falls, Stanton
wrote the speeches that her friend Susan B. Anthony, whom she met
in 1851, traveled the country to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stanton kept up a progressive domestic life,
constructing a gymnasium in the barn for her boys and girls,
teaching her sons kitchen skills, dancing, playing the piano and
hosting conversation nights for her many and varied guests.
</P>
<P>
   Long before most of her peers, Stanton advocated birth control,
girls' sports, equal pay, day care, coeducation, dress reform,
labor unions, divorce law, custody reform and cooperative kitchens.
She spoke publicly about her enjoyment of sex.
</P>
<P>
   From her public lectures to her speeches before the state
Legislature and relentless letters to editors, Stanton kept
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   As time went on, her radical stands and acerbic wit caused her
to lose friends and political support. She broke with abolitionists
who backed the 14th Amendment, which granted suffrage to former
male slaves in 1868, but not to women.
</P>
<P>
   Even after her death, Stanton's public image continued to erode
as the more prim and acceptable Anthony was elevated to represent
the suffrage struggle. But Stanton, the fiercer half of that
50-year partnership, is clearly the matriarch of the women's
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Passionately aware of the inequities, insistent and eloquent in
her advocacy and, often, courageously alone, she persevered.
</P>
<P>
   As Anthony put it: ``Cautious, careful people ... never can
bring about reform. Those who are really in earnest must be willing
to ... avow their sympathy with despised and persecuted ideas ...
and bear the consequences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
