<HEADER>
A3863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-N     07-07 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 12,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORY  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POP-MUSIC (Tokyo) _ For the past two decades, Japan has
been home to the world's largest music industry next to America,
but only recently _ in the face of economic crisis and sweeping
social changes _ has it reached the diversity and originality
necessary to propel its musicians in the West. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRAWING-SCHOOL (New York) _ When the drawing marathon at the New
York Studio School of Drawing, Painting and Sculpture on a Monday
morning in mid-June, 97 artists, students, architects, Sunday
painters, art critics and teachers from Australia, Mexico,
Switzerland, England, Israel, the Philippines, California, Alabama,
Massachusetts, Washington, stood ready at their easels to draw for
eight hours a day, five days a week, in seven separate studios.
This biannual event, dreamed up 10 years ago by Graham Nickson, an
enigmatic, soft-spoken British painter who is the dean of the
school, seemed to be far better known outside New York than inside.
Few had come from close by. Many had traveled thousands of miles
for it. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GREAT-CITIES (Undated) _ Here is an urban theme and five
variations. D.W. Winnicott, the great British child psychoanalyst,
believed that artists are driven by the conflict between the desire
to communicate and the even stronger desire to hide. Flip this idea
around, and you arrive at a useful theory for interpreting the
contemporary city: Great cities are driven by the conflict between
the desire to expose and the even stronger desire to overlook. By
Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NOVELTIES-DANCE (New York) _ It was Sol Hurok, an impresario
with a keen eye on the box office, who grasped the ballet public's
hunger for what he called ``novelties.'' These were new
productions, mainly premieres but also revivals of works so rarely
seen that they took on the aura of a premiere. A prime example was
Hurok's historic presentation of a full-length ``Sleeping Beauty''
when the Sadler's Wells Ballet made its New York debut in 1949.
During their recent seasons, American Ballet Theater and New York
City Ballet each offered the same two kinds of ``novelties.'' Both
commissioned a new work and presented an unusual revival,
transferred from another company. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAFURA-DELSBAUS-THEATER (Barcelona) _ La Fura Del Baus is as
unusual a name in Catalan as it is in English: The Ferret from the
Baus. But there was method to the fantasy of the five young street
performers who chose the name of their new experimental theater
company in Barcelona in 1979. Today, La Fura dels Baus is
synonymous with an unorthodox multidisciplinary form of theater
that uses loud music, violent movement, bizarre machinery and
almost no words to create a near-apocalyptic atmosphere. By Alan
Riding.
</P>
<P>
   IRVING-CIDERHOUSE-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ When John Irving began
work on ``The Cider House Rules,'' his sprawling 1985 novel about
eight decades in the life of a rural Maine orphanage, he says he
had no intention of writing a wrenching polemic on abortion or, it
seems safe to say, a work that would be the basis for a 2-part,
6-hour marathon play with 22 actors portraying 120 characters in
150 scenes. But 13 years after the book's publication and 6 years
after a trio of theater professionals conceived the notion of
dramatizing it, ``The Cider House Rules'' has become all that and
more in a production of the same name that opened July 11 at the
Mark Taper Forum here and runs through Sept. 27. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER-BRAIN (New York) _ ``A New Brain,'' William Finn's
latest chamber opera, is the composer-lyricist's attempt to deal
with what was obviously a doomy, seriously traumatic experience:
the preliminary diagnosis of an inoperable brain tumor, which he
received in 1992 just two weeks after winning Tonys for his book
and score for ``Falsettos.'' By Vincent Canby.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PRETEENS (Undated) _ Placing the pre- or early-adolescent
point of view in the thick of sophisticated conflict has a
venerable cinematic past, of course _ think of Truffaut's ``400
Blows'' and Spielberg's ``E.T.'' And its practical esthetic appeal
is a compelling one that's not so difficult to decipher: the pre-
or early adolescent is old enough to be both perceptive witness and
provocative participant yet young enough not to have retreated
fully behind the blinkers of self-contemplation and social
convention. By Will Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   ROMERO-HORROR-MOVIES (Undated) _ Released in 1985, ``Day of the
Dead'' is one of four Romero titles just reissued on video by
Anchor Bay. Included is his first feature film and zombie original,
``Night of the Living Dead'' (1968), shot in black and white in
Pittsburgh for $114,000. ``It would be fun to dismiss this as
undoubtedly the best movie ever made in Pittsburgh,'' the critic
Pauline Kael wrote, ``but it also happens to be one of the most
gruesomely terrifying movies ever made.'' By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   SADNESS-SEX-MOVIE (Undated) _ In late 1994 a film was made that
centered on me and my dark whimsies about romance and heartbreak:
``The Sadness of Sex,'' from my book of the same name. Here's my
sorry tale of how this odd independent movie was brought briefly to
the screen _ and then to the shelf, where it now sits, maybe for
good. The story is my two cents toward the updating of ``Candide''
that famously takes place when a neophyte like me gets involved in
the mad, bad world of glamour-grabbing and economic hardball that
is the film business. By Barry Yourgrau.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC-PARADISE-TV (Undated) _ It happens at night in the
summertime when the moon is full and the tides are just right. The
coral reefs of Palau go into a spasm of reproductive surrender,
sowing warm currents with trillions of eggs and sperm that swirl
and dance and ultimately merge to form new life. The orgy is so
wild that in some places, eggs rise through the sea like
snowflakes, blizzards of them. Even sea cucumbers get into the
mood. In the moonlight they suddenly rise up and dance in hypnotic
rhythms, swaying back and forth to seed a new generation. These are
some of the remarkable sights of ``Palau: Paradise of the
Pacific,'' to be shown on Wednesday at 9:00 p.m. on the PBS series
``The Living Edens.'' By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   OZ-TV-NEWSEASON (Undated) _ Don't look for Dorothy or Toto.
That's the other place. This is Oz, short for Oswald Maximum
Security Penitentiary. Emerald City, the high-tech experimental
prison-within-a-prison _ referred to as Em City _ stresses
rehabilitation. It's run by Tim McManus (Terry Kinney), a 1960's
throwback who believes even the most hardened criminal can change.
Ernie Hudson plays his boss, the warden, a forceful authority
figure who knows better. The critically acclaimed HBO drama series
begins its second eight-episode season July 13 at 10 p.m. By Paula
Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
