<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASH-CHERRIES-ART-2TA     07-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-CHERRIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO DIFFICULT IN THE FIELD, SO SWEET ON THE TONGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOXEE CITY, Wash. _ They were about to start the Rainiers, and
Bob Harris was getting himself psyched up. ``This is a crazy
business,'' he said, ``and anyone who can do anything else should
stay out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The business at hand was cherries in this, the nation's prime
cherry country, with its acres of luscious garnet Bings and
Lamberts, and especially Rainiers, which are some of the sweetest
and most highly prized cherries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Harris begins harvesting his Rainier cherries is
a tense time. Hundreds of thousands of dollars hang in the balance.
A rainstorm, even a few unexpected gusts of wind, can wipe out the
work of a year in hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most earlier-maturing cherries had already been picked, Harris
said. If his Rainiers and some even later cherries came in without
incident, it might even be a record crop _ or close.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new variety, the Rainier was developed at the
Washington State University experimental station at Prosser in the
1960s, and it is a cross between the well-known Bing and the
little-known Van. The Rainier costs an average of about $2 a pound
retail in the United States, but connoisseurs in Taiwan and Hong
Kong are willing to pay 10 times that.
</P>
<P>
   Balding and 50-ish, tanned and fit, Harris grows his cherries,
some 300 acres, here in the Yakima Valley, 150 miles southeast of
Seattle. He pretends not to like what he does.
</P>
<P>
   I had flown down from the West Side, as people in the hot, dry
eastern part of Washington refer to the western slope of the
Cascades, which is green, wet and cool. On the drive over to
Harris', the woman on NPR said it was 64 in Seattle; the dusty
thermometer outside Bob Harris' dusty office read 98.
</P>
<P>
   Yakima County produces more cherries than most states. Of
course, this one county is almost as large as Connecticut. But
cherries are just for starters: the county also produces more
apples, more hops, more winter pears than any other in America. It
is rapidly becoming one of the most important areas in the country
for wine grapes and, for good measure, leads the world in the
production of mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yakima farmers work hard, and the fertile land has repaid them,
often handsomely. The old farmhouses have given way to spacious
air-conditioned mansions. New cars are in every driveway, and
private planes are not uncommon. Arizona vacations and foreign
tariffs are as much a part of coffee shop gossip as taxes and rain.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to those dormant (well, mostly dormant) volcanoes off to
the west _ Mount Rainier, Mount Adams, Mount St. Helens _ the soil
here is largely volcanic and rich in nitrogen. Those snowcapped
mountains give the Yakima Valley more than its fruitful soil.
Rainfall here is about eight inches a year, so without Mount
Rainier's melting snow, much of this verdant land would be a
desert. There would be no cherry trees. Rainier, then, is a
singularly appropriate name for the new star of these cherry
orchards.
</P>
<P>
   But as is the way with stars, the Rainier can be ornery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's murder to grow,'' Harris muttered, almost as if he
begrudged the fruit its popularity. ``It bruises easily, and you
have to go through the orchard three times. With other cherries,
the whole tree ripens at once. Not with the Rainiers.'' Even so, he
admitted, growers can't keep up with the demand.
</P>
<P>
   All cherries are difficult to grow. Not for nothing have they
been called the riskiest fruit. Their deadliest enemies are frost,
birds and rain, with wind and hail not far behind. Rows of smudge
pots in the growers' sheds (some in empty shell casings from a
nearby Army artillery range) and airplane propellers mounted on
tall shafts throughout the orchards (to circulate the warmed air)
testify of the annual battle to fend off frost.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes as much effort to pick 5 acres of Rainiers as it
does 50 acres of dark cherries like Bings and Lapins. Even on a
given tree, Rainiers ripen at different rates.
</P>
<P>
   Picking starts at 4 a.m. and ends at noon so the newly picked
fruit won't have to sit out in the hot sun. Only skilled pickers
work with Rainiers. For one thing, they can be handled only by
their stems. Because they are so delicate and bruise so easily, no
more than 30 percent of the crop goes into the premium packs. A
picker may need two weeks to pick 24 trees, going to each one as
many as eight times.
</P>
<P>
   A flock of hungry birds can be as devastating as any frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' Harris said, pulling a half-eaten Rainier from
a tree. The bird hadn't nibbled much _ just enough to make it
unsalable.
</P>
<P>
   Colonists brought cherries to America in 1629. The fruit arrived
in the Pacific Northwest with a pioneer named Henderson Lewelling,
who planted seeds in western Oregon in 1847. America's best-known
sweet cherry, the Bing, was developed on his farm in 1875. It was
named for one of his Chinese workers.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the extra-sweet Rainiers is understandably high, but
they make up less than 5 percent of the annual Northwest cherry
crop.
</P>
<P>
   Bings, which make up about 85 percent of the crop here, begin to
appear in supermarkets in mid-June and last until mid-August. They
are the biggest cherries and at their best are mahogany colored, in
both skin and flesh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainiers, golden-colored with a reddish-pink blush and clear
flesh, begin to arrive a week or two after the Bings show up and
are available through the first week of August.
</P>
<P>
   A third variety, the Lambert, comes to market around the end of
June and is available through mid-August. It looks and tastes like
the Bing, but is a bit smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The Bing and the Lambert contain 17 to 19 percent fruit sugar;
the Rainier, 20 to 23 percent. That extra little percentage adds to
the all-important sweetness and helps explain the cherry's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rainier's only marketing problem is its color,'' Harris
said. ``People like rich color.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To give his Rainiers more color this year, he spread strips of
gleaming Mylar film between the rows of trees, to bounce the sun's
rays up into the lower branches much as suntan fanatics use
reflective collars.
</P>
<P>
   And big cherries sell better than small ones. Most growers carry
a seven-hole plastic template in their back pockets. If a cherry
fits through only the largest hole, it's called a nine-row; if it
can get through the smallest, it's a twelve-row. The jargon dates
back to earlier times when cherries were packed in small boxes. If
the packers could fit only nine in a row, they had big cherries and
were happy. With twelve-in-a-row cherries, they knew they would get
less money per box. The boxes are bigger now, but the size
principle hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cherries are sweet. Tart cherries, once called sours,
come mostly from the Midwest _ Michigan is a major producer. They
are the best for canning. Each year about 30 percent of the sweet
cherry crop is exported, mostly to Japan, Taiwan and Hong Kong.
Because of Japan's economic problems, the prospects for cherry
sales there are ``guarded'' this year, said Eric Melton of
Northwest Cherry Growers, the industry's promotional group, but he
added that the Taiwan and Hong Kong markets are growing and might
take up some of the slack. American cherries count as an exotic
fruit in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Bob Harris warily eyeing his fruit-heavy Rainier trees,
I drove over to Roy Farms, where Mark Roy was receiving flat boxes
filled with newly picked cherries. The boxes, in stacks about six
feet high, are rolled slowly though what looks like a large
bathroom shower. The water, a frigid 35 degrees, drops the
temperature of the delicate cherries to preserve them through the
packing process, on what is called ``the line.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-generation farmer in the Yakima Valley, Roy is a bit
more relaxed than Harris, perhaps because the Roys are more
diversified. ``We started in hops,'' he said. ``When that market
died, we moved into apples, and when apples began to slow down, we
got into cherries.'' The hops market slackened when the beer market
stalled, but the 20-foot-tall plants are still highly visible
throughout the Yakima Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Temperature is everything in cherry shipping. Cherries destined
for the Northeast travel directly from packing plants in Washington
to the Hunts Point Market in the Bronx in refrigerated trucks. ``We
put recorders in the trucks,'' said B.J. Thurlby, promotion
director for the Washington State Fruit Commission. ``It's a
five-day trip to New York, and constant refrigeration at 32 degrees
is expensive. Let's say some truckers might be tempted to turn it
off now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherries may be difficult to deal with, but these are relatively
happy days in the Yakima Valley orchards. Demand in the United
States continues to grow, and markets overseas are expanding, if
slowly. Last year's crop, more than 90,000 tons of all the
varieties grown here, was the largest on record, and the experts
are predicting that as young trees come into production, crops of
110,000 tons and more are possible over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, conditions and tastes change. One day there might
even be a glut. Chances of that are slim, though, because everyone
who works in the business keeps eating cherries. As he walked
through his orchard complaining, Harris kept pulling cherries off
the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try this,'' he'd say. ``It's delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   I did. And he was right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
