<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IMPORTANT FIRST SIP: NOT TO BE TAKEN LIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you remember the wine that first won you over? The bottle
that first made you say ``I don't know anything about wine but this
is good stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a wine you would blush to serve anyone _ or be
caught drinking _ today. But it tasted great at the time and it
introduced you to a new world, another level of sensual enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   The wine books are full of tales of vinous epiphanies. Most of
them seem to start with Bordeaux. ``I had just turned 16,'' one of
them will begin. ``My father gave me a sip from his glass; the '34
Latour. I'll never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Very dramatic, but I don't believe those tales. Cutting one's
teeth on a Bordeaux first growth is like starting out on music with
Mahler. Not impossible but most improbable. With wine or music, you
have to work your way up.
</P>
<P>
   What started me thinking along these lines was an informal
little tasting I had in Seattle last week with David Lake, the
winemaker at the Columbia Winery. David pulled out most of his
lineup, about 15 wines, single-vineyard chardonnays, a pinot gris,
merlots, a syrah and some rare, older cabernets. He also opened two
easygoing wines, a light, moderately sweet riesling and a simple,
undemanding chenin blanc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of those two as starter wines,'' he said, ``wines for
people who are used to soft drinks and who are just getting into
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Both wines were light-bodied, with lots of fruit, by which I
mean the taste of the grape they are made from, and a noticeable
touch of sweetness. Not enough to be cloying but enough to ease the
transition from Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   For someone with no previous wine-drinking experience, starting
off with a big red wine like the 1934 Chateau Latour would probably
be a shock; enough of a shock to turn that someone off wine
forever. It is the difference between Norman Rockwell and Andrew
Wyeth. Both well done, but one is infinitely more subtle and
nuanced and ultimately more memorable than the other.
</P>
<P>
   A great red wine is completely dry; all the sugar has been
fermented out. To the trained palate, the wine is balanced; there
is perfect, or near perfect, harmony among tannins, fruit and acid.
An inexperienced wine drinker might find the wine astringent; he or
she will express this by saying it is sour, or too sharp on the
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable wine producers try to cushion the shock for
newcomers by leaving some sugar in the wine during the fermentation
process. It is a technique that made Kendall-Jackson Winery's
Vintners Reserve Chardonnay one of the most popular of all
entry-level wines.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one gets the impression that many relatively
inexpensive wines are a bit sweeter than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans talk dry,'' a saying in the wine trade contends,
``but they drink sweet.'' Is it any wonder, when ketchups and
supposedly spicy barbecue sauces are heavily laced with sugar; when
so many breakfast cereals are more like candy than food?
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 1970s, Americans favored heavily sweetened,
fortified wines like sherry and port. But there is no evidence that
drinking these wines led to an interest in and a taste for table
wines. No more than did the succession of lighter sweet wines that
have been favored over the years by American consumers, wines like
sangria, cold duck and apple wine and, more recently, the immensely
popular wine coolers and the Italian lambruscos like Riunite.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of these wines, known in the trade as pop (for popular)
wines, tend to stick with them or, more precisely, to skip from one
to another. Like Hula-Hoops and tail fins, pop wines tend to come
into fashion quickly, then disappear just as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Serious wine drinkers, people who know their vintages and grape
varieties, who buy good glasses and call their local wine man by
his first name, are a different breed. More often than not, they
like the idea of wine before they get to the wine itself.
</P>
<P>
   The unlucky ones start out with an expensive Bordeaux or
California cabernet and are so put off by the taste that they go
back to beer. The fortunate ones get help from friends or a savvy
wineshop clerk. They start out with simple wines and, determinedly,
educate their palates.
</P>
<P>
   If they get sound advice, they will start with the softer white
wines, like riesling and chenin blanc, and with lighter chardonnays
like Fetzer's Sundance and Kendall-Jackson's Vintner's Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   They will experiment with pinot grigio, like one from Santa
Margherita, which is not sweet but light and uncomplicated. A
flowery, fruity gewuerztraminer, from Navarro, in Mendocino,
Calif., is a perfect starter. It gives the impression of sweetness
without being seriously sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Most people get into red wines these day by asking for merlot,
mostly because it is somewhat trendy. There are excellent merlots
around, but they are not necessarily introductory wines.
</P>
<P>
   Beaujolais, however, is easily the best way to get friendly with
red wine. It is fruity, fresh and uncomplicated and can be chilled
or served with ice. The current vintage is always the best, and the
price is almost always under $10 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Rose is another entrance wine that cannot be ignored. Some
excellent roses have come from the Languedoc region of France in
recent years under labels like Fortant de France and Les Jamelles.
They are real wines and quite capable of fostering an interest in
something better.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is always white zinfandel, which is more pink
than white and which may be both sweetened and carbonated. Mostly,
it is a harmless warm-weather drink that has very little to do with
real table wine and bears hardly any resemblance to genuine red
zinfandel, one of America's best wines.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple that are pretty good: Beringer Vineyards
makes one, and Sutter Home makes another. Will they create an
interest in ``real'' wine? It's possible; they're not that far from
a tasty glass of Beaujolais. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
