<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-CARIBBEAN-2TA     07-07 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-CARIBBEAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLUMBUS OF CHEFS AMONG THE PAPAYAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ On a blistering South Florida afternoon whose heat
approximates a restaurant kitchen's, Norman VanAken, dressed from
chin to cuffs in a white chef's outfit, looks refreshed and cool as
he cuts a path through sweaty shoppers in the Palacio de los Jugos
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Juice Palace started a generation ago on the west side of
Miami as a lowly sidewalk juice bar and sprouted piecemeal into a
sprawling produce and food market filled with intoxicating smells
and high-voltage Spanish chatter. It looks less than regal.
</P>
<P>
   But for Van Aken, the fresh fruits and vegetables shipped here
daily from the Caribbean, Latin America and other tropical lands
represent the raw material for dishes fit for gastronomic royalty.
</P>
<P>
   On this Saturday, he is paying a brief visit to buy mammee
sapota, a starchy fruit he will use to sweeten a few dishes on his
dinner menu.
</P>
<P>
   Van Aken, 46, is the head chef and partner of Norman's in nearby
Coral Gables, which is widely considered the best restaurant in
South Florida. A pioneer in the Florida-Caribbean fusion cooking
that he calls New World cuisine, Van Aken is perhaps the best known
of the Miami chefs who are called the Mango Gang.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, they invented a cuisine that dipped into
the traditions and flavors of the Western Hemisphere to produce
intensely flavored dishes with imaginative menu descriptions, which
are, like the food itself, a mouthful.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Van Aken's recently published cookbook, ``Norman's
New World Cuisine'' (Random House, $50), offers recipes like
Grilled Florida Spiny Lobster With an Exotic Fruit-Black Bean Salsa
and a Spicy Cumin Seed Drizzle; Rhum and Pepper-Painted Grouper
With a Mango-Habanero Mojo, and Sweet Pan-Fried Plantains and
Snapper Escabeche Ensalada With Salsa Romesco, Arbequine Olives,
Avocado, Oranges and Ribbons of Greens.
</P>
<P>
   Van Aken also expands the definition of New World beyond the
hemisphere and includes Asian climes like the Spice Islands (``the
place Christopher Columbus was trying to find in 1492''). It is a
cuisine, he says, with the common denominators of ``tropical heat,
spices and the sensual zest of regional dishes made with flavorful
fresh food.''
</P>
<P>
   He observes confidently, more in cold analysis than pure boast,
``No one else in Florida has taken it as fast and as far as I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   He disdains those critics who mock some elements of fusion
cooking as trendy or pretentious and lacking in the codified
traditions of, say, French cuisine. He also has contempt for
retrocuisine types at the other extreme, who maintain that all a
restaurant really requires is a good steak and an extra-dry
martini.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diners in my restaurant don't need a Ph.D. to be hit right in
the taste buds,'' he says with a twinkle that lights up his dark
brown eyes, which often turn pensive. ``To them it doesn't matter
how I arrived at these recipes _ all they needed to know was the
food tastes good and is flavorful.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Aken says he never tires of wandering the aisles of the
Palacio de los Jugos with other shoppers whose homelands may be
anywhere in the hemisphere, picking out fresh, unrefrigerated
produce, which, as he puts it, ``has not been yanked against its
will from the earth before its time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying three avocado-shape mammees in a small cardboard box
under one arm, he is led by drifting aromas to tables piled high
with dozens of choices like canary-yellow Honduran squashes,
emerald-green plantains from Hawaii and Jamaican papayas. He scoops
up a piece of fruit and takes a quick whiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sapodilla,'' he announces before adding it to his box. ``It
has a nice root-beer taste that goes well in pastries.''
</P>
<P>
   On impulse, he selects several more items that he will work into
dishes over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   For a bright young man from a blue-collar family in Illinois
whose only connection to a professional kitchen was through his
mother, a waitress, the journey up the cooking ladder was a long
climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be a writer and took jobs in restaurants to
pay the bills, though I did love the cooking end of it,'' Van Aken
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   After studying literature at colleges in Illinois and Hawaii, he
dropped out at 20 to work full time as a breakfast cook in a diner
near his hometown. He struggled through stints in a short-order
kitchen, an all-night barbecue stand and restaurants with
predictable menus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like being a cook had no future,'' he says,
recalling the years spent in kitchens with hard men who looked
older than their years and who hid open bottles of booze in the
lettuce bin and slurped wine sauce out of half-eaten scampi dishes.
``There were a lot of kitchens that broke your heart if you were
serious about food.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Aken made his way to Key West in the mid-1970s, drawn by the
romance of the place and its connection to Ernest Hemingway. It was
there that his link with the Caribbean was forged.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in the kitchens of restaurants with solid reputations
among local food lovers and visitors: Louie's Backyard, the Pier
House and Chez Nancy. With his wife, Janet, also a cook, he
devoured classical cooking books as well as ``The Chez Panisse Menu
Cookbook'' by Alice Waters, who introduced Americans to the
pleasures of fresh regional ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   He soon tried to integrate into his own menus the traditions of
Key West's small Cuban-Bahamian eating places, which serve red
snapper or shrimp sauteed in pungent citrus-based mojo sauce,
steaming plates of black beans and rice, and fried plantains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little joints in Key West rang my bell,'' he says, his
eyes dancing again. ``I threw off the training wheels and pedaled
in my own direction. It was being a jazz musician in a jam session,
doing someone else's set and becoming more than just a good
sideman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing thing was we were doing black beans and rice in a
white tablecloth restaurant with no apology. Mangos and mustard
sauce on roast chicken. We welded the purity of flavorful rustic
food with classical technique to serve the freshest local food
available, side by side with a proper mousse or sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Key West in 1980 to run kitchens elsewhere, he
returned four years later to become head chef at Louie's Backyard,
a move that added luster to his growing reputation. After an
article on the restaurant appeared in Bon Appetit in 1987 and
publication of his first cookbook, ``Feast of Sunlight,'' he opened
his own Key West restaurant, Mira. Despite glowing reviews, it
closed after 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had 38 seats, and we got crushed during the slow
summer season,'' he notes with the sorrow of one who lost something
very dear. ``It was a heartbreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   After an unhappy stopover in a Boca Raton restaurant, he opened
A Mano in Miami Beach and burnished his reputation with celebrities
and visiting food critics in the fast-paced South Beach scene. He
left in 1993 in a dispute with his partners.
</P>
<P>
   He opened Norman's with seven partners in 1995. For the first
time in his nearly three-decade climb up the food chain, Van Aken
has hit the big time. Rave reviews led to cooking shows on national
television, a national book tour and consulting work, most notably
an assignment by United Airlines to overhaul its first-class dining
fare on flights to South America.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the kitchen is his milieu, whether he's coaxing a gravy
to brown or watching with satisfaction the smoky bubbling of a fish
fillet in hot oil. And there is the daily business of finding the
right string of words to fill a menu with evocative descriptions of
a new dish.
</P>
<P>
   To make one's way through Van Aken's degustation menu is to
marvel at the flavorful bursts in dishes like one described as
pan-roasted chorizo-crusted dolphin on a plantain paella Valenciana
with olives, peas, garbanzos and Romesco aioli.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his menu is a mouthful. It brings to mind the scene in
``Amadeus'' when Emperor Joseph II of Austria chides Mozart for
using too many notes in his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' Van Aken says, considering the comparison. ``But how
many people remember the name of that king? Everyone knows
Mozart's.''
</P>
<P>
   SNAPPER ESCABECHE ENSALADA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Norman's, Coral Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ hours, including refrigeration
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1\ pounds boneless, skinless red snapper fillets
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   { red onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup loosely packed, torn cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup gold tequila
</P>
<P>
   { cup Spanish sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   } cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 small handfuls mixed lettuce (like romaine, red leaf,
radicchio, Belgian endive or curly endive), cut into thin ribbons
</P>
<P>
   2 Valencia or navel oranges, peeled and divided into segments
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, peeled, pitted and sliced into thin wedges
</P>
<P>
   20 to 24 Arbequine or other small black olives, pitted or not as
desired.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small dry skillet over medium heat, combine cumin seeds
and peppercorns. Allow to heat until they are fragrant and slightly
smoking, about 30 seconds to 1 minute. Transfer to a spice grinder,
and pulverize until not quite finely ground. Place in a small bowl,
add the sugar, } teaspoon of salt, and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place fish fillets in a wide shallow dish. Rub fish on one
side only with ground spice mixture. Cover and refrigerate for at
least 30 minutes or as long as 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove fish from refrigerator and set aside to bring to room
temperature. In a nonreactive mixing bowl, combine garlic, red
onion, cilantro leaves, tequila, \ cup of the sherry vinegar, the
lime juice, \ cup of the orange juice and \ cup of the virgin olive
oil.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a large nonstick or well-seasoned skillet over a high
flame, heat peanut oil until it begins to smoke. Immediately add
fish fillets, and sear for 15 seconds on each side. Transfer
fillets to a wide shallow dish, and allow to cool. Add marinade in
the mixing bowl to the fish, coating fillets well. Cover, and
refrigerate for 1 to 3 hours, depending on the thickness of the
fish.
</P>
<P>
   5. To prepare a vinaigrette, in a small pan over high heat,
bring the remaining { cup orange juice to a boil and reduce to \
cup. In a large mixing bowl, combine the remaining \ cup vinegar,
reduced orange juice and salt to taste. Whisk to blend. Add the
remaining virgin olive oil, extra virgin olive oil, shallots and
black pepper to taste. Whisk to combine, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, remove fish from marinade, and slice into fingers.
Place lettuce in a large mixing bowl, and toss with vinaigrette.
Mound the salad on cool serving plates. Arrange the fish slices
around the salad with the orange segments, avocado slices and
olives. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
