(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
WILLIAMS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ To be downright cartoonish about it,
country singer-songwriter Lucinda Williams can almost be viewed as
Superwoman battling the forces of nature and record company
politics to make the album of the year. The six years it took to
cut her widely acclaimed new record, ``Car Wheels On A Gravel
Road,'' illustrates the number of things that can go wrong for an
artist trying to get it just right. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-MUSIC-LADN     07-07 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONG, HARD ROAD TO ACCLAIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To be downright cartoonish about it, country
singer-songwriter Lucinda Williams can almost be pictured as
Superwoman battling the forces of nature and record-company
politics to make the album of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The six years it took to cut her widely acclaimed new record,
``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' illustrates that when it comes to
her music, Williams would rather make great art than cash in on the
wave of attention that greeted her when she won a songwriter's
Grammy Award for Mary Chapin Carpenter's cover of ``Passionate
Kisses'' a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As well as being a critic's favorite and a songwriter's
songwriter, Williams is someone who doesn't cave in easily. When
labels and producers have attempted to mold her into the next
Bonnie Raitt, Williams has shown herself to be as stubborn as she
is talented.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everybody agrees Williams should be a good deal more
famous than she actually is. However, it's more important to her to
make the best music possible rather than release something that
isn't the very best she can give.
</P>
<P>
   That's why tales of her hair-pulling perfectionism during the
making of ``Car Wheels'' have traveled extensively throughout the
music industry for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not that big of an ordeal,'' Williams downplays.
``It's really just part of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, she tells of a tornado that shut down
the recording studio, an infestation of giant bugs that terrorized
Nashville, and a record company that placed her so far in the
proverbial outfield someone had to call her on a nearby pay phone
to say her team was up at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also faced her own insecurities, forcing her to recut
the record twice from scratch and then lay on overdubs _ all with
the goal of making the songs sound less produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took so long partly because I kept wanting to try different
things,'' Williams, 45, said. ``Then, things weren't happening in
the normal way, and everything came to a screeching halt, putting
me in a state of limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   The years of effort paid off. ``Car Wheels'' has received
through-the-roof reviews from Rolling Stone (``a country-soul
masterpiece''), Spin (``album of the year''), Newsweek (``like Bob
Dylan's `Time Out of Mind,' `Car Wheels' is poised to be an
exhilarating mid-career breakthrough'') and Entertainment Weekly
(which gave it an ``A'') plus raves from No Depression and the
Village Voice online site, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Blackstock, co-editor of No Depression magazine, which
covers the alternative country scene, said he expected the
long-awaited record would suffer the ill effects of too many cooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been so long in the works and so many people were
involved that I didn't think the songs would survive,'' he said.
``Lucinda deserves a lot of credit for sticking to her guns. It's a
terrific album.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughter of Southern poet/university professor Miller Williams
(who read his work at President Clinton's second inauguration),
Lucinda is famous for clashing with labels, producers and business
types, but she's also considered one of the best songwriters in the
field, with a knack for nailing characters with the telling detail.
Her songs have also been covered by Patty Loveless and Tom Petty.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to start work on ``Car Wheels'' (Mercury), her
fifth album, Williams entered an Austin, Texas, studio with a
longtime friend and resident genius, guitarist-producer Gurf
Morlix.
</P>
<P>
   But after singing on Steve Earle's 1996 album, ``I Feel
Alright,'' Williams fell for its production sound, fired Morlix and
hired the Twang Trust _ Earle and producer Ray Kennedy _ to recut
most of her tracks in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, she brought in E Street Band keyboardist Roy
Bittan to produce even more overdubs in Los Angeles. A string of
top guitarists began traipsing through the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a history of taking a long time to make her records,''
said prolific session musician Greg Leisz, who played 12-string
guitar and mandolin on two ``Car Wheels'' tracks. ``It's really
part of her process where she has to feel completely satisfied with
what she sends out into the world. She's going on her instincts,
and that may be inconvenient for anyone expecting her to get the
album done by a certain time. She has a hard time letting go.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a tribute to Lucinda's perseverance that after so
many people told her the record was finished and great the way it
was, she listened to her inner voice, which told her it wasn't
really ready yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has had famously bad luck with record companies. She
recorded two albums of folk, blues and country standards for
Smithsonian/Folkways before putting out ``Lucinda Williams'' on the
indie Rough Trade, which folded a few years later and never gave
the album much push.
</P>
<P>
   Her most recent record before ``Car Wheels'' was 1992's lively
``Sweet Old World'' for the now-defunct indie Chameleon. As usual,
critics and fans found the disc irresistible, but the troubled
label did little to promote it.
</P>
<P>
   Then she signed with Rick Rubin's American Recordings, which
went through structural changes last year before inking a
distribution deal with Columbia, further delaying ``Car Wheels.''
Williams signed with Mercury after splitting with American.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' rough-edged voice sounds as if she's speaking directly
from the heart on such sad, powerful songs of loss as ``Right in
Time,'' ``Drunken Angel,'' ``Lake Charles,'' ``Jackson'' and the
new album's title track.
</P>
<P>
   She says that when London-based folk-rock producer Joe Boyd
(Nick Drake, Fairport Convention) got an advance copy of ``Car
Wheels,'' he sent Williams a postcard saying the music reminded him
of Bob Dylan's ``Blonde on Blonde'' masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has a loyal cult following, the Nashville-based
Williams is hopeful Mercury will put some marketing muscle behind
the disc. Already some rock and country stations are airing ``Still
I Long for Your Kiss,'' a different version of a song from ``Car
Wheels'' that appears on the soundtrack to ``The Horse Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the songs on ``Car Wheels'' are about Southern places
Williams knows from her youth _ Lake Charles (the Louisiana town
where she was born), Lafayette, Lake Ponchartrain, Baton Rouge,
Macon, Greenville, Vicksburg, Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Some songs, she says, were inspired by two books of photographs
_ Shelby Lee Adams' ``Appalachian Legacy,'' with its portraits of
the region's citizens, and Birney Imes' ``Juke Joint,'' which
depicts funky old Mississippi Delta bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I think what happens when you're writing is you're
almost writing from your subconscious and don't even know it until
you finish,'' Williams said. ``Later, you realize you were
expressing something where you put yourself in that place. There
are so many levels.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Williams tell it, mastering sessions for ``Car Wheels''
were interrupted when a tornado hit town the day they were to
begin, just before giant bugs descended on Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``First the power went off,'' she said. ``Then came the cicadas,
these insects that hibernate for 13 years and come out, discard
their shells and buzz around. They look like locusts and they hang
around and make this intense noise for six weeks while they mate.
Then, they die and the larva drops on the ground and they burrow
and feed off roots and live underground for the next 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said cicadas, while substantial, are basically
harmless.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just big, dumb bugs,'' she said. ``You don't even
notice they're there after a while. But they make this high-pitched
noise that carries on day and night. The fact that they came out in
Nashville the same year as my record gave us something to think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who recently appeared in two sold-out shows in New
York, will play some Lilith Fair dates before Los Angeles shows in
late summer. In the past few months, she's sung on tribute albums
to Kate Wolf, Howlin' Wolf and Gram Parsons (with close friend
Emmylou Harris, who also sings on ``Car Wheels'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and Joey Ramone asked me to write something for Ronnie
Spector's album, so I'm kind of excited about that,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her superb new album, Williams isn't optimistic about
her future on country radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it,'' she says. ``They don't even play Emmylou. It's
like, `We'd like to thank the country music industry for all their
support!' There's just nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
