<SLUG> BC-CITIES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CITIES HEALTHIER FINANCIALLY, BUT WORRIES REMAIN
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most U.S. cities are riding high on the nation's
economic boom, but rough times could be ahead, the National League
of Cities reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven out of 10 cities said they were better off financially
compared to a year ago, according to the league's survey of 314
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things look pretty good,'' said Brian O'Neill, a councilman
from Philadelphia and president of the league. Most cities are
doing well because of ``a continuing effort by cities to work
harder, smarter, more efficiently and more creatively then ever
before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While most cities report improvement over last year, the gap
between city revenues and the growth of the domestic economy
continues to widen, the report says. In the past 10 years, city
revenues have grown 46 percent while state revenues have grown by
67 percent and federal revenues by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, cities are being asked to take on more and
more duties once regarded as federal or state responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trends look very, very scary,'' O'Neill said. ``City
leaders are balancing scarce resources alongside a daunting list of
priorities and needs.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, with welfare reform the responsibility has
shifted from the federal government to the state and local level.
</P>
<P>
   The league is also concerned about efforts by the federal
government to block cities' access to new revenue, such as an
Internet tax proposal that has already passed the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would block an estimated 30,000 state and local
governments from levying new taxes on business conducted via the
Internet. Sponsors say the legislation is intended to encourage the
use of Internet-based business.
</P>
<P>
   But state and local officials fear the moratorium could deplete
public coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we need is someone in Washington pulling the
plug on our businesses and our tax base by creating another special
tax haven _ at our expense _ that no one needs,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings in the survey include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nearly 30 percent of cities increased local user fees or other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thirty-seven percent of cities increased the size of their
work force, while 10 percent reduced it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nineteen percent of cities increased property tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nineteen percent of cities increased education spending.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In cities with more than 300,000 population, 91 percent spent
more money on public safety.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reductions in property tax occurred most among cities in the
Midwest and the South.
</P>
<P>
   The 314 cities in the survey included 27 of the 51 largest U.S.
cities, 40 percent of cities with populations between 100,000 and
300,000, and one-third of cities with populations from 50,000 to
100,000. It also included a random sample of 115 cities and towns
with populations between 10,000 and 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
