<HEADER>
A4031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRUNCH-ART-2TAKES-     07-07 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRUNCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BRUNCH, THE MORE BIZARRE THE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the weekend arrives and the city's daytime motor
shifts into idle, New York prepares to greet its favorite meal. It
is called brunch, and it is weird. A linguistic and culinary
hybrid, brunch is a breakfast that begins with a cocktail. Or a
lunch that's organized around a stack of buckwheat pancakes. It's
neither fish nor fowl nor good red herring, although all three can
wind up on the same plate.
</P>
<P>
   At Cafe Botanica, in the Essex House, patrons glide past a
buffet table that starts with danishes and bagels on one end, moves
quickly to a mountain of peeled cold shrimp, and takes a sharp left
turn toward a medley of Oriental dishes like vegetable dumplings
with a soy dipping sauce and a three-color seaweed salad.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer oddness, however, nothing on the table quite matches
the sardine-potato tart at Home restaurant in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of mashed potatoes left over one Saturday night,
and I remembered some sardines I'd seen at Murray's Cheese Shop,
packed in salt,'' said David Page, Home's owner and chef,
explaining the origin of the dish. ``I came up with a kind of cake
with a red bell-pepper sauce, and a poached egg on top.'' The dish,
now served with a roasted tomato sauce, has never been off the menu
since.
</P>
<P>
   The strange world of brunch continues to expand, generating
bizarre new life forms, embracing flavors and ingredients never
before associated with mankind's pre-noon existence. There was a
time when huevos rancheros represented the outer limit of
brunchtime experimentation, but as chefs have ranged far and wide,
and then farther and wider, in search of new influences, and as
diners have adopted a global outlook, the always fluid boundaries
of brunch have stretched to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   No one is complaining _ not in New York, where every weekend the
faithful line up outside hot spots like Isabella's on the Upper
West Side, or Friend of a Farmer on Irving Place, or E.J.'s
Luncheonette on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Rain or shine, brunch lures everybody: couples who may or may
not have met the night before, young people treating their parents,
couples with children, young women in pairs or 10-strong gangs and,
in the gay brunch belts of west Greenwich Village and Chelsea, men
in pairs and big groups.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers notoriously chafe at lines and delays, but come the
weekend, they meekly tolerate a wait of 30 minutes for a crack at
oysters on the half shell, baby spinach omelets and Irish steel-cut
oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   For the hundreds of restaurants that routinely serve a Saturday
brunch as well as the more traditional Sunday one, the brunch
stampede is a bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Popover Cafe, a 90-seat restaurant on the Upper West Side,
serves nearly 500 brunches on a busy Sunday. Isabella's, a 195-seat
restaurant on Columbus Avenue, serves 1,000 or more. Matthew's, on
the Upper East Side, does its biggest business of the week at
Sunday brunch. ``Any restaurant that's open for brunch is packed,''
said John Villa, the executive chef at Park View at the Boathouse,
in Central Park. ``It's guaranteed business.''
</P>
<P>
   Chefs hate brunch. ``They hate cooking it and they hate thinking
about it,'' Bobby Flay, the chef at Mesa Grill, said. ``Saturday
night tends to be the busiest of the week, and they've probably
gone out to have a few drinks afterward. Suddenly it's Sunday
morning and you have to come in and cook eggs.'' Flay says that he
happens to love brunch, but on this issue, he is out there alone.
</P>
<P>
   Villa said: ``To me, it's one of the hardest menus to write. You
have to have a balance, but you can't have too many breakfast
items, because the meal carries on until 4 p.m.'' In his case, that
means a Thai-influenced shrimp frittata and a grouper club sandwich
side by side with granola and yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   If chefs seem to be taking license with brunch, that's because
freedom is written into the charter of this oddity among meals.
</P>
<P>
   Although the meal itself came to glory in the United States, the
word is a British invention, coined in 1895 by Guy Beringer in a
visionary article titled ``Brunch: A Plea.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of England's early Sunday dinner, a postchurch ordeal of
heavy meats and savory pies, the author wrote, why not a new meal,
served around noon, that starts with tea or coffee, marmalade and
other breakfast fixtures before moving along to the heavier fare?
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating the need to get up early on Sunday, brunch would
make life brighter for Saturday-night carousers. It would promote
human happiness in other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brunch is cheerful, sociable and inciting,'' Beringer wrote.
``It is talk-compelling. It puts you in a good temper, it makes you
satisfied with yourself and your fellow beings, it sweeps away the
worries and cobwebs of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a century later, Beringer's template for brunch
remains as valid as the day it was created, perhaps because, in
drafting his culinary declaration of independence, he was not
overly specific about what dishes should be served. He demanded
``everything good, plenty of it, variety and selection.'' In a
postscript, he suggested that beer and whiskey could be served
instead of coffee and tea, laying down a precedent for the mimosa,
the Bloody Mary and the screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   It took a while for brunch to drift across the Atlantic, but
after World War I, Americans embraced brunch and made it their own.
The Jazz Age even created a novelty, a kind of second brunch that
filled the gap between dinner and the last, mad grab for excitement
as dawn poked its intrusive rosy finger into the party.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The Nation, noting that brunch had hitherto been a meal for poor
students and ``the lie-abed lady,'' described with some amusement
the mad 5 a.m. dash for sausages, pancakes and ``doughnuts, as
dainty and sugared as our grandmother never knew how to make
them.'' Then it was back to the dance floor for ``camel walks and
other steps from the zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   What might Beringer have made of the ``Sunday Strollers'
Brunch'' served at the Fifth Avenue Hotel in the 1940s, with its
sauerkraut juice, its clam cocktails, its chicken liver omelet in
Madeira, its calf's liver with hash browns, its Scotch woodcock? Or
House &AMP; Garden's brunch recipe, offered in 1952, for rice almond
pancakes served with herbed shad roe? ``A delicate hash, light fish
balls, and liver and bacon are all appropriate,'' one women's
magazine wrote in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Beringer asked for variety and selection, which is exactly
what the brunch menu at the River Cafe offers. Diners can start
with Cheddar soup or codfish cakes before advancing to omelets and
pancakes. At Mesa Grill, you can lead into the cinnamon and pecan
waffles or ranch-style eggs with a cornmeal-coated chili relleno
filled with goat cheese or a grilled white corn taco wrapped around
barbecued pork, potatoes and tomatillo relish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as much a state of mind as it is a meal,'' said Michael
McLaughlin, who ruled that chili, pizza and leg of lamb did not
belong in the brunch section of his cookbook ``Good Mornings,'' but
chili-rubbed steaks, Gruyere fondue and brownies did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast has regional differences, but it is more
clear-cut,'' he said. ``Brunch is much more eclectic, although I
would say that it has to be on a weekend, it has a festive aspect
to it, and it's social. You never have brunch alone, while
breakfast for one is perfect, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunch may be short on rules, but people have strong feelings
about what makes a good one. ``I like the fun of all the different
foods you can get,'' Elizabeth England, a writer, said. Lara
Shriftman, a public relations executive, said she gravitates toward
Friend of a Farmer because it feels ``very country, earthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, of Home, says it is no coincidence that family groups turn
out for a meal at a restaurant with a name like his, as though
searching for the ideal, family-around-the-table experience that
Americans regard wistfully on the television screen but never
actually put into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Brunch spells warmth, abundance and homeyness. It is, in many of
its associations, an invitation to go back to childhood. ``People
respond to the smell of coffee and bacon in the morning,'' said
Carrie Levine, the chef and owner of Good Enough to Eat, a cozy
restaurant on the Upper West Side. ``It reminds you of childhood,
when someone was cooking for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. England said, ``I like those places that have that homey,
baked-goody sort of feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levine has observed that bad economic news somehow
translates into increased brunch business, as nail-chewing traders
and brokers seek solace in the foods that bring them back to a
simpler time.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of this gentle picture is that, for the restaurant
staff, brunch can be hell. It's not easy feeding hundreds of
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brunch people tend to be very fussy,'' Marc Propper, the owner
of Grove in Greenwich Village, said. ``They want their eggs this
way, not that way, they want sauce on the side. The list of special
requirements goes on and on.'' One customer actually insisted that
the staff butter his toast. ``We didn't do it,'' Propper said. ``We
had to draw the line somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levine has seen the same customers. ``Even the words they
use when ordering tend to be childish,'' she said. ``They'll say
they don't want their bacon mushy.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame them, really? New York is a tough town. No wonder
its citizens wake up on Saturday and Sunday desperate for a little
coddling, and ready for a spiritual return to the wholesome,
abundant meals that good folks out in the heartland are eating.
They want lemon ricotta pancakes, a lobster and arugula omelet, and
a nice cold pitcher of tequila punch. What's so odd about that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
