<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMERO-HORROR-MOVIES-     07-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMERO-HORROR-MOVIES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORROR AS AN EVERLASTING FAILURE TO COMMUNICATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 12) 
(th) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in George A. Romero's ``Day of the Dead'' there is a
revelation. In a huge subterranean cavern cut off from what's left
of human civilization, a doctor in a blood-soaked smock rips and
pulls at a male body on an operating table.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unspeakably gory things being done to him, the
fellow lies there blinking as if nothing is happening until
suddenly something riles him. Sitting up, he reaches for the doctor
and loses most of his intestines.
</P>
<P>
   Typical zombie. Outside, a million of them are clawing their way
toward soldiers and scientists in the cavern. Inside, the doctor
picks up a power drill and bores a hole in the forehead of his
patient _ or specimen, or whatever you want to call it. The body
expires. The doctor is pleased and excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be domesticated,'' he cries. ``Knowing what they are,
we can condition and control them.''
</P>
<P>
   Released in 1985, ``Day of the Dead'' is one of four Romero
titles just reissued on video by Anchor Bay. Included is his first
feature film and zombie original, ``Night of the Living Dead''
(1968), shot in black and white in Pittsburgh for $114,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fun to dismiss this as undoubtedly the best movie
ever made in Pittsburgh,'' the critic Pauline Kael wrote, ``but it
also happens to be one of the most gruesomely terrifying movies
ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   These days it's silly to think of gangs of dead people, most of
them looking as if they were dressed at Bob's Discount, lurching
around in a trancelike state. On re-watching the films, however, it
can be said that their methodology has lost none of its force.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Roger Corman, Romero, 58, is credited with adding
extreme violence and gore to the modern horror film.
</P>
<P>
   ``George literally created a brand new world,'' said John
Carpenter, the director of ``Halloween'' and other horror films.
``The dead feeding on the living _ an incredibly simple but creepy
idea pulled off with a bravado style.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Day of the Dead,'' the soldiers are itching to blast
zombies, but with countless numbers to contend with, that would be
hopeless. Instead the doctor suggests a constructive alternative.
Romero films often hold out solutions. If only people would listen,
which, of course, they don't.
</P>
<P>
   In Romero movies, trouble is always snowballing, unstoppable in
the face of misinformation, paranoia and mistaken impressions,
distrust and plain stupidity. For example, in ``The Crazies''
(1973), a lesser-known film in the Anchor Bay package, a town
threatened by a biological weapon goes berserk when the Army
refuses to tell the people what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   As if in a nightmare, Romero protagonists never get the two ends
together. ``The themes are very simple,'' he said recently.
``People don't communicate well enough with each other, which means
that anything out of the ordinary leaves them befuddled.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Night of the Living Dead,'' heightened radiation is causing
corpses to rise in mutated form and go off looking for food:
people. In the first sequel, ``Dawn of the Dead,'' released in
1978, humans barricaded in a shopping mall manage to hold off the
proliferating zombies. By ``Day of the Dead,'' however, the ghouls
outnumber the living by 400,000 to 1 and have feasted their way
from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the hands of someone as talented as Romero, outlandish
subject matter and low production budgets merge into a striking
reality. At present he writes scripts and proposes
multimillion-dollar projects (all in various states of development,
he says), but he began his career making industrial films and later
used many of the same people in his first features. Camaraderie and
inexperience bred freshness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the innocence of the bunch of us making a movie
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His notion of horror took form when he was a child living in the
Bronx. ``I always loved the genre stuff,'' he said. ``When I was
growing up, horror had an allegory underneath _ stop the bomb,
radiation is killing us _ but on the surface it was a
roller-coaster ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he refined the mix. ``Basically my films are about the
unwillingness to accept change,'' he said. ``Once you fix that
thought, you can go in and do the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   By the ride he means a wild spree of blood and mayhem. Prompted
by the success of the first two ``dead'' films, backers offered
Romero $7 million to make ``Day.'' They also insisted that the
picture have an R rating, which would have been impossible with
hundreds of zombies ripping people's heads off, gnawing on limbs
and wolfing down great quantities of entrails.
</P>
<P>
   If he had got the $7 million, Romero said, he might have tried a
more complicated turn of plot. The doctor could have induced the
zombies to fight one another, which would have made a nicely
Romeroesque comment on the human condition. Instead he was given $3
million, which limited the film to a simpler scenario.
</P>
<P>
   In the cavern, the scientists and a grubby collection of troops
can't find a solution to their mutual zombie problem because they
can't get beyond their chronic disdain for one another.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor does train a ghoul called Bub to perform basic
functions with a toothbrush and a telephone, but then he makes the
mistake of feeding Bub a couple of dead soldiers. A psychotic
captain responds with a sustained burst of machine-gun fire to the
doctor's midsection.
</P>
<P>
   So much for experimentation. Bub does go on to prove that a
zombie can indeed be trained to do human bidding if properly
rewarded _ meaning fed. Like all zombies, he was a flesh-and-blood
human once himself. In fact, aside from their facial craters,
zipper scars and glazed expressions, zombies seem weirdly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a lot like us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically they're innocents lumbering their way through it,
just trying to put bread on the table,'' Romero said. ``They're the
blue-collar monster in the cotton fields. Lugosi's up in the
mansion.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1711EDT &QL; 
