r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     07-07 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME WRITERS ARE AT THEIR BEST IN SHORT FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most who read for pleasure read fiction, and most who read
fiction read novels. And that's unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the novel on its best behavior is what D.H. Lawrence
called it, the ``bright book of life.'' But many novels behave
badly, because their parents are deficient in discipline and
perhaps in understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking another metaphor I've long enjoyed, the late Texas
author George Sessions Perry said, ``A short story is a girl you
take on a date. A novel is the woman you marry.'' (Perry himself
wrote some exhilarating short stories before delivering a splendid
novel _ ``Hold Autumn in Your Hand'' _ which, however, provoked his
suicide. Not all marriages have happy endings.)
</P>
<P>
   The point is, people do not read short stories, but they should.
They cling to a practice of novel-reading that became a habit, on
both sides of the Atlantic, in the long-ago Victorian age.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, authors profiled as novelists often made their
more nearly perfect accomplishments in the shorter form. Consider,
for example, Henry James. He is the acknowledged master of the
novel of psychological insight; yet many among today's readers,
accustomed as they are to the quick fix, consider James a windbag.
The economical ghost tale, ``The Turn of the Screw,'' is an
exception, pointing to what readers should do: Read Henry James'
incomparable short stories.
</P>
<P>
   It is also said of present-day premier novelists _ e.g., Larry
McMurtry (''Lonesome Dove,'') Charles Frazier (''Cold Mountain'') _
that just getting into their long novels is difficult. Today many
readers start novels they never will finish. A short story, though,
is unlikely to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many writers, happy and secure in short-story production,
recognize the novel as an obligation, a prerequisite for
recognition as an ``author.'' Nathaniel Hawthorne's marvelous
``Twice-Told Tales'' were apprentice pieces for his destiny as
America's first unarguably great novelist. Edgar Allan Poe followed
Hawthorne's path and pattern but died at 40 before we had a Poe
novel. More recently, Raymond Carver was ``working up'' to a novel
when the Reaper claimed that superb short-story writer at age 50.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is complex, usually characterized by intricate
plotting. In the short story plot is very nearly absent, as the
narrative usually revolves around a single incident.
</P>
<P>
   Few are the authors who do not respond to the siren lure of the
novel and are content to write short stories exclusively. Canada's
Alice Munro apparently is one of them. For more than 30 years she
has been mining gold in the short-story terrain, consistently
earning critical raves. But other than people who both buy and read
``The New Yorker,'' few to this day know who Alice Munro is.
</P>
<P>
   When Munro's ``Lives of Girls and Women'' arrived in the early
1970s, the publisher (McGraw-Hill) labeled the work a novel. Like
Sherwood Anderson's famous ``Winesburg, Ohio,'' it had a unified
setting and background characters who kept bobbing up in different
narrative vignettes. Munro, though, did not agree; and ``Lives of
Girls and Women'' eventually was republished as a collection of
short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Munro, prose poet of the commonplace, may be the very best
short story writer on the present scene _ because of, rather than
despite, her limited canvas. The small Canadian town of Jubilee is
Munro's own Gibbsville or Yoknapatawpha. Her understanding of its
people and their place never fails to beguile. There is a
just-rightness in her every detail.
</P>
<P>
   But most of our literary gods are enjoyable in the short-story
realm _ Hawthorne and Poe; Herman Melville and Mark Twain; Edith
Wharton and Willa Cather; Raymond Chandler and Dashiell Hammett;
Scott Fitzgerald and Thomas Wolfe; and especially Ernest Hemingway,
some of whose novels actually are clunkers, but for whom redemption
is absolute in his short stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
