<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW SALTING CUCUMBERS WORKS MAGIC IN A DISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Recipe at end.) 
(th) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, a simple salad features such powerful flavors that by
adding a couple of straightforward ingredients, a whole meal
appears, as if by magic.
</P>
<P>
   The starting place here is a Southeast Asian-style cucumber
salad with a dressing made from lime juice, lemon grass, fish sauce
(called nam pla in Thailand and nuoc mam in Vietnam) and a few
other strong seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   This dressing mingles perfectly with the natural juice of the
cucumbers, which I draw out by salting, a process that takes some
time but almost no effort.
</P>
<P>
   If you slice cucumbers before salting and squeeze them after
they've sat for a while, you wind up with ultra-crisp slices that
contain little remaining liquid. But for a salad like this one, I
cut the cucumber lengthwise and salt the seeded sides before
slicing, thereby removing some but not all of their liquid. The
result is firm but still quite moist cucumbers that continue to
weep after slicing.
</P>
<P>
   This step transforms a dressing that is already juicy into one
that is quite thin. This consistency, I realized, has its
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   When I placed the cucumbers on top of a bed of salad greens,
their dressing moistened the greens instantly. And by adding a few
grilled scallops to the top, I created an easy one-dish meal whose
flavor really jumped off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   It looks lovely, too, especially if the cucumbers have not been
waxed and you can leave them unpeeled. And it is extremely low in
fat (although not by design, I assure you).
</P>
<P>
   If some of the ingredients here are new to you, be assured they
can be found at many city markets and in most large suburban
supermarkets. Although fish sauce may be an acquired taste, the
only ingredient here that requires what might be an unfamiliar
technique is whole lemon grass, which is usually sold by the stalk
and looks like a scallion.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off the top and bottom of the stalk, then make a slit along
its length. Peel off the tough outer sheath to reveal the tender
inner core: that's the part of the lemon grass to use. (Sometimes,
supermarkets sell the leaves of young lemon grass in packages;
simply mince them.)
</P>
<P>
   Although I like scallops best to finish this salad, they are far
from the only option. I tried a couple of pieces of pan-seared
halibut with great success. A lightly grilled steak or boneless
chicken breasts would work beautifully, too.
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER SALAD WITH SCALLOPS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   4 medium cucumbers, at least 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 limes
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 small chili, finely minced, or to taste (\ teaspoon of crushed
red pepper flakes is a good substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced lemon grass
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 cups mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 pounds sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon neutral oil, like canola
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped mint, cilantro, basil or a combination
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dark sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel cucumbers if they have been waxed, then trim their ends
and cut them in half the long way. Scoop out seeds with a teaspoon.
Sprinkle each half with about 1/4 teaspoon of salt, then place them
in a colander. Let drain for about 30 minutes. Rinse lightly, and
drain again. Cut into 1/8- to 1/4-inch-thick slices and place in a
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mix together the fish sauce, lime juice, garlic, chili, lemon
grass and sugar. Thin with a tablespoon of water. Taste, and add
more of any flavoring you wish. Toss dressing with cucumbers, and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place greens on a large platter. Put a large nonstick skillet
over high heat. In a bowl, toss scallops with oil, then sprinkle
them with salt and cayenne. When skillet begins to smoke, add
scallops one at a time; do not crowd them. Cook for about 2 minutes
on the first side, turning as they brown; depending on their size,
cook for 1 to 3 minutes on the second side. (Scallops are best when
their interior is slightly underdone; cut into one to check it.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Toss cucumbers with most of the herbs, and spoon them and the
dressing over the greens. Top with the scallops. Drizzle with
sesame oil, and top with remaining herbs. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
