<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-INFLUE     07-07 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-RIGHTS-INFLUENCES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE AMERICANS OFFER LESSONS ON ROLE OF WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (With WOMEN'S-RIGHTS.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The actions and support of many women in the
suffrage and reform movements read throughout the Northeast like
the roots of an ever-strengthening tree.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of those influences:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIVE AMERICANS
</P>
<P>
   If Seneca Falls, N.Y., was a cradle of reform in 1848, it could
be said that an Iroquois hand was rocking the cradle. Early
suffragists needed to look no further than their Seneca and
Onondaga neighbors to witness women active in government and
financially independent.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers like Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Matilda Joslyn Gage
visited Iroquois women. And Lucretia Mott spent a month at a Quaker
school with the Senecas at Cattaraugus in 1848, just before she
traveled to Seneca Falls for the world's first women's rights
convention, Sally Roesch Wagner explains in her essay collection:
``The Untold Story of the Iroquois Influence on Early Feminists.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their self-described ``modern'' white counterparts,
Iroquois women had the power to nominate political leaders, issued
the last word on whether to wage war, had custody of their children
and were not victims of male violence, Wagner writes. Even
bloomers, the first popular female pants, resembled a loose tunic
and leggings worn by the Native American friends of their creator,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Stanton, Gage, Mott, and their feminist contemporaries, the
Native American conception of everyday decency, nonviolence and
gender justice must have seemed the promised land,'' Wagner wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOJOURNER TRUTH
</P>
<P>
   Born a slave named Isabella to a Dutch owner in 1797, Truth more
than any other woman embodied the fusion of the abolition and
suffrage movements. In 1843 she changed her name to Sojourner Truth
and began to travel and preach, later lecturing for the
abolitionist cause.
</P>
<P>
   She attended her first women's rights convention in 1850 and in
1851 delivered her famous ``Ain't I a Woman'' speech at the Woman's
Rights Convention in Akron, Ohio. After the Civil War she found
homes and jobs for recently freed slaves.
</P>
<P>
   In visit to the Stanton home, Sojourner Truth leaned back and
smoked her pipe as Stanton's daughter read her the newspapers. When
Harriot Stanton asked Truth if she could read, she recalled Truth's
reply: ``Oh, no, honey, I can't read little things like letters. I
read big things, like men.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMELIA BLOOMER
</P>
<P>
   A governess from Homer, N.Y., Amelia Bloomer moved to Seneca
Falls with her husband. Male editors refused to publish women
writers, so Bloomer started her own monthly temperance paper _ The
Lily _ in 1849, one of several such female papers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Cady Stanton wrote articles under the pen name
``Sunflower.'' In 1852, The Lily's published sketches of the
``bloomer'' costume, a knee-length dress over trousers gathered at
the ankles. The outfit was created by Elizabeth Smith Miller,
daughter of abolitionist Gerrit Smith and a Stanton cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Miller reportedly adopted the set so she could climb stairs with
a lamp in one hand and a child in the other.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN B. ANTHONY
</P>
<P>
   Susan B. Anthony, who spent most of her life stoking the embers
of women's revolt, was a 50-year friend and unwavering ally of
Stanton _ ``my good angel,'' as Stanton put it, ``always pushing
and goading me to work ... it has been said that I forged the
thunderbolts and she fired them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony didn't learn of the 1848 women's rights convention until
it was over. She met Stanton in 1851 when Amelia Bloomer introduced
them in Seneca Falls after an anti-slavery speech organized by
Henry Stanton and William Lloyd Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1872 Anthony was arrested for voting and fined $100. She
refused to pay to a government that denied her representation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARY BAKER EDDY
</P>
<P>
   As the activists gathered for women's rights at Seneca Falls in
1848, Mary Baker Eddy was a widowed New Hampshire mother in her
late 20s who had lost rights to her property when her husband died.
A victim of chronic ill health, she began to experiment with the
homeopathic healing that eventually led her to become the founder
of Christian Science.
</P>
<P>
   As pastor of her own church in Boston, she built twin pulpits
for a Mother and Father God. Male doctors scorned her as she healed
their patients. She later published ``Science and Health with Key
to the Scriptures'' and began The Christian Science Monitor
newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
