<SLUG> BC-STATES-HUMA08-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  RIGHTS GROUP SLAPS PHILA.'S NYPD BLUE APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 7 -- A human rights group says Philadelphia and
other cities trying to model their police departments after New
York City's aggressive, zero-tolerance approach to crime should be
wary of the law of unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four years of New York's aggressive community
policing -- which is credited with dramatic decreases in crime,
including a 70 percent drop in murder -- complaints of excessive
force by police shot up 62 percent, according to Human Rights
Watch.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based group contended that Philadelphia already has
``one of the worst reputations of big city police departments in
the United States'', citing the old controversies from the rogue
cops in the city's 39th District. But the group's directors said
the problem could grow worse if new Commissioner John Timoney
doesn't place stricter controls on his troops in their crackdown on
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be at least as aggressive in crimes by police,''
said Kenneth Roth, Human Rights Watch's executive director,
promising to make police abuse in America ``the international
injustice that it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   One contributor to the report, however, said that Human Rights
Watch missed the point on New York's get-tough approach to crime,
which began in 1994. Then, New York Police Chief William Bratton
and his deputies, including Timoney, made it easier for citizens to
file complaints against police, something that has always been
difficult in Philadelphia, according to James J. Fyfe, a former New
York cop who is now a criminologist at Temple University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, New York's citizen review board fielded 5,487
complaints about police, including 2,173 citing excessive force; by
1996, it took in 8,869 complaints, 3,139 of which were based on
excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, by contrast, had just 577 citizen complaints in
1996, with 221 alleging physical abuse, according to the Internal
Affairs Division. Of those, 67 percent were from Hispanics or
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Allyson Collins, senior researcher at Human Rights Watch, said
anecdotal evidence had shown similar upticks in police violence
complaints in New Orleans and Washington, both of which adopted the
New York approach to crime. But Fyfe contended that many complaints
in these cities lack merit, coming from petty criminals not used to
being hassled by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if you have cops acting more aggressive, you'll
have more complaints,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Fyfe said the biggest problems confronting Timoney was that he
held firing power of only a handful of his deputies, unlike
Baltimore, where the commissioner appoints the 29 cops directly
below him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No boss has ever been held accountable (in Philadelphia),''
Fyfe said, something Human Rights Watch would agree with. ``It's
possible to enforce the law vigorously without using excessive
force.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
