<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES: A TELL-ALL VOLUME ABOUT SMOOTHIES AND JUICES; SHOPPING
NOURISHMENT; ICE CREAM'S NEW FACE; KOSHER PARMESAN; CHANGING
HORSES; CALIFORNIA-SOUTHERN; COUNTRY IN TOWN; CHEFS ON THE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Tell-All Volume About Smoothies and Juices
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a banana and some yogurt in the blender or sticking
some orange halves on a reamer is not all it takes to make a
smoothie or some juice. ``Smoothies and Juices,'' a new book by Ed
Marquand (Abbeville Press, $12.95), will set you straight.
</P>
<P>
   This attractive little volume leaves no detail unexplained:
whether to peel or pit certain fruits before processing them, how
to shop for ingredients, what equipment is needed, what it takes to
turn a juice into a smoothie and even how to add supplements to
increase the nutrient value of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are simple, tasty combinations, like a blood orange
and banana drink; a carrot, tomato and jalapeno juice, and a
nectarine, strawberry and blueberry mixture. None are sweetened
with sugar, though a few call for honey.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping Nourishment
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here is a street cart that has always been out of the
reach of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, as it is stationed on the steps
near the doorway of ABC Carpet and Home, 888 Broadway (18th
Street). Shoppers in the store and people in the neighborhood line
up for the high-quality fare, which comes from the Parlor Cafe
inside ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent muffins, scones, brioches, doughnuts, cinnamon buns
and cookies, $1.25 to $1.85, are sold from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily,
along with coffee, juices and fresh lemonade. The cart also has
sorbets and gelatos, mainly in the afternoon, $2 to $4.
</P>
<P>
   Ice Cream's New Face
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeremy Kraus is so proud of his accomplishment that
he has put his face on the containers of Jeremy's Microbatch Ice
Creams. Kraus, 22, introduced his brand last year and started
selling it in the New York region a few months ago. It is called
Microbatch because the ice cream is made in relatively small
amounts and only a few flavors at a time. It is produced at
Perry's, an ice-cream company near Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee chocolate chip, chocolate peanut butter, and vanilla
oatmeal raisin are the three flavors available at supermarkets,
including Pathmark, Grand Union and Shop Rite, for $2.75 to $4 a
pint. In August, these will be replaced by three new flavors,
including a Fuzzy Navel, which was inspired by a peach schnapps
cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Zabar's, at 80th Street and Broadway, has received
its first shipment of kosher Parmigiano-Reggiano. The cheese was
produced by Pieffe Co. of Reggio Emilia, Italy, in November 1996
under the supervision of a rabbi, and has been aging since then. It
is the only imported kosher Italian parmesan, and it is kosher for
Passover.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese comes precut in wedges of about 3/4 pound and 2 1/4
pounds. Zabar's sells it in these two sizes for $12.98 a pound.
Because Zabar's is not a kosher store, the cheese cannot be cut on
the premises. The cheese is good quality, but because it is sealed
in plastic, it is fairly moist and somewhat less crumbly than a
typical Parmigiano-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   Changing Horses
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the years, David Ruggerio, the chef and owner of
Le Chantilly at 106 East 57th St. has gradually shifted the
restaurant's focus from classic French to more contemporary
American food. Now, he has really broken with the past: He has
changed the name to David Ruggerio and is redecorating the place.
</P>
<P>
   The murals showing horse-racing scenes from Chantilly have been
removed (Ruggerio said he is keeping them for some future use). And
when the restaurant, which is now temporarily closed, reopens at
the end of the month, the menu will even include some Italian
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   California-Southern
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In August, when the peach season is in full swing,
Bobby Ochs plans to open Peaches, at 206 East 63rd St. The
Georgia-born Marla Maples will be a partner in the restaurant,
which will combine California-style fare with some of Ms. Maples'
Southern favorites, like fresh trout and peach cobbler. The chef
will be Antonio Maroto, who was previously at Flowers in the
Flatiron district.
</P>
<P>
   Country in Town
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christina's Country Kitchen, 493 10th Ave. (37th
Street), is not a movie set. But with its weathered siding, sagging
porch and working water wheel, it looks like something you'd find
on some back road, not on a busy avenue. Christina Bierling, who
owns the Gold Rush Bar and Grill next door, said it had been a
storage building. It serves breakfast 24 hours a day; steak and
eggs are $10.95, and assorted omelets $4.95 to $6.95, all with
grits if you wish.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs on the Move
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Essex House has promoted Luc Dimnet, the
sous-chef at Les Celebrites, to chef de cuisine, replacing
Christian Delouvrier, who is moving to Lespinasse at the St. Regis.
Gray Kunz, the chef at Lespinasse, has announced his resignation,
effective July 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
