<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DRUGS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO UNVEIL ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGN IN ATLANTA
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Launching the largest media campaign ever
undertaken by the federal government, President Clinton will unveil
a $2 billion national anti-drug program in Atlanta on Thursday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   Already tested in 12 cities, including Atlanta, the TV and radio
spots, billboard and newspaper displays, and Internet messages are
designed to counter a ``generational forgetting'' among young
people about the physical, social and psychological risks of drug
abuse, according to the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year campaign will be so pervasive that the targeted
audience _ children between the ages of 9 and 18 and their parents
_ will see or hear an anti-drug message an average of four times
per week, the sponsors vow.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes several weeks after Gen. Barry McCaffrey,
director of the federal anti-drug agency, reported that while the
nation's crack cocaine epidemic appears to be waning, more young
people are using marijuana and heroin. Marijuana is gaining
popularity among middle school students, and many suburban
teen-agers mistakenly believe they can avoid heroin addiction by
sniffing or smoking the drug rather than injecting it.
</P>
<P>
   These trends illustrated the need for the new media campaign,
McCaffrey recently told the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``We have a
new generation of kids. We have to start over,'' he told the panel
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was chosen for the national launch because of the pilot
program's success there and because of the community's other active
anti-drug programs, said Bob Weiner, a spokesman for the drug
control office. Both Clinton and McCaffrey will participate in the
event at the World Congress Center from 9 to 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner said the president has been involved from the start in
the campaign, which features an assortment of ``powerful'' spots
crafted to pierce a teenager's armor of attitude and to overcome
the reluctance of many Baby Boomer parents who smoked pot in the
Sixties to discuss drugs with their children.
</P>
<P>
   One TV spot, for instance, begins with the now-familiar shot of
the frying pan featured in the earlier ``this is your brain on
drugs'' campaign, but then shows the frying pan being used to smash
a kitchen to illustrate the carnage that drugs inflict on a user's
family and friends. Another uses a ``mommy's'' dramatic silence to
push parents to talk to children at an early age about the dangers
of drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The federal drug agency deemed the eight-week pilot program a
success and will now take it national. While $195 million in
federal funding was allocated for the campaign's initial year, the
expanded effort is counting largely on $1.8 billion in donated
media time and space for the anti-drug messages. The combination
will ``lead to unprecedented exposure for anti-drug messages
targeting both youth and adults,'' predicted the drug control
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
