<HEADER>
A4100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      07-07 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTER CHEF: GIVING A RAGOUT A LITTLE FORM AND TEXTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: recipe at end of article) 
This is the third of eight columns by Deborah Madison, the former
chef at Greens in San Francisco and the author of ``Vegetarian
Cooking for Everyone.'' Her collaborator is Mark Bittman. 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH MADISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing more satisfying than a warm stew or ragout.
Although they are among my favorite dishes, they are difficult to
serve at a serious restaurant. The very qualities that make them so
pleasing _ a comforting formlessness and simplicity _ also make
them less than elegant on the plate. And on a nice evening out,
elegant is what many people want.
</P>
<P>
   All of this explains why I was so taken by the noodle cakes I
saw in a Chinese restaurant years ago. The cakes were large, soft
pillows waiting to be served as beds for stir-fries. These
pan-fried cakes, I thought, could have a role in my own cooking,
but I would top them with a vegetable stew instead.
</P>
<P>
   What I like so much about the noodle cakes is that they do
indeed have a form, something for the eye to settle on. And since I
make mine with a crisp exterior, there's also something for the
knife and fork. In these two important ways _ form and texture _
noodle cakes seemed the perfect complement to tender braised
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   At first I modified the noodles only slightly, substituting
olive oil for the peanut oil used in Chinese cooking. Then I
discovered the cakes worked whether I used fresh noodles or dry,
Chinese or Italian, fat or thin _ although I do especially like the
look of the fine threads formed by capellini.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before I began to enliven their flavor with
herbs. Then I had the idea of laying half the noodles in the pan,
followed by some cheese and the remaining noodles. The result is a
crisp cake with a luxuriously creamy center. You can vary the
cheese _ and the herb, of course _ according to the vegetable
accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   I chose these vegetables because they are in season now. Small
eggplants combined with colorful peppers look wonderful and gain an
almost jammy sweetness after long cooking. You can make the dish
even more substantial by adding a few cubes of lamb, right from the
beginning, or finishing it with some tender white beans or
chickpeas.
</P>
<P>
   The time it takes to assemble this depends on how you choose to
work. Moving quickly, you can put together both noodle cake and
vegetables in less than an hour. If you prepare the noodle cake in
advance (it can be reheated), figure about 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   CRISP NOODLE CAKE WITH VEGETABLE RAGOUT  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 to 1{ hours  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { pound capellini or other thin pasta
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   } cup minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 small eggplants (about 2 pounds), cut lengthwise into
quarters
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large bell peppers (preferably 1 red and 1 orange or yellow),
cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   5 plum tomatoes, peeled, seeded, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups chicken stock or water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup or more freshly grated mozzarella, Gruyere or other
semisoft cheese, or a combination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Cook the pasta
until it is tender but firm. Drain, rinse in cold water, and drain
again. Toss with 1 tablespoon of the olive oil and { cup of the
parsley. Set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Put 3 tablespoons of the oil in a large skillet over
medium-high heat. Add the eggplants, and brown on all sides,
turning frequently, until tender, 10 to 15 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Put 2 tablespoons of the olive oil in a large Dutch oven or
saucepan over medium heat. Add the onion, bell pepper and garlic.
Cook, stirring occasionally, until they soften. Add the paprika,
tomato paste, eggplants, tomatoes, the remaining parsley, and salt
and pepper to taste. Add the liquid gradually, scraping the pan to
loosen any browned bits. Cover, and turn heat to low. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until the mixture is quite thick and soft,
about 30 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Put 1 tablespoon of the olive oil in a 10- or 12-inch
nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. After a minute, add half
the pasta, spreading them out with a spatula. Top with the cheese
and the remaining noodles, again spreading them out evenly. Lower
the heat to medium (the cake must not brown too fast), and cook,
shaking the pan occasionally, until the cake is lightly browned on
the bottom, 5 to 10 minutes. Slide it out onto a plate, top with
another plate, and invert. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Add the remaining oil to skillet, and slide the cake back in,
cooked side up. Brown the second side, then remove to a platter. To
serve, place a wedge of noodle cake on a plate with some of the
stew alongside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGETABLES-BOOK-REVIE     07-07 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETABLES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE BOOK: VEGETABLE DISHES WITH SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recipes for fennel, orange and walnut salad appear in many
cookbooks. But few of these recipes instruct you to rub the onions
with salt, which softens them and draws out any bitter juices, or
to toss the fennel with lemon juice, salt and pepper as soon as it
is sliced.
</P>
<P>
   The one in James Peterson's latest book, ``Vegetables'' (William
Morrow, $40), does. And this is exactly what makes his book such a
treasure, and so refreshingly different from the masses of
vegetable cookbooks on bookstore shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recipes are simple _ sometimes too simple for an
experienced cook _ and familiar, but they are meticulously
formulated and carefully written. Reading them, you can imagine
Peterson like a scientist in his kitchen, diligently working out
just the right order in which to mix the ingredients in his tomato,
basil and macaroni salad or his summer Italian-style mixed
vegetable salad.
</P>
<P>
   The book, his first since ``Fish and Shellfish,'' for which he
won a Julia Child cookbook award in 1997, begins with sections on
each vegetable, with ample descriptions, shopping hints, a list of
recipes in which the vegetable appears in the book, trimming and
cooking instructions, and evocative but simple ideas for preparing
the vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in the section on avocados (which Peterson
acknowledges are in fact fruit), he offers this idea for enjoying
the essence of ripe avocados, peeled and cut into sections: ``Crush
them on slices of toasted and buttered French bread, and sprinkle
with a little lemon juice, salt and pepper for a light lunch or
afternoon snack.'' It made me run to the store for avocados, which,
to me, is the power of a well-written cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are organized by cooking style and technique, like
vegetable gratins and casseroles and pureed vegetables. It is a
system that fails now and then, in sections like ``Baked
Vegetables,'' which contains just two recipes. And some vegetables
seem to be neglected. For example, Peterson uses far more baby
artichokes than large ones. In New York, at least, large artichokes
are much more readily available than baby ones.
</P>
<P>
   But he easily compensates for these flaws with mounds of useful
information. There are easy-to-read charts for boiling, steaming
and grilling, broken down by individual vegetable, as well as a
chart revealing vegetable yields after cooking. A thorough list of
sources is provided for unusual ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The style of the recipes is at once current and traditional.
Vegetables prepared a la grecque hark back to classic French
cooking, while a small stream of Indian-influenced recipes, like a
delicious sweet potato salad, and dishes that seem inspired from a
trip to a greenmarket, like baked peppers stuffed with fresh
mozzarella and basil, give a contemporary feel to the book.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from minor mistakes, like not salting the pasta water for
orecchiette with broccoli rape (it was good anyway), the recipes
work quite well, adding strength to an already solidly researched
and well-executed cookbook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
