u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT &LR;      07-07 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THERE'S A PIT, THERE'S A WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among kitchen gadgets, the cherry pitter has one of
the narrowest roles. It does not slice cherries or remove their
stems. It only pits them. And even if you're an ambitious cook, you
use it maybe once a year.
</P>
<P>
   But a fresh cherry pie is almost impossible to make without one.
So, cherry pitters hang in stores all year, and then sell like
crazy during June and July, the cherry season.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, though, few gadget companies have figured out how to
design one that actually works.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular models looks and functions much like a
syringe. The cherry is placed on a round doughnut-shaped plate, and
a thin stainless-steel shaft on a spring is pushed down with the
thumb to pierce the cherry and push the pit out through the hole in
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But the spring is so tight that by the time you have enough
cherries for a pie, you might also have carpal tunnel syndrome. And
the shaft is so thin that it often misses the pit _ especially in a
ripe cherry _ and you end up piercing the cherry so many times that
it is mutilated before the elusive pit finally decides to fall out.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Norpro and Fox Run Craftsmen versions of this pitter
are $2.29 at Zabar's, Broadway and 80th Street, (212) 787-2004. The
Cooks Club model, identical to those at Zabar's, is $2.99 at
Lechters stores around the city. In each case, the pitter worked on
the first try one of four times.
</P>
<P>
   Another standard design works more like a hand-held stapler. The
cherry is placed on a small doughnut-shaped plate, and when the two
sides of the pitter are squeezed together, a stainless-steel shaft
pierces the cherry and pushes the pit through the hole in the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Westmark Kernex cherry pitter, at Zabar's for $6.98, works
like this, but its plastic handle makes it feel flimsy. Large Bing
cherries hardly fit on the plate that holds the cherry, and the
hole in the plate is too small for some pits to fit through. So,
you have to hit the pit directly or it gets pushed to the side and
buried in the flesh of the cherry. Just one of four cherries I
pitted worked on the first try.
</P>
<P>
   Similar in design is the Leifheit cherry pitter, available at
Williams-Sonoma stores and from the store's catalog, (800)
541-2233, for $12.50. Of all the pitters I tried, it was by far the
best, with a pitting success rate of four out of four. Made
entirely of stainless steel, it is solid but not heavy. The shaft
that pierces the fruit and pushes the pit through the plate is
thick enough to grab hold of the pit and direct it out of the
cherry, not to the side. And it has a lever that holds the pitter
closed and compact for storage.
</P>
<P>
   But don't run out to buy a cherry pitter just yet; you may
already have a makeshift one that, to my mind, works better than
any of the gadgets. In the July/August issue of Cook's Illustrated
magazine, a reader suggests using a small star pastry tip (3/16 of
an inch in diameter, with five to seven points) to pit cherries.
The sharp tip, which is shaped like a cone and made of stainless
steel, is placed point upward on a work surface, and the cherry is
pushed over it, stem end down. In concept, it seems more like a
medieval dare: if you miss the pit, your fingers are slashed. But
it works unbelievably well _ just don't push down too hard, too
quickly. You can also use a smooth round pastry tip (3/16 of an
inch) instead of a star tip.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of the pastry-tip method are that you can control
the cherry better with your fingers and that the pit consistently
comes out easily and clean, held by the point of the pastry tip,
although it does split the cherry.
</P>
<P>
   And it leaves you with one less thing to have to stuff in that
gadget drawer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
