<SLUG> BC-LICORICE-BAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PANDA BAR: FOR LICORICE LOVERS, A SUBLIME CONFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me say this straight out: I love licorice and always have.
On Halloween, I was the kid avidly collecting the black jelly beans
as fast as my friends could discard them.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, like root beer, licorice is a strong flavor that you either
love or hate. While it seems to inspire squeals of disgust among
most American adults, it is beloved in Europe. So it's no wonder
that the best commercial licorice bar around, the Panda bar, comes
from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Made of only natural ingredients _ molasses, wheat flour,
licorice extract (derived from the root of the licorice shrub) and
aniseed oil _ this soft, glistening bar, black outside and the
color of dry earth within, is a wonderfully pure example of
licorice flavor. By the way, no need to say ``black licorice'';
there is no other kind. Those red twisted ropes are simply flavored
candies, enjoyed by those who don't yet know the pleasures of the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Panda bar is available at almost any health food shop and
many candy stores, and usually costs 50 cents to $1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1736EDT &QL; 
