<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-WAITERS-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE WAITER MARATHON TRAFFIC WILL BEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Sunday, in anticipation of Bastille Day, waiters
from New York's French restaurants will walk the walk. Slowed down
by a long waiter's apron, they will race back and forth four times
between Park Avenue and Fifth Avenue on 60th Street, balancing a
tray that holds two filled plastic glasses and a bottle of _ say
what?
</P>
<P>
   Look closely. It's Pineau des Charentes, an aperitif that needs
no introduction in France but remains a sort of wine-world trivia
question here. Too bad, because Pineau des Charentes, a fruity,
fragrant blend of Cognac and unfermented grape juice, brilliantly
performs the predinner task that a glass of chardonnay was never
really meant to do. Served chilled, it cossets and stimulates the
taste buds with a honeyed, nectarine sweetness that refuses to
cloy.
</P>
<P>
   Pineau des Charentes comes in two versions, a blond and a
ruby-color rose, which is a rarity in the United States. Styles
differ from house to house. The pineau of Pierre Ferrand, light and
restrained, has a delicate, floral aroma. Prunier produces a
Sauternes-like pineau with ripe apricot flavors. A. de Fussigny's
is slightly pruny. All three cost between $20 and $25. Other easily
found pineaus are Marnier, Bernard Boutinet and Reynac.
</P>
<P>
   Drink one and stand up for ``La Marseillaise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
