<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 8, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain and thunder will be common in the northern
Appalachians and southern New England as low pressure tracks east
across upstate New York. The merging of three streams of moist air
over the Northeast will result in flooding rains from the Hudson
Valley to Cape Cod. A cool, damp air current from the North
Atlantic will keep much of New England near 70 degrees. Sultry
weather from the South will direct tropical air into the Middle
Atlantic region. A mild, moist flow from the northwest will add
further moisture to the already saturated air.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and strong thunderstorms will erupt in the steamy air
mass over the Southeast, particularly in the Appalachians and
Piedmont plateau. Near record heat is expected again along the
Coast and in northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A weak cold front pushing south into the Ohio Valley will mark
the leading edge of somewhat less humid air. A second cold front
poised north of the Great Lakes represents an advancing cooler air
mass, which will sweep into the Northeast on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air ascending the central Plains will be injected with
torrid air from Texas in the presence of a jet stream disturbance.
The result will be a large cluster of strong to severe
thunderstorms over Kansas, Colorado and western Nebraska. A few
storms will develop from the Red River Valley to the Tennessee
Valley. Afternoon thunderheads will form over the southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The West will be dominated by high pressure which will sponsor
considerable sunshine and above seasonal temperatures. Fog will
stay near the Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tardy Heat
</P>
<P>
   Monday passed at Fresno, Calif., without temperatures reaching
100 degrees, setting the city's all-time record for the latest date
without a triple-digit reading. Fresno's mark followed on the heels
of a similar record set at Bakersfield on Sunday. Both cities lie
in the San Joaquin Valley, which is sheltered from routine sea
breezes by coastal mountains. Under relentless sunshine and with
nary a cooling thunderstorm, average daytime highs in the valley
climb into the upper 90s by the end of July, with triple-digit
readings typically already logged into weather annals much
earlier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFOTAINMENT08-COX     07-07 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFOTAINMENT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDIA MERGERS NEEDN'T RESTRICT MARKETPLACE, CONGRESS TOLD
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SHANNON JOYCE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unless new telecommunications giants block access
to a competitor's channels or Internet servers, mergers between
telephone companies, cable services and entertainment conglomerates
will give customers a wider variety of services in one convenient,
affordable package, industry experts told a Senate panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The recent proposed merger of the AT&AMP;T long-distance giant and
the cable provider TCI prompted the hearing by the Senate Judiciary
antitrust subcommittee to look at the benefits and drawbacks of
media consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wave of mergers that has swept across American industry
has led to concerns that there will be diminished competition in
the marketplace; that the free market of ideas will in some manners
be constrained, and that consolidation within these industries will
dampen innovation and creativity,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio,
the panel's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Chief Executive Officer C. Michael Armstrong tried to
soothe government concerns and discourage efforts to regulate the
changing telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to offer all consumers the broadest array of
communications services that are modular in choice, simple to use,
and affordable to enjoy,'' Armstrong told the panel. ``But this
merger is only a step in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong and others stressed the need to build the combined
phone, cable and Internet services into a universal system
customers can use to link to various resources.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems President John Marselle said he feared
competitors wouldn't stick to an open system. Sun developed the
universal Java computer language, and Marselle warned against a
Microsoft-like stronghold dominating the new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I constantly worry about the choke point,'' Marselle said,
meaning the place where an information provider can restrict
access, usually by creating a product that cannot read a
competitor's work.
</P>
<P>
   Marselle asked the panel to prevent a shift to a dominant system
that would not be universally accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can count on that because it's in our own self-interest,''
Armstrong said about maintaining an open system. For example,
Armstrong said that if subscribers to AT&AMP;T and TCI's new menu of
services would rather use outside Internet provider instead of the
one they provide, it would benefit both companies to let users sign
on. Otherwise, both could loose customers and money.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the promise of maintaining an open system, DeWine
said it concerned him that so many news organizations are owned by
private businesses, such as the partnership between ABC and Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it possible,'' DeWine asked, ``that you can become so
integrated and have so much cross-ownership you won't be able to
make objective decisions?''
</P>
<P>
   Television executives Robert Iger, president of ABC, and Richard
Parsons, president of Time Warner, assured committee members the
media mergers would not endanger the network's news departments or
restrict editorial judgement.
</P>
<P>
   ``News needs to maintain its independence and objectivity,''
Iger said. Despite ABC's merger with Disney, he said ABC reporters
continue to provide detailed and objective coverage of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said in some cases, the larger corporations formed by
the merger can compete where smaller companies can't. Using Time
Warner's CNN as an example, Parsons said only a large conglomerate
could have launched the network's two major competitors, the Fox
News Channel and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
