<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Wednesday, July 8. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ABIOLA (Washington) _ Moshood Abiola, Nigeria's most
prominent political prisoner, died of a heart attack on Tuesday
after meeting with visiting American delegation, according to the
Nigerian government. The United States says it has no reason to
doubt that Abiola died of natural causes. By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ Developments in the IMF negotiations with
Russia. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SECRETSERVICE (Washington) _ Federal Appeals Court rules
that Secret Service officials must tell a grand jury what they
observed of Monica Lewinsky and President Clinton at the White
House. The ruling, upholding district Judge Norma Johnson, may be
appealed either to the full appeals court or to the Supreme Court.
By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-JUDGE-REMOVED (New York) _ The N.Y. Court of Appeals upholds
the dismissal of ``Junk Judge'' Lorin Duckman.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SURPLUS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gov. Pete Wilson began his
tenure here seven summers ago with the largest budget gap that any
state had ever faced, a $14.3-billion shortfall that forced him and
the Legislature to raise $7 billion in new taxes and slash spending
by a like amount. The budget was finally passed 17 days after the
July 1 deadline. The next year, the wrangling was even worse, with
a record 63-day standoff over how to spread the pain. Now Wilson is
in his last year in office, contemplating another run for the White
House and eager to leave a legacy _ and California is once again
without a budget one week into the new fiscal year. But this time,
as in other state capitals this season, the fight is over what to
do with a surplus; but the debate about cutting taxes and expanding
services is proving just as bitter. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PALESTINIANS (United Nations) _ The General Assembly voted
overwhelmingly on Tuesday to give the Palestinians a larger role in
the United Nations and a voice in many of its peripheral
activities. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MISSING (New York) _ An investigation into the disappearance
of the owner of an opulent Upper East Side townhouse has led the
police to two unusual suspects: a mother-and-son con artist team
that is also being questioned in the recent murder of a wealthy
86-year-old man from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE (Paris) _ A strange thing has happened on
the way to the World Cup final: this fractious country, never in
agreement about anything, eternally divided, deeply skeptical, has
united around a soccer team that is now lauded by workers, women,
and even intellectuals. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
