<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO AVOID MELTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The paper said that June was the hottest month on record, but
what I want to know is why.
</P>
<P>
   After all, if June was the hottest month on record, there is no
reason why July won't be hotter still and August even hotter than
that, until, by September, we're all baked down to carbon-based
life forms the size of charcoal briquettes.
</P>
<P>
   And if everybody is reduced to glowing lumps of coal, we will
not be able to take advantage of our upcoming ``tax holiday,''
brought to us courtesy of the Florida Legislature (motto: No Stunt
Too Stupid If It Gets Us Re-elected), whereby we can save up to
$3.50 on the purchase of our next bowling shirt, but not our next
pair of bowling shoes, or perhaps it's the other way around. I'm
not sure. (Zippers will be taxed but belts will not, but what use
is a tax-free belt to someone who's a charcoal briquette?)
</P>
<P>
   So, you see, it's imperative that we find out why June was the
hottest month on record and correct the problem by mid-August so we
can all drive across town to the mall on congested, potholed
streets, past the overcrowded schools and under-funded police
department, in order to avoid paying the tax on a $50 fur coat.
(Don't tell the clerk you're going to wear your $50 fur coat as a
Halloween costume because then you'll have to pay sales tax.)
</P>
<P>
   I've been trying to think if there was anything I did,
personally, to cause June's record heat wave. I know that if my car
has been sitting in the sun all day and I open the door, a blast of
super-heated air smacks me in the face like solar wind, singing my
nose hairs and fusing the frames of my glasses onto my temples. If
everybody in Florida opened their car doors at the same time, I
expect the polar ice cap would melt and people in Iowa would find
themselves owning beachfront property.
</P>
<P>
   But I opened my car door no differently this June than I did in
Junes past, so I can't see how this could account for the record
heat.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, but not likely, that the tearing down of
Ringling Towers caused the heat wave. Demolishing an historic
landmark generates a lot of civic angst, but, to my knowledge, it
has not been scientifically proven that civic angst affects the
daytime highs or causes any other sort of climatic changes that
would lead to record-setting heat.
</P>
<P>
   Rampant cell phone use could have nudged the thermometer up a
degree or two, but, again, the scientific basis for this claim is
dubious at best. However, cell phone users can be irritating, like
when you're waiting in line at the convenience store to buy a
lottery ticket and some clown in front of you is calling his
girlfriend to find out if she wants the regular Slim Jims or the
spicy.
</P>
<P>
   But what part cell-phone-related irritation played in last
month's heat wave is a matter of conjecture, and, to tell the
truth, it is probably no greater an influence than the irritation
caused by the U.S. soccer team, talk radio or Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   (Would it be constitutionally permissible to outlaw the
McLaughlin Group if it was found that feuding pundits contributed
to global warming?)
</P>
<P>
   If push came to shove (and let's hope it doesn't in this heat)
and I had to choose the one thing that was most responsible for
last month's miserable weather, it would be sport utility vehicles.
Not only do they spew out more heat-trapping emissions than other
cars, the people who drive them own a disproportionate number of
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to record heat, with no relief in sight.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
