<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-HASEOTES-BOS     07-07 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HASEOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APHRODITE HASEOTES, 96; HEADED CUMBERLAND FARMS FAMILY FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aphrodite (Bassis) Haseotes, matriarch of the Haseotes clan,
which owns and operates the Cumberland Farms chain of convenience
stores and gas stations, died Sunday in Bay Path Nursing home in
Duxbury, Mass. She was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Haseotes and her late husband, Vasilios, parlayed a couple
of cows on a dairy farm in Rhode Island into a convenience store
chain with about 1,000 outlets across the country.
</P>
<P>
   She was senior vice president of Cumberland Farms and was widely
regarded as the power behind the throne at the multi-million dollar
family-owned conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in the village of Nymfeon in Macedonia, Greece, in
1902. She immigrated to the United States when she was 7 years old.
She and her husband, also a Greek immigrant, lived in Providence
until 1938, when Mr. Haseotes took the savings he had accumulated
by working in bakeries and selling fruit and vegetables and bought
a large tract of wooded land in Cumberland, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after they acquired the property, they bought a cow and
calf. It took them three years to pay off the $84 they paid for the
animals.
</P>
<P>
   They opened their first jug milk store in Bellingham, Mass. in
1956. Cumberland Farms was incorporated in 1957. By 1968 there were
500 stores. The first gas station was added to a store in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Growth accelerated during the Arab oil embargo in the mid-1970s,
when Cumberland swallowed up choice store and service station sites
abandoned by the major gasoline dealers in the Northeast and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, when she was 74, the conglomerate consisted of 17
corporate entities. In a story published in the Boston Globe on
Oct. 10, 1976, her children made it clear that she was a major
factor in the firms' success. ``Mother has the attitude that if you
want to do something, there's a way to do it,'' said one daughter,
Lily Hasiotes Bentas. ``Father worked hard, but he's more
easygoing.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves three sons, Demetrios B. of Cumberland, R.I., George
of Duxbury, and Byron of Southborough, Mass.; four daughters, Hytho
Pantazelos of Lincoln, Mass., Anastasia Marty of Princeton, N.J.,
Lily Bentas of Boston, and Joann Tambakis of West Palm Beach, Fla.;
a sister, Athena Bassis of North Attleborough, Mass.; a brother,
Thomas of Attleboro; and 16 grandchildren and nine
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
