<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANTS-TAXES-HNS &LR;      07-07 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS IMMIGRANTS GIVE MORE TO THE COUNTRY THAN THEY RECEIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Immigrants pay more in taxes than they receive in
benefits, but most of that money is going to the federal government
and is bypassing the states and cities hit hardest by their
arrival, according to a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, produced by the National Immigration Forum (NIF) and
the Cato Institute, said immigrants paid roughly $133 billion in
federal, state and local taxes in 1997, more than 8 percent of the
total. The figure included taxes on income and sales.
</P>
<P>
   However, the costs and benefits of immigrants are not spread
evenly among federal, state and local governments, according to
Stephen Moore, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government tends to receive about two-thirds of the
taxes paid by the immigrants, with the remaining one-third going to
state and local governments, according to the report, which was
based on dozens of university and government studies and U.S.
Census Bureau statistics. But state and local governments usually
provide about two-thirds of the benefits _ such as health care,
schools and roads _ given to immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the federal government is reaping a
windfall at the expense of state and local governments,'' said
Moore, an economist at the Cato Institute, a Washington-based think
tank that promotes free markets and limited government.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of all immigrants live in just six states:
Arizona, California, Florida, Illinois, New York and Texas. In
addition, more than 20 percent of the population of many large
cities _ including Chicago, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami and New
York _ is foreign born.
</P>
<P>
   Moore cited a study by the National Research Council that
concluded that each new immigrant costs these state and local
governments about $25,000 over a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been true for a long time that the federal government
should look at some form of economic aid for states and cities that
have large immigrant populations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said that over the course of their lifetimes, immigrants
pay about $80,000 more in taxes than they use in services.
</P>
<P>
   He said immigrants generally cost the government money when they
initially arrive in the country but that after 10 to 15 years in
the United States, they begin to contribute more in taxes than they
receive in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, they need a little time to get into the economy
and to begin moving up the pay scales,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the most important predictors of immigrants'
success in the United States were their education level and ability
to speak English.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 21 million legal immigrants in the United
States, with an estimated 4 million to 6 million illegal immigrants
living in the country. The report's definition of immigrant
included both legal and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But the report's conclusion that immigrants pay more in taxes
than receive in benefits came under fire from one Washington-based
lobbying organization that favors limits on immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Stein, executive director of the Federation for Immigration
Reform, called the report ``junk science.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a piece of propaganda ... to distort the findings of
recent studies that show that we must rethink our immigration
policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stein cited a recent federal study that found that immigrants as
a whole cost American households an average of between $150 and
$250 per year in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government should lower the annual number of
immigrants allowed into the country and give preference to people
with higher education levels.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Sharry, executive director of the NIF, said the report
proved that immigrants are not a drain on government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is this: We may not like the fact that we are
a nation of taxpayers, but should be grateful that our load is
lightened by the fact that we are a nation of immigrants'' Sharry
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NIF promotes legal immigration and has lobbied against
congressional efforts to curb the ability of immigrants to bring
family members to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 immigrants are admitted into the United States
each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore also said immigrants would play a key role in keeping the
nation's Social Security system solvent as 40 million baby boomers
begin to hit retirement age in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Because immigrants tend to arrive in the United States in their
20s and 30s, they will provide a needed boost to the dwindling
number of younger, native-born workers supporting Social Security
beneficiaries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, each Social Security beneficiary was supported by 16
workers. By 1993, the number of workers per beneficiary had dropped
to about three. The government predicts that number will fall to
1.8 by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cut off immigration today, the Social Security system
could not operate as is for very much longer,'' Moore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
