<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:If you must diet, try to schedule it in melon season
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a couple of evil unacceptable aspects to having an
illness _ of any kind, I suppose. I won't go into the worst one
_the hospital bedpan that no human being ought to experience. But
now the diet ...
</P>
<P>
   I have been on diets in my life, and it is my considered opinion
that food of all kinds is so good a free-thinking American citizen
should have an inalienable right to eat anything.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a new bride, I read somewhere that a three-day liquid
diet would do wonders for the body and the mind. My husband and I
stocked up on juices and embarked on the diet. At that time, we
lived in a tidy garage apartment on Pensacola Bay. It was tidy
because we had a three-days-a-week maid who kept an immaculate
house.
</P>
<P>
   But one day, we came home to find the apartment in a shambles
and a note stuck to the refrigerator: ``I have went home. I am
sick. I think it is the hungry headache.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been many times since that diet when I have felt
afflicted by the hungry headache. When they leave the salt, the
sugar and the fat out of your food, you may decide to forgo food
altogether. The only thing that saves you is fruit, and watermelon
season was the greatest bonanza to hit my recent illness.
</P>
<P>
   Alford, the little northwest Florida town where my mother lived
the last 38 years of her life and where my son now lives, was a few
years ago a great watermelon shipping center. Our friend Miss Pearl
Scott was the depot agent _ when they had a depot _ and normally
she could put on her sun hat, open her umbrella and walk two blocks
down the sun-baked street for lunch at home.
</P>
<P>
   Not in watermelon season. Trucks and wagons filled all the space
around the loading platform, awaiting the train that would take
sweet Jackson County melons to the underprivileged citizens of the
North. My mother knew some of the farmers and they were generous
with their melons. When my children visited, they could count on
watermelon being cut every afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now with melons in our stores priced at close to $5, a daily
cutting seems outrageous. And a watermelon cooling in a tub of
water in the shade of the pecan tree seems as extravagant as an
emerald necklace.
</P>
<P>
   Still it was the season, and nothing else tasted like anything
much, and my son decided to go find us a watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   A friend who runs a produce stand came through. The melon was
more costly than in the old days, but Miss Ardella threw in
cantaloupes and tomatoes from her garden _ the greatest feast I had
enjoyed in days. The fatal blow to any diet is the cookbook. I have
many, some of them very beguiling, and when you lie in the porch
swing and sip iced tea, unsweetened, or lemonade, ditto, there's
always a cookbook handy to read, the kind with lemon meringue pie
and strawberry shortcake on the cover. I was done in by Frances
Shultz's lamb stew a few weeks ago, but fortunately a houseful of
company made short shrift of that. The other day, I turned down an
invitation from my daughter to eat barbecued pork ribs with the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, thanks,'' I said valiantly. ``I'm having a tuna fish
sandwich. Low-fat mayonnaise.''
</P>
<P>
   They diagnosed my case as pure insanity. How can you be sane and
not have fat, sugar and salt?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a benign grocer marked his watermelons down as a
patriotic Fourth of July gesture, and I now have those two
important American artifacts, a flag flying over the front door and
a watermelon cooling on the back porch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
