</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LMAY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Meal behind the scenes quite a find
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, I've played this scene and played it again: On the
way out of a restaurant after a long lunch _ when employees have
gathered in the dining room to have their own meal _ I glance at
their plates, note their enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that you're having?'' I ask. Never has the answer been
something on the menu; usually, it's a generic dish.
</P>
<P>
   I go away, having enjoyed a fine meal of my own, one that went
on until the place was closing _ but I carry with me an insatiable
appetite for what I didn't have. Call it another quest for
something different, another pursuit of tasty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   So it has gone in cities around the country, in eateries of all
kinds, from Japanese to French to Mexican to Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the other day, I finally did it. Joined staff members for
lunch at Hsu's Gourmet Chinese Restaurant in downtown Atlanta. The
occasion was as delightful as I had imagined all those times I'd
been an onlooker.
</P>
<P>
   The meal began at 2 o'clock, as about a dozen of us sat in
booths across from the bar. In my booth were owners Anna and
Raymond Hsu, and maitre d' George Hull. Chatting before we dined,
the Hsus were explaining that employee meals usually are based on
what the restaurant has a lot of on a given day.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond went on to say that the dishes (Hsu's serves lunch and
dinner) must be interesting _ and different from what the public is
served: ``We don't want to repeat the menus.'' Moreover, they must
be economical, as employees are not charged. All this requires ``a
creative chef,'' he noted. That would be Charlie Shan, Anna's
brother.
</P>
<P>
   He came through with fine style and taste. First, egg drop soup
and a side dish combining pickles, cilantro, peppers. Then, a
robust-looking creation: fried sea bass on the bottom and on top,
bok choy, onions, black mushrooms, deep-fried tofu and barbecued
pork. Not on the menu, it was a wonderful surprise of blended
flavors, mingled juices and textures. So good, we talked about
whether it should be named and put on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   The meals often are expanded when someone brings in a dish from
home. On this day, Ellen Shan, the chef's wife, brought in kimchi
(spiced, pickled Korean cabbage). It was my dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my best efforts, I could not finish off the sea bass at
our table. ``There's always plenty _ more than enough,'' said Hull,
the maitre d'. ``You never go away hungry.'' To be sure.
</P>
<P>
   And to think the whole thing is repeated at around 10 p.m., when
employee dinner is served. (No, I haven't done the late meal. Not
yet.)
</P>
<P>
   Why does a restaurant do this? (Others provide employee meals,
too, some free, some charging discount prices.) Why go to the
trouble of creating extra meals twice a day?
</P>
<P>
   Anna, refreshingly to the point, had the answer: ``We have to
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   And they do it well.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
