<HEADER>
A4193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PEAS-COX     07-07 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PEAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love, peas &AMP; happiness
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An old lady sits outside in a lawn chair. It's midsummer, and
she is wearing a cotton house dress covered with thousands of faded
purple violets. Her hands zip back and forth through a big enamel
dish pan that is balanced on her lap. She is shelling peas.
</P>
<P>
   A baby picks up a sweet, buttery crowder pea, pops it into her
mouth, and her face grows round and happy. She smacks, gives a
little kick, reaches for another.
</P>
<P>
   Down through the ages, Southern field peas have been a comfort
to old and young alike, a ritual of summer as constant as corn,
okra and tomatoes. Though there are innumerable ways to cook a
field pea _ from soups and stews to pilaus and pea cakes _ any
Southerner will tell you that his way is the only way:
</P>
<P>
   Pick a mess with the dew still on them. Shell them carefully.
Wash them gently. And simmer them slowly with a hunk of ham or pat
of butter.
</P>
<P>
   On a parched summer day, with nothing more than a little chopped
onion, a slice of corn bread and a pitcher of sweet-lemony iced
tea, a lunch of field peas can be as refreshing as a dip in the
pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my field peas to taste like field peas and not much
else. If they're good and fresh, who wants to mess 'em up?'' says
Savannah cookbook writer Damon Lee Fowler. Though he fancies them
in hoppin' Johns and ragouts, the only field pea recipe in his new
book _ ``Beans, Green and Sweet Georgia Peaches: The Southern Way
of Cooking Fruits and Vegetables'' (Broadway, $17.50) _ is for a
classic, pork-scented pot o' peas with snaps.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced via Africa and the slave trade, these legendary
legumes come in dozens of varieties, with lovely monikers that
connote their various attributes: black-eyeds and pink-eyeds, cow
peas and lady peas, purple hulls and zippers, butter beans and
butter peas. According to culinary historian Karen Hess, there's
even a whippoorwill pea and a corn-field pea.
</P>
<P>
   Field peas can be light or dark, plain or mottled, vivid as
jewels or murky as dishwater. But our kidney-shaped field pea
should never be confused with the more common English type, often
associated with vegetable ``medleys,'' TV dinners and the phrase
``pea green with envy.''
</P>
<P>
   Snap open a field pea, and you will notice a fragrance as
distinctive as that of freshly cut grass. Yet it is subtler _ clean
and slightly soapy smelling. As you open the pod, the peas will
fall out of their lacunae, sometimes swaddled in a gauzy veil of
white, like a newborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for nothing, you see, that ``sweet pea'' and ``butter
bean'' have become terms of endearment for our most precious loved
ones. Peas are primordial, seeds of life, symbols of regeneration.
And they are meant to be cooked and shared with love.
</P>
<P>
   In Mary Randolph's ``The Virginia House-wife'' of 1824, the
first Southern cookbook, she suggests boiling them, mashing them
into cakes, frying them and topping with bacon bits. Today, you
could plate those pea cakes with a salad of heirloom tomatoes, a
sprig of basil and a splash of vinaigrette, and you'd have an
appetizer that's at once timeless and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   In Birmingham, chef Frank Stitt (Highlands Bar &AMP; Grill, Bottega)
does a succotash of peas, corn and okra, and tosses it with penne
pasta, chunks of fresh tomatoes and lots of olive oil. He also
makes pink-eyed pea and green-tomato risotto with summer herbs, and
pairs it with grilled tuna. You can also use field peas to make the
Italian classic risi e bisi (rice and peas) or puree them with
chicken stock and potatoes to make soup. For a hearty stew of
summer vegetables, you might combine peas or beans with tomatoes,
corn, okra, collards or whatever's fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, pea-shelling seems to be going the way of rocking on the
porch. ``It's getting to be a lost art,'' says Mike Coolick, a
produce buyer at Harry's Farmers Market in Alpharetta, Ga., noting
that most markets are now outfitted with mechanical shellers.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, I was at the market the other day, happily loading
a bag with cream-colored crowder peas, when I saw two ladies
scooping up shelled peas. ``Why don't you buy these?'' they barked.
``They're cheaper. And they are already shelled!'' Never mind that
they were smashed _ and that you couldn't tell what kind they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies,'' I thought, ``you don't know what you are missing.''
</P>
<P>
   In my mind's eye, I see my grandmother. She is wearing her
clunky lace-up support shoes and a dress covered with tiny purple
flowers. ``Oooh, it sure is sultry,'' she says, stopping to fan
herself, or swat a fly. We are sitting under an oak tree, shelling
peas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
