<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECPSWAP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Easy casserole aims to please many palates
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Versatility is a sign of a good recipe. So when Sonya Burnette
sent us an e-mail request for a broccoli casserole using sharp
cheddar cheese, we knew the one Barbara Montague sent us would fit
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple, one-dish casserole that's hearty enough to be a
main course for a meatless meal but also works well as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a recipe book made by the Campbell Soup Co., it's
not surprising that the binder in this dish is a creamy soup. But
you have the choice of creamed soups, depending on your personal
favorite. Cream of celery, chicken or mushroom all work well. And
you can top it with buttered bread crumbs or crumbled Ritz
crackers.
</P>
<P>
   And if broccoli doesn't please your taste buds, try this with
cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable Cheese Bake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1large bunch broccoli or head cauliflower (or two 10-ounce
packages
</P>
<P>
   frozen), cooked and drained
</P>
<P>
   110 1/2-ounce can cream of vegetable, celery, chicken or
mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1/3to 1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup shredded sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup buttered bread crumbs or crumbled Ritz crackers
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place cooked broccoli or
cauliflower in 7-by-11-inch baking pan. In medium bowl, mix soup,
milk and cheese and pour over vegetables. Top with crumbs. Bake 30
minutes until bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 105 calories, 5 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 54), 8 grams carbohydrates, 9 milligrams
cholesterol, 390 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Lois Bowen of Lilburn, Ga. is looking for a ``witch'' cake,
which has dark chocolate layers and a ``special'' type of white
icing. She also is interested in a canasta cake, which Roberta
Gorey requested several weeks ago. Does anyone have recipes for
either?
</P>
<P>
   -- Shirley Chapman of Atlanta is looking for a pecan pie that
has a custard filling instead of syrup. She recalls a similar pie
from years ago at the Dutch Oven Cafe in Abbeville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
Include a daytime telephone number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEAS-RECIPES-COX     07-07 2198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEAS-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peas can be a side dish or a main course
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agrarian South has historically been a place where pigs and
peas are plentiful. We plant the field peas to replenish the soil
with nitrogen, then cook 'em up with a bit of pork fat or ham.
</P>
<P>
   But never say we are set in our ways.
</P>
<P>
   One of the recipes below is actually vegan (the penne with
peas). For that and the risotto, you season the peas by cooking
them in an aromatic broth. You may also build layers of flavor by
sauteing onion and garlic in olive oil, then adding the peas _ and
whatever else you like _ to simmer in water.
</P>
<P>
   As hot as it is outside right now, most of these dishes make a
good main course. Just don't forget the corn bread and the iced
tea.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Purple-Hull Peas With Pork
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a doctored-up version of the classic Southern pot of
peas. If you want the genuine article, omit everything but the
pork, salt, water and peas. For a more refined and healthful broth,
cook the peas in a pork stock (boil a ham hock or other pork pieces
for 1-1 1/2 hours, strain and discard pork, skim fat). Serve with
corn bread and sliced tomatoes and you have a traditional country
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   4cups shelled purple-hull, black-eyed or crowder peas
</P>
<P>
   6ounces pickled pork, salt pork or smoked slab bacon (rind
removed), diced
</P>
<P>
   1large russet potato, peeled, cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   1medium bell pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon picante sauce, preferably Tabasco brand, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons minced parsley, preferably flat-leaf
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   7 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a heavy 4-quart saucepan. Bring to a
boil over medium-high heat; skim foam from surface. Reduce heat so
liquid barely simmers. Cover and cook until peas are tender and
potato has broken down to thicken the cooking liquid (about 45
minutes to an hour for fresh peas). Taste and adjust seasonings.
Serve hot. _ Adapted from Terry Thompson's ``Taste of the South''
(HPBooks).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 401 calories, 24 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 16), 63 grams carbohydrates, 9
milligrams cholesterol, 511 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Nanny's Corn Pones
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/4 hour
</P>
<P>
   This is a singular recipe for corn bread, not just because it
was my grandmother's but because of the technique. By slow baking
at a low temperature, you achieve a crisp crust and a cakey
interior. The buttermilk gives the bread a very slight tartness. I
owe my Aunt Libby Allen and my cousin, Meredith Allen, 23, a big
thank-you for writing it down. It's an heirloom now. Leftovers may
be sliced in two, dotted with butter, put under the broiler and
served with a salad.
</P>
<P>
   2cups fine-grind cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. In a medium bowl, mix cornmeal,
salt, buttermilk and oil with a spoon until well-combined. With
your hands squeeze the dough to get all the lumps out; then shape
into 4 corn pones. Place pones on a very well-greased baking sheet
or cast-iron griddle. Pat top of each lightly with oil. Bake until
lightly browned, turning when bottom is brown and crusty (about 45
minutes); continue cooking for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 319 calories, 8 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 28), 51 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 415 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pink-Eyed Pea
</P>
<P>
   and Green-Tomato Risotto with
</P>
<P>
   Summer Herbs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   At Birmingham's Highlands Bar &AMP; Grill, Chef Frank Stitt serves
this lovely risotto with grilled tuna. I can't imagine anything it
would not taste good with. When fresh peas are out of season, he
uses fresh-frozen ones, and recommends Mackenzie brand.
</P>
<P>
   4cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   1onion, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1celery stalk, broken in half
</P>
<P>
   2cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Several sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2cups fresh peas (pink-eyes, crowders, butter peas or little
baby butter beans), rinsed and picked over
</P>
<P>
   2cups reserved pea broth
</P>
<P>
   2cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1onion (Vidalia, if possible), halved, peeled and finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   1garlic clove, crushed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   2sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   1dried hot chili pepper
</P>
<P>
   2cups arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2green tomatoes, cored and cubed
</P>
<P>
   2green onions, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   Several leaves basil, mint and cilantro, coarsely torn
</P>
<P>
   For the peas: In a medium saucepan, heat cold water, onion,
celery, garlic, bay leaves, thyme and salt. Simmer for 20 minutes.
Add peas, skim and cook until tender, about 25 minutes. Remove from
heat and allow peas to cool in their broth. Discard aromatics.
Strain and reserve broth.
</P>
<P>
   For the risotto: Combine the pea broth and chicken stock and
bring to a simmer (if there is not enough broth, add water to make
4 cups). In a medium saucepan, warm the olive oil and butter, add
onion and soften for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add garlic,
thyme, chili pepper and rice and cook over medium heat for 2
minutes. Add wine and cook, stirring, for 2 minutes. Add 4 ounces
warm broth; stir vigorously until broth is absorbed. Repeat until
rice is tender but still firm, adding extra water if needed. Season
with salt and pepper. Toss peas into risotto and season with salt
and pepper and a little extra-virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Toss the green tomatoes with the green onions, herbs
and 2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil and place on the risotto.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 438 calories, 17 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 16), 75 grams carbohydrates, 4
milligrams cholesterol, 42 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Penne With Peas
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chef Frank Stitt told me he's serving this dish _ or something
like it _ at Bottega, his Mediterranean-inflected restaurant in
Birmingham. So I took his idea and ran with it. The results were
vibrant and delicious _ kinda Southern, kinda Italian. The key is
to toss in the ripest possible tomatoes at the last minute, with
plenty of olive oil. We used butter beans for our
photograph(DIRECTIONAL, IF YOU USE PHOTO), but you can use any
field pea.
</P>
<P>
   2cups field peas or butter beans
</P>
<P>
   1large carrot, cut into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   1onion, cut into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   1stalk celery, cut into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   2sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   4sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   8ounces penne pasta
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons finely minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   36pods baby okra, hard part of stem removed, split in half
lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2ears corn, kernels cut, but not scraped, from cob
</P>
<P>
   2large tomatoes, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons basil leaves, roughly torn with hands
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the peas: Place peas in medium pot along with carrot, onion,
celery, thyme and parsley. Add 1 teaspoon salt. Cover with water
and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to a simmer and cook until peas
are tender. The fresher the pea, the faster it cooks. Check
doneness in 15 to 20 minutes (butter beans may take 30 minutes).
Strain peas, saving 1/2 cup broth. Discard the aromatics. Set peas
aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the penne: In a large stockpot, bring 3 quarts of water to a
boil and stir in the remaining teaspoon salt. Add penne to the
salted boiling water. Stir occasionally to keep pasta from sticking
together. When the water returns to a boil, cook until al dente,
about 10 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   For the vegetables: Place a large saute pan over medium-high
flame and add 1 1/2 tablespoons olive oil and the garlic. Saute 3
minutes. Add okra and corn to the garlic in the saute pan and cook
another 3-5 minutes. Add 1/2 cup pea broth and simmer 3-5 minutes
or until okra is just tender. Add peas and tomatoes to
corn-and-okra mixture, along with the remaining 2 tablespoons olive
oil. Raise the heat to medium and cook until tomatoes are heated
through, about 3-5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: In a large serving bowl, toss the pasta with the
vegetable mixture and the basil. Use more olive oil, if desired.
Season with salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 324 calories, 10 grams protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 26), 52 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 421 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   A Stew of Peas, Collards and Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A few of my favorite things. Use dark peas (such as purple hulls
or black-eyes) _ or a mixture. Serve with white rice and corn
bread.
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons pancetta grease or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2red pepper pods
</P>
<P>
   1ham hock
</P>
<P>
   4 cups field peas, shelled and washed
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   8cups collard greens, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   128-ounce can Italian style tomatoes, drained and roughly
chopped
</P>
<P>
   18medium to large okra pods, hard part of stem removed
</P>
<P>
   In a soup kettle, heat the grease or oil over medium-high flame.
Add garlic and onion and saute until cooked through but not brown,
about 5 minutes. Throw in the pepper pods (use one if you are
heat-shy), ham hock and peas and cover with water. Add 1 teaspoon
salt, give it a stir and bring to a boil. When mixture starts to
boil, turn flame down to medium and allow to simmer gently until
the peas are almost, but not quite, tender (about 45 minutes, if
fresh). Don't cover, and be sure to dip all the scum out of the pot
as it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out the ham hock, add the collards and tomatoes and bring
to a high simmer. Reduce heat and let simmer for 15-20 minutes,
until the tomatoes have cooked down. Check for salt. Then top the
pot with the okra, cover with lid and allow to cook until the pods
are just tender, about 10 minutes. Ladle into bowls and serve at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 205 calories, 10 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 27 grams carbohydrates, 7
milligrams cholesterol, 298 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pilau of Crowder Peas, Country Ham and Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is from Savannah author Damon Lee Fowler _ sort of.
His new book on Southern vegetables, ``Beans, Greens, and Sweet
Georgia Peaches'' (Broadway, $17.50), has a recipe for Peanut
Ragout with Tomatoes and Country Ham, which is an object lesson on
how goobers may be used in place of peas or beans, and vice versa.
But as I adapted it with extremely ripe tomatoes and tender peas
(which have a low cook time), I ended up with vegetable soup. So I
added well-soaked rice and got a perfect pilau. Serve with Frogmore
Stew, or any seafood or meat dish.
</P>
<P>
   1cup long-grain rice (such as basmati)
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons bacon drippings or extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2large cloves garlic, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1medium yellow onion, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2ounces julienned country ham or prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon chopped fresh thyme or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1to 2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1whole pod hot red pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 cups shelled and washed crowder peas or other field peas
</P>
<P>
   2pounds ripe tomatoes, roughly chopped (you may blanch, peel and
seed if you like) or one 28-ounce can Italian plum tomatoes, seeded
and chopped, with juice
</P>
<P>
   2cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Rinse rice in several changes of cool water; place in small
bowl. Cover with hot (not boiling) water, cover and let sit for
15-20 minutes. Drain in colander for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While rice soaks, put bacon drippings or olive oil in a large
nonstick lidded pot or saucepan and place over medium-high heat.
Add garlic and onion and saute until garlic and onion begin to
soften, about 3 minutes. Add ham and saute, tossing frequently,
about 5 minutes. Add thyme, parsley, bay leaves and pepper pod.
Toss, cooking another minute or so. Add peas, tomatoes and broth.
Raise heat to medium-high and bring to a boil, then reduce heat to
medium-low. Cover pot loosely and simmer slowly until peas are just
tender, about 30 minutes, depending on freshness. Check for salt.
</P>
<P>
   Add drained rice; stir well. Raise flame to high and bring to a
boil again. When mixture begins to boil, turn heat to lowest
possible setting, cover and cook for 20 minutes, without stirring.
Remove from heat; let pot sit for about 10 minutes. Fluff with fork
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 225 calories, 9 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 22), 36 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 257 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
