<HEADER>
A4197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEAS-TIPS-COX     07-07 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEAS-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pea pointers: A guide to shelling, cooking, and storing
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Measuring unshelled peas: A good rule of thumb: It takes
about 4 pounds unshelled peas to make 4 cups shelled. Pack one of
those plastic bags at the farmers market with unshelled peas, and
you will have approximately 4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shelling time: An adult should be able to shell 4 cups in
about an hour. But let the kids help. They tend to last for a good
1/2 cup or so.
</P>
<P>
   -- Freshness and cooking time: The fresher (and lighter-colored)
the pea, the less time it takes to soften. For instance, cream peas
(which are lighter in color and texture) might take 20-30 minutes.
Darker peas (such as purple hulls, black-eyes and pink-eyes) might
take 30-45 minutes or more. Butter beans are thicker and firmer and
need more time than peas.
</P>
<P>
   So taste. And let your palate decide.
</P>
<P>
   -- To freeze: For butter beans or limas, wash, shell and sort
according to size. Water-blanch small beans 2 minutes, medium beans
3 minutes and large beans 4 minutes. To water blanch, cover beans
in water, allow to come to a simmer, then begin counting the time.
Cool promptly, drain and package, leaving 1/2 inch head space. Seal
and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   For field peas, wash, shell and discard old or immature seed and
those with bug spots. Wash and water blanch for 2 minutes. Cool,
package and freeze as above.
</P>
<P>
   A palette of purples and greens
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference in a field pea, a butter bean and a green
bean? Field peas come in long, slender pods, 10-12 inches long. The
color of the shell indicates the treasures within. Butter-bean pods
are flat and crescent-shaped, 3-4 inches long, with just a handful
of beans inside.
</P>
<P>
   Green beans, haricots verts, snap beans, pole beans and runner
beans are another genre altogether, because you cook them in their
shells.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some common Southern field peas:
</P>
<P>
   -- Purple hulls have green shells with bright purple marks; the
peas are light green when raw; once cooked, they become a dusty
purple.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pink-eyes have even more vivid shells than purple hulls _
sometimes the entire pod is strikingly hued. The pea itself has a
deep-pink eye, very similar to a black-eye. But they are more
faintly colored, and more subtly flavored, than a black-eye.
</P>
<P>
   -- Black-eyes have verdant hulls with a tiny black mark at the
pointed end. Fresh ones remain green when cooked and taste kind of
like a boiled peanut.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cream peas (also called lady or white acre peas) seem to be
everyone's favorite. When cooked, they're tender, sweet and
buttery.
</P>
<P>
   -- Butter beans are essentially green lima beans. Occasionally,
you shell them to find that the beans are mottled with purple.
</P>
<P>
   -- Butter peas are a cross between a butter bean and a field pea
_ the seeds are squat and fat, the shells diminutive.
</P>
<P>
   -- Zipper peas (or white crowder) look kind of like the fashion
device: The peas seem to bulge from the pod, with thick, pronounced
sutures that are easily unzipped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
