<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LAKECHATUGE-CO     07-07 1925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LAKECHATUGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lake Chatuge and environs overcome midsummer blahs with
recreation, crafts, and a heart tugging play
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hiawassee, Ga.--A small sign next to a Fieldstone Inn footpath
on the shores of Lake Chatuge bears the wisdom of naturalist John
Muir: ``Everyone needs beauty as well as bread, a place to play in
and pray in where nature may heal and give strength to body and
soul alike.''
</P>
<P>
   This is such a place _ and not just the Fieldstone, where
flower-covered lawns bright with red salvia, yellow day lilies,
fuchsia, white impatiens, crimson cannas and lavender hydrangeas
slope down to the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding green valleys, which hold such magic that folks
here call them ``enchanted,'' cradle the sparkling lake created
when the Tennessee Valley Authority flooded farmland in the late
'30s to bring electrical power to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The story is bittersweet. The formation of the Lake Chatuge
Reservoir displaced farms and families who had no choice but to
move to higher ground _ including Wiley and Bessie Cloer, parents
of Fieldstone Inn owner Bob Cloer. It heralded a new day for the
mountain people and the passing of an era. It was, as they say,
progress, but it took a toll on a way of life dear to the people
for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reach of Song,'' the state's official historic drama,
playing through Aug. 23 in nearby Young Harris, celebrates in song,
dance and stories a time when the rest of the world was somewhere
over the next mountain ridge. Among its cast members are those who
grew up in the area and recall how things used to be in the days
when women gossiped at quilting bees, men chewed the fat on the
whittler's bench and girls and their beaus courted at church
suppers.
</P>
<P>
   Only a 2 1/2-hour drive from Atlanta, the area around Lake
Chatuge _ Towns County and Hayesville, N.C., just across the state
line _ is near enough for a quick quickaway. And it's an easy area
to poke around: the loop from Hiawassee to Young Harris to
Hayesville and back isn't more than about 30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   We marveled at the changes since our last visit three summer
ago, especially in downtown Hiawassee, where new lodgings, shops
and restaurants signal growth in tourism, thanks partly to expanded
programming at the Georgia Mountain Fairgrounds. But mostly, we
reveled in the natural beauty of the land that has inspired poets
and pickers, artists and anglers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lake Chatuge: Its lakeside location and fleet of rental boats
makes the Fieldstone Inn on U.S. 76 our lodging of choice in
Hiawassee. Of course, you don't have to go out on a boat to be
renewed by the power of water; just gazing out at the cool,
tranquil lake has a calming effect.
</P>
<P>
   Fieldstone makes it easy to drink in the lake vista, placing
benches and swings under the trees on the shore and erecting a dock
that stretches into the lake. (The sign at the dock says it all:
``It would be wonderful if every child could do some fishing and
every adult could do some sitting.'')
</P>
<P>
   A 20-foot pontoon boat, which carries up to eight, was bigger
than we needed for the three of us, but the 14-foot fishing boats,
canoes and wave runners carry only two passengers max. The big
clunkers ($65 for two hours, $80 four hours, $110 all day) are
great for floating parties and motoring around the
7,500-square-foot lake, up to the Chatuge Dam on the North Carolina
side, past campgrounds, no-frills cabins and multistoried lake
homes or east to the peninsula where the Georgia Mountains
Fairground and Anderson Music Hall nestle in the hardwoods. The
boat's canvas canopy provides welcome shade.
</P>
<P>
   The Fieldstone's large pool is a good place to cool off after a
day on the lake. There are also tennis courts, a health spa and
whirlpool. The restaurant overlooking the lake is open for
breakfast, lunch and dinner seven days, featuring both a buffet and
a la carte selections at each meal. We dined on a Saturday night,
when the prime rib buffet ($18.95) features a spread that includes
baby back ribs, eggplant parmesan, seafood fettuccine and lots of
vegetables and salad fixings. Sunday night, for a change of
scenery, we drove to the nearby Brasstown Valley Resort, where the
fresh mountain trout was the hit of the table.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Reach of Song'': Farmer by the broiling sun of day and
poet by the oil lamp's soft light at night, Byron Herbert Reece was
a son of Appalachia whose poetry captured the rhythm of the
mountains and ``the inspirational song of life'' that filled the
hollows. Reece's life and words provide the framework for ``The
Reach of Song,'' now in its 10th year. The title comes from one of
his poems: ``From chips and shards in idle times, I made these
stories, shaped these rhymes. May they engage some friendly tongue
when I am past the reach of song.''
</P>
<P>
   Performed at Young Harris College, where Reece once taught, the
play is a patchwork of traditional music and dance stitched
together with oral histories from old-timers in the community,
compiled by playwright Tom DeTitta. Reece walks about the stage
like a ghost, unseen by other characters, making keen observations
about the people and land he knows and loves. Occasionally, he
interacts with the others, becoming a part of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reach'' helps visitors understand the attachment long-time
residents as well as newcomers have for this beautiful country.
Slides _ vintage photographs as well as scenics _ projected larger
than life on three screens provide not only a backdrop for the
lively action but a context for the stories.
</P>
<P>
   Songs sung a cappella or with acoustic accompaniment range from
the lilting ``Tennessee Waltz'' to the soaring ``Amazing Grace,''
from the haunting ``What Wondrous Love Is This?'' to the rousing
``Have a Little Talk With Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   While celebrating the simple joys of rural life and the
hardships that brought communities together, ``Reach'' has a darker
side: the changes wrought by the coming of electricity to the
valley and the advent of World War II as well as Reece's descent
into a personal hell that ended with his suicide in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the play's appeal is that many of the actors are just
regular folks with roots firmly planted in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live on the same farm my great-grandparents settled in the
1880s,'' says Hazel Farmer, 77, a six-year cast veteran who plays
the character Maybelle and also shares personal stories, including
her courtship with her late husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in it is just the way it used to be,'' says Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   David Hyatt, 59, of Brasstown, N.C., back in the role of Zack
Haskins after a two-year absence, says the play brings back lots of
memories. ``You don't walk away from it too easy,'' he says. Hyatt
knows about putting down roots: His father, who died at age 105,
lived in the same house for 102 years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Visiting art studios: Armed with a copy of ``The Craft
Heritage Trails of Western North Carolina'' (Handmade in America,
$11.95), we hit the back roads to find two Hayesville artists
featured in the book.
</P>
<P>
   We follow the directions to David Goldhagen's glassblowing
studio to the letter: from the light at U.S. 64 in Hayesville, we
drive a mile toward Franklin, then turn right at the sign for
Hinton Rural Life Center and wind through the valley for two miles
until we spy the blue mailbox on the right.
</P>
<P>
   We're here. He's not. An assistant lets us tour the huge studio
overlooking Lake Chatuge where Goldhagen (who, it turns out, is in
California for a show) creates abstract glass pieces in swirls of
color. His menorahs are especially distinctive, and much in demand.
His studio is usually open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. weekdays, but next time
we'll call ahead to make sure he's there: 828-389-8847.
</P>
<P>
   Robert St. Pierre was at home _ in fact, he was mowing a field
when we pulled up at his studio near Hayesville. St. Pierre is
happy to show us how he creates his wood vessels without benefit of
a lathe. He employs only saws and sanders to turn rough planks into
works of art, and nothing is stained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just how they come out of the tree,'' he says. ``I
haven't found a board yet that wasn't beautiful in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly he uses indigenous woods _ walnut, maple, poplar _ from
dead, storm-damaged or diseased trees. Distinctive markings result
from rotting, minerals or fungus.
</P>
<P>
   Pencil containers start at $16, cremation urns go for $200 and
up and a 4-foot-tall decorative urn of Honduras mahogany is $3,000.
``I'd say there are 50 items in here under $50,'' he is quick to
point out.
</P>
<P>
   When he moved to Hayesville five years ago from Massachusetts,
he doubted anyone would come out to his studio/shop in Compass
Meadows nearly 10 miles outside town. Most days, 15 or more visit.
(Go north on N.C. 69, go through the light at U.S. 64, take a left
on Main Street, then left when the road dead-ends into Tusquittee
Street and watch for the signs; it's on the left. Open 9 a.m.-5
p.m. daily; 828-389-6639.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very inspirational and magical here,'' he says of his
adopted home.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even, as they say, enchanted.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: From Atlanta, take I-85 north to I-985 north
to U.S. 365, then left on Ga. 384. This road will take you to Ga.
75; turn right and drive through Helen and continue on Ga. 17 to
U.S. 76, then left (west) to Hiawassee. Another option is taking
U.S. 129 off I-985 at Gainesville and traveling through Cleveland
to reach Helen and pick up Ga. 17.
</P>
<P>
   -- Staying over: Fieldstone Inn, $89-$150, 1-800-545-3408;
Brasstown Valley Resort, $99-$250, 1-800-201-3205; Henson Cove
Place Bed and Breakfast and Cabins, $70-$75, 1-800-714-5542;
Boundary Waters Resort and Marina, $70-$125, 1-800-323-3562; Laurel
Mountain Cabins, $99-$125, 1-888-859-6018; Salale Lodge, $49-$69,
706-896-3943; Lakeshore Cottages, $55-$75, 706-896-3759; Lake
Chatuge Lodge, $99, 1-800-613-4349; and Holiday Inn Express Hotel
and Suites, $89 and $99 (king executive with jacuzzi),
706-896-8884.
</P>
<P>
   -- Upcoming at the Georgia Mountain Fairground: Georgia Mountain
Fair: Aug. 5-16. Fall Festival: Oct. 9-18. Concert series: July 25:
Boots Randolph, Danny Davis and John Berry. Aug. 22: Mel Tillis and
Steve Wariner. Sept. 5: Pam Tillis and Blackhawk. Sept. 19: Sammy
Kershaw and Aaron Tippin. Oct. 3: Mark Chesnutt and Ronnie Milsaps.
Oct. 24: Trace Adkins and Patty Loveless. 706-896-4191.
</P>
<P>
   -- Food finds: Locals flock to the little yellow Country Cottage
Restaurant between Hiawassee and Hayesville on N.C. 69, standing in
line for huge breakfasts (featuring homemade sausage and cat-head
biscuits), home-cooked vegetables, fresh trout and some of the best
pies and cakes you've ever tasted. 828-389-8621. We spotted the
Best L'il Corner Ice Cream Parlor at 34 Yellow Jacket Drive in
Hayesville on the way to St. Pierre's studio. ``We opened four
weeks ago,'' says owner Sheila Bellassai, ``but we've been
restoring it for six years. It was a general store in the '40s and
'50s and then Johnny's Superette.'' In honor of the former owner,
you can dig into a Johnny's Delight, a brownie and ice cream
concoction that costs $3.75. Check out the antique ice cream scoops
and other collectibles at the soda fountain. 828-389-0164.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 1-800-984-1543 (Towns County Tourism
Association) or 706-896-4966 (Towns County Chamber of Commerce);
Web site: www.townscountrytourism.com.
</P>
