<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WONDER BABIES REQUIRE ADVISERS, OF COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I may borrow a phrase from Rosie O'Donnell, my godson is a
real ``cutey patootey''!
</P>
<P>
   I knew he was going to be a bright, handsome lad because his
mother, Denise, suffered so during her pregnancy. She had
heartburn, hypertension, hemorrhoids, hangnails and really limp
hair that wouldn't hold a curl, but we told her she looked cute
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There is definitely a connection between difficult pregnancies
and astonishingly handsome, genius-like babies. Well, you know, I
was practically on life support during both my pregnancies. I
really was afraid that the government was going to come and take
both my boys off to a research facility the moment they were born.
It was so obvious to me from the second they entered the world that
they were clearly a cut above those illiterate babies lying in the
hospital nursery with them. Luckily, both of my sons refrained from
speaking until the appropriate time developmentally, or who knows
what might have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, my godson, Theron, (I know, we tried to talk them out of
that name, but it's a family tradition) well, he's just a little
milk-chocolate cherub. He's got a headful of curly black hair and
these fat cheeks that have ``kiss me'' written all over them. Even
his little crystal-clear drool is precious _ from afar and when I'm
not wearing silk.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Theron was born, I hosted a baby shower for his
mother. The other women brought very expensive toys wrapped in very
expensive paper: Fisher Price, Tonka, Little Tykes, Tyco, Carter,
Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   I am a very practical person so I bought Little T a very
practical present. I presented his mother with a large pot and a
wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this for?'' she asked incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the baby,'' I replied with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll be cooking anything for the baby for quite
some time,'' she said, ``but I appreciate the thought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear friend, I promise you this will be your child's
favorite toy. He will bypass all of these other colorful,
academically correct toys to get to Auntie Moe's pot and spoon,'' I
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we formed a Circle of Wisdom and took turns dispensing
advice to the mother-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you breast-feed,'' advised a mother of four.
``Breast-feeding makes the kids healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids are healthy and I never breast-fed,'' countered
Denise's sister.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing debate over formula versus mother's milk almost
turned into a brawl. When Denise's sister started taking off her
earrings and pumps, I knew I had to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait! Wait!'' I pleaded. ``I have cheesecake, chocolate
cheesecake. Does anyone want cheesecake? It's fat-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that got their attention. Why argue when you can have
cheesecake instead? So it wasn't really fat-free cheesecake. What
do you want from me? I had a crisis on my hands.
</P>
<P>
   But we survived the shower and Denise survived labor and
delivery. She called me this week. I could barely hear her over the
pounding in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Bam! Bam! Bam!
</P>
<P>
   ``Your godson loves the toy you gave him just a little too much.
He's been banging on that pot for two hours,'' she said. ``You
should include a bottle of aspirin with that little present in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on my way,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you bringing another pot?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, something even better,'' I said. ``Wrapping paper. Kids
love gift wrap and it's quieter.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington wife, mother and
dentist. Write in care of the Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
