<HEADER>
A4215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-MATISSE-760(2T     07-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-MATISSE-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERRE MATISSE'S ARCHIVES ARE A BONANZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During his 60 years as a dealer, Pierre Matisse
exhibited some of the greatest artists of this century in his
gallery in the Fuller Building at 41 East 57th St., including
modern masters like Miro, Balthus, Chagall, Dubuffet, Tanguy,
Mondrian, Giacometti, de Chirico and his own father, Henri Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre, a pack rat who was intensely devoted to promoting his
artists, hardly ever parted with a scrap of paper, and by the time
of his death in 1989, he had amassed files stuffed with
correspondence from all the artists with whom he had worked (many
letters were accompanied by original drawings), letters from his
father, exhibition catalogs, gallery records and letters from
museums and collectors, as well as photographs and prints.
</P>
<P>
   These archives, which document nine decades of 20th-century art
in New York, have been given by the Pierre Matisse Foundation to
the Pierpont Morgan Library. They will be available for study in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary treasure trove,'' said Charles Pierce
Jr., the director of the Morgan, which was founded as a public
institution in 1924. ``In terms of developing our 20th-century
holdings, this is about as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Morgan usually moves in a slow way,'' continued Pierce,
who in his 11 years as director has tried to take an institution
with a reputation for being closed and stuffy and make it more
accessible to the public. ``But with this collection we have
Rollerbladed into the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the second bonanza for the Morgan in less than six months.
In February it received the Carter Burden collection of American
literature, more than 30,000 volumes plus rare manuscripts, letters
and other papers, from the Burden family.
</P>
<P>
   Both an art museum and a study center, the Morgan has a
collection of artists' letters dating from the 15th to the 20th
century, all housed in McKim, Mead &AMP; White's version of an Italian
Renaissance villa at 29 East 36th St. Its strength has been its
holdings of Italian Renaissance artists and many unusual documents,
like a series of 30 letters written by Manet during the 1870-1871
siege of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   With this new gift, the Morgan will not only document the
recognition of some of the greatest artists of this century but
will also give scholars a peek at a very private man who opened
American eyes to their work.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer's passionate belief in his artists was a lonely
undertaking. ``In the beginning my father spent a lot of time in
the gallery alone,'' his son Paul said. ``Year after year during
the 1930s he just sat there believing in the value of these artists
when few other people did. There would be hours and hours before
anyone would come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember once, when he had a Miro show up, all of a sudden
this crowd of people came into the gallery and he said he thought,
`Finally his work has been recognized.' You see, the reaction to
Miro had often been `My kid could do this.' But it was all a big
misunderstanding. The group of people were out for St. Patrick's
Day and had thought they recognized something in Miro's name.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents housed in 209 acid-free boxes are about
2,000 letters from artists like Balthus, Chagall, Dubuffet,
Giacometti, Miro and Tanguy, many of them actually series of
letters. Some are fancifully illustrated; others are accompanied by
watercolors or drawings that were discovered only when the
foundation's archivists were going through the material.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the most talked-about shows, ``Artists in Exile,'' a
1942 exhibition where for the first and last time, Mondrian, Leger,
Ernst, Chagall, Matta, Andre Masson and other European exiles
showed in the same space, a photograph of all the artists was taken
in Matisse's living room. There are also scrapbooks of all the
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   He often asked well-known writers to contribute to his show's
catalogs. Sartre wrote an introduction to a Giacometti exhibition
in 1948, the original of which is in the archives along with
corrections in Giacometti's own hand. Hemingway also contributed to
some of the catalogs. In 1933 he wrote a preface to a Miro
exhibition and the following year an essay for a show of works by
the Spanish artist Luis Quintanilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierre Matisse took special care with all his catalogs,'' said
Robert Parks, the curator of literary and historical manuscripts at
the Morgan. The collection includes the original gouache created by
Miro for the cover of a catalog accompanying a 1947 show of his
work, as well as the catalog and invitation to the opening.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Myriad Details of 300 Shows
</P>
<P>
   Matisse held more than 300 exhibitions at the gallery and kept
checklists of works in each show, catalogs, announcements,
installation photographs, reviews, detailed financial transactions
and correspondence with his artists and his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent clients represented include Ralph Colin, a Manhattan
lawyer who founded the Art Dealers Association of America; Wright
S. Ludington, a collector and founder of the Santa Barbara Museum
of Art in California; Florene Schoenborn, the department-store
heiress whose important collection of modern art was left to the
Metropolitan Museum and the Museum of Modern Art two years ago;
Duncan Phillips of the Phillips Collection in Washington; Joseph R.
Pulitzer Jr., the publisher; Edward G. Robinson, the actor, and
James Thrall Soby, the Connecticut millionaire, collector and
curator whose family fortune came from the manufacture of pay
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Records of purchase prices and other confidential financial
information will not be accessible until 2005 to 2020. Parks said
the library will release these documents sequentially over time at
the foundation's request.
</P>
<P>
   Letters exchanged between Henri and Pierre Matisse have also
been restricted until 2008, at the request of the family.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Pierre Matisse and his father has
always been a subject of speculation. At the 50th anniversary of
the gallery, Pierre Matisse told John Russell of The New York
Times: ``My father didn't want me to be a dealer. If I'd been a bad
writer or a bad musician, he wouldn't have minded. But all artists
are wary of all dealers, and he just didn't want me to get mixed up
with the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Matisse, who is also an artist, said the letters
actually show how close father and son were. ``They are very
personal letters that indicated a very strong family attachment,''
he said. ``His father would berate him for not writing enough. He
had a tremendous interest in Pierre and knowing what he was
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria-Gaetana Matisse, Pierre's widow, said she believed it was
perhaps a good thing that Henri Matisse was in France and his son
in New York. ``It made correspondence necessary,'' she said. ``The
letters will give a very different view about their relationship
than people think. That they were distant is not true. They were,
in fact, amazingly close.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pierre's death nearly a decade ago, his heirs _ his widow,
his daughter, Jacqueline Matisse Monnier, and his two sons, Paul
and Pierre-Noel _ set up the Pierre Matisse Foundation, whose sole
mission was to organize the records for eventual donation to an
appropriate library or museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked in the gallery,'' said Mrs. Matisse. ``So for us
these were just working papers.'' The gallery's inventory _ 2,300
works by artists like Miro, Chagall and Dubuffet _ was sold for
$143 million in 1990 to Sotheby's and the Acquavella Gallery. But
the heirs say they never intended to sell the archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were a private matter,'' she said. ``And anyway what
value would you put on these things? Their only value is the
signatures.'' (Officials at the Morgan say they couldn't begin to
estimate the worth of the archives, because there has been nothing
comparable.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt strongly that they should stay in New York since this
was where the gallery was,'' said Paul Matisse. ``In the end we
felt unanimously that the Morgan was the best home for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the archives in good order took about six years with a
staff of five working full time. ``Pierre Matisse did everything
himself, which was not uncommon for dealers of his time,'' said
Olive Bragazzi, director of the foundation. ``He was absolutely
devoted to his artists and making them known.''
</P>
<P>
   `Happy Coincidence' in Gift's Timing
</P>
<P>
   Today there is hardly an American museum that has not acquired
something from Pierre Matisse. It is through his salesmanship that
the Museum of Modern Art acquired his father's famous ``Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the gift comes at a fortuitous moment in the
Morgan's history. Curators are hard at work on ``New York Collects:
Drawings and Watercolors, 1900-1950,'' an exhibition of about 130
works from private collections that is scheduled to open in May
1999. A selection of artists' letters and other materials from the
Pierre Matisse Gallery archives will be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy coincidence this material arrived in time for the
show,'' said Parks. ``Several artists whose work will be featured
had been exhibited at the Pierre Matisse Gallery, and some of the
correspondence with the dealer will be on view to help tell the
story of their art.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
