<SLUG> BC-DILLARD-OFFER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DILLARD'S AGAIN EXTENDS TENDER OFFER FOR SHARES OF MERCANTILE
STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Dillard's Inc. said Monday that for the second time it
was extending its tender offer for shares of Mercantile Stores Co.
Inc. to allow an antitrust review of the deal to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   The offer of $80 a share was to have lapsed Monday, but the
extension now gives Mercantile shareholders until July 21 to tender
their shares. Analysts said that the extension was routine and that
there was no reason to be concerned that the acquisition was in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The extension gives the Federal Trade Commission more time to
review the purchase for antitrust implications. Dillard's said it
had been providing information to the federal agency and expected
to satisfactorily resolve any antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Stephen M. Long of Prudential Securities said the
Dillard's purchase of Mercantile was not viewed as having an
antitrust problem. Dillard's has short-circuited any potential
problem by agreeing to sell or swap up to 25 percent of the
Mercantile stores.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation increased Monday about which retailers would be
interested in obtaining Mercantile stores that Dillard's decides to
sell or trade. Dillard's on Monday stood by its policy of not
commenting on any Mercantile stores it might sell or swap until the
acquisition is completed.
</P>
<P>
   But Long said Proffitt's Inc. increasingly was seen as
interested in at least some of the stores.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's, which operates the Proffitt's, Younkers and Carson
Pirie Scott chains, said Monday that it planned to buy Saks Fifth
Avenue department stores for $2.82 billion in stock and assumed
debt. Analysts said that, even with the Saks purchase, Proffitt's
had resources to acquire more stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got plenty of money,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   The Saks deal will give Proffitt's stores in new markets. Long
said Proffitt's probably would be interested in adding stores in
those markets to spread distribution and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's attention has been focused on the Saks deal. Now it
can turn to the possibility of picking up some of the Mercantile
stores, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   A Proffitt's spokesman could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Other retailers thought to be interested in some of the
Mercantile stores are Federated Department Stores, which owns
Macy's and Bloomingdale's, and May Department Stores, which owns
Famous Barr and Lord &AMP; Taylor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
