<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-HARVEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD RED WINTER WHEAT HARVEST IN KANSAS IS NEARLY COMPLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) It's all but a wrap for this year's Kansas hard red
winter wheat harvest.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sunday, the harvest was 97 percent complete, compared with
68 percent last week. A year ago at this time, the harvest was 58
percent complete, and the average for this time of year is 59
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is the leading producer of hard red winter wheat, which
is used to make bread and similar products such as hamburger buns.
Hard red winter wheat is planted in the fall and harvested in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas farmers are expected to harvest 393.9 million bushels of
wheat this year, based on June 1 conditions. The estimate is up
from the 377.4 million estimate of May 1. The next official
estimate will be Friday and will be based on conditions as of last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest, which usually isn't completed until the middle of
the month, was helped this year by generally good weather.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Hand, an agricultural statistician with the Kansas
Department of Agriculture, said hot, dry weather in early June
allowed wheat to ripen faster than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a cool, wet spring helped wheat plants recover from
an early spring freeze but slowed ripening and delayed the start of
harvest, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide in the past week, there were 5.1 days suitable for
field work. Major field activities involved harvesting of wheat;
cultivating of corn; and planting of fall crops, such as sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, the leading U.S. producer of sorghum, harvested 273
million bushels last year. Currently, 97 percent of the state's
sorghum crop has emerged. Sorghum is used as a livestock feed.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas corn crop has been rated at 11 percent excellent and
57 percent good. Thirty-one percent of the crop has begun to silk,
ahead of last year's pace of 21 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-COX     07-07 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN controversy still a hot topic of discussion
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite extraordinary efforts at disclosure, a retraction and an
apology, CNN's Operation Tailwind debacle refuses to die.
</P>
<P>
   CNN staffers and outside critics continue to express concerns
about the role of two key players: CNN-US president Richard Kaplan,
who launched the ``NewsStand'' program where the report aired, and
correspondent Peter Arnett, the on-camera reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was scheduled to fly back to Atlanta from his vacation in
Oregon Tuesday for a meeting with CNN chairman Tom Johnson Tuesday
night. Johnson is reviewing Arnett's role in the Tailwind report to
determine whether Arnett's reprimand, issued Thursday, is
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Tuesday morning with about 150 CNN
employees, CNN chairman Tom Johnson expressed full confidence in
Kaplan, and said Kaplan would not be leaving.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   -- Johnson told CNN staffers Tuesday he has named Richard Davis,
currently vice president of Washington public affairs programming,
as executive vice president of editorial standards and practices, a
new office set up to try to prevent a recurrence of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   -- Johnson also told CNN staffers that he had tendered his
resignation over Tailwind twice to CNN founder Ted Turner, but that
Turner had rejected it, confirming widespread rumors within CNN.
</P>
<P>
   -- Producer April Oliver, one of three CNN producers who lost
their jobs because of the Tailwind story, said Tuesday that she
initially asked for an hour for a more in-depth report on Tailwind
that would have included more of the other side, but was told it
would appear as a segment on ``NewsStand.'' The story aired in less
than 20 minutes on ``NewsStand's'' debut episode.
</P>
<P>
   -- Johnson and Kaplan have decided not to attend the Television
Critics Association meeting on Friday in Pasadena, Calif. Johnson
has not yet spoken with outside reporters about the Tailwind story
and its retraction.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, a ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP;Time'' report alleged that in
1970, U.S. military forces dropped sarin nerve gas on U.S.
defectors and civilians in Laos. Almost immediately, participants
and critics charged CNN with journalistic malfeasance, and Johnson
eventually asked an outside attorney to investigate. On Thursday,
CNN retracted the story and apologized to viewers and military
personnel. A ``NewsStand'' follow-up Sunday aired CNN outtakes of
some of the Tailwind interviews, an extremely rare break with TV
news tradition of not showing outtakes.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN staffers still peppered Johnson with tough questions
during three in-house conference calls he held Monday and Tuesday
with hundreds of CNN employees. Johnson fielded questions _ so
pointed they might have been considered insubordinate under other
circumstances _ as to why Kaplan, who has a reputation as a
hands-on manager, had not resigned. Johnson strongly expressed
confidence in Kaplan and said he would not be leaving CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered resigning,'' Kaplan said Saturday on CNN's
``Reliable Sources.'' But he said he had been misled by the show's
producers and senior staff. ``I really didn't have an opportunity
to get to the truth of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's claiming that he's not in the loop, then he should
have been in the loop,'' Oliver, who lives in Washington, said
Tuesday. ``I wasn't in Atlanta when the piece was assembled, but my
editor told me Rick was beaming from ear to ear. No one suggested
the piece was tilted.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Perry M. Smith (Ret.), CNN's military adviser who
resigned in protest over the Tailwind report, said Tuesday that
Kaplan should go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most egregious piece of journalism in the history
of American television,'' Smith said Tuesday. ``CNN has gotten rid
of the lieutenants and majors, but the generals still haven't been
disciplined. Until that happens, CNN hasn't gotten to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't just happen on his watch,'' S. Robert Lichter,
director of the Center for Media and Public Affairs, said of
Kaplan. ``This was his baby. That baby let out quite a howl,''
Lichter added. ``Kaplan is going to have to personally demonstrate
he belongs at the top of a major news organization.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson's comments Tuesday seemed to settle Kaplan's status,
Peter Arnett's position is increasingly unclear. A former Pulitzer
Prize-winner for reporting during the Vietnam War, Arnett was the
only Western correspondent in Iraq for much of the Persian Gulf
War. With Christiane Amanpour, he ranks at the very top of CNN's
corps of correspondents in status and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Now some worry that Arnett's prestige might have shielded him
from more serious consequences in the Tailwind investigation,
allegations that Johnson is looking into.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the lead reporter, no question,'' Oliver said. ``I wrote
the script. But he (Arnett) would not have been a part of this if
he did not believe in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett conducted three of the interviews, including one that
wasn't used initially, with a Tailwind pilot who said he dropped
tear gas, not nerve gas. (The interview was used in Sunday's
follow-up on ``NewsStand.'') Arnett's name and Oliver's shared a
joint byline as co-authors of Time magazine's report on Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett joined one of the CNN phone conferences Monday from his
vacation in Oregon and said he had contributed very little to the
reporting of the Tailwind report.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Kaplan called Arnett's reprimand ``within a hair
of actually being a dismissal.'' Kaplan also defended Arnett on
``Reliable Sources'', saying the reporter relied on Oliver's notes
and research.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Smith said Arentt's byline in Time is damaging no
matter what the truth is. ``If he didn't write the story, his
byline is dishonest,'' Smith said. ``If he did, he has to take
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military in general will not feel that CNN has completed
this action until Peter Arnett has left the scene,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported that Arnett, in his CNN conference
call Monday, said he was ``not going to let my reputation go down
the tubes'' over the report.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was unavailable for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
