<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO AHEAD AND SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) In these columns I am content to speak of small
things, leaving the more important matters to those who pretend to
know about them.
</P>
<P>
   Today's homily concerns (among other things) small
(ital)envelopes.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   I mean those envelopes that are enclosed in notices from
creditors or from the government, in which one is instructed to
return a payment or some completed form.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone go to all the trouble to order and send out
return envelopes that are a fraction too small to accept whatever
it is you're supposed to put in them?
</P>
<P>
   I have turned the possible explanations in mind, and the first
that occurred was that the folks who do it may be passionate
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that the number of return envelopes in each
day's mail must run into the millions for the country as a whole,
even a slight reduction in size _ say a sixteenth of an inch top,
bottom and ends _ would mean the saving of a good many trees.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, it could amount to a whole forest. Maybe even half of
Canada or the Amazon Basin, or wherever it is we plan to get
pulpwood after we've ground up all our own trees to make computer
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is one aspect of a giant research project whose
purpose is to determine the level of frustration a population like
ours can endure before lurching with a howl over the precipice of
lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that those childproof medicine bottles and
plastic-packs of lunch meat, which cannot be opened without tearing
shoulder ligaments and damaging the rotator cuff, are part of the
same scientific inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   I also have been struck by how strange it is, even as some
people are saving paper with their undersized envelopes, the way
others are recklessly wasting it.
</P>
<P>
   My bank, for example. Pass money through the window to the
teller and what you get back is a slip of paper called a deposit
receipt. Conveniently, these receipts may be saved in a pocket of
the checkbook. They are of a size to fit there exactly _ (ital)11
months of the year.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the Christmas season. And as a thoughtful little
gesture to its customers, the bank issues deposit receipts printed
with colorful bells and cheery greetings, and made just enough
larger that they will not fit in the checkbook's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Every year it's the same. The teller takes my money. She gives
me the receipt. I (ital)know(end ital) it's the wrong size, but I
try anyway. And of course it won't go in.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of the season gives way to sudden, unreasonable fury.
</P>
<P>
   (ital)``Why do you do this?''(end ital) I hiss at the teller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beg pardon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've made these too large again!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't really noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, look here! (ital)Do you see?(end ital)'' I show her how,
because of its size, the receipt tears when you try to slip it in
the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``A thing like that can't be accidental,'' I say. ``It has to be
(ital)deliberate!(end ital)''
</P>
<P>
   The teller is noticing the odd way my eyes shine, and how the
cords stand out on my neck.
</P>
<P>
   Her hand moves nervously toward the hidden alarm button under
her counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind,'' I tell her. And stumble out of there before the
armed security guard can be alerted.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsequential vexations, you may say these are. But I would
bet that on a day-to-day and year-to-year basis they affect more
people than politics, the fate of the yen, whale songs or the
expansion of the universe, over which such a huge deal is made in
print.
</P>
<P>
   Other writers are welcome to the big issues.
</P>
<P>
   My little corner of the paper here is concerned with quality of
life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
