<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FEATURE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pak gives South Koreans 'Hope, Encouragement'
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There aren't many occasions when an individual sports
achievement, especially from a golfer, has the potential to affect
a country's economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   When Arnold Palmer hitched up his pants in the '60s, it didn't
cause an explosion in the United States textile industry. Golfers
didn't rush out to buy treadmills when Jack Nicklaus trimmed down
in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Tiger Woods blew onto the professional scene two years
ago, not everyone felt the urge to go out and get a Nike tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri Pak, 20, of South Korea, however, could be another story.
With the Asian economy having taken such a beating to Old Man Par
lately, her win in Sunday's U.S. Women's Open in Kohler, Wis.,
seemingly can do nothing but help.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines in South Korea on Tuesday after Pak's sudden-death
playoff win over amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn _ a Thai-American who
made it an All-Asian final _ proclaimed Pak ``Our Hope, Our
Encouragement.'' Lee Hong-koo, the South Korean ambassador to the
United States, was quoted as saying, ``She's the best news South
Korea has had this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably isn't an exaggeration. In December, South Korea had
to seek a $58 billion bailout from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Pak clearly boosted the country's national pride with the win,
not to mention the financial portfolio of her sponsor, Samsung.
When Pak won her first major, the McDonald's LPGA Championship in
May, the company estimated $150 million in advertising benefits
from the display of the Samsung logo and gave Pak a $290,000 bonus.
The company announced Tuesday that it will launch a new sportswear
brand named ``SERIPAK.'' While Asians and Asian-Americans probably
want to draw parallels between Woods and Pak, they are quite
different. Woods, who was raised in California by an American
father and Thai mother, is quick to smile and equally quick to slam
a club. Pak barely changes expressions, whether bunkered or
birdieing, and speaks in charming, although sometimes confusing,
English. Sometimes she uses feet to describe the length of a putt,
but means either yards or meters. Several times last week at
Blackwolf Run, indicating her calm approach to the most important
tournament in women's golf, she repeated, ``I have no nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing she has in common with Woods is an emphasis on the
major championships, and her record is a Tiger fantasy. Pak, who
took up the game only six years ago, has won both majors for which
she was eligible as a pro. Woods, who had a golf club in his hand
as a toddler, is 1-for-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Open notwithstanding, Pak does not think that she is the
world's best player. ``No, not yet,'' she said. ``I have many years
left. I am just starting. But I have good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
