<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notes
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than just Disney World
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you haven't noticed, but Orlando quietly has become the
center of the golf world. Who calls it home? Who doesn't? Just
look: Arnold Palmer, Tiger Woods, Ernie Els, Lee Janzen, Se Ri Pak
and The Golf Channel. More PGA Tour and LPGA Tour players live
there than in any other city. There's also three-time Masters
champion Nick Faldo and 1998 champ Mark O'Meara; and two-time
Sarazen World Open champion Frank Nobilo. There's Payne Stewart,
Corey Pavin, Scott Hoch and Matt Kuchar, who is from nearby Lake
Mary, Fla. The appeal is both practical and financial. Obviously, a
major factor is warm, year-round weather for keeping a golf game in
shape. And not to be minimized are Orlando's assorted family
attractions. But, yes, money also is an issue. Florida is one of
two states without an income tax; the other is Texas. It's no
accident that Dallas also is a popular address for tour players.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredsson runs out of patience
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Helen Alfredsson fired her caddie, Jason Hamilton,
after the fifth hole of her second round at the U.S. Women's Open
and handed her bag to fiance Leo Cuellar. Asked what happened,
Alfredsson just said, ``Oops!'' The next day, when the winds turned
Blackwolf Run into a horror show, her 2-over 73 tied for low round.
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs were the rule this weekend. The Greater Hartford Open
and the Murphy's Irish Open both went to sudden-death. The U.S.
Women's Open used a Monday 18-hole playoff. ... Jack Nicklaus says
he thinks that the 18-hole playoff is the truest way to determine a
champion but in these days of television commitments, Monday
outings and travel connections it's probably no longer feasible.
... Casey Martin, who missed the cut at the Canon Greater Hartford
Open on Sunday, also is playing in this week's Quad Cities Open.
... It took 11 years for Larry Mize to get some repayment for his
140-foot chip-in to win the 1987 Masters. Maybe Olin Browne will
get a congratulatory telegram from the injured Greg Norman, a
victim that day at Augusta. Browne calls Mize's famous chip ``the
greatest shot I ever saw,'' but he made some history of his own
Sunday by holing out from 40 feet Sunday at Hartford to become the
sixth first-time winner on the PGA Tour this year. ``I've had a lot
of good breaks in my time,'' said Mize, who lost a four-stroke lead
with four holes to play. ... David Duval, another former Georgia
Tech player, regained the PGA Tour money lead Sunday, pushing his
earnings to $1,610,449. ... Australia's Ian Baker-Finch, whose
deteriorated golf game forced an early retirement, returns next
week to Royal Birkdale Golf Club, the site of his 1991 British Open
victory, without his golf clubs. He begins a two-year broadcasting
contract with ABC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
