<SLUG> BC-GROWTH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONFERENCE OFFERS STATES GUIDANCE FOR 'SMART GROWTH'
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Pointing to the success of curbing ``urban sprawl''
in his state, Maryland's governor urged the rest of the states
Tuesday to be smarter about how they grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 50 years, Americans have acted as if moving out meant
moving up,'' Gov. Parris Glendening told the opening session of a
two-day National Governors Association conference. ``We have paid
too little attention to agricultural communities when farms are
fragmented by development, or what happens to forests and the
wildlife that lives in them when they are chopped up by roads or
strip malls.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, ``we never wanted ``no growth'' or even ``slow
growth,'' Glendening said. ``What we were after was the unplanned
or poorly planned growth that was eating up our countryside at an
alarming rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at the conference outlined measures states should take
to channel growth and preserve green space.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's plan, which reserves $16 billion in its annual budget
for ``smart growth'' initiatives, ``stresses guidelines and
incentives for growth instead of regulations,'' Moe said.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives in the Maryland program include financial assistance
to companies that clean up and redevelop properties contaminated by
others, grants to employees who buy homes in targeted ``smart
growth'' neighborhoods, and tax credits to companies who create 25
or more jobs in a ``smart growth'' area.
</P>
<P>
   To restrain sprawl, Maryland does not provide state funding to
help establish new communities in undeveloped areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local governments can still decide where they want development
can occur _ but if they opt for sprawl, they can't assume that the
state will help pay for it,'' Moe said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Moe outlined several overall strategies to combat
sprawl, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Creating comprehensive plans to address growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Creating an inventory of existing state development policies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Develop policies to strengthen downtowns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Encouraging local governments to plan for better land use and
protect their scenic and historic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, sprawl leads to a decline of the countryside's
character and contributes to the loss of a ``sense of community,''
Moe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue to allow our communities to deteriorate and our
countryside to be paved over, we stand to lose a major part of
America's memory of itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
