<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-QUARTERS-TEX     07-07 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-QUARTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LINES ALREADY FORMING OVER QUARTER DESIGN FOR LONE STAR
STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Remember the Alamo! Or, maybe we should remember
the Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders. The Texas longhorn? The armadillo?
</P>
<P>
   The final decision is at least five years away, but battle lines
are already forming over which Texas icon should represent the
state on special-edition quarters due for release in 2004. Under a
program approved by Congress last year, each state will have a
quarter designed in its honor beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Five states will qualify for redesigned coins each year,
according to when they were admitted to the Union. Designs for the
first five states _ Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Connecticut
and Georgia _ will be heading to the engraver late this year.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington's portrait will remain on the front of the
coin, but the eagle on the back will be replaced by various state
symbols. The choice of a symbol is left to each state, and early
experience indicates that it is not an easy decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are already offended because we went with some designs
instead of others,'' said Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman for New
Jersey Gov. Christine Whitman. In the end, New Jersey opted for the
famous image of Washington crossing the Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge was deluged with more than 5,300
suggestions before settling on a please-`em-all compromise that
includes ``Lady Commonwealth,'' an outline of the state, the
``Keystone State'' symbol and the state slogan, ``Virtue, Liberty,
Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge jettisoned proposals to decorate the coins with images of
the Three Mile Island nuclear plant, the Hershey's kiss, celluloid
boxer Rocky Balboa, the groundhog known as Punxsutawney Phil and
the Great Dane, the state dog.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut opted for the Charter Oak, a Colonial-era tree that
fell more than 142 years ago. In 1687, early settlers hid the
state's charter in the tree to avoid its revocation by British
authorities. Among the rejected proposals were the hamburger and
the pizza, both of which were supposedly introduced to Americans by
New Haven restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Horgan, a columnist for the Hartford Courant newspaper,
chided state officials for shying away from more contemporary
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't want to decorate the coin with a golf ball or a
poker chip _ the state's principal diversions _ why not a
pothole?'' Horgan wrote. ``Like Montana has buffaloes, we have axle
busters that swallow up compact cars and jar loose teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which will submit its choice to the U.S. Mint in 2003,
also faces a long list of options. Nearly everyone, it seems, has
an opinion on the perfect state image.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas longhorn is the symbol of Texas. I don't know what
else you could put on it,'' said Don King, executive director of
the Texas Longhorn Breeders Association, based in Fort Worth.
``They were here before people were. It's the only symbol for
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the longhorn is also the mascot for the University of
Texas, so that image might not sit well with fans of archrival
Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't suppose they would consider the traditional thumbs-up
sign for Texas A&AMP;M,'' Aggie spokesman Jim Ashlock said. ``If we
have a longhorn on the coin, perhaps the horn should be sawed off.
You see a lot of those around A&AMP;M. We wouldn't object to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Dohmann of Alvin thinks he has an idea that the entire
state could rally behind: the state tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has more native pecan trees than any other state in the
country'' _ about 30 million, to be precise, Dohmann said. ``I
think it would be ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dohmann, who operates a commercial pecan orchard in Columbus, is
admittedly something of a pecan nut, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat Pecans!'' his company's Web site urges. ``10,000,000
squirrels can't be wrong.'' Still, even Dohmann concedes that the
ubiquitous tree faces tough competition from another Texas plant,
the bluebonnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love bluebonnets,'' he said. ``I've got a huge patch of them
myself, but for advertising, it's kind of wimpy.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like flora and fauna, how about a slice of Texas
history? The Alamo is sure to have plenty of defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pecans? Everybody is going to think Texas is full of a bunch
of nuts,'' said Jennifer Schulle of the Daughters of the Republic
of Texas, which oversees the San Antonio shrine. ``We don't need
that. The Alamo is definitely better.''
</P>
<P>
   In what may be a preview of the coming debate, junior high
school students in Karnes City are conducting an Internet poll on
Texas symbols for a class project. In addition to the usual
suspects, the students' list includes the Dallas Cowboys
cheerleaders, the cactus, the armadillo, the yellow rose, the
Indian paintbrush, the whitetail deer, the windmill, the oil
derrick, the mockingbird, the rattlesnake and the Texas Rangers
(the law enforcement agency, not the baseball team).
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a hard time narrowing it down,'' teacher Jan Johnson
said. Johnson said she tried to talk the seventh- and eighth-grade
students out of listing cheerleaders as a Texas symbol, without
success.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the balloting, she needn't have bothered. Out of
132 votes cast so far, the cheerleaders have captured five votes.
The winner to date: the horned toad, with 19 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a cheerleader isn't such a bad idea after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
