u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISA-SPEEDUP-BOS &LR;      07-07 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SPEEDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISA SPEEDUP STALLED IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A plan to boost the number of skilled foreign
workers admitted to the United States has become stalled in
Congress, and a series of negotiating sessions between lawmakers
has so far had little success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is at an impasse, but we are still talking,'' said
one business lobbyist, who asked not to be named. Another said odds
of a bill passing this year are ``about 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become contentious, with employers, particularly
high-tech firms like those around Boston, saying that the strong
economy has left a shortage of computer programmers and other
skilled workers. Employee groups and unions say that companies
merely want to replace Americans with low-cost foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
   Employers won a victory in May when the Senate voted to increase
the annual allotment of so-called H-1B visas, which allow a
foreigner to work at a skilled US job for up to six years. But now,
business groups are balking at the House version of the
legislation, already approved by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   That bill would boost the number of visas, but it would also
require employers to certify that they tried to recruit American
workers before hiring foreigners. Employers would also have to
certify to the Department of Labor that they did not lay off US
workers in the six months prior to hiring a foreigner on a H-1B
visa, or for three months afterward.
</P>
<P>
   House members say those requirements will prevent companies from
dislodging US workers to make way for foreigners. But business
groups say a company using H-1B labor might find itself in
violation of the law merely for closing down a product line,
subcontracting work to a partner or reorganizing in some other way,
which could leave it vulnerable to charges that it laid off US
workers while retaining foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This basically says the Department of Labor will determine who
you can hire, why you can hire them and when you can hire them, and
that the department will be looking over your shoulder every time
there is a business operations change,'' said Susan Marshall of the
Information Technology Association of America, a Washington trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   US companies reached the current quota of 65,000 visas in May,
five months before the end of the federal fiscal year. The Senate
and House bills would allow about 115,000 visas annually.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate and business groups opposed to the House bill, a
small group of lawmakers has held at least two lengthy meetings to
resolve the differences. The group included Republican Senators
Spencer Abraham of Michigan and Phil Gramm of Texas, and House
Republicans Lamar Smith of Texas, Henry Hyde of Illinois and Dick
Armey, the House Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is chairman of the House subcommittee that wrote the new
requirements for businesses using H-1B visas, and Hyde is chairman
of the House Judicary Committee, which approved them. Abraham
sponsored the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conflict is really within the Republican Party, between
the House and Senate,'' said Austin Fragomen, an immigration lawyer
who leads the American Council on International Personnel, which
represents about 350 multinational corporations. ``Smith has on his
side not only Republicans, but all the Democrats and the
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   When the talks between lawmakers made little progress, Smith
held several meetings with business groups to try to negotiate a
resolution, congressional sources said. More meetings are expected
once the House returns from recess next week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has made some concessions during the talks, agreeing that
not all companies should have to certify that they tried to recruit
Americans before hiring H-1B labor. That rule would apply only to
companies that count H-1B workers as 15 percent or more of their
work force.
</P>
<P>
   But all companies would have to certify that they did not lay
off Americans before hiring H-1B workers, a requirement that
business groups so far oppose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
