A4248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIDERHOUSE-THEATER-RE     07-07 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDERHOUSE-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CIDERHOUSE': ANOTHER MAJOR MARATHON AT THE TAPER (WITH DINNER
BREAK) 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When John Irving began work on ``The Cider House
Rules,'' his sprawling 1985 novel about eight decades in the life
of a rural Maine orphanage, he had no intention, he says, of
writing a wrenching polemic on abortion _ or, it seems safe to say,
a work that would be the basis for a two-part, six-hour play with
22 actors portraying 120 characters in 150 scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But 13 years after the book's publication and six years after a
trio of theater professionals conceived the notion of dramatizing
it, ``The Cider House Rules'' has become all that and more in a
production of the same name that opened here Tuesday at the Mark
Taper Forum and runs through Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The play blends the dramatic naturalism of Thornton Wilder with
the read-aloud fidelity of a Victorian literary circle, the
characters speaking not only their lines but their thoughts and the
author's wry commentary on them in a rapid-fire mix of declamation
and attribution. The effect is an unusual amalgam of conventional
drama and a staged reading.
</P>
<P>
   As adapted by playwright Peter Parnell and staged by a pair of
actor-directors, Tom Hulce and Jane Jones, the saga of ``Cider
House'' takes on more resonance than ever in a nation riven by
violence over abortion. The play tells the story of Dr. Wilbur
Larch, the kindly obstetrician of St. Cloud's Orphanage, who,
``when he was asked, and when it was safe,'' was an abortionist,
too.
</P>
<P>
   When Homer Wells, the young orphan who becomes Dr. Larch's
protege, eventually rebels at performing the procedure himself, he
opens a moral argument that mirrors every agonizing angle of the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom first approached me with this idea, I'd always been
very sym0athetic to his talent,'' Irving recalled by telephone the
other day from his home in Vermont, referring to the co-director
whose acting career has embraced everything from the frat-house
high jinks of ``Animal House'' to the genius of Mozart in
``Amadeus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I must say, I thought he was nuts. It seemed to me to be a
singularly difficult thing to do at the length he was describing,
and yet I had so much confidence in his instincts in a world that
I'm very inexperienced in, that I said, `Sure, go ahead and show me
what you can get.'''
</P>
<P>
   What Hulce, Ms. Jones and Parnell have got _ together with a
company of mostly West Coast actors, about half of whom have
performed in earlier incarnations of the play over the last two
years _ is a vast social panorama that involves audience and
performers in a communal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Royal Shakespeare Company's marathon ``Nicholas
Nickleby'' and Tony Kushner's two-part ``Angels in Amerca,''
``Cider House'' harks back to earlier eras of epic dramatic
storytelling, when ancient Greek or Elizabethan audiences made the
theater a daylong festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the multiple-marathon producers,'' said Gordon Davidson,
artistic director of the Taper, which originally produced both
``Angels'' and the two-part historical drama ``The Kentucky
Cycle.'' Over the last 30 years, Davidson has directed such
socially conscious plays as ``The Trial of the Catonsville Nine''
(with its debate over the Vietnam War) and ``Children of a Lesser
God'' (with its portrait of a deaf student and her teacher).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of it, certainly,'' Davidson said of the play's
extreme length, ``and I welcome it as part of the challenge of both
producing and of broadening people's horizons and challenging their
notions of what drama is and how to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences here can experience ``Cider House'' in two ways: in
two weeknight performances, or in a weekend marathon of a matinee
and evening performance, with a dinner break between.
</P>
<P>
   With its large cast, and complicated rehearsal and performance
schedules, the play is a major undertaking for the Taper. The
theater has a producing arrangement with the Jujamcyn organization
in New York, which helped finance a workshop of the play here this
spring and, Davidson said, there is interest in taking it to
Broadway when its run ends here.
</P>
<P>
   Irving acknowledged that the whole notion of the play was at
first off-putting to him, in part because he found the constant
shifts between dialogue and narration jarring in the script. But
when he showed it to his son, Colin, an actor who is now an
understudy for several roles in the Taper production, he was
reassured that the words would play much differently on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Cider House'' was first produced at the Seattle Repertory
Theater in 1996, Irving avoided seeing it because he was struggling
to condense the novel into a two-hour screenplay (which is to be
directed by Lasse Hallstrom for Miramax this fall) and did not want
to be confused.
</P>
<P>
   When Irving finally saw Part 2 in Seattle last year, he
recalled: ``I was just bowled over by it, I just loved it. The only
thing that made me feel bad about any of it was how sorry I felt
for myself and my screenplay. I was envious of all the things they
were able to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   This is music to the ears of Parnell, Hulce and Ms. Jones, who
first met at Playwrights Horizons in New York in 1982 when Hulce
and Ms. Jones were acting in Parnell's play ``The Rise and Rise of
Daniel Rocket.'' They kept in touch over the years, and when Hulce
was approached nearly a decade ago about playing Homer Wells in a
proposed film of ``Cider House'' that never got off the ground, he
was immediately drawn to ``the great scope of the story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he realized that the moments in it that most excited him
``were all theatrical, they were not cinematic, they were moments
that required the audience's use of imagination, moments that would
be more potent if they weren't literal.''
</P>
<P>
   So he approached Ms. Jones, who by this time had founded a
Seattle repertory company called Book-It that had produced verbatim
dramatizations of about 150 short stories, and who was looking for
a big, fat novel to expand her horizons.
</P>
<P>
   Parnell joined the team and, with Irving's halting consent, they
began a series of workshop productions aimed at preserving the
self-consciously Dickensian sweep of ``Cider House,'' in which Dr.
Larch reads ``David Copperfield'' and ``Jane Eyre'' aloud to the
orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the workshops and readings from the Juilliard School to
the Breadloaf Writers Conference in Vermont to the Lincoln Center
Theater, they finally reached Seattle, where Davidson saw the play
and commissioned yet another workshop in Los Angeles this spring
before the current run.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of actors would come in to audition for this and say to
us, `How the hell are you going to do this?''' Ms. Jones said
recently between rehearsals, during an interview with the three
collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about activating the narrative to then use it. It's
so hard for the actors to do, but once they get it, it's no more
difficult than Shakespeare, really, in a way, because it's
language-driven. And you have to play a very strong objective
through the language, through the narration, so that it not only
transports you in time and place, but transforms you through
psychic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to creep into the mind of a character and
therefore retain and preserve the author's full intention of what's
going on, not only physically, but mentally with the character, as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The form seems to be powerful. Hulce said that when the play was
first in development in Seattle, there were several instances when
members of the audience fainted at graphic descriptions of
obstetrical and surgical procedures. ``And we weren't doing
anything except speaking the language,'' Hulce said.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, ``Cider House,'' staged on a spare, stylized set of
louvered panels and catwalks designed by John Arnone, is full of
stern stuff, from haunting descriptions of the effects of botched
abortions to Homer's horror as he contemplates what he takes to be
an aborted fetus' smile. And, as befits a work by the author of
``The World According to Garp,'' the play is also a universe in
which every act of carnal indulgence carries momentous and painful
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the story is the avuncular Dr. Larch (played by
Michael Winters, a Seattle-based veteran), whose youthful
experience with the tragedies of back-alley abortions convinces him
he should, in the words of the play, deliver not only babies but
mothers; and Homer Wells (played by Josh Hamilton, a young New York
actor), the orphan who becomes the doctor's beloved surrogate son
and sorcerer's apprentice. The moral and intellectual disagreement
between the emotionally scarred and celibate doctor and his
wistful, wide-eyed charge becomes the pivot for a three-generation
tale that also examines topics from 20th-century class tensions to
the socio-sexual implications of drive-in movies.
</P>
<P>
   For Parnell, who is used to telling his own stories as a
playwright (he is also the author of ``The Sorrows of Stephen'' and
``Flaubert's Latest,'' among others), the narrative form sometimes
posed particular challenges, as in the big set-piece abortion
debate between Homer and Larch near the end of Part 1. Would
injecting the author's narrative into what would otherwise stand as
a classic dueling dialogue ``let the audience down a little bit,''
or would it ``force the audience into the character's mind because
we're able to say what the inner voice of that character is
saying,'' he debated.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Jones said, keeping most of the narration seemed
the way to stay closest to the world of John Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Parnell likened the intense collaborative process to the demands
of fine-tuning a musical comedy in out-of-town tryouts. ``We'll get
to a point and decide, no, this has to be done more quickly, or it
can be done partly in narrative and partly in dialogue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the creative team are quick to say that Part 2
posed the biggest dramaturgical problems. At that point in the
story, Homer leaves the orphanage to work on an apple farm, whose
workaday rules (often broken) give the play its title, and a raft
of new characters are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we let Larch and Homer get too far away from each other,
then we don't have that heartbeat of the story anymore,'' Ms. Jones
said. ``And Homer becomes a wait-and-see type person in much of
Part 2, which is really hard to activate in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the novel, the play avoids easy answers to the moral issue
at its core, but still makes clear its sympathies are in favor of a
woman's privacy, and her right to choose whether she can perform
what Irving calls the ``act of service'' that is childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to grapple with that central thesis is a big part of
what has propelled Hulce to put his acting career on hold for the
last two years, and moved Ms. Jones and Parnell to devote so much
of their lives to what Parnell says has become a kind of home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being what I considered the `womb' here, the women's issues
have been highly motivating and challenging,'' Ms. Jones said.
``And how beautifully both characters can argue for the right to
choice continues to be moving to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with abortion under renewed attack around the nation,
and with nearly 60 percent of all physicians who perform abortions
now over 65 years of age and many younger doctors declining to
perform them, or even to learn how, Irving says he finds his story
``more topical now than when the book was published.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider House'' remains his second-best-selling book worldwide,
after ``A Prayer for Owen Meany'' and far ahead of ``Garp,''
popular perceptions to the contrary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of places, when it was published, people said, `Oh, it's
kind of quaint, that issue's behind us,''' Irving said. ``The
crisis of abortion rights laid pretty low, and people were,
wrongly, I think, taking for granted a right that had barely been
in existence for 10 years. And especially younger people, who had
no experience in their sexually conscious lives of a time when it
wasn't available, were comfortable taking for granted that if they
needed it, it would be there. That right has to be protected again
and again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
