<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRD-THEATER-REVIEW-N     07-07 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEET BIRD OF YOUTH': TARNISHED GODDESS, ALLOY OF IRON AND PAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I like you,'' says the boy to the bizarre,
larger-than-life creature in his bed. ``You're a nice monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the boy, as it happens, is a burned-out case, 29 going on
dead; the object of his endearments isn't exactly Puff the Magic
Dragon, either, but a boozed-up, washed-up, sex-addicted movie star
named Alexandra del Lago.
</P>
<P>
   The young man has a point, though. Miss del Lago is an awfully
nice _ and, yes, even lovable _ monster, at least as portrayed by
Elizabeth Ashley in the Shakespeare Theater's revival of Tennessee
Williams' ``Sweet Bird of Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest interpretation of Williams' overheated tale of a
Hollywood diva and her gigolo, which seemed the dernier cri in
lurid adult drama when it opened on Broadway in 1959, has been a
popular hit in Washington, and it's easy to understand why. Ms.
Ashley is giving the kind of barnstorming, crowd-courting star
performance that you rarely see on a stage these days. She seems
high not on the little pink pills that are Alexandra's favorites
but on the thrill of having a live audience to play with.
</P>
<P>
   She's an intense presence, for sure, but also a comfortingly
benign one, and the warmth she gives off is as much maternal as
erotic. While her Alexandra may have spent much of her recent life
in a haze of intoxication and hangovers, there is nothing numb
about her. Indeed, by the end of the production, which has been
unevenly directed by Michael Kahn, this decadent, derelict screen
goddess emerges as a role model: a vital, tenacious and
compassionate survivor whose version of rolling with the punches is
just a little more literal than most people's.
</P>
<P>
   If your main acquaintance with Alexandra (a k a the Princess
Kosmonopolis) is through Geraldine Page's electric, hyperneurotic
performance in the original stage production and movie version,
this portrait won't jibe with your memories of the character. Ms.
Ashley appears to have conceived the Princess as a later
incarnation of the life-affirming Maggie in Williams' ``Cat on a
Hot Tin Roof,'' in which Ms. Ashley memorably starred in Kahn's
Broadway revival in 1975 _ that is, if Maggie had dropped her limp
Brick and moved to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that strips the play of much of its darkness
and troubled ambivalence. All the same, Ms. Ashley is great fun to
watch, while crucially reminding you that Williams' female
characters weren't all wilting neurasthenics a la Blanche DuBois
and Alma Winemiller. The real trouble is that this Princess blows
everyone else, including the gifted Michael Hayden as Chance Wayne,
Alexandra's pet stud, off the stage. Given that the Princess is
absent for a good third of the play, this is even more of a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, it has always been a problem. In an earlier
version, presented in Miami in 1956, ``Bird'' was effectively a
two-character play, composed of what are now its first and third
acts. In transforming the work for Broadway with the director Elia
Kazan, Williams shakily expanded the story surrounding Chance's
return to his hometown in Florida, where he is awaited by the girl
he done wrong but still loves, her vengeful politician of a father
and the sort of grisly fate that tends to befall Williams' young
men.
</P>
<P>
   The embellishments have a Williams-by-the-numbers quality, and
you can't help comparing them with more completely drawn versions
of the same thing. Heavenly Finley (here played by Elizabeth
Sastre), who has undergone sterilizing surgery after contracting
syphilis from Chance, is a stick-figure version of the imperiled
Catharine in ``Suddenly Last Summer,'' and Boss Finley (David
Sabin), her fire-breathing father, is a grossly politicized cartoon
of Big Daddy in ``Cat.'' And the threat of castration by committee,
a Williams specialty, that hangs over Chance is given more urgency
and vividness in ``Orpheus Descending.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kahn nor his actors succeed in animating these wooden,
morality-play statues. Sabin does provide an intelligent, measured
blueprint of a performance, an exaggerated counterpoint of bluster
and calm, but it never assumes human flesh. As his understandably
sullen children, Ms. Sastre and Willis Sparks are merely
mechanical, when an enlivening touch of camp would, for once, be
welcome. Samuel Maupin, as a terminally corrupted doctor, and Robin
Moseley, as Finley's forthright mistress, mercifully give more
credible dimensions to their slender parts.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, in the role originated by Paul Newman, is at least by no
means wooden. This appealing young actor, who shone in the New York
revivals of ``Carousel'' and ``All My Sons,'' would seem to be a
fine choice for Chance, the best-looking boy from St. Cloud, Fla.,
who went on to fail as an actor and succeed as a hustler. But here
he is all exposed nerves and magnolia accent, pronouncing
``terror'' as ``Tara,'' a male cousin to Blanche DuBois.
</P>
<P>
   You can sense the character's pain but not his craftiness or the
remains of his swaggering confidence; it's hard to imagine him ever
having been the idolized golden boy that Chance once was. As a
consequence, what should be a pas de deux of mutual dependence and
power-struggling between Chance and the Princess as they fester in
an expensive hotel suite, is largely a solo act.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ms. Ashley's Alexandra pleads with Chance to indulge
her, physically and emotionally, he registers as a fragile,
whirling toy that she could step on and crush whenever she chose.
She's Stanley, if you will, to his Blanche. ``When monster meets
monster, one monster has to give way,'' the Princess bellows, and
though the conclusion is foregone, the couple's scenes demand more
adversarial tension than Hayden can give them.
</P>
<P>
   This imbalance doesn't stop the cyclone of Ms. Ashley's
performance, which is nicely set off by the calm, abstract elegance
of Michael Yeargan's set and Howell Binkley's lighting. Her
throaty, cigarette-scarred voice, which seems to issue from a
watery grave, is the voice of the hangover eternal. And taking
disgusted inventory of her fleshy torso encased in a black satin
slip or checking out the merchandise beneath Hayden's pajamas,
she's a bawdy delight.
</P>
<P>
   Her Princess never seems potentially tragic or even pathetic,
however, which isn't necessarily a good thing in a character
defined by lost beauty and an awareness of what Williams called
``the enemy, time.'' Ms. Ashley delivers her monologues on these
subjects with a blowsy, attention-fixing charm. But you keep
looking for the depths of fear to explain Alexandra's desperate
behavior; what you're given instead is a plucky, game-for-anything
attitude and a ``c'est la vie'' shrug.
</P>
<P>
   The Princess, by the way, was partly inspired by the excessive,
hedonistic Tallulah Bankhead. But Williams, who had been living
with the discontents of fame for more than a decade when the play
was written, also admitted: ``I was Alexandra del Lago from start
to finish. I've probably made every speech she made. And I meant
them twice as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Seen in this context, Ms. Ashley's performance takes on a
poignant glow of generosity and affection. The actress became close
to Williams during the revival of ``Cat,'' and she knows very well
that, for all his much-publicized breakdowns and addictions, the
dramatist was a tough old bird who kept on writing until he died.
It's the self-amused, self-dramatizing and finally self-aware
survivor that Ms. Ashley pulls to the surface here. Even if the
performance doesn't always serve the play, it's refreshing to see a
Williams heroine enjoy herself with such gusto.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   SWEET BIRD OF YOUTH
</P>
<P>
   By Tennessee Williams; directed by Michael Kahn; set by Michael
Yeargan; costumes by Martin Pakledinaz; lighting by Howell Binkley;
composer, Adam Wernick; vocal consultant, Sarah Felder; resident
assistant director, Eleanor Holdridge; stage manager, Martin
Lechner; director of production, Dennis A. Blackledge. Presented by
the Shakespeare Theater, 450 Seventh Avenue N.W., between D and E
Streets, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With: Michael Hayden (Chance Wayne), Elizabeth Ashley (the
Princess Kosmonopolis), David Sabin (Boss Finley), Willis Sparks
(Tom Junior), Elizabeth Sastre (Heavenly Finley), Samuel Maupin
(George Scudder), Nancy Robinette (Aunt Nonnie), Robin Moseley
(Miss Lucy), Joseph McKenna (the Heckler), Jason Nuzzo (Stuff),
Paul Takacs (Scotty), David M. Fendig (Bud), Laurena Mullins
(Violet) and Jennifer Gerdts (Edna). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
