<HEADER>
A4274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-BOND-NYT &LR;      07-07 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-BOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY BOND PRICES FALL WITH THE DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities fell for the first time
in three days Tuesday as the dollar slumped in world currency
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond declined 15/32, to 107
16/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, rose to 5.60 percent, from 5.57 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed out that bonds have moved in tandem with the
dollar recently. And Tuesday the dollar slumped after statements
from Japan increased expectations of an income tax cut to help pull
that nation out of its recession.
</P>
<P>
   Several media reported that a Japanese official said Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had said that government tax changes
would include an income tax cut. Some analysts noted that the
comments appeared to run counter to remarks the prime minister made
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are watching to see to what extent the Japanese commit
themselves to tax cuts, because a permanent cut could dry up the
flight to U.S. Treasury securities, limiting further rallies in the
American market. Still many remain convinced that the weakened
Asian economies will place a drag on the U.S. economy and continue
to help subdue inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Burtnick, an analyst with Technical Data in Boston, said
trading was light and was mostly currency driven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond market,'' he said, ``is trading very close to the
high end of its most recent trading range, an indication that
people now need to see more weakness in the economy before rates
can go significantly lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have also seen some selling in Treasury securities, as
dealers set up for a growing supply of corporate debt expected to
hit the market this week, something in the neighborhood of about $6
billion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the municipal bond market Tuesday, $1.02 billion of Detroit
Metropolitan Wayne County Airport revenue bonds were priced through
underwriters led by Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The securities are in two parts with the bulk, $859.6 million
series A, priced to yield a maximum 5.35 percent for a bond due in
2028. For a bond due in 2022, the yield was 5.33 percent. For
shorter maturities, yields ranged from 4.30 percent for an issue
due in 2002 to 5.31 percent for an issue due in 2019.
</P>
<P>
   In the $163.6 million series B, the maximum yield was 5.22
percent for a bond due in 2028 and 5.19 percent for a bond due in
2023, with shorter maturities initially priced to yield from 4.25
percent in 2003 to 5.17 percent in 2018.
</P>
<P>
   Both series carry insurance from the Municipal Bond Investors
Assurance Corp. covering interest and principal payment, which
gives the bonds a triple-A rating from Moody's Investors Service
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
