<P>
   &QL; 
SQUAWPEAK (Phoenix) - An Arizona state board is poised to rename
Phoenix's Squaw Peak, but Arizona's Indian tribes are wondering
what all the fuss is about. The Arizona Board of Geographic and
Historical names was scheduled to address a proposal Tuesday that
would change the name of the peak to Iron Mountain. Representatives
of the tribes claim the issue is an import from the mid-West, where
the word ``squaw`` carries a more derogatory meaning than it does
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   By RUBEN NAVARRETTE Jr. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEATH PLEA (Phoenix) - The Maricopa County courthouse has been
buzzing since public defender Jamie McAlister begged a judge to
sentence her client to death - in a case for which the state hadn't
even asked for death. We interview the convicted murderer, Douglas
Smith, about his reasons for wanting to be killed. Smith, who beat
a man to death, has brain seizures and worries he'll end up in
solitary confinement for the rest of his life because of them. He
believes his death will bring solace to his victim's family
members. Meanwhile, many in the legal community are highly critical
of McAlister's act. A deaf and disabled attorney, McAlister said
she can relate to her client's disability and will continue to
fight for him. By VICKY HARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
