<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LIABILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS PROPOSE EXCLUDING GUN MAKERS FROM LEGAL LIABILITY LID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Democratic senators announced Tuesday they want
to keep gun manufacturers from benefiting from a lid on lawsuit
damages that the Senate is considering for other small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Dianne Feinstein of California and Robert Torricelli of
New Jersey said they would seek to amend pending product-liability
legislation so that makers and sellers of guns wouldn't benefit
from a $250,000 cap on punitive damages that businesses with fewer
than 25 people and less than $5 million in sales would face.
</P>
<P>
   The bill already would exclude tobacco companies and makers of
silicone breast implants from its legal protections.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said damage suits against firearm manufacturers is
the only way to force the firms to put child safety locks on guns
and to stop designing guns designed to evade airport metal
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace can protect some of these abuses if there is
liability,'' Torricelli told a news conference, adding he wants to
``keep the court house door open.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said small businesses as defined by the bill
manufacture one-quarter of all the guns sold in America. Some
30,000 Americans are victims of gun violence each year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no product manufactured or sold in America subject to
more abuse or damaging to more lives than guns,'' Torricelli said.
``Gun manufacturers have not only failed to improve their products
but have gone to great difficulties to evade the law in their
design and manufacture.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said the product-liability legislation in the Senate
is ``flawed'' because it excludes tobacco companies from its legal
protections but allow gun and ammunition manufacturers and dealers
to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the same level of accountability should really apply
to gun manufacturers that applies to tobacco manufacturers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said there are signs that public sentiment and the
courts are turning against gun manufacturers, citing the California
case three weeks ago in which an Oakland judge allowed a lawsuit to
proceed against Beretta U.S.A. Corp. for failing to put a child
safety device on one of its guns. In that case, 15-year-old Kenzo
Dix of Berkeley was killed by a schoolmate who pointed a Beretta
with an empty ammunition magazine at him, not realizing that a
round was already in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said legal recourse in such cases must remain open
since federal safety agencies have no jurisdiction to regulate
guns.
</P>
<P>
   She said Republican senators who excluded tobacco companies from
the bill's liability protections did not exclude the gun industry
because ``they didn't want to incur the wrath'' of the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya Metaksa, chief lobbyist for the National Rifle
Association, said the amendment is being proposed because Feinstein
and Torricelli ``are intent on shrinking and then strangling the
gun industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been unable to pass legislation on the consumer side
for more gun control, so now they're trying to do it on the supply
side,'' Metaksa said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein and Torricelli have sponsored other measures to limit
the private ownership of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Metaksa said the NRA will urge the Senate to defeat the
amendment, adding, ``I think it's going to be real close.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who has pressed for child safety
locks on guns, said the legal protections for small businesses in
the product-liability bill would let many manufacturers of assault
weapons and Saturday Night Specials ``off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, who opposes the overall product-liability bill, said it
would enable big gun manufacturers to split into two companies to
get the legal protection provided to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a bullet-proof vest to every gun manufacturer and
would allow lawsuits to just bounce off them,'' Boxer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
