</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CHURCH-ATTENDANCE-220&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE URGES REGULAR ATTENDANCE OF SUNDAY MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Hoping to shake his flock loose from the grip of secular
pastimes and preoccupations, Pope John Paul II reminded Catholics
on Tuesday of their obligation to attend Sunday Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In a 95-page apostolic letter, the pope wrote, ``Unfortunately,
when Sunday loses its fundamental meaning and becomes merely a part
of a weekend, it can happen that people stay locked within a
horizon so limited that they can no longer see the heavens.''
</P>
<P>
   Battling a modern world where church attendance is declining and
a growing number of Catholics ignore church teachings on divorce
and birth control, Pope John Paul has often reminded Catholics of
the fundamental rules of their faith.
</P>
<P>
   But by affirming the primacy of Sunday worship in an apostolic
letter, the 30th he has published in his 20 years as pope, John
Paul II also underscored what he wants his spiritual legacy to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of my pontificate,'' he wrote, ``I have not
ceased to repeat, `Do not be afraid! Open, open wide the doors to
Christ!' In the same way, today I would strongly urge everyone to
rediscover Sunday: Do not be afraid to give your time to Christ!''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, entitled ``Dies Domini,'' the Day of the Lord,
the pope reaffirmed that the church considers it a sin if a
Catholic fails to go to Mass weekly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The percentage of those attending the liturgy is strikingly low,
he wrote. Last month the pope traveled to Austria, where only 17
percent of Catholics regularly attend Sunday services. In Italy the
figure is 28 percent. And in some parts of Latin America the figure
drops below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the distractions of modern life make it
difficult for Catholics to follow their faith. ``Changes in
socioeconomic conditions have often led to profound modifications
of social behavior and hence of the character of Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's message was a comfort to Catholic leaders around the
world who have also been battling entrenched cultural attitudes
that they complain encroach on church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, recently
created a stir when he said he would boycott all Major League
Baseball games this year because some were held on Good Friday. He
was also heavily criticized for complaining about Little League
games on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, the pope did not condemn sports or other forms of
leisure that may distract the faithful from their Sunday duties.
</P>
<P>
   And in soccer-mad Italy, where sociologists speak not of soccer
moms but soccer widows, the Italian clergy has been careful not to
formally ask Italian soccer leagues to stop playing on Sundays, an
act that would be viewed by many Italians as tantamount to treason.
</P>
<P>
   At a Vatican news conference Tuesday, Bishop Geraldo Majella
Agnelo, secretary of the Vatican Department of Worship, was asked
whether Catholics should avoid soccer on Sundays. ``Sport is also
part of that letting off of steam on Sunday,'' he replied. ``There
is no harm in sports.'' Agnelo is from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who begins a six-week summer holiday Wednesday, made
it clear that the Lord's day should be set aside by the faithful as
a day of rest, reflection and acts of charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians,'' he said, ``are obliged in conscience to arrange
their Sunday rest in a way that allows them to take part in the
Eucharist, refraining from work and activities that are
incompatible with the sanctification of the Lord's day, with its
characteristic joy and necessary rest for spirit and body.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the reforms of Vatican Council II, many Catholic rules,
like requirements that the faithful abstain from meat on Fridays or
fast from midnight before taking Communion, have been loosened.
</P>
<P>
   In many dioceses, bishops now permit Catholics to meet their
obligations for Sunday Mass by attending on Saturday evenings. But
the church still considers it a sin for a Catholic to fail to
attend weekly Mass without a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual consequences of such a slip are less clear,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Catholic refuses to got to Mass, then he excludes himself
from the church,'' said Bishop Piero Marini, the Vatican's director
of liturgical celebrations. ``But if someone has a headache or some
other reason to skip a Mass, I could not bring myself to condemn
them for all eternity.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
