<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-HNS &LR;      07-07 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE CHIEF ARMSTRONG VOWS THAT AT&AMP;T-TCI MERGER WILL GO THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 BY NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael Armstrong told Congress
Tuesday that the proposed merger between the nation's largest
long-distance phone company and Tele-Communications Inc., its
second-largest cable TV firm, will go through despite a sharp drop
in AT&AMP;T stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is done. The deal will go through pending a
shareholders' vote,'' Armstrong said in response to a query from
Sen. Herbert H. Kohl, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, who questioned AT&AMP;T's financial muscle in face of the
``dramatic drop'' in the company's stock, asked, ``What assurances
are there that the deal will go through as planned and the company
will have the capital to upgrade'' the systems of the combined
firm.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T stock closed at $65.38 on June 24, the day the proposed
merger was announced, then skidded about 10 points in little more
than a week. It rebounded somewhat Tuesday, closing at $56.19.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong noted that AT&AMP;T has gone through a period of ``churn''
and said that ``whenever you have churn, generally, the stock goes
down.'' He also said, ``I anticipate that shareholder value will
not only be restored but will appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no change in the original merger plan, and TCI
will continue an $1.8 billion cable-system upgrade in the meantime,
he declared.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the assurances during a hearing of the Senate Judiciary
Subcommittee on Antitrust, Business Rights and Competition, adding
that AT&AMP;T still ``has an outstanding balance sheet and has an
outstanding cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The merged conglomerate would offer consumers virtually all
electronic services such as long distance and cellular phone calls,
cable TV and high-speed access to the Internet, the global computer
network.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would benefit both AT&AMP;T and its customers, Armstrong
said, predicting that it would heighten, not kill, competition and
provide more services to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said that the Bell companies, GTE ``and other
incumbent local carriers will not sit idly by as TCI continues to
upgrade its network and add telephone service capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the merger, which he hopes will be approved within nine
months, would allow AT&AMP;T to gain direct access to households
through TCI's owned and affiliated cable lines, which serve about a
third of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, chairman of the Judiciary panel, asked
if the $32 billion merger would lead to control of the information
industry by only a few powerful owners.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong replied, ``One word we must adhere to is `open.' We
have to make sure the markets stay open. ... We have to make sure
we are open to technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable upgrade includes a two-way capability for Internet and
information services that, by 1999, will be 60 percent complete,
Armstrong said. Under the merger, AT&AMP;T would be able to deliver the
services to customers in 2000 at an average cost of $300 to $500
per household, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
