<HEADLINE>
DIXON DINOSAUR AND OTHER MOVING PARTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The City Council of Benicia, Calif., has passed a resolution
welcoming Dixie, a 50-foot-tall Brachiosaurus that later this month
is to be carried from Dixon by helicopter to Benicia, to a resting
place in front of the headquarters of the discount chain Cigarettes
Cheaper!
</P>
<P>
   Dixie, which weighs 12 tons, is 71 feet long and has been
hovering over Interstate 80 in front of a Cheaper! grocery store
since 1994, was evicted by the sale of the site to Chevron. The
move, ``38 miles by the road,'' said Cheaper! owner  &UR; Ned Roscoe &LR; ,
``but shorter as the dinosaur flies,'' will cost about $50,000.
Roscoe says he's shelling out that much to please his 4-year-old
son, who drives by Dixie with his mother every day.
</P>
<P>
   The steel and fiberglass dinosaur was commissioned by Roscoe and
his brother &UR; John &LR; , owners of the Cheaper! chain, after they saw
``Jurassic Park.'' The brothers overcame the objections of Dixon
officials to its original placement by calling it art, likening it
to an oversized lawn flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie will be wrapped in a net and carried to her new home by
heavy-lift helicopter, at 6:30 a.m. on July 18.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICAL PARTIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the great accomplishments of the Reagan administration,
says Part II of Vanity Fair's series about  &UR; Ronald &LR;  and  &UR; Nancy
Reagan &LR; , is that they made it possible for presidents to socialize
across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   It all began with invitations to and from  &UR; Katharine Graham &LR;  of
the Washington Post, and expanded to include many Democratic
members of the Georgetown social set.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrat hostess  &UR; Jennifer Phillips &LR;  explained to the
magazine:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand it, but Republicans are more fun _ at
least a kind of upper class Republicans. They're not guilt-ridden
and they're not self-righteous. That unrelenting earnestness of
Democrats, particularly of Democrats who have made it, just really
gets to be tedious after a while. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, if you say it's nice outside, they talk about global
warming.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In a personals ad in the latest issue of New York magazine, a
``Petite, Beautiful  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR; '' is ``looking for my  &UR; Phil &LR; 
 &UR; Bronstein &LR;  without the 'stache. ... I am the specialist and will
captivate all your basic instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Has he captured our romantic souls, then sold us out for
profit? &UR; Tony Bennett &LR;  sings ``I Left My Heart in San Francisco'' in
a new ad for Visa check cards.
</P>
<P>
   _ In answer to the question posed herein recently, ``What do
spies eat?''  &UR; Bob Lacey &LR;  suggests Eggs  &UR; Benedict Arnold &LR; , which
they order at Traitor Vic's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Upon learning that &UR; Barbra Streisand  &LR; had blasted the media
outside her wedding for four hours with his heavy metal song
``Thunder Kiss,''  &UR; Rob Zombie &LR;  of White Zombie told the New York
Daily News that he hoped she would use one of his new tracks ``to
ward off meddling paparazzi at her divorce hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Publishers Weekly makes note of  &UR; Tom Newcomb &LR; 's new book, ``To
Start a Little War'' (New Adventure; $10.95), part of a series of
novels about a right-wing action hero. The book is about a band of
Navy retirees that sets forth from America determined to find a new
home not overrun with ``kids, women and minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was just starting out reading my poetry, I used to
clear my throat and spit at the beginning of a reading, and some of
the auditorium people got all agitated about that, so then I did it
even more. ... A local New Jersey newspaper nicknamed me The Keeper
of the Phlegm. I still like to spit when I perform. Somehow it sets
the mood right off.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Patti Smith in the Resident, a New York weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
