A4318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-PROBE-BOS &LR;      07-07 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET SERVICE EMPLOYEES ORDERED TO TESTIFY IN LEWINSKY PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court panel, in a setback to
President Clinton, Tuesday ordered three Secret Service employees
to answer questions before the grand jury investigating whether
Clinton had an affair with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky and
urged her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, a Maryland grand jury launched an investigation into
whether Linda R. Tripp illegally tape-recorded her conversations
with Lewinsky. Tripp said the Maryland probe was ``politically
motivated,'' noting that it began while she was testifying Tuesday
for the third time before a grand jury in Washington about the
allegations involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who lives in Howard County, Md., is being investigated
for possible violations of a state law prohibiting the
tape-recording of conversations without the consent of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe today's announcement is the latest in a series of
attempts to intimidate me,'' Tripp said in a statement read by her
lawyer. ``This has occurred at the very moment I am testifying
before the federal grand jury. I am not intimidated in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge federal panel, in ordering the Secret Service
employees to testify, rejected the Clinton administration's
arguments that the president would be in greater danger of being
assassinated if he didn't feel comfortable talking in front of
agents assigned to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not think ... that the Secret Service has shown with
compelling clarity that failure to recognize the proposed privilege
will jeopardize the ability of the Secret Service effectively to
protect the president,'' the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a welcome victory for independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr, who last week was criticized by a federal judge who threw
out the prosecutor's tax case against former Associate Attorney
General Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust the Secret Service will now join us in helping the
grand jury gather information that is relevant to this
investigation,'' Starr said in a statement Tuesday. ``It is
fundamental in our country that all law enforcement officers
cooperate fully in responding to requests for relevant information
in a federal grand jury investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said the appeals court decision showed ``the rule of law
is not incompatible with the profound national interest in
protecting the life of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling upholds a decision by US District Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson, but is not final. Clinton administration lawyers
have the option of asking for a ruling by the full appeals court or
appealing the decision to the Supreme Court, which does not return
from summer recess until October.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling upholds a decision by US District Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson, but is not final. The Clinton administration has
the option of asking for a ruling by the full appeals court or
appealing the decision to the Supreme Court, which does not return
from summer recess until October.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling is expected to be appealed, but White House
spokesman James Kennedy said that decision will be made by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not part of this case and will not play any role in
deciding what the next step will be,'' Kennedy said. Justice
Department officials said Tuesday they were disappointed with the
decision and would decide within seven days whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court has yet to rule on another crucial aspect of
Starr's investigation, whether deputy White House counsel Bruce
Lindsey must divulge his conversations with the president. The
White House has maintained the conversations are subject to
attorney-client privilege, but Starr has argued that Lindsey has no
such protection because he is not Clinton's personal attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been seeking testimony from three Secret Service
employees who may know if Clinton and Lewinsky were together.
Clinton and Lewinsky have each denied having an affair, but
Lewinsky reportedly boasted about such a relationship in
conversations secretly recorded by Tripp. Starr is investigating
whether Clinton or his associates tried to cover up evidence in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is in the midst of negotiating with Lewinsky's lawyers to
have her testify before the grand jury in exchange for immunity
from prosecution. If the Secret Service employees testify that they
saw Lewinsky in the White House with the president _ thus becoming
crucial witnesses _ it could put pressure on Lewinsky to make a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear, however, what the Secret Service workers
would say. There have been a variety of unconfirmed and retracted
reports about agents and members of the Secret Service's uniformed
division who supposedly saw Clinton and Lewinsky together.
</P>
<P>
   The administration opposed any testimony by the Secret Service
employees, arguing that Clinton and future presidents would be
unable to conduct their private business if they know anything they
say might be revealed in court. Former President Bush also told the
court that it would set a bad precedent to force Secret Service
agents to testify. The Secret Service also opposed such testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Former US Attorney Benito Romano, who served in the Bush
administration, called Tuesday's ruling ``an adverse development''
for the president. ``There are very few witnesses available to
testify _ the president, Ms. Lewinsky and presumably a handful of
people at the White House, presumably including Secret Service
agents,'' Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Romano called the decision a ``wrong ruling''
because it could ``weaken the shield'' of protection around the
president. ``Taking the president's security detail and converting
them to possible witnesses could cause the president to hesitate to
be near his security detail and could cause him danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The three employees affected by the ruling are Secret Service
officers Gary Byrne and Brian Henderson and lawyer John Kelleher.
The three refused to answer certain questions posed by Starr's
office earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling was made by three Republican-appointed judges
who sit on the federal appeals court in Washington: Raymond
Randolph, Stephen Williams and Douglas Ginsburg. They said there is
no built-in ``privilege'' that exempts Secret Service employees
from having to testify. The judges also said it is up to Congress
to decide whether Secret Service employees should be granted such a
privilege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
