<HEADLINE>
'98 FRENCH TEAM FAR DIFFERENT THAN THE 80S VERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They are the spiritual offspring of the greatest
generation of French footballers ever. But, unlike the France teams
of the 1980s, they will not have to contend with Germany in the
World Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, France will meet Croatia at Stade de France today, and
a victory will put Les Bleus in the championship game for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of destiny about this team, which learned the
game from watching those teams of the 1980s and also from the
coaching of former players such as Michel Platini, president of the
organizing committee of France '98.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a much different team than the elegant squads of the
'80s, which had skillful, stylish midfielders such as Platini,
Alain Giresse, Jean Fernandez, and Dominique Rocheteau.
</P>
<P>
   Youri Djorkaeff and Zinedine Zidane provide technical brilliance
in midfield, yet the strengths of the team are rock-solid defenders
Laurent Blanc and Marcel Desailly, and midfield ball-winners Didier
Deschamps, Christian Karembeu, and Emmanuel Petit.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably a canard to say the French will accept only a
stylish brand of play _ so-called ``champagne soccer'' _ from the
national team. So far, the country seems quite satisfied with the
torturous progress of the team. After the glorious failures of
1958, when Just Fontaine set the World Cup record with 13 goals,
and the '80s, there is a feeling that substance will be as welcome
with or without style.
</P>
<P>
   France has scored just once in the last 234 minutes, edging
Paraguay in overtime and eliminating Italy on penalty kicks. The
front line has not scored since the first round, and only Thierry
Henry has more than one goal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, fans could not have been much more celebratory after the
penalty-kick victory over Italy, when they drove through Paris
honking horns late into the night. Possibly, French sensibilities
have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our national team is historically always too preoccupied with
the spectacle,'' Platini told Italy's La Gazzetta dello Sport.
``Now it is nearing the hour of the great result, that which we
deserved in the '80s, when we lost two semifinals against
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Those French teams set high standards for the next generation,
which struggled to reconcile the balance between aesthetics and
results. Eric Cantona and David Ginola, who found riches and fame
in England, were considered two of the most brilliant of that
group, and they were blamed for the incredible failure to qualify
for USA '94, when France squandered leads to Bulgaria and Israel at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Cantona has retired, but Ginola remains the most effective
French left-side midfielder, though he has been excluded from the
national team.
</P>
<P>
   Since the disappointments of the '80s, there has been an
atmosphere of impending letdown about France. Ginola, whose
graceful play is reminiscent of previous French stars, is regarded
as a symbol of this.
</P>
<P>
   The mentality of the national team has changed, at the expense
of technical brilliance. It is unclear whether this is a result of
coach Aimee Jacquet's choices or the changing nature of the French
player, many of whom have honed their competitive instincts in
England and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be regarded as an old imbecile, saying that
everything that used to be was better,'' Platini said. ``However,
the midfielders and attackers of today would not make anyone from
my era jealous. Consequently, we have a game which is less
technical.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ``FILS'' of Platini were anticipating a match with
Germany, seeking vengeance especially for the rough tactics German
goalkeeper Toni Schumacher had used at Spain '82. But Croatia could
provide just as difficult, and physical, a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``To quality for the quarterfinals was the minimum, the
semifinal is already an optimum result,'' Platini said. ``With this
assurance, from now on it will be a bonus for everyone _ the ideal
conditions to enter into legendary status.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
