<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SURPLUS-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DEBATES HOW TO USE $4.4 BILLION SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Pete Wilson began his tenure here
seven summers ago with the largest budget gap that any state ever
faced, a $14.3 billion shortfall that forced him and the
Legislature to raise $7 billion in new taxes and slash spending by
the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was finally passed 17 days after the July 1 deadline,
and the next year the wrangling was even worse, with a record
63-day standoff over how to spread the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wilson is in his last year in office, contemplating another
run for the White House and eager to leave a legacy _ and
California is once again without a budget one week into the new
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, as in other state capitals buoyed by a strong
economy this season, the fight is over what to do with a surplus _
$4.4 billion generated by the Golden State's booming economic
recovery _ and while the question now is about cutting taxes and
expanding services, the debate is proving just as bitter as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bigger problem, in a way,'' said John Burton, the
beleaguered Democratic leader of the state Senate, who noted that a
surplus _ in an election year to boot _ inspires less cooperation
and more partisanship than in tough times.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson agreed, saying dryly of his adversaries in the
Democratic-controlled Legislature, ``They seem to find it more
difficult to come to grips with plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by states like Virginia and Arizona, where the issue
has proved to be political catnip, Wilson and his fellow
Republicans want a $3.6 billion cut in the state's vehicle-license
tax over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   That would amount to a 75 percent reduction in the unpopular
tax, a Depression-era relic that is based on 2 percent of a
vehicle's value (adjusted by a set depreciation schedule) and
translates into several hundred dollars a year for owners of newer
cars. Such a cut would also allow Wilson to claim that, overall, he
has reduced taxes more than he has raised them in his two terms in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Because the car tax revenues go to cities and counties to
finance local services, the Democrats contend that cutting the tax
could jeopardize police protection if the economy took a turn for
the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in what was regarded as no more than an opening bid,
the Democratic-controlled Senate unanimously passed an alternative,
a one-year, one-quarter-cent cut in the state's 6 percent sales
tax, and on Monday, the Assembly followed suit. But Wilson derided
the idea as ``much too little and much too brief'' and vowed to
veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said in an interview that he expected face-to-face
negotiations with the governor and the Democratic Assembly speaker,
Antonio Villaraigosa, to begin soon, but the Assembly and Senate
have yet to agree on an overall budget plan of their own.
</P>
<P>
   And Burton and Villaraigosa have held their posts for just a few
months, replacing colleagues forced to move on by term limits,
while Wilson, himself barred from seeking a third term, is a
veteran with a proven stomach for budget standoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And despite being in his last year as governor, Wilson is
provided with strong advantages by the state Constitution. It
requires a two-thirds vote in each house for the budget to be
passed, making it hard for the Democrats to peel off enough
Republicans to force the governor's hand, and it gives the governor
line-item veto power to punish legislators by cutting their pet
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart money is looking at late August now,'' said Dan
Schnur, a former top aide to Wilson who is a political consultant
in San Francisco. ``In the past, the choices have been so painful
that they led to paralysis. It takes two or three months to decide
whether you're going to take guide dogs away from blind people. But
there isn't any road map for what they're dealing with now.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Wilson said that it should not take so
long to reach agreement, but he added that he would not be
surprised if it did, noting that ``there doesn't seem to be even
common direction'' among the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And the governor dismissed any notion that the surplus is a
short-term phenomenon. Beginning two years ago, with the recovery
reaching full force, the state's revenue collections started
exceeding forecasts, and there was a somewhat smaller surplus last
year, though Wilson curtailed debate over how to spend it, by
unilaterally using most of it to replenish a state pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep having these nonrecurring surpluses,'' he said
sardonically, adding that this situation means ``California's tax
structure takes too big a bite.'' Wilson argues that the vehicle
tax, which costs the average car owner $185 a year, is particularly
onerous and affects almost everyone in a state with 24 million
registered vehicles, more than there are houses. His proposal would
save the average owner $135 a year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Twenty states impose no value-based taxes on motor vehicles,
opting for flat annual registration fees. But the 30 remaining
states impose either a personal-property tax on cars or, like
California, a value-based tax in lieu of property tax.
</P>
<P>
   In California's case, the car tax is the sole legacy of the
state's old personal-property tax, in which assessors visited homes
each year to survey the value of contents. But cars were always
mysteriously absent from driveways on assessment day, so in 1935
the state abandoned the personal-property tax in favor of a tax on
cars, imposed at annual registration.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the National Conference of State Legislatures
found considerable support around the nation for rolling back such
taxes, after the successful candidacy for governor of James Gilmore
III in Virginia, who campaigned last year on a platform of reducing
that state's local property tax on automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, states including Kansas, Kentucky, Rhode Island,
South Carolina and Arizona have either passed reductions or are
considering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tax is particularly disliked,'' said Mandy Rafool, a
conference policy analyst who conducted the study. ``People hate
property taxes in general, and this is a big chunk at once.''
</P>
<P>
   All the players here agree that there will be a tax cut, with
the only question being how big. Both sides are also proposing more
spending on education, with the Democrats demanding more than
Wilson has offered. But the governor repeated Tuesday that he was
``not interested in temporary relief'' from taxes and said that the
Legislature had so far offered no more than ``this little drill.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Burton _ an old Sacramento hand who is on his
second career after a stint here and in Congress collapsed as a
result of alcohol and drug abuse _ confessed in an interview, ``All
I want is to get out alive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
