<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRANCE-ZIZOU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIZOU READY FOR MATCH AGAINST CROATIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Zizou went `zinzin'. Zinedine Zidane
couldn't stand still, couldn't keep quiet. He glanced at the TV
monitor, which kept showing Lolo Blanc's ``golden goal'' that beat
Paraguay in overtime and began laughing like a madman, running,
jumping, hugging anyone within reach. ``Zizou was completely in a
trance,'' testified goalkeeper Fabien Barthez.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Zidane had just been freed from one. For two weeks,
France's best soccer player had been banished for peevishly
stepping on a fallen Saudi rival and drawing a red card that put
him out of the next two matches.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 days, Zidane had been the ancient mariner of Les Bleus,
wearing a reeking albatross around his neck while his mates played
the World Cup without him, biting his knuckles on the bench and
praying that the tournament wouldn't end before his penance did.
</P>
<P>
   Came ``La Delivrance'' _ Blanc's goal in the 114th minute _ and
Zidane was a man redeemed, reborn. He was the man of the match in
last Friday's shootout victory over Italy, driving Les Bleus
forward for 120 minutes and nailing the first penalty kick. And if
France is to beat Croatia Wednesday night in the Stade de France
here and make the Cup final for the first time, Zizou will be the
man who leads them there.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane is what Michel Platini was to France's stylish but
ill-starred teams that also made the Cup semifinals in 1982 and
1986 _ their mainspring, their alchemist, their visionary. ``He's
the guiding light of the French team,'' says Italian forward
Alessandro Del Piero, who plays alongside Zidane for Juventus of
Turin.
</P>
<P>
   Without Zidane, Les Bleus were aimless, punchless, clueless
against Paraguay. With him, they were daring and confident against
Italy. They may have lacked for a finisher, but not a creator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he didn't score or produce the vital pass, we know
how important he is,'' says Italian defender Gianluca Pessotto, who
had to mark Zidane. ``I hope he wins the World Cup, because he
deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   His global rivals say the 26-year-old Zidane is the world's
second-best player after Brazil's Ronaldo and its best playmaker.
The French have already installed him in their pantheon alongside
Platini, with whom Zidane shares a number (10), a legacy _ and a
burden.
</P>
<P>
   When Zidane took the field against the Italians, a banner in the
stands proclaimed ``Zizou, t'es le roi (Zizou, you're the king)''.
``They expect a lot of me, and so do I,'' says Zidane. ``But that
doesn't bother me. I'm not a messiah _ just a player whose role is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Zidane, who grew up in an Algerian neighborhood in the northern
part of Marseille, was still a boy wizard, a ``gamin'', when
Platini led France to the final four in 1986. The directors of
Septemes, his local club, kept telling Smail Zidane that his
youngest child ``Yaziz'' could play internationally some day.
Before long, recruiters from Marseille and Lyon and Cannes were
knocking on Zidane's door.
</P>
<P>
   The messiah business came later, after Zidane went off to master
his craft in Juventus's striped shirt (``That's where I learned to
win.''), after he took over France's midfield. Even then, Zidane
developed a reputation for disappearing in the big matches. Not so,
Zidane insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lost, it wasn't that I wasn't good,'' he says. ``It
was either that there was a combination of circumstances or that we
were up against a better team. I believe the contrary _ that I'm
better when I'm playing for something important.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it killed Zidane to miss two matches just when Les
Bleus had dreams of at least getting to the Cup semifinals. Only a
hot-headed ``bobo'' would get himself chucked out of a match that
his mates were winning easily. Didier Deschamps, the French
captain, told Zidane so. ``It's his Mediterranean temper, which he
cannot always control,'' Deschamps said. ``In the heat of the
moment, I lost my temper with him.''
</P>
<P>
   So Zidane, ``disappointed and deflated'', went into an odd sort
of exile _ part cheerleader, part penitent, part spectator. He
trained with his mates, then sat on the bench in warmup gear and
watched them struggle without him to beat the Danes and win their
group.
</P>
<P>
   Then Zidane sweated blood as France and Paraguay stayed
scoreless for an eternity in their second-round match. ``It was
hard, even terrible,'' he said. ``To lose without being on the
field would have been awful. During the extra time, I felt an
impossible stress. I put myself behind my buddies, I wanted to help
them with little things, but they had to manage by themselves. The
longer it went, the more I suffered, up to the deliverance. Then, I
exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Zizou went zinzin. ``He was the happiest of all of us,'' coach
Aime Jacquet said. He was Ebenezer Scrooge, come out of the
nightmare to find it was still Christmas Day. He embraced
midfielder Youri Djorkaeff, who'd shouldered his load, and thanked
him profoundly. ``The words will stay between us,'' Djorkaeff said,
``but they are unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus was Zizou unchained. The Italy match, he vowed, would be
``le plus important de ma carriere''. He was Platini,
orchestrating, inspiring, pushing Les Bleus upfield. When it came
time for the shootout, Jacquet sent Zidane up first.
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, and Les Bleus had prevailed, 4-3, Platini (now
head of the Cup organizing committee), stood in the VIP box with
his arms up in a victory salute. ``I am not Platini,'' Zidane says,
``but having pressure on my shoulders gives me energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zidane and Les Bleus go up against a country that didn't exist
the last time France played in a Mondiale. If they win, they'll
play in Sunday's final, with Jacques Chirac looking on and Zidane
the man carrying the dreams of la France. Chirac may be president
around here, but Zizou is le roi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
