u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKBOSTON-LAYOFFS-BO     07-07 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKBOSTON-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON BEGINS SHEDDING JOBS   IN TRIMDOWN EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp. said Tuesday that it would shed 114
jobs, the first staffing cutbacks in a broad overhaul designed to
fine-tune operations, cut costs, and boost profits at New England's
second largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's restructuring effort, which will last through 1999
and is likely to entail further layoffs, is not a grand remaking of
the bank's basic strategy. Rather, it is for now a collection of
nips and tucks across units ranging from retail and private banking
to small business and consumer lending. Future phases of the
restructuring initiative may affect the company's other core areas,
which include capital markets, corporate banking, and operations in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing was not a strategy review,'' said Thomas J.
Hollister, Bank Boston's executive vice president in charge of
consumer and small business lending.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the effort, begun last fall but only now
being implemented, was aimed at making the bank more customer
focused by cutting down on paper handling and integrating the
bank's various service channels.
</P>
<P>
   Evoking on-line bookselling as a model of consumer-focused
service, a BankBoston memo to employees Tuesday said the company
would aim to know clients' needs better by collecting more
information about customers in a centralized fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks are fighting to win back market share from
financial services firms, whose arsenal of investment products pose
stiff competition. Banks, especially those in New England, also
face tighter profit margins from traditional branch banking. And as
increasing numbers of customers communicate with banks via personal
computers, telephones, and automated teller machines, banks are
racing to offer more products and services on line.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its restructuring, BankBoston also plans to set up
branches selling only a limited number of core products instead of
the traditional broad array of banking services. But in other
branches, the company will expand its offerings to include more
mutual funds and insurance products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to have a multichannel approach,'' BankBoston
president Henrique Meirelles said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cutbacks announced Tuesday affect BankBoston's
Providence, R.I. telephone banking unit, where 80 night-shift
employees will be given the opportunity to take day jobs, commute
to Dedham, Mass., or retire early.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, the nation's 16th-largest bank holding company, with
$71.4 billion in assets, has not said how much its restructuring
effort will cost or what kinds of savings will result. But both
numbers will run into at least the tens of millions, with savings
to be reinvested primarily in new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts have impressed Wall Street, which has put
BankBoston's share price in record territory lately, and industry
analysts, who are keen on the company's growth prospects and
management style. ``They are very enthusiastic about Internet
banking,'' said analyst Nancy A. Bush of Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``All of
the redesign indicates that they want to be a niche player'' in
retail banking.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston laid off 2,000 employees when it merged with BayBanks
Inc. in 1996, three years after crosstown rival Fleet Financial
Group Inc., the region's largest bank, slashed 3,000 jobs. Both
efforts boosted the bottom line but hurt morale and caused service
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the size of future layoffs, Meirelles said,
``We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston shares rose 1/2 to close Tuesdayat 58 1/2, a record
high, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
