<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION CANDIDATE VOWS REFORMS IN MEXICAN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The first governor elected from the leftist
Democratic Revolutionary Party (PRD) vowed Tuesday he would support
political reforms and an across-the-board attack on poverty in the
state of Zacatecas.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Monreal Avila, the PRD candidate in the central Mexican
state, told reporters at the party's national headquarters that he
would form a ``pluralistic and citizen-based'' government, and he
urged other elected officials to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   The ground-breaking victory came as the dominant Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) regained the governor's office in
Chihuahua state and retained its ascendancy in Durango in state
elections held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Monreal quit the centrist PRI earlier this year to run on the
PRD slate in Zacatecas, although he has not yet technically joined
the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   He did not specify when he would formalize his association with
the party, but he said that when he signed onto the party's ticket,
he ``subscribed to the PRD's principles and that (he was) committed
to fulfilling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Amalia Garcia, a national senator and the PRD's secretary of
political relations, called the unusual alliance ``Monrealismo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He won, and we won,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD leader rejected suggestions that Monreal
opportunistically jumped ship when he encountered problems within
his former party and that the PRD took advantage of the former
federal deputy's home-state popularity to gain its first statehouse
since the party was founded in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Party founder Cuauhtemoc Cardenas became Mexico City's first
elected mayor in modern history during elections a year ago, when
the PRD also combined with the National Action Party (PAN) to break
the PRI's 70-year hold on the national Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the PRD feel that we won the election on Sunday, just as
we won last July 6,'' Garcia said. ``We have party militants here
who used to belong to the PRI, but now we are all in the PRD.''
</P>
<P>
   Monreal promised to build Zacatecas' industrial and tourism
bases, rebuild its educational system, and bring better health care
to the mining state's poor.
</P>
<P>
   A killing drought has devastated Zacatecas' agriculture, and
Monreal said he would design an emergency relief program to benefit
farmers and the state's urban poor.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised initiatives for referendums, plebiscites and
popular recall, as well constitutional reforms that would allow the
50 percent of the state's population now living in the United
States to vote in state elections.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD won 12 seats in the state legislature. The PRI also won
12 seats while PAN candidates took five.
</P>
<P>
   The victory of PRI candidate Patricio Martinez over the PAN's
Ramon Galindo in Chihuahua may signal a return to health in what
had been considered an ailing party.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing PAN Gov. Francisco Barrios was very popular, but under
Mexican law could not stand for re-election. Galindo was not
considered as strong a candidate as Martinez in Chihuahua, a state
that borders New Mexico and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI used a first-time open primary to select its candidates
in Chihuahua, something President Ernesto Zedillo has said he wants
to institute nationally to select the party's presidential
candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The loss reduces to five the number of statehouses held by PAN,
primarily in the country's conservative north, and is one more
setback after a dismal showing in the Mexico City mayoral election
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   PAN has long been considered Mexico's strongest opposition party
and it continues to rule most of Mexico's biggest cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
