<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWLAUNDRIES-AZR &LR;      07-07 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWLAUNDRIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN LAUNDRIES FRESHEN IMAGE, SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Say goodbye to burnt-orange decor, walletloads of
quarters, poorly lit buildings and absentee owners who treat
coin-operated laundries like second jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to supergiant washing machines, debit cards that
provide flexible prices, round-the-clock attendants and national,
brand-name chains.
</P>
<P>
   The coin-operated laundry business is changing its dingy image.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies new to the Phoenix area, SpinCycle Inc. of
Scottsdale (Ariz.) and Super Wash of Phoenix, are introducing
innovation and pushing consolidation in this $3.5 billion industry.
Some even say these companies and other pioneers will bring to the
coin laundry industry the big-box format and nationwide uniformity
that Blockbuster Entertainment brought to the once independent
video-store business a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a safe, secure, high level of customer service
place to do their laundry. And we're creating a national brand,''
said Peter Ax, chairman and chief executive officer of SpinCycle.
</P>
<P>
   A competitive attitude is heating up as both chains and the
Valley's independent operators target similar demographic groups _
densely populated neighborhoods with large families, high
percentages of renters and household incomes in the $25,000 to
$30,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   While they may steal market share from the competition, both
chains say they also create business from apartment dwellers fed up
with dark, dirty laundry rooms and from busy homeowners who want to
wash more in less time.
</P>
<P>
   National statistics also indicate healthy growth for the
business, according to the Downers Grove, Ill.-based Coin Laundry
Association. The percentages of renters is growing, more homeowners
are becoming aware of modern laundries' convenience, and
wash-dry-and-fold services are gaining popularity with dual-income
families, spokesman Brian Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past few years, the industry revolution has meant
several changes for consumers, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ More and bigger washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle stores offer a variety of washers for loads from 18 to
50 pounds. Super Wash goes them one better, with supergiant
machines that handle 75 pounds of laundry for $5.59.
</P>
<P>
   Both chains' stores have upper and lower rows of dryers, a
capacity-doubling innovation that Super Wash President Michael
Cutter says is less than 10 years old and ``one of the best
inventions in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bigger, brighter, safer buildings.
</P>
<P>
   New stores can be as big as 5,500 square feet, more than double
the typical store size, the better to accommodate extra machines,
folding tables and seating.
</P>
<P>
   Bright interior lighting and plenty of big windows make store
activities visible to passers-by. Full-time attendants help people
with machines and keep an eye out for troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   - The budding use of ``smart cards,'' credit-card-size pieces of
plastic whose computer chips store a sum of money and deduct the
cost as a service is used.
</P>
<P>
   The cards make scrounging for quarters obsolete, budgeting for
laundry expenses manageable. Super Wash, first in the coin-laundry
industry to adopt smart-card technology, has put five of its 17
stores on the cards and has plans for more. Maytag distributor Coin
and Professional Equipment Co. of Phoenix recently installed
debit-card technology at two west-side laundries, President Dave
Svancara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fears were customer acceptance and dependability,''
but customers quickly embraced the cards' safety and convenience,
Super Wash's Cutter said. One factor in his favor, he said, is that
many Hispanic customers were already familiar with the concept
because of prepaid phone cards widely used in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other marketing twists like free dryers and wash-dry-and-fold
service.
</P>
<P>
   Super Wash builds the price of drying into its wash price, then
advertises dryers as free to washer-using customers. Attendants and
paying customers enforce the policy, Cutter said.
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle is introducing wash-and-fold service this month that
it hopes will bring in business from busy middle-income households,
traditionally light users of coin laundry services. The move also
will allow SpinCycle to put its stores and attendants to work on
light days and overnight, Ax said.
</P>
<P>
   Cutter, an ex-restaurateur whose family operated parking lots in
California, bought and sold his first laundries in Dallas in the
early '80s. He started building Super Wash 10 years ago when one of
his buyers defaulted and a business broker told him laundries in
Dallas were going for bargain-basement prices.
</P>
<P>
   Super Wash entered the Phoenix market three years ago, opened in
Las Vegas last fall and last month moved its headquarters to
Phoenix. Super Wash has had as many as 27 locations, but Cutter
sold the smaller ones and now has 17 stores, including seven around
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   With 65 employees and projecting more than $3.5 million in
annual sales, Cutter says Super Wash is growing through
acquisitions financed through internal growth, bank loans and in
the future, private investors. Salt Lake City, Tucson and Reno are
its next possible markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle, by contrast, was born in 1995 when New York
investment banker Ax and Blockbuster veterans Patrick Clifton and
Christopher Lombardi decided to start their own company and
targeted the laundry business.
</P>
<P>
   They built their first store in Chicago in 1996 and, financed in
part by $50 million raised in three rounds of private equity, have
since built or acquired 110 stores stretching from Philadelphia and
Baltimore to Miami and Albuquerque. Its sole Arizona location, in
Tempe, opened just weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle recently completed a $100 million bond offering and,
as Ax said, ``we are positioned to continue to grow very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle projects 200 stores, 1,200 employees and $40 million
in sales by year end, Ax said. It plans to enter 15 new markets in
1999 and look at Mexico and Latin America as international
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   SpinCycle would be ripe to go public in a year, Ax said. Cutter
says he isn't interested in selling Super Wash but will position
the company for a possible public offering, too.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are tapping technology to give them the cash
control and accountability unprecedented in the coin-operated
laundry business.
</P>
<P>
   Computer cards installed in each SpinCycle machine collect data
on how often a machine is used and how much cash collected. The
information is downloaded each night to SpinCycle headquarters,
where it is used to generate management reports and reconcile sums
with the amounts on-site attendants collected.
</P>
<P>
   Super Wash says its smart cards free attendants from having to
collect coins and repair jammed machines. They also allow the
company to change prices and offer bonuses. Super Wash cuts prices
40 percent between midnight and 6 a.m. to help drum up business at
an otherwise slow time, and it entices customers with offers of $22
worth of service for $20 cash, Cutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Super Wash sets prices so the cards never zero out, giving
customers incentive to come back to its stores, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to give people a reason to go elsewhere, unless
we're more expensive. And we're not, with the free dry,'' Cutter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag distributor Svancara said the competition could even
benefit independent operators. When companies like SpinCycle offer
more service at higher prices, it could give the independents room
to raise their prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Blockbuster, could chains' growth drive out
competition?
</P>
<P>
   ``If stores aren't managed well, yes it would,'' he said. &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The coin laundry business at a glance &QL; 
_ There are 35,000 coin-operated laundries in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are 30,000 owners of such laundries, meaning the
industry is dominated by individual owner-operators. The number of
multiple-store owners is growing, though most are limited by the
number of stores they can service in a geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laundries are capital-intensive to start, but they typically
have no inventory and no accounts receivable. They generally rent
retail space through leases lasting 10 to 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laundries can generate cash flow of $15,000 to $200,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Renters are the primary customer base for laundries. There
were 89 million renters in the United States at the time of the
1990 census. &QL; 
Source: Coin Laundry Association &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
