<SLUG> BC-RESTOCKING-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GROUP WARNS OF SKY-HIGH RESTOCKING FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rosemary Coronella bought a $2,800 computer for her daughter
last Christmas at Circuit City. When she couldn't get it to work,
she says, the retailer refused to refund her money, offered her a
store credit instead and slapped her with a $370 restocking fee.
</P>
<P>
   Coronella's predicament is apparently not unique. A report
issued Tuesday by the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group,
a consumer activist group, said a growing number of computer, auto
part and home supply retailers are imposing restocking fees ranging
from 5 to 30 percent of the original purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   The Masspirg survey also indicated many of those same retailers
are failing to comply with Massachusetts laws on returns. Deirdre
Cummings, legislative director for Masspirg, said 12 of 28
retailers surveyed violated at least one of two state laws. Eight
retailers failed to offer customers the option of a full refund in
the case of a defective product. Six failed to adequately post
their return policy or disclose the existence of a restocking fee.
</P>
<P>
   According to Masspirg, Circuit City violated both laws at its
Somerville, Mass. store. Its return policy was posted at the
returns counter but not disclosed to consumers prior to a purchase,
as the law requires. Circuit City also failed to give customers the
option of a full refund for defective goods, offering only to
repair the defective product, exchange it for a new one or issue a
store credit.
</P>
<P>
   Coronella, who bought her daughter's computer at the Circuit
City in Dedham, Mass., said it froze up repeatedly and support
technicians were unable to correct the problem. She said the
computer was such a nightmare that she decided to return the
product and collect a full refund.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I didn't ever want to go in that store again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said Circuit City offered her only a store credit and
also charged her a $370.50 restocking fee.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stewart, a spokesman for Circuit City in Richmond, Va.,
said the company allows customers to return computer products
within 14 days, sometimes longer at the store manager's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   If the customer wants a refund and the product has been opened,
he said, a 15 percent restocking fee is charged. (It was unclear
Tuesday why the restocking fee charged to Coronella was less than
15 percent.) If the customer merely wants to exchange the product
for another of equal or greater value, no restocking fee is
charged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to protect our ability to offer low prices,''
Stewart said. ``It discourages abuses of our return policies. It
discourages customers who try to `rent' products.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also said restocking, or open box, fees are needed to
offset the cost of handling returned merchandise. He said retailers
cannot return opened computer equipment to the manufacturer and
have to mark down the price sharply to resell it. ``There's not
much profit to begin with on a computer product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why no restocking fee is charged when the customer
exchanges one product for another, Stewart said, ``Let's call it
consumerism.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings of Masspirg said she believes the restocking fee is
being used by retailers to discourage customers from making
returns. She said she doubted there were significant actual costs
to restock the returned product.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a defective product, Stewart said Circuit City
gives a customer the option of having it repaired or replaced or
given a store credit. He said no restocking fee is charged in these
cases. Stewart was unable to explain why Coronella was issued a
store credit and a restocking fee, although he said it was possible
she had been given a credit on her credit card. Coronella said that
was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Masspirg charge that Circuit City's failure to offer
a full refund for defective merchandise violates Massachusetts law,
Stewart said he believes the retailer is in compliance with the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Massachusetts Attorney General Scott Harshbarger's
office said Circuit City's interpretation of state law is
incorrect. A spokesman said the attorney general will review the
Masspirg results carefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
