<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIFFEL-TOWER-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH OUTRAGED OVER AMERICAN TALKS ON BUYING EIFFEL TOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sell the Eiffel Tower to the Americans? Paris Mayor Jean
Tiberi was as outraged at the idea Tuesday as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani might be at a suggestion that the Brooklyn Bridge was for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no risk to the ownership of this monument,'' Tiberi
assured fellow Gaullists in a stormy City Council meeting Tuesday
morning, after conservative renegades trying to unseat him spread
the alarm that a subsidiary of GMAC, the financial arm of the
General Motors Corp., was on the verge of acquiring operating
rights to the tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be inconceivable and unacceptable for the tower to
come under the control of an American group as its subsidiary,''
Philippe Dominati, another conservative, thundered as the renegades
cheered.
</P>
<P>
   GMAC Commercial Mortgage in Horsham, Pa., is indeed interested,
along with the Bass brothers of Texas, in buying a 70 percent
interest in the state-owned Credit Foncier de France. Credit
Foncier owns half of a management company that has a 70 percent
interest in the Eiffel Tower's operating company.
</P>
<P>
   According to French law, the tower is the ``inalienable''
property of the City of Paris, which means aliens of any kind,
including Americans, cannot buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine whoever is negotiating this for us on the
ground is aware of that,'' said Scott Rombach, GMAC Commercial
Mortgage's spokesman in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The 984-foot-high latticework tower, the highest in the world
when Gustave Eiffel designed it for a centennial exposition in
1889, attracts almost as many tourists as Notre Dame. Its
operations include a highly regarded restaurant, the Jules Verne,
on its second ``floor,'' and elevators that take tourists up to the
most thrilling view in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tower is not for sale, de Gaulle might have objected
to the sale of Credit Foncier itself, which may not be the Eiffel
Tower or the Arc de Triomphe but has serious credentials of its
own. It was founded by decree of Louis Napoleon and financed Baron
Georges-Eugene Haussmann's vast remaking of Paris in the late 19th
century, before entering the equally vast French market for
subsidized housing in the 20th.
</P>
<P>
   But after the property market went sour in the 1990s, Credit
Foncier lost $1.9 billion in 1996 and the conservative government
of the day let it be known that it was thinking of breaking it up
and selling it.
</P>
<P>
   Employees _ some of them civil servants who had been paid 16
monthly salaries a year, according to French accounts _ held the
bank's chairman hostage for a few days in January 1997 in protest,
and a few months later, voters threw out the conservatives and
elected a Socialist-led government, which continued to try to find
a buyer for Credit Foncier.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital, a subsidiary of General Electric Co., considered but
decided against a bid, and the bank's unions agitated for a sale to
the French post office. Now the question of whether the bank will
be sold to GMAC and the Bass group is up to the minister of the
economy, finance and industry, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, who is
expected to make a decision later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Strauss-Kahn's office dismissed the whole matter as
political posturing by conservatives desperate to hold onto power
in the city but losing their grip after the mayor for nearly two
decades, Jacques Chirac, became president three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A leading possible Socialist candidate for the mayor's job in
the next election, in 2001, is Strauss-Kahn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
