A4348 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     07-07 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCY FINDS FREEDOM IN THE WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - It turns out the old cliche is true: You can look at
something for a long time and never see its true value, its real
worth.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this recently by a story in another newspaper,
the ``Roanoke (Va.) Times.'' The story was about my niece, Lucy,
who was about to embark on a trip to Minneapolis for the USA
Swimming Disabilities Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy, 14, has McCune-Albright syndrome. It's remarkably rare _
the story said about 35 people in the United States are believed to
have it.
</P>
<P>
   Since she was 2, Lucy has been poked, prodded, operated on,
studied, stitched up and put into casts for cruel lengths of time:
time she spent lying on her back or stomach as the world went on
around her.
</P>
<P>
   I knew about the disease, of course, and I knew that Lucy was a
member of the local swim team.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen her swim, cruising along in the water in a smooth
manner that the disease doesn't allow her on land. Walking can be
tough for her; in the water, she's free.
</P>
<P>
   I also knew about the article. My sister told me a reporter was
going to interview Lucy, and she alerted me when the story appeared
on the ``Roanoke Times''' Web site, so I'd be sure to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you write about other people all the time, you
sometimes forget the impact what you're writing will have on their
lives. I'm not flattering myself here. It's just that I'll
occasionally receive a personal reminder of how powerful a medium
newspapers can be.
</P>
<P>
   The article about Lucy was one such reminder, and a happy one. I
clicked my way through several Web pages until I found the story,
written by a reporter named Neal Richards. The headline alone made
something catch in my throat:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unsinkable Lucy Gilmore.''
</P>
<P>
   I read on:
</P>
<P>
   ``On June 26, Lucy Gilmore will compete on equal ground _ make
that in equal water _ for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards wrote about Lucy's experience in regular meets, how she
often came in last and how this never discouraged her. He recounted
the five surgeries on her right femur, using bone grafts from a
cadaver. He mentioned the spinal-fusion surgery, the operation to
remove bone cysts from her skull.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about how Lucy qualified in six events for the
Minneapolis meet, about the effort she put into preparation, about
how she trained at 6 a.m. every day.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy is shy around strangers, but Richards coaxed a nice little
quote out of her, one that captured her feelings about the whole
experience:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like to swim.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing new to me in this story. As I said, I knew
about the disease, the surgeries, the swim meets, the early-morning
practices (one friend noted that if she likes to get up at 6 a.m.
to practice, not much of my blood courses through her veins).
</P>
<P>
   Yet from those first four words _ ``the Unsinkable Lucy
Gilmore'' _ the story made me think of Lucy in a whole new way.
</P>
<P>
   Before, she was my niece. Courageous, sure. But still my niece,
one of the kids I snapped with a towel on family trips to the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because of the great job my sister and her husband
have done raising Lucy. She has chores, just like her three
sisters. When she doesn't do them, she's punished, like the others.
Nothing about her life suggests that she has ever been anything but
``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   I have never once heard Lucy utter the word ``handicap.'' I
doubt I ever will.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why I didn't see what was right in front of me all
this time _ that Lucy isn't just a courageous kid.
</P>
<P>
   She's downright inspirational.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy won five medals in Minneapolis and qualified for the
International Paralympic Committee World Championships in New
Zealand in October. She's competing at the world-class level.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she's still Lucy. She's still my niece. I'm still
going to snap her with a towel at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I'll still look at her the same way.
</P>
<P>
   I'll just see her a little differently. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
