u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKS-NICOTINE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-NICOTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS HEIGHTENED EFFECT OF NICOTINE IN BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   African-Americans take in as much as 30 percent more nicotine
than whites or Hispanics with every cigarette they smoke, report
scientists who say the reason may be a combination of the way
blacks smoke and their genes.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the higher nicotine intake may explain why
blacks have more trouble quitting smoking and suffer from a higher
rate of lethal lung cancer, say the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   One of a pair of studies published in the current Journal of the
American Medical Association shows that blacks had higher levels of
a breakdown product of nicotine in their blood than did whites or
Hispanics. The study adjusted for the fact that blacks generally
smoke fewer cigarettes per day.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Ralph S. Caraballo of the US Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, interviewed 2,136 white, black and
Mexican American volunteers over 17 who had participated in
nationwide health and nutrition study called NHANES III betweeen
1988 and 1991. During the study, they had given blood samples that
were analyzed for levels of cotinin, a chemical formed when the
body metabolizes nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans turned out to have significantly higher
amounts of cotinin in their blood, indicating they had absorbed
more nicotine, even though they smoked the same number of
cigarettes as Hispanics and whites. One factor may be blacks' heavy
preference for mentholated cigarettes, which cool the throat and
make it possible to inhale more deeply, but the CDC scientists said
this didn't entirely account for the difference.
</P>
<P>
   While they couldn't fully explain that difference, the
scientists said the finding of higher cotinin levels in blacks is
important, because black smokers are more likely to try to quit
smoking but have less success, and blacks are at higher risk of
developing and dying from lung cancer. The difficulty quitting
could be the result of taking in more nicotine per cigarette, and
the higher cancer rate may stem from black smokers' inhaling more
cancer-causing ``tars,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that blacks suffer more from the health risks of
smoking because their bodies don't clear out nicotine and
carcinogens as fast as other ethnic groups, said the scientists.
Other racial differences in metabolizing drugs and carcinogens have
been found previously, but not for nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, scientists at San Francisco General Hospital
reported that blacks do metabolize cotinin more slowly than whites
or Hispanics. This may mean that blacks metabolize carcinogenic
substances more slowly, making them more prone to cancer, said the
researchers. The study, however, did not find a difference in
metabolism of nicotine itself. The tests did show that black
smokers took in 30 percent more nicotine than whites, said Drs.
Eliseo J. Perez-Stable and Neal L. Benowitz.
</P>
<P>
   As in the other study, the reason wasn't clear. But, Benowitz
said, ``almost all blacks smoke menthol cigarettes, which have a
cooling effect allowing deeper inhalation; but it could also be
that blacks in general are poorer, and if you have less money you
may smoke each cigarette more intensely.''
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial in the journal, Dr. Edward M. Sellers of the
University of Toronto pointed out that there are differences among
racial and ethnic groups in how they react to tobacco smoke. More
than 50 percent of Japanese men smoke, but they have some of the
lowest rates of lung cancer, said Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers's own research has shown that some people have mutations
in a metabolic gene that make them less likely to become hooked on
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists noted that tobacco companies have targeted
advertising for menthol cigarettes at the black community. And
Gregory Connolly, director of the Massachusetts Tobacco Control
Program, said ``the tobacco industry has designed brands
specifically for blacks that allow greater efficiency of extraction
of nicotine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
