<HEADLINE>
TYSON DELAYS PETITION FOR NEW NEVADA LICENSE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson is eligible to apply to the Nevada State Athletic
Commission on Thursday for re-instatement of his boxing license,
but the commission hasn't heard from him. Shelly Finkel, the boxing
manager who is advising Tyson, said it would be two weeks before
Tyson, the former heavyweight champion, petitions the commission to
return his license.
</P>
<P>
   And even after that, it will be another two to three weeks
before the commission schedules a hearing, according to a
commission spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel said that nothing would be submitted on Tyson's behalf
this week. ``We're going over all the options right now,'' Finkel
said. ``We'll make our appeal when we're done with that.'' He said
he could not comment on the options.
</P>
<P>
   When Tyson was suspended last July 9 for biting off a piece of
the right ear of Evander Holyfield during their heavyweight title
bout on June 28, his license was revoked indefinitely. There are no
guarantees that even if Tyson does re-apply that he will be granted
his license to box again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson fired his co-managers John Horne and Rory Holloway and
sued them, and also sued promoter Don King for $100 million,
alleging breach of contract and fraud, and is seeking to get out of
his contract with King on that basis.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is now being advised by entertainment executive Jeff Wald,
entertainment attorney John Branca, both based in the Los Angeles
area, and Finkel. Other than a World Wrestling Federation
pay-per-view event, Tyson has kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really made over his behavior in the last year,''
Finkel said. ``And he has done things that will be favorable to his
getting his license back. He's working out. He's been doing some
charity work. He's a changed person. He has really gotten a lot
more at peace with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   JONES GOES PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roy Jones Jr. and Lou Del Valle, who will meet at The
Theater in Madison Square Garden on July 18 in a light heavyweight
title bout, will conduct public workouts at 12:30 p.m. Thursday at
Bryant Park in Manhattan. Jones and Del Valle were once sparring
partners, but they won't be going at it against each other during
the public workout.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kelley of Flushing, Queens, will fight Derrick ``Smoke''
Gainer on the undercard. It will be the second time in a year that
Kelley, who was one of the Garden's house fighters, will get second
billing on a card at the arena. In December, Kelley fought Prince
Naseem Hamed at Madison Square Garden _ losing on a fourth-round
knockout _ but it was Hamed's American debut and HBO had spent $1
million marketing him to the public here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point where fighting at the Garden doesn't
even feel like a homecoming to me,'' Kelley said. ``I don't care.
It doesn't matter. My people will be there for me. I'm a fighter.
I'd fight this guy in a bathroom if I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, with one eye closed from too many punches, knocked out
Gainer in the eighth round in their first fight.
</P>
<P>
   AKINWANDE STILL CONTAGIOUS
</P>
<P>
   The latest blood test conducted on heavyweight Henry Akinwande
shows that he is still positive for hepatitis B, the contagious
disease that postponed his June 6 bout against Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande is awaiting another round of tests that might show he
is less contagious. That still might not be enough to persuade the
New York State Athletic Commission to give its approval for a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   The fight might be moved to Nevada, which doesn't test for
hepatitis B, but then Holyfield and his doctors would have to be
satisfied that Akinwande isn't still contagious. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
