<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES SECRET SERVICE AGENTS MUST TESTIFY IN CLINTON
INVESTIGATION  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Tuesday dealt a setback to
President Clinton and his protectors, ruling that Secret Service
agents must testify before a grand jury investigating allegations
of a presidential affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory for special counsel Kenneth Starr, the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Washington rejected the government's argument
that Secret Service agents could not be compelled to tell about the
content of private presidential conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel, in a decision that could be appealed to
the Supreme Court, ruled the Secret Service has no ``protective
privilege'' from testifying. The government had contended that
presidents would shun the protective detail _ and, therefore, risk
their lives _ if the agents could be ordered to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ... doubts about both the need for and efficacy of the
proposed privilege,'' the panel wrote in an opinion none of the
judges signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the need, the greatest danger to the president arises
when he is in public, yet the privilege presumably would have its
greatest effect when he is in the White House or in private
meetings ...
</P>
<P>
   ``As for efficacy, we suspect conscience might impel a president
to distance himself from Secret Service agents when engaging in
wrongful conduct, as might a simple desire for privacy at other
times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and Secret Service issued a joint
statement saying they were ``disappointed'' by the court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be concerned that any action that could
distance the Secret Service from the president increases the danger
to his life and that of future presidents,'' the statement said.
``We are reviewing whether to appeal and hope to have a decision
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling upheld U.S. District Court Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson's order that Secret Service agents Gary Byrne and
Brian Henderson and agency attorney John Kelleher answer questions
before a federal grand jury investigating whether Clinton engaged
in a cover-up of alleged sexual indiscretions with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the former White House intern have denied under oath
that they had sex, but Lewinsky reportedly admits to such a
relationship in phone conversations taped by co-worker Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he was ``gratified'' by the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fundamental in our country that all law-enforcement
officers cooperate fully in responding to requests for relevant
information in a federal grand jury investigation,'' he said. ``The
court of appeals today reaffirmed that bedrock principle,
emphasizing that the rule of law is not incompatible with the
profound national interest in protecting the life of the
president.``
</P>
<P>
   As part of his case, Starr wants to show that Clinton and
Lewinsky met alone at the White House, and the independent counsel
has asserted that Secret Service agents have information to support
that contention.
</P>
<P>
   Starr argued that if the Secret Service needed an exemption from
testifying in criminal cases, the agency should ask Congress to
pass a law and not seek a court ruling for which there is no
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court agreed and took the Secret Service to task for
asserting the need to protect the president's confidential
communications while refusing to require its agents to sign
confidentiality agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, a former agent who is not bound by any agreement or
rule will suffer no adverse consequences by cooperating in an
investigation of the president; second, the secretary of the
Treasury, who heads the Secret Service, has no way of knowing when
such a cooperative former agent is about to testify,'' the court
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If preventing testimony is as critical to the success of its
mission as the Secret Service now claims, it seems anomalous that
the service has no better mechanism in place to discourage former
agents from revealing confidences.''
</P>
<P>
   The three judges, all Republican appointees, are Douglas H.
Ginsburg, A. Raymond Randolph and Stephen F. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling came as Tripp returned for a third day
before Starr's grand jury. But she may soon be facing legal trouble
of her own.
</P>
<P>
   As Tripp continued her testimony for Starr, a Howard County,
Md., grand jury began to probe whether she violated state law when
she secretly recorded her conversations with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's wiretapping law prohibits people from recording
conversations without the other person's knowledge. However,
prosecutors must show that the person doing the taping showed a
reckless disregard for or intended to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   This might allow Tripp to avoid culpability by showing she did
not know she was violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp called Maryland State Prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli's
convening of the grand jury ``the latest in a series of attempts to
intimidate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying she is ``not intimidated in any way,'' Tripp pledged to
``continue to testify truthfully and completely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
