<HEADLINE>
SLIDE IN OIL AND INTERNET SHARES HELPS STALL SUMMER RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A summer rally stalled Tuesday as concerns about
stock valuations caused investors to sell shares that had strong
gains in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Recent high-flying Internet shares and oil producers, weakened
by falling crude oil prices, were at the center of the declines.
After climbing as much as 59 points, the Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 6.73 points, to 9,085.04, with Chevron among
the average's leading decliners. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index fell 2.67 points, to 1,154.66, and the Nasdaq composite index
slipped 1.36 points, to 1,908.11.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was weighed down by sizable declines
in several Internet-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, which soared 20 1/2 on Monday after the company announced
plans for a 2-for-1 stock split, plunged 14 9/16 Tuesday, to 85.
The stock had more than tripled this year, to 99 9/16 on Monday
from a low of 33 1/8 on Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet shares, including America Online, Yahoo,
Doubleclick and Earthlink, fell sharply. The shares had been rising
recently on speculation about potential acquisitions or
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the Internet bookseller, fell 17 3/8, to 122 1/8.
Still, the stock has risen more than 300 percent this year. As a
result of such lofty gains, said Charles Pradilla, chief investment
strategist at Cowen &AMP; Co., Amazon and other Internet shares were
poised to fall as investors expressed skepticism about whether the
stocks had become too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very nervous about it,'' Pradilla said about the gains.
``Some of these companies are two years away from making money.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were some notable gains Tuesday. Merrill Lynch rose 3
5/16, to 104 5/16, a 52-week high. The shares moved higher amid
speculation that the company would split its stock, which would
allow more individual investors to buy shares. Merrill officials
declined to comment. Merrill last split its stock on May 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric rose 3/4, to 92 5/8 _ a new high _ as it became
the first American company with a market capitalization of more
than $300 billion. Its market capitalization, or the value of its
outstanding shares multiplied by its stock price, stood at $301.7
billion at the end of trading Tuesday. So far this year, GE shares
have gained more than 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such gains underscored the belief of some analysts that
Tuesday's declines would be short-lived and that the summer rally
would soon resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the summer rally is over yet,'' Pradilla said.
His confidence is grounded in the current low interest rates and
expectations that corporations will report strong second-quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   James Griffin, senior vice president in charge of investment
strategy at Aeltus Investment Management, said, ``We're in a moment
of everything going right, and the real risks to this balance are
everything overseas'' in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, think American companies may have
already felt the worst sting from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the third quarter will be an important psychological
turning point,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Beginning in August and September,
people will start to value stocks based on 1999 earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   And by September, the effect of economic measures enacted by the
Japanese government earlier this year should be apparent, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the third quarter, we should have more answers than
questions,'' Galvin said, ``and if investors just think that we've
started to hit a bottom, that's all we need to improve. Uncertainty
is usually the worst side of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, shares of large domestic banks fell sharply during
the fourth quarter of 1997 because of their exposure to Asia. That
drag on profits should not happen again this year, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
