<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DEATH OF NIGERIAN LEADER MAY EXACERBATE CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the abrupt death Tuesday of Nigeria's most prominent
civilian politician, Moshood K.O. Abiola, Nigeria has suddenly lost
in the space of only one month the two leaders whose rivalry has
locked this country in a costly four-year stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   When Abiola's one-time friend and, more recently, jailer and
tormentor, President Sani Abacha, died last month, many Nigerians
were relieved, saying that finally, with the steel-fisted dictator
gone, political life could at last move forward.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition wanted Abiola proclaimed the rightful president
because he was clearly winning the 1993 elections before the
military annulled them. But the seemingly more moderate generals
who succeeded Abacha balked at the idea of Abiola as president.
Instead, the new government and, Nigerian opposition figures say,
some Western diplomats appeared set on persuading Abiola that he
had no claim on the presidency and should gracefully fade from the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   At one level Abiola's death, apparently after a heart attack,
would seem to settle the issue neatly.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country where few events _ especially sudden deaths _
rest on their readiest interpretations, where ethnic and regional
divisions remain immense and where the military's history of
dominating politics is so complete, Abiola's surprising end is only
likely to further complicate matters, at least in the turbulent
short term.
</P>
<P>
   There is already considerable resentment in Nigeria about what
is seen as a failure on the part of Western powers to demand that
the military turn over government to civilian democratic rule. Add
to this Abiola's death, and the main result is a potentially
explosive situation in which everyone distrusts everyone else,
including the outside brokers who come to help ease the country
forward.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance the outsider is the U.N. secretary-general,
Kofi Annan, who came to Nigeria last week and announced after a
meeting with Abiola that the politician wanted to ``get on with his
life'' and would no longer insist on claiming the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's family and close supporters immediately disputed these
statements and asked bitterly why the jailed politician had not
been allowed to speak to the nation directly, or even meet with his
own advisers?
</P>
<P>
   Annan's visit was followed on Tuesday of last week by that of
Thomas Pickering, the U.S. undersecretary of state for political
affairs and a former ambassador to Nigeria, who met with Nigeria's
new leader, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, and was with Abiola when he
became ill.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in Pickering's delegation said they had come to
Nigeria to insist on the release of all political prisoners, a
return to civilian rule and an early date for new elections.
Conspicuously absent, however, was any demand for a formal
political role for Abiola, the presumed winner of what have been
widely called the country's most democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   In comments not intended for attribution, Western diplomats have
told journalists that Abiola's 1993 election can no longer be
considered valid, and it is widely assumed that they, like Annan,
were seeking to ease Abiola from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of these missions was good in theory if they were
aimed at pressuring the government to release Abiola and the other
prisoners and get on with elections,'' said Walter Carrington, a
recent U.S. ambassador to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``But starting with Annan's statements about renouncing a claim
to the presidency, any effort to get Abiola to relinquish his
mandate was very wrong. We should have insisted on his
unconditional release and that he be allowed to meet with his
supporters and not be forced to make agreements under duress.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its source is hard to pinpoint, Western ambivalence
toward Abiola is longstanding. After the 1993 elections were
annulled, Washington and London protested for a time, but then
stopped short of seeking validation for the results.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Western diplomats routinely urged the government to
release Abiola on humanitarian grounds, but never dwelled on his
presumed mandate or political legitimacy. The reasons for this
ambivalence, always invoked off the record, ranged from his
supposedly mercurial character to the demands he made for Western
reparations for the African slave trade, to his supposed contacts
with Nigerian drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his shady business dealings with military leaders,
including Abacha himself, and high-level involvement in the heavily
corrupt civilian politics of the 1980s, Abiola's more recent
democratic credentials were as solid as they come in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian government officials and Western diplomats alike
acknowledge that in the 1993 race, Abiola, a millionaire
businessman, was winning in every region of this traditionally
polarized country. This included leading his rival, Bashir Tofa, in
his heavily Muslim native city, Kano, in the far north.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's acceptance outside his native southwest was helped by
his conversion to Islam long ago, and a history of deep-pocket
philanthropy that spread to every region.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian reaction to Abiola's death, and to the latest
diplomacy, has been swift and powerfully bitter, particularly in
the southwest, where his Yoruba ethnic group _ one of the nation's
three largest _ deeply resents what it sees as yet another chapter
in its deliberate exclusion from power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in Nigeria will believe that M.K.O. Abiola renounced
the presidency,'' said Gani Fawehinmi, leader of the Joint Action
Committee of Nigeria, a major umbrella group of anti-military
opposition forces. ``What people will rather believe is that all of
the pressure being placed on him killed Abiola. But those who
wanted to be rid of Abiola will soon wish that he was back.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with reports of scattered unrest spreading through Lagos
and other parts of the Yoruba southwest, the liability of not
having Abiola around as a calming factor is already apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief Abiola was the closest thing this nation had to a
leader,'' said Emanuel Ibru, a member of the opposition alliance
Nadeco. ``We are not just in shock and mourning; we are leaderless
now, and that is a very dangerous thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
