</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BONDS-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO UNVEIL NEW TYPE OF INFLATION-ADJUSTED SAVINGS BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration plans to unveil
Wednesday a new type of government savings bond whose return will
rise and fall with inflation, to protect investors' gains as well
as to help finance the federal debt, Clinton administration
officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds will be sold in eight denominations, ranging from $50
to $10,000, and will mature in 30 years. Most of the denominations,
which bear the likenesses of Helen Keller, the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr., Albert Einstein, and others, are to go on sale in
September. Two more denominations _ $200 and $10,000 _ will go on
sale next May.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the new securities, Vice President Al Gore plans
to promote them as offering an attractive means for middle-income
people to prepare for their retirements or a child's education.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the bonds as ``inflation insurance,'' a senior
Treasury official said on Tuesday that he expected them ``to be
attractive for people who want to be able to guarantee that they're
earning a substantial inflation-adjusted return on their money,
that'll double their money in real terms in less than a
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares for the presidential race in 2000, Gore is trying
to burnish his economic credentials, one White House official said,
and the administration's decision to have him rather than President
Clinton present the new bonds is part of that effort. Gore will
make the announcement at the Treasury Department with Secretary
Robert Rubin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In January 1997, the Treasury Department introduced its first
so-called inflation-indexed bonds, which were generally intended
for large institutional investors. Until then, the federal
government had financed the national debt by relying on fixed-rate
securities, which have a set, unchanging interest rate. Such bonds,
whose returns can be eroded or wiped out by inflation, have not
been a popular option compared to stocks or corporate bonds or
401(k) plans and other forms of long-term savings.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration hopes that the new, inflation-indexed
bonds _ or ``I-Bonds,'' as officials are calling them _ will appeal
to small investors. ``They're meant for and designed for small
investors,'' one official said. ``We think this is important to
avail small investors of the same benefits of inflation protection
that larger investors have.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other inflation-adjusted bonds _ but like other savings
bonds _ the new securities offer special tax benefits. As long as
investors hold their bonds, they may defer paying taxes on their
earnings, which are automatically reinvested and added to the
principal. Like other bonds issued by the Treasury, the new ones
are exempt from state and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The tax protection ``would be a very nice feature for someone
who is, say, several years from retirement and in a high income
bracket, who wants to protect his portfolio from inflation but
without generating higher income,'' said Dan Pederson, president of
The Savings Bond Informer, Inc., a Detroit-based information
service provider for investors.
</P>
<P>
   If the bond is redeemed before its 30-year maturity to pay for
college tuition or other fees, investors may exclude part or all of
the interest from their income in calculating their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The average American is far more likely to hold savings bonds
than Treasury bonds: Roughly 55 million Americans, or approximately
1 in 3 households, own savings bonds, according to Pederson. In
all, investors hold about $180 billion in savings bonds, according
to the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' earnings from the new bonds will be determined by two
rates: a rate set by the Treasury Department that will remain the
same for the life of the bond; and a rate of inflation determined
every six months by the Bureau of Labor Statistics to reflect
changes in a version of the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The new bonds are expected to be offered at a rate between 3
percent and 3.5 percent, less than the rate carried by fixed-rate
securities that offer no inflation protection.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the bonds will have some protection if deflation
sets in. Any decline in the consumer price index could eat into the
fixed rate, but it would not touch the underlying principal,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has given two major speeches recently on the economy, one
this spring before the Economic Club of Detroit and one last month
before the Center for National Policy in Washington. White House
aides said that the Wednesday announcement was intended to further
remind voters of his role in the administration's economic policy.
``The whole idea is to start building his profile more and more on
the economy, for obvious reasons,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also stepped up his partisan commentary on economic
matters. His speech before the Center for National Policy amounted
to a sharp critique of Republican economic policies. He accused the
Republican Congress of threatening ``to unravel our fiscal
discipline _ even at the risk of raising interest rates, shattering
confidence in our economy, and squandering the resources we need to
finally close the generational deficit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
