<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOCH-COX     07-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expansion of Georgia nature areas at issue in Gingrich bill
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The future of two of Georgia's crown jewels _ the
Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area and the Cumberland
Island National Seashore _ could be significantly affected by two
new bills in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists are hailing a proposal by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich to expand the Chattahoochee recreation area as the first
big step toward a 48-mile-long greenway along the river between
Lake Lanier and Peachtree Creek.
</P>
<P>
   But they contend a measure introduced by Rep. Jack Kingston, a
Savannah Republican, would weaken protection of Cumberland Island.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the Gingrich bill is scheduled for July 16 in
Washington. Kingston hopes a hearing on his bill by the end of the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's measure would allow the park to include up to 10,000
acres, with the idea of creating a continuous 2,000-foot-wide
greenway along each side of the river. Currently, the park, which
attracts more than 3.5 million visitors per year, can be no bigger
than 6,800 acres, specified by legislation that created it 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation also has left the park divided into 14 units,
each separated by private property. A continuous greenway along the
river would join those units and other publicly owned areas along
the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision is that a person could walk or jog along 48 miles
of the river, from Buford Dam to Peachtree Creek,'' says Suzanne
Lewis, superintendent of the Chattahoochee recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens depends on the availability of funds and
whether private landowners are willing to sell their property to
the National Park Service, which manages the recreation area.
Gingrich's bill specifies that no private acreage will be condemned
for the park.
</P>
<P>
   But a lack of funds and the unwillingness of some landowners to
sell their property already have hampered the agency's ability to
acquire all of the 6,800 acres originally authorized by Congress
for the park, which now contains only about 4,500 acres. Some of
the land originally authorized has been lost to development,
especially areas along Holcomb Bridge Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several neighborhoods that are now in the recreation
area boundaries, but we certainly are not going to condemn
neighborhoods for park land,'' says Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's has estimated that the cost of acquiring the greenway
land is about $65 million. His bill calls for the federal
government to provide $25 million; the rest would come from state
and local governments, private foundations, corporations and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   A public-private partnership acquired much of the 4,500 acres
that now make up the recreation area. For instance, the Trust for
Public Land, a conservation organization, helped negotiate
protection of 10 properties along the Chattahoochee, including the
Powers Homestead and Hyde Farm in Cobb County, and five properties
to complete three miles of river frontage along Bowman's Island in
Gwinnett and Forsyth counties.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich acknowledges that the TPL will play a major role in
acquiring the greenway land. ``We're looking at tracts up and down
the river,'' says TPL director Rand Wentworth.
</P>
<P>
   On Georgia's coast, the Cumberland Island National Seashore,
known for its haunting beauty and as the site of John F. Kennedy
Jr.'s wedding, is the subject of a new bill that has drawn intense
fire from environmentalists. Critics say Kingston's measure would
wreck efforts by the Nature Conservancy of Georgia to acquire the
privately owned 1,100-acre Greyfield tract and make it part of the
national seashore.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Authorize federal funds to restore historic buildings on the
island, including the 22,000-square-foot Plum Orchard Mansion built
in 1898 by the Carnegie family. Plum Orchard and the main road
through the 18-mile-long island would be removed from wilderness
designation, allowing vehicles in portions of the island now
off-limits to cars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Authorize a land-swap deal championed by Kingston, in which
the heirs of Coca-Cola founder Asa Candler would purchase the
Greyfield tract that splits the national seashore boundaries and
give it to the national seashore. In return, the Candler family
would reclaim another tract of roughly 1,000 acres on the north tip
of the island that the family owned until 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to develop a consensus,'' Kingston says. ``People
are going to have to recognize there'll be things in (his bill)
they like and things they don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
