<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORY FOR OFT-OVERLOOKED BRAZILIAN GOALKEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ In Brazil, the common wisdom goes, the
goalkeepers are the players who were not blessed with dancing feet.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian goalkeepers have their moments, however, and Claudio
Andre Mergen Taffarel, known to all the soccer world as Taffarel,
had his moment Tuesday night, stopping two of four penalty kicks to
help Brazil win a tiebreaker over the Netherlands, after the two
had battled to a 1-1 tie in the semifinal of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil will now go on to play the winner of Wednesday night's
France-Croatia match in the final on Sunday in St. Denis. The
Brazilians won their fourth World Cup in 1994 when Taffarel stopped
Italy after a dispassionate 0-0 tie in the mid-afternoon California
heat, a brutal game time dictated by European television.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's game, played under a near full moon with a
breeze cooling a heat wave, was far superior to the 1994 finale.
This was a run-and-shoot battle between the world's great soccer
dynasty and the nation that is proud to be called The Brazil of
Europe, strong praise for a nation that has never won a World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo scored early in the second half on a quick strike, and
the Netherlands bravely held on, staging a gallant goal in the 87th
minute on a header by Patrick Kluivert, the third time the Dutch
had scored late in their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   If the crowd at Stade Velodrome had been given a vote, it would
surely have pleaded for the two teams to continue playing after the
120 minutes. Instead, it was time for the shootout in the world's
only major sport with a dice-rolling way of ending a tie. Ronaldo
shot past Erwin Van Der Sar, the towering 6-foot-6 Dutch
goalkeeper. Then Frank DeBoer, the resolute Dutch captain who spent
the night marking Ronaldo, scored past Taffarel.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo made his penalty cleanly and Dennis Bergkamp, barely
noticeable all night, made his. Emerson, a late substitute, made
Brazil's third penalty. Then Philip Cocu, the offensive-minded
midfielder, took his turn. Taffarel did a little dance in place,
then dived to his left and punched the ball away with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga, with his military-style flat-top cut, made his penalty.
Ronald DeBoer, the twin brother of the Dutch captain, was next.
Taffarel did his little dance, then dove to his right and smothered
a low kick and came up brandishing his two index fingers and baying
at the full moon.
</P>
<P>
   The game was over, although the Dutch players stayed around in
the orange shirts. Many of them play with the Brazilians in the
Italian and Spanish leagues, and there was considerable embracing
and kind words. This was the third game of this World Cup to be
decided on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very organized, very aware, they made good rushes,''
Mario Zagallo, the Argentine coach, said, complimenting the
Netherlands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were more than enough thrills for both sides, each of
which played without a starting defender because of an accumulation
of yellow cards. In addition, the top Dutch replacement was out
with a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players who replaced them did a good job,'' said Gus
Hiddink, the Dutch coach. ``We must not search for excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses were needed. The two teams traded feints in the first
half, with long runs and expert passes.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after halftime, Brazil scored. Rivaldo slipped a
ball through to Ronaldo, who rushed the goal with Cocu grabbing at
his shirt, but Ronaldo put the ball under Van Der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   In the 62nd minute, Ronaldo burst through and hit the goalkeeper
in the head with his lower leg. The keeper sat on the ground for
several minutes before the game resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil picked up the tempo when Zagallo sent in Denilson for
Bebeto, a highly popular move with Brazilian fans. The Brazilians
suddenly seemed to have an extra attacker. In the 78th minute,
Rivaldo fed Denilson, who returned the ball to Rivaldo, who was
stopped by Van Der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Kluivert used his height to send several headers at
Taffarel. But the Dutch were still scoreless at the 87th minute,
when Cocu send a ball down the right sideline. The whole stadium
swiveled to watch Ronald DeBoer make what might have been the last
Dutch strike.
</P>
<P>
   DeBoer made the most of it, with a hard, twisting kick that came
down in the goal area, where Kluivert connected with his head,
putting the ball to the left of Taffarel and tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   In the first overtime, the two teams traded chances. In the
second overtime, Frank DeBoer took down Ronaldo in the penalty box,
a move that would have been worth a red card for most of this
tournament, but the official, Ali Mohamed Bujsaim of the United
Arab Emirates, let it go. The teams still were going at it when the
final whistle set up the lottery of the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I selected my players carefully,'' Zagallo said. ``I wanted to
show confidence in my players.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach was asked if this was an individual victory because
Taffarel stopped two penalties. He said, ``No, this is a victory
for everybody. We're here to represent Brazil. Every player
contributed to this victory. All over the world, Brazilian fans are
celebrating. We have to wait, because we only celebrate after the
championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil can talk about championship games. The Dutch can only
talk about playing exciting soccer, and falling short, once again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
