<HEADLINE>
TWO BORDER PATROL AGENTS SHOT DEAD IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Complete writethru _ adds death of suspect, info on search
for others.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER and JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ Two U.S. Border Patrol agents were ambushed
and killed early Tuesday while helping local authorities
investigate a fatal shooting near this South Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspect came out of the cornfield and literally ambushed
my agents. All indications are they never had a chance to use their
guns,'' said Joe Garza, the Border Patrol chief in McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   The dead agents were identified as Ricardo Guillermo Salinas,
24, of San Antonio, who graduated from the Border Patrol Academy in
January, and Susan L. Rodriguez, 28, of Harlingen, daughter of a
retired Border Patrol deputy chief.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rodriguez, who was a training officer, nor Salinas, who
was nearing the end of his probationary period, had drawn a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The man detained in connection with the deaths of the two agents
and of two women in Rio Hondo died in a Harlingen hospital late
Tuesday following surgery for multiple gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials identified him as Ernest Moore, 24, of San
Benito.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known who shot Moore or under what circumstances. It
also was not clear whether Moore acted alone, but hundreds of law
enforcement officers continued to search for at least one more
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``These killers will be found,'' said Doris Meissner,
commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, which
oversees the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deaths of these fine young people cannot go unpunished. We
will do everything in our power to see that the person or persons
responsible for this tragedy are swiftly brought to justice,'' said
Meissner, who flew to Texas after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The two civilians killed in Rio Hondo, a small community
northeast of Harlingen, were identified as Dalia Morin, 31, and her
mother, Margarita Flores, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Sheriff's Deputy Raul Rodriguez and Dan Morin,
22, were wounded in Rio Hondo. They were being treated at Valley
Baptist Medical Center for gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the bloody sequence of events began shortly
after 5 a.m. when Dalia and Dan Morin and Flores were shot at a
house in Rio Hondo.
</P>
<P>
   The police responded and put out an alert for a white pickup
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez spotted the truck, gave chase, lost it and radioed for
assistance. Rodriguez and three Border Patrol agents later found
the truck outside Moore's home south of San Benito.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio, the four were
about to search the adjacent area when they were attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped out of the cornfield and cut them down,'' Lucio
said of the suspected gunman.
</P>
<P>
   The third Border Patrol agent involved had not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first killing of a Border Patrol agent in Texas since
1996. Rodriguez was the first woman agent killed on active duty.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said authorities were looking for one or two additional
people who were spotted with Moore after the Rio Hondo shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to mention any suspects yet because we want to
make sure we have an airtight case,'' the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Lopez, 15, who lives near the Moore residence, awoke to
the sound of gunshots Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real rapid. It was like it wouldn't stop,'' said Lopez,
who said a steady stream of police cars, followed by aircraft,
responded to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Gonzalez, chief of the four-man Rio Hondo Police
Department, said the victims of the shooting apparently did not
know their assailant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he is an ex-boyfriend of one of the people staying
at the residence. She may have been a guest of theirs, but at this
time we cannot confirm she was there,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a motive for the shooting remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interviewing witnesses, but they are hysterical. The
only thing we know for certain is that the alleged assailant gained
entrance to the residence, and the victims were shot in the
hallway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Hondo is a quiet rural community of about 2,000. Gonzalez
said the killings were the first in his seven years on the police
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had an incident like this, and the community is
beside itself. They can't believe it actually happened here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson Barr, 33, assigned to Eagle Pass, was the last Border
Patrol agent killed in Texas. Barr was shot to death while
attempting to apprehend drug smugglers in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent agent killed before the Tuesday shootings was
Alexander Kirpnick, who was shot to death June 3 near Nogales,
Ariz., while investigating drug smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-one agents have died in the 77-year history of the Border
Patrol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
