<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOVELTIES-DANCE-$ADV1     07-07 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVELTIES-DANCE-$ADV12-700&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A PAGE FROM EACH OTHER'S PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Sol Hurok, an impresario with a keen eye on the box
office, who grasped the ballet public's hunger for what he insisted
on calling novelties. These were new productions, mainly premieres
but also revivals of works so rarely seen that they took on the
aura of a premiere. A prime example was Hurok's historic
presentation of a full-length ``Sleeping Beauty'' when the Sadler's
Wells Ballet made its New York debut in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   During their recent seasons, American Ballet Theater and New
York City Ballet each offered the same two kinds of novelties. Both
commissioned a new work and presented an unusual revival,
transferred from another company.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Martins, City Ballet's artistic director, choreographed
``River of Light,'' named after the score that Charles Wuorinen
wrote for him. Ballet Theater's original work was ``The Snow
Maiden,'' co-produced with Houston Ballet and choreographed by Ben
Stevenson, Houston's artistic director. The first performance in
both Houston and New York was led by the same ballerina in the
title role, Nina Ananiashvili.
</P>
<P>
   City Ballet's company premiere was ``Les Noces,'' Jerome
Robbins' treatment of Stravinsky's score, first done in 1965 for
Ballet Theater. This season, that troupe adapted ``Le Corsaire''
from a 1997 Boston Ballet production. The Boston staging was the
first American version of Marius Petipa's 1899 full-length classic,
itself redone by Soviet choreographers, including Konstantin
Sergeyev. It was his 1992 staging for the Bolshoi Ballet (tightened
and with some set pieces moved around) that was on view in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   This pairing of a genuine premiere and a work new to a company
made for variety and historical texture, especially at City Ballet,
where the emphasis is on original ballets. ``Le Corsaire'' was the
season's mega-hit, thanks to its powerhouse male dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Novelties may seem a paradox in an art form that is defined by
repertory, an established body of works. Yet even dancers and
audiences loyal to the ballets that initially attracted them can
tire of their repetition. Incidentally, ballet owes its repertory
to creativity. Old works were once new.
</P>
<P>
   As things turn out, the City Ballet premiere, ``River of Light''
is one of Martins' best pieces, exceptional in its extension of the
classical vocabulary. Wuorinen and Martins are on the same wave
length. Danciness, supported by a sustained melodic phrase, is too
sentimental for them, but emotion and drama are not absent from the
entangled complexities of their fusion of sound and movement.
``River of Light'' evokes tension but also resolution. There is
even a ritualized cast to the action onstage for three couples who
end up with new partners.
</P>
<P>
   On a formal level, Martins is concerned with variations on the
ballet adagio. His images are angular and sculptural, succinctly
inverting conventional shapes but not the academic steps that
define his choreography as neo-classical. Each couple is identified
by the color of its leotards: black for Monique Meunier and Jock
Soto, white for Alexandra Ansanelli and Charles Askegard, red for
Darci Kistler and Sebastien Marcovici.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stanley's effective if unsubtle lighting amplifies the
visual impact. Rectangles and pools of light confine the space, but
V-shaped beams on the backdrop intensify the dancing toward the
end. When the couples pair up with different partners, the drama
stems not from the implied wife-swapping but from formal structure.
Will the different partnerships create a new context and modify our
initial view of the dancers?
</P>
<P>
   Each soloist does in fact react differently to the second
partner. Ms. Meunier, a splendid allegro dancer, finally has an
adagio role that suits her. There is a striking image in which she
and Soto seem to be holding onto each other while pulling apart.
Ms. Ansanelli and Askegard, both stretching the linear into the
angular, are less disputatious, while Ms. Kistler, swooning in
Marcovici's arms, telegraphs passion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the second half, the pairing of Ms. Meunier and Askegard
(black and white leotards) is built on contrast and contortions.
Ms. Ansanelli and Marcovici (white and red) fit their angular
bodies into a jigsaw puzzle. Ms. Kistler and Soto (red and black)
have the hot number. Soto is more dominant than in his duet with
Ms. Meunier, and he covers Ms. Kistler's eyes with her own hands
before maneuvering her into tilts and lifts. The sound of chimes
ushers in the final image: revolving men holding the women
overhead, an eternal round of human passions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ansanelli contributed her star presence as the bride in the
Russian peasant wedding of ``Les Noces.'' Like Robert Wersinger,
the groom , she captured the submissiveness and exultation that
Robbins infuses into his interpretation of the Stravinsky score.
Bronislava Nijinska, who choreographed the original version, in
1923, saw things differently and made her characters anonymous and
abstract. The Robbins women are in laced shoes while Nijinska's
were on toe, which did not prevent the critic Andre Levinson, a
staunch defender of classicism, from calling her choreography
mechanistic. George Balanchine agreed with him later that
Stravinsky's score was a cantata, meant to be heard and not danced.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Stravinsky wrote a ballet score and Robbins'
theatricality might be as effective as it still was in the 1970s if
he dropped his current use of a recording and went back to his
initial staging. To see four grand pianos, a chorus and dancers
before the two huge saints on Oliver Smith's backdrop was to see no
ordinary spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacle, one suspects, was the word that Kevin McKenzie,
Ballet Theater's artistic director, keeps in mind in his search for
three-act ballets to fill the Metropolitan Opera House. As a
premiere, ``The Snow Maiden'' fit the bill but only up to a point.
The story, drawn from various Russian sources, of a snow fairy who
melts under the sun for love of a mortal, is a perfect vehicle for
ballerinas like Ms. Ananiashvili and Susan Jaffe. Desmond Heeley's
sets and costumes are beautiful, and Stevenson's choreography for
the principals has some rich intricacies. But ours is not a
Romantic era, and an ersatz Romantic ballet can look pretty rather
than deep. A two-act version would work better, especially since
the Tchaikovsky pieces that John Lanchbery has stitched into a
ballet score fail to offer consistent dance support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Corsaire'' was more of a risk, a hodgepodge production
viable only if its interpolations from various composers and
choreographers over a century were rendered coherent. Inconsistent
technique in some casts reduced the ballet to an amusing adventure
yarn about a pirate rescuing his beloved from assorted villains.
But on the whole, it was a gamble fabulously won. Anyone who saw
the astonishing bravura of Angel Corella, Ethan Stiefel, Jose
Manuel Carreno, Parrish Maynard, Vladimir Malakhov, Giuseppe Picone
and John Selya as well as the exquisite Petipa fragment for three
very classical Odalisques in powder-blue tutus will not forget
these performances. The most spectacular dancing in the world was
on view here; now,  &UR; that &LR;  was ballet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
