<HEADLINE>
30 NON-STARS INVITED TO USA BASKETBALL TROUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not Grant Hill or Tim Duncan. It's more like Otis Hill and
Earl Duncan. That's what happens when you have to redo things at
the 11th hour.
</P>
<P>
   USA Basketball Tuesday released a list of 30 players who have
accepted invitations to this week's tryout camp to select a team
for the upcoming world championships. Suffice it to say, this may
well be the worst assemblage of talent for a USA Basketball men's
team since, well, Acie Earl missed free throws shooting alone.
</P>
<P>
   Whoops. Acie Earl is one of the 30. How do you say zone
qualifier in Spanish?
</P>
<P>
   This is the team that was put together on short notice after the
12 NBA players were replaced last month for refusing to
unequivocally commit pending the imposition of a lockout by the
league. While USA Basketball is not a part of the NBA, the players
felt they would be advertising and marketing commodities for the
league and decided not to go. The league, of course, locked out the
players two weeks after USA Basketball dis-invited the NBA
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several ``marquee'' players without a current NBA
affiliation, such as Clyde Drexler, Dominique Wilkins, and Byron
Scott, were thought to be under consideration. Wilkins told the
Globe last week that while flattered to be considered, he could not
``betray'' the NBA players by participating.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the replacement team. Of the 30 candidates, 24 played
in the CBA or Europe last season, four are college underclassmen,
and two have just completed their college eligibility. Earl is one
of three players who have donned a Celtics uniform; the others are
point guard Michael Hawkins and shooting guard Jimmy Oliver. Many
have some NBA experience and they range in age from 34 (Wendell
Alexis, Tim Kempton) to 20 (UConn's Richard Hamilton).
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich of the Rockets, who is coaching the team with
help from Del Harris, Lon Kruger (Illinois), and Mike Jarvis (St.
John's), said in a statement from USA Basketball that ``we feel
confident that out of this group, we can and will field a very
competitive team. There's limited training time, but we will try
and give these players a real good look.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have spent some time in the NBA include Earl,
Kempton, David Wood (involved in a Dennis Rodman trade), Larry
Stewart, Oliver, Randy Livingston (Boston Shootout star), Jimmy
King, Hawkins, Tim Breaux, and Ashraf Amaya. Wood, Livingston, and
Breaux have all played for Tomjanovich. The four collegians are
Hamilton, Duke's Trajan Langdon, Northwestern's Evan Eschmeyer, and
Mateen Cleaves from Michigan State. The two who just completed
school are Earl Boykins of Eastern Michigan and Brad Miller of
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the team to train in Chicago through July 14 and
then a 12-man group will head to Europe. While in Europe, the team
will train in Monte Carlo and Rome and play exhibition games
against France, Spain, and Italy. The world championships will be
held July 29-Aug. 9 in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The team must win the gold medal in the championships to gain an
automatic bye in the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney. Short of that,
the US must qualify for the Games in a pre-Olympic tournament,
probably in Central or South America, either in 1999 or 2000.
Normally, the top four finishers qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA players originally selected to participate were Vin
Baker, Gary Payton, Chris Webber, Tim Hardaway, Tim Duncan, Grant
Hill, Allan Houston, Glen Rice, Terrell Brandon, Christian
Laettner, Kevin Garnett, and Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
