<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MD-GOLDSTEIN-FUNERAL-     07-07 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-GOLDSTEIN-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND MOURNS A POLITICAL FIXTURE AS RACE TO SUCCEED HIM HEATS
UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCE FREDERICK, Md. _ If only for a moment Tuesday, the tumult
of Maryland state politics this year was calmed.
</P>
<P>
   More than a thousand friends, relatives and colleagues of all
political persuasion traveled deep into southern Maryland on
Tuesday, to pay their last respects to Louis Goldstein, Maryland's
comptroller for the last 40 years. He died of a heart attack at his
home here Friday at the age of 85.
</P>
<P>
   At an hourlong funeral service at the Trinity United Methodist
Church here, they listened as Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., told them
what most already felt, that Goldstein, a fellow Democrat,
''ennobled our politics and enriched our lives. We shall miss him
dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, the void left by Goldstein's death was filled
rapidly. When he announced last month that he intended to seek an
11th term as the state's tax collector, just one Republican stepped
up to challenge him, and few politicians of either party gave him
much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But by the filing deadline Monday, 7 Republicans and 12
Democrats _ including former Gov. William Donald Schaefer _ had
decided to run for comptroller in the September primary. The list
also included Michael Barnes, a former congressman who was
appointed earlier in the day by Gov. Parris Glendening to serve out
the remaining six months of Goldstein's term.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein was the closest thing to a sure bet in Maryland
politics. He was victorious in 14 of 15 elections, dating back to
his years as a state legislator _ his only loss came in the 1964
primary for the U.S. Senate. The virtual certainty that he would
have won again this year gave state Democrats one of their few
sources of electoral tranquility. The year has been otherwise
marked by rancor and divided loyalties, leaving Glendening as one
of the few incumbent governors vulnerable to a strong challenge
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening faces a determined run in the primary by Harford
County Executive Eileen Rehrmann, who has the support of two
influential politicians, Mayor Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke and
Prince George's County Executive Wayne Curry.
</P>
<P>
   If Glendening prevails, he faces a probable rematch in the
general election with Ellen Sauerbrey, a Republican who lost to him
by fewer than 6,000 votes in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sauerbrey, a former state legislator, was the only major
state politician who did not attend Goldstein's funeral, which
attracted a virtual who's who of Maryland officials, including
three of Glendening's predecessors _ Schaefer, Harry Hughes and
Marvin Mandel. Jim Dornan, a spokesman for Ms. Sauerbrey, said she
was attending a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Sauerbrey missed was an endearing sendoff for a public
servant whose style and stripe has largely disappeared from the
American political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an old breed of politician, who brought Republicans and
Democrats together,'' said Thomas Miller, a Democrat who serves as
president of the Maryland Senate. ``Now, you find a minority of
people trust in government, but he was from the old school, someone
who believed that government service was public service. He
believed it was a noble calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Republican Party chairman Joyce Terhes, who lives not
far from Goldstein's home, said that his friendship always
transcended politics. She called him ''a wonderfully good
politician'' but also a family friend who always honored their
political differences by assuring her, ``I go to bed every night
with a Republican,'' referring to his wife, Hazel, who died in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Before, during and after the service, stories of Goldstein's
unflagging energy filled the air. Mandel recalled joining him on a
campaign stop at a Chestertown, Md., department store, where
employees lined up to greet them. Goldstein shook every hand
extended, Mandel said, but grew concerned when one that did not
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was shaking hands with a mannequin,'' Mandel said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Sarbanes recalled the time when Goldstein
climbed a utility pole to greet a telephone company lineman and
another when he drove along a rural lane waving at an apparently
empty barn ''just in case someone was inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendening, who called Goldstein's death ``clearly, the end of
an age,'' said he always found it ironic that Goldstein was ``a tax
collector who was beloved'' by the state's taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   That was clearly evident by the size of the audience, 300 who
filled the church and more than three times that number who sat on
folding chairs outside of it, listening to the service over loud
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   If one sentiment seemed to unite them it was spoken by Perry
Bowen, a former judge and old friend of Goldstein's, who followed
Sarbanes to the altar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only going to miss him once,'' Bowen said. ``That's
always.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
