<SLUG> BC-SUPREMACIST-PARADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREMACIST SAYS LEGAL FEES NEARING $150,000 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Miss.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leader of a Mississippi-based white supremacist
organization, which won a court ruling invalidating the Boston
ordinance that regulates parade permits, said his legal fees in the
case may reach $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge George A. O'Toole has ordered Boston to pay
the fees of Richard Barrett's group known as the Nationalist
Movement. O'Toole ruled city officials illegally denied the group a
permit to march in South Boston in 1994, because they disagreed
with the group's ideas. The judge will eventually decide if the
fees sought by Barrett are reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole also awarded Barrett $700 in extra travel expenses he
incurred fighting for the permit .
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my only wish that (Mayor Thomas M.) Menino would have to
pay it out of his own pocket,'' said Barrett, who is general
counsel of his group. ``He was a shill for the homosexual and
minority lobby. It is not right to run to roughshod over the rights
of everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the mayor declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boston civil rights lawyer, Harvey A. Schwartz, who represented
the Nationalist Movement in the suit, could not be reached for
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said his group has won 13 other similar First Amendment
suits throughout the county and lost only one -- in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Several people have asked him to move to South Boston, Barrett
said last night, adding ``I might consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   In striking down the ordinance, O'Toole said it illegally gave
city officials wide discretion to grant or deny permits without any
limiting standards.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole said the reasons the city offered for denying Barrett a
permit _ traffic congestion and concerns about public safety _ were
pretexts. He noted the city had granted permits to other groups
under similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett came to Boston in 1994 after organizers of the South
Boston St Patrick's Day Parade canceled it rather than comply with
a court order requiring them to allow a gay and lesbian group to
march.
</P>
<P>
   Without a permit Barrett went ahead and marched along the
sidewalk on Broadway ending with a rally in front of South Boston
High School. Police kept a large crowd of counter demonstrators
away from the marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week O'Toole entered a permanent injunction prohibiting the
city from enforcing the parade permit ordinance and said it must be
rewritten to leave ``no leeway for content-based restrictions as to
who ought to be permitted to march.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature and content of the Nationalist Movement's message
was the predominant reason it was treated differently and had its
permit request denied,'' the judge declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
