<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAWING-SCHOOL-ART-$A     07-07 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAWING-SCHOOL-ART-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDSUMMER MADNESS IN CHARCOAL AND PASTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By SARAH BOXER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a steamy afternoon during the drawing marathon at
the New York Studio School of Drawing, Painting and Sculpture, I
learned the meaning of repentance. How had I sinned by drawing?
That was not immediately evident. But there I was, muttering
``repent, repent, repent'' under my breath and erasing furiously.
</P>
<P>
   When the drawing marathon began, in mid-June, 97 artists,
students, architects, Sunday painters, art critics and teachers
from Australia, Mexico, Switzerland, England, Israel, California,
Alabama, Massachusetts and Washington, D.C. stood ready at their
easels to draw for eight hours a day, five days a week, in the
rambling building that had once been the original Whitney Museum.
</P>
<P>
   This two-week ordeal was invented a decade ago by Graham
Nickson, a quick-witted, soft-spoken British painter who is the
dean of the school, in order to kick-start his students. But this
summer it seemed far better known outside New York than inside. Few
had come from close by. Many had traveled thousands of miles.
</P>
<P>
   In the studio, I expected to see a single model stretched out on
a piece of cloth. Instead there was a bizarre set inspired by a
Giotto fresco. There were striped and solid awnings held up by four
tall, red wooden posts nailed to a low white platform. The platform
was littered with tables, bottles, bowls, baskets and a dead tree
with boards nailed to its branches and the bottom of its trunk
wrapped in a sheet. On the floor outside the arcade were rivers of
cloth, more baskets and bowls, fruits and onions, pitchers and
trays. And there were three nude models: a thin man sitting on the
platform and leaning against a wooden settee, a tall lanky woman
stretched out on a pillow on her belly and a small blond woman
dozing near the edge of the platform.
</P>
<P>
   This was the scene for the whole week. The models were not going
to move from their poses (except for breaks) and we were not going
to move either. I was stationed between a high school student from
Massachusetts who wondered whether she would ever emerge with a
nice drawing to take home and an Australian man with penchant for
loudly poking his paper with his charcoals and pastels.
</P>
<P>
   The marathon began with charcoal. After a morning of struggle
with the male model's hand and leg and that cursed settee he was
leaning on, it was time for our first critique, or ``crit,'' the
heart of the formal instruction. The drawings were pinned on the
wall. Nickson pointed at them one by one with the tiny red light
from a laser pen. Our moral education was about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   First came the vocabulary. The rectangle is good, a force to be
used, filling in drawings is bad, finding a pathway through
drawings is good, making corrections is good (``When in doubt,
correct''), letting the energy of a drawing evaporate at the edge
of the page is bad, embellishing is bad, democracy (in which figure
is no better than ground) is good, keeping a drawing open is good,
closing it down, or polishing it, is bad, floating figures are bad,
weighty ones are good, perceptual drawing (in which you rely on the
eye) is good, conceptual drawing (relying on presuppositions) is
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing like an architect or carpenter (building a structure and
fitting in objects later) is bad, drawing like you're ticking off a
shopping list of objects is bad, fighting and struggling for a form
is good, engaging in wishful thinking is bad (``This artist is
wishing he was in front of the model''), finding a synergy or
relationship between shapes is good (``that plate is a surrogate
head'') leaving ``footprints in the sand'' where you've traveled is
good, finding caves and lumps in a space is good, Apollonian space
(the one you've reasoned should be there) is bad, Dionysian space
(the one you've stumbled into) is good, desperation is good,
searching is good, Arthur Dove is bad, Matisse is good. Andrew
Wyeth is bad, Degas is good.
</P>
<P>
   In the first crit, I was scorned as a carpenter. I had built a
structure and put objects inside it. I had not yet admitted that
there was a higher power _ the rectangle _ and that I was weak
before it.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, we were made to cut up our drawings into three
vertical segments. I heard the high school student next to me give
a little yelp of resistance. We glued the two ends, severed from
their middle, onto one sheet of paper in their proper places. We
glued the middle section onto the middle of another sheet. In the
remaining hours, we drew in some of the missing passages.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Nickson asked the crowd of charcoal-stained faces:
``Was this a good idea? Or was it just a funny thing for the end of
the day?'' It wasn't funny. It must have been a good idea. It was a
way for us to think about how the size of the image was related to
the rectangular paper. If you're going to do a large drawing, he
said, you have to keep the unity. You need to see everything in
relational terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is space?'' he asked. The answers came: ``awareness,''
``everything between everything else.'' Nickson had his own
definition: ``Think of negative space as yogurt and then drop a
raspberry into it. The berry doesn't sink. It's held in place by
the yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning we attacked both drawings with charcoal. And
just when we thought we had them licked, we were told to cut them
in two and swap their top halves. Then we unified the mismatched
drawings square by square, finding pathways, negative spaces,
relations between shapes. Nickson came by and asked, ``Are you
embellishing?'' No, I am too busy confusing the seat of the settee
with its arms.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, we picked up Indian-red pastels and went
through one of the drawings clockwise correcting mistakes. Then we
went over it again with charcoal. Once that drawing was fully
smudged, we started on the other one. We used cerulean blue pastels
to mark out the caves, or deep spaces, and caput mortum, a
brownish-red, to mark out the lumps, or protruding forms. One of
the models went to the hospital with a rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happened today that was quite radical,'' Nickson
told us that evening. The room was silent. He asked, ``What
happened?'' And one guy answered: ``We all got suicidal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickson had something else in mind: ``We were forced to correct,
to travel around the rectangle. The reason for walking through the
sections is to make us travel to places we wouldn't think of as
being important.'' So, he asked: ``Why did we cut our drawings? Was
that pure sadism? Let's talk about the act of cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have hurt. It should be meaningful. It's savagery,''
he said. ``What else? Why did we switch the two tops? It gave us
new adventures, new possibilities. Things didn't match up so we had
to correct. Correction is the lifeblood of drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   What about color. ``Was that a chance to embellish? To decorate?
To be optimistic?'' Color was used as scaffolding. Color became
metaphorical. Skin isn't cerulean blue. And that made us aware of
the metaphorical nature of drawing. These are marks on a page.
Color articulates form. It should be democratic in the drawing, all
over the place. The less object-oriented, the less narrative a
drawing is, the better. It is the density of a drawing, the
accumulation of decisions, that gives it its power.
</P>
<P>
   When my drawings went up, they were called ``decorative,''
``architectural,'' and I was accused of coloring in and neglecting
the corners. I was a traitor to perception. Then a ray of hope
shone. This drawing, Nickson generously said, pointing, is
``umbrioco,'' the Italian word for drunk. He said it gave him the
feeling of stumbling through a cubist space.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning we used string and tacks to grid our poor,
overworked pictures into eighths, then 16ths. We wound our way from
square to square, with charcoal, then pastel, then charcoal, then
pastel. My drunken picture turned into a sickening case of delirium
tremens.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon brought fresh white space. We abandoned our easels
and stapled huge sheets, 6 feet by 6 feet, onto the bare walls.
Then we tacked up a big X of string from one corner to another.
``There's a synergy between the corner and the center,'' Nickson
said, ``and you've just found it.'' I had never drawn on such a
large sheet. We made a little square in the center of the sheet,
and that, he explained, would be the module, the small unit of the
big square of paper.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for a five-minute meditation. ``I want you to find
something in the room to be the center of your drawing. Maybe it
will be this onion here.'' We were warned to choose the object
carefully and not to waste any space. ``I've seen it happen,'' he
said. The center should be the raison d'etre of the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   I was quickly drawn to the darkest spot in the setup: where the
lanky model's buttocks met the negative space between her legs. But
that seemed too risky as a raison d'etre, so I went for a small
flaw on the trunk of the dead tree. Two seconds later, I had
trouble locating it again. The next 20 minutes were to be devoted
to sketching the corners with charcoal. I spent them regretting my
decision. The spot kept shifting.
</P>
<P>
   That night at the crit, Nickson's quiet observations about our
being ``on a journey with no idea of what the destination was going
to be'' were overcome by loud claps of thunder outside. And our
pictures on the wall, which he had compared and contrasted with
drawings by Gauguin, Seurat, Degas, Bonnard, Giacometti, Vuillard,
Masaccio, Derain, El Greco and Ingres, were upstaged by the
lightning. The snakes, clouds, sunbursts and deer molded in low
relief on the ceiling were illuminated, and the fireplace,
whimsically decorated with plaster flames, came alive. Buckets of
rain came down outside. The leaves were a lurid green. The casement
windows slammed shut with the wind. ``What do we think of this
drawing?'' Nickson asked. ``Or are we too captivated by the rain?''
He had lost us.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning brought a deep funk. We were to go back into
our big drawings using cerulean blue, concentrating on square-foot
sections. Next we cut up squares of paper and pasted them onto our
drawings to map out a pathway. The squares of white were supposed
to open up our drawings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the students compared the marathon to a Buddhist retreat.
Some Buddhist teachers, she said, ``will get you up at 4 in the
morning to do an hour of prostration and then sit still.'' We had
tasks, too. We were asked to cut up our pictures, shift the whole
drawing over six inches every few minutes, or correct one another's
pictures for two-hour stints. That kind of thing, she said,
``pushes you over the edge of your usual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon brought no relief from the relentless cut and
paste. We glued more squares on the hollows and hills in the
drawing, more squares on the apexes closest to us. ``It's like
going in and dropping supplies to the army,'' Nickson explained. I
ran out of hollows and hills and started gluing squares over the
sections that I hated. I heard someone across the room moan, ``Are
we just going to be broken down, and broken down and broken down?''
</P>
<P>
   The evening proved fateful. Nickson showed us the pentimenti,
the ghost traces left from an erasure, in a picture. He clearly
admired the space they had created and the honesty they indicated.
Mistakes were made. Mistakes were corrected. The word pentimenti,
he explained, comes from the Italian world for repent. ``If you
make a mark you thought was honest and you find it wasn't, then you
repent, and the mark that's left is a sign of your repentance.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Lord, I have sinned.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, we went back into the caves of our picture with blue
and climbed the hills with caput mortum. I struggled desperately to
be honest. But honestly, things kept shifting. The table leg was
behind the tree, then it wasn't. A little cave that was definitely
there suddenly vanished. An onion turned into an orange. The arm of
the settee was pointing right into the man's head, then it was a
few inches away. My god, even the raison d'etre of my drawing, that
damn spot on the tree, wouldn't stay still for me.
</P>
<P>
   Finally I was saved. One of the full-time students pointed out
that my perspective kept changing because I was climbing on a chair
to reach the top part of the drawing, ducking down to reach the
bottom and wandering back and forth to get to the edges. To keep
everything still, you have to keep coming back to the same spot to
look, and then memorize where you want to make your mark.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the world stopped reeling. I heard the happy scraping
of charcoal and pastel all around me. I heard a woman fall off her
ladder from sheer concentration. I heard one man yell at another
for tampering with the setup. I didn't care. The world had stopped
spinning. Everything was exactly where I thought it was. And I went
in with my charcoal to do some heavy repenting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
