</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-DEBERG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeBerg thinks experience in NFL will be on his side
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sports-talk radio stations from coast to coast were
buzzing Tuesday about 44-year-old Steve DeBerg signing with the
Atlanta Falcons and supplanting Warren Moon as the oldest player in
the NFL. But DeBerg, showing a sense of humor, took it all in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire Warren, but he's a young guy,'' said DeBerg, a
17-year veteran who on Tuesday threw a handful of passes during the
Falcons' mandatory mini-camp. ``There's a lot to (the idea that the
NFL favors such older quarterbacks as Moon and Super Bowl champion
John Elway, 37).
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses have gotten so advanced it takes more just to
understand what you can and can't do,'' DeBerg said. ``I would bet
I can be more productive this year than the two quarterbacks
drafted first (No. 1 pick Peyton Manning of Indianapolis, and No. 2
Ryan Leaf of San Diego). The learning curve is so steep.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg is expected to back up starting quarterback Chris
Chandler and tutor second-year QB Tony Graziani or rookie free
agent Brian Brennan. They're the quarterbacks in camp now that
would-be backup Mark Rypien is all but certain not to join the team
in time for training camp on July 23. Rypien, signed earlier by the
Falcons, is dealing with serious health problems suffered by his
wife and son. Coach Dan Reeves said one of the three backups will
be cut.
</P>
<P>
   After splitting 1993 between Tampa Bay and Miami, DeBerg coached
quarterbacks in 1995-96 under Reeves with the Giants. When he
didn't get a coaching job last year, he began working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It began as a way to get in shape,'' said DeBerg, who was
called by radio call-in shows around the country Tuesday, chiefly
in cities where he played -- San Francisco, Tampa Bay and Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't doing much, other than being 43, retired, and having
my share of fun. I did a lot of throwing into nets, a lot of
running and leg weight work, and it went from there,'' DeBerg said.
``As a coach, you prepare so much more. I began studying throwing
technique, because I had to explain it. I learned a lot about quick
release, power and accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg knew nothing about the illnesses in the Rypien family
when he went looking for tryouts last month. First, he called Tampa
Bay. Next, he called Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I know Dan (for whom he played in Denver 1981-83), I
told him what I was thinking, and he told me they weren't sure what
was going to happen with Ryp,'' DeBerg said. ``I called back the
next day and asked if it would be OK if I drove up (from Tampa) and
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, DeBerg signed a one-year deal. If DeBerg makes the
Falcons, Moon, who starts for Seattle, will become the
second-oldest player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I just love throwing footballs,'' DeBerg said. ``Maybe
my arm isn't as strong as it was, but my release is quicker, and my
mechanics are better. I got out of the huddle fine today.
Everything seemed to be moving kind of fast, but it will slow down.
I wouldn't be here if I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
