</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons convened Tuesday in Suwanee for
the team's three-day mini-camp, and veterans underwent physicals
and were tested for their ``power output'' and general conditioning
before participating in a one-hour practice.
</P>
<P>
   Players loathed the conditioning test, where they had to run ten
40-yard dashes, all within 10 percent of their top time, with a
20-second rest between each. But the mood was upbeat, considering
the rarity of a mandatory mini-camp so close to the July 23 start
of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves said there's a reason for that schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Players are ending a 16-week stretch of voluntary _ but heavily
encouraged _ conditioning work. Teams used to go straight from
mini-camp to training camp. But a couple of years ago, a new rule
in the collective-bargaining agreement specified that veterans must
have 10 days off immediately before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 10-day moratorium, from my perspective, is one of the
worst things they've done,'' Reeves said. ``It takes a long time to
get in shape, but you can get out of shape real quick. We have the
mini-camp now, and do these tests so guys can see where they are.
Some will see they need to get in even better shape. Some veterans
will do nothing (in the 10 off days), and that 16 weeks can go to
waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight of 81 players were present Tuesday. Starting right
guard Gene Williams, punter Dan Stryzinski and backup quarterback
Mark Rypien were excused for personal reasons. . . . After they
signedreserve quarterback Steve DeBerg, the Falcons waived
free-agent kicker David Akers to remain at the NFL's limit of 80
players under contract. . . . Third-round draft choice Jammi
German, a wide receiver from Miami, remains the only one of nine
draftees still unsigned. Atlanta will have to waive another player
when German signs. German's agent, Alan Wade of Memphis, is asking
for a larger signing bonus than the Falcons are offering. The bonus
will be in the vicinity of $365,000, and the contract, probably for
three years, will be worth nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons suffered no serious injuries Tuesday, although
cornerback Ray Buchanan tweaked a hamstring while running 40s;
German is fighting a sore ankle. . . . General manager Harold
Richardson had informal talks with Frank Bauer, the agent for
quarterback Chris Chandler, about a contract extension, but nothing
is imminent. Chandler, 32, is entering the last year of his
contract, and both sides say they would like an extension. . . .
The mandatory portion of mini-camp ends Thursday, but the team will
have a voluntary passing camp Friday morning, the last formal
gathering before training camp. Rookies will remain in Suwanee
right up to camp. . . . Former lineman Keith Loneker, who was in
camp with the Falcons last summer before being cut, has a small
role in the George Clooney movie, ``Out of Sight.'' Loneker, who
was on the Rams, plays a bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
