s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PRETEENS-$ADV1     07-07 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PRETEENS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH THE EYES OF A CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (JT ) 
 By WILL JOYNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 6-year-old boy tries to protect his mother as she is thrown
around a tiny apartment by a charismatic crook posing as an army
officer in the Soviet Union of the early 1950s. An 11-year-old girl
discovers her mother sitting with self-inflicted wounds in the
basement of their western Massachusetts house one afternoon in
1963, a few hours after the assassination of President John F.
Kennedy. An 8-year-old girl serves as a shrewd translator for her
deaf parents as they appeal to a bank worker for a loan in the
prosperous Germany of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these scenes is from a movie in theaters now or about to
be, and each is from a movie intended primarily for adults. More
important, each is indicative of a prominent tendency among
thoughtful filmmakers these days to present insights about
complicated adult situations through the consciousnesses and mouths
of near-babes rather than of jaded midlifers, dreamy Gen-X drifters
or renegade teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Placing the pre- or early-adolescent point of view in the thick
of sophisticated conflict has a venerable cinematic past, of course
_ think of Truffaut's ``400 Blows'' and Spielberg's ``E.T.'' And
its practical esthetic appeal is a compelling one that's not so
difficult to decipher: the pre- or early adolescent is old enough
to be both perceptive witness and provocative participant yet young
enough not to have retreated fully behind the blinkers of
self-contemplation and social convention. What's striking, though,
is not only the number of new films centered on such characters _
the movies mentioned above, respectively, ``The Thief,'' ``Home
Before Dark'' and ``Beyond Silence,'' come directly on the heels of
``Lawn Dogs,'' ``The Butcher Boy'' and ``Mendel'' in the spring and
``Eve's Bayou'' and ``My Life in Pink'' last winter. What's also
striking is the refinement with which the approach is being used.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Thief,'' a recent best-foreign-film Oscar nominee from
Russia that opens in American theaters on July 17, Sanya (Misha
Philipchuk) is a shyly charming 6-year-old with his own distinct
set of tics and fears. But with a virtual absence of contrivance,
the director and screenwriter, Pavel Chukhrai, has him personify
nothing less than the entire Russian people under Stalin as well.
</P>
<P>
   During a period of great national dislocation, Sanya's mother,
Katya (Yekaterina Rednikova), latches on to Tolyan (Vladimir
Mashkov), a hard, handsome man who she thinks is a soldier and will
be an effective provider. Sanya is haunted by indistinct visions of
his real father, a good soldier now dead who appears to him asking,
``Will you avenge me?'' As the boy resists, then idolizes, then
sees through the interloper Tolyan, the lessons of ``The Thief'' _
like many of the lessons of childhood itself, when thought back
upon _ seem intimate and historically vast at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same is true of Alexander Rosler's ``Mendel,'' which is
about a German-Jewish family that moves to Norway in 1954. The
title character is a 9-year-old boy who has been kept in the dark
concerning the Holocaust; he doesn't know the details of what
happened to the many relatives his parents speak of only in
whispers. But as he detects how unsettling the move to Norway is
for his parents and older brother, and senses the reasons for this,
he becomes a kind of provocateur. Forcing them to reveal the
specifics of their family's loss and their notion of Jewishness,
Mendel comes to represent the challenge of articulating and
maintaining postwar Jewish identity, a large subject indeed.
</P>
<P>
   More often, the children at the heart of this sort of film are
agents of emotional truth in the face of smaller if timeless adult
realities like middle-class complacency, adultery, alcoholism,
madness and alienation related to illness or physical disability.
They are walking and talking, often infuriating reminders of the
way things should be, or could be, if the world weren't what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, this truth-telling status _ and the darker side of
the human condition _ is fulfilled with a loss of innocence. In
Neil Jordan's ``Butcher Boy,'' for example, the 12-year-old Francie
Brady (memorably played by a newcomer, Eamon Owens) echoes the
disintegration of each of his parents in a small Irish town by
disintegrating himself, and carrying out an appalling act of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the truth-teller, on a more hopeful note, courageously
maintains or restores reason and order. In Maureen Foley's ``Home
Before Dark,'' which opened on Friday, 11-year-old Nora reacts to
her mother's suicide attempt on the day of the Kennedy
assassination by refusing to let anyone not face the facts. In
Caroline Link's ``Beyond Silence,'' another recent Oscar nominee,
young Lara balances care for her deaf parents with her musical
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's telling that these movies are not, strictly
speaking, coming-of-age narratives. The point is usually not that
the central child is gaining knowledge that will make him or her
more like us adults, but that the child is still in touch with a
manner of understanding largely lost to us. Perhaps that's what
makes these films _ some of which are fully realized, some of which
are not _ seem more essential than so much of what's on view today.
They let us look at ourselves with an acuity we'd love to recover
for good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
