<HEADER>
A4398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
i n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ABIOLA-BOS &LR;      07-07 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABIOLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN LEADER ABIOLA COLLAPSES, DIES IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moshood Abiola, the millionaire executive who was seen as
winning the 1993 Nigerian presidential election, collapsed and died
during a meeting with Nigerian and visiting US officials Tuesday,
just hours before he was expected to be released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, who suffered cardiac arrest, was rushed from the meeting
and died at a hospital in the capital, Abuja, the government said.
But the timing of the death _ a month after the death by heart
attack of his archrival, dictator Sani Abacha _ raised suspicions
of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected death prompted looting and violence in parts of
Lagos, Nigeria's commercial capital. Young people ran through the
streets, shouting that Abiola had been murdered. The government
cordoned off Abiola's house in Lagos and put police on alert, but
the disturbances subsided by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   After General Abacha's sudden death, in recent days US officials
and Nigerian democracy activists had pinned their hopes on Abiola,
who was 60, for a peaceful transition in the troubled country. When
Abiola declared himself president in 1994, after the military
regime annulled the election, he was imprisoned alone in a dark
cell and blocked from contact with doctors and family members,
despite his history of high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with Abacha's successor, General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, last week, UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said Abiola
and dozens of other political prisoners would be freed. Abiola had
been kept secluded with only a Bible and the Koran to read but was
``physically fit and mentally alert,'' Annan said. In fact, he
said, Abiola was so cut off from the world that he thought former
UN secretary general Boutros Boutros-Ghali, who left the post
nearly two years ago, was still running the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had only been informed that he was going to meet a very
important man,'' Annan said Tuesday. ```Who are you?,''' he asked
Annan. ```What happened to the Egyptian?'''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for the first time since he was detained four years
ago, Abiola was allowed to see American officials, including
Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering, the State Department's
third-highest-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that he started coughing and wheezing and he died''
when rushed to a hospital, his daughter, Hafsat Abiola, said by
telephone from her home in suburban Maryland. As an undergraduate
at Harvard University, she had campaigned for the release of her
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong suspicion that this is foul play _ it is just
too coincidental,'' said Abiola, 23, who graduated last year and
has crisscrossed the country speaking to college audiences about
human rights in her homeland, the world's most populous black
nation. ``No matter what happened, the military bears full
responsibility because of the way they treated him ... and he was
in their custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshood Abiola's wife, Kudirat, who also campaigned for his
release, was shot dead two years ago in Lagos in a crime that many
in the family attribute to the dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola earned a fortune in publishing and other businesses. He
was not beloved by all Nigerians, but almost everyone in the
country said that he had handily won the elections before they were
annulled. The military government clamped down on the press and
political parties, executed opponents and jailed labor leaders,
journalists, students, environmentalists, and others without
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just stunning news and all of us who know Nigeria well
are shocked,'' said Peter M. Lewis, a professor of international
relations at American University and co-author of ``Stabilizing
Nigeria.'' ``There's a great risk that most Nigerians will not
believe that what happened was spontaneous and a result of natural
causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the Clinton administration exacerbated Nigeria's
problems by not consistently denouncing the dictatorship or fully
embracing grass-roots democracy movements. Although the US Agency
for International Development had a $3 million budget for helping
democracy groups in the country last year, only 10 percent of the
money was distributed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, President Clinton said he was ``deeply
saddened'' by Abiola's death and urged the country to move toward
democracy. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Abiola ``had
become the symbol of democracy in Nigeria.'' Statements by the US
and British government did not suggest any hint of foul play, but a
State Department official said the timing of the heart attack
appeared to be ``pretty suspicious.'' Still, there is no
information that indicates a homicide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Muslim custom, Abiola should be buried Wednesday and no
autopsy should be allowed. But Abiola's children demanded an
autopsy and the government ordered one Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We'd be glad to see an autopsy ... because of all the
rumors going around about the cause of Abiola's death,'' said Janet
Fleishman, who monitors Africa for Human Rights Watch in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch and other nongovernmental groups in the
United States and Africa said the military must honor a pledge to
hold elections in August and surrender power peacefully in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the government will make good on its pledge to release
all remaining political prisoners, unconditionally, and to define a
credible process for the democratic transition to civilian rule
within a reasonable time frame,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the American University professor, said the military
government is split between hard-liners who want to crack down and
reformers who want to allow civilians to rule. He predicted that
unrest will grow as frustrated Nigerians demand an investigation
into Abiola's death. ``This death creates a pall of uncertainty,''
he said. ``If there are riots in the streets, that will strengthen
the hand of the hard-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the military, Nigeria's political opposition movement is
divided and debating what to do next, said Margaret Vogt, a
Nigerian scholar at the International Peace Academy in New York.
``The Nigerian people didn't vote for Abiola because he was so
good, they voted for change, and Abiola symbolized that change,''
Vogt said. ``Now, the pressure for change will be stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Colum Lynch contributed to this report from
New York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
