<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIAN COACH HAS SEEN IT ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France __ Miroslav Blazevic has seen much in his 63
years, everything from a war that tore his homeland asunder to the
inside of a jail cell in which he was housed in the wake of his
sport's most notorious scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Few expected him to see what his Croatian side has achieved the
past weeks, rising seemingly from nowhere to grab a spot in
tonight's World Cup semifinal against France at the Stade de
France. The colorful Blazevic wasn't among them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he'd been tipped off to the Croats' imminent success
before the Cup began. Superstitious, tempermental and with an
unerring faith in astrology, Blazevic was informed by his
astrologer that his squad would progress far in its first World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He also was told he might have a heart attack while sitting on
the bench during the competition. If it comes tonight, or in
Sunday's final, he's sure to exit this world as happy as a man can
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was convinced we were ready for something big in France,''
said Blazevic, known as ``Ciro'' at home. ``Croatian players are
the most gifted in Europe. They are the Brazilians of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   With a gendarme's hat in one hand and a burning cigarette in the
other, Blazevic has been the surprise success in France, guiding a
team that few saw capable of contending for the crown to the brink
of winning it.
</P>
<P>
   He's done so by instilling confidence in his players, by taking
a group of talented individuals --- including millionaires Davor
Suker (Real Madrid), Zvonimir Boban (AC Milan), Aljosa Asanovic
(Napoli), Robert Jarni (Real Betis), Goran Vlaovic (Valencia) and
Slaven Bilic (Everton) --- and molding them into a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``His secret is that he has an inner-communication with the
players,'' said Branko Miksa, the president of Croatia's soccer
federation. ``He is like a psychologist; he understands the
players' psyche and he has a great knowledge of football. He is
able to combine the two to achieve these results.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't always been so revered. He spent two weeks in a French
jail after being implicated in the Olympique Marseille match-fixing
scandal --- he was never charged --- and Croatian fans were calling
for his head after a controversial quarterfinal loss to Germany in
the 1996 European Championship, and again after a difficult road
through qualifying for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   His friendship with Croatian president Franjo Tudjman helped him
keep control, and after struggles in its early Cup games --- wins
over Jamaica and Japan and a loss to Argentina --- his squad has
come on in the knockout phase, beating Romania and playing a
brilliant tactical game to upset Germany in the quarterfinals. Now
his players believe they can win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Blazevic told us two years ago that we were the best in
the world, we all laughed,'' Bilic said after the win over Germany.
``We are laughing less and less now. ... I'm not saying we're going
to be champions, but now we have a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazevic never doubted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few people gave us a chance of getting to the semifinals, but
I've always had this feeling we could go further,'' he said.
``Personally, I am far too ambitious to be happy with what we have
achieved so far. I want to go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazevic, who coached French club Nantes as well as teams in
Croatia, Yugoslavia and Switzerland, carries with him the
gendarme's cap, or ``kepi,'' in honor of Daniel Nivel, the Lens
policeman beaten by German thugs after a first-round match last
month. ``The local gendarme chief gave it to me,'' he explained.
``He wanted me to keep it with me to bring luck to (Nivel).''
</P>
<P>
   It has also brought luck to the Croats. Not that they needed
any.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a surprise,'' he said, ``only for people who are
ignorant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
