u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BLACK-BEATEN-BOS &LR;      07-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BLACK-BEATEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE OF BEATEN BLACK REJECTS POLICE FINDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Mass. _ Although Charles L. Love's wife says he was
the victim of a racial attack July 4, police have told prosecutors
they no longer believe the assault was racially motivated but
stemmed from a disagreement between two families over drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy Love, who is white, says Jeffrey Klier and two of his
relatives, all white, yelled racial slurs as they beat her black
husband in front Klier's Lawrence home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they say, (the slurs) if they were not prejudiced in
some way?'' asked Brandy Love, 50, of Methuen. ``This has nothing
to with drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Brandy Love told investigators her 44-year-old
husband was beaten by the three men with baseball bats who
shattered his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Love, a native of Jasper, Texas, where a black man was
allegedly dragged to death by three white supremacists last month,
was in stable condition at Lawrence General Hospital with his jaw
wired shut.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Klier, 44, of Lawrence has been charged with attempted
murder and violating Love's civil rights. Authorities are looking
for the other alleged attackers, including Klier's son.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Klier was being held in lieu of $75,000 bail. A
spokesman for the Essex County Distict Attorney's office said Klier
has a criminal record going back to 1972, including six convictions
for assault, and three for breaking and entering, but none for
civil rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence police Capt. Michael Molchan said police have told
prosecutors they do not think the July 4 attack was a racial.
Molchan said the assault on Love came about after Klier lost a
fight ``over drugs'' to two of Love's relatives earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The families have known one another for more than 12 years,
Brandy Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Molchan said Lawrence police are leaving the decision on whether
to continue charging Klier with civil right violations up to the
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to them whether they will go forward on those charges
or not,'' said Molchan.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen O'Connell, a spokesman for the district attorney's
office, said Tuesday prosecutors have not decided whether to press
the civil rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still checking into the cause of the dispute,'' said
O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   Molchan said that investigators have determined that after
losing the fight at the Loves' Chase Street house in Methuen, Klier
went home, enlisted some relatives and returned to Love's home,
damaging property there.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Brandy Love then went to Klier's home, about a half
mile away, to find out what was wrong and Charles was attacked when
he got out of his car, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brandy Love tells a different story.
</P>
<P>
   She said she and her husband, who have lived in Methuen for 14
years, were holding a barbeque to celebrate their 20th wedding
anniversary when Klier and two other men showed up in a car,
circling the Loves' block and yelling racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Klier and the others left and the Loves decided to go to the
Klier house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find out what was going on,'' said Brandy Love.
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband got out of the car in Lawrence and started
talking to Jeffrey Klier, when Charles was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to kill him and then they turned on me,''
said Brandy Love. She said Jeffrey Klier chased her to her car, and
broke all the windows out before he ran away when he heard police
sirens.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Klier's 20-year-old son, also named Jeffrey, gave yet
another version of the attack. He said his father got his nose
bloodied and face swollen in an earlier assault by Love's step son
and another man over a drug dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Klier, who is being sought by police, denied his
father went back to the Love's home but said later in the day
Charles and Brandy Love came to the Klier home and Charles Love
exited his car, brandished a knife and said: `` `We have a problem
here? Let's take care of it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is no angel,'' the younger Jeffery Klier said, ``but
he's not prejudiced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-ROUGH-NECKS-ART-2     07-07 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ROUGH-NECKS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of inspectors. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the jobs basically take brawn and endurance, one
cannot just walk off the street and become a roughneck. Working a
drill rig takes teamwork and coordination, with even simple jobs on
platforms, like cleaning and painting, involving an element of
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Davis, who runs the school and coordinates its safety
program, told one class that in Alaska the decks of offshore
platforms are about 150 feet above the freezing water, with
currents often running at 30 to 40 knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you fall off,'' he said, ``they've got five minutes to get
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He also warns students about hydrogen sulfide, a highly
poisonous gas that smells like rotten eggs. When released in
drilling, it can quickly overcome workers and, in high
concentrations, even kill them if they don't make a quick exit or
don a protective mask.
</P>
<P>
   And Davis repeatedly stressed the importance of teamwork. ``It
takes a while to fit in with everybody,'' Hooper stressed. ``If
you're in a crew that doesn't know what they are doing, it gets
pretty tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the trainees did not finish the course because they
found the adjustment difficult, he said, adding, ``You have to have
that grit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bolton seemed to have it. After several weeks, she was able
to maneuver huge wrench-like tools that weigh 500 pounds. During a
training session, amid the roar of motorized drill bits and
winches, she moved them smoothly just in time to tighten and loosen
drilling pipe.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, she recalled, she was working as a
nursing-home aide for $4.35 an hour. When her parole officer told
her she could learn the trade that her father and brother made
their living at, she jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bolton, her brown hair gathered into a ponytail under her
hard hat, worked quietly and comfortably with the young men on the
rig, training herself for the rigors ahead.
</P>
<P>
   She realized she would have a harder time proving she is up to
the challenge. ``They wonder, `Can she do it?''' she said. ``It
just makes me want to prove more that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilgreth, a wiry University of Texas student, was attracted by
the numerous ads offering jobs, but, when he called, found that
everyone wanted experienced people. He decided to quit college for
a while and come to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make enough to invest in something,'' he said,
taking quick drags on a cigarette during a lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   With oil prices dropping again, the bloom of the upturn has
begun to fade. Rates for drilling rigs have begun to fall as
smaller companies have cut back. Wells that made sense to drill
when oil was $18 to $20 a barrel do not at the recent $13 to $14.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Smith, an assistant drilling superintendent for Key
Energy, a local drilling contractor, had all his 32 rigs working
earlier this year. To attract reliable, skilled workers, his
company raised the basic starting wage from $9.35 an hour in
November to $12.35 and began offering 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   The recent decline in oil prices, however, has caused him to
mothball about half the rigs.
</P>
<P>
   And other smaller companies have begun to lay off workers as
they shut down less productive wells.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that most smaller independent oil companies were
waiting to see what happened on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries in Vienna last month, leading oil-producing nations like
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela were able to put together cuts of 1.4
million barrels a day. Combined with cuts from non-OPEC countries
like Mexico and Norway, this has led to total reductions of close
to 3 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how far these cuts will go in helping oil prices
recover because demand may also fall because of recessions in big
oil-importing nations like Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like puppets on a string,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, so are the graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, strapping at 6 foot 2, has just started working with a
crew near Laredo, Tex., for Grey Wolf Drilling. He is working
12-hour shifts, from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m., seven days straight. He
earns $10 an hour, but after 40 hours in a week, he gets the $15
overtime rate. When he is working, he lives in a six-bunk trailer
with 10 other workers in the middle of a desolate area, often
battered by wind-borne dust, where temperatures can reach 110
degrees. About the only diversion is satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, he often does the simple tasks, like fetching
wrenches, tying cables and using his powerful arms to lock down
nuts and bolts. His concern is whether this job will last.
</P>
<P>
   Recently some of his co-workers were laid off, but he was kept
on because of his training.
</P>
<P>
   For Daniel Shumate, who had been driving a cement truck for $8
an hour _ not enough to enable him to own a car _ the school is his
chance to ``make it into the middle bracket.'' After waiting for a
over a month and a half he just landed a job Tuesday with an oil
well service company starting at $6.25 an hour and has several
prospects to work on an offshore platform at much higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to make it since if things don't work out:
``I'm back to square one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
