<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ZIDANE GOES, SO GOES FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ The impoverished neighborhood that sits in
the shadows of the Stade de France is home to several thousand of
the 3 million Algerians who call France home.
</P>
<P>
   The futuristic stadium, the crowning glory of this World Cup,
has done little for them but illuminate the hardship they must
endure. It has brought new taxes to Paris' most depressed
industrial suburb and few benefits, instead offering a rich
contrast between how France envisions itself --- a modern land,
looking to the future --- and the reality of its poor, its
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking the poorest quarter of Saint-Denis is Zinedine
Zidane, standing six stories tall. His face stares out from a
towering adidas ad, but it's much more than a means to sell shoes.
To the people here, especially the Algerians, it's as if God
himself were looking down on them, watching over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are like Zidane --- before he had money,'' explains
a woman, working the counter at one of perhaps a dozen Algerian
restaurants between the Periphique, the freeway that encircles
Paris, and the stadium. ``He is so close to our feelings, he
represents us. From here we can hear the crowd, but we can watch
only on the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Zizou is playing, I feel more French than the
French.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a role Zidane neither relishes nor refuses, but his
abilities with a soccer ball --- like a wizard's, or a magician's
--- his vision and his intelligence has clearly marked him as the
prime talent on a team full of extremely talented players. He's the
world's best playmaker, perhaps the best since Michel Platini
starred for France more than a decade ago, and --- and this is
important, in Saint-Denis and his native Marseille and across the
Mediterranean in Algiers, too --- he is Algerian.
</P>
<P>
   That means plenty in what is increasingly becoming a land of
immigrants, in a country where the far right --- led by politician
Jean-Marie Le Pen --- has preached that France is for Frenchmen,
and that immigrants, such as Zidane's family, should go home.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane's mastery of this game, something he doubtless will
demonstrate in tonight's World Cup semifinal against Croatia at the
Stade de France, and the success that has followed for a French
side that features more than a half-dozen players with roots
elsewhere --- including Marcel Desailly, Lilian Thuram, Christian
Karembeu, Thierry Henry and Youri Djorkaeff --- has done more for
the cause of immigrants in France than anyone could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   A recent cartoon in Le Monde, France's most distinguished
newspaper, showed a Frenchman in a beret, a baguette under his arm,
answering a pollster. ``So, you don't really detest foreigners
then?'' the pollster asked. The Frenchman's answer: ``Not as long
as they keep scoring goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The French have had trouble scoring goals in their past two
matches, an overtime victory over Paraguay and a penalty-kick
triumph over Italy. Zidane was missing for the first, suspended for
stamping on a Saudi player during a first-round match. In the
second, he supplied his teammates with dozens of chances, all for
naught.
</P>
<P>
   He is of such importance to France's effort that winning the
World Cup is inconceivable without him. ``We all know how important
Zizou is,'' says French captain Didier Deschamps. ``Our attacking
game depends almost entirely upon him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody does not know what to do with the ball,'' adds
midfielder Emmanuel Petit, ``he gives it to Zizou, and he finds out
instantly what the best solution is.''
</P>
<P>
   That vision was borne on the streets of Marseille's La
Castellane district, a neighborhood not unlike Saint-Denis, where
he and his brother, Farid --- the sons of Algerian immigrants ---
played soccer daily on a cement square perhaps 150 yards long and
15 yards wide. ``A field to play on?'' he says. ``That was too much
to ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as it is too much for the Algerians of Saint-Denis to ask
to see the brilliant field that overlooks their homes. Tickets are
far too expensive, but Zidane offers them the opportunity to call
the stadium, the $200 million edifice to a modern France, their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three million Frenchmen unemployed,'' says an
another of Saint-Denis' Algerians. ``So why put so much money into
a stadium, which will be used only for this World Cup and then will
become our liability?''
</P>
<P>
   They'll pay for it for years --- residents claim their taxes
will rise 5 percent next year, and another 5 percent the year after
that, and so on. None of it seems worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Then they take another look at Zidane, standing tall, watching
over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This helps us to accept the cost of everything,'' says the
Algerian woman behind the counter. ``We can look out the windows
and see him. It is an enormous feeling of pride. ... He has
dignity, you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
