<SLUG> BC-POLICE-BRUTALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUP CITES POLICE BRUTALITY IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police brutality across the nation is responsible
for unjustified shootings, beatings, chokings and other forms of
physical abuse, and officers often are not held accountable for
their actions, according to a report released Tuesday by Human
Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police brutality is one of the most serious, enduring, and
divisive human rights violations in the United States,'' said the
report by the organization that monitors human rights abuses in 70
nations. ``The problem is nationwide, and its nature is
institutionalized.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the problem, however, is not clear because
national data on excessive force is scarce. A recent Justice
Department report shows that less than 1 percent of the 44.6
million people who had face-to-face contact with the police in 1996
were exposed to physical force ranging from being hit, held,
pushed, or choked.
</P>
<P>
   Boston bucked the findings in the report. Human Rights Watch
found fewer cases of serious police brutality in the city than in
the other 13 cities studied in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Boston fared well in a survey of police shootings in
20 cities conducted earlier this year by Newhouse News Service
showing Boston had the lowest rate of fatal shootings by police
officers _ lower than cities such as New York and Los Angeles, and
smaller cities such as Knoxville, Tenn. and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report said the continued failure to resolve the
case of Michael A. Cox, an officer allegedly beaten by other
officers while on duty, indicates that the ``code of silence''
between police has not been broken.
</P>
<P>
   The report questioned the Boston Police Department's commitment
to dealing effectively with complaints. Citizens, they said,
faulted the department for dragging out investigations. The report
also called Boston's Community Affairs Board a ``farce,'' saying it
receives few complaints because citizens are either discouraged by
the board or unaware it exists.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Police Department did not reply Tuesday to requests
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, patterns of abusive behavior by police officers
persist because of shoddy internal investigations, failures of
leadership, and a union stranglehold on power, according to the
report, which was based on 2 1/2 years of interviews with lawyers,
police officers, experts, victim representatives, and Justice
Department officials, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Roth, executive director of Human Rights Watch, said at
a news conference Tuesday that the majority of police officers do
not rely on excessive force. Those who did were protected by
secretive police investigations and by prosecutors reluctant to
press charges against officers.
</P>
<P>
   Roth accused the Justice Department of ``dropping the ball,''
pointing out that only a ``handful'' of the thousands of civil
rights complaints were prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perez, deputy assistant attorney general for civil rights in
the Justice Department, said the department had prosecuted 289
officers for criminal violations in 159 cases since 1992. He said
the department is ``carefully studying'' the report's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be vigilant in the prosecution and prevention of
police abuse,'' he said. ``Police work is a difficult job and most
officers are hardworking and law-abiding, but when they cross the
line, justice must be prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   City and state prosecutors did not compile statistics on the
number of officers facing criminal charges, but such cases ``appear
to be rare,'' the report said. The report received mixed reviews
from other law enforcement groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vindication and a verification for us,'' said Ronald
Hampton, president of the National Black Police Association, which
endorsed the findings of the report. He pointed out that according
to the report minorities, particularly Latinos and African
Americans, are disproportionately brutalized by police.
</P>
<P>
   The International Association of the Chiefs of Police, on the
other hand, criticized the report for what it called its small
sampling and broad, unfair attack on the integrity of police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you say these things you have a real obligation to be
fair because they undermine public confidence,''said Bobby Moody,
the association's president.
</P>
<P>
   Police executives have made a concerted effort to address issues
of excessive force and accountability, Moody noted. Despite the
criticisms, Moody conceded that Human Rights Watch identified a
real problem. ``I want us to do more,'' he said. ``We don't do
enough in this area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
