<SLUG> BC-CHINA-LOTT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP CHIEF ASSAILS CLINTON ON CHINA AND TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Neb., N.J., Miss., Ark.)   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott criticized
President Clinton on Tuesday for making ``serious mistakes'' on his
trip to China, tempering earlier praise from Republicans that
Clinton's visit was a political triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Lott said on Tuesday that he had grave concerns
about Clinton's articulation of U.S. policy toward Taiwan and
introduced a bipartisan resolution to reaffirm the commitment of
Congress to a democratic Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of pressing Beijing to renounce the use of force
against Taiwan, President Clinton accepted Beijing's position on
Taiwan,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's declaration in China that the United States
would not support Taiwan's independence from the mainland was the
same as past statements by other administration officials. But it
was the first time that Clinton had described his policy.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insist that Clinton did not alter
policy one iota. Washington recognizes Beijing as the sole legal
government of China and acknowledges that Taiwan is a part of
China. At the same time Washington is committed to sell Taiwan what
is needed to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   But the slightest shift in tone or phrasing on that sensitive
foreign policy sets off seismic waves in Washington and in Asia.
``The thing that really concerned us about what the president had
to say was it seemed to open the door to something different,''
Lott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting last week in Shanghai, Clinton appeared to grant a
concession to his Chinese hosts by making a declaration of a policy
known as the ``three no's'' _ no U.S. support for an independent
Taiwan, no recognition for a Taiwan government and no support for
Taiwan's entry into international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's stance is not new, he failed to cloak it in
the usual ambiguity that allows all sides to interpret what they
want. As a result the statement jangled nerves in Taipei and
stirred supporters of Taiwan on Capitol Hill on Tuesday to lob
accusations at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That nuance, said Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., amounted to this,
``We've acknowledged the Taiwan position in the past, but we have
not embraced it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said: ``Why am I concerned with
the president's choice of words while he was in China? Because I
think it is misleading, dangerously misleading. It indicates to the
Chinese and the Taiwanese that our policy on Taiwan has changed,
when the president says it hasn't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At least one Republican asked what all the fuss was about.
``What's really new here?'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who
supports engagement with China. ``I wonder if this isn't some way
to get a jab in at the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles of Oklahoma said the Senate
resolution would reassert what he called the old policy on Taiwan.
But when he was asked what that old policy was, Nickles said he did
not want to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic sponsor of the Taiwan resolution, Sen. Robert
Torricelli of New Jersey, said the bill aimed to clarify some of
Clinton's comments. ``He came home with real substantive
accomplishments, but we need to make clear what has changed and
what has not,'' said Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had refrained from criticizing the administration's
record on China while Clinton was there, observing an unwritten
rule that Congress shall not challenge a president's foreign policy
toward a country he is visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Republicans conceded in interviews last week that
Clinton had delivered a polished performance in his televised news
conferences in China and had struck the right tone on many
sensitive issues like human rights and religious liberties.
</P>
<P>
   But with Clinton back home and the Senate returning from a
week's recess, the gloves came off. Speaking to reporters this
morning and again Tuesday afternoon Lott said that Clinton had
failed to address adequately issues like the spread of nuclear
weapons, religious persecution and the trade imbalance between
China and the United States. Lott said Congress might have to act
to ``repair the damage that has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Senate committees will hold hearings Wednesday and
Thursday on whether sensitive U.S. missile technology was given to
Chinese rocket scientists for the launching of U.S. satellites in
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
