<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEARS-PROTECT-BOS &LR;      07-07 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARS-PROTECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDLIFE GROUPS CRITICIZE BEAR PROTECTION MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate is trying to protect Smokey Bear and his
friends, saying they are in danger of being poached. But several
wildlife groups testified Tuesday that the bill is all smoke and no
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Protection Act would ban the import, export, sale, and
transportation of bear parts in the United States. Senator Mitch
McConnell, the Kentucky Republican and sponsor of the measure, said
the legislation would help reduce poaching for bear gall bladders
and bear feet, which are used for traditional Asian medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poaching of bears is a national problem that is destined
to become worse,'' he said Tuesday in prepared testimony for a
Senate hearing. ``Currently, there are enforcement and
jurisdictional loopholes, which exist as a result of a patchwork of
state laws, that allow this illegal poaching to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said American bears are in danger because ``the
dramatic decline of bear populations outside the US has led
poachers to turn to American bears to fill the increasing demand.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said bear parts are ``used to treat everything from
heart disease to hangovers, and is also popular as an ingredient in
luxury shampoos and as an aphrodisiac.''
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the representatives for wildlife protection
groups who testified before the Senate Committee on Environment and
Public Works said such legislation is uneccesary, because bear
poaching is not a significant problem in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Ginette Hemley, the World Wildlife Fund's vice president for
species conservation, said illegal trade in black bear body parts
has not endangered the American bear population.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of occasional documented reports of illegal trade in
black bear body parts associated with the traditional Asian
medicine trade, state wildlife management authorities indicate
black bear populations are generally stable or increasing
throughout the country, in some cases dramatically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Rogers, deputy director for the US Fish and Wildlife
Service, said the agency does not have evidence that bears in the
United States are threatened by the demand for bear parts.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said about 70 illegal shipments of bear parts in the past
five years have been discovered by the wildlife service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Service believes that bears in the United States have been
adequately protected to date and that this legislation addresses an
issue which has not been a major resource problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary J. Taylor, legislative director for the International
Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies, said if the bill becomes
law, it would be ``an inappropriate federal intrusion into state
management authorities and prerogatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said such legislation would unnecessarily divert wildlife
enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wayne Pacelle, a senior vice president for the Humane
Society of the United States, said his group fully supports the
bill, because it ``represents a thoughtful, proactive approach to
wildlife protection that will contribute to the longterm
conservation of the world's remaining bear species. It is wrong for
this nation to allow poachers and smugglers to exploit the current
inconsistencies in state laws and profit from the sale of bear
parts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
