<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-2TAKES-NYT     07-07 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS SAY LOAN FROM IMF MAY BE LESS THAN NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The International Monetary Fund and the Yeltsin
government are negotiating an aid package that may produce less
money than foreign investors say is needed to help ease Russia's
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have publicly stated they need $10 billion to
$15 billion in assistance from the Fund and other lenders. As
Russia's stocks, bonds and currency took a pounding on Tuesday,
some Western investment bankers say Russia may need $20 billion or
even more to rebuild investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But the IMF has privately indicated it may only be willing to
provide $5.6 billion in new loans, forcing Russia to scramble for
additional funds, Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The exact amount of financing from the Fund is still under
negotiation and will ultimately depend on whether the Russians take
concrete steps to cut their deficit and restructure their economy,
said Fund officials. They added, however, that after huge Asia
bailouts, IMF resources are limited.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia managed to fulfill all of the IMF's tough demands and
obtained substantial funding from commercial banks and other
institutions, it may be possible that the Kremlim could reach its
$15 billion goal, IMF officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting all of the Fund's conditions, however, will be
politically difficult.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, for example, has urged Parliament to
adopt an ambitious ``anti-crisis'' plan to cut Russia's budget
deficit. But the IMF privately informed Russia last week that
Yeltsin's plan only goes half way toward meeting its demand that
the Russian deficit be reduced next year to 2 percent to 2.5
percent of the economy from 5.5 percent currently.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is also insisting that Russia pass a new tax code, adopt
legislation on budget procedures, tighten bank regulation and take
bold steps to end the troublesome culture of nonpayment _ where
wages go unpaid, tax debts accumulate and companies do business in
barter.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's markets took a beating on Tuesday, as interest rates
for short-term Russian treasury bills soared to 120 percent from 90
percent on Monday, and the government acknowledged it may not be
able to find a buyer willing to pay $1.6 billion for Rosneft, the
state oil company. A rescue plan for a major Russian bank,
Tokobank, also collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to bring calm to Russia's markets, the IMF, the World
Bank and Russian officials stepped up their talks on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators later said they had agreed on some of the conditions
set by the Fund. But there are still some differences over Russia's
ability to raise new revenue and impose measures to control its
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an understanding in principle on the biggest
issues,'' Anatoly Chubais, the chief Russian negotiator said on
Tuesday in an effort to reassure foreign investors. He added that
the negotiators would meet on Thursday to resolve the outstanding
issues.
</P>
<P>
   One Western official said, however, that it would difficult to
wrap up the negotiations this week, and he stressed that the
package still needed to be approved by Yeltsin and the
Communist-dominated Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and Western officials have couched the fiscal crisis as
a acid test for Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and his young team
of aides. The West has applauded Kiriyenko's free market philosophy
and his forthright manner. But now, the IMF and its allies
maintain, it is time for the new team to show that it can take
tough decisions and make them stick.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's markets have soured, however, the focus is not just
on what Moscow is prepared to do. It is also on whether the IMF is
doing enough to help end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``To avoid an even worse financial meltdown, a larger and more
imaginative program is required than the markets have heard about
so far,'' said Charles Blitzer, the director of emerging market
research at Donaldson, Lufkin, Jenrette, and a former World Bank
official.
</P>
<P>
   Defining how much money Russia needs is a judgment call about
the reserves of its Central Bank's reserves, Russia's mountain of
debt and the more amorphous question of how much assistance is
needed to restore confidence in Russia's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yegor Gaidar, the former prime minister who currently advises
the Yeltsin government, said that Russia needs $10 billion to $15
billion in assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money would be used to strengthen the Central Banks'
reserves, which are now about $15 billion. Economists say that
foreign investors hold about $20 billion in Russian treasury bills.
If they were to cash in their bills when they mature, and refuse to
accept new debt, the Central Bank's reserves would be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some new loans could be used to restructure
Russia's short-term debt, which carries very high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, however, has maintained from the start that it is not
in the business of making new loans simply to calm investors and,
in any event, it is husbanding its dwindling resources after
fashioning a $43 billion bailout for Indonesia and an even larger
one for South Korea. It says that Russia is chiefly responsible for
solving its crisis and that in the other bailouts, additional
sources of funds, such as international banks, must also be found.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, the IMF's first deputy managing director, said
last month that a $10 billion to $15 billion contribution by the
Fund is now ``more than the IMF can give to one economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the fund stress they have not decided exactly how
much to give. They said the precise amount will depend on how much
Russia is prepared to do to put its fiscal house in order and
restructure its economy. If Russia does not undertake further
reforms before the aid is disbursed, the IMF argues, the money may
be wasted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Fund doctrine that the stronger the measures the country
takes the more assistance the fund can provide,'' Fischer said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Many Western investment bankers assert, however, that the fund
does not appreciate just how jittery investors are. They say that
the IMF should try to determine how much assistance is needed to
calm the markets and then provide it on the condition that Russia
agrees to a realistic program of reforms. There is no sense, they
say, in the IMF position that the more a nation does the more it
should receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the longer the IMF waits, the more damage is
done in the process,'' said Marc Holtzman, the president of
corporate finance for ABN Amro, a leading Dutch bank. ``It is
already happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say that one approach discussed by the IMF
would provide a total of $5.6 billion in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   Half of that aid would come from expanding Russia's existing
loan, which is dubbed the Extended Fund Facility. The rest would
come from a special fund that would compensate Russia for the
effect falling oil prices have had on oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the IMF would expedite the next $670 million
payment on Russia's existing loan. That would bring the IMF's
package up to about $6.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That amount would be far less than Russia says it needs. But
Russian officials say they hope to negotiate an additional $1
billion in assistance from the World Bank. Russia also hopes to
expedite $1.5 billion in financing that the Japanese government has
agreed to provide in coordination with the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Securing all of this additional funding would not be easy, as
the World Bank has proposed its own conditions, including the
breakup of Gazprom, the huge Russian natural gas monopoly, and
other steps to restructure the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But taken together with the IMF money, these additional sources
could generate more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Billions in additional loans could be obtained from commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the two sides sought to accent the positive. But
Western officials and experts at the international financial
institutions remained worried that Yeltsin government would not be
able to follow through.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that the Parliament has already rebuffed some
important aspects of the Yeltsin's anti-crisis plan on tax policy,
including legislation on the personal income tax and other tax
changes. But Russian officials have also privately expressed
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was in the Fund's position I would give a lot to solve
the problem or I would not give anything,'' said a senior Russian
official who asked not to be identified. ``The Fund seems to feel
it has to give us something but it should not be too much. It may
lead to a negative result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
