<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4426 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREAT-CITIES-$ADV12-N     07-07 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-CITIES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW IT OFF OR IGNORE IT: HOW THE CITY IS A HAREM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sundat, July 12.)  
 (JT)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is an urban theme and five variations. The great British
child psychoanalyst D.W. Winnicott believed that artists are driven
by the conflict between the desire to communicate and the even
stronger desire to hide. Flip this idea around, and you arrive at a
useful theory for interpreting the contemporary city: Great cities
are driven by the conflict between the desire to expose and the
even stronger desire to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   This dynamic is vividly displayed during mayoral campaigns. The
challenger's job is to expose problems the incumbent hopes voters
will ignore. Yes, street crime is down, the economy is up. But
public schools are crumbling, the homeless have reclaimed the
subways, and the city's feel-good mood seems oddly similar to
paranoid delusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between exposure and overlooking is cultural as
well as political. A mayoral debate enables citizens not only to
choose between two different depictions of the city but also to
form images of their own. The debate produces raw material. The
public shapes this matter into meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Like psychiatry and the law, architecture is a way of describing
social arrangements. The Ottoman rulers had a different way of
organizing intern programs for young women. It was called the
Imperial Harem. When Monica Lewinsky first gained the public eye, I
thought it might be useful to look at the floor plans of Istanbul's
Topkapi Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The harem was sort of a dive: windowless, labyrinthine,
jerry-built. The sultan and his mother lived in the harem, too, of
course, but their quarters were splendid. For the royal wives,
concubines, eunuchs, dwarfs and other retainers, the accommodations
became increasingly dismal with the descent in social station, and
they got worse over time. As the harem's population increased,
large halls were divided into small, misshapen rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a small number of the harem women were consorts of the
sultan,'' writes Gulru Necipoglu in ``Architecture, Ceremonial, and
Power,'' an architectural history of Topkapi Palace in the 15th and
16th centuries. ``The rest were girls in their teens who were
educated full time, before being promoted to serve the sultan or
his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The word harem refers not only to concubines but also to a space
of absolute privacy. The term derives from the Arabic harim, an
inviolable area. Thus the harem was less about sexuality than about
power. Privacy was a reflection of power, and so was the ability to
share your living quarters with hundreds of people without
sacrificing privacy. Their numbers counted for nothing. This was
not a public space.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky matter may also have less to do with sexuality than
with privacy as an expression of power. The White House and the
office of the independent counsel both want to operate in secrecy.
Both sides complain about leaks while making them. Both claim
immunity from public scrutiny. And the public remains fascinated
not only by this contest of wills but by its own conflict between
the desire to expose and the desire to overlook what is going on
behind both sets of closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us would prefer not to know about private goings-on,
either at the White House or in the grand jury room. But we
understand that democracy doesn't work that way. Public officials
are subject to public scrutiny, and it cannot be left to individual
officials to draw the line between public and private realms. The
information coming out of Washington may not be pitched on
civilization's highest plane. But the conflict is generating the
raw material from which meaning can arise.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings as well as cities can be animated by the interplay
between exposure and disregarding. Two of Washington's most
important buildings in recent decades draw on that dynamic. Set
below ground level on the Mall, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial is
nearly invisible from a distance. But the soft swell of earth and
the slow movement of people draws the visitor toward the footpath
and into the design: first the chevron of black granite, then the
names of the dead and the reflections of self and others hovering
ghostlike behind the names. Ultimately, one's own emotions stand
exposed: painful memories not only of the war abroad but of the
conflict the war generated at home.
</P>
<P>
   The granite facade of the United States Memorial Holocaust
Museum mimics the classical dictates of official Washington, but
with an exaggerated sense of hollowness and vacancy. Thus the
facade becomes a symbol of the deception and concealment of the
totalitarian state. Inside, the barbarism and madness of Nazi
Germany are exposed almost beyond the viewer's tolerance, not only
by the exhibits but also by the harshness and distortions of the
building itself. At the roofline, a series of brick forms
resembling watchtowers recalls the state's surveillance of those
deprived of all right to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   By using different kinds of dynamic interplay between
transparency, opacity and reflection, some of New York's greatest
modern buildings also draw on the friction between exposure and
tuning out: the CBS Building, the Ford Foundation, the Seagram
Building, the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Chase Bank on
Fifth Avenue at 43d Street. And recently, Raimund Abraham's design
for the Austrian Cultural Institute demonstrates that this theme
has not been artistically exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, a suburban mentality has gripped the
city's designers. In her classic study, ``The Moral Order of a
Suburb,'' the sociologist M.P. Baumgartner suggests that suburbs
are driven by the desire to ignore conflict. In affluent suburban
communities, she writes, people regard conflict as a ``social
contaminant,'' something to be prevented if at all possible and
ended quickly once begun. ``Should interpersonal conflicts have
positive functions or be in any sense a desirable property of
social life, these suburbanites are unaware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar outlook has taken hold in places like Battery Park
City. Modeled after New York's residential architecture of the
1920s, the buildings disregard the extent to which the city has
changed since then. Instead of allowing architecture to respond
imaginatively to the changing city, these buildings stick glumly to
the lowest common denominator of taste.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Giuliani's plan for an emergency management bunker
sounds suspiciously like a harem: an inviolable area of privacy
that symbolizes the Mayor's view of his power. And this bomb-proof
seraglio is philosophically of a piece with Giuliani's so-called
civility campaign. Civility is fine, but stifling criticism is not,
nor is trying to evade public scrutiny as by, for instance, burying
plans for the harem in the city budget.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, the civility campaign is anti-urban as well as
undemocratic. Most politicians recognize that in the
post-industrial age, culture is not just an ornament of the city
but a cornerstone of its future. Without culture there is no city,
and without conflict there is no culture. The only good thing about
the civility campaign is the rudeness with which it has been waged
(mayor to Grammies: Get Lost!). Museums, theaters and concert halls
are all magnificent public attractions, but conflict remains the
most important cultural product a great city puts out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
