<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS ON THE CANALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
(JT) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ In many cities the hotels with the best
locations and views command the highest prices. But in Amsterdam a
web of canals threads through the central city, insuring that even
those without deluxe accommodation budgets can ensconce themselves
in rooms with glorious waterfront views.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, who works in Amsterdam, has become an expert on
hotels and restaurants that tourists often overlook. For my visit
in March, she suggested the Ambassade, a hotel created out of 10
adjacent houses four and five stories high along the posh
Herengracht (one of the city's central canals) that the two owners
began converting in 1953. A 10-minute walk from the heart of
downtown Amsterdam, the small, intimate and elegant Ambassade is
not precisely a business hotel: There are no answering machines or
faxes in each room, although voice mail has since been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want a slightly larger hotel but like the notion
of living in the period houses the Dutch favor, there is the
Pulitzer, also close to the heart of the city, but with 224 rooms
and a more institutional feel.
</P>
<P>
   Many Dutch, particularly those who live in cities, speak
excellent English and are generally friendly. The staff at the
Ambassade, for example, is efficient at taking messages and making
restaurant reservations as well as finding museum and train
schedules, so a business traveler seeking a bit of atmosphere need
not feel out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   The Ambassade's rooms are $174 a night and suites are $228, with
tax (at 1.86 guilders to $1). My spacious room had a double bed
with large, soft pillows and a thick yellow bedspread-comforter,
which came in handy. The two reading chairs _ reproduction Louis
XVI _ were covered in yellow and pink striped silk that went nicely
with a small Louis XVI style writing desk and side tables.
</P>
<P>
   The spacious bathroom contained fluffy white terry robes, an
ample pile of towels and a hair dryer. And the bath was deep and
long enough to sink into after a full day of strolling.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast, which is included in the room price, can be ordered
through room service, which my daughter and I did the previous
evening. It arrived punctually, and we discovered that the Dutch
version of a bare-bones Continental breakfast is far more ample
than the French edition of rolls and coffee. Our breakfast included
boiled eggs, orange juice and three different breads.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch, avid chocoholics, like chocolate sprinkles or a thick
chocolate pudding-like spread atop their bread and butter. There
were small packets of the spread, as well as pate, peanut butter,
jams and honey.
</P>
<P>
   Room service is undoubtedly a luxury; still, breakfast in the
Ambassade's dining room, with its gleaming laquered white walls, is
itself a treat. The glass panes of the two-story windows are
meticulously polished, and the white and blue tablecloths are just
as painstakingly ironed. For more than the standard breakfast, the
buffet offered a selection of cereals and yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   There is no bar as such, but one can order drinks in the large
sitting room, which has a dramatic view of the canals and is
furnished with some stunning antiques, including a signed 1700s
Dutch grandfather clock.
</P>
<P>
   My outdated guidebook said that the Rijksmuseum was closed on
Monday, but the hotel staff knew that major museums are now open
seven days. They also quickly got the train schedule for the Hague
when I made a pilgrimage to the Mauritshuis, one of the country's
greatest small museums.
</P>
<P>
   Umbrellas are a necessity in the Netherlands, where it rains
often. A large collection sits in the lobby, and guests can use
them for the day, a gesture for which I was particularly grateful
on a morning where I awoke to a rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it does rain so much the Dutch are avid readers.
There are often lines at the checkout counters in bookstores, and
the hotel, small as it is, stocked the International Herald
Tribune, The Wall Street Journal, USA Today, Time and Newsweek in
the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Though the hotel now has just 52 rooms, the owners are
remodeling the 10th house, which faces the Singel canal, and will
have six more rooms and a second elevator by the end of 1999. About
two thirds of the rooms face directly onto the canal, so be sure to
ask and reserve well ahead. Even in rainy March, the hotel was
heavily booked.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year the Ambassade opened a flotation-tank and
massage center down the street. But hotel guests have no priority
over the general public, so floats ($27 for 45 minutes) and
massages ($32 for 45 minutes) are often booked in advance; reserve
on arrival or earlier.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
