u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-MEDIAGUIDES-COX     07-07 0160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MEDIAGUIDES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longhorns are No. 1 - at least in media guides
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It is no cause for an orange Tower, riotous
swarming of the Drag, parades or gaudy trophies.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're a proud University of Texas alum who needs
something in the athletic program to be proud about, there's this
recent development:
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, the Longhorns won six national titles, including a
sweep of the three big men's sports _ football, basketball and
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   For media guides.
</P>
<P>
   When bragging, that last part's on a need-to-know basis.
</P>
<P>
   At its recent convention in Spokane, Wash., the College Sports
Information Directors of America also honored the UT guides for
men's swimming and diving and men's track and field as tops in the
nation. The women's basketball guide cover was also chosen No. 1;
the guide itself No. 2 behind Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Of the school's 15 media guides, 11 fini
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV     07-07 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV12-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AMSTERDAM: or earlier.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In contrast to the tranquil, cozy Ambassade, the Hotel Pulitzer
Hotel, now an ITT Sheraton, bustles with three restaurants, an art
gallery and a new business center with rentals of personal
computers, faxes, laser printers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Ambassade it is made up of a series of internally
joined landmark homes that border two canals, in this case the
Prinsengracht and Keizersgracht.
</P>
<P>
   Many of its 224 rooms in the 24 adjacent buidings offer water
views as extraordinary as those at the Ambassade and the staff at
the Pulitzer, though more harried, attempts to be accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   Here the similarities end, however. The Pulitzer is larger and
more impersonal and more oriented to the business traveler. Because
the hotel owns houses on two canals and has interconnected them,
the lobby essentially runs from the entrance on the Prinsengracht
through to the main restaurants, which are on the Keizersgracht.
The lobby now includes a lounge that serves coffee and snacks
beginning at 8 a.m., a nice touch because many flights from the
United States arrive early in the morning before rooms are ready.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those rooms are decorated similarly, in the pink-beige
that seems to be generic in many American hotels. My comfortably
large room had the requisite pale beige rugs, wicker furniture with
pink upholstery and a wicker table and desk. The bedspreads,
predictably, were also pinkish. The bath was modern and clean, and
comfortably large. But ordinary decor could not undermine the
stunning views across the Prinsengracht from my fifth-floor room.
</P>
<P>
   Those views are particularly magical at night. Not only are the
most popular bridges illuminated with tiny lights around their
arches, but in the center of Amsterdam, many buildings are
illuminated, too. And the doors and windows are impeccably painted
to a shining gloss as if responding to some official mandate to
keep up appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch often leave their curtains open, perhaps a remnant of
the Calvinist belief that draped windows might hide sins. Often,
while walking, one can peek in on families at home. And from both
my hotel rooms I could get glimpses into dining rooms and bedrooms
missed at the street level.
</P>
<P>
   Although my room at the Pulitzer overlooked the water, the young
woman who gave me a tour of other rooms explained that some rooms
are on the interior garden, which is indeed lovely and boasts some
sculptures, and some are on an internal courtyard. The rooms on the
canal and the garden cost $304 to $339 a night, and 80 of the
Pulitzer's rooms have been redecorated either in a scheme of green
and red, or blue and gold. All have data-port phones and a handful
offer faxes, copiers and larger desks. The rooms on the courtyard
are $263 to $309. In booking ahead, it might be wise to pin down
what view you would like and ask for a written confirmation. The
hotel does not have an exercise room, although most tourists walk
so much in Amsterdam, they might well be too tired to face a gym.
</P>
<P>
   I was not told, nor was my travel agent, that the hotel was
undergoing expansion, and though the noise was not bothersome, much
of the lobby was not really usable.
</P>
<P>
   The renovations (now complete) did not excuse the lack of diet
cola and a bottle opener in the otherwise well-stocked mini-bar,
but it may have triggered a cable problem that shut down all the TV
sets in the hotel for several hours after I arrived.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pulitzer, breakfast was not included in the room price.
The informal dining area is a wicker wonderland that could be in
any United States city, but the view gives away the location: It
overlooks a canal and a slew of shops including a flower stall
where, even in the pouring rain, plants were everywhere. The $17.75
breakfast included a buffet table with dry cereals and hot plates
with scrambled eggs, sausages and bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the remodeling, the more modest dining room was
closed for dinner, though a casual bar was open. Given the weather,
three of us decided to eat at de Goudsbloem, the hotel's fancier
restaurant. It was costly though intriguing because the menu,
according to my Dutch guest, was inordinately ambitious. Although
it changes regularly, the lineup that night was typical. Among the
appetizers: salad of baked breast of pigeon with horse mushrooms
and a beet-root vinaigrette ($14.25) and a salad of candied veal
cheeks with kumquats and caraway vinaigrette ($9.25). Main courses
included a choice of filet of suckling pig covered with a crust of
garlic and tarragon juice ($21.25) or a tart of guinea fowl in a
crust with a sauce of onions ($21.25). The green dining room was
quiet and a bit formal, with classical columns separating one part
of the dining room from the other, and tables comfortably far
apart. Service was friendly and the food adequate. The bill for
three, with tip, was $135.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed good value in contrast to the coffee I ordered the
morning I left, for which I was charged $1.75. The good news: It
was delivered to my room at 6 a.m. on the dot as requested, and a
friendly doorman with the necessary large umbrella showed me to my
waiting cab.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Ambassade, 341 Herengracht, 1016 az Amsterdam, telephone
(31-20) 626-2333, fax (31-20) 624-5321. The 52 rooms range from
$174 for a standard double to $228 for a suite (at 1.86 guilders to
$1). Rates include breakfast, service and tax. Rooms are decorated
individually and each has the personal feel of a chic apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Pulitzer, 315-331 Prinsengracht, 1016 gz Amsterdam,
(31-20) 523-5235, fax (31-20) 627-6753. It has 224 rooms; those on
either the canals or the garden are $304 to $349 a day, on the
courtyard $263 to $309. Breakfast and taxes are extra. Some higher
priced rooms have computers and faxes. The staff suggests calling
Sheraton reservations, (800) 325-3535, for possible discounts.
</P>
<P>
   With both hotels, a written confirmation is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
