<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND INVESTIGATES TRIPP'S TAPING OF LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Linda Tripp returned to the federal grand jury
investigating the Lewinsky matter, Maryland officials said Tuesday
that they had begun a separate criminal inquiry into whether Mrs.
Tripp violated a state law that makes it a crime for one person to
record a telephone conversation without the consent of the other.
</P>
<P>
   A Maryland prosecutor has convened a grand jury to begin
investigating whether Mrs. Tripp should be prosecuted for taping
about 20 hours of telephone conversations she had with Monica
Lewinsky, a fellow Pentagon worker, beginning last year. The tapes
formed the basis for the Lewinsky inquiry that began nearly six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But any prosecution against Mrs. Tripp could be problematic
because she has received two grants of immunity, one from the
Whitewater independent counsel's office and the other from a
federal judge in a sealed order, lawyers and other people involved
in the Lewinsky matter said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said those grants of immunity sharply limited the ability
of any prosecutor to use either the tapes or testimony by Mrs.
Tripp to build a criminal case against her for unlawful telephone
taping.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about her possible liability under Maryland law, Mrs.
Tripp decided to become a cooperating witness last January only
after receiving the grants of immunity, lawyers involved in the
case said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for immunity and she got it,'' said James Moody, her
lawyer at the time. ``I knew it was routine for whistle-blowers to
be in fear of retaliation and so I made the request for the
immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order relies on a federal law that says no testimony
or evidence directly or indirectly received from a witness ``may be
used against the witness in any criminal case, except a prosecution
for perjury, giving a false statement, or otherwise failing to
comply with the order.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the Maryland prosecutor, Stephen
Montanarelli, knew the extent of the immunity that has been
conferred on Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp has become a central witness in the investigation by
the independent counsel into whether anyone committed perjury or
obstruction in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against
President Clinton. Mrs. Tripp has told investigators in the
independent counsel's office that Ms. Lewinsky encouraged her to
lie in the lawsuit about Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the
president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Mrs. Tripp completed her third day of testimony before the
grand jury here, her lawyer Anthony Zaccagnini appeared on the
courthouse steps Tuesday to read a statement she had issued about
the Maryland grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe today's announcement is the latest in a series of
attempts to intimidate me,'' the statement said. ``This is
evidenced by the fact that this occurs at the very moment I am
testifying before the federal grand jury. I am not intimidated in
any way. I will continue to testify truthfully and completely and I
urge everyone involved to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaccagnini met Tuesday with officials in the independent
counsel's office to discuss the Maryland inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, who is in Southern California, suggested through
her spokeswoman that she was pleased by the decision of the
Maryland prosecutor to open the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American has the right to and the expectation of privacy
in their private conversations,'' said the spokeswoman, Judy Smith.
``The decision of the state attorney to empanel a grand jury to
investigate Linda Tripp and perhaps others concerning the recording
of private conversations will help establish that our cherished
right of privacy cannot be trampled on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Mrs. Tripp said they expect her to return to the
grand jury Thursday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
