</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAFURA-DELSBAUS-THEATER-$ADV12-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURIOUS FABRICATORS OF A FAUST FOR THE DIGITAL ERA  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ La Fura Dels Baus is as unusual a name in
Catalan as it is in English: the Ferret from the Baus. But there
was method to the fantasy of the five young street performers who
chose the name of their new experimental theater company in
Barcelona in 1979. The ferret, which can be trained but not tamed,
appealed to their anarchic instincts, while the Baus is the name of
a dark ravine near their hometown of Moya, 30 miles north of
Barcelona, where the five would hang out before they moved here in
their late teens. So it sort of made sense.
</P>
<P>
   The group has offered other, perhaps fanciful, translations in
the past. But by now the name has long outgrown deconstruction.
Today, at least to its legion of fans across Western Europe, La
Fura dels Baus is synonymous with an unorthodox, multidisciplinary
form of theater that uses loud music, violent movement, bizarre
machinery and almost no words to create a near-apocalyptic
atmosphere. It likes to perform before a standing audience in
nontheatrical spaces like plazas and warehouses, frequently taking
the action into the crowd. It has even spawned a Spanish adjective,
furero, to describe its special lenguaje furero, its Furan
language.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed appropriate, then, that Carlos Padrissa, one of La
Fura's founders, felt a need to explain, even justify, the break
with tradition represented by its latest work, ``F(AT)ust, Version
3.0,'' which will be performed July 22 through 26 at the New York
State Theater as part of this year's Lincoln Center Festival. The
company has not surrendered to convention. Yet, for the first time,
it is presenting a theatrical work before a seated audience using a
written text, in this case inspired by no less than Goethe. Over
the past two months, the play has been performed here, mainly in
Catalan, at the National Theater of Catalonia. In New York, the
show, which lasts 99 minutes without a break, will be in Spanish
with English supertitles.
</P>
<P>
   So could it be that success is corrupting the enfants terribles
of La Fura into respectability? Or is the lenguaje furero now so
persuasive that it is penetrating mainstream theater? The way that
``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' came about suggests the latter. In 1996,
the Granada International Dance and Music Festival invited Padrissa
and another company member, Alex Olle, to try their hand at musical
theater. Their production of Manuel de Falla's ``Atlantida'' was
seen by Gerard Mortier, the director of the Salzburg Festival, who
promptly invited them to direct ``The Damnation of Faust'' by
Berlioz in Salzburg in 1999. It was as a result of this commission
that they turned their attention to the legend of Faust, and
``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' came about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read Goethe's `Faust' as a kid, but only Part I,''
recalled Padrissa, a wiry, balding man of 39. ``We began to read it
again and saw it would work for our language because Goethe was the
first to break with a linear sense of time. If the character of
Faust was eternally unhappy, he would be still unhappier at the end
of the millennium. So we decided to do a theater version of
`Faust,' but using our own methods. We remain loyal to the spirit
of the work, but the form is new.''
</P>
<P>
   Having seen ``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' here last month, Mortier
has now asked La Fura to take it to Salzburg along with ``The
Damnation of Faust'' next summer. How German and Austrian audiences
respond to this information-age reworking of Goethe's masterpiece,
in which the work's very name plays upon the language of software,
may be one of the more interesting footnotes of the 1999 festival.
``Our Faust is not a post-Renaissance elitist,'' Padrissa
explained. ``Today, with the Internet, anyone can have access to
information. Goethe's Faust had wisdom and was unhappy. Today
people become dissatisfied through information. That's why there
are more Fausts today. Faust can be all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with the non-Furans Pablo Ley, who adapted and wrote the
text, and Magda Puyo, who directed the eight actors brought in for
the play, Padrissa and Olle present their ``F(AT)ust'' as a secular
morality play: the combat is not between God and the Devil, but
between the good and evil sides of Faust's personality.
Mephistopheles appears, but he may also be Faust's imaginary alter
ego. Even Faust's ill-fated teen-age mistress, Margarethe, is cast
as the universal victim of all violence against the weak.
</P>
<P>
   Faust, who has cultivated reason all his life, is unhappy and
tries to kill himself,'' Padrissa said, summarizing the plot.
``When he fails, his neglected instinctive side says to him, `Give
me your life and I will give you happiness.' That's the pact. But
when his base instincts take over, he kills Margarethe's brother,
he leaves her pregnant, she kills her baby and Faust's unhappiness
grows until he finally shoots himself. In Part II, while Goethe has
him sleeping in a field in the Alps, our Faust lies paralyzed on a
hospital bed. With no body and only a mind, he now hallucinates
being visited by mythological figures. Finally, when he awakens, he
understands that thoughts can be as dark as, well, you know, sex,
drugs and rock and roll.''
</P>
<P>
   This story is told in lenguaje furero, with Faust's struggle
lived out through images taken from the Internet, television,
advertising and live video and projected on a giant screen,
accompanied by electro-acoustical music (with breaks for Mozart's
``Requiem'') played by a disk jockey acting the part of conductor.
Padrissa and Olle cannot resist including a few machines, like one
that spins Faust head-over-heels as if in training for a space
walk. And, as always, they come up with striking visual effects:
Faust hanging in a water-filled plastic bag as an unborn embryo, or
Faust and Margarethe courting as they climb a net of thick rope,
their shadows magnified on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take time to absorb everything,'' Olle, 38, said after
a warmly applauded performance here one recent evening. ``The hope
is that the images stay with them, maybe return to them later.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4444 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAFURA-DELSBAUS-THEAT     07-07 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAFURA-DELSBAUS-THEATER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BARCELONA, Spain: them later.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Padrissa, Olle is a company veteran, although he was not
one of the five original founders from Moya whose theatrical roots
were very much in the tradition of village fiestas. By the time he
joined in 1981, La Fura was growing rapidly _ at one point it had
30 members _ and was putting on improvised shows at alternative
sites across Barcelona. Then in 1984 the company was reduced to
just nine young men, because only nine would fit into a small van,
and began touring Catalonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment was important,'' Padrissa said. ``Franco died in
1975 and suddenly everything seemed possible. But by 1984, the
fight for freedom was over and economic recession had set in. The
dream was over for those who thought the world would change. The
reality was a lot of unemployment. The fiesta element of our work
evaporated. We created apocalyptic scenes to make people react,
like electric shock treatment. We'd smash cars, set off explosions,
burn sets, whatever. All to music.''
</P>
<P>
   With its first formal creation, ``Accions,'' in 1984, La Fura
established its theatrical language. And this was developed in five
other works that have been described as spectacles of controlled
techno-mayhem: ``Suz/o/Suz'' (which was part of the New York
International Festival of the Arts in 1991), ``Tier Mon,''
``Noun,'' ``MTM'' and, most recently, ``Manes.'' All of these have
toured widely in Europe, with the company winning a particularly
strong following in Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992, La Fura began to strike out in new directions. Until
then, its members did everything: directing, composing, building
machines and performing. However, when they presented a spectacular
show to accompany the globally televised opening of the Barcelona
Summer Olympics in 1992, they needed a cast of 1,500. And since
then, the company members _ there are seven now, all men _ have
taken to hiring actors to perform their pieces, leaving themselves
time for further diversification. Pera Tantina _ he and Padrissa
are the only members of the Moya Five to remain in La Fura _ is
involved with ``Manes''; Miki Espuma is concentrating on
composition; and Hansel Cereza, Jurgen Muller and Pep Gatelli are
currently preparing new shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVOLUTION-EDUC-NYT &LR;      07-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLUTION'S ADVOCATES BEGIN TACKLING PUBLIC DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ As a major scientific field,
evolutionary biology is in an extraordinary position: its basic
tenets, surveys show, are rejected as false by one of every two
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Further, at a time when an increasing number of school districts
are endorsing the teaching of creationism, evolutionary biology can
be a particularly incendiary topic in discussions of education.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the furor, though, one group has kept a surprisingly
low profile. Now that is apparently about to change. The oldest and
largest professional association of evolutionary biologists, the
Society for the Study of Evolution, an international body of some
3,500 scientists, has begun reaching out to a doubting public.
</P>
<P>
   The insular society, founded half a century ago, has long
focused on research and is hardly practiced at shaping public
opinion. It does not have a Web site or even a permanent office or
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   But at its annual meeting here in June, where many presentations
drew audiences of 20 or fewer, overflow crowds attended the
society's first session ever devoted to educational issues.
</P>
<P>
   A room big enough to hold 150 had evolutionary biologists
spilling into the aisles and even into the hallways, eager to hear
a discussion of why their field was so poorly understood and often
so poorly taught, at all levels _ and what they could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary biology is no stranger to hostility, from students
inside the classroom or school boards and politicians outside. In
recent years, the Tennessee Legislature has considered a measure,
ultimately rejected, to let school boards dismiss teachers who
present evolution as fact rather than theory; a Georgia district
has endorsed the teaching of creationism, which holds that all life
forms, including humans, were fully formed by a Creator and did not
evolve, and Alabama has approved a disclaimer, to be inserted in
biology textbooks, calling evolution only ``a controversial
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   It was against such a backdrop that the evolutionary biologists
flocked to the education-issues session in Vancouver, organized by
Dr. Peter Wimberger, an evolutionary biologist at the University of
Puget Sound in Tacoma, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students don't come in doubting that F equals ma,'' Wimberger
said, referring to the familiar physics equation that force equals
mass times acceleration. ``But about half come in doubting the fact
that evolution occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting the potential power of professional societies, Irene
Eckstrand, chairwoman of the society's new education committee, led
off the session by proposing some basics like a resource list of
evolutionists willing to talk to schoolteachers and a Web site,
both of which are now being developed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she announced that the society would have an
evolution workshop and booth this November at the annual meeting of
the National Association of Biology Teachers, in Reno, where the
society will be represented by Dr. Stephen Palumbi of Harvard
University and Dr. David Jablonski of the University of Chicago.
The organization is also preparing its own teacher training
workshop for its annual meeting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers described model projects in progress, which try
to make evolution not only believable but also quite real to
students at every level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole creation-evolution issue rears its head every time
you teach,'' said Wimberger, who described a collaborative project
in which Washington state high school students collect data on
genetic variation, the basis of evolutionary change, from salmon
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To these students, salmon are familiar,'' Wimberger said.
``They're a cultural icon. They're the focus of conservation
issues. This gets the students doing something real.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jackie Brown of Grinnell College described experiments for
college laboratories, a rare component of evolution classes,
including one in which students go into the field and measure the
strength of natural selection on a fly. As maggots, the flies live
in plant tissue and produce a ball-like growth around themselves
known as a gall. Students discover that the chances of a maggot's
being killed by a predator or a parasite _ the strength of natural
selection _ are highly dependent on the size of its gall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demystifies natural selection,'' Dr. Brown said of the
experiment. It is ``not something that just descends from above.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Alters, a science education specialist at McGill
University and Harvard, drew the largest audience of the session
with his presentation of findings on why even college students are
prone to reject evolution. Religious issues aside, the obstacles
are plentiful, said Dr. Alters, who surveyed more than 1,000
students from 10 universities across the United States and found
that they ``always came back to things that most scientists would
consider scientific misconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Students who reject evolution, Alters determined, are much more
likely than those who accept it to subscribe to misconceptions like
believing that the methods used to date fossils and other rocks are
not accurate, that mutations are never beneficial to animals, that
it is statistically impossible for life to arise by chance and that
there is scientific evidence that humans were supernaturally
created.
</P>
<P>
   Alters reported that even in a survey of science education
graduate students _ those who will go on to careers as
schoolteachers or as teachers of teachers _ 20 percent said they
did not accept evolution (although that 20 percent said they would
teach it).
</P>
<P>
   Given findings like those, the evolutionary biologists came away
from the conference committed to more outreach and perhaps even
politics, from which they have always kept a marked distance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike professional associations with offices in Washington, the
society ``hasn't been an advocate,'' said its secretary, Dr. Daphne
Fairbairn of Concordia University in Montreal. ``It hasn't done
lobbying or politics. We may do more of that in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
