u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTO-RICO-STRIKE-NY     07-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN LABOR PROTEST DISRUPTS TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Chanting ``struggle yes, surrender no,''
strikers blocked access to San Juan's international airport for
several hours Tuesday morning on the first day of a 48-hour general
strike aimed at halting the government's sale of Puerto Rico
Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
   The airport protest brought traffic to a standstill on San
Juan's main thoroughfare, the Baldorioty De Castro Expressway, and
forced tourists to walk for more than a mile from their buses to to
the airport terminal.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, riot police, who had been surprised by the
pre-dawn blockade, reached an agreement with protesters that
allowed traffic to begin flowing back into the airport.
</P>
<P>
   But bus service was also brought to a halt in San Juan, and most
taxi drivers opted not to work in a show of solidarity. The Puerto
Rico Tourism Co. and private hotels provided transportation for
guests to and from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said that about a half million workers from over
50 labor unions have joined the two-day strike, with picket lines
and boisterous demonstrations outside government offices, banks and
commercial centers across the island.
</P>
<P>
   Most shopping malls, including the Caribbean's largest, Plaza
Las Americas, have closed during the strike. Likewise, the island's
largest bank, Banco Popular de Puerto Rico, shuttered its 198
island branches. Its parent, Popular Inc., is involved in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Many offices and banks in the Hato Rey financial district were
also closed, as were shops in the usually bustling tourism sectors
of Old San Juan and Condado.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders prepared for the strike on Monday as if bracing for a
hurricane, with merchants erecting steel shutters over store
windows and residents stripping supermarkets bare of essentials
like water, batteries, bread and milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very successful,'' said Annie Cruz, president of
the labor coalition the Umbrella Committee of Labor, Civic,
Cultural, Political and Religious Groups, known by its Spanish
acronym as CAOS. ``We have been able to paralyze the airport. Banco
Popular has closed. The commercial centers are closed.''
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines canceled a 7:30 a.m. Miami flight because only
59 of its 138 passengers were able to reach the airport. LIAT
airlines, based in Antigua, canceled all its San Juan flights,
while two cruise ships, Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines' The Grandeur
of the Seas and Carnival Cruise Lines' Destiny, canceled scheduled
stops at San Juan harbor. Hoteliers were reporting some
cancellations as well.
</P>
<P>
   False bomb threats and fake bombs kept police on alert
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-hour strike was called last week to support 6,400
telephone company workers who walked off their jobs June 19 in an
effort to stop the sale of their company.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium led by GTE Corp. proposes to buy a 50 percent plus
one share stake in the utility in a $1.875 billion deal, which has
been approved by the governor and Legislature but still must get
Federal Communications Commission approval. Spain's Telefonica
Internacional also placed a bid for the utility, which government
officials are still considering. Workers fear a sale will lead to
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Saboteurs have inflicted an estimated $2.59 million worth of
damage on telephone company installations since the strike began.
More than 260,323 customers have had their telephone service
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Anger at Banco Popular, which is seeking to purchase a 5 percent
stake in the telephone company as part of the GTE group, is
especially high. Two bombs have exploded at bank branches, One of
them blowing off a policeman's finger. Overnight, gunmen also
riddled one San Juan branch with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the unions participating in the strike represent workers
for government public corporations that control essential services
such as water and electricity. Other unions represent airport, port
and bus workers. No widespread electric or water outages were
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Private sector unions, from teamsters to hotel workers, also
took part in the strike. Their concerns go beyond the sale of the
telephone company, because the administration of Gov. Pedro
Rossello has launched an aggressive campaign to sell government
hotels, hospitals and other assets. The unions accuse the
pro-statehood administration of selling the national patrimony.
</P>
<P>
   The governor remained steadfast on selling the telephone
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't change our determination to sell La Telefonica,''
Rossello said at a mid-day news conference. ``These decisions
aren't taken by intimidation. They aren't taken by who pushes more
or who shouts louder. They are taken on the basis of what is
reasonable, and what is best for the common good.''
</P>
<P>
   A previous attempt to sell the telephone company in 1990 under
former Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon failed because of large labor
protests and political opposition. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
