A4457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      07-07 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THREATS AND LOSING CASH IN GM STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ A monthlong strike by the United Automobile
Workers against General Motors Corp. is starting to drain the cash
reserves of both sides and is prompting GM in particular to begin
reviewing ways to save money.
</P>
<P>
   GM and the UAW both have enormous financial strength, and
neither needs to call a truce soon for lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   But the erosion of GM's market share as the company's dealers
run out of cars and light trucks poses a more serious risk to the
company and its employees. Some lost customers may defect to rival
automakers and never come back, GM executives warn, and some UAW
officials privately acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators participated in lengthy meetings Tuesday as both
sides struggled to settle the dispute, which began with a quarrel
over whether workers at a parts factory were collecting a full
day's pay for four to six hours of work and over whether GM had
broken a promise to invest more money here.
</P>
<P>
   GM has raised the stakes by threatening to close some of its car
factories permanently to become more competitive. The UAW has
responded by threatening further strikes this autumn at important
parts factories in Dayton, Ohio, and Indianapolis, where workers
also want GM to increase investment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
that the union would like to settle outstanding issues at the
Dayton and Indianapolis factories as part of a deal here.
</P>
<P>
   But while both sides would like a deal by Thursday, which would
allow a ratification vote over the weekend and a resumption of
production Monday, the growing number of disputes has made it
harder to reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
   A constant worry for the union is that if GM is pushed too far,
it might simply sell Delphi Automotive Systems, its sprawling auto
parts subsidiary. A new owner would be a tough bargaining opponent
for the UAW, because the new owner would not have the numerous,
high-cost assembly plants that make GM vulnerable to UAW strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite union objections, GM sold four parts factories in 1996
to Peregrine Inc., an auto parts company. Peregrine announced
Tuesday night that it would close two of the factories: one here in
Flint and the other in Livonia, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   All 1,000 UAW workers at the two closed factories will be
allowed to transfer back to GM under a deal negotiated by the UAW
two years ago, but the closings confirmed some of the union's worst
fears.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already said that the strike cost it $1.18
billion in after-tax losses during the second quarter, but in
recent days GM officials have been expressing more concern about
the strike's effects on the company's $13.6 billion in cash
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The last big UAW strike against GM, a 17-day walkout in 1996,
temporarily reduced the company's cash reserves by $2.3 billion, as
the company continued to pay the salaries of white-collar employees
and bills from outside suppliers of auto parts, but no longer took
in money from selling new cars and light trucks to dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The current strike has lasted 32 days, although the last 11 days
have fallen during the company's annual two-week summer shutdown,
when GM always experiences a temporary drain of cash. Donald
Hackworth, GM's group vice president for North American car
operations, said Tuesday that the company was seeking to reduce the
outflow of cash.GM
</P>
<P>
   GM has already taken many small steps to stanch the loss of
cash. It has turned the power off at assembly plants closed by the
strike, a step that will add a day or two to the time needed to
restart them later. GM has also cut back on business travel,
off-site meetings and the use of consultants.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street analysts said GM had enough cash for a prolonged
confrontation. ``It's going to take a very, very long time for GM
to face any real liquidity concerns as a result of the strike,''
said Scott Sprinzen, the chief auto credit analyst at Standard &AMP;
Poor's. GM can easily borrow money or sell car loans to raise
money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Girsky, an auto analyst at Morgan Stanley, said that in
addition to the $1.18 billion in lost profits, GM's cash reserves
had likely fallen by an additional $3 billion as bills came due for
auto parts purchased before the strike. The impact on the cash
reserves should now slow, he said, as GM stops further purchases of
parts and because the company has laid off many workers.
</P>
<P>
   The union is also finding the strike expensive, but, like the
company, can afford to continue on its course. While union
officials refuse to provide precise numbers, the strike appears to
have taken about $10 million so far from a $725 million strike
fund, which is one of the largest in organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has been paying $150 a week in strike benefits to 9,200
striking workers here, and has been covering their health care
costs since July 1, when GM stopped its medical coverage for them.
</P>
<P>
   GM has filed petitions with state governments asking that they
not pay unemployment benefits to nearly 120,000 UAW workers that GM
has laid off, because GM contends that they are indirectly involved
in the strike through their union membership and therefore should
be ineligible for unemployment compensation. GM filed similar
petitions in 1996, and while most states rejected them, Texas
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, union officials said that they had already decided
to pay $150 a week in strike benefits to 1,400 workers at a sport
utility vehicle factory in Arlington, Texas. The workers would have
to repay the money if Texas later decided to pay unemployment
benefits anyway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
