<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-FIGHTING-AR     07-07 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-FIGHTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH NEW TOOLS, FLORIDA FIRES PRESENT A HUGE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tools for fighting wildfires these days include airplanes to
dump chemicals and water, satellites to locate hot-spots and laptop
computers to keep track of blazes, trucks and people. But the
firefighters' basic technique has been the same for decades: trying
to throw a defensive perimeter around each fire, and praying for
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The essential work of firefighting is cutting down trees and
shrubs and building a dead zone with no fuel, because putting them
out in a large area is beyond human resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forest fires are monumental challenges,'' said Patrick
Reynolds, an assistant professor at a University of Cincinnati
program for training firefighters. Unlike house fires, wildfires
face few natural boundaries and have a continuous source of fuel,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Florida presents special challenges because of its lush
growth and its topography _ what there is of it. Unlike the western
United States, where firefighters can look down from mountaintops
to see fires, or stand in valleys and watch them climb ridges,
Florida is so flat that seeing a fire's progress from the ground is
nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant shrubs and a thick carpet of roots and decaying
vegetation also can shelter and nurture a fire for days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have a storm come through there and a few days later
it's burning again,'' said Jason Greenlee, executive director of
the International Association of Wildland Fire, in Spokane, Wash.
Even after an inch or two of rain, he said, ``once the sun comes
out, that moisture's being evaporated off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're really going to need a good gully-washer to put these
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers Tuesday did little to put out the small fires
that continued to smolder among the burned trees, The Associated
Press reported. Fifty-four new fires broke out statewide on Monday,
burning 8,700 new acres, according to AP.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is a ``fire-dependent ecosystem,'' said David Bunnell, a
forester at the Department of Agriculture, but this is not the kind
it needs. Bunnell, based at the Interagency Fire Center in Boise,
Idaho, said that the native pine species, loblolly, long leaf and
sand pine, are fire-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   In small fires, as the bark heats up, flakes pop off the tree
before they burn, so that a fire must heat a new area of bark. But
those fires kill off oaks and other deciduous invaders, he said,
allowing the native pines to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   The natural system is based on fires every three to five years,
he said, and in places where people build their houses out in the
woods, ``social values'' intervene, meaning people impose their
preferences on nature.
</P>
<P>
   The small fires that would ordinarily clean out the undergrowth
of palmetto and gallberry are routinely extinguished by
firefighters before they can do so, he said, and ``prescriptive
fires,'' often ordered by forest managers to prevent such
build-ups, are banned because the forests' new neighbors see them
as smoke-causing nuisances, or threats.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bunnell said, in an especially dry year, the fires catch
up, and what follows kills everything.
</P>
<P>
   But the new tools now available can help firefighters intervene.
One tool is better weather forecasting, which can tell firefighters
when to expect strong winds or rain. Another is a hand-held
navigation unit that uses a global positioning system to keep
firefighters from getting lost. It can tell managers by radio
precisely where the fires and firefighters are.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline-powered pumps that can feed thousands of gallons from a
pond through a hose are now built light enough to be carried easily
by one person. New chain saws are designed better so they overheat
less often.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, firefighters use aircraft. Many are antiques like
DC-3s retrofitted for the job or military cast-off C-130's. One in
use now in Florida, a Canadair CL-415, a twin-engine turboprop,
skims over a lake or bay at 115 mph and lowers two probes that
scoop up 1,600 gallons in 12 seconds. Aloft gain, it can mix a
fire-retardant thickener into the water, so the foam it drops will
cling to vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   If the water source is near the fire, the Canadair can make 20
drops an hour or more, compared with one drop every 45 to 60
minutes for planes that must land at an airport, taxi to a loading
point, fill up and take off again. The plane, on loan from North
Carolina and operating this week out of Deland, Fla., can soak an
area 440 feet long and 50 feet wide, or 350 feet long and 80 feet
wide, depending on how the pilot drops his slug of water.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters can be even more precise and can dunk buckets into
water sources as small as swimming pools for quick runs back to the
target zones.
</P>
<P>
   But the fires can easily dwarf the resources. ``Even when we're
working with hoses and aircraft, we're only working the outer edge
of the fire,'' said Greenlee, the fire agency director, who works
part of each year as a smoke jumper. ``Once you get a fire
contained, maybe the order of the day will be, we're going to mop
up 100 yards in from the fire line. The next day, it might be 150
yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell, the agriculture department forester, said that in an
average year, firefighters could hope to surround some fires and
then march in and put some out. But, with a dry year and lots of
fuel available because of paucity of fires in the last few years,
he said, ``we cannot overwhelm this part of the natural process
with personnel and equipment and expertise.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
