<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SECRETSERVICE     07-07 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SECRETSERVICE-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES SECRET SERVICE OFFICIALS MUST TESTIFY IN
LEWINSKY INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dealing a sharp setback to the Clinton
administration, a federal appeals court on Tuesday ordered Secret
Service officials to testify before a grand jury about what they
knew of any relationship between President Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision handed down with unusual speed, the
three-judge panel rejected the Clinton administration's claim that
the Secret Service enjoyed a special privilege that was essential
to the president's safety and that shielded its officials from
having to testify. The judges said it was up to Congress to decide
whether to grant such a privilege.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision broadly dismissed the administration's claim
of a novel ``protective function privilege,'' it is not known
whether the ruling would have any practical effect on the inquiry
into whether anyone lied or obstructed justice about the
president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment suit. The independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, who
has suffered some legal setbacks in recent weeks, has been pressing
for months for the testimony of two uniformed officers and the
service's chief counsel. His investigators want to determine if the
officers discussed Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, with
the counsel, according to lawyers involved in the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Secret Service have said that they know of no
witnesses to anything improper involving Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky.
But with Tuesday's ruling, Starr's investigators can begin to
question more closely all of the guards and agents who watch over
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said on Tuesday that they had not
decided whether to seek an appeal of the decision by the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia .
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Service and the Justice Department are disappointed
by the D.C. Circuit's decision,'' said Bert Brandenburg, the
Justice Department's chief spokesman. ``We continue to be concerned
that any action that could distance the Secret Service from the
president increases the danger to his life and that of future
presidents. We are reviewing whether to appeal, and hope to have a
decision soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service had argued that if Starr established a legal
precedent by compelling agents to testify about the private lives
of the first family, Clinton and future presidents would push their
guards away, making protection impossible and risking future
assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision rejected that argument, noting that former
Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter had said that agents should
testify in a criminal case and that a federal law obliges all
presidents to accept protection.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing concerns raised by the director of the Secret Service
and many current and retired agents, the judges said concern over
whether a president keeps Secret Service agents at a distance was
unnecessary because of the president's own self-interest in having
his bodyguards stay close, regardless of the law governing
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a profound personal interest in being well
protected, and the president knows that effective protection
depends upon proximity to his protectors,'' the judges said,
paraphrasing a lower court decision that was affirmed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel, Judges Douglas Ginsburg, A. Raymond Randolph
and Stephen Williams, appeared to craft a carefully written opinion
that did not address some of the broader issues on the law
governing privileges. As such, the opinion does not appear to have
any direct impact on a second legal dispute, widely regarded as a
closer case, that is now before a different federal appeals panel
here. That case involves whether one of Clinton's closest aides,
Bruce Lindsey, can refuse to answer some grand jury questions on
the ground that they are protected by the lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has said that it is not involved in the
dispute between the Secret Service and the independent counsel,
declined to comment about Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Starr hailed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fundamental in our country that all law enforcement
officers cooperate fully in responding to requests for relevant
information in a federal grand jury investigation,'' he said in a
brief written statement. ``The Court of Appeals today reaffirmed
that bedrock principle, emphasizing that the rule of law is not
incompatible with the profound national interest in protecting the
life of the President. We trust that the Secret Service will now
join us in helping the grand jury gather information that is
relevant to this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has sought grand jury testimony from John Kelleher, the
chief counsel of the Secret Service, and from two uniformed
officers, Gary Byrne and Brian Henderson, according to lawyers
involved in the appeal. They said that investigators want to know
whether Byrne and Henderson discussed Ms. Lewinsky with Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that Byrne told Evelyn Lieberman, then
deputy chief of staff at the White House, in the spring of 1996
that he had seen Ms. Lewinsky in the West Wing when he did not
believe she was authorized to be there. Ms. Lieberman has said she
removed Ms. Lewinsky from her White House job at around that time
because of ``immature and inappropriate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The precise issue before the appeals court was whether Rule 501
of the Federal Rules of Evidence, the main rule on privileges,
should be interpreted so as to shield Secret Service officials and
agents from testimony about the president. The Secret Service has
already testified about a wide variety of matters at the White
House in the Lewinsky matter not directly involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks ago, federal district Judge Norma Holloway Johnson,
who is overseeing the grand jury inquiry into the Lewinsky
investigation, ruled that the agents can be compelled to testify.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In affirming that decision on Tuesday, the appeals court judges
found that the administration had failed to show by a clear and
convincing standard ``both the need for and the efficacy of the
proposed privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for need, the greatest danger to the President arises when
he is in public, yet the privilege presumably would have its
greatest effect when he is in the White House or in private
meetings,'' the court said. ``As for efficacy, we suspect that even
with a protective function privilege in place, conscience might
impel a President to distance himself from Secret Service agents
when engaging in wrongful conduct, as might a simple desire for
privacy at other times.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges rejected the administration's claim as to which
official can invoke the privilege, how long such a privilege might
last, whether the administration could use it to limit the
testimony of retired agents and how broadly it could be applied.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that the Secret Service does not require its agents
to sign confidentiality agreements and that it was unusual for the
administration to claim that the secretary of the Treasury holds
the privilege, not the president. The Treasury oversees the Secret
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Secret Service have been the most forceful
advocates of the proposed privilege, making it clear that, were it
up to them, they would take the matter to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But the final decision about an appeal rests with Attorney
General Janet Reno and the solicitor general, Seth Waxman. With the
administration having to rely on policy arguments because of the
dearth of legal precedent for such a privilege, some Justice
Department officials had previously cautioned against any appeals.
</P>
<P>
   If the administration does decide to seek a further review, it
has three options.
</P>
<P>
   It has seven days to decide whether to seek a rehearing before
the three judges or a hearing by the full appeals court. Or it
could file an appeal to the Supreme Court. The rules gives the
Justice Department 90 days to seek such an appeal, although the
independent counsel could try to force the issue by once again
calling Secret Service officers to the grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2055EDT &QL; 
