u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-UNINSURED-HNS &LR;      07-07 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-UNINSURED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.2 MILLION IN HOUSTON AREA HAVE NO HEALTH INSURANCE, STUDY
INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trims) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Almost one-third of the Houston-area population has
no health insurance, the highest percentage of uninsured among the
nation's largest metropolitan areas, a recent study indicates.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the Employee Benefit Research Institute,
used 1996 census bureau samplings to determine that about 1.2
million people, or 30.1 percent of the people in the eight-county
Houston metropolitan area, did not have health insurance. That
compares to a 18.2 percent average for 18 metropolitan areas
included in the study, and a 17.7 percent average nationwide. The
study excludes the elderly, who receive federal health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of uninsured in the Houston area is due to
factors common in a number of southern and southwest states that
traditionally have large numbers of uninsured, said Ken McDonnell,
an analyst with the Washington-based institute.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor, which has been successful in bargaining for
health-care benefits for its members, does not have a major
presence in Houston, he said. By contrast the Detroit area, with
its large number of unionized automotive workers, has an uninsured
rate of 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the region has a high percentage of Hispanics, many of
them noncitizens who do not qualify for public programs such as
Medicaid. Los Angeles and Miami, the metropolitan areas in the
study with uninsured rates approaching Houston's level, also have
large Hispanic populations.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, state and local governments in Texas have not
traditionally provided for the poor and unemployed as generously as
governments in other parts of the country, particularly the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the New York metropolitan area, about 14.4
percent of the population is enrolled in Medicaid, the
state-administered health insurance program for the poor. By
contrast about 8.9 percent of individuals in Houston are on
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern states are nonactivists. You don't see Texas
extending a lot of its Medicaid services to a lot of its people,''
McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   However, those reasons do not explain why the Houston rate is
higher than the 26.7 percent average for Texas and the 21.5 percent
average for the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, a smaller percentage of people are on Medicaid than
in Houston, but a much larger percentage get their health care
through their employers. In Dallas about 66.9 percent have
employer-based coverage compared to 57.2 percent in the Houston
area.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the federally defined Houston Consolidated
Metropolitan Statistical Area included Brazoria, Chambers, Fort
Bend, Galveston, Harris, Liberty, Montgomery and Waller counties.
</P>
<P>
   Health and insurance officials in Texas could not explain the
high rates for the Houston area, with several saying that earlier
studies showed the region ranked average among large cities. Those
studies could have encompassed larger or smaller areas and used
different census samples, McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Houston would be higher than the rest of the state, that's
a tough one,'' said Lee Jones, a spokesman for the Texas Department
of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year the state started a high-risk insurance pool for those
who have trouble getting health insurance. The program was set up
to comply with a new federal law that prohibits insurance companies
from dropping people with medical conditions or when they change
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in January the program has enrolled 1,202
people _ a number not likely to make much of a dent in the
uninsured in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones suggested that there are various reasons why people don't
have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people don't want it,'' he said, relating how some
workers would rather have bigger paycheck than benefits.
</P>
<P>
   However a union official said that the Houston area has long
been known as a low wage region where employers shun paying
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is a union presence you will have benefits and
where there isn't one you likely will not find them,'' said Richard
Shaw, the secretary treasurer of the Harris County chapter of the
AFL -CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said there are about 60,000 unionized workers in Harris
County, all of whom have health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hickman, who works for Watson Wyatt &AMP; Company, a benefits
consulting firm in Houston, speculated that the region may have a
high number of uninsured because of the large number of small
businesses that either offer no benefits or require an extremely
high co-payment by employees.
</P>
<P>
   Even though people may not have health insurance many still get
medical treatment and end up in taxpayer-funded facilities such as
those run by the Harris County Hospital District.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of health insurance was a major issue during
President Clinton's first two years in office when he proposed a
complex and ambitious plan to guarantee that all Americans have
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That plan was buried after it met fierce opposition from
employer groups and the insurance industry. However, the issue has
not gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the booming economy, about 3 million more people are
without health insurance now than when Clinton first took office,
according to the EBRI analysis, for a total of 41.4 million
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell said that many individuals who were laid off by large
corporations during the last recession had to settle for new jobs
that did not offer the same health care benefits. However, since
1993, the biggest reason for the increase in the uninsured has been
the decline in public sources for health insurance, such as the
military.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton announced he was moving to penalize
insurance companies that are not complying with a 1996 law that
bars health insurers from dropping people who change jobs or have
certain medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Government Accounting Office study found that some of
the large insurers were either charging exorbitantly high rates or
discouraging consumers from applying for policies under the new
law.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that insurers found to be violating the law would
be barred from participating in the Federal Employees Health
Benefits Program, which covers nine million people through 350
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The health care issue will be high on Congress' agenda next
week, when the House GOP leadership expects to introduce
legislation that provides some regulation of managed care plans,
including giving individuals more ability to appeal decisions made
by their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   That GOP bill also is expected to give trade associations the
ability to offer health plans to many of their members who may not
now be able to afford health care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have signaled they intend to make health care an
election year issue, charging that Republicans are not sufficiently
responding to the public's dissatisfaction with managed care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
