<HEADLINE>
BEING A GOOD CITIZEN IS GOOD FOR BUSINESS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Employers, whose low opinion of American public education has
generated much alarm in recent years, have come under growing
pressure to get involved with their local high schools by offering
everything from materials to tutorials about the world of work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the first nationwide study of corporate participation in
schools shows that by doing good, companies are also doing well.
Those that have worked closely with their local high schools show a
turnover rate among young employees that is as low as half that of
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the study shows, companies with close school
involvement look far more carefully at high school transcripts as a
basis for hiring decisions, something educators have been pushing
to raise their students' achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question that keeps being asked is, `Is being
a good corporate citizen good for business?''' said Robert Zemsky,
director of the Institute for Research on Higher Education at the
University of Pennsylvania, which carried out the study. ``This is
the first broad-based demonstration that employers who fit a common
definition of good citizen run their businesses differently, in
particular with regard to how young workers view them, and benefit
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The data are from the 1997 National Employer Survey,
administered by the Bureau of the Census, and involved a
representative sampling of all private businesses with 20 or more
employees. About 5,400 establishments responded to a telephone
survey, a response rate of 78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study classified about 25 percent of businesses as strongly
involved with schools, meaning they engaged in at least eight
activities listed by the researchers, like visiting classes,
tutoring, sponsoring clubs and assisting with curriculum
development.
</P>
<P>
   When comparing the annual rates for resignations and dismissals
of workers 18 to 25 years old within that group of companies, the
researchers said, the involved companies had ``a young-worker
turnover rate that is half the youth turnover rate for employers
that do not actively participate with high schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By actively engaging their local education systems,'' the
researchers said, ``establishments may be helping to generate a
future labor force that is more stable, more work-ready, and
presumably better matched to the workplace of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The data show a gradual drop in the rates of youth employee
turnover to 25 percent for companies with extensive involvement
from 50 percent among companies with little or no school
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The paper, written by Daniel Shapiro of the University of
Pennsylvania and Maria Iannozzi, an education writer, is to be
published in the September issue of The Annals of the American
Academy of Political and Social Science.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Census Bureau's survey was taken with guarantees of
anonymity, the researchers have not been able to follow up with
specific employers. The scholars said they needed to focus future
research on whether certain kinds of involvement produced the
retention results.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Phyllis Eisen, executive director of the Center for
Workforce Success at the National Association of Manufacturers,
said the study was significant. Many people have been arguing for
the value of corporate involvement in schools but there have been
virtually no data demonstrating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our organization's top priority _ to close the skills
gap and disconnect between school and work,'' Ms. Eisen said. ``In
this tight job market, we have seen a continuing trend of companies
worrying about the pipeline of future workers. Given their ongoing
anxiety about what high schools are producing, they are realizing
that they have to get more involved.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that companies were also motivated to help improve
local schools because potential employees being recruited from
other cities considered the quality of local schools to be among
the most important criteria in deciding whether to accept a job
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, employee turnover, especially among young workers, is
a source of great concern for businesses. Most transitions from
school to work are rocky with wasted time and many mismatches,
producing problems for young people and for the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much attention in recent years to school-to-work
programs modeled on apprenticeships in Europe. But Zemsky said
Americans seemed to require a different model. Instead of systems,
he said, Americans build informal networks.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, businesses have tended to run apprenticeships through
powerful guilds or chambers of commerce. But in this country, there
has been little appetite for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we find works is flexible and nonformulaic,'' Professor
Zemsky said. ``We want to make these young people more purposeful
and explicitly show them that if they want to work they have to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton Goldberg, executive vice president of the National
Alliance of Business, a nonprofit pro-business organization, said
he was pleased to hear about the emphasis on high school
transcripts. His group has started a campaign to increase the
importance of high school transcripts in hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early evidence suggests that, as a result of the campaign,
course-taking patterns are changing and schools' knowledge of what
companies want is improving,'' Goldberg said. ``We are also trying
to change transcripts so they give more information useful to
employers, like attitudes and teamwork skills.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that evidence was growing that when companies sent
representatives to schools, students were more motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly algebra and geometry in constructing a tractor become
real,'' Goldberg said. ``It is clear that when schools and
businesses communicate with one another and provide opportunities
for one another, it makes learning for youngsters far more relevant
to the world outside. Businesses are beginning to understand that
the quality of education is strongly related to the quality of life
in a community and that, in turn, is crucial for businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
