<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA CITES SMALL PROFIT, AFTER FORECASTING LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc., which warned Wall Street last month
that it was headed for its first losing quarter in 13 years, said
late Tuesday that it had instead managed to eke out a small
operating profit.
</P>
<P>
   Before a one-time charge, the company earned $6 million, or 1
cent a diluted share, in the second quarter, which ended June 27.
Analysts had expected a loss of 4 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was little sign behind the numbers that Motorola's
woes in its semiconductor and wireless communications markets had
bottomed out. Total revenue was $7.02 billion, down 6.6 percent
from $7.52 billion in the second quarter of 1997, and new orders
were down even more than sales in most of Motorola's major business
segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we indicated last month, the second-quarter results reflect
the further slowing of demand and continuing global pricing
pressure,'' said Robert Growney, Motorola's president and chief
operating officer, adding that the declines were ``driven primarily
by economic conditions in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola chief executive Christopher Galvin warned that Asia
would continue to hurt the company for at least the remainder of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The company released its results after the stock market closed.
Earlier, its shares rose $1.4375, or 2.7 percent, to $55. For the
year, its shares are down 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola had been regarded as a bellwether for the entire
technology sector and a major influence on the stock market because
it is among the first companies to report quarterly earnings. But
its results have increasingly been regarded as a suspect indicator
by analysts because many of its earnings disappointments in recent
quarters have been linked to a failure to keep up with innovation
in its key businesses rather than to general market conditions. The
company is still seen as a barometer of conditions in Asia because
it is among the leading multinational investors there, and
Tuesday's news was not very cheerful.
</P>
<P>
   Growney reported, for instance, that sales of Motorola's
semiconductor products fell nearly 11 percent, to $1.81 billion
from $2.03 billion, but that new orders fell 25 percent, led by a
large drop in Japan and Asia. The segment of the company that
includes paging took an even larger hit, with sales falling 35
percent, to $771 million. The decline hit North America but was
worse in the huge Chinese market, where pagers are often used as an
alternative to the primitive phone system.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pattern held in the cellular phone business, where
sales fell 1 percent, to $2.78 billion, while new orders tumbled 11
percent, led down by Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orders in their core businesses were pretty ugly,'' said Mark
McKechnie, an analyst with Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian economic woes hit Motorola in two ways, cutting demand
for products in a region where it once enjoyed booming growth while
also weakening Asian currencies enough to make Asian electronics
manufacturers more competitive with Motorola all over the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Mo4orola said that its previously announced plans to cut its
work force, close some semiconductor and paging operations and sell
off money-losing operations resulted in a $1.91 billion pretax
charge against earnings in the quarter, resulting in a net loss of
$1.3 billion, or $2.22 a fully diluted share, compared with
earnings of $268 million, or 44 cents a share, in the comparable
quarter a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The year-earlier quarter included a charge against earnings of
$190 million, or 20 cents a share after taxes, to cover the cost of
exiting memory chip operations.
</P>
<P>
   Growney repeated the company's projection that a planned
revamping should produce annual saving of $750 million a year once
it is completed next summer. Motorola has also told analysts to
expect news soon about the long-awaited introduction of a new
generation of digital cellular phones. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
