<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE CURTAIN AND INTO THE BRUTAL LAND OF 'OZ' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (JT)  
 By PAULA SCHWARTZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look for Dorothy or Toto. That's the other place. This is
Oz, short for Oswald Maximum Security Penitentiary. Emerald City,
the high-tech experimental prison-within-a-prison _ referred to as
Em City _ stresses rehabilitation. It's run by Tim McManus (Terry
Kinney), a 1960s throwback who believes even the most hardened
criminal can change. Ernie Hudson plays his boss, the warden, a
forceful authority figure who knows better.
</P>
<P>
   The critically acclaimed HBO drama series begins its second
eight-episode season July 13 at 10 p.m. (after sneak previews July
11 and 12.) All the episodes are written by Tom Fontana, who is
co-executive producer with Barry Levinson. They are also
responsible for NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Homicide'' is gritty, ``Oz'' is off the charts. It has full
frontal nudity, four-letter words and lots of sex and violence and
specializes in relentlessly gruesome details (like a close-up of a
charcoal-broiled prisoner or a man with a fork stuck in his neck).
There's a strong cringe factor.
</P>
<P>
   Things got difficult for the inmates last season. There were
warring ethnic groups and scores to settle, along with outside
forces like budget cuts and political backstabbing. Then officials
took away conjugal visits. A riot in the final episode left six
prisoners and two guards dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months later, as the new season begins, Oz reopens. Who
survived? At the beginning of last season no one would have banked
on Tobias Beecher (Lee Tergesen). The meek yuppie lawyer, jailed
for vehicular manslaughter, was almost normal. But that was before
he was beaten, sodomized, branded with a swastika and forced to
sing ``I've Got It Bad and That Ain't Good'' in drag. That's bound
to make a man mean. And the angel dust didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Only one man was not laughing while Beecher was forced to sing
his torch song in front of the entire prison population. That was
Ryan O'Reilly, standing in the shadows, leaning against a wall,
scheming, trying to figure out how he could use Beecher to his
advantage. The angel dust was his gift.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly is smart. He's easily the most dangerous character in
Oz. And not only because he forced a prisoner to eat ground-up
glass. He's Iago to Beecher's Othello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who died at Oz died directly or indirectly because of
O'Reilly,'' explains Dean Winters, the young New York actor who
plays the role. Yet if Internet interest is any indication,
O'Reilly is clearly the series' most popular character.
</P>
<P>
   Winters never expected that kind of fan adulation. ``I'm amazed
at the reaction to the character, especially on the street,'' he
says. ``They come up to me and profess their undying love for
O'Reilly. I mean, you have to wonder about those people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
