<HEADLINE>
CHANCELLOR MAKES A FORAY INTO TV WITH LIN PURCHASE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Chancellor Media Corp., the second-largest radio
company in the country, announced Tuesday that it would enter the
television industry with the acquisition of Lin Television Corp.
for about $902.7 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Lin, about 70 percent of which is owned by the buyout firm
Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, owns or operates 12 network-affiliated
stations in places like Connecticut, Buffalo, N.Y., and
Indianapolis, and has minority interests in NBC affiliates in
Dallas and San Diego. It is the 22nd-largest television broadcaster
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor owns and operates 108 radio stations in 22 of the
largest markets in the nation and has a combined weekly listener
base of more than 46 million people. Only the CBS collection of
radio stations is larger.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Muse, which is based in Dallas, holds stakes in both Lin
and Chancellor and will have an 18 percent ownership in Chancellor
if the acquisition of Lin is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition comes on the heels of an announcement last month
that Chancellor, which is based in Irving, Texas, would buy the
outdoor advertising business Martin Media LP. With the addition of
Lin, Chancellor can offer advertisers radio, television and
billboards in individual markets.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Chancellor can now combine Martin Media's outdoor
advertising in Hartford with Lin's two television stations in that
market. Hicks, Muse also owns 55 percent of Capstar Broadcasting
Corp., which also holds radio interests in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Marcus, who became president and chief executive of
Chancellor on June 1, said that the Lin acquisition ``gives us our
first leg in the television business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at our business as a three-legged stool,'' he said.
``Radio, television and outdoor.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, 51, came to Chancellor after a controlling interest in
the company he founded, Marcus Cable, was sold in April to Paul
Allen, co-founder of Microsoft Corp. He remains president and chief
executive of Marcus while he manages Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor will issue 17.7 million shares of stock to acquire
Lin. The exchange ratio is based on a price for Chancellor common
stock of $51 a share, which was the closing price on July 1, for a
total of $902.7 million. Chancellor will also assume $769 million
of Lin debt.
</P>
<P>
   The $902.7 million is less than Hicks, Muse paid last year for
Lin but represents a double-digit profit after including $815
million that the buyout firm recouped from selling a majority stake
in two Lin television stations to NBC, according to Joseph Jaffoni,
a Chancellor spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chancellor fell $3.0625 Tuesday, closing at $50.75.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Marsh, a senior broadcasting and publishing analyst at
Prudential Securities, said investors might be squeamish about the
taking on of television assets, which have generally had slower
growth than either radio or outdoor advertising, and therefore have
been trading at lower multiples.
</P>
<P>
   He added that some might question the deal because of Hicks,
Muse's connection to both the acquirer and the acquiree. ``I think
people are a little concerned when you're merging companies that
you own into a public company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Marsh called Lin a ``jewel'' in the TV broadcasting
industry, with high margins and esteemed management. Lin's
president and chief executive, Gary Chapman, will become president
of Chancellor's television operations and will take a seat on the
company's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid a full price but a fair price,'' Marsh said of the
transaction. Whether the deal benefits investors in the end depends
on whether Chancellor can push up the growth rate for its new
television segment, he said, adding, ``It's a tough call at this
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was scrutinized by Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Company for
fairness, said Jaffoni, the Chancellor spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said that his company would continue to look for good
television and outdoor advertising acquisitions, but that he
expected radio to remain its focus. After the Lin purchase, about
80 percent of the company's cash flow will still be from radio, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase also includes Lin's preferred stock position in the
Dallas Stars hockey team and the Texas Rangers baseball team.
Whether the company keeps that interest will depend in part on the
sale price paid when a company holding the teams goes public, as is
now being planned, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter advised Chancellor Media on the
transaction. Greenhill &AMP; Co. advised Lin Television. The
transaction is subject to a vote of Chancellor stockholders. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
