<HEADLINE>
JUDGES REJECT SIERRA BLANCA NUCLEAR WASTE DISPOSAL SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trims) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a stunning setback to proponents of a
low-level radioactive waste disposal site near Sierra Blanca, two
administrative law judges Tuesday recommended against issuing an
operating license for the project in the West Texas desert.
</P>
<P>
   They cited two factors: the uncertain potential for earthquake
damage to the proposed repository and unanswered questions about
the socio-economic impact on Sierra Blanca if it becomes home to a
second dump for imported toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
   The judges from the State Office of Administrative Hearings said
the license applicant, the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal
Authority, failed to prove that the Sierra Blanca site would not
pose an ``unreasonable risk to the health and safety of the public
or have a long-term detrimental impact on the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision said the disposal authority ``failed to adequately
characterize the fault directly beneath the site'' and failed to
``adequately address potential negative socioeconomic impacts from
the proposed facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonbinding recommendation was submitted to the three-member
Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, which by autumn is
expected to accept or reject the judges' ``proposal for decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling resulted from a series of tedious, technical hearings
spanning 10 weeks that pitted the state disposal authority and
nongovernmental backers, including utilities and medical centers
that generate low-level wastes, against a tiny band of Sierra
Blanca protesters who were backed by a few scientists and
anti-nuclear celebrities and even fewer politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the $34 million project site were planning to
accept waste beginning in 2000 for disposal in concrete canisters
that were to be placed in deep trenches designed not to allow
seepage into underground water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But fears that water in the Rio Grande, about 16 miles away,
could be contaminated caused Mexican officials to join vocal Texas
opposition, which centered on fears that Sierra Blanca would become
the ``nation's pay toilet'' because it already disposes of sewage
sludge from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The low-level waste site is needed, state officials said,
because of federal mandates that states find long-term burial plots
for the waste they generate. Texas, however, has plans to accept
waste from Maine and Vermont to help underwrite the expenses. Both
states are in the process of decommissioning nuclear plants and are
seeking final resting places for some large components.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Alvarado, the Texas disposal authority's chief engineer,
said officials were huddling to map their strategy in the wake of
the judges' recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very surprised and disappointed,'' Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that throughout the hearing we met our burden of
proof, that we demonstrated that there was a need for this facility
and that the location proposed for the facility near Sierra Blanca
was technically suitable. We still believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the TNRCC staff issued an environmental assessment that
concluded the license should be granted. That, he said, and the
fact that ``we don't feel that we are alone in this view'' could
cause the disposal authority to ask the commission to override the
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sit down and go through this and re-double our
efforts to satisfy whatever these concerns are and try to move
forward with this again,'' Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elated Sierra Blanca resident Bill Addington, a leader among
Hudspeth County residents who oppose the license, likewise
registered surprise at the recommendation. He had already drafted a
press release based on a finding in favor of a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't believe it,'' Addington said. But, he added,
``it's still not over. I still believe that politics has a major
role in this _ politics has been kicking this around for 14
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the commission, made up of appointees of Gov.
George W. Bush, ``could still say `yes,' and they probably will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be about science and about protecting
human health and safety. I just hope the governor will keep his
promise and listen to the administrative law judges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated his vow not to go through with the project if it
is deemed unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am troubled that two administrative law judges, who spent a
great deal of time reviewing the facts and listening to the
arguments in this case, do not feel the applicants have proven the
safety of the Sierra Blanca site,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said all along that if the site is not proven safe, I
will not support it. I urge the TNRCC to thoroughly review this
recommendation and the facts and to make their decision based on
sound science and the health and safety of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Generators of low-level radioactive wastes were meeting late
Tuesday to map their next move. Eddie Selig, director of Advocates
for Responsible Disposal in Texas, a group including utilities,
universities and medical centers, said ``we were disappointed and
surprised by the judge's decision. The TNRCC itself, the staff,
concluded that the issuance of a license for this proposed project
will not pose an unacceptable risk to public health.''
</P>
<P>
   A test trench has been dug at the proposed site, about five
miles east of Sierra Blanca and a few hundred yards from Interstate
10. But no other major construction has taken place, pending the
outcome of the licensing process.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative law judges noted that, ``no preferable
alternatives to the proposed facility have been established.'' But
they said the Sierra Blanca site might be suitable if it accepts
far less radioactive material than planned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
