<SLUG> BC-POLICESTUDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Human Rights Watch study: Police monitors no more than
ineffective 'paper tiger'
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An international human rights organization said
Tuesday that citizen review of police conduct in Atlanta is the
weakest of 14 cities it examined.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch said the citizen panel that monitors the
Atlanta Police Department is a lackadaisical and ineffective
``paper tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   The human rights watchdog released a report Tuesday that also
found problems with the department's internal affairs division,
calling it biased and secretive when investigating complaints of
police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   HRW said it found evidence of unchecked police brutality in all
the cities it surveyed. In virtually every city, at least one
officer was allowed to remain in his department despite numerous
brutality complaints, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The group also said Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard was
vague in her responses to written questions from HRW about the
internal affairs unit and its procedures for receiving police
brutality complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can be said is that the complaint-intake process is
flawed, which discourages even legitimate complaints,'' researcher
Allyson Collins wrote about Atlanta. ``The police department
resists revealing information about the cases it has received and
investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said cities were chosen because they made news with
police brutality reports. Collins based the report on interviews
with people who are part of or come in contact with police
departments in the cities evaluated, which included Chicago, Los
Angeles, New York and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard also responded only to written questions about the
report from The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. The mayor's office
did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report certainly strikes the wrong chord that we would be
a department that is not concerned about police brutality,''
Harvard said. ``Certainly I would be concerned about any officer
that uses unnecessary and excessive force. The report gives no
credit or credence to the fact that maybe we are a police
department that is not saddled with a great number of brutal police
officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins discounted the department's claim that it has a low rate
of police brutality complaints, noting that the department's Office
of Professional Standards, its internal affairs division, chooses
which complaints merit investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she was surprised by that statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely not true that we pick and choose which
complaints to investigate,'' she said. ``We investigate all
complaints that come to OPS. I get a lot of feedback from the
public in various meetings and OPS and the way it handles
complaints, is not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a citizen has a complaint about how an OPS investigation
was handled, that citizen can contact me and I always review those
complaints myself,'' Harvard added.
</P>
<P>
   But the HRW report painted a different picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to police abuse experts in the city, there is a
perception that the internal affairs unit is not interested in
pursuing complaints against police officers, resulting in distrust
of OPS in many affected communities,'' Collins wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And Atlanta's Civilian Review Board of 29 citizens is an
ineffective alternative, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some in the community deride the CRB as a 'paper tiger'
... that label would suggest that, on paper, the board has powers
that it does not have in practice,'' the report said. ``In fact,
its powers ... are hardly impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel was created in 1983 but did virtually nothing until
January 1996, following the police shooting of a civilian at a
downtown Atlanta motorcycle repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   The board has no subpoena power. It cannot consider a case that
is under investigation internally or is involved in a lawsuit. The
board only reviews cases referred to it by the department's
internal affairs unit and cannot co
</P>
</TEXT>
