u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISS-LAWSUIT-COX     07-07 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISS-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patent suit could bring ISS down
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A California company has unleashed a potentially
lethal legal salvo at Atlanta-based Internet Security Systems,
charging Tuesday that the key software used by the highflying young
firm is taken from someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by Santa Clara, Calif.-based Network Associates could
threaten the rocket-sled start of ISS, setting up a legal
confrontation as both companies compete for a potentially huge
market in the systems that protect computer networks. The action
filed in federal court for the Northern District of California
alleges that the software called RealSecure from ISS infringes on a
patent for technology that lets managers protect computers from all
manner of computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates is asking the court to assess the amount of
damages done to it and then to award it triple that amount. But if
Network Associates has its way, the court would also forbid ISS
from making or selling RealSecure, and that move would virtually
cut the heart out of ISS _ and its ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ISS rejected the allegation Tuesday, firing back a
countercharge. William Larson, Network Associates' chief executive,
last week told a group of analysts that he would sue ISS in an
effort to slow down its market momentum, according to Tom Noonan,
ISS president and chief executive officer. ``We believe these
tactics are inappropriate. We think the facts will show that this
suit is frivolous and without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ISS, which last year had revenues of $13 million, sees itself as
a David facing the Goliath of $612 million-a-year Network
Associates. However, ISS believes that its size is less critical
than its sudden spate of successes. ``Competitive people do not
like losing,'' Noonan said.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the suit had been filed came the same day ISS won
a multiyear contract to provide the Army with RealSecure software
to defend 400 of its facilities from computer assault. Noonan
declined to say how much revenue the deal will produce except to
say the sale is significant and extends the ISS relationship with
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army views ISS as a trusted security adviser. This is a
long-term relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Network Associates also sells its security software to the
Army, as well as to Microsoft and various banks, said Art Wong,
Network Associates' director of intrusion protection.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off Noonan's charges. ``This is not about the CEO
and what the CEO says. It's about protecting intellectual property.
We own it, and we owe it to our shareholders to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   ISS got its start with software developed by founder Christopher
Klaus in a Georgia Tech dorm room. The company seemed to have a
headstart into a potentially multibillion-dollar market, since
virtually every organization that uses computers worries about
security.
</P>
<P>
   While Network Associates is much larger, it has only recently
entered the same markets targeted by ISS. Moreover, much-smaller
ISS has gobbled nearly one-third of the growing market, according
to a report released this week by the Yankee Group. That report
gives ISS 30 percent of the market, followed by Axent Technologies
with 19 percent. Network Associates and Cisco Systems follow with
11 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Group predicts the security market will grow from $45
million last year to $747 million in 2003 _ a compounded annual
growth rate of 49 percent. Should ISS maintain its current market
share in such a market, its revenues would be $224 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Network Associates alleges that ISS has taken a ``method and
system for detecting intrusion into and misuse of a data processing
system,'' Wong said. It said the patent had been owned by Haystack
Labs of Austin, Texas, which was bought by Maryland-based Trusted
Information Systems, which was purchased by Network Associates in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutiny of the newly acquired company revealed the
infringement, Wong said. ``We just want to make sure that we
protect what is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   ISS asserts that the suit is more about market maneuvering than
technology or legality. Network Associates is simply anxious to
take the steam out of ISS, he said. Noonan accuses Network
Associates of having ``cobbled'' together smaller companies that
can offer network security. He declined to say whether ISS had been
approached as a potential acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But Noonan denied any infringement. ISS has worked with
Haystack, he said. ``We are very familiar with the patent. But we
invented that type of technology and we clearly don't infringe the
patent.''
</P>
<P>
   ISS landed in the spotlight with its first public offering of
stock. On the first day of trading in March, ISS raised $66 million
and its stock price nearly doubled. On Tuesday, company stock rose
62 1/2 cents to close at $44.12 1/2 in slightly heavier than normal
trading. Shares of Network Associates were also up 62 1/2 cents to
$48.75 a share, just $3 shy of its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
