<HEADER>
A4487 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACIFIC-PARADISE-TV-$     07-07 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PARADISE-TV-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE TO FACE WITH AN UNDERWATER PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (JT)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens at night in the summertime when the moon is full and
the tides are just right. The coral reefs of Palau, some of the
world's richest, go into a spasm of reproductive surrender, sowing
warm currents with trillions of eggs and sperm that swirl and dance
and ultimately merge to form new life. The orgy is so wild that in
some places, eggs rise through the sea like snowflakes, blizzards
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Even sea cucumbers get into the mood. Ugly by human standards,
these creatures are normally slow and sedentary, looking like fat
worms and seemingly incapable of lust. But in the moonlight they
suddenly rise up and dance in hypnotic rhythms, swaying back and
forth to seed a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the remarkable sights of ``Palau: Paradise of
the Pacific,'' to be shown on Wednesday at 9:00 p.m. on the PBS
series ``The Living Edens.''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong documentary ranks Palau high among the contemporary
Edens. But romantic cliches are no match for actually seeing the
archipelago's beauty, through the eyes of this documentary. Palau's
200 isles of the equatorial Pacific, heavily forested and lightly
populated, are surrounded by endless miles of coral reefs that teem
with exotic forms of life. It is one of the world's richest
assemblages of species.
</P>
<P>
   The show is the handiwork of Al Giddings, a legend of undersea
photography who helped film underwater scenes for the megahit
``Titanic'' and has made many oceanic dramas and documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   People often see fish as healthy meals. But Giddings' portrait
of undersea Palau puts intriguing new faces on a riot of sea
creatures, revealing complex lives of surprising depth and
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a female titan triggerfish as she tends her eggs. A
male triggerfish, fearing that her hatchlings will compete with his
own, lures her from her nest with a mock attack. She returns too
late. Her eggs have been pillaged by an army of small predators,
and she darts away, clearly upset.
</P>
<P>
   Or, on a lighter note, consider the unusual goings-on near a
large outcrop of coral. Here the war between predator and prey is
suspended by a truce of mutual benefit as small fish called wrasses
remove the parasites that annoy larger fish. Signaling their
readiness by assuming a relaxed pose, bigger fish allow the
cleaners to enter gills and mouths to eat away parasites and
fungus.
</P>
<P>
   At these cleaning stations, even sharks open their fearsome jaws
wide with no menace. ``In this special zone,'' the narrator, James
Coburn, remarks, ``the lords of the reef come out not to hunt small
creatures but to seek their help.''
</P>
<P>
   Painlessly, as befits a tropic dream, yet with thoroughness and
preciseness, the show explores the scientific basis of the
archipelago's abundant life. Overall, the narrative carefully
disentangles the elements and rhythms that make up Palau's biologic
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The coral of Palau comes in a bewildering variety of shapes and
sizes and, we learn, represents more than 300 species, a staggering
number by world standards. These colonies of tiny animals feed on
the microscopic drifters of the sea that continuously float by.
</P>
<P>
   Fields of tiny eels rise from seabed burrows to eat the rain of
plankton, as do giant, 15-foot-wide manta rays, their wings flying
them gracefully, their mouths wide and cavernous.
</P>
<P>
   The tropic sun is the power behind this feast, fueling both the
flotillas of tiny drifting plants and the microscopic algae that
dwell inside each coral polyp. The algae live on coral wastes and
in turn produce food, abetting meals that the corals grab from the
sea with tiny tentacles of bold coloration.
</P>
<P>
   Palau's reefs are underwater cities, providing food and shelter
for crabs and shrimps and giant clams and fish and all kinds of
gooey invertebrates. The reefs are also nurseries. We see a female
cuttlefish, a deadly predator related to the octopus, deposit her
eggs for safekeeping. More than a month later, tiny hatchlings
wiggle out of egg cases, revealing themselves to be perfect
miniatures of their parents and knowing instinctively that the
recesses of the reef offer safety.
</P>
<P>
   At night, strange animals wary of sunlight emerge to join the
reef's pandemonium. A five-foot-long sea cucumber feeds itself,
using feathery tentacles. A nudibranch, a snail without a shell,
flies through the water. It seems to be dressed in a ruffled skirt
and is known as the Spanish Dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking of the nighttime denizens is the lion fish.
Clothed in an outrageous costume of feathery fins and poisonous
barbs, it moves slowly to stalk its prey. With lightning speed that
the filmmakers slow down and show from several angles, the lion
fish snaps up its meal and then moves stealthily forward looking
for another.
</P>
<P>
   The islands of Palau are unusual not only for their opulent
corals but also for more than 70 saltwater lakes, which are fed by
the nearby sea through an underground maze of tunnels and cracks.
Tangles of mangrove roots cover the banks and harbor saltwater
crocodiles. One remote lake is home to more than a million
jellyfish that migrate endlessly as a giant herd. Over time they
have lost their stingers and now, instead of killing, live in
symbiosis with algae. At night the jellies descend to fertilize
their captive algae with the rich nutrients of bottom waters and
during the day rise to absorb the sun's rays. Such jellyfish are
not known to exist anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   With unromantic clarity, the show reveals how these gelatinous
peacemongers can be ruthlessly attacked by predator fish and sea
anemones, who wrap them in pedallike tentacles and feed with
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   The show also teaches us something of Palau's people, who live
on the reef's bounty and know the sea's rhythms intimately. A boy
gathers up a sea cucumber and squeezes out its gooey discharge to
form makeshift shoes. The sticky threads, normally used to entangle
enemies, here protect the boy's feet from sharp coral. Such
cucumbers, the show notes, are returned to the sea, stressed but
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Palau, as in few other places,'' the narrator says, ``human
life is not dominant over nature, but still part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the filmmakers have erred, it is here, seeing people through
a romantic lens that ignores the troubles in paradise, which are
startling in their range and seriousness. Like people elsewhere in
the Pacific, native Palauans set off dynamite charges to fish en
masse, blasting holes 10 or 15 feet wide in coral reefs. Meanwhile,
tourists and scuba divers, often in luxury dive boats, are
descending on reef areas that are still pristine.
</P>
<P>
   And commercial boats scoop up fish for the live trade centering
on restaurants and aquariums, a booming global business fueled by
staggering sums of money. Rumors suggested they were doing so
illegally with cyanide, which stuns the fish into submission and
kills coral reefs. This poison, the same stuff used to execute
human prisoners, has already cut a wide swath of destruction
through Pacific coral.
</P>
<P>
   The human excesses around Palau are shown by Carl Safina in his
1997 book ``Song for the Blue Ocean,'' which devotes three chapters
to the lush isles. Safina, a scientist with the National Audubon
Society, recounts visits there to experts fighting to conserve the
archipelago's wonders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
