 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Apple Ripe For N.Y. Macworld   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
New York 
 
Is Apple ready for a revival in the Big Apple?
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the personal computer-maker prepares for its first Macworld
Expo trade show here this week, many contend the worm has already
turned.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by cost-dicing measures and a hike in PC shipments, Apple
has reported back-to-back profitable quarters this year, and
sources said interim chief executive Steve Jobs will announce a
third straight profit _ about $50 million _ in a keynote speech
today. Jobs is making the presentation via satellite from
Cupertino, &UR;  &LR; where he has a previous commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, a consummate showman, might pull Mickey Mouse out of his
hat for the event: Reportedly, Apple is close to inking a deal with
Walt Disney Co. to install thousands of Apple's new iMac computers
in Disney hotel rooms, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The financial news gets better: Orders of the iMac home computer
are booming more than a month before they hit retailers' shelves,
and market researchers predict the company could ship as many as
400,000 machines by the end of September. That should be good
enough for Apple to squeeze out yet another quarter in the black,
industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All indications are the company will turn its first annual
profit since (fiscal year) 1995,'' said analyst James Staten of
Dataquest Inc. in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a company that lost almost $2 billion the previous
two years and has seen its Lilliputian market share scare away
software developers in droves. A year ago this week, former Apple
CEO Gil Amelio was jettisoned, and Jobs was ushered in as de facto
leader. Jobs was later named interim chief in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese have a wonderful phrase: You sweep the stairs
from the top down,'' said Phil Schiller, Apple vice president of
worldwide product marketing at Apple. ``We first had to make
changes at the top before we worked on new products and made Apple
a viable business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl England, publisher of MacAddict, a monthly magazine in
Brisbane, said: ``Amelio was billed as the adult supervisor, but
there was utter chaos and he exacerbated the problem. What's
amazing is that Steve Jobs, who has the public image of a brat, has
been able to bring a calming, practical influence to Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   The Machiavellian Jobs _ who was ousted from Apple in a power
play more than a decade before he orchestrated the overthrow of
Amelio _ has adopted an addition-by-subtraction management style.
Jobs has spiked more than a dozen computer models from the
company's product line; performed surgery on operating costs with
staff cutbacks at the Claris and Newton divisions; introduced the
sleek new iMac PC; and effectively killed off the Rhapsody
operating system and melded it into the new Mac OS X.
</P>
<P>
   ``The levels of bureaucracy have been stripped away,'' England
said. ``He has made the best of a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple executives also credit Chief Financial Officer Fred
Anderson, sole high-ranking holdover from the Amelio era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred has the knack for working with Steve's powerful
personality,'' said Jerry York, former chief financial officer of
IBM Corp. and Chrysler Corp. and a current Apple board member. ``He
(Fred) has the ability to bring matters to Steve's attention
without attracting fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   The austerity program and a new management team stacked with
Jobs' cronies have done wonders for Apple's stock. Shares, which
bottomed out at $12.94 in December, closed at $30.50 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has done a bang-up job,'' Adobe Systems CEO John Warnock
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others think the changes are superficial and don't go far
enough to sustain Apple beyond the next 12 months. Despite rumors
of an Internet set-top box, handheld computers and a Disney
partnership, &UR;  &LR; Apple has done little to establish itself in markets
other than education and desktop publishing. The computer-maker is
catering to the latter crowd this week by situating Macworld in New
York, the heart of the publishing world, instead of its regular
Boston haunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a comeback. It's more of a Band Aid strategy designed
to stem the bleeding,'' said analyst Tom Rhinelander, of Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``Basically, they've been reining in
the core of their business without improving revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Zlotnikov, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein Co. in New
York, said Apple has ``demonstrated a spectacular ability to reduce
costs and build profit margins, but must prove they have the
ability to achieve significant revenue growth.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, sales for Apple's second quarter ended March 27
were down 12 percent from the year-ago quarter, to $1.4 billion
from $1.6 billion. Even though the company has sold more than
500,000 of its speedy Power Mac G3 computers since they were
introduced in the fall, its overall market share has stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's 4.1 percent take of the domestic PC market hasn't budged
from a year ago, according to Dataquest. If anything, the numbers
are down because they don't include Macintosh clone sales, which
accounted for 1.8 percent of the U.S. market last year. Last
summer, Jobs scotched clone agreements with PC-makers because he
feared they were siphoning sales away from Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of (Apple) is 100 times better than a year ago, but
everything is relative,'' Forrester's Rhinelander said. ``Last
year, everyone thought a great icon was dead. Now, they have some
inkling what they want to do and people are willing to give them a
shot. But Apple better do something dramatic _ fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
