<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 KKR Rings Up Profits as It Slowly Takes Safeway Off Its Shelves   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
It has taken more than 12 years, but buyout specialist Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. is slowly but surely cashing out what remains
of its stake in Safeway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the investment firm's latest unloading of shares is yet
another example of savvy investors taking money off the table
before the game breaks up.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Safeway filed documents with the Securities and
Exchange Commission indicating that the grocery giant plans to sell
about 25 million shares owned by KKR and affiliates. After the
proposed secondary offering is completed, KKR and friends will be
left holding only 17 percent of the nation's second-largest food
and drug chain. (That's down from 22 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   That still may seem like a lot, but it's nothing compared with
the whole enchilada that it owned after its leveraged buyout of the
Pleasanton company back in 1986. The investment group, led by Henry
Kravis and George Roberts, has demonstrated eminent patience with
their Safeway turnaround, which included taking the company public
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   And as they say in supermarket parlance, KKR &AMP; friends have made
out well at the register. They paid about 50 cents a share for
Safeway and have been selling those shares for anywhere from $43 to
$58 over the past year or so, according to Bloomberg LP of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad trade, to say the least. KKR should be credited with
``making a great investment,''says high-yield bond analyst Robert
Lupo of BancAmerica Robertson Stephens in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Lupo says the timing of the secondary offering isn't surprising
because KKR has to cash out sometime. And the stock has been
trading near its 52-week high of $42.94 reached on June 30. (The
price is adjusted to reflect a 2-for-1 split earlier this year.)
But what does KKR's bailing mean for current and future holders?
</P>
<P>
   Investors weren't thrilled with the news of a secondary
offering. Safeway closed yesterday at $41.56, down $1.31. And while
the offering shouldn't dilute the value of existing Safeway shares,
at least one sell-side analyst has a ``hold'' rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Charles Cerankosky of McDonald &AMP; Co. in Cleveland is
still a fan of the company and of chief executive Steven Burd, to
whom he attributes much of the company's success. However,
Cerankosky says Safeway is ``fairly valued'' and not exactly a
bargain. Under Burd's leadership, Safeway grew its operating profit
margins from 3.29 percent in 1994 to 5.69 percent in 1997. And
Cerankosky contends that there is more margin growth to come,
mostly from continued assimilation of the Vons merger that was
completed in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which has been deemed a success by most industry
observers, now has some analysts anxiously awaiting the next deal.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway is ``out there looking for another nice acquisition. I
would say they would love to do something in the East'' where the
company has a presence in the Baltimore-Washington, D.C., corridor,
Cerankosky says. Safeway officials did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you're not willing to pay a premium for the prospect
of another merger, then you might do so on the basis of Safeway's
second-quarter earnings due out tomorrow, says analyst Mark Husson
of Merrill Lynch in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Husson expects Safeway earnings to be up 33 percent to 36 cents
a share (not accounting for a labor strike in the comparable
period).
</P>
<P>
   Husson isn't alone. The Street as a whole is bullish on Safeway
(88 percent of the analysts rate the stock a ``buy'') despite the
fact that KKR, its largest shareholders, are at the checkout
counter.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as little surprise then that more than 10 Wall
Street firms _ many of whose sell-side analysts cover the company _
have lined up to manage Safeway's secondary offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka(at
sign)sfgate.com. He also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak on Tuesdays
and Thursdays.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
