<HEADLINE>
THIRD OF BABIES AREN'T REGISTERED, UNICEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Perhaps one-third of all babies do not have
their births registered, leaving them in an official limbo that can
mean missed educational opportunities and health care, UNICEF says
in a new report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without proof of birth, a child cannot be legally vaccinated
in at least 20 countries,'' said the report, to be published
Wednesday by UNICEF, the U.N. children's fund. ``More than 30
countries require birth registration before a child can be treated
in a health center. Most countries demand to see a birth
certificate before enrolling a child in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``The Progress of Nations 1998,'' calls the birth
certificate a crucial piece of paper, ``proof of what might be
called the `first right,' the right to an official identity.''
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said in an interview
Monday that the organization began to focus on birth registration
because of a series of experiences. UNICEF officials saw Rwandan
refugee children being thrown into adult camps with men who had
carried out genocidal attacks, but UNICEF found it hard to separate
them because they had no proof of ages.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, immunization campaigns often uncovered
previously uncounted children, she said. And work with street
children revealed the difficulties inherent in finding them schools
if they did not have birth certificates. The missing information
locally led to the worldwide survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a third of the children who are born every year are in
essence nonexistent in the eyes of states, then it puts them at
risk,'' Ms. Bellamy said. ``Not having a birth certificate is the
functional equivalent of not having been born.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of certificates allows children to be more easily
exploited as child labor or sex workers, she added.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF found that registration was lowest in sub-Saharan Africa
and some Asian nations, notably India and Myanmar, where a half to
a third of births were registered, and Cambodia, which had no
registration system at all. Vietnam did not have enough data to
make even an educated guess.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty alone does not determine the level of registration, the
report found, citing high registration rates in most of Latin
America, central Asia and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bellamy acknowledged that many figures in the study, which
point to 40 million unregistered births a year, were based on
estimates. ``These are guesstimates, but these are the best
guesstimates we have,'' she said. ``It is always interesting to me
when we say we had a national immunization day and we had 105
percent coverage. How do you get 105 percent coverage? Because
X-number more children came than the official statistics indicated
existed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
