<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 North Face's Stock Skids 17% On HQ Move   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The stock of North Face Inc. dropped nearly 17 percent yesterday,
one day after the outdoor apparel-maker said it will move its
headquarters to a Colorado site near its chief executive's home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Face said Monday that it will spend millions of dollars to
establish a new home base in Carbondale, Colo. About 70 workers
will be relocated from the current San Leandro headquarters, while
some 175 staffers will remain in San Leandro.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things don't look good'' said a Wall Street analyst who
follows the stock. ``Not only are people concerned about the
self-interests at work here, but (North Face is) also splitting up
the company, which raises some risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The move allows North Face President and Chief Executive Officer
James Fifield, an avid skier, to be close to his home near Aspen.
Fifield joined North Face in May.
</P>
<P>
   James Reilly, the company's chief operating officer, said the
decision to move was made after an extensive cost-based analysis of
several locations. The Carbondale move will save significant labor
and other expenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company decided to leave functions such as retailing, buying
and information systems in San Leandro because people in those jobs
prefer living in the Bay Area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Face expects to accrue costs as high as $7 million to
relocate its workers, house them in a temporary headquarters and
expand its sourcing operations in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   That amount does not include a pending purchase of 36 acres of
land in Carbondale and construction of a headquarters there, said
Reilly, who added that the company got good location incentives
from Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Colorado move, investors are unhappy about
North Face's acquisition of Italian footwear-maker La Sportiva
S.r.L. announced Monday because that deal will lower earnings in
the near-term, said Shawn Milne, a securities analyst with
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Milne said he has lowered his 1998 earnings expectations for
North Face to $1.13 per share from $1.21. However, the La Sportiva
deal should help the company in the long-term, he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Face shares yesterday dropped $4 to $20.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
