<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-TRIAL-2TAKES-NY     07-07 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKHASEV FOUND GUILTY IN COSBY MURDER TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A jury took less than six hours on Tuesday to find
19-year-old Mikail Markhasev guilty of murdering Ennis Cosby, the
son of the entertainer Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev smiled briefly in the packed courtroom as the verdict
was read, then stood expressionless as Cosby's family members began
to sob and hug. Markhasev was found guilty of both first-degree
murder and attempted robbery under circumstances that could bring
him a sentence of life in prison without parole. Superior Court
Judge David Perez scheduled the sentencing for Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors lauded the verdict, Henry Hall, one of the two
public defenders who represented Markhasev, said he believed the
intense media scrutiny and fame of Cosby's father had contributed
to an unfair judgement by turning attention away from a sober
analysis of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference after the verdict was read, Hall said the
``societal presumption was that there would be a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Cosby, who was 27 and studying for a Ph.D in
education at Columbia University at the time of his killing on Jan.
16, 1997, was shot once in the head while changing a flat tire late
at night alongside a highway here. Police said it appeared to have
been a crime of opportunity, an unplanned but botched robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the entirely circumstantial nature of the prosecution's
case, which relied on a hair found with the murder weapon, letters
handed over by a convicted forgerer, and a tip to the National
Enquirer, the jury seemed to have dispatched quickly with
Markhasev's defense that a friend of his had actually shot Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev's mother had testified that her son had been with her
the night of the murder, and his attorneys had argued that the
incriminating letters, supposedly written by Markhasev to a friend
from jail, had been forged. In one of the letters, Markhasev wrote
that he had killed a black man _ he used an epithet in referring to
Cosby's race _ during a robbery turned bad.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began with several claims that were ultimately
unsubstantiated. Early in the trial the prosecution made the
sensational claim that Markhasev was a member of a notorious prison
gang, and Markhasev's attorneys said they would prove that Eli
Zakaria, a friend of Markhasev, had committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   None of the those assertions were proved. Ultimately, the case
boiled down to the accidental and ultimately tragic crossing of the
paths of the two young men, one who slid into a life of crime after
immigrating here from the Ukraine, and the other working to build a
career as an educator out of the shadow of his wealthy and famous
father.
</P>
<P>
