A4495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFIT08-COX     07-07 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFIT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profit Recovery making acquisition
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Profit Recovery Group International said Tuesday it
agreed to buy California-based Loder, Drew &AMP; Associates for $70
million cash and 803,535 shares of unregistered, restricted stock.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's closing price of $32.62 1/2, the stock portion of
the deal would be valued at $26 million. The stock can only be sold
after a specified time.
</P>
<P>
   Loder, Drew ``broadens the universe of clients that we can
provide service to outside of our core businesses of retail,
wholesale and government,'' said Donald E. Ellis Jr., chief
financial officer for Profit Recovery, a Cobb County-based audit
recovery and accounts payable firm. Its clients include retail
giant Wal-Mart Stores. Loder, Drew reported 1997 revenues of $22
million.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to close at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Credit line issued
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Loder, Drew could receive as much as $70
million more, depending on future performance.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Recovery said it received a commitment from NationsBank
NA for $125 million in revolving credit, some of which will be used
in the Loder, Drew deal.
</P>
<P>
   This is the largest acquisition for Profit Recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Loder, Drew, which is based in San Juan Capistrano, Calif., has
a heavy concentration in high-technology, industrial, entertainment
and financial services. Its clients include Walt Disney and Texas
Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald K. Loder, president and chief executive officer, and H.
Richard Byrne, chief operating officer, will remain in their
current roles. At closing, Loder will join the board of Profit
Recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted favorably to the deal. Earlier in the day,
Profit Recovery's stock reached a 52-week high of $32.75. The stock
closed at $32.62 1/2, up $4.31 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profit Recovery has proven itself pretty adept at identifying,
making and integrating acquisitions,'' said Alexander Paris Jr. of
Barrington Research of Chicago. ``With this acquisition, they
become the undisputed largest player in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris said the benefits of the acquisition should be reflected
in the third- and fourth-quarter earnings, adding a cent to each.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Recovery has more than 1,300 employees in 18 nations.
Loder, Drew has 208 employees with offices in the United States,
Canada, England and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
