<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAD-COX     07-07 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two more metro stocks take tumble
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner and Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two more Atlanta firms that have been Wall Street
favorites stumbled Tuesday on disappointing earnings news.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Atlanta-based Harbinger, which makes software for
electronic commerce, fell 29 percent after it said second-quarter
earnings and revenue will miss forecasts because it failed to ship
$1 million of software by the end of the quarter. Harbinger told
investors to expect second-quarter earnings of 10 cents a share,
below analysts' 12 cents-a-share estimate. Revenue will be about
$35 million, 5 percent below analysts' estimates, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   First Albany analyst Ullas Naik told Bloomberg News he's
reviewing his ``buy'' rating on the stock. ``It should take them
two to three quarters to clean it up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the stock of Radiant Systems, an Alpharetta firm that
makes computer systems and software used by restaurants,
convenience stores and movie theater chains, plunged 50 percent
after the company told investors to expect a second-quarter loss of
8 to 10 cents a share. The company blamed the shortfall on higher
operating costs, delays in orders and investments in new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the year our revenues were impacted by (the
consolidation of some customers), and that has continued,'' said
John Heyman, Radiant Systems' chief financial officer. Heyman
declined to comment on the stock drop or the company's outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's double wallop follows a string of sharp stock price
drops for several metro Atlanta companies once considered Wall
Street favorites. Shares of health care firms Medirisk and
Theragenics fell last week, 69 percent and 36 percent,
respectively. Medirisk reported its second-quarter results would
fall short of analysts' expectations. Analysts' concern over
competition for Theragenics' cancer treatment device sent its stock
down.
</P>
<P>
   Since late May, eight Georgia companies have warned of a
shortfall in quarterly results. And that has devastated their
stocks, which have lost a combined $3.01 billion in value since
their highs earlier this year, when investors were more
enthusiastic about the companies' earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest loser was telecommunications provider Premiere
Technologies, which had a market value of $1.62 billion on March
25. It's now worth $345.6 million. In the case of Radiant Systems,
analysts remain optimistic because much of the problems are outside
the company's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of changes occurring that are interrupting the
flow of orders from those customers,'' said Cato Carpenter, a BT
Alex Brown analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're normal changes. But they seem to have bunched up in an
abnormal number in the first half of the year, which has thrown off
the whole year for Radiant. They haven't lost any business,
customers or contracts. No competitors are gaining on them. So I
think they will do better in the future. It's a matter of them
getting through the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
