<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENTS OFFER NEW FORUM FOR COMPLAINTS ABOUT AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moved in `t' news file.) 
(jw) 
 By JANET PIORKO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Passengers with gripes about airlines have a new way to
complain, courtesy of the American Society of Travel Agents, which
has issued an Air Traveler's Bill of Rights and is inviting
feedback on flights at a new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The society plans to publish the results of the Web surveys
periodically.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``rights'' decreed by the society are the right to
truth in advertised prices, schedules and seat availability; equal
access to unbiased, comparative travel information and all fare and
service options; a comfortable seat, reasonable space for carry-on
luggage, healthful meals and clean lavatories; use of all, part or
none of the segments of a lawfully purchased ticket, and timely,
complete and truthful information regarding delays, cancellations
and equipment changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to hear this rising chorus of unhappiness among
the traveling public about one of the main products our members
sell,'' said Paul Ruden, senior vice president for legal and
industry affairs of the travel agents' group. ``We decided to set
out a set of principles that would address this in the English
language in the hope that the airlines would embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened yet. The Air Transport Association, the
major airlines' trade group, sees the action as a display of
agents' continued anger over carriers' decisions to cut travel
agents' commissions last year. ``Its motivation has nothing to do
with consumers,'' said David Fuscus, a spokesman for the airlines'
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planes are fuller than they've ever been, but the system's
handling it well,'' he said, citing a survey in May that showed an
approval rate of 70 percent for the airlines, with 11 percent of
consumers disapproving and the rest having no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Will travel agents be issuing a cruise passenger's bill of
rights or a hotel guest's bill of rights in the future? ``We will
look at that,'' Ruden said. ``We wanted to deal first with the most
obvious problem, and from the standpoint of the business of the
industry, this is the largest segment.'' Travelers can weigh in
with a confidential survey rating their flights at the new Web site
(www.astanet.com/travelersrights).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of complaints about the airlines filed the
old-fashioned way, with the Department of Transportation, jumped in
May: There were 914, almost 30 percent more than in April and 25
percent more than in May 1997, according to the department's Air
Travel Consumer Report for the month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATES UP, OCCUPANCY DOWN
</P>
<P>
   The average daily room rate at U.S. hotels will rise 5 percent
this year, to $78.94, according to the Price Waterhouse Coopers
Lodging Research Network, even though hotel occupancies are
expected to decline slightly (less than 1 percentage point) for the
second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancies are still very high, and ``hotel operators are
confident the rates will be accepted,'' according to Bjorn Hanson,
a lodging consultant with Price Waterhouse Coopers. Markets such as
New York and San Francisco, where hotel rooms are in great demand,
are also contributing to higher average prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the rate of increase has slowed, from 6.1 percent
in 1997. And increases for 1999 and 2000 are predicted to be
smaller, at 4.6 percent and 4 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   LEAVING THE KEYS
</P>
<P>
   Valet parking has come to Newark International Airport, and
should soon arrive at Kennedy International Airport. At Newark,
passengers can drive to Monorail Station E and drop off their cars
with an attendant, then take the monorail to their terminal. The
introductory rate is $18 a day. The service, operated by Ampco
System Parking of Los Angeles, uses a dedicated 800-space lot to
which only the attendants have access, according to Bill Cahill, a
spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. The
authority plans to extend the service to Kennedy ``probably before
the end of July,'' Cahill said.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta Air Lines and UAL's United Airlines will become partners
in each other's frequent-flier programs on Sept. 1. Members of
Delta's Sky Miles program and United's Mileage Plus program will be
able to accrue miles in either account on flights within the United
States and Puerto Rico that are not part of an international
itinerary. The two carriers plan to establish a timetable for
reciprocal redemption of miles shortly.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Trans Air began flying between La Guardia Airport and
Midway Airport in Chicago on Tuesday with introductory
nonrefundable one-way fares starting at $88 for July. Tickets must
be purchased by July 17. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
