A4509 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHANCELLOR-LIN-TEX     07-07 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANCELLOR-LIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCELLOR MEDIA, LIN TELEVISION PLAN HICKS MULTIMEDIA MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shape and direction of Tom Hicks' media empire became
clearer Tuesday, after the Dallas investor agreed to combine Lin
Television with Chancellor Media Corp. in a stock-and-debt
transaction valued at $1.64 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, owner of the Texas Rangers baseball team and the Dallas
Stars hockey club, is chairman of both Lin Television and
Chancellor Media. His Dallas investment firm, Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP;
Furst, founded Chancellor four years ago by acquiring a string of
radio stations in major markets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Irving-based Chancellor, the nation's
second-largest radio company, a foothold in television, and it
moves Hicks closer to his vision of a media conglomerate that can
leverage its size, efficiency and reach.
</P>
<P>
   With holdings in TV, radio and billboards, Chancellor expects to
heavily cross-promote its properties and entice advertisers with
one-stop shopping that gives them an easy way to establish their
brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Hicks is a great visionary, and this is a vision we've
been talking about for a long time,'' said Jeffrey Marcus, chief
executive for Chancellor Media and an investor with Hicks. ``It's a
great opportunity to sell across many mediums. And in this
business, you sell impressions, and the more you make, the better
off you are.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Marcus said, an advertiser could tout a movie on
billboards and in broadcast ads, and then put the film's stars on
local radio and TV programs _ all properties controlled by Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year ago, Hicks, Muse announced plans to buy Lin, and
closed on that $2 billion deal in March. In North Texas, Lin owned
KXAS/Channel 5, but Hicks has since dealt 80 percent of that
station to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   If the Chancellor-Lin stock swap is approved by regulators, the
Hicks, Muse stake would double to about 18 percent of Chancellor
Media.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hicks is directly involved in both Chancellor and Lin,
Marcus said, Chancellor Media appointed a special committee to
review the transaction. He said Hicks did not participate in the
board discussion Monday, when the deal was approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very much an arms-length transaction,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved the deal after an investment firm,
Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co., reported that the swap was fair to
Chancellor shareholders. A separate firm, Greenhill &AMP; Co., advised
Lin shareholders, who are primarily Hicks, Muse investors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to close this year, calls for Lin
shareholders to get 0.03 share of Chancellor for each share of Lin
stock, and for Chancellor to assume $769 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor will issue 17.7 million shares of stock, and the
company said the acquisition would boost after-tax cash flow by 6
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The total value of the deal is $1.64 billion, Marcus said,
representing 12.7 times Lin's projected cash flow for 1999.
Although the total sales figure is lower than what Hicks, Muse paid
for Lin, most of KXAS/Channel 5 and the NBC affiliate in San Diego
have been dealt to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Chancellor-Lin deal closes, Marcus said, the
value of the Lin property would have increased 13.6 percent since
Hicks, Muse first committed to buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Lin's holdings include 12 TV stations _ eight are network
affiliates, and four are independents that have local marketing
alliances with affiliates. Among the markets served are
Indianapolis; New Haven, Conn.; Buffalo, N.Y.; and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lin's operating assets account for almost $1.5 billion of the
sale price. Additional assets include a 20 percent stake in
KXAS/Channel 5, valued at $75 million, and a limited stake in
Southwest Sports, valued at about $50 million, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Sports includes the sports enterprises that Hicks has
acquired independently, separate from his investment firm. That
includes KXTX/Channel 39, the Rangers, the Stars and some real
estate around The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, if Hicks succeeds in taking the sports venture
public, Marcus said, Chancellor would either cash out its stake or
continue as a major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Radio will continue to be the dominant element in Hicks' media
play, accounting for roughly 80 percent of a projected $1.8 billion
in 1999 revenue for Chancellor, Marcus said. Hicks, Muse also owns
55 percent of Capstar Broadcasting, an Austin-based company that
has more than 300 stations in smaller markets.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, who joined Chancellor in April after agreeing to sell
most of Marcus Cable to software billionaire Paul Allen, repeated
Tuesday that Capstar will make a good fit under the Chancellor
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, it makes sense, but we have to make the numbers
work,'' Marcus said, adding that the deal will require special
review committees and protracted negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But observers expect it to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of if, it's a question of when,'' said
Paul Leonard, managing director of Star Media Group, a Dallas
investment firm that specializes in radio deals.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said the combinations make sense for the Hicks team,
because they offer the chance to make synergies work. For all the
talk about combining operations, many companies fail to commit
fully to the concept so they don't reap the benefits, Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor could be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need common ownership to make it work,'' Leonard said.
``When you're just sister companies, trying to work together, it
can be a lot of talk. But when you're under one umbrella _ formally
_ it can really bear fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street may be more skeptical. Chancellor's stock, traded as
AMFM, fell $3.0625 Tuesday, closing at $50.75.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
