<SLUG> BC-CUSTODY-DISPUTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER GETS CUSTODY OF SON TAKEN FROM BEIJING BY FATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It took flying halfway around the world, a court
appearance in rural Texas and six long weeks, but Chinese-American
Xiaonan Su Hawke was reunited Tuesday with her only child, whom she
feared she would never see again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy. I thought I had lost my son,'' the
38-year-old Beijing resident, a naturalized U.S. citizen, said in
halting English.
</P>
<P>
   On May 21, her American husband left their luxury apartment in
the Chinese capital with their 10-year-old son, Aaron, when their
marriage collapsed amid threats and accusations, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hawke, 45, a longtime Beijing resident fluent in Chinese
and president of a subsidiary of a Chicago-based fertilizer
company, flew to Texas and Arizona, where Aaron participated in
basketball camps and played with cousins.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Xiaonan Su Hawke was granted temporary custody of
her son in 266th District Court in Stephenville, Texas, home of her
husband's brother. But Frank Hawke failed to heed a court order to
appear with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The father withdrew a petition requesting custody the day
before, and said he thought he was no longer required to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Aaron Hawke arrived on the 42nd-floor offices of a
Dallas law firm with a backpack, an armload of race car toys, an
uncle and a paternal grandfather. But he refused to hug his mother
until a conference room was cleared of TV crews and reporters
called by her attorney's public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very afraid of the cameras and said, `Give me a bag for
my head,' '' Xiaonan Su Hawke said later. Her son also turned down
an offer to visit Disneyland, telling her, ``I want to go back to
Beijing today.''
</P>
<P>
   She emphasized that whatever the outcome of a divorce action in
China, she would never prevent her son from seeing his father or
having a normal relationship with him.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and son will return to China with a Texas court order
granting her sole custody for 90 days, preventing her husband from
flying on the same plane, and declaring that jurisdiction in the
case rests with the Chinese legal system because all parties are
Beijing residents.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hawke, in the petition filed in 266th District Court, said
he had left China because of his wife's false accusations of
spying, treason and ``heinous capital'' crimes, which were made
``all in the presence and hearing of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   A news release issued by his wife's law firm quotes her as
saying that the marriage broke down after he had an extramarital
affair. Her attorney quoted a statement from Hawke saying the
relationship with the other woman was ``public and above board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was quite upset at the press release _ that his mom
would do that _ try to embarrass him through embarrassing his
father,'' Frank Hawke said Tuesday. ``So I've been very leery of
getting involved in a public spat with my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very private person, and everything I've done since
this whole thing started was, in my mind, done in the best
interests of my son,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``That's
been the spirit of my actions. The reason for my silence was to
protect him. I don't believe this belongs in a public forum. This
is a sensitive family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In his court filing, Frank Hawke said the influence of his
wife's family in Beijing would prevent him from getting a fair
hearing in a Chinese court. Her father is a retired Red Army
general who accompanied Communist leader Mao Tse-tung on the
1933-34 Long March.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about her family's clout, Xiaonan Su Hawke said that in
China, ``everybody is equal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
