<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLSTAR-WEISS-COX     07-07 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-WEISS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weiss family get All-Star treatmen
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Everything has been a rush these days for Braves
shortstop Walt Weiss and Tuesday was more rushed than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we got a game tonight?'' Weiss responded, somewhat
sarcastically, when a reporter asked him about his upcoming
All-Star appearance. ``To be honest, I haven't even thought about
it , nothing about it. I just haven't had a chance it's been so
crazy around here. But I think when I get in there it will all hit
me, that I am an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   And little Brody was right there to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The spunky 3-year-old who last week at this time was in an
Atlanta hospital bed fighting E. coli, was in section 126 at Coors
Field watching old dad play in the midsummer classic.
</P>
<P>
   At such a young age, Brody probably doesn't have any idea of the
significance of Walt being on the field and his son being in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   But said a proud father, ``I think when all this is over we will
look back at this and really appreciate it as a family. But right
now things are still pretty hectic, I still feel right in the
middle of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody was at the game with mother Terri and brother Blake. They
were treated like royalty as this has become a national story, one
that has been written in almost every major-league town. In
Tuesday's Rocky Mountain News, one of two hometown newspapers, the
headline read: ``Weiss still feeling son's illness.'' The city has
welcomed the Weiss' with open arms and well they should with Weiss
having spent four years as a Colorado Rockie. Owner Jerry McMorris
even sent out his private jet to pick the family up in Atlanta and
bring them to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something that I will never forget, that he reached
out to me and my family'' he said. ``Collectively, this city has
been amazing. I can't tell you how nice everyone had been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Weiss' have been staying at their home in a Denver suburb,
something they kept despite Weiss signing with the Braves. And
while Weiss will be heading to Miami tonight where the Braves open
up the second half of the season on Thursday, the family will
remain in Denver as Brody will continue to be checked by their
family doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are out of the woods as far as Brody is
concerned,'' Weiss said. ``There may be some long terms things but
nothing serious.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite all, Weiss has been very patient, answering one
question after another, doing radio and television interviews. He
never said an ugly word, never snapped at anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But for several hours Tuesday night, Weiss' attention shifted
back on the field. When he was introduced to the crowd, he received
a standing ovation. It was the longest of the pregame activities,
even longer than that of fan favorite Cal Ripken Jr. And on the big
screen television, there was Brody sitting on Terri's lap, both
smiling away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to expect out there,'' he said. ``I
haven't thought about what it would be like. But I have always
wanted to be an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, both on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
