<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DATEK-MARKETPLACE-ART     07-07 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATEK-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: SEC PROBE DIMS A STAR OF ONLINE TRADING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on Datek market share and trading volume is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Datek Online, one of the nation's fastest-growing
online brokerage firms, has postponed an initial public offering of
stock because of widening investigations into its trading
practices, according to people close to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has won praise in recent years from Wall Street and
federal regulators for its innovative technology, including a
flourishing electronic stock exchange, the Island E.C.N.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, Datek's practices came under question after the
office of Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said it was
investigating whether Datek had participated in a money-laundering
operation.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the Securities and Exchange Commission appears to be
going beyond an initial investigation into off-shore transactions
involving Datek and looking into whether the firm offered customers
guaranteed stock returns, a practice that could run afoul of SEC
antifraud provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is also investigating whether Datek encouraged
illegal trading practices by some of the more than 200 day traders
on its desks in the 1990s, according to people who said they were
interviewed by the SEC two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations could be a big setback for the company, now
the fifth-largest online brokerage firm, with 95,000 customers and
$2 billion in assets under its watch. Datek, whose online unit is
not a target of any investigation, has won high ratings from
publications like Barron's and Smart Money in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear exactly which parts of the once-sprawling company
are being investigated, but the inquiries cover activities as
recent as 1997, when Datek had both trading and online units,
according to those who have been interviewed by law enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Datek, which is based in Iselin, N.J., said in a statement
Tuesday that it ``does not comment on its capital-raising or
financing activities,'' such as a public stock offering, or on
press reports about investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The company has in recent months distanced itself from its old
trading unit, which was spun off in March to Heartland Securities,
a money management firm. Still, in Tuesday's statement, Datek
denied guaranteeing stock returns to its customers or engaging in
illegal trading activity.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, law enforcement officials say that two
investigations into possible stock manipulation and fraudulent
off-shore deals intersected and that Datek's activities were found
at the crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   One of those cases, they said, involved A.R. Baron &AMP; Co., a
brokerage firm, now defunct, whose top executives pled guilty or
were convicted in the last year of defrauding investors in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Although the details are sketchy, officials in one investigation
are looking into whether Datek and at least one person in the A.R.
Baron case were involved in manipulating the stocks of companies
that sold unregistered shares to overseas investors in Regulation S
offerings, which have been the subject of numerous investigations
in recent years by the SEC and Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate investigation, the SEC filed suit three months ago
against Sheldon Maschler, who once headed Datek's trading
operation. The suit contended that he took part in a scheme to
manipulate the shares of Alter Sales Co., an auto company based in
Miami. Datek was not named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has also been investigating whether Datek manipulated
shares of Fortune Petroleum Co. in conjunction with a Regulation S
stock offering, according to people interviewed by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street stock analysts say that Datek continues to tighten
its controls under the leadership of Jeffrey A. Citron, the
27-year-old chairman and chief executive. Datek, they say, is
hoping that its profitable online operation can survive, and indeed
thrive, unscathed by the investigations, making a public offering
possible at a much later date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attractive company in an attractive market,'' said
James Marks, an online analyst at CS First Boston, which has held
discussions with Datek about a public offering. ``But these issues
under investigation have to be resolved for a successful IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, SEC investigators met or spoke with several
former traders about trading practices at Datek, and several months
ago traders told officials from the district attorney's office that
for several years Datek's trading operation had orally guaranteed
customers a return of 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, they said, encouraged traders to sign up relatives and
friends to invest large sums of money to bolster trading
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew some shady dealings were going on,'' said Dale A.
Tucker, a trader who recently left the firm to go to graduate
school. ``We didn't understand the accounts up there, but I think a
lot of people didn't care because we were making a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Datek, which was founded in 1970, began as a small brokerage
firm serving customers in Brooklyn. In the mid-1980s, it opened a
Manhattan branch. Citron, who was hired as a clerk just after
graduating from high school, helped transform the small firm, which
had trading profits of $2 million in 1991, to one with profits of
more than $94 million in 1996. The company used computers to
exploit the Nasdaq stock market's small-order execution system, and
its people became known on Wall Street as ``SOES bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Datek moved into online trading, and quickly
established itself as a leader there, winning acclaim for its $9.99
trading fees and its fast executions. When profits in that area
soared, Maschler _ who Datek says is no longer an employee _ led
the push for an initial public offering, according to his
associates.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts have been enthusiastic about the company's
prospects and some expected Datek to raise $150 million in an
offering this year. Piper Jaffray was one of the investment houses
prepared to take Datek public, according to analysts, before the
investigations tabled those plans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
