<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-BRAZ-NETH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL THWARTS NETHERLANDS BID IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE -- Maybe they should have just gone on until dawn.
There was a full moon in a clear sky and a cool breeze off the
Mediterranean and nobody had anything scheduled until the weekend.
Why did the best match of the World Cup have to come down to
penalty kicks? And why, the Dutch moaned, did they have to be the
ones standing around numbly at the end? Maybe the Almighty really
is a Brazilian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was God helping me,'' insisted keeper Taffarel after he'd
blocked two shots to thwart the Netherlands 4-2 in a shootout
(after a 1-1) tie and put his mates into Sunday's final for the
second straight time with a chance to win their fifth Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Brazilians had beaten Italy for the Cup in a
shootout when Roberto Baggio's kick sailed over the bar in the Rose
Bowl. Tuesday in the Stade Velodrome, they escaped when Taffarel
knocked aside the last two shots by Phillip Cocu and Ron de Boer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should go in,'' shrugged de Boer, after he'd watched
Taffarel come up exulting and pointing his index fingers to the
heavens. ``It's a very dreadful feeling. We could have won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch had also gone out to the Brazilians last time, 3-2 in
the quarterfinals, after coming from two goals down to tie. But
this time hurt much worse. This time, the Dutch were one step
closer to winning the prize that had eluded their Clockwork Orange
teams in 1974 and 1978. This time, the Dutch had tied the match in
the 87th minute on a Patrick Kluivert header and had twice kept
Ronaldo from beating them in overtime, only to see it come to
nothing. ``After we tied it, I truly believed we'd win,'' said de
Boer.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, who'll become the first team since 1962 (also
Brazil) to repeat as champions if they beat Wednesday's
France-Croatia victor in the final, dodged a bullet last night and
they knew it. The Dutch had them backed into their half for most of
the game, attacking and attacking and attacking some more. And yet,
because of one moment of brilliance from the 21-year-old Ronaldo,
the Brazilians thought they had it won before overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch had tied them in knots for the first half, closing
down the midfield, tripping up Ronaldo whenever he came near the
ball and nearly scoring themselves on shots by Dennis Bergkamp and
Kluivert that just went over the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Then, half a minute into the second half, Ronaldo had Brazil on
the board. Taking a deft through ball from Rivaldo, he dashed into
the area, as Cocu desperately tried to get a piece of him, and put
the ball past keeper Edwin Van Der Sar for his fourth goal of the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Dutch had been behind in the
tournament and they came back with a fierce resolve. In the 53rd
minute, here was Kluivert heading a corner down to Wim Jonk, whose
point-blank shot Taffarel barely managed to block. In the 65th,
Kluivert just missed on another header off a corner, covering his
face in dismay.
</P>
<P>
   In came Denilson for Bebeto, and Brazil came back to life.
Rivaldo sent in Ronaldo again, five yards in the clear this time,
but Edgar Davids and Van Der Sar combined to thwart him. Then
Denilson crossed nicely for Rivaldo, who was sitting on the turf
but managed to poke a shot at Van Der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   So it went, with the Brazilians eager to put the Dutch away and
the Dutch, who had won their last two matches with Yugoslavia and
Argentina in the final minute, confident they could find a way to
stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Kluivert, the 22-year-old whippet from AC Milan, had
been misfiring, his mates kept looking for him. Finally de Boer,
alone on the right side, sent over a high cross and Kluivert,
skying above three yellow jerseys, knocked it in.
</P>
<P>
   So it came to overtime, with Ronaldo trying to win it by
himself. He nearly did, twice in a minute, on a bicycle kick that
Frank de Boer headed away with Van Der Sar out and a blast that Van
Der Sar knocked away.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo had one last burst in him, two minutes into the second
overtime period, but Frank de Boer managed to get the ball from
behind in the area, narrowly averting a foul that could have
finished the Dutch there.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, for another 30 minutes of this. But referee Ali Mohamed
Bujsaim called for a shootout -- the third of the tournament -- and
now everybody was in the circle, the Brazilians kneeling, the Dutch
standing with their arms around one another.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, who've now been in shootouts in three of the
last four Cups, calmly slammed home four shots -- first Ronaldo,
then Rivaldo, then Emerson, then Dunga. Frank de Boer and Dennis
Bergkamp cashed theirs for the Dutch, but Taffarel dove left to
deny Cocu. Now came Ron de Boer, stutter-stepping to throw Taffarel
off, then watching in shock as the keeper dove right and knocked
the ball awry.
</P>
<P>
   For a long while, the Dutch stood on the pitch, hands on hips,
reluctant to leave. It had been 20 years since they'd been this
close. ``The dream is over,'' said Ron de Boer. ``It's a pity.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Brazilians, the only non-European team to win the Cup in
Europe (in 1958), the party continues. ``In Brazil, people are
already celebrating,'' said coach Mario Zagallo. ``But will we only
celebrate after the final. We are here only to win -- and we will
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
