<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-DEFECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SAY PAKISTANI DEFECTOR IS NOT CREDIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of scientists who questioned the Pakistani claiming to
be a defector from his country's nuclear weapons program have
concluded that he knows nothing about nuclear physics.
</P>
<P>
   The story told by Iftikhar Khan Chaudhry, who is seeking asylum
in the United States, ``just seems to be made up out of whole
cloth,'' said Frank von Hipple, a professor of public and
international affairs at Princeton University who helped organize
the questioning, which was conducted both in English and in Khan's
native Urdu.
</P>
<P>
   Khan had told a series of news conferences last week that as a
research scientist in Pakistan's nuclear arms program he had been
present at a meeting on April 25 _ weeks before India and Pakistan
drew international alarm with dueling nuclear tests _ at which the
military high command, fearing a strike by India, authorized a
pre-emptive nuclear attack on New Delhi within 48 hours. He said he
was ready to disclose sensitive secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But the story is now being greeted with skepticism. In the
ensuing days, Pakistani officials said he was actually a low-paid
accountant for a bathroom tile manufacturer and experts on the
region expressed considerable skepticism over the details he
provided. His story, however, was front-page news in India,
increasing strain in the already tense subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to him, in the first few sentences, it was clear his
story was not quite credible,'' Dr. Abdul Nayyar, a professor of
physics at Quaid-i-Azam University in Islamabad and a visiting
research fellow at Princeton, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave either no answers or very wrong answers,'' Nayyar
said, adding in a cricket metaphor common to Pakistan, ``He
completely bowled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nayyar, who graduated from Karachi University, which Khan also
claimed as his alma mater, said he could not describe courses there
and that when he was asked about his teachers ``he was just
concocting names.'' Indeed, he said, Khan put a physics building in
the wrong place on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Zia Mian, a Pakistani physicist and research associate at the
Woodrow Wilson school at Princeton who asked questions in Urdu with
Nayyar during a telephone conference call on Monday to the
Manhattan office of Khan's lawyer, Michael Wildes, was also
unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him what is a reactor and after much hesitation he
said it's where a reaction takes place,'' Mian said. ``We asked him
what a moderator was, and he didn't know. Now anyone who has been
reading a newspaper there the past few months would know that,
there has been so much written. He just had no comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview with Khan was set up by the Federation of American
Scientists, an organization concerned about the spread of nuclear
weapons. The group tries to support nuclear ``whistleblowers''
against persecution by their governments, and wanted to be sure the
purported defector was treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   But, said von Hipple, ``when we got into specifics, it was clear
he didn't know anything about physics or nuclear weapons.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2130EDT &QL; 
