</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-NOTEBOOK08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gonzalez on pace for the impossible
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He's quiet and relatively unobtrusive, and he trails
Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey both in home runs and interview
requests.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez was the only
player walking around this year's All-Star Game with 101 RBI, and
that's amazing to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely unbelievable,'' said McGwire, whose 37 home runs
lead all of baseball. ``It's so remarkable for anybody to have over
100 RBIs by the All Star break. He's a great, great hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   The record for RBI by the All-Star break is 103, by Hank
Greenberg in 1935. How unappreciated a statistic is the RBI?
Greenberg wasn't selected to the All Star team that season.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez is on a pace to challenge Hack Wilson's
single-season record of 190 RBI, set in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different thing than trying to hit home runs,''
Gonzalez said. ``Mark McGwire is the big guy right now in baseball.
If he stays healthy all season, he has a good chance to break the
home run record. I'm in the race for the RBI record, so I have to
stay healthy, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has played 87 games this season. After 87 game sin
1930, Hack Wilson had just 89 RBI. Of course, he hit 53 in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think about the record,'' Gonzalez said. ``I just
think about getting the runs in.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, as Griffey points out, is something he has a lot of
chances to do since he hits in the middle of that Texas lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really Juan that's impressive, it's the guys in front
of him,'' Griffey said. ``Those getting on base and being in
scoring position, that's what is impressive about the whole thing.
The guys they have hitting one, two and three, they're on base all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that only six players have ever had as many as
170 RBI in a season (Lou Gehrig did it three times and Greenberg
did it twice), and that no one's done it since 1938 (Jimmie Foxx),
makes it a stat beyond comprehension in today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one (record) I want to see broken, or at least
somebody make a run at,'' Dodgers and former Marlins outfielder
Gary Sheffield said. ``Because that's...190 RBI? That's
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graziano writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
