<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANCELLOR MEDIA IS BUYING LIN TV FOR $902.7 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chancellor Media, the nation's second-largest radio
company behind CBS, fell after it announced that it was expanding
into television with the acquisition of Lin Television for $902.7
million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have Lin's 12 network-affiliated
television stations and minority stakes in NBC affiliates as well
as Chancellor Media's 108 radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN AID MAY NOT BE ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund and the Yeltsin Government are
negotiating an aid package that may produce less money than foreign
investors say is needed to help ease Russia's financial crisis.
Russian officials have publicly stated that they need $10 billion
to $15 billion in assistance from the fund and other lenders, but
some Western investment bankers say Russia may need $20 billion or
more to rebuild investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   2 EUROPEAN EXCHANGES PLAN ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   The stock exchanges of London and Frankfurt announced a broad
alliance aimed at creating a pan-European trading system.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL AS SUMMER RALLY FALTERS
</P>
<P>
   The summer rally stalled as concerns about stock valuations
caused investors to sell shares with strong gains. Hardest hit were
Internet companies and oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond rose to 5.60 percent, from 5.57
percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOA REPORTS STRONG PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   The Aluminum Company of America, the world's largest aluminum
producer, reported a 6.3 percent increase in second-quarter
earnings, greater than expected, as increased shipments offset
lower aluminum prices.
</P>
<P>
   TWO RETAILERS WARN ABOUT EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Venator Group and Sports Authority said that their
second-quarter earnings would be less than expected, causing their
shares to fall and threatening the merger of the two biggest United
States sellers of athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL STRIKE IN PUERTO RICO
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders in Puerto Rico said that about a half-million
workers from more than 50 labor unions had joined a two-day general
strike that disrupted travel and caused many banks and businesses
to close. The strikers are seeking to halt the government's
privatization of the Puerto Rico Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
   VW FUND FOR SLAVE WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen, in an about-face, agreed to set up a fund to
compensate workers who were forced into slave labor in World War
II. According to a company-financed history, Volkswagen employed
15,000 slave laborers in the war. Volkswagen declined to say how
much it would pay or whether it would make payments to victims'
families.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS AGHAST AT POSSIBLE TOWER SALE
</P>
<P>
   Can an American company buy the Eiffel Tower? A subsidiary of
GMAC, GM's financial arm, is interested, along with the Bass
brothers of Texas, in buying a 70 percent interest in the
state-owned Credit Foncier de France, which has a stake in the
company that manages the famed tower. The move is seen as an
outrage by many Parisians, who say that the law forbids aliens of
any kind, including Americans, to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS' BUSINESS PARTNERS
</P>
<P>
   A new nationwide study shows that employers that work closely
with their local high schools _ offering everything from materials
to tutorials about the world of work _ have a turnover rate among
young employees as low as half that of other companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
