<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ABIOLA-940(2T     07-07 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABIOLA-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILED NIGERIAN DIES DURING ENVOYS' VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nigeria's most prominent political prisoner,
Moshood Abiola, died Tuesday, apparently of a heart attack, further
complicating an already turbulent political situation in Africa's
most populous country.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, who was 60 years old, became ill while meeting with U.S.
and Nigerian officials at a government guest house in Abuja, the
capital. He died shortly afterward in a hospital, U.S. and Nigerian
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said in Washington
on Tuesday, ``We do not have any reason to believe this is anything
but natural causes.'' But at least one of Abiola's children said
the death was suspicious and another said that the government that
had kept her father imprisoned and denied him medical care was
culpable in his death. The Nigerian government promised a full,
prompt autopsy in cooperation with Abiola's personal physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's death was the second stunning development in Nigeria in
less than a month. On June 9, Gen. Sani Abacha, the unrelenting
dictator who had thrown Abiola into jail in 1994, died suddenly,
also of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, Abacha's successor, had been expected
to free Abiola, the apparent victor in Nigeria's aborted 1993
elections, soon. The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, said after
meeting Abiola in Nigeria last week that he had promised to
forswear his claim to the presidency and work toward a smooth
transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that Abiola fell ill Tuesday while speaking to Thomas
Pickering, the undersecretary of state for political affairs, and
Susan Rice the assistant secretary for African affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first 10 minutes, Abiola starts wheezing and coughing
and then collapsing in some form,'' Rubin told reporters here. ``I
don't know if he lost consciousness. They get him in an ambulance
or car. They get him to the hospital, where he dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering told National Public Radio that when Abiola came into
the meeting he appeared to be in good health and good spirits, but
that his condition quickly deteriorated and that he began to cough
and was ``clearly disturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, speaking by telephone to NPR, explained that Abiola
excused himself from the meeting, went to a restroom, and returned
in more distress. ``When he came out of the toilet, he asked for
painkillers. And then sat on a couch and was overheated and asked
for the room to be cooled, and removed some of his garments, and
then clearly began to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said he took Abiola's pulse and said he was ``clearly
very cold and very disturbed and in some significant pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola was taken to a hospital, accompanied by the U.S.
officials, who watched as doctors worked to save him, Pickering
told the radio program ``All Things Considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering's delegation extended its stay until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hafsat Abiola, the 23-year-old daughter of Abiola, blamed her
father's death on the Nigerian military. In a telephone interview
from suburban Maryland, where she lives with five of her 18
siblings, Ms. Abiola said: ``My position is simple. My father was
in their custody. Anything that happened to him while he was in
their custody is their responsibility. I can't believe they did
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father had not been well lately, Ms. Abiola said, adding
that she had repeatedly asked Nigerian authorities to let a doctor
see him. A U.S. official involved in African policy said that
Abiola suffered from high blood pressure and swollen limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Another daughter, Wura Abiola, told CNN that the family
considered the death ``very suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan said Tuesday he had attempted to inquire about Abiola's
health when he met with him last week. ``He was alert and asked
questions. But it was obvious from the questions that he was in
isolation,'' Annan said. ``For example, he didn't know who I was. I
walked in, shook hands and smiled and started asking about his
health. He asked, `Who are you?' And I explained that I'm the
secretary-general of the United Nations. And then he asked, `What
happened to the Egyptian, is he gone?''' in a reference to Annan's
predecessor, Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who spoke at an impromptu news conference at the United
Nations on Tuesday, said: ``I'm not in a position to describe the
conditions under which he was kept. But he did say that he had been
in solitary confinement and was allowed no television, no press, no
media except the Bible and the Koran.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan added, ``I hope the government of Nigeria will make good
on its pledge to release all remaining political prisoners
unconditionally and to define a credible process for the transition
to civilian rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's release had been delayed, in part because Abiola's
followers, mainly members of the Yoruba tribe in southwestern
Nigeria, around the old capital of Lagos, insisted that he should
be permitted to take office. In Lagos on Tuesday some rioting and
looting were reported after the news of Abiola's death, Reuters
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which is dominated by Hausa officers from
Northern Nigeria, now faces the possibility of severe tribal
tensions. In the late 1960s, the Ibo and their allies in
southeastern Nigeria precipitated a civil war when they proclaimed
the independent state of Biafra. Diplomats have expressed fears in
the last few weeks that violence may lie just beneath the surface
now.
</P>
<P>
   Any fighting in Nigeria, which with its oil and natural
resources has the potential for being the richest country in
sub-Saharan Africa, could destabilize the weaker neighboring
countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by Annan and Western leaders to move his country onto
the road to democracy, Abubakar has already released Gen. Olusegun
Obasanjo, a former military ruler, and 25 other political
prisoners, but 250 or more remain in Lagos jails, intelligence
officials said. Many of them are not nearly as prominent as Abiola,
a wealthy businessman and tribal chief.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that Pickering ``had not received agreement in terms
of a firm timetable to let Abiola out, but the government did make
clear that he would be out soon.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a written statement released Tuesday,
said, ``I was deeply saddened to learn of the sudden and untimely
death of M.K.O. Abiola, a distinguished citizen and patriot of
Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria remains in economic chaos, ravaged by corruption and
incompetence. Despite the country's immense oil reserves _ it is
the fifth-largest supplier of petroleum to the United States _
motorists are forced to wait for hours at the small number of
filling stations that function.
</P>
<P>
   Limited sanctions imposed by the United States and others have
compounded the country's difficulties. Abacha ignored the rest of
the world but Abubakar has appeared eager to reach out to friendly
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's mission to Nigeria, which was not announced in advance,
followed several telephone conversations with Abubakar and a secret
meeting with the Nigerian foreign minister, according to William
Shawcross, a British journalist who covered the Annan visit.
Shawcross said Abubakar told the secretary-general that he wanted
to hand power back to a democratically elected government but
implied that some other generals were not so sure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
