<HEADLINE>
ROCHAM CLINTON TO VISIT MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton will visit Pittsfield, Mass. next week as
part of a four-day bus tour of ``America's Treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady's press office said she will kick off the tour in
Washington next Monday, but would not confirm the sites to be
visited. However the Berkshire Eagle reported Tuesday that it would
be Pittsfield's historic Colonial Theater.
</P>
<P>
   An official announcement of the trip will be made Wednesday,
said Julie Mason, a Clinton spokeswoman. ``She's hoping to
highlight some of these pieces of our heritage,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   On the four-day trip, the First Lady will visit potential
preservation sites, Mason said. Mrs. Clinton is honorary chairwoman
of the Millennium Committee to Save America's Treasures, a
public-private partnership created to preserve historic sites and
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will begin Monday at the Smithsonian's Museum of
American History, where the President and Mrs. Clinton will view
the original copy of ``The Star-Spangled Banner,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   The culmination of the trip will be in Seneca Falls, N.Y., for
the 150th anniversary of the Seneca Falls Convention, birthplace of
the women's suffrage movement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
