<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNN-JENNIFER-SPI &LR;      07-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNN-JENNIFER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER DUNN FINDS A RARITY ON HER CAMPAIGN TRAIL: A DETERMINED
CHALLENGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ With her name increasingly mentioned as a
post-Gingrich Speaker of the House, Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., is
campaigning across the country and opening her ample coffers to
worthy GOP candidates for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In her district east of Seattle, however, Dunn faces something
unusual _ a determined opponent in Heidi Behrens-Benedict.
Democrats are trying to convince themselves that Dunn, who hasn't
had a serious challenge in years, is ripe for an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, 57, vows never to be caught napping. ``I don't mess around
with campaigns,'' she said. ``I always take my opponents seriously
and run full bore campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens-Benedict, 50, is a political novice, drawn into the 8th
District race by her outrage at the recent shootings at a
Springfield, Ore., high school and the feeling that she needed to
take a stand against gun violence and the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I researched Jennifer's votes in the House and found her
record so polarizing, 100 percent for the National Rifle
Association and zero for children, that it does not represent folks
in this district,'' she said. ``I think Dunn is voting the straight
right-wing party line. She is out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``As mothers and parents, it is our obligation to protect our
children, not only the children of our body but the children of our
community and country. I am the person to make that case against
Jennifer Dunn.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a shot aimed directly at the core of Dunn's efforts these
days. Dunn has spearheaded an extensive post-1996 Republican effort
to uncover and remedy the party's weakness with women voters, which
doomed Bob Dole's presidential candidacy two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn has also been given increasing public exposure as a
comforting presence in a House GOP leadership known for its harsh
public statements on social policy. ``They bring her in to be the
picture of what today's Republican woman should be,'' said Cathy
Allen, a liberal Seattle political consultant who has, nonetheless,
been courted in Dunn's effort to make the Republican Party more
appealing to women.
</P>
<P>
   One shot by a challenger does not win a war. Dunn has already
gone over the $1 million mark in her fund raising.
Behrens-Benedict, a small business owner, has raised about $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, a three-term House member, has enjoyed only token
opposition in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, Democratic-aligned constituency groups, while
opposed to Dunn, are muted in their support for Behrens-Benedict's
side.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Cooper, state director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League, has long argued that Dunn talks a pro-choice line
while voting to restrict abortions for poor women. ``We'll probably
endorse _ What's her name? Heidi? _ but the resources, I don't
know,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Arthur, the Sierra Club's Northwest director, gets mad
every time he sees one of Dunn's TV spots featuring herds of elk or
the congresswoman in a canoe. Dunn's latest rating on environmental
votes by the League of Conservation Voters is 6 (out of 100).
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't looked particularly at that race, no,'' Arthur
said. ``Whether or not we will, I don't know. I'm going to be
hard-pressed to move beyond the races we have already staked out.
We try to be in places where we can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is leaving nothing to chance. Last week, at the Bellevue
Botanical Garden, she assembled a powerful lineup of
conservationists and good-government activists to announce
legislation designed to preserve commercial forest lands at a time
of rapid population growth.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would allow local governments to issue bonds, which
would be used by non-profit groups to buy up forest land. Trees
would be cut, but at less intensity and with more preservation of
recreation land and streamside habitats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an environmental policy that is out of the lands of
government and into the hands of local communities,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   James Ellis, a Seattle civic leader whose causes have ranged
from cleanup of Lake Washington to the Mountains-to-Sound Greenway,
praised Dunn as ``a national leader of significant ability and
prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn has the power to push such ideas. She has a seat on the
tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee, and is vice chairwoman
of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is promising that the GOP-run 105th Congress will be able
to point to accomplishments by the time it adjourns at the end of
September. She predicts a ``narrowly focused tobacco bill,'' reform
of the Internal Revenue Service, and a limited patient's bill of
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn has a knack for making controversial leadership positions
palatable. On patients rights, House GOP chieftains torpedoed a
sweeping accountability plan for health maintenance organizations
submitted by Republican Reps. Greg Ganske of Iowa and Charlie
Norwood of Georgia. Ganske is a surgeon, Norwood a dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they wanted was too many regulations,'' Dunn said. And,
as on many other issues, she promised that the leadership's
scaled-back health plan ``will have no new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is a poised picture of power. Behrens-Benedict is
passionate but unschooled in what has been her opponent's
profession for two decades. ``Lack of experience is like natural
childbirth,'' the challenger joked. ``Lots of this I do not know,
but I am not naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens-Benedict bristles at the suggestion that Democrats may
be using her to tie down Dunn and keep Dunn's fund-raising prowess
from deployment in other, closer races. ``I am in this for the long
haul and I actually expect to win,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One symbol of Dunn's leisurely 1992, 1994 and 1996 races was an
oft-aired TV spot showing her canoeing with one of her two sons. As
if to acknowledge that Dunn has a serious foe, she has retired the
canoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my favorite commercial of all time, but we're going to do
something different this year,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
