<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4533 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-TRIAL-1STLD-WRI     07-07 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout. Story is now complete in 1
take) MARKHASEV FOUND GUILTY OF MURDERING ENNIS COSBY 
 (sw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A jury took less than six hours on Tuesday to find
19-year-old Mikail Markhasev guilty of murdering Ennis Cosby, the
son of the entertainer Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev smiled briefly in the packed courtroom as the verdict
was read, then he stood expressionless as the slain man's mother
and sisters hugged each other and began to sob.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev was found guilty of first-degree murder and attempted
robbery under circumstances that could bring him a sentence of life
in prison without parole. Judge David Perez of Superior Court in
Santa Monica scheduled the sentencing for Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors lauded the verdict, Henry Hall, one of the two
public defenders who represented Markhasev, said at a news
conference afterward that he believed the intense media scrutiny
and fame of Cosby's father had turned attention away from a sober
analysis of the evidence and had brought about an unfair verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Hall made a fine distinction. He said the jury was not directly
tainted and that ``the celebrity of the Cosby family I don't think
had a direct impact on the trial.'' But he also insisted, ``The
societal presumption was that there would be a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Ingalls, the deputy district attorney who prosecuted the
case, vigorously dispute Hall's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the jury was extremely responsible in what they
did,'' Ms. Ingalls said. ``I think that the evidence convicted Mr.
Markhasev. I think that Mr. Markhasev convicted Mr. Markhasev and
not the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby attended the trial for the first time on Monday, the
day the closing arguments concluded. He was there with his wife,
Camille, and his daughters Erika and Erinn.
</P>
<P>
   He was not present on Tuesday, but through a spokesman he issued
a statement after the verdict was read, saying, ``The Cosby family
is satisfied with the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ennis Cosby was 27 and a doctoral student of education at
Columbia University when he was fatally shot once in the head while
changing a flat tire alongside a highway in the early morning hours
of Jan. 16, 1997. The police said it appeared to have been an
unplanned but botched robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the entirely circumstantial nature of the prosecution's
case, which relied on a hair found with the murder weapon, letters
handed over by a man facing unrelated forgery charges and a tip to
the National Enquirer, the jury seemed to have dispatched quickly
with Markhasev's defense that a friend of his had actually shot
Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   In the letters prosecutors said Markhasev wrote after his
arrest, to the forgery suspect and others, a fellow inmate in the
county jail, he referred to the Cosby killing as a ``robbery gone
bad.'' DNA evidence showed that the hair, found inside a cap
wrapped around the murder weapon, was almost certainly Markhasev's.
And Christopher So, who was paid $40,000 by The National Enquirer
for interviews and stands to get a $100,000 reward from the
magazine if Markhasev is convicted because he led the police to the
murder weapon, testified that Markhasev had said he shot a black
man, and that ``It's all over the news.''
</P>
<P>
   But Markhasev's mother testified that her son had been with her
the night of the murder, and his lawyers had argued that the
incriminating letters had been forged.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began with several claims that were ultimately
unsubstantiated. Early in the trial the prosecution made the
sensational claim that Markhasev was a member of a notorious prison
gang, and Markhasev's lawyers said they would prove that Eli
Zakaria, a friend of Markhasev, had committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   None of the those assertions were proved. Ultimately, the case
boiled down to the accidental and ultimately tragic crossing of the
paths of the two young men, one who had done reasonably well in
school after immigrating here from the Ukraine before sliding into
a life of crime, and the other apparently working hard to build a
career as an educator out of the shadow of his wealthy and famous
father.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev was arrested in March, 1997, after a highly publicized
police search following what appeared from the start to have been a
senseless crime. Ennis Cosby had apparently been driving in his
father's Mercedes-Benz to visit a friend when the car got a flat
tire. He pulled off the highway at a quiet spot and called a friend
to help him change the tire.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Stephanie Crane, showed up and witnessed a man
threatening Cosby. She was forced to leave, then came back to find
Cosby dead, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   The police used her description to create a sketch of the
murderer, but they were unable to make an arrest until The National
Enquirer received a tip from So, a friend of Markhasev, who hoped
to claim the $100,000 reward. So led the police to a field where
they found the gun that seemed to have been used in the killing.
Markhasev was arrested and charged with the crime shortly
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev never took the witness stand. His lawyers argued that
the witnesses against him were motivated by greed and a desire to
receive more favorable treatment from police in unrelated charges
that each of them faced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
