</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-TAFFAREL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL GOALIE HAS ANSWER FOR BRAZIL FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLES, France _ Without a job as recently as 1995, Claudio
Taffarel was fully employed Tuesday night, and when he had finished
his long evening's work in the Brazilian goal, his gift for getting
in the way of penalty kicks had made him a soccer hero at home
again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he stopped three in a semifinal victory over the
Germans at the Summer Olympics in Seoul. In 1994, he stopped one
and watched attempts by Franco Baresi and Roberto Baggio sail over
his crossbar in the victory over Italy in the World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he was back in the crucible against the Dutch in
the semifinals, and after his more famous teammates Ronaldo,
Roberto Carlos and Rivaldo failed to make the difference in 120
minutes of conventional soccer, Taffarel calmly took his spot on
the goal line and took over.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch captain, Frank de Boer, and the star striker Dennis
Bergkamp, who took the first two penalty kicks for the Netherlands,
both scored, but Taffarel had still guessed the direction of their
shots correctly. He would do better against the next two Dutchmen:
diving to his left to block Philip Cocu and diving to his right to
deflect the shot of de Boer's twin brother, Ronald.
</P>
<P>
   What he proved unable to fend off was the human wave of
Brazilian players and officials who quickly engulfed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so very happy, and I hope that the Brazilian people now
will trust me and the team more,'' Taffarel said. ``They have been
very hard on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Taffarel owes his place on the national team to the trust of
coach Mario Zagallo, who chose to ignore Brazilian critics who
believed Taffarel was too old and slow at 32 to play in a third
consecutive World Cup. There were calls for Dida, a 24-year-old who
plays for the Brazilian club Cruzeiro; calls for Carlos Germano, a
28-year-old who plays for the Brazilian club Vasco de Gama.
</P>
<P>
   But Zagallo held firm, and Tuesday night, with a reflex save off
a Bergkamp blast early in the second half and his two educated
guesses in the penalty kick phase, Taffarel returned the favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud that I was able to show my gratitude for the
opportunity that Zagallo gave me,'' Taffarel said.
</P>
<P>
   The goalkeeper also showed his gratitude to God. Since 1988, he
has been a member of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes _ a group
to which teammate Cesar Sampaio also belongs _ and after stopping
De Boer's shot, he stared into the summer sky and said a few words.
</P>
<P>
   Faith has long proved important to Taffarel, and he said last
week that it seldom helped him more than in November 1994, when,
after playing a key role in Brazil's run to an unprecedented fourth
World Cup title, he found himself out of a job after failing to
impress his employers at the Italian first division club Reggiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``World champion and no club,'' he said. ``It's incredible but
true. For seven months, I was unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   But not inactive. To occupy his ample free time, he played
striker for a church team in the suburbs of Reggiana, wearing No. 9
instead of his customary No. 1. Though he scored 15 goals in seven
matches, he eventually found work in the Brazilian first division,
and he has now found more profitable work beginning this fall with
the Turkish club Galatasaray, which recently signed him to a
two-year contract worth $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeepers are seldom the focus in Brazil, a nation where
strikers and playmakers are the heroes that youngsters imitate on
the beaches and in the city streets. But after Tuesday night, it is
possible that young Brazilians may be busy imitating Taffarel along
with Ronaldo this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite becoming a goalkeeper at the advanced age of 17,
Taffarel and the team captain, Dunga, now have appeared in more
matches in the World Cup finals than any other Brazilians before
them: 18. Taffarel only hopes his 19th on Sunday in the final does
not have quite so thrilling a finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more penalty kicks,'' he said. ``I know the Brazilians
suffer too much when we get to that stage.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
