<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH3-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL DEFEATS NETHERLANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE _ Brazil's dream of an unprecedented fifth World Cup
title appeared in danger so many times Tuesday night that when it
lived on, thanks to two tremendous saves by Claudio Taffarel, there
seemed to be more to it than what was readily apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Taffarel, never the most capable of goalkeepers, was
otherworldly when it mattered most, stopping the Netherlands in the
shootout as the Brazilians, despite spending much of the match on
their heels, earned the chance to defend their title with a
semifinal triumph at Stade Velodrome in Marseille.
</P>
<P>
   Diving left to stop Phillip Cocu, then right to halt Ronald de
Boer, Taffarel handed the world's most respected team a 4-2 victory
on penalty kicks following an often stirring 1-1 draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't me,'' he protested when it was over. ``This was God
helping me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, despite a superb Ronaldo goal seconds into the
second half, needed supreme guidance to survive as Holland,
outplaying them at their own game, created chance after chance
after chance.
</P>
<P>
   That only one of them, an 87th-minute header by Patrick
Kluivert, found the net had more to do with Dutch inaccuracy
Brazil's defensive brilliance, although the South Americans in a
move that seemed to go against everything they espouse spent most
of the second half bundled up in front of their net, using a
counterattack as their only weapon.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wise tactic that nearly paid off with a regulation
victory; Kluivert's goal, Holland's fourth late tally of the
tournament, ended that, and the 30-minute overtime period that
followed brought the sort of soccer anticipated from these powers:
attacking, entertaining, often enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over after penalty kicks had determined the
Brazilians would play on, against France or Croatia at the Stade de
France, and that Holland would meet the other in Saturday's
third-place game Brazil coach Mario Zagallo wept openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penalties are a lottery,'' he said, ``but I went to the
players one by one and told them we are going to win this
championship. ... In Brazil right now people are celebrating. We're
only going to celebrate at the final.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch, he admitted, ``were superior, but they didn't know
how to translate this into goals.'' The inability of Dennis
Bergkamp, Holland's top forward, to make any impact whatsoever,
didn't help, but they had plenty of chances in the second half and
overtime to take control.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil had the upper hand once Ronaldo fired it ahead with his
fourth goal of the Cup. It occurred off the second-half kickoff,
with Rivaldo sending a ball into the box from the left flank,
curling it ahead of the onrushing striker, who took it on the
outside of his left foot, then placed it neatly under goalkeeper
Edwin Van der Sar all the while fending off Cocu.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, the Brazilians sat back and let the Dutch
own the ball, limiting most of their attacks to counters. Unable to
penetrate, the Dutch created just two strong chances a Jaap Stam
blast off a corner kick that Taffarel stopped, and a Kluivert
misfire off a fine give-and-go with substitute Pierre Van Hooijdonk
before Kluivert evened things with only three minutes plus injury
time to play.
</P>
<P>
   The counter nearly served up a handful of Brazilian goals. Twice
Ronaldo bore down on Van der Sar, once in overtime, but Edgar
Davids and Frank de Boer the two best players on the field took him
out of the play. On the former, Davids was fortunate not to pick up
a second yellow card or surrender a penalty kick, and Ronaldo fired
inches wide of the post.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo, too, nearly tallied, but Stam redirected a Denilson
feed under the Brazilian; by the time Rivaldo got his shot off, Van
der Sar was there to bury it.
</P>
<P>
   Kluivert's goal was superb. It came off a turnover, a poor
clearance off Davids' chest that Cocu headed down, then sent to
Ronald de Boer on the right wing. De Boer's cross found Kluivert
all alone about 8 yards out, and his header left Taffarel no
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded chances in overtime, with Ronaldo twice coming
close Frank de Boer making the big stop and Kluivert firing just
wide of the far post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extra time,'' Zagallo said, ``was all heart, disposition,
determination.''
</P>
<P>
   That sent the game to the shootout, in which Brazil has had
notable success before. In its triumph over Italy in the 1994
final, Taffarel had little to do, watching two Italians Franco
Baresi and Roberto Baggio clearing the crossbar with shots.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he came up big.
</P>
<P>
   The first five shooters Ronaldo, Rivaldo and Emerson for Brazil,
and Frank de Boer and Bergkamp for the Dutch connected, but Cocu
put his shot too close to center, and Taffarel easily knocked it
away.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga followed with a drive over the diving Van der Sar to make
it 4-2, and then Ronald de Boer's attempt to the lower left found
an outstretched Taffarel instead of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like lotto,'' Ronald de Boer said. ``It should go in
there. It's a very dreadful feeling; that's all I can say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream is over. It's a pity.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutch coach Guus Hiddink, who was missing two starters injured
winger Marc Overmars and suspended defender Arthur Numan as well as
Numan's planned replacement, injured Winston Bogarde, tried to keep
from making excuses for losing and failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hide behind excuses,'' he said. ``It's always
rather cheap to (bring up players who can't play). I don't want to
look at this as an excuse. I think we have a good squad. ... You
must not look for excuses like injuries or a day less rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Taffarel didn't need to look for reasons for the win, and he
acknowledged it wasn't victory enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won anything yet except a very tough battle,'' he
said. ``This Brazil is ready to be five-times champion. And we'll
do everything we can to win it. The team is very much ready for the
final.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
