A4539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOUGING-TRIAL-TEX     07-07 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOUGING-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN PLEADS GUILTY IN EYE GOUGING, IS SENTENCED TO MILITARY SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MEDE NIX 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Just before a judge expected to declare a mistrial
Tuesday because of a deadlocked jury, a high school wrestler agreed
to a plea bargain for gouging the eyes of a gang member during a
fight and will be sent to a military school in Pennsylvania until
he turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   The swift and surprising conclusion to 21/2 days of
deliberations by a jury that repeatedly declared it could not reach
a decision left female friends of the former wrestler, Daniel G.
Johnson, 17, in tears and friends of the almost-blinded
16-year-old, Jason Prickett, shocked that Johnson was headed to
Glen Mills School in a Philadelphia suburb instead of a Texas Youth
Commission facility.
</P>
<P>
   But District Judge Hal Gaither, who called prosecutors and
defense attorneys together Tuesday afternoon to tell them he
expected a mistrial Wednesday, said it was the best solution. The
military academy is renowned for dealing with gang members and
youths with anger and aggression problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gaither told Johnson that if he gets into trouble at Glen Mills,
he faces 20 years in prison, the maximum sentence for the
second-degree felony of aggravated assault. But if he successfully
completes the program at Glen Mills, it will be as if he never had
a criminal record. Johnson will turn 18 on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he would agree to anything that would get him back
in school,'' defense attorney David Scoggins said of his client.
``The state wanted TYC, and we wanted probation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gaither declined both, noting that juvenile courts will have
jurisdiction over Johnson only until he turns 18. Gaither said he
has sent about ``10 kids'' to Glen Mills, which costs about $96 a
day, compared to about $120 per day to keep a youth in a Texas
Youth Commission facility, he said. Texas will pay for his
Pennsylvania stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen Mills is run just like West Point is run,'' he said. ``It
is very discipline-oriented. It costs somewhat less to go to Glen
Mills, but the issue is what's best for the community. I'm
satisfied that this is best for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ward, 16, a friend of Prickett, said: ``I don't feel that
his sentence was strong enough. It should have been a lot stronger.
Jason is blind for life and (Johnson) is going to a military school
for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Prickett's mother, Beverly, who testified that her son's medical
bills are up to about $20,000, asked the judge to sentence Johnson
to a Texas Youth Commission facility. She said she cannot pay the
bills and she has applied for help from a victim's assistance fund.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was a glimpse into the haves and have-nots of suburban
teen life in Richardson, a suburb of Dallas. Friends of Prickett,
with unusual hairstyles, multiple earrings and baggy clothes, held
an uneasy truce in the halls of the Henry Wade Juvenile Justice
Center with Johnson's well-dressed upper-middle-class friends from
J.J. Pearce High School.
</P>
<P>
   The defense made much of Prickett's status as a ninth-grade
dropout and leader of a street gang called Third Power, contending
Prickett precipitated the fight with threats against Johnson and
other Pearce students. But the prosecution made no apologies for
Prickett's lifestyle. Prosecutor Denise Hale said Prickett ``is
what he is'' but did not deserve what he got. Prickett lost sight
in his left eye and has impaired vision in his right, injuries that
prosecutors said went far beyond self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson testified Wednesday that he gouged Prickett's eyes in
self-defense during a confrontation between gang members and Pearce
athletes in a Richardson field April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Prickett, who was not in court when the compromise was reached,
told his friends that he is upset with the outcome and didn't want
to talk, said another friend, Shawn Smith, 20.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were pleased that Johnson pleaded guilty but were
disappointed with the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he was a candidate for TYC,'' said Charlie Martin,
another prosecutor. ``It was vicious. But at least he won't be in
Richardson, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen's father, Jerry Johnson, said he is relieved that the
matter was resolved, but said his son should have been cleared of
the charges. He said his son was trying to protect others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected Danny to be released. He was righting everything
that they were doing. He stood up for his friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Johnson said his son regrets that Prickett was so badly
injured. ``He is sorry the boy was injured. He is not an
optometrist. He didn't know how much damage he did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors did not talk to the media, but Gaither said they told him
they were hung up over the issue of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some confusion over the testimony and who did what
and when,'' Gaither said. ``They were solidly entrenched, but they
were willing to work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, before last week's holiday break, jurors told the
judge they were deadlocked at 9-3. On Monday, it was a 10-2
deadlock, but notes to the judge never indicated which verdict the
majority favored. Gaither said he wouldn't reveal that either,
although defense attorneys speculated that the majority was in
favor of a finding of delinquent conduct, which is equivalent to a
guilty verdict in adult court.
</P>
<P>
   Gaither said that if he had declared a mistrial, he would have
rescheduled the trial for July 20. In a second trial, the
prosecution would have had an advantage because it would have seen
all the defense's case and bolstered its weaknesses, Gaither said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Bill Teeter contributed to this report. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
