<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOUGING-TRIAL-SCHOOL-     07-07 0168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOUGING-TRIAL-SCHOOL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-GOUGING-TRIAL-TEX) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glen Mills School is a private, nonprofit, all-male residential
treatment program in Concordville, Pa., specializing in treating
tough, gang-oriented youths from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   All students must compete in sports and are pushed hard to earn
their high school diplomas and complete courses in vocational
skills. The school, which has no fences or bars, has produced
numerous college graduates and even Rhodes Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which was modeled after West Point, operates on the
philosophy that changes in behavior come from peer pressure,
positive staff members and role models and recognition of personal
effort. Students have to earn privileges, such as going home for
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   (Sources: District Judge Hal Gaither, Glen Mills School)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
