<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/7/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BRIELLE, N.J. -- July 7, 1998 -- DATEK-MARKETPLACE, 7-7
-- Even without the big payout a stock offering would bring,
Jeffrey Citron, the 27-year-old chief of Datek Online, has been
able to buy a home complete with an elaborate sculpture garden in
Brielle. Datek, one of the nation's fastest-growing online
brokerage firms, has postponed an initial public offering of stock
because of widening investigations into its trading practices,
according to people close to the firm. (Steven O. Boljonis/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 7, 1998 -- NY-JUDGE-REMOVED, 7-7 --
Lorin Duckman, the New York City judge who became a favorite target
of politicians' complaints about a fuzzy-minded, too-lenient
judiciary, lost his final bid to retain his job Tuesday, when the
state's highest court ruled that a state commission was right to
remove him from the bench. Last October, on a 7 to 4 vote, the
commission ordered him removed from the bench. (Nancy Siesel/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRINCE FREDERICK, Md. -- July 7, 1998 --
MD-GOLDSTEIN-FUNERAL, 7-7 -- Mrs. Frances Glendening, far left,
Gov. Parris Glendening of Maryland and Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy
Townsend lead a group of mourners Tuesday from the funeral for
Louis Goldstein, Maryland's comptroller for the last 40 years, to
the cemetery a quarter-mile away. Goldstein died of a heart attack
at his home here Friday at the age of 85. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) EAST MADISON, Maine -- July 7, 1998 --
ARTISTS-COLONY-BOS, 7-7 -- Fresco Instructor Daniel Bohzkov of
Bulgaria, right, works with students at the Showhegan School of
Painting and Sculpture in East Madison. With no phones or
televisions in the dorms, what feels confining at first becomes
liberating. Friends don't expect you to return calls. Laundry gets
ignored. Pick-up soccer games and browsing in the library take the
place of household chores. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- July 7, 1998 -- VIKING-SAIL-BOS, 7-7 -- W.
Hodding Carter (at the helm) and his nine-man crew have set sail
once again on the Snorri, a 54-foot wooden replica of a Viking
ship, and are attempting to recreate Q as authentically as possible
Q the voyage of Leif Ericsson. During last year's maiden voyage, a
rudder broke and the boat was towed back to Greenland by the
Canadian Coast Guard. ``It was horrible,'' Carter says. ``I kept
fooling myself, saying we can keep on going. We would have probably
died.'' (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- July 7, 1998 -- FREUD-EXHIBIT, 7-7 --
Michael Roth, curator of the Library of Congress exhibition called
``Sigmund Freud: Conflict and Culture,'' which is set to open on
Oct. 15. ``It will show Freud's contested legacy,'' says Roth.
``But it will show that Freud was responding to issues that remain
vital today, such as explosive violence, and the fact that people
remain deeply troubled even though they have the capacity for
satisfaction in love and work.'' (Marissa Roth/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 7, 1998 -- NY-BRUNCH, 7-7 -- At Grange
Hall in Greenwich Village, a typical brunch now has bagels mingling
with seaweed salads. The strange world of brunch continues to
expand, generating bizarre new life forms, embracing flavors and
ingredients never before associated with mankind's pre-noon
existence. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 7, 1998 -- ALLENDE-COOKING, 7-7 --
In her San Francisco kitchen and in her writing, Isabel Allende
explores food as magic. Tending family tradition is second nature
to the 56-year-old Chilean novelist, who says of her extended
family that ``Love and sympathy keep us close.'' (Terrence
Mccarthy/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 7, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 7-7 -- This light
Italian pinot grigio is by Santa Margherita. Fortunate wine-tasting
beginners get help from friends or a savvy wineshop clerk. They
start out with simple wines and, determinedly, educate their
palates. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 7, 1998 -- OBIT-ROGERS-B&AMP;W, 7-6 -- Roy
Rogers, a shoe factory worker's son from Cincinnati who rode a
golden palomino horse and a harmonious voice to fame as Hollywood's
most beloved and quintessential singing cowboy, died Monday at his
ranch in Apple Valley near Victorville, Calif. He was 86. Rogers is
shown here cheering patients aboard Trigger, his wonder horse, at
Bellevue Hospital in Manhattan in 1952. (Eddie Hausner/1952 New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
