<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT &LR;      07-07 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER OF CNN STAR HANGS IN THE BALANCE OVER A REPUDIATED REPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one man can make a network. But if it is possible for one man
to give a network a recognizable face, Peter Arnett did that for
Cable News Network when American bombs began to fall on Baghdad in
1991. It was his kind of story _ ``action'' is the word he comes
back to, over an over, in describing what has been the signature of
his career for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not an action story that left his career in limbo and
put him on a plane Tuesday for Atlanta for a meeting Wednesday with
network executives. That meeting could determine how long CNN's
most famous face will remain with the network.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, for Arnett's colleagues, goes to the heart of the
inner workings of television news _ how much responsibility he, as
a correspondent, bears for a now-repudiated CNN report that the
U.S. military used nerve gas in a secret 1970 mission, ``Operation
Tailwind,'' to kill American defectors in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   For CNN executives, the issue has further complexity. They are
struggling with how to stanch a public relations wound and how to
deal with perhaps their most visible star and an important asset.
The network lacks the stable of heavyweight stars of CBS, NBC and
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   There is internal dissension, too. At a meeting on Monday, some
CNN staff members who questioned Arnett's role were asking,
according to one who spoke on the condition of anonymity, why he
should be treated differently.
</P>
<P>
   If the lead producer on the report, April Oliver, can be
dismissed, if her immediate supervisor, senior producer Jack Smith,
can be dismissed, if the resignation of senior executive producer
Pamela Hill can be accepted, what about the correspondent?
</P>
<P>
   The issue, for Arnett, is how much responsibility he can be
expected to take for the investigative work of others, when he
spends his days shuttling between war zones, media conferences at
which he represents the network and magazine reports like the
repudiated one on the June 7 premiere broadcast of ``Newsstand: CNN
and Time.'' His byline appeared with Ms. Smith's on a version of
the report in Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be terribly disappointed if they saw that I had failed
the network in my relationship with this story,'' Arnett said in a
telephone interview. ``I hope they don't saddle me with the blame.
I think it's a cop-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett said he would not argue that his long service under fire
should save his 17-year career with the network, but rather that
``they should judge me on the totality of this story and my
involvement in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have to bring up Baghdad,'' he said, in a reference
to the moment that, for many, made his reputation as a television
journalist and marked the end of any derisive references to CNN as
``Chicken Noodle News.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett's reputation, however, was made earlier. After graduating
from high school in Bluff, New Zealand, the correspondent _ with
the body of a fireplug and the face slightly skewed by an early
career as a boxer _ began to irritate the people he covered early
on.
</P>
<P>
   He was thrown out of Indonesia by its government in the early
1960s. He went from there to Vietnam, where he became one of the
best known reporters in that conflict, winning a Pulitzer Prize in
1966 while working for The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   It was his Vietnam experience that made him an obvious candidate
to work on the Tailwind piece.
</P>
<P>
   It was not his idea, Arnett said, to lean so heavily on the work
of others. ``In Central America, in Baghdad during the Gulf war,
even today on action stories like covering the Baghdad crisis,'' he
said, ``we do have some producers and some assistants. But on
deadline you write the story. You're directly involved in getting
the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any choice but to be fully conversant with what
we're covering.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arnett said _ and a network spokesman confirmed _ that
although news magazine programs like CNN's ``Impact'' and its
successor, ``Newsstand,'' had some correspondents permanently
assigned to them, other correspondents, like Arnett and Christiane
Amanpour, would be called in to narrate reports developed by
others.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver and Smith, well-regarded veterans in the business
before this episode, have defended their reporting repeatedly since
their dismissals. Both say they believe that the network caved in
to pressure from former top officials, like Henry Kissinger and
Gen. Colin Powell. Network executives deny this.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett said he first heard about Ms. Oliver's research into
allegations of nerve gas use in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was traveling a lot,'' he said. ``She would call and say,
`I've got a great one. Do you want to be a part of it?' '' The two
had earlier worked on a report about units devoted to secret
operations in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was part of the team,'' he said, ``but I didn't have
supervising authority.''
</P>
<P>
   There were signs that something might be amiss. He did three
interviews, including a crucial one with a pilot who flew the
mission but said he dropped tear gas, not nerve gas. Arnett said he
flew to San Diego from Oregon to do the interview with the pilot,
Art Bishop, then immediately flew to a conference in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-second clip of the interview was cut at the last minute in
Atlanta because of time constraints. When asked if he had pushed to
have this interview included in the final script, he said: ``They
gave me the list. I asked these questions. The producers took the
tape and I was gone. I was the face.''
</P>
<P>
   But the implication that on-air correspondents are simply
mouthpieces for hardworking producers who do all the work is
infuriating to some of Arnett's colleagues. ``There are a hell of a
lot of correspondents in this business who do our own work, who ask
questions, who read, who talk to people who conduct interviews,''
said Ralph Begleiter, CNN's world affairs correspondent and, like
Arnett, a 17-year veteran of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing I could do to halt the onward rush of this
story,'' Arnett said. He did say he had called an old source, a man
who was once the second in command to Gen. Creighton Abrams in
Vietnam, and was told that the officer had never heard of the use
of nerve gas, or of Operation Tailwind. He passed this information
on to the producers, he said. But he did not use it to question the
basic premise of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions Arnett raised _ and he did not say he had raised
many _ brought crisp, sure answers. ``They had the goods,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And at another point, he noted, ``Obviously, I felt like an
idiot that I'd been in Vietnam for years and never heard about
this. But I'm also willing to believe that there are things that
happened in Vietnam that we didn't know.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
