<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE ATTORNEY'S PLEA FOR DEATH PENALTY FOR CLIENT STIRS LEGAL
STORM 
</HEADLINE>
 PLEA-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ No one knows why Samuel Ambrose was beaten bloody and
left to die on the floor of his condominium near Metrocenter.
</P>
<P>
   But the man convicted of his murder says he wants to die for the
crime, even though prosecutors didn't seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   And when the man's own defense attorney formally requested the
death penalty _ then pledged to seek it again on appeal _ the case
sparked an uproar in the Phoenix area legal community that is still
bubbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit in here 24 hours a day, seven days a week, having
nothing to think about but it,'' Douglas Alan Smith, 34, said
during a jail interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the rest of my life, every time I look in the mirror, this
will confront me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, his public defender, Jamie McAlister, asked a
judge to do just that: sentence Smith to death even though county
prosecutors never sought it.
</P>
<P>
   Even chain-gang inmates waiting in the courtroom looked
dumbstruck when McAlister asked Superior Court Judge Bernard
Dougherty to give Smith death.
</P>
<P>
   In her motion, McAlister called Ambrose's 1995 death
``especially cruel,'' stating, ``He was beaten over and over with
anything defendant could grab _ bottles, vases, what-have-you.
Samuel sustained a torrential rain of blows, 60-plus by one count.
. . . He had time to feel fear and terror.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister told the judge that she was suffering a ``great deal
of schizophrenia'' over the motion, but that it was her duty to
follow her client's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty promptly denied the request.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as promptly, McAlister abruptly reversed course and
asked for a hearing to argue for her client to receive the shortest
sentence possible.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, McAlister and co-counsel Robert Ellig were
removed from the case by the head of the public defender's office,
Dean Trebesch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of criminal-defense attorneys arguing for the death
penalty is disturbing and unacceptable to me and the vast majority
of, if not all, public defenders and other criminal-defense
attorneys,'' Trebesch said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister left the office to go into private practice. Within a
matter of days, she was reassigned to Smith's case upon his request
over another public defender's protests that her representation
could later be considered ``ineffective'' by an appeals judge.
</P>
<P>
   Although she plans to argue for a light sentence, McAlister said
she will continue to fight for her client's death if that is his
wish when the case is appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Which has angered many in the Phoenix area legal community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the old-fashioned way where the county attorney asks
for the death penalty,'' said one defense attorney, who asked to
remain unidentified.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Baich of the federal public defender's office, said, ``I
think it's outrageous that a lawyer would ask for the death penalty
when the state did not believe it was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others _ including county prosecutor Juan Martinez _
called the request akin to allowing a client to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Mr. Smith has insisted that he be put to death, the
state is not in the business of assisting in suicide,'' Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister, dismayed by her peers' reaction, said she and Smith
agonized over the decision for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the death penalty is an abomination. I think it is a
sin before God. Period,'' McAlister said. But Smith should be
allowed to die, she said, because of his mental disability _ a type
of epilepsy that causes the brain to go into seizures and
deteriorate without state-of-the-art treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Being deaf and disabled herself, McAlister said she was able to
relate to Smith's fears about deteriorating into a ``vegetative
state'' in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Because Smith can become violent when he is having a seizure, he
likely will end up in solitary confinement permanently, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he would rather die than ``end up living with a bunch
of monkeys throwing feces at each other'' in a prison mental ward.
</P>
<P>
   His death also might bring solace to Ambrose's surviving
relatives who asked for the death penalty, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel like I know them,'' Smith said about Ambrose's
widow and family. ``I sit in bed at night and think about them. I
can't wait until my sentencing. I finally get to open my mouth and
say I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was suffering from seizures in July 1995 and can
remember only being picked up by Ambrose, going home with him and
being locked in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that after the slaying, Smith turned off the
stove in Ambrose's kitchen, grabbed Ambrose's wallet and keys and
took off in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Smith in Flagstaff after stopping him in
Ambrose's car and noticing blood on his clothing. Checking
Ambrose's address, police found the bloody body of the 68-year-old
man and evidence of a struggle. Smith was convicted of first-degree
murder; a motive has never been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Smith does not believe he killed Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not voluntarily end up in this mess,'' he said. ``I'm a
victim, too. It makes me very sick. I'm very ashamed.'' &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
