u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ENDORSEMENT-COX     07-07 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENDORSEMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another Democrat backs Gov. Bush for new term
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON, Texas _ Another day, another Democratic endorsement for
Republican Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In an event becoming almost as routine as polls showing him as a
top presidential contender, Bush on Tuesday collected high praise
from a high-profile Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Former Houston Mayor Bob Lanier said backing Bush over
Democratic challenger Garry Mauro in the November general election
was an easy call, and should be for all voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Garry Mauro and I like him fine,'' Lanier said at a
news conference in his 34th-floor Houston penthouse apartment.
``But my goodness, in the private sector if you had a chief
executive who makes you lots of money and was well-regarded and
business was going great, you wouldn't seek to replace him with a
fellow who was going to learn the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier also said he would support Democrats John Sharp, who is
running against Rick Perry for lieutenant governor, and Paul Hobby,
who faces Carole Rylander in the comptroller race.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mauro was unimpressed by Lanier's endorsement of
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most popular Democrat in Texas _ Ann Richards _ and the
biggest Democrat in the world _ President Bill Clinton _ are
working to elect Garry Mauro governor, and that type of support is
significant,'' said Joe Cutbirth.
</P>
<P>
   But Lanier said he is confident that, as a Democrat for Bush, he
is in the majority among top Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, collecting and showing off Democratic endorsements like
trophies, said Lanier's support would have a ``huge effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Bob would have been leader of this city for a long, long
time if people had their way,'' Bush said of Lanier, who remained
overwhelmingly popular here last year when he hit the six-year term
limit and could not seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier, who backed Richards in 1990 when she defeated Republican
Clayton Williams for governor, declined to say whether he voted for
Bush or Richards in 1994. As a mayor elected in nonpartisan
balloting, Lanier did not endorse candidates while he was in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier is lining up this time with Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, House
Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell of San Angelo and scores of
lesser-known Democrats who have jumped the party ship. Mauro, polls
show, could be headed for a November disaster of Titanic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also has been stung by the refusal of Sharp and Hobby to
back his candidacy. A long-time player in state politics, Lanier
was appointed to the state highway commission in 1983 by then-Gov.
Mark White, a Democrat he backed. In 1980, however, Lanier
supported Republican Ronald Reagan's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Lanier said, he backed Democratic candidates about 75
percent of the time. Lanier has raised money for Clinton's
presidential campaigns, but noted that he has also hosted events
for the Republican National Committee. His goal, Lanier said, was
to ``develop sort of an ambidextrous ability'' while mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Elyse Lanier, the ex-mayor's wife, was a Richards appointee on
the University of Houston System Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   The Lanier endorsement comes a week before Bush and Mauro file
campaign finance reports expected to show that Mauro also is
getting buried in the money chase. Bush said he has about $14
million on hand. Cutbirth declined to say how much Mauro has. The
challenger spent heavily on spring TV ads that failed to move poll
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Texas Poll showed Bush with a 53-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
