<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
MOST POTENTIAL JURORS FAMILIAR WITH CADET CASE (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Even 250 miles from the site of Adrianne
Jones' slaying more than two years ago, the story lingers in the
minds of many residents.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 57 prospective jurors for David Graham's capital murder
trial interviewed Tuesday, seven indicated that they are unfamiliar
with the charges against the former Air Force Academy cadet.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Comal County residents questioned individually by
Tarrant County District Judge Don Leonard, who moved the case here
in an effort to diminish the effect of heavy publicity, said they
know basic details about Jones' slaying and the arrests of Graham
and his former fiancee Diane Zamora. Two of the panelists said they
had watched a TV docudrama based on the case, and one said he had
read one of the two books written about the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they had formed opinions about Graham's guilt or
innocence but said that they could set their feelings aside and
rule solely on the evidence. Eighteen of the 57 were excused from
jury service because they said they could not be impartial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember there were two people with outstanding capabilities
that I wished I'd had,'' said one prospective juror who was excused
from service. ``Something went dreadfully wrong, and no one won in
my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Dan Cogdell said jurors who are familiar with
the case can still be valuable for the defense if they are
``free-thinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a bunch of lambs being led to slaughter by what
the press thinks they ought to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 21, watched and took notes during the questioning, which
lasted three to five minutes for each panelist. Cogdell said Graham
was observing the potential jurors' reactions toward him, such as
looking away, frowning or staring.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the questioning, Cogdell lashed out at news
media accounts that the case against Graham is ``open and shut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense quite simply is that David Graham is not guilty,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant District Attorney Mike Parrish said Cogdell is
``trying to get sympathy'' and perhaps create jurors with a
``hidden agenda'' partial to the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are that David Graham confessed to murdering
Adrianne Jones,'' Parrish said. ``That's evidence that the jury
will hear next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said he's optimistic that a pool of 114 jurors can be
assembled by the end of the week. The potential jurors completed an
83-page questionnaire that will be analyzed by prosecutors and
defense attorneys before final jury selection takes place Monday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Leonard will consider several pretrial hearings,
including a prosecution motion to use a written confession that
Zamora made to investigators before her arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Another motion would allow Graham's mother, Janice Graham, to be
taken off the prosecution witness list in exchange for her pretrial
testimony identifying her son's handwriting in 13 letters to Zamora
after their arrests. If Janice Graham remains on the witness list,
she will not be allowed to watch the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Graham faces life in prison if convicted of the December 1995
abduction and slaying of Jones, a Mansfield High School sophomore
who was found beaten and shot to death along a rural southwest
Grand Prairie road. Zamora was convicted in February for her role
in the slaying and is serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
