</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohioans shortchanged by Medicare, report says
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Only two states are shortchanging low-income
Medicare beneficiaries more money in federal subsidies than Ohio,
according to data released Tuesday by Families USA, a non-partisan
health advocacy group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Close to two-thirds of Ohioans entitled to have their Medicare
premiums paid for are not receiving such assistance, the
organization's report said.
</P>
<P>
   The result, said Families USA, is more than 233,000 Ohioans are
losing between $122 million and $138 million a year in unpaid funds
from the state-administered programs.
</P>
<P>
   That money is coming from seniors and disabled people who can
least afford it, the report said. They're unnecessarily paying
Medicare premiums of $1,051.20 a year for low-income couples and
$525.60 for those living alone. The singles' premiums are scheduled
to rise 140 percent to $1,268.40 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the problems are resolved, the federal government will
take an even larger bite out of the meager Social Security checks
of widows and widowers in years to come,'' said Families USA
executive director Ron Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   Congress established programs in 1988 and 1990 to pay Medicare
premiums for beneficiaries with incomes below 120 percent of the
poverty level, and also to pay deductibles and co-payments for
those living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Social Security Administration is withholding about $2
billion a year nationally from people entitled to these subsidies
but apparently unaware of them, according to Families USA's
estimate. President Clinton responded with plans to reach the
affected 3.3 million to 3.9 million Americans through a publicity
campaign involving mass mailings, field workers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that eligible beneficiaries either aren't finding
out about the programs or are reluctant to pursue them, said
spokesmen for Ohio's departments of Human Services and Aging. The
subsidies are paid only to those who apply for them through the
state's Medicaid program in the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage people not to feel any type of negative view
about these programs,'' said Randy Leffler of the Department of
Aging, which operates a joint program with the Department of
Insurance in every county to educate Ohio seniors about insurance
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the report said only Texas and Florida have more
eligible beneficiaries missing out on the subsidies, and only six
states are leaving out higher percentages of eligible people.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, Families USA estimated that 59 percent to 67 percent of
those eligible for the benefits aren't receiving them. The figures
range from 9 percent to 80 percent among individual states, with
the national estimate at 42 percent to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ohioans can find out if they're eligible for federal funding of
their Medicare premiums by answering a questionnaire through the
Department of Aging's Benefits Eligibility Screening Service. Ohio
has the only Internet-based screening service at
www.state.oh.us/age/, and the service also can be called toll-free
at (800) 282-1206.
</P>
<P>
   The departments of Aging and Insurance manage the Ohio Senior
Health Insurance Information Program to answer questions about
insurance issues. Professionals answer the toll-free number at
(800) 686-1578 and volunteers in every county meet with groups or
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Applications for the federal Medicare subsidies are available at
each county's Department of Human Services, listed in the
blue-bordered government pages of the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb is a staff writer for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
