<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-07 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAINTIFF'S LAWYER CALLS BRAWLEY'S ADVISERS SELF-PROMOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ In the final argument before the jurors
consider the Tawana Brawley defamation case, the lawyer for the
plaintiff called Ms. Brawley's three advisers evil men and
self-promoters who destroyed the lives of others for their own
advancement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, William Stanton, delivered a staccato summation of
an hour and 20 minutes that seemed intended to return the focus to
what he said was the simple injustice done to his client, Steven
Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Distortions, falsehoods and calculated efforts at
self-promotion, Stanton said, were behind the advisers' accusations
a decade ago that Pagones, an assistant district attorney who is
white, was guilty of the rape and kidnapping of a black teen-ager.
Stanton urged the jurors to cut through the ``baloney'' and find
against the advisers, the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and
Alton H. Maddox Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men are dangerous,'' Stanton said. ``They are bad. They
are evil. Don't let them get away with this.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the advisers used a tactic that reminded him of Josef
Goebbels, the Nazi propagandist who he said believed that ``if you
repeat the lie often enough, people will believe it.'' He added,
``Don't fall into that trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations are expected to begin Wednesday after the judge
gives legal instructions to the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton spoke in terse phrases, reminding the jurors that Ms.
Brawley, at the center of the case, never testified. ``Where's
Tawana?'' he asked. ``Why isn't she here?''
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly returned to the theme of trying to hold the
advisers accountable. That was the theme Pagones set by filing the
civil suit after a grand jury discredited Ms. Brawley's account a
decade ago. ``These people have no conscience,'' Stanton said.
</P>
<P>
   After more than seven months in the courtroom, Stanton said he
was keeping his remarks short because ``there's nothing more to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   But his summation seemed to rekindle the passions of a case that
had dulled over the months. The courtroom, which is usually packed
with black supporters of the advisers, was dominated Tuesday by
rows of white supporters of Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   As Stanton finished, the Pagones supporters burst into applause,
which was quickly squelched by the court officers. But the outburst
seemed to be a declaration that Pagones supporters were back in the
courtroom, which has sometimes seemed to be the advisers' domain.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Dutchess County Courthouse, as well, there was a
return of the impassioned rhetoric that marked the case when it
began in November. Sharpton's lawyer, Michael Hardy, said it was
not the defendants but Ms. Brawley's attackers who had relied on
Nazi tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Mason said Stanton's remarks amounted to a racist appeal to the
Dutchess County jurors. Two of the six jurors are black and four
are white. ``Why don't you just use the N word, you racist, because
you did it impliedly,'' Mason said to the assembled reporters, with
his supporters cheering him on.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping his remarks in court so short, Stanton seemed to
assume that the jurors were already persuaded by the evidence and
needed little more than a framework.
</P>
<P>
   He spent much of his time ridiculing the defense's dark
suggestions that Pagones was part of a large conspiracy including,
as Maddox put it in his summation, ``fat cats from New York City.''
Who else was in the conspiracy, Stanton asked with a sneer, the
Queen of England? The Rockefellers? ``Who else do you want to throw
in, Ronald McDonald?''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton gave short shrift to the defense assertion that the
advisers were civil rights leaders who needed the freedom to speak
openly about official misdeeds. ``This case is not about
Mississippi in 1955,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton picked out a few facts to quarrel with the defense
interpretation. Maddox, for example, said on Monday that the lack
of any powder residue on the hands of Harry Crist Jr., a friend of
Pagones who died of a gunshot wound, proved that Crist had not
committed suicide, as a grand jury found in 1988, but had been
murdered. Maddox said Pagones was the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrably false, said Stanton on Tuesday. The grand jury
report included evidence that there was powder residue. Crist
committed suicide, Stanton said, and the advisers had committed a
new injustice by subjecting Crist's family to new speculation about
his death during the trial in State Supreme Court here.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, Stanton left the tangle of the case's
facts alone, instead drawing the sorts of expansive conclusions
about the advisers that have attracted widespread attention to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   They ignored information, he said, that would have raised
questions about their assertion that Pagones had been part of a
group of white men who attacked Ms. Brawley. ``We don't want to
know that,'' Stanton suggested was their approach.
</P>
<P>
   Because the case is civil, only five of the six jurors will have
to agree on any of the more than 100 questions they are to be asked
on a verdict sheet. The jurors are not to be sequestered.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict sheet will include sections for each of the 22
separate statements that Pagones says defamed him. For each
statement, the jurors will have to answer questions like whether
that statement was defamatory and whether it was made with
knowledge of its falsity or with reckless disregard for whether it
was true.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, over defense objections, the jurors will be asked
whether the advisers acted in a conspiracy. If the jurors answer
yes, each of the advisers could be held liable for the statements
of the others.
</P>
<P>
   While the advisers have portrayed themselves as separate
entities, Stanton worked Tuesday to cast them as a single unit,
sharing responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three of them were joined at the hip,'' Stanton said.
``They were self-promoters. They didn't care who they stepped on or
stepped over. They destroyed lives for their own
self-advancement.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
