<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-EULOGIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DARK DAY IN THE HISTORY OF THE BORDER PATROL' AS AGENTS GUNNED
DOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: This is a sidebar to story slugged AGENTS-KILLED, which will
be filed shortly.) 
 
(See optional ending) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ Immigration officials delivered sad eulogies
Tuesday for two young agents cut down at the beginning of what were
expected to be long, successful careers.
</P>
<P>
   The agents _ Susan Lynn Rodriguez, 28, and Ricardo Guillermo
Salinas, 24 _ were felled by gunfire from an assault rifle fired by
a suspect in a double homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, immigration authorities said, was the first woman
Border Patrol agent killed in the line of duty and the daughter of
a former high-ranking Border Patrol official. Salinas was a
well-regarded rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two of our finest. This is a very dark day in the
history of the Border Patrol, the Border Patrol family,'' said Joe
Garza, chief of the McAllen Border Patrol sector, at an afternoon
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   It was in January that Garza swore in Salinas as a new agent,
one of hundreds of trainees assigned to the Texas-Mexico border
under an enhanced border control effort known as Operation Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Garza and other officials were telling reporters about
Salinas _ and the fiancee and family in San Antonio the young agent
had left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Salinas has been with us for less than a year, just out
of the academy,'' Garza said. ``He was going to take his 10-month
probationary examination on Thursday, so he was a relatively new
agent. He was doing well, and was very well thought of.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza noted that Rodriguez, who joined the Border Patrol in
1992, was married to an immigration officer stationed in Harlingen
and the couple had a 1-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an outstanding young agent, one of our training
officers,'' Garza said. She is the daughter of retired Deputy
Border Patrol Chief Steve Williams of the El Paso Sector.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, the commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service who also attended the press conference,
remarked on those connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a strong immigration law enforcement family, this
saddens us even more because she is the first woman Border Patrol
agent we have lost in the line of duty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas and Rodriguez became the third and fourth Border Patrol
agents killed in the line of duty this year, and the first in Texas
since Jan. 19, 1996, when Senior Agent Jefferson Barr was shot to
death by a suspected drug trafficker near Eagle Pass. In all, 81
agents have died in action since the border force was established
in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said Border Patrol agents are part of the local
communities, and are frequently called to help local law
enforcement authorities, as they were Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men and women of the United States Border Patrol put their
lives on the line every day and, as this tragedy illustrates, not
just protecting the nation's borders,'' the INS chief said. ``We
will miss agents Salinas and Rodriguez, they were a part of the INS
family. We will remember them for the dedication and hard work here
in Harlingen, and the other places they served.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Meissner attended a memorial service for an agent
shot in the head by a suspected drug smuggler just north of the
Mexican border near Nogales, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped it would also be the last,'' Meissner said
Tuesday. ``Now, so soon, two more courageous and heroic officers
have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza said his agents frequently find themselves in
confrontations with well-armed assailants along the border and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of crime in the Valley, and the Valley is
growing very rapidly,'' said Garza. ``We constantly encounter
people who are armed, heavily armed. This is just another example
of how quickly a tragedy like this can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
