<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN     07-07 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: YOUTH-INFLUENCED ANTI-SMOKING EFFORT DOESN'T MINCE
WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next phase of an ambitious anti-smoking campaign, created
for and in part by teen-agers, is as audacious as any tobacco
company advertisement featuring anthropomorphic animals, fit and
healthy athletes or models who flash sparkling white teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising, by Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky in Miami, is the
continuation of an effort formally known as the Florida Pilot
Program on Tobacco Control, which is being financed by the tobacco
industry under a settlement reached last year with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The new installments of the television, print, outdoor and
interactive campaign, carrying over a theme centered on ``truth,''
boldly assert that youngsters can resist the imagery that sells
cigarettes if they understand the mendacious ploys being foisted
upon them by the denizens of Tobacco Road, Madison Avenue and
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message that smoking is bad for you has been out there for
so long, but it's obvious that message is not getting through,''
said Jared Perez, 17, who will be a senior at Palm Harbor
University High School in Palm Harbor, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is the marketing director for Students Working Against
Tobacco, or SWAT, a youth advocacy group that was formed by
teen-age Floridians to funnel advice and ideas about the campaign
to Crispin Porter and the Florida Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use our ads to pitch a different message,'' Perez
said, ``not that smoking is bad for you _ because we know that _
but that the industry is manipulating and targeting youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states sponsoring anti-tobacco ads include Arizona,
California, Massachusetts and New York. Interestingly, as the money
spent to advertise cigarettes declines, the money spent on
counter-campaigns _ often financed by tobacco settlements or
cigarette taxes _ is increasing. So agencies may decide they would
rather switch than fight.
</P>
<P>
   The states' ads have met with widely divergent responses. The
California campaign, for instance, has been praised for such
unconventional approaches as showing limp cigarettes to symbolize
impotence caused by smoking. A recent campaign from New York, by
contrast, has been roundly criticized as conventional and
formulaic; one spot shows Attorney General Dennis Vacco, who is up
for re-election, standing next to an American flag and lecturing to
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking campaigns need to be ``guerrilla advertising, a
little under the radar,'' and ``using the kids' language,'' said
Alex Bogusky, partner, vice chairman and creative director at
Crispin Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is ``part of a review board to which we send the ads in
rough form,'' he added, ``and then we get suggestions back to help
us avoid any large missteps.''
</P>
<P>
   One important lesson ``from working with the kids,'' Bogusky
said, is that ``the subject is a big deal to them, but the ads
don't have to be heavy; they should be kept light and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind a new television commercial about the
perils of secondhand smoke that offers a dead-on parody of the
opening credits and theme song of ``The Brady Bunch'' sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The tune has been rewritten to tell ``a story of a chain-smoking
lady'' and a man ``who was busy with three packs of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's children are shown coughing and wincing as their
parents puff away. At the end of the spot, a nurse who looks like
Alice, the Brady housekeeper, places an oxygen mask over one boy's
face.
</P>
<P>
   Print ads and posters take a similar tack in tackling other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost,'' the headline on one ad reads. ``Goes by the name of
`Conscience.''' The text continues: ``Belongs to advertising agency
executive. It was lost while he was creating tobacco ads.'' At the
bottom of the ad are names and telephone numbers of agencies with
tobacco accounts; they are designed to resemble the tear-off strips
usually found on ads on bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 agencies cited include the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago,
Gyro Worldwide in Philadelphia and Mezzina/Brown in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A second ad, carrying the headline ``Help wanted,'' says:
``Looking for talented Hollywood screenwriters. Most possess the
ability to create cool, sexy or rebellious characters without
copping out by having them smoke.'' That ad has at the bottom, also
in the style of tear-off strips, the telephone number of the Motion
Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   And a poster for shopping mall kiosks mimics the rating advisory
in a movie ad. But it presents an imaginary rating of ``L'' for
``Lazy'': ``The makers of this film couldn't think of a way to make
their characters seem cool or sexy or rebellious. So instead
they'll just smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mitchell, marketing director for the pilot program at the
Florida Department of Health in Tallahassee, said: ``No one who
smokes as much as an action character in a movie could run a mile
in six minutes. He'd get three feet and then he'd cough.''
</P>
<P>
   The television commercial is running on stations in Florida. The
print ads are scheduled to appear in the August and September
issues of national magazines such as Rolling Stone, Seventeen,
Spin, Teen and YM. The kiosk poster is appearing in malls
throughout Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the current part of the campaign is more than
$5.1 million; the total campaign, which began in April, has an
initial budget of $25 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
