<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDRAISER-INDICT-NYT     07-07 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISER-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND-RAISER IS INDICTED IN TAX CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A California Democratic fund-raiser who has already
been charged with disguising illegal campaign contributions to
President Clinton's re-election campaign was indicted Tuesday on
federal tax charges.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Hsia, a Los Angeles immigration consultant, was accused of
failing to file a 1994 tax return, underreporting her income in
1995 and 1996 and helping to file a fraudulent corporate tax return
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hsia, (pronounced shaw) a naturalized U.S. citizen born in
Taiwan, has been free on bond pending her trial on the political
fund-raising indictment that was returned in February. Since then,
she has traveled to China with judicial approval to work with
clients seeking help in immigrating to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The tax charges were filed in a federal court in California, but
will be prosecuted by the Justice Department's campaign-finance
team, which operates from Washington under the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hsai's lawyer, Nancy Luque, said Tuesday that the charges
were false and represented an effort by federal prosecutors to
pressure Ms. Hsia into pleading guilty to the campaign-finance
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indictment is totally bogus,'' said Ms. Luque. ``These
are technical violations with no loss to the government. I thought
we'd seen the last of IRS cases brought for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, a grand jury here charged Ms. Hsia with disguising
$65,000 in illegal campaign contributions from a California
Buddhist temple to the Clinton-Gore re-election campaign and other
politicians between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Hsi Lai Temple, in the Los Angeles suburb of Hacienda
Heights, Calif., was named as an unindicted co-conspirator. Three
temple nuns told a Senate committee last fall that the temple
illegally reimbursed donors after an April 1996 fund-raiser
attended by Vice President Al Gore. Gore has said he did not know
it was a fund-raising event, but a Senate panel said he should have
known.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's charges appear unrelated to Ms. Hsia's political
activities. The charge of failing to file a 1994 federal income-tax
return carries a maximum penalty of a year in prison and a $100,000
fine. Each of the three charges involving false returns carries a
maximum penalty of three years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Ms. Hsia of underreporting her income in
1995 and 1996 and underreporting the gross receipts of her
immigration consulting business, Hsia &AMP; Associates Inc., in
Arcadia, Calif., on its corporate tax return. Ms. Hsia incorporated
the company and owned 20 percent of its stock, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said that Ms. Hsia had a gross income of more
than $8,050 in 1994, but did not file a tax return. In addition,
the indictment said that Ms. Hsia reported total income of $16,314
for 1995 and total income of $10,026 for 1996 although she made
more than that each year. The government did not disclose how much
income it believes she actually earned during the years in
question.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also said Hsia &AMP; Associates reported 1995 gross
receipts of $240,189, although Hsia knew its receipts were
``substantially greater.'' The documents filed Tuesday did not
provide any government estimate of Ms. Hsia's actual income. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
