<HEADER>
A4596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-RETIREMENT-RULES     07-07 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-RETIREMENT-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF ACCUSED GENERAL LEADS ARMY TO ALTER RETIREMENT PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army said Tuesday that it had revised its
procedures for allowing generals to retire, a result of a
controversy over the deputy Army inspector general who was allowed
to retire quietly in February even though he was under
investigation for sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said that under the new
procedures, an Army general would be allowed to retire only after
there was ``full disclosure,'' to the highest reaches of the
service, ``of any problems or allegations that a person may be
facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the changes were ordered last month by Army Secretary
Michael Walker as a result of the circumstances surrounding the
retirement of the deputy inspector general, Maj. Gen. David R.E.
Hale. Pentagon officials said the other armed services would
consider similar changes in their retirement policies for senior
officers.
</P>
<P>
   A Defense Department report given to members of Congress on
Monday said Hale had engaged in a pattern of ``inappropriate
behavior'' or adulterous affairs with the wives of four officers
under his command in a previous assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the Pentagon's inspector general, found that Hale
had also ``sanctioned the misuse of government resources'' to pay
for international travel by one of the women and that he had lied
``in an effort to deceive others concerning his conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale, who has denied the accusations, was allowed to retire in
February even though other senior Army officials were reportedly
aware of some of the charges against him. In an interview earlier
this year with NBC News, the Army's chief of staff, Gen. Dennis
Reimer, acknowledged that he knew about some of the accusations
when he approved the retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Reimer declined to comment on the case
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But at a regular news conference at the Pentagon, Bacon offered
a spirited defense of the chief of staff, reminding reporters
repeatedly that ``Gen. Reimer's actions are not under review
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's under review,'' he said, ``are the Army's procedures
for dealing with retirement requests by general officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Defense Secretary William Cohen ``has complete
confidence in Gen. Reimer.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding Hale's retirement has led to
sentiment on Capitol Hill and among lawyers who specialize in
military justice that the Army has a double standard in which
senior officers accused of wrongdoing are treated with leniency
while the careers of accused enlisted personnel or junior officers
are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Army, alleging 18 counts of sexual misconduct,
vigorously prosecuted its senior enlisted soldier, Sgt. Maj. Gene
McKinney, whose lawyers insisted that they knew of Army generals
who had been allowed to retire quietly rather than face trial on
similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the prosecution, the Army refused to grant
McKinney's request for retirement. He was convicted of only one
charge, of obstruction of justice, and was eventually allowed to
retire with full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon denied that the Army had a double standard, and said this
would become clear once all the details about the case against Hale
were known.
</P>
<P>
   The Army announced last week that it was opening a criminal
investigation of Hale, 53. The accusations against him involve a
period from 1996 to 1997, when he was stationed in Turkey as deputy
commanding general for NATO land forces in southeastern Europe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
