<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-JUSTICE-NYT &LR;      07-07 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-JUSTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE TAKES ITS SWEET TIME IN SON'S DEATH  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reynold Jordan waited three years to see his son
Trevor's killer convicted. During that vigil, he and his family
were frustrated by the knowledge that although two of them had seen
Patrick Stephens kill 19-year-old Trevor outside their Brooklyn
home, the gunman was living in the relative refuge of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan knew this because while he grew impatient with the pace
of the investigation in New York, he did a little digging of his
own. A friend who lived in one of the identical brick houses that
line the streets of his East Flatbush neighborhood gave him reports
on Stephens' whereabouts. He passed that information to
investigators, he said, only to have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the delay was caused by conflicting reports
from witnesses who had offered different accounts of whom they saw
at the scene. Nor did it help that during the course of the
investigation two detectives retired from the force and another
died. Finally, last December, the police arrested Stephens and
charged him with second-degree murder. After a brief trial in June,
he was convicted and sentenced last week to 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a Pentecostal minister who also drives a delivery truck
for The New York Times, feels a mixture of relief and restlessness
over how things took so long to be resolved. He was determined not
to be silenced by grief over the murder of his son, a young man
whose musical talent made him sort of a one-man band at his church
in Brooklyn. And he refused to allow his East Flatbush street,
where his family had been among the first black homeowners, to be
desecrated by violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man needs to protect his home,'' Jordan said. ``I am a
person who does not give up on anything. I know things don't happen
one-two-three. It took Moses 40 years to make it. Things take time.
But I say here, after all this evidence, my wife would not lie
about seeing Patrick shoot my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor was shot a few days after arguing with some girls who
were friendly with Stephens, his father said. Trevor had tried to
break up a fight, Jordan said, and one girl had cut the young man.
They were arrested, he said, and one of them was jailed. She
returned to the neighborhood, where Jordan said she and friends
goaded his son and threatened his life.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor was killed on the morning of June 6, 1995, shot first as
he got out of his car, and then again, in the head, after
staggering down the street. His younger brother, Reynold, ran
outside when he heard the gunfire, and his mother also ran to the
window. Both said they saw the gunman, whom Reynold identified as
Stephens. Another witness, prosecutors said, identified someone
fitting a different description.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecutors made a judgment that these conflicts presented
a substantial barrier in the search for the truth,'' said Patrick
Clark, a spokesman for the Brooklyn district attorney. ``The
barrier was surmounted when we were able to obtain evidence from
the defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after Trevor's death, the brother of one of Stephens'
friends was involved in the commission of a triple murder in a
nearby housing project. Jordan, looking for the slenderest of
threads on which to hang his hopes for justice, vowed he would go
on television to say the triple murder was preventable. By his
reasoning, the brother would have been deterred from committing any
crime had he known that justice was swift and unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan never went public with his complaint. Prosecutors and
investigators assured him they would move on the case, and they
did. When Stephens came to trial, the jury deliberated mere hours
before convicting him. ``It was an easy case,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was thinking about numbers the other day, and not the
kind Trevor used to play on the piano. He would have preferred the
death penalty for the killer, rather than the prison sentence that
was mandated by the law. The Bible, he said, talked about avenging
death with death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should not be in jail eating my tax dollars,'' he said.
``If you find 25 to life in the Bible, I'll accept that. That's why
we have chaos. Twenty-five to life is not God's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Another number offered consolation. The conviction came almost
three years to the day of Trevor's death. Jordan reached for a
well-worn book on numerology and the Bible, paging quickly to the
entry for the number three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to be good,'' he said. ``Three means completion.
Resurrection time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
