<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4602 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SADNESS-SEX-MOVIE-$AD     07-07 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADNESS-SEX-MOVIE-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FITS-AND-STARTS EDUCATION OF A MOVIE-WORLD BEGINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 12)  
(jt) 
 By BARRY YOURGRAU    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In late 1994 a film was made that centered on me and my dark
whimsies about romance and heartbreak: ``The Sadness of Sex,'' from
my book of the same name. Here's my sorry tale of how this odd
independent movie was brought briefly to the screen _ and then to
the shelf, where it now sits, maybe for good. The story is my two
cents toward the updating of ``Candide'' that famously takes place
when a neophyte like me gets involved in the mad, bad world of
glamour-grabbing and economic hardball that is the film business.
</P>
<P>
   And it even stars Peta Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spalding Gray is like Woody Allen; you're like _ Fellini!''
cried Rupert Wainwright, a director of big-money television
commercials, that night in February 1994. He had just seen my
spoken-word act at the Luna Park club in Los Angeles and had been
inspired then and there to scratch notes for a performance movie.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I remember his effusions exactly. As a bicoastal bohemian _
a creature of Paris Review salons and hipster cabarets like Luna
Park and New York's Fez, plus a few minutes on ``MTV Unplugged'' _
here I was finally going to draw my ticket to the commercialization
of a career: my own ``Swimming to Cambodia.'' At 45, I made a
somewhat hoary Candide.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, for Rupert, in his mid-30s, the project was a
mad pure-hearted stroke to save his esthetic soul from Ballpark
Franks spots, Michael Jackson promos and ``Home Alone'' knockoffs.
Sure, he had a Grammy for his Hammer videos. But big, blond Rupert
was also an Oxford English-literature grad.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, I see that the pathos surrounding both our
ambitions wags the tale of ``The Sadness of Sex'' _ as do our
brands of hubris and naivete. Yet credit Rupert for a real miracle,
which is the one of getting our unconventionally unconventional
movie made at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we began so miraculously, before the farce to come last
year in Los Angeles, where the film had a short run, and the shock
in New York this spring, when to top everything I got called a
``smug lecher'' in a review, even though the film ended up not
opening at all.
</P>
<P>
   For two glorious, brutal weeks we shot in Toronto's chill fall
of '94. A Canadian commercials-production firm had put up half a
million dollars _ finally, in what I would come to know well as the
film business' puckish, yes-no, yes-no style. Under Rupert's lash I
took to the stage and hammed to the camera the stories he and I had
shaped into my surreal romantic history.
</P>
<P>
   Then on location for story re-enactments, I did a screen kiss,
heart pounding, with a young blond Australian ex-model. A couple of
years later, she would be widely known as the star of television's
``La Femme Nikita.'' To my shock _ that word again (the script
called for body doubles) _ Peta Wilson and I wound up in a
closed-set naked love scene. I had another shock, on another closed
set. Outdoors, dressed like Sam Spade, I climbed a shaky fire
ladder to fetch a runaway vagina up a tree . I shook, myself, in
fear and authorial jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film makes `Swimming to Cambodia' look like an
infomercial,'' some bumptious soul cackled in post-production.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, indeed. Fully assembled, it was a cross between MTV and
``Aida,'' plus a splash of Hallmark cards. The photography was
sumptuous, with Peta blazing in negligee and angels' wings; an
editor from ``Natural Born Killers'' had kaleidoscoped my 90-minute
solo with live-action sequences, animation, video footage and photo
stills, and Rupert and the big-time music supervisor from
``J.F.K.'' had brought in a marquee-worthy original soundtrack for
a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, ``The Sadness of Sex'' was a grandiose, double
oddity: a quirky little art film cranked to a fare-the-well by
loving Hollywood-savvy hands. It blinded any grainy indie
stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Was I, the author, happy with this extravagant movie version of
me and my whimsies? Today, I might hem about sensibilities. At the
time, happy wasn't the word. I was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   The film festivals weren't. All the majors and many minors _
including the hometown event in Toronto _ turned us down.
</P>
<P>
   Because we didn't look cheap enough, snorted one of our
distribution agents, trying to steady my distress. These agents had
been crucial in attracting financing. They were big in
feature-to-television rights (``Robocop'' the series); at selling
movies like ours, they were new.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the Hamptons festival threw open its arms. Rupert jetted
in from the Great Wall of China, where he was filming a commercial.
We had buzz, a journalist told me (though he hadn't seen the film).
A wisecracking 20-year-old from Brooklyn who showed part of a
rough-cut on video got one of the extra jury awards. The glories of
``The Sadness of Sex'' got no award _ and no distribution offer.
Rupert could have taken the boat.
</P>
<P>
   He and I sat our version of an indie post-mortem at a TriBeCa
restaurant, with Richard Harris, father of Peta's boyfriend. The
Irish film star stroked the tiny dog that was snuggling inside his
shirt, gave Rupert thumbs up and burred on about ``the great Joe
Losey.'' Misty-eyed, Rupert swore to me that whatever it took, he
would find us a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Such grand moments fortified for a while, until the mixed review
in Variety. I barely registered ``original and often provocative,''
``excessive MTV-like style,'' ``commercial prospects skimpy'' and
``tech credits nothing short of stunning'' because I found myself
referred to, prominently, as Peta Wilson. First I had given up
credit, on screen, as an author (no mention of the underlying book,
only ``written by Barry Yourgrau and Rupert Wainwright'') _ and
now, in the industry trade paper, I had vanished as a performer!
Who'd God put in charge of movies, Don Rickles?
</P>
<P>
   But what's a few flying pies, when a whole cruel bakery awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of Slamdance, the counter-festival to Sundance;
nothing of San Jose, where our sumptuous reels showed in wrong
order. Rupert perched away gallantly in distributors' offices with
a line about ``another `Il Postino.''' No one agreed, for months on
end.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't handling it well. I hadn't the nerves. I couldn't
understand: we had people who loved the film whenever we screened
it; why wouldn't somebody take a chance on us?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, Barry,'' blurted David Lancaster, our senior
producer, ``it's still essentially 90 minutes of one guy talking.
Spalding Gray already had a name, from theater!'' I could feel my
Big Break slipping away. Frantic, I became someone who showed up at
dinner parties with a video clip.
</P>
<P>
   Enter, magically it seemed, Tara Releasing, with the original
Dutch thriller ``The Vanishing'' to its release credit. It was, of
course, a so-called ``micro-distributor.'' Its president mainly ran
a canoe-rental business.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sadness of Sex'' opened in its glory at a reputable Los
Angeles art house in the spring of '97, right after April Fools'
Day _ appropriately so, given the wincing Hollywood sendup of
independent-film ambitions to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Comic highlights: Rupert rushing the two of us, plus cell phone,
around Sunset Strip in his new Jag convertible, to Scotchtape our
homemade deluxe mini-posters onto mailboxes and lamps, beneath the
towering billboard of my ``Sadness'' lovemate, now far off being
Nikita to millions; literary bohemian movie star riding public
transport daily to Rupert's grand suite on the Sony lot, to
publicity-monger on the phones, which was all the author-performer
really did anymore.
</P>
<P>
   More comic highlights: director and movie star roaming
supermarket lots and pedestrian malls with Xeroxes of glowing
review (``a striking film'' _ The Los Angeles Times), getting
chased at high speed out of the Directors' Guild parking garage for
plastering windshields; anguished studio-lot conference calls to a
northern California canoe-rental shop, pleading for posters, ads,
promotional help; hangdog bohemian movie star (``ideal for the
camera'' _ The Los Angeles Times) and resolute linen-suited
millionaire director (``expands the boundaries of cinema'' _ New
Times) trudging side by side, night after night, from windshield to
windshield down the winding curbsides, the Hollywood sign looming
in the dark behind them.
</P>
<P>
   It was, altogether, a triumph of leafleting. ``Thought you guys
already had a distributor,'' someone wondered at the Los Angeles
Independent Film Festival, as we worked the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Tara drifted out of business, slowly and over dim months of
nothing, without announcement. ``The Sadness of Sex'' became ours
again. Lucky us. We had a jazzed-up one-man movie with a great Los
Angeles Time review, other fine blurbs _ and a feeble
couple-of-weeks run featuring a box-office gross to make any
distributor laugh and claw his hair.
</P>
<P>
   By now Rupert and I were the only ones with anything really to
gain from an opening in New York, instead of going right to video,
with Peta on the box cover. But Rupert and I would not give up on
the New York prestige, the attention. I was desperately sure we'd
find our audience here, where our incorrect blend of high gloss,
absurd poetic poignancies and young beauties in lingerie would be
treated as, say, a sexy European-style vision (more like Fellini,
perhaps, than ``Il Postino'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Not European,'' a Spanish journalist friend calculated subtly.
``Australian.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupert finagled a small self-release budget from our television
sales to eastern Europe (as part of a package with ``The Last Don''
mini-series). Screen space in Manhattan art houses is a jungle,
ruled by Miramax and other big beasts. But there we were, booked
prettily at a venerable showcase for quality unaffiliated
eccentricities and sexy European features. Peta agreed to fly in
for promotion. I went into hyping overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 13, a Friday (when else?), the polling came back from
our first press screening. ``Shocking'' won't do it. Few major
reviewers had attended, and none had tipped their hands, but the
viewers who did were united in a hiss of contempt. It was as if our
glam literary bauble had committed a cultural outrage of criminal
pretentiousness. The second screening was hardly better. We were
aghast.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert _ Rupert, who I would boast had switched agents to make
this film, who had never given up, who had kissed me at the end of
filming for giving him back his life _ Rupert, my champion, had
just been green-lighted for a big-budget Hollywood movie. It was
his first studio project since Disney's ``Blank Check'' in '94. I
could hear the struggle in his voice. Tortured conference calls
revealed his overriding concern: a bad review of ``The Sadness of
Sex'' must not appear in The New York Times on the Friday we
opened. He would not risk a review then _ at all.
</P>
<P>
   I heard myself sputtering heroic cliches: he was captain of our
ship (I'd just seen ``Titanic''); we were proud of what we'd done,
should ride it to its end and keep courage. Rupert informed me,
tautly, that those metaphors meant nothing to him.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he gave in to having ``The Sadness of Sex'' open _ on
the condition that no reviewer from The Times would see it in time
for Friday review. He canceled the remaining screenings (which he
had been paying for; he had already called off the premiere party),
and schemed a delay in screening cassettes going out to the news
media. Our publicity agent informed me that she was in the business
of publicizing films, not hiding them.
</P>
<P>
   I had always cleaved to Rupert, out of gratitude and because I
felt that he had the most power of us all and that his ambition
ultimately served mine. Now I found myself in a nightmare, joining
with the producer Lancaster, who was as appalled as I was, in not
interfering as screening cassettes went out as normal. I waited in
mutinous double-dread for the premiere.
</P>
<P>
   The theater, which knew none of this, trumped all this amateur
gore by canceling on us, four days to go. I heard the punch line as
I stood with The New Yorker in my hands: ``The Sadness of Sex'' was
featured in its film listings that week with ``The Big Lebowski.''
I was due on radio in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It was something about us not spending enough on ads and missing
a round of them. There was nothing we could do or say. Another film
was already in or slot. Imploring got us nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, ads had to be pulled frantically; desperate calls had to be
made, appealing that reviews be held _ especially to the weeklies,
which were already going to press. ``If a bad review shows up in a
weekly, no one else's going to book us; it's over!'' cried
Lancaster. What a setup line.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, on cue, The Village Voice finished its review in
this way: ``Yourgrau hogs the camera, oozing lecherous
self-satisfaction.'' On line, the headline was positively waggish:
``15 Short Films About a Smug Lecher.'' Some epitaph for a movie
about a man walking around sighing and being sad a lot.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, the owners of the theater, as distinct from
its booker, were chagrined to learn what had happened. They have
offered an open, certain date. But our release budget has been
pretty much exhausted. I'm informed that Anthology Film Archives
seems interested. And a video deal may be forthcoming. I told an
indie-filmmaker friend from Los Angeles the whole story, and she
laughed and said she would probably have done as Rupert did.
</P>
<P>
   I rang him up just now, to note that I was writing my candid
take on our movie-to-screen experience, and wondering what his
reflections might be. We hadn't spoken since early March; he had
been busy, I gathered, with ``Toby's Story,' his religious thriller
for MGM.
</P>
<P>
   I must say our talk wasn't pleasant. Rupert insisted vehemently
that his New York actions were solely to give ``The Sadness of
Sex'' a chance in the theater, before the critics tore it to bits,
as seemed their wont. What's more, after all the toil, all the
money he had spent on our film, he felt hurt and outraged at what
he saw as the possibility of my stabbing him in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Which shows that a sense of betrayal in the movies is a feeling
not exclusive to anyone. That grand Hollywood term ``lawsuit''
floated over the telephone wire.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the inevitable place to end a film-world tale. But
let's try for a happier finis. Me, I've actually had another book
optioned _ by a studio. Dennis Hopper tantalized briefly, on
something else. Billy Bob Thornton, too. No new Candide-ian
miracles yet. But at least I get to change topics from
you-know-what.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
