<HEADLINE>
MERCURY, SHOCK HAVE LEAGUE'S AUSSIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Say today's Mercury game at Detroit was at
a tennis venue instead of The Palace of Auburn Hills.
</P>
<P>
   And say there were about 8,000 fewer people in attendance, the
drabber uniforms said ``Adelaide'' and ``Sydney,'' the pay was
minuscule and, well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, the WNBA isn't. But it may feel a bit like Down Under
on the court tonight when six of the league's seven active Aussies
will be playing, with another working the bench as an assistant
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, we've all played our best for and against each
other, and it'll be nice to catch up,'' said Mercury point guard
Michelle Timms, who began her professional career in 1984 with the
Bulleen Boomers of Australia's Women's National Basketball League
and has played professionally for 13 years. ``But as soon as we
cross the lines there, it's going to be white-line fever and it
won't matter. It is definitely indicative of how far Australia
basketball has come.''
</P>
<P>
   Timms was joined this summer on the Mercury (7-3) by her
Australian national team backup, Kristi Harrower, reigning WNBL
Most Valuable Player Michelle Griffiths and national team assistant
coach Carrie Graf, a Mercury assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, they joined forces with the Shock's Sandy
Brondello, Rachael Sporn and Carla Porter to bring Australia a
bronze medal at the World Championships, with an eye peeled for the
2000 Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Phoenix Aussies will try to derail their Detroit
counterparts, who had won six straight until a Monday loss at New
York dropped the Shock to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Timms, Griffiths, Brondello and Porter likely will start in the
WNBA's biggest cultural fest to date. Both teams have seven
international players, tops in the league, but the other eight
non-Americans are from eight different nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing them in a different environment
outside Australia,'' Griffiths said. ``It's an advantage and a
disadvantage. We know them, and they know us.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths and her fellow Opals, as the national players are
called, are not strangers to the idea of pro basketball. The WNBL
was established in Australia in 1981, but despite its 17 years of
existence, it is nowhere near WNBA standards.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's minimum salary ($13,000) is equal to some Australian
teams' payrolls. Most of the WNBL arenas hold about 7,000 people,
but even those look empty. Game crowds start with a few hundred and
normally crawl up to about 1,000 only because they are played as
doubleheaders, with the men's league teams playing in the later
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Final championship game draws an average of 7,000 to
the 15,000-seat Melbourne Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd in Phoenix is so loud to me,'' said Griffiths, who
works for an employment agency despite her elite status at home.
``I had an ear infection my first game and my ears were ringing. I
had goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Australians work as basketball players the way American kids get
jobs at the mall. Most of them start playing professionally when
they are teenagers. Porter was 15 when she started, while nearly
all of the others began later in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would freak out about that here (in the United States),''
said Porter, who joined the WNBA expansion Shock this year with
Brondello and Sporn. ``No one was being paid anything when I
started (eight years ago). It's changed to reasonable money and has
become more professional. Our profiles are lifted because we are on
TV now.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter remembers holding raffles and carwashes to fund her first
pro team. Timms used to attend college, work the 9 p.m. to 7 a.m.
shift at Denny's and train at night while holding down other
off-season jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never professional in regard to the financial part, but
it was always a full-time commitment,'' Timms said.
</P>
<P>
   Timms is the Australian women's basketball icon. She put stars
in the eyes of kids such as Harrower, who has evolved from grade
school admirer to her backup. Harrower left her native island for
the first time ever because Timms put in the word to acquire her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, Timmsy is like a Cheryl Miller,'' Harrower said.
``She put Australia on the map. When we were in New York, somebody
came up and asked, `Are you Michelle Timms?' In New York? That's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball still fights for its place in Australia. Cricket,
tennis and Australian Rules Football are the nation's passions.
Basketball just recently has become the nation's favorite women's
sport, Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty surprising considering how well we do on the
international level,'' said Graf, whose duties as an Australian pro
team coach included landing sponsors and writing press releases.
</P>
<P>
   Timms, Brondello and Sporn were the only Australians that the
WNBA actually recruited. The rest were signed or drafted by teams,
mostly because they were looking to increase their tempo of play.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a language barrier doesn't hurt, although many
American players will tell you they could use a translator when
speaking with the Australians.
</P>
<P>
   With 33 WNBA players from outside the United States, only
Bulgaria comes even close to Australia's seven-player
representation, with three Bulgarians in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to run and play aggressive defense,'' Timms said.
``That's why so many Australians play here compared to others
because the game is so similar to the style here. Our game is more
disciplined, though. If you don't make it through the offense at
home, you're dragged off the court.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
