<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK WANTS TALKS TO RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There has been no contact between the Coyotes and team
captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk in the eight days since General Manager
 &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Smith pulled the team's latest offer on a contract extension off
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk's agent,  &UR; Bob Murray of Boston, said he is still willing
to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   If negotiations are not re-opened before training camp begins in
early September, Tkachuk could be headed for a lengthy holdout
despite the fact he has two years remaining on his current deal
worth $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful he will agree to play out those final two seasons
as is, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, however, might not make any more offers beyond the
three-year extension Tkachuk rejected worth a total of $33 million
_ an average of $6.5 million a year for five years. There are no
guarantees that offer still exists, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't cut the talks off, they did,'' Murray said. ``We're
prepared to negotiate and we have been, but we can't force (Smith)
back to the table. . . . If he wants to, fine. That's his choice.
We've never shut the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, has indicated Murray and Tkachuk won't budge
from their $8 million-per-year asking price, a restructured,
five-year deal worth $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a question of ``if'' they can pay it,''
Murray said. ``I think it's a question of do they ``want'' to pay
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray wouldn't say if he will attempt to re-open talks himself
by calling Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get hung up on who calls who,'' he said.
``We're here. We've been here. We're prepared to negotiate at any
time and hopefully, it'll happen.'' &QL; 
Quint on trading block &QL; 
Defenseman  &UR; Deron Quint, who was expected to be promoted to the
Coyotes' everyday six-man rotation next season, apparently is on
the trading block and could be dealt within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   At least three teams have entered negotiations with Phoenix,
sources said, to land the 22-year-old offensive defenseman, who
scored four goals and 11 points in 32 games last season. It isn't
known whom the Coyotes are seeking in return.
</P>
<P>
   Quint, the franchise's first pick in the 1994 draft, never
really meshed with Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld despite his potential.
Four years ago, during his last year of juniors, he scored 29 goals
and 89 points in 65 games for Seattle in the Western Hockey League.
Since then, he's split his time between the NHL and the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Quint, a restricted free agent who earned $400,000 a year ago,
must clear waivers if he is sent to the minors at any point next
season. &QL; 
Baron ready to move &QL; 
The agent for Coyotes unrestricted free agent defenseman  &UR; Murray
Baron said his client is close to signing with another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen as early as (today),''  &UR; Steve Mountain said
Tuesday, ``but I'm not going to be in any hurry now that I've seen
some of these recent deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who could have re-signed Baron for $1.3 million per
year last season, won't attempt to pay him the $2 million Baron now
likely will get on the open market. He also became expendable when
Phoenix shocked several NHL teams Friday by signing free-agent
defenseman  &UR; Jyrki Limme of Vancouver to a five-year, $17 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Baron, who likely will sign a three-year deal worth at least
$6.6 million, is being courted by several teams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
