<HEADLINE>
INFUSION OF CAPITAL LIFTS OUTLOOK FOR MUSTANGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Minor league hockey has apparently gotten a reprieve
in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Mustangs of the West Coast Hockey League appeared to
be headed toward extinction after only one season because of
financial problems. But a local hotel developer has stepped up to
purchase 50 percent of the team and keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jenkins, president of Phoenix-based Hotel Development
Corp. and partner in Seattle-based West Coast Hotels, which
includes among its holdings the Executive Park on North Central,
has purchased half of the club from owner Mike Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   WCHL President Mike McCall said the transaction has been
approved, and the deal will be completed by the middle of July.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, McCall said Jenkins will be managing
general partner of the club and also will manage Veterans Memorial
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Jenkins has a solid background,'' McCall said. ``He's an
outstanding businessman and a good person. I'm ecstatic. The
capital is there to really operate the team properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be someone there with hands on locally, which has
to happen in this business. It just doesn't work any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think money will be a problem anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge problem last season.
</P>
<P>
   The club amassed about $250,000 in debt, some of it the result
of a league policy that requires the home team to pay for hotel
accommodations for the visiting clubs.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said Jenkins will address the debt and put the franchise
back on firm footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's responsible for a hotel business with 12,000 employees in
the western United States,'' McCall said. ``That ($250,000) is a
substantial debt if you don't have any money. But he's taking care
of that immediately. He has total credibility. He will enhance the
team's integrity immensely. He'll take care of those (financial)
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said he ultimately could become involved in an
arena-hotel project in Mesa as well. He has developed and is in the
process of developing similar projects in other areas of the West,
including one in Boise, Idaho, which houses another WCHL team.
</P>
<P>
   Another group is working on a plan for an arena-hotel complex in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see what that group is going to do, and I'd love to talk
to them about being a tenant there,'' Jenkins said. ``If they don't
(go forward), we would be willing to step in, or do a joint
venture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs, who played their games at Veterans Memorial
Coliseum, were competitive in their first year, going 36-25 before
getting swept by San Diego in the first round of the playoffs. But
the business end of the organization was in such disarray ownership
cleaned out the entire front office staff, including General
Manager Adam Keller, at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   It was the club's first season in the fledgling 10-team league,
which includes a franchise in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affordable hockey can go here (in Phoenix),'' Jenkins said.
``You can take a family to a Mustangs game for what you pay for one
person to go to a Coyotes game. And you can see all the game from
our seats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
