<HEADLINE>
SEMTECH PAINTS POOR QUARTERLY PROFIT PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Chip producer Semtech Corp., in a move likely to
further hammer its already-slack stock price, announced after U.S.
stock markets closed that quarterly profits will fall far short of
Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Semtech blamed weak demand from the personal computer and
automated test equipment markets. It added that those trends have
been aggravated by the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which sells to the communications, computer and
industrial markets, said profits in its second quarter ending Aug.
2 will be 40 percent to 50 percent lower than first-quarter
earnings of $4.7 million, or 30 cents per diluted share. Wall
Street's consensus estimate of five analysts polled by IBES called
for second-quarter profits of 30 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arun Veerappan of Bancamerica Robertson Stephens said
the announcement caught him off guard. ``We knew that the industry
was in a slowdown, but the magnitude of this decline is a
surprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan said the company remains fundamentally sound and
should be able to improve its results in subsequent quarters. He
added that he retains his ``buy'' rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Semtech said second-quarter sales will be down 15 percent from
first-quarter revenues of $23.2 million. It also announced it will
take a $2.5 million pretax restructuring charge to cut production
capacity and write off the value of those assets.
</P>
<P>
   Semtech stock has lost more than half its value since February,
when it hit $29.75, as chip issues have fallen out of favor because
of the Asian crisis. On Monday it lost 3] to $14.375 as analyst
Douglas Lee of NationsBanc Montgomery cut his quarterly estimate to
27 cents from 30 cents, citing weak industry conditions from excess
inventory and slowing in Europe. The issue gained 1/16 to $14.4375
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Tuesday that he will keep his ``buy'' rating. ``The
magnitude of the earnings shortfall is surprising, so they'll have
to take a near-term hit, but they are taking the right steps to
position themselves for long-term growth,'' he added, citing bright
prospects in Semtech's circuit protection products.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Newbury Park in neighboring Ventura
County, did not disclose on Tuesday whether it will cut any jobs.
It also said the computer market might improve slightly in the
third quarter with sustainable growth in the fourth quarter; flat
results in the test equipment market for the rest of the year, with
growth resuming in the first quarter of 1999; and a fundamentally
solid performance in communications.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
