</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-LAB-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY LED BY TOP ADMIRAL BUYS VACCINE LAB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state of Michigan on Tuesday approved the sale of the United
States' only licensed manufacturer of anthrax and rabies vaccine to
a company led by Adm. William Crowe Jr., a former chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff and the U.S. ambassador to Britain until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Michigan Biologic Products Institute, the last
state-owned vaccine laboratory in the United States, gives Crowe's
newly formed company, BioPort Corp., an inside track on at least
$60 million in Pentagon contracts for anthrax vaccine to protect
the nation's 2.4 million members of the armed forces and reservists
against an anthrax attack.
</P>
<P>
   The rickety plant, which has been run by the Michigan Department
of Community Health, has lost millions of dollars annually for
years. So in 1996 Michigan decided to sell it to the highest
bidder. No one was seriously interested, even after the Pentagon
announced it would pay for a $1.8 million renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The situation changed in December 1997 when the Clinton
administration threatened to go to war over Iraq's intransigence in
giving free access to U.N. inspectors. Defense Secretary William
Cohen announced that all U.S. troops and reservists would get
anthrax shots _ a first for the military.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the old plant was a hot property. Michigan reopened the
bidding in January and a dozen companies considered the plant. Five
made firm offers and, in late May, the Pentagon made the deal even
sweeter by announcing plans to invest an additional $15 million to
double the plant's vaccine output. The plant is currently closed
for renovation.
</P>
<P>
   BioPort, whose headquarters are in Lansing, Mich., is made up of
several partners besides Crowe. One is Fuad El-Hibri, a German
citizen of Lebanese descent who has marketed drugs and succeeded in
turning a British government plant for vaccine production into a
successful private venture.
</P>
<P>
   The other partners are Neogen Corp., a Lansing-based company
that develops and markets diagnostic tests, and Michigan Biologic
Products Inc., which is made up of seven managers of the
state-owned plant, including the laboratory's director, Robert
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   State employees were specifically permitted by the Michigan
Legislature to bid on the sale; the legislators hoped that
retaining local management as investors would help keep the
money-losing plant and its 174 jobs in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said that on June 2 the state commission
responsible for selling the plant chose BioPort over four other
bidders. BioPort, it said, offered nearly $25 million in cash,
secured notes, product donations and royalties. On Tuesday, a board
under the chairmanship of Michigan's governor, John Engler,
approved the decision, the final stage of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also disclosed that BioPort's bid included only
$3.5 million in up-front cash payable at the closing, but also
$12.1 million in secured notes, product donations valued at $4.6
million and $5 million in royalties to be paid over five years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Defense contractors often hire retired officers like Crowe. The
practice, as old as Washington's revolving door, gives companies
insights into the often Byzantine workings of the military
bureaucracy. But it also has been faulted for the favoritism that
can arise when officers deal with former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff from 1985
to 1989, when he retired after 47 years in the military, said in a
recent interview that he was aware of the risk of favoritism and
the perception of it, but that he believed a move to strengthen the
nation's defenses against an anthrax attack was more important.
</P>
<P>
   The 73-year-old retired Navy admiral, who resigned as ambassador
to Britain last year, was one of the most senior military figures
to support Clinton in the 1992 presidential campaign. Crowe said he
had not discussed with the president the vaccine issue or his
effort to buy the plant. Crowe also said he had not received any
favorable consideration from senior Defense Department officials
who had met with the final bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The former ambassador said he had put no personal assets into
the plant's purchase and would be compensated only when, and if,
the plant made money. And he acknowledged that his personal
experience in pharmaceuticals was limited to once having served on
the board of Pfizer, one of the world's leading drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that his knowledge of the Defense Department would
prove useful, because BioPort would soon be negotiating with the
department over the purchase price of future batches of vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The profitability of their venture hinges largely on whether
BioPort can cut a favorable deal with the military, the
laboratory's main customer.
</P>
<P>
   State officials called the sale a good deal for Michigan. A 1996
estimate of its value _ done before plans were announced to
vaccinate all troops and to expand and renovate the plant _ put its
value at anywhere from ``nominal'' to $10.5 million, depending on
how much anthrax vaccine was sold at what price.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe said that he was not sure if his team's investment would
make money in his lifetime, and that his main motive was to
preserve a national asset. ``The Michigan lab cannot be allowed to
go under,'' he said, adding that its success is ``imperative for
the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
