<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS WANTS SWINGS AT BOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Diamondbacks outfielder  &UR; David Dellucci remembers
a lanky outfielder who helped Auburn to the College World Series
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That outfielder, Cardinals wide receiver  &UR; Frank Sanders,
remembers Dellucci as a ``crusher, a guy who can hit'' from when
Dellucci played against him in the Southeastern Conference at
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sanders would like to show Dellucci his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to go (to Bank One Ballpark) and take batting
practice,'' said Sanders, who hit .270 his junior year and was
named All-SEC Western Division.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is running out of time if he wants to take batting
practice. The Cardinals open training camp July 23 in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, meanwhile, return to Bank One Ballpark on
Friday for a three-game series against the Cincinnati Reds. &QL; 
Quick healer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive end  &UR; Brad  &UR; Ottis, who suffered a broken bone
in his left foot two months ago, has started running.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials think Ottis might be limited at the beginning of
training camp but should be at full strength for most of camp.
</P>
<P>
   Ottis was scheduled to start at left defensive end during
minicamp before the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie  &UR; Andre Wadsworth, the team's first-round draft choice
from Florida State, replaced Ottis as a starter during minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth and second-round pick  &UR; Corey Chavous, a defensive back
from Vanderbilt, are unsigned. &QL; 
Joining the club &QL; 
Cardinals quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer is the newest member of the NFL
Quarterback Club, an exclusive group of league quarterbacks who
market themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer joined Tuesday along with  &UR; Brad Johnson of Minnesota,
 &UR; Danny Kanell of the New York Giants and rookies  &UR; Peyton Manning of
Indianapolis and  &UR; Ryan Leaf of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   A few non-quarterbacks are in the group, including  &UR; Terrell
 &UR; Davis, the Denver Broncos running back who was the Most Valuable
Player of Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   The group was formed in 1991 and, according to league officials,
``offers corporate America a chance to tap in the popularity and
power of the NFL's biggest stars.'' &QL; 
Versatile performer &QL; 
Navy offensive tackle  &UR; Mike  &UR; Wahle, one of the top players
available in Thursday's supplemental draft, continues to receive a
lot of interest from teams around the league.
</P>
<P>
   Wahle, pronounced ``Wall,'' visited an undisclosed team Monday
after coming to Tempe last month to meet with Cardinals officials.
</P>
<P>
   His agent,  &UR; Neil Cornrich, said ``numerous'' teams have brought
Wahle in for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Wahle, 6 feet 5, 302 pounds, played left tackle at Navy, but
Cornrich said he could play any position on the line.
</P>
<P>
   He recently bench-pressed 225 pounds 35 times. He also has run
the 40-yard dash in 4.9 seconds. &QL; 
Historical perspective &QL; 
Chavous, who has 400 videotapes of NFL games in his personal
library, continues to wow people with his sense of league history.
</P>
<P>
   He stole the show at last week's NFL symposium during a session
about dealing with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous questioned the moderator, former New York Giants
quarterback  &UR; Phil Simms, who will be a CBS-TV analyst this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil, in 1990 when the Giants started 11-0 and (Jeff)
Hostetler took over and (the Giants) won the Super Bowl, how did
you handle the media pressure the next year in training camp?''
Chavous asked.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous also asked Denver Broncos quarterback  &UR; John Elway about
his disastrous debut in 1983 in Pittsburgh. Elway completed only 1
of 8 passes, was sacked four times and was intercepted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
