<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGENTS-KILLED-HNS &LR;      07-07 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-KILLED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MAN KILLS 4, INCLUDING BORDER AGENTS, BEFORE BEING FATALLY
SHOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
ALLAN TURNER 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ A Rio Grande Valley man, reportedly enraged
over a broken love affair, went on a rampage Tuesday with assault
weapons, killing his rival's mother and sister and two U.S. Border
Patrol agents before being fatally wounded by lawmen's bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The victims included the first woman Border Patrol agent killed
in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Also injured in the early morning shootings were the man's
romantic rival, who was in critical condition after six hours of
surgery at a Harlingen hospital, and a Cameron County sheriff's
deputy, who was in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   The first gunfire, which erupted shortly after 5 a.m. at a Rio
Hondo residence, was followed by a shootout between the suspect and
law officers about two hours later south of San Benito, about 15
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings launched a massive land and air search for
additional suspects in the San Benito area. For almost eight hours,
more than a 150 officers from at least a dozen federal, state and
local agencies probed a field of head-high corn in search of
additional gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The search was called off shortly after 2 p.m. when authorities
concluded that there were no other suspects in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities identified the gunman as Ernie Moore, 24, the son of
a Harlingen police detective &UR;  &LR; and the brother of a San Benito
police patrolman.  &UR;  &LR; Surgeons worked for four hours Tuesday
afternoon in an attempt to repair the damage caused by multiple
gunshot wounds, but Moore died about 5 p.m. at Valley Baptist
Medical Center in nearby Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's purported rival, Dan Morin, 22, remained in critical
condition late in the day. The sheriff's deputy, Raul Rodriguez,
32, was in stable condition after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Killed by Moore's hand, police said, were Morin's 53-year-old
mother, Margarita Flores, his sister, Delia Morin, 31, and Border
Patrol agents Susan Lynn Rodriguez, 28, and Ricardo Guillermo
Salinas, 24, both of Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy. It's unexpected as well, but we do live in a
changing world,'' said Rio Hondo Police Chief Carlos Gonzalez.
Gonzalez, who has been chief law officer in the town of 2,500 for
seven years, said Tuesday's killings are the first he's been called
upon to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the Rio Hondo victims who gathered at the hospital
Tuesday said Dan Morin had been dating Moore's former girlfriend,
Julie Cox, for about a month. Authorities said Cox had been hiding
out from Moore at the family's home at the time of the incident.
She was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Morin's brother, Donald Morin, said he woke up about 5 a.m. and
was going into the garage to retrieve a fan when he saw Moore pull
up in his pickup. Moore entered the home through the unlocked
garage door.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw me, he pointed that gun at my head,'' Donald Morin
said. ``He came prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore then demanded to see his ex-girlfriend. When Donald Morin
returned from a rear room with his brother and Cox, Moore demanded
that the woman leave with him.
</P>
<P>
   When Flores unexpectedly emerged from a bathroom, Moore turned
and opened fire. Delia Morin, apparently alerted by the noise, then
walked from the living room and also was fatally shot. Then Moore
turned his weapon on Dan Morin and shot him four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and he was fixing to shoot me and I had to do
something,'' Donald Morin said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Donald Morin and two other men in the house
attacked Moore and disarmed him. After a brief struggle, Moore fled
the house and sped south in a white Chevrolet extended-cab pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio said deputies, alerted to the
crime, chased the vehicle a short distance before losing sight of
it west of the San Benito city limits. About 30 minutes later,
deputies spotted the truck parked at the home of the suspect's
father and called for assistance. The Border Patrol agents and
others responded.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Ranger Ray Cano said officers briefly talked with the
man's father. As they returned to their patrol cars, Moore rose
from a nearby corn field and opened fire with a .223-caliber
semiautomatic rifle, striking the sheriff's deputy and the two
Border Patrol agents. Other deputies returned fire, striking Moore
four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Border Patrol agents) didn't even get a chance to take
our their weapons,'' said Harry Beall, assistant chief agent for
the McAllen Border Patrol sector. ``This guy hopped out right by
the Border Patrol vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the guns _ a Chinese-made version of an AK-47
and the semiautomatic rifle _ were part of a private family gun
collection and were not police department property.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a deputy's report that Moore had been accompanied by
two other individuals, authorities sealed off the area around the
senior Moore's home and began the intensive search.
</P>
<P>
   For hours, Border Patrol airplanes and helicopters circled the
area as officers on horseback and on foot and bloodhounds scoured
the rugged terrain. The area is marked by cotton and corn fields,
and waterways surrounded by dense brush. At one point, authorities
contemplated leveling the corn fields with a tractor, but
ultimately decided against that option.
</P>
<P>
   The search was abandoned by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only suspect we have right now,'' Sheriff Lucio said a
short time later, ``is the one in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, authorities have not discounted the deputy's
assertion that three people occupied the truck. ``We're still
investigating,'' Lucio said.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Morin said his family was unaware that Cox had come to
their home for protection. She had been living there for the past
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just said that today (at the hospital),'' he said. ``If I
had known that, I'd have thrown her out of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Cox told him Tuesday that Moore had threatened her
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had always made threats that he was going to rob banks,
that he was going to do this and that, that he was going to kill
her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol spokesmen said Susan Rodriguez, the daughter of a
retired deputy chief patrol agent with the Border Patrol who had
been an agent for six years, and Salinas, who had been with the
organization since last year, were the third and fourth agents to
die in the line of duty this year.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-one agents have died while on duty since the agency was
founded 74 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of Rodriguez and Salinas, both federal agents, will
lead the FBI to enter the investigation, Roderick Beverly, special
agent in charge of the San Antonio FBI office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Doris Meissner, commissioner of the Border Patrol's
parent Immigration and Naturalization Service, cut short a tour of
Laredo INS facilities to go to the lower Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   She described Rodriguez and Salinas as ``courageous and heroic
officers,'' and decried violence directed at the agency's officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message should be loud and clear,'' she said. ``Those
cutting down law enforcement officers will be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
