<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-NETWORK-NETSERVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY NETWORK ACQUIRES NETSERVE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bay Network Inc. has acquired a small German
networking company called Netserve. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is an attempt by Bay to capitalize on the AT&AMP;T
agreement to acquire Tele-Communications Inc. Using TCI's cable
television network, AT&AMP;T hopes to deliver local telephone service
and high-speed access to the internet.
</P>
<P>
   Netserve makes technology that allows cable systems to carry
telephone calls. By acquiring Netserve, Bay is trying to sell more
equipment to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4616 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-TV-LIFETIME-AZR &LR;      07-07 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-TV-LIFETIME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFETIME NETWORK FEATURES ALL-FEMALE PRODUCTION FOR WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Having an almost all-female team involved in the
production of WNBA telecasts might seem to be a strategic decision
by the Lifetime Television Network, but in reality, it was just
luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the interesting thing,'' said Doug McCormick, president
and CEO of Lifetime. ``We didn't plan it this way. When we put out
the word that we were looking for people for the crew, it attracted
the best women in the business. A lot of them wanted to work on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wound up getting the best people in the business, and they
happened to be women. This is a classic example of not setting out
to do that. That was no gimmickry involved at all, just the luck of
the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   And even the lone male member of the crew, broadcaster Reggie
Miller, fits right in. His sister, Cheryl, is the coach of the
Mercury, whose game Friday against the Rockers will be broadcast on
Lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The on-air team is headed by Michelle Tafoya, who previously
drew good reviews for her work for CBS-TV. Meghan Pattyson, a
former assistant coach at the University of Connecticut, joins
Miller as an analyst. Others on the team include courtside reporter
Summers Sanders; halftime host Maura Driscoll; and Mary Murphy,
former coach of the Monarchs, who offers insights in a ``Murphy's
Law'' segment.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the telecasts is Lisa Seltzer. Others in the
background include line producer Amy Rosenfeld, sideline producer
Denise Cavanaugh, and halftime producer Maureen Hassett.
</P>
<P>
   In the overall scheme, `this is a significant step in televised
sports production,'' McCormick said. ``There are many excellent
women in sports production who've never been given the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did Reggie Miller of the Indiana Pacers wind up in this
group?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, putting aside my feelings of being a New York Knicks
fan, Reggie brings a wonderful presence to the air,'' McCormick
said. ``Secondly, with his connection to Cheryl, he brings good
input into the sport, and he's a very strong proponent of women
athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime also televised WNBA games in the inaugural 1997 season,
and its ratings are up slightly, according to McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone as high as 1.0, but mostly we're in the .6 range,''
he said. ``We're not as high as we are when a movie is on, but the
good news is that we are bringing new women (viewers) to the sport.
We know that because if you take a look at ESPN and NBC, for
example, the majority of viewership is male. Only on Lifetime is
the majority of viewership women.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime will televise 16 WNBA games, including playoffs, this
season. One other Mercury game, July 31 in Los Angeles, is part of
the package.
</P>
<P>
   The network also will air women's college basketball, a women's
triathlon and the LPGA Tournament of Champions for Breast Cancer
Awareness. In addition, Lifetime is an official sponsor of the
Women's World Cup soccer championship, to be contested next year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
