<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDGE-REMOVED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS REMOVAL OF JUDGE WHOSE LENIENCY LED TO OUTRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lorin Duckman, the New York City judge who became
a favorite target of politicians' complaints about a fuzzy-minded,
too-lenient judiciary, lost his final bid to retain his job Tuesday
when the state's highest court ruled that a state commission was
right to remove him from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   For Duckman, the ruling completes an unusual and abrupt journey
from obscure Criminal Court judge in Brooklyn to political pariah
because of his decision to lower the bail of a man jailed on
domestic abuse charges who was then released and who subsequently
killed his former girlfriend, Galina Komar, and himself.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Benito Oliver, had been jailed on charges that he beat
and threatened Ms. Komar and violated court orders to stay away
from her. Although prosecutors strenuously objected to a lower
bail, Duckman ruled otherwise and said all would be well if Ms.
Komar would just return Oliver's dog.
</P>
<P>
   The case brought declarations of outrage from Gov. George
Pataki, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and others and led to an
investigation by the State Commission on Judicial Conduct. The
commission did not find fault with Duckman's handling of the Oliver
case, but did find that in many other cases he had shown a
pro-defense bias, breaking rules to benefit the accused and roundly
abusing prosecutors. Last October, on a 7-4 vote, it ordered him
removed from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was highly unusual, in that few judges in New York
are removed for the way they conduct cases in court, and when they
are, it is almost always for unfairly favoring the prosecution, not
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Court of Appeals, in a 5-2 decision, upheld the
commission's decision. Duckman was moved to the Civil Court after
Ms. Komar was killed, and was put on paid leave after the
commission's decision. Tuesday's ruling removes him from office
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   At his home in Brooklyn, a drawn-looking Duckman said, ``I had
faith in the process, and I feel it failed,'' but he refused to be
drawn into a discussion of the politics of his case.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he had acted improperly in some cases. ``I
am not an ideologue or judicial ogre,'' he added. ``There are
things I said in court that should not have been said, and in
retrospect, had I had an opportunity to say them, I would not.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know what he would do next.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the court found that Duckman refused to hear
prosecutors' arguments when he decided to dismiss cases, dismissed
cases in which the defense had not requested dismissal and did not
give prosecutors notice before dismissing cases, all in violation
of the rules of criminal procedure.
</P>
<P>
   He was often derisive toward prosecutors, telling one, ``You
don't have an objection, you are just mouthing some words that
somebody told you, for no reason, and insulting me,'' and asking
another if he had got his law license ``on the back of an orange
juice carton.'' He told one prosecutor that she was ``too sexy'' to
wear flat shoes, and another that she looked better in short
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki welcomed the ruling. ``By upholding the removal of Judge
Duckman, the Court of Appeals has also upheld my belief that there
is no room on the bench for judges who willfully disregard the law,
abuse their judicial powers and demonstrate a pattern of bias
against the prosecution and police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Commission on Judicial Conduct was created in its
current form in 1979, it has removed 124 judges from the bench,
many of them part-time town and village justices. Of those, 55 have
appealed the decision to the Court of Appeals, where 47 have lost.
Judges have been removed for misconduct out of court, like
falsifying credit applications or drunken driving, for sexual
harassment and for lying to the commission's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The commission administrator, Gerald Stern, said that ``maybe a
dozen'' judges had been removed, like Duckman, for willfully
ignoring the law in their handling of cases, abusing their
discretion or mistreating people in the courtroom. Most of those,
he said, were part-time judges in small towns. No judge in New York
City has been removed for such reasons since 1983, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
