</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROM-BABY-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GUILTY PLEA EXPECTED IN DEATH OF NEWBORN AT PROM  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than risk a murder conviction and life in prison, the New
Jersey teen-ager accused of killing her newborn son at her senior
prom 13 months ago has decided to plead guilty to a lesser charge,
a person familiar with the case said.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of plea negotiations, the teen-ager, Melissa
Drexler, of Forked River, has agreed to plead guilty to a charge of
aggravated manslaughter in exchange for the prosecutor's
recommendation that she serve no more than 15 years in prison, said
the person familiar with the case, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drexler, now 19, is expected to enter the plea Thursday
morning before Judge John Ricciardi of New Jersey Superior Court in
Freehold, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Her court appearance would coincide, by chance, with the
sentencing in Delaware on the same day of Amy Grossberg and Brian
Peterson, the two 19-year-old former sweethearts from Wyckoff,
N.J., who are the principals in another widely publicized case of
suburban teen-agers accused of killing their newborns. Both Ms.
Grossberg and Peterson have pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the
death of their infant son at a motel near Ms. Grossberg's dormitory
at the University of Delaware in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware's sentencing guidelines suggest a 30-month prison term
for first-time offenders who plead guilty to manslaughter. But the
sentencing judge, Henry duPont Ridgely of Delaware Superior Court,
is not bound by the guidelines and is free to impose anything up to
the maximum possible term, 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of proceedings against the three teen-agers, it
seems possible that Ms. Drexler could receive a stiffer jail
sentence than Ms. Grossberg or Peterson, even though New Jersey
prosecutors were more lenient than their Delaware counterparts in
the early handling of the cases. The New Jersey charge is the more
serious, and the minimum possible penalty in the New Jersey case is
10 years, the same as the maximum in the Delaware case.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Ms. Grossberg's and Peterson's arrests, officials
in the Delaware attorney general's office talked openly about the
possibility of seeking the death penalty. In New Jersey, on the
other hand, John Kaye, the Monmouth County prosecutor, ruled out
seeking the death penalty for Ms. Drexler, characterizing her as a
``frightened young kid'' at the time of the birth. She is accused
of either strangling or suffocating her newborn son after
delivering him in a bathroom stall at her prom on June 6, 1997. She
was under ``extreme mental or emotional disturbance,'' Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware prosecutors have not publicly discussed Ms. Grossberg's
mental state. Although they eventually softened their talk about a
death penalty, calling it one of several sentencing options, the
possibility was not formally eliminated until the state dropped a
murder charge against her in early April, three weeks after
Peterson pleaded guilty to manslaughter and agreed to testify
against her. Ms. Grossberg soon agreed to plead guilty to the same
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye has said Ms. Drexler's case was the fourth infanticide he
has prosecuted in 16 years in office. In the others, he eventually
allowed the mothers to plead guilty to lesser charges, including
aggravated manslaughter in two of the cases and manslaughter in the
other.
</P>
<P>
   A murder conviction in New Jersey carries a life sentence with
no chance of parole before 30 years. Aggravated manslaughter is the
state's second most serious homicide charge and carries a penalty
of 10 to 30 years. During the plea bargaining, Ms. Drexler pressed
for a limit to her sentence, and Kaye agreed to propose 15 years,
the person familiar with the case said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey law does not require a minimum sentence for those
convicted of aggravated manslaughter. Generally, a convict becomes
eligible for parole after serving a third of the sentence. If Ms.
Drexler is sentenced to 15 years, parole hearings could start after
she serves five years.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye and his top aides have refused to discuss Ms. Drexler's
case, other than to say that she will appear in court Thursday and
that Kaye will hold a news conference afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Steven Secare, declined through an office assistant
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
