<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINDU-HUGGING-NYT &LR;      07-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDU-HUGGING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINING UP FOR HUGS FROM A GURU OF TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The line of people seated crosslegged on the floor
snaked the length of the Universalist Church on Central Park West
on Tuesday, as young and old, healthy and infirm waited their turn
for a hug from a sari-clad woman with a diamond in her nose.
</P>
<P>
   But it was no ordinary hug of affection that drew admirers from
Manhattan's Upper West Side to California to Colombia to Mata
Amritandandamayi, an Indian guru whose name means ``mother of
immortal bliss.'' Rather, she enveloped her admirers in much the
way a mother comforts her crying child. But her hug is meant to
impart divine inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   As individuals or family groups, her followers laid their heads
in her lap for the hug, accompanied by a back massage and blessings
spoken gently into their ears. Always she ended by throwing rose
petals at the supplicants and giving them Hershey's Kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Commonly known as Amma or Ammachi or simply Ma, the 43-year old
woman rose from an impoverished childhood in southern India to
become a ``living saint'' in her homeland. She has established or
inspired the organization of hospitals, schools, orphanages and
hospitals there and soup kitchens in the United States. Funds for
Amma's projects are raised from donors and from the sale of books,
recordings, jewelry and clothing at her hugging sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay Amma, stay Amma, stay Amma, please stay,'' a young man
wept Tuesday into her lap. But even as she comforted him, she could
not fulfill his wish. Her three-day visit to New York, part of a
nine-city tour of the nation, ends with two sessions Wednesday. By
then she will have hugged thousands.
</P>
<P>
   She never seems to tire. Speaking in Malayalam, the language of
her native state, Kerala, and translated by her chief disciple,
Swami Amritaswarup, she said, ``People's happiness is my rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a poor fisherman in southern India, she was said
to have been born with a bluish hue to her skin and became an
outcast. Her father withdrew her from school in the fourth grade
and she was made to serve as a family slave.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, ``I had direct experience with the suffering of
others and visited neighboring elderly, sick and starving,'' she
said. ``I always wanted to know the cause of misery and thought if
sorrow is a truth then there must be a cause and a way out. I
realized my purpose is to console, to personally wipe away tears
through selfless love, compassion and service.''
</P>
<P>
   Though brought up a Hindu, she does not believe in the supremacy
of any single religion. ``Love is a universal religion and what
society really needs,'' she said. ``Religion is just a means and
once you attain that goal, you don't need the means.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the line and in the pews agreed, saying that they were
seeking a spirituality that is broader than any single set of
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up as a nice Jewish girl, celebrating the
holidays,'' said Holly Liebman, a yoga teacher from Dobbs Ferry,
N.Y., who now uses the first name Brahmani. ``I still celebrate the
holidays, but this has brought me back to honoring all
traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Janani gave up her given name, Beverley Noia, and
her possessions to follow Amma and live in her ashram in the
village of Vallickau. She said: ``All religions are there. We come
around her because this is how God's word comes through in the 20th
and 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Janani, who is 53, accompanies Amma on all her travels.
``Before, I had everything I ever dreamed of,'' Janani said. ``I
was a teacher in a prep school in Denver and at a university and
had tenure. I had a Victorian house in the city, a weekend house in
the mountains and a camper. People say to me, `What a sacrifice you
have made.' I answer, `What a sacrifice it would be not to do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though Amma is not considered a faith healer, some people say
that she can alleviate physical illness. ``She has done miracles
for my child,'' said Sadhana Barriere, who lifted her blind
6-year-old son, Prasad, who has cerebral palsy and epilepsy, into
Amma's lap for a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to have 400 seizures a day,'' Ms. Barriere said.
``After he saw her it went to twice a week and then to once every
seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   When Paula Lajaunie, the director of Tibetan rug shop in SoHo,
left the church, she said: ``My reaction is very mixed. The kernel
of the experience was very deep. I could feel her deep love but I
am a spiritual seeker so there was not anything done here that I
haven't experienced in deep meditation.''
</P>
<P>
   German Castillos, an import-export company executive who
traveled from Bogota to persuade Amma to come to Colombia, had no
such reservations. ``We need someone spiritually powerful to give
us lessons,'' he said. ``We need love and compassion to see if we
can get out of violence, drugs, criminality. That is the only
salvation for us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Anthony McShane and his partner, Pamela LaFrance, who live
in Cooperstown, N.Y., the encounter seemed some sort of epiphany
and they sat weeping in a pew afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even know she existed till a month ago,'' Ms.
LaFrance said. ``Now I am more peaceful than I can express. Being
in her arms was like being a baby who totally loses herself in her
mother's arms.''
</P>
<P>
   McShane, who owns a shop specializing in spiritual books in
Oneonta, N.Y., nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was released,'' he said. ``I feel I don't deserve
what I've gotten. I don't even know what it is, but honey, I know
you can't buy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
