u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-TRIAL-2NDLD-WRI     07-07 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CONVICTED IN COSBY DEATH; FACES LIFE TERM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf to delete reference to Ennis Cosby's mother being
present in court and for other changes throughout. Adds four grafs
at end of story.)  (sw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A jury took less than six hours on Tuesday to find
19-year-old Mikail Markhasev guilty of murdering Ennis Cosby, the
son of the entertainer Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev smiled briefly in the packed courtroom as the verdict
was read, then he stood expressionless as the slain man's sisters
hugged each other and began to sob.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev was found guilty of first-degree murder and attempted
robbery in the death of Cosby, who was fatally shot in an apparent
robbery while changing a flat tire on Jan. 16, 1997. Markhasev
could receive a term of life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Perez of Superior Court in Santa Monica scheduled
the sentencing for Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors lauded the verdict, Henry Hall, one of the two
public defenders who represented Markhasev, said at a news
conference afterward that he believed that the intense publicity
and the fame of Cosby's father had turned attention away from a
sober analysis of the evidence and had brought about an unfair
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the jury had not been directly tainted and that ``the
celebrity of the Cosby family, I don't think, had a direct impact
on the trial.'' But he also insisted, ``The societal presumption
was that there would be a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Ingalls, the deputy district attorney who prosecuted the
case, disputed Hall's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the jury was extremely responsible in what they
did,'' Ms. Ingalls said. ``I think that the evidence convicted Mr.
Markhasev. I think that Mr. Markhasev convicted Mr. Markhasev and
not the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby attended the trial for the first time on Monday, the
day the closing arguments concluded. He was there with his wife,
Camille, and his daughters Erika and Erinn.
</P>
<P>
   While Cosby's daughters were in court on Tuesday, he and his
wife were not, but through a spokesman he issued a statement after
the verdict was read, saying, ``The Cosby family is satisfied with
the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ennis Cosby was 27 and a doctoral student in education at
Columbia University when he was shot in the head while changing a
flat tire alongside a Los Angeles highway in the early morning of
Jan. 16, 1997. The police said it appeared to have been an
unplanned but botched robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the entirely circumstantial nature of the prosecution's
case, which relied on a hair found with the murder weapon, letters
handed over by a man facing unrelated forgery charges and a tip to
The National Enquirer, the jury seemed to have dispatched quickly
with Markhasev's defense that a friend of his had actually shot
Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   In the letters that prosecutors said Markhasev wrote after his
arrest to the forgery suspect and others, he referred to the Cosby
killing as a ``robbery gone bad.'' DNA evidence showed that the
hair, found inside a cap wrapped around the murder weapon, was
almost certainly Markhasev's. And Christopher So, who was paid
$40,000 by The National Enquirer for interviews and stands to get a
$100,000 reward from the newspaper if Markhasev is convicted,
testified that Markhasev had said he shot a black man, and that
``it's all over the news.''
</P>
<P>
   But Markhasev's mother testified that her son had been with her
the night of the murder and his lawyers had argued that the
incriminating letters had been forged.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began with several claims that were ultimately
unsubstantiated. Early in the trial the prosecution had made the
claim that Markhasev was a member of a notorious prison gang, the
Mexican Mafia, and Markhasev's lawyers had said they would prove
that Eli Zakaria, a friend of Markhasev, had committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Neither assertion was proved. Ultimately, the case boiled down
to the accidental and ultimately tragic crossing of the paths of
the two young men, one who had done reasonably well in school after
immigrating here from Ukraine before sliding into a life of crime,
and the other apparently working hard to build a career as an
educator out of the shadow of his wealthy and famous father.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev was arrested in March 1997 after a highly publicized
police search following what appeared from the start to have been a
senseless crime. Cosby had apparently been driving his father's
Mercedes-Benz to visit a friend when the car got a flat tire. He
pulled off the highway at a quiet spot and called the friend to
help him change the tire.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, Stephanie Crane, showed up and was threatened by a
man who came up to the window of her car. She fled and came back
minutes later to find Mr. Cosby dead, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   The police used her description to create a sketch of the
murderer, but they were unable to make an arrest until The National
Enquirer received a tip from So, a friend of Markhasev, who hoped
to get the reward.
</P>
<P>
   So said that two days after the murder Markhasev took him and a
friend to a field where Markhasev said he had thrown the gun. So
said they tried to find the gun but could not. So later led the
police to the field, where they found a .38-caliber handgun,
wrapped in the knit cap. Ballistic tests later showed the weapon
had been used to kill Cosby. Markhasev was arrested and charged
with the crime shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev never took the witness stand. His lawyers argued that
the witnesses against him were motivated by greed and a desire to
receive more favorable treatment from the police in unrelated
charges that each of them faced. They also insisted that Zakaria,
who had been with Markhasev on the night of the murder, was the
actual killer.
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria was called to testify, but he refused, citing his Fifth
Amendment right against forced self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution insisted there was nothing to support this
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that Eli Zakaria had been involved in
this,'' Ms. Ingalls said at the news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
