<SLUG> BC-SQUAW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BOARD TO CONSIDER NAME CHANGE FOR SQUAW PEAK
</HEADLINE>
   By RUBEN NAVARETTE JR.  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ A little-known state board Wednesday will consider
changing the name of one of Phoenix's best-known land marks from
Squaw Peak to Iron Mountain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But even if the Arizona Board of Geographic and Historical Names
adopts the new name, which is the English translation of the Akimel
O'odham word for the site, the names of the Squaw Peak Parkway and
other sites would not change.
</P>
<P>
   The board, intent on not involving itself in what has become, at
times, a heated public debate over the word's offensiveness, is not
going to allow any public comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be discussing whether the word is offensive,'' Norton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But others disagree with that approach and claim that the board
cannot divorce itself from the con troversy that produced the
proposal in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't say that this isn't political,'' said Michele
Curran, a historian hired by the American Indian Movement. ``It's
all politi cal.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal before the board has its origins in a public
campaign by a pair of teenage girls to expunge ``squaw'' from the
Arizona vernac ular.
</P>
<P>
   Delena Waddle and Siepe Flood, both 17, were inspired by a
success ful movement in Minnesota in 1995 to remove ``squaw'' from
place names in that state. After research ing the origin of the
word, Waddle and Flood concluded that it was offensive and sexually
explicit, den oting female genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   In July of 1997, Waddle and Flood petitioned the nine-member
board to change the name of Squaw Peak, which had been known as
Iron Mountain until 1910.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has to take a look at the research, the historical
origins of the word, and weigh public senti ment on the issue and
then decide,'' said board chairman Tim Norton.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said that, despite rumors to the contrary, renaming the
moun tain after late U.S. Senator Barry Goldwater was not possible.
Federal regulations require that an individ ual be dead for at
least five years before something can be named after him.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater died in May and would not eligible for such a state
honor until 2003, Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Deep passion has long sur rounded the name-change issue.
</P>
<P>
   For Waddle, the passing of time has not changed her mind that
``squaw'' is a word that wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know why we want to change it,'' she said. ``I just hope
they see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddle brushed aside claims by some that other Native Americans
do not object to the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten tons of support from Indian people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And some of that support has come from people who initially saw
nothing wrong with the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``That word has been around forever,'' said Leona Kakar, Ak-Chin
tribal chairwoman. ``We didn't care before because we really didn't
know what it meant in another language.''
</P>
<P>
   Kakar said that since she became aware of just how strongly the
word is objected to by tribes in other parts of the country,
especially in the Midwest and Northeast, she has become more
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is an offensive word to other tribes, then we would also
be opposed to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For others, charges that there is dissension in the Native
American community on the issue are reminis cent of a familiar
strategy of undermining Indian unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just divide and conquer,'' said Lisa Foster, a Lakota
whose husband, Vernon, is director of AIM's southwest region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Foster also faults Native American people for breaking
ranks too easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stuck together, we'd have a stronger voice.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Ruben Navarrette Jr. can be reached at
 &UR; 444-4977 or at ruben.navarrette &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
