<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SLAY-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT LEAVES FIVE DEAD, INCLUDING TWO BORDER AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Rewrites 1st 2 grafs, and also the 2 grafs beginning ``At
5:20 Tuesday.'' No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ A young man armed with military assault
rifles killed a mother and daughter, and then fatally shot two
Border Patrol agents pursuing him here Tuesday, law-enforcement
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials say the shootings in the lower Rio Grande valley,
in which the gunman died and a local sheriff's deputy was seriously
wounded, illustrates the growing risks Border Patrol agents face in
a territory transformed into a combat zone as officers pursue drug
smugglers, as well as people moving illegal immigrants across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of the Border Patrol have swollen to fight these
crimes and now its agents are also summoned to aid the local
authorities in other situations.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect, Ernest Moore, 24, was also wounded in the shootout
and died early Tuesday night at Valley Baptist Medical Center in
Harlingen, the police said, adding that he was the son of a police
officer in Harlingen, a larger city northwest of San Benito.
</P>
<P>
   The two agents, one of whom is the first woman slain while on
duty, were the third and fourth to die this year. Eighty-one agents
have died in the Border Patrol's 74-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, the head of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, the agency that oversees the Border Patrol, said at a
local news conference that she had attended a service for another
slain agent only a month ago. ``I had hoped that it would be the
last,'' she said. ``Now, so soon, two more courageous and heroic
officers have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   While the greatest risk to agents usually lies along the border,
they are increasingly being summoned by local police and sheriff's
departments.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:20 Tuesday morning, deputies in the Cameron County
Sheriff's Department investigated a report that shots had been
fired in Rio Hondo, another Harlingen suburb. Sheriff Omar Lucio
said they had found Margarita Flores, 53, and one of her daughters,
Delia Morin, dead, and her son seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said later that Moore had been looking for a
woman staying in Ms. Flores' home. Leaving behind what deputies
said was an AK-47 assault rifle, he fled before dawn in a white
pickup truck, in which he was seen with two other men after the
shootings at the house. The authorities are investigating whether
those men also played a role in the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the Border Patrol, deputies spotted the pickup
about a half-hour later in the driveway of a San Benito house the
police said Moore had shared with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies and agents were searching the home and then the
nearby cornfields, when they heard rifle fire. Ricardo Salinas, 24,
a Border Patrol trainee, and Susan Rodriguez, a 28-year-old agent,
were fatally wounded. Officers later found an AR-15, a civilian
version of the M-16 assault rifle used by the military.
</P>
<P>
   After taking Moore into custody, more than 150 law-enforcement
officials combed the fields and dusty roads for the two men spotted
in the truck. In 100-degree heat, assault teams from several
federal, state and local agencies advanced in helmets and flak
jackets, as a helicopter whirred overhead. Even the police from
Edinburg, a nearby city, rumbled up in an armored vehicle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By early afternoon, the officers began wrapping up their search,
saying they had scoured the area and would pursue other leads.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded deputy, Raul Rodriguez, 32, was in critical
condition at Valley Baptist Medical Center. The wounded brother,
Danny Morin, 22, was reported to be in serious condition at the
same hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said that they had no reason believe
that drugs were involved in the disputes, and that the suspect
appeared to have no criminal record.
</P>
</TEXT>
