<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC BID FOR ARLINGTON REMAINS ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, they were supposed to be out of the Olympic business.
</P>
<P>
   Snickered out of the U.S. Olympic Committee meetings. Made to
look homely. And sent to their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But the garbage guy with the Olympic dream, Grady Hicks, just
won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire, in fact. The unflappable Mr. Hicks charged through
one USOC deadline last week and eagerly awaits another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, even more so,'' Hicks said yesterday, when asked if he was
just as enthused now as he was last fall about an Arlington area
Olympic bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fantastic thing for our area.''
</P>
<P>
   In true Olympic spirit, Hicks sounds determined to go the
distance _ or, like the legendary Phidippides, keel over at the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   What sounded like a frivolous publicity stunt nine months ago
took another conspicuous step last week by meeting the USOC
deadline for formalizing its bid committee and having it recognized
as a nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington-Fort Worth-Dallas group was joined by similar
dreamers from Los Angeles, San Francisco, Seattle, Tampa,
Cincinnati and Baltimore-Washington. They all are competing to be
the U.S. bid city for the 2012 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   To give credit where due, it should be noted that Hicks and his
committeemen have impressively done their homework. They have read
the 80 pounds of binders and etiquette books that the USOC has
issued them.
</P>
<P>
   They can now talk the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas-Fort Worth area has the best base _ corporately _
of all the bid cities to pull off an Olympics,'' said Dallas' Ken
Luce, who is helping serve as the group's spokesman. ``You look at
Penney's, NationsBank, American Airlines, Pier One, Tandy. They are
all based here. And that's our biggest asset, by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine months ago, alas, the Arlington group didn't have any
assets. It had a receipt for Hicks' six-figure bid deposit. It had
a couple of handshakes. It had a roll of the eyes from the USOC
people, who tried hard to take Hicks' bid seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond that, it didn't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of bid-city seminars, workshops and Olympic
protocol cramming sessions seem to have turned Hicks and Luce into
deft Olympi-bidders.
</P>
<P>
   They can talk the talk. But can they walk the walk?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people in this area realize that we're only a
couple of facilities short of being able to host a major sports
festival right now,'' Luce said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, true. Sort of. But one of those ``facilities'' would have
to be a $200 million-plus stadium for track and field and the
opening and closing ceremonies. Somebody would have to pay for that
_ Dallas? Fort Worth? Arlington?
</P>
<P>
   But Luce's greater point is that the Olympic idea isn't all
half-baked. Again, they've done their homework. The notion of
recruiting the area's corporate community to aid in the bid would
give the Arlington group an advantage that most of the other
bidders can't match.
</P>
<P>
   Without Coca-Cola, would Atlanta have gotten the 1996 Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   A good question. But the fact is that with Coke, Atlanta did.
</P>
<P>
   Amusingly, the Arlington bid committee still exists in briefcase
form only. They plan to open a real office in September, but in the
meantime, the workbooks, mail and phone calls are being shuffled
between Hicks' office and periodic committee meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The idea won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Douglas of the Dallas Chamber of Commerce has met with the
committee and has been quietly working to gather support of the
corporate community. The next step _ a major one, as far as the
USOC is concerned _ would be a formal endorsement from the Dallas
mayor's office. It likely will come by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   And then what?
</P>
<P>
   It has been written and suggested that Atlanta schmoozed its way
to the '96 Games. The Atlanta bid people unfurled a provocative red
carpet for visiting International Olympic Committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Wining and dining, Luce shrugged, is right up this area's alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people in this town who would be very good
at that,'' Luce said.
</P>
<P>
   They have done their homework. Hicks wisely spoke yesterday
about the ample consolation prizes that are out there for cities
who don't make the USOC's final cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to stop tomorrow dead in our tracks,'' Hicks said,
``what this has done for our area is fantastic. Every one of the
amateur sports federations across the country know the Dallas-Fort
Worth area now. They know we're an Olympic-bid city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know we're a player now for some of their best events.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, indeed, sounded even more enthusiastic than the naive
soul who unveiled his Olympic dream last autumn.
</P>
<P>
   At USOC headquarters in Colorado, they're not rolling their eyes
anymore. To them, Arlington is like Cincinnati, which is like San
Francisco, which is like all the other eight cities who dream of
holding the 2012 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Stunning as that may sound here, that's a major step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
