<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-ANALYSIS-TEX     07-07 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSENT WITHIN NCAA BECOMES EASY TO SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Construction is under way on the NCAA's new offices in
Indianapolis, which are scheduled to open in August 1999. But
cracks are beginning to show in the collegiate sports
organization's figurative foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the NCAA has been around for a century, there has
been talk like that before, that the association is falling
apart,'' NCAA president Cedric Dempsey said. ``And historically,
the NCAA has adapted and moved on. All of these recent occurrences
shouldn't be construed as everything is falling apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this is the summer of the organization's
discontent.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has settled a lawsuit with basketball coach Jerry
Tarkanian (price: $2.5 million); lost a lawsuit concerning
restricted earnings for basketball assistant coaches (price: $67
million, under appeal); and has reached an agreement with the U.S.
Justice Department regarding admissions of student-athletes with
learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a controversial rule that allows student-athletes
to work and earn up to $2,000 during the school year goes into
effect Aug. 1. And, the NCAA is considering proposals to lower SAT
and American College Test scores for initial eligibility for
freshmen athletes. This after spending a decade enacting
legislation requiring higher test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's new governance structure is less than a year old, but
already is being fitted for a new suit. Designed to streamline the
legislative process, several commissioners and athletic directors
have registered vocal complaints about the new system's
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   And there continues to be rumbling that 60 to 80 elite
football-playing Division I schools will secede from the union and
form their own college sports organization.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it appears the NCAA's lists of negatives far
outweigh the positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these things came to a head at the same time, but
were not related to each other at all,'' Dempsey said. ``I think
there are a lot of positives and I think we have a structure in
place that will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissent within the organization is not hard to find, however.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten Conference commissioner Jim Delany believes that the
NCAA has become too cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have reasonable and defensible rules to give us
structure,'' he said. ``We don't need rules that are as extensive
as they are now. We need rules regarding the number of
scholarships, coaches, games, decipherable recruiting rules, some
minimum academic standards. We don't need micro-management.''
</P>
<P>
   Division I-A schools _ the major football programs _ in the big
conferences want more control and say over the legislation that
directly affects them. That, along with the splitting of the
16-team Western Athletic Conference, has some envisioning a
Darwinian evolution in the upper echelon of college sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been a certain survival of the fittest issues
in intercollegiate athletics,'' Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said.
``The importance of TV revenue as we try to manage our budgets may
continue to create problems for some schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds is more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere, somehow there's going to be a Division IV or
something, a weeding out of Division I-A,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinning out, expansion, controversy are a part of any
meaningful organization,'' said Syracuse Chancellor Kenneth Shaw,
chair of the Division I board of directors. ``By that standard the
NCAA must be a very meaningful organization. ... There will always
be rumors of members bolting.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions have been stirred within the NCAA because of the
restricted-earnings ruling and frustration about the new governance
structure.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA fails in the appeals process in the
restricted-earnings case _ and it plans to take it to the Supreme
Court if necessary _ Division I schools will foot the bill. It
could cost each school between $200,000 to $300,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Delany said the NCAA should learn from what went wrong with the
restricted-earnings case.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, the membership should get the strong message that you
can't solve every problem legislatively,'' Delany said. ``Two, the
NCAA staff leadership, lawyers, need to do a better job of
filtering out and advising on rules that could have consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third, I think we need to re-examine the NCAA function. What
can it do that conferences do not? Conferences can't do our own
enforcement and we can't stage national championships. We need the
NCAA to provide a forum for reasonable recruiting and academic
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The restricted-earnings rule was passed during an NCAA
Convention, a delight for Roberts Rules of Order fans but a
confusing and unwieldy vehicle for rule-making. The new governance
structure has eliminated the convention as a rules-making entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of our people believe it's working quite well,
but they're finding it's hard to keep up with the flow of
legislation,'' Pacific-10 commissioner Tom Hansen said. ``I know
some people are frustrated, but there are more people involved with
things than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten away from 3,000 people sitting in a ballroom
trying to write sentences in legislation. That wasn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the new structure in service less than a year, several
college sports leaders are frustrated with how it functions.
Difficulties in tracking legislation and changes to legislation are
the most common complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restructuring is a work in progress,'' Shaw said. ``For any
viable social institution, that is the case. We will always be
getting suggestions for improvement. All will be taken seriously.
Good suggestions will be dealt with _ and the process guarantees
that all will be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, which has about $3 million budgeted for the upcoming
year for legal fees, plans on retaining a law firm that specializes
in anti-trust legislation. The restricted-earnings ruling was based
on anti-trust rulings and there is thought that the rule allowing
student-athletes to work but capping their income also could be
vulnerable to an anti-trust suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what we've been through recently, we're concerned
about all of our legislation,'' Dempsey said, referring to the
NCAA's strategy for legal aid.
</P>
<P>
   After a string of court victories that extended through three
decades, the NCAA is on a losing streak. The defeats have hurt the
organization's image, which has always been hazy. As Dempsey points
out, the NCAA is merely an organization of 933 schools whose
representatives make up the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the concept of the NCAA has a big-spending, rule-making,
probation-rendering Big Brother lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey recently received a raise of about $150,000. With the
restricted-earnings settlement looming and athletic departments
struggling to make financial ends meet in this era of Title IX
equity, Dempsey's $650,000 salary raises eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the NCAA has hired a public-relations firm to affirm
the organization's image and to put a positive spin on the news the
NCAA considers good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
