<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-KILLING-COX     07-07 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-KILLING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Border Patrol agents ambushed
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell and Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ A suspect in the predawn slaying of a mother
and daughter ambushed officers from a field of tall corn early
Tuesday, fatally shooting two Border Patrol agents, including the
first female officer slain in the agency's 74-year history.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's deputy also was wounded before officers could return
fire, hitting suspect Ernest Moore four times.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 25, of San Benito, died about 10 hours later after
extensive surgery at Valley Baptist Medical Center in Harlingen,
Texas. The Cameron County deputy, Raul Rodriguez, was in stable
condition at Valley Baptist's critical care unit Tuesday night, a
hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to express how saddened we are today,'' said
Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner,
who traveled to Harlingen after the shooting. ``We extend our most
sincere and heartfelt condolences to their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents Susan Lynn Rodriguez and Ricardo Guillermo
Salinas were killed in the surprise attack. Both lived in
Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, the mother of a 1-year-old girl, would have turned 29
Saturday. She had been an agent almost six years and was married to
an immigration officer. Salinas, 24, had graduated from the Border
Patrol academy in January and was preparing to take a probationary
exam this week. ``This is a very dark day in the history of the
Border Patrol family,'' said Joe Garza, chief of the Border
Patrol's McAllen sector.
</P>
<P>
   The events began at 5:30 a.m. when two women were killed and a
man critically injured about five miles northeast of Harlingen in
the small farming community of Rio Hondo, home to 1,700 people and
two traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Public Safety, Border Patrol and
other agencies, here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   Moore arrived at the home of Fidencio Jaramillo and Margarita
Flores before sunrise in search of his ex-girlfriend, who had been
a guest in the Flores home. Met at the door by members of the
Flores family, Moore opened fire with an AK-47 assaultrifle,
hitting Margarita Flores, 52, and her daughter, Delia Morin Flores,
31.
</P>
<P>
   Moore threw the semiautomatic weapon aside and fled in a white
pickup. A 911 call summoned police, who arrived a short time later
to find the women dead in the front hallway of their home. It was
Rio Hondo's first murder since 1987, said Carlos Gonzalez, Rio
Hondo police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo, married to Margarita Flores for 15 years, was
awakened by the gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got up and went to the hall, I saw my wife and
stepdaughter shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling for his wife's pulse, Jaramillo, 62, learned she was
dead. He then pushed his stepdaughter's 8- and 9-year-old children
out the home's rear window so they would not see their mother's
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Morin, Margarita Flores' 23-year-old son, also was shot
several times, including a bullet to the back that required several
hours of surgery to repair. Morin was in critical condition Tuesday
night at Valley Baptist Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted by Rio Hondo police, a Cameron County sheriff's deputy
spotted Moore's white pickup and began pursuit, reporting there
appeared to be three people in the truck. That report would add a
great deal of confusion over the next several hours.
</P>
<P>
   After a short pursuit, the deputy lost sight of the vehicle and
radioed for help. Three Border Patrol officers joined the search.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 7 a.m., the Border Patrol agents and other
officers arrived at the home owned by Moore's father near San
Benito, about 10 miles south of the Rio Hondo shooting scene. Moore
has lived with his father since 1992, records show.
</P>
<P>
   When officers arrived, they found the white pickup parked
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to the father, the officers began walking to
their cars when Moore popped up in a nearby field of corn and, from
about 30 to 40 yards away, began firing a .223 semiautomatic rifle.
Border Patrol officers Rodriguez and Salinas were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other officers had arrived by that time, and they returned
fire and wounded the man,'' DPS spokesman Mike Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next seven hours, about 200 law enforcement officers
and two helicopters searched the cornfield and surrounding areas
for two other suspects erroneously reported to be in Moore's
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, authorities announced the arrest of a second
suspect in the cornfield. Officials later recanted the mistaken
report without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   When the confusion was finally resolved, the search was called
off shortly after 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol spokeswoman Letty Garza said it is common for
agency officers to help other agencies along the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement agencies work very closely with each other
down here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The last on-duty Border Patrol agent killed in Texas was
Jefferson Barr, 33, who was shot near Eagle Pass, about 60
southeast of Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Four Border Patrol officers have been killed in the line of duty
this year. Most recently, Border Patrol agent Alexander Kirpnick
was killed June 3 _ shot in the head by a suspected drug smuggler
near the Arizona border town of Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last month I went to a memorial service,'' said Meissner,
``I had hoped it would also be the last. Now, so soon, two more
courageous and heroic officers have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell and Dave Harmon are staff writers for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980707.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTOROLA-COX     07-07 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola posts $1.3 billion loss
 &HT;    By Omar Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc. on Tuesday posted a second-quarter
loss after taking a $1.98 billion charge to pay for a large
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., said weak economic
conditions in Asia and the slumping semiconductor market continued
to hurt the company, as revenues fell 7 percent during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Galvin, Motorola's chief executive, said the
negative effect of the Asian crisis would continue for the rest of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   During the second quarter, Motorola had said it would eliminate
15,000 of its 150,000 jobs worldwide to reduce costs. No further
announcements were made on Tuesday, but a spokesman in Austin said
a ``lot of people'' have taken the voluntary severance package the
company is offering. He declined to say how many workers have taken
the package. For the quarter, the company lost $1.3 billion, or
$2.22 per share, compared with a profit of $268 million, or 44
cents per share, in the 1997 second quarter. Revenue for the 1998
quarter was $7 billion, down from $7.5 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Without the charge, Motorola would have posted a $6 million
profit, or 1 cent per share. Stock analysts had expected the
company to post an operating loss of 4 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's shares rose in trading Tuesday, $1.43 3/4 to $55 a
share. Earnings were released after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   AMD Inc., another chip maker with Austin operations, is to
announce its results today after the market closes. Motorola's
stock has hovered near its 52-week low for several weeks, and
analysts have cited everything from bad leadership to a slow
introduction of digital communication products for the company's
woes.
</P>
<P>
   In the announcement Tuesday, Galvin confirmed that Motorola
would soon announce a restructuring that is expected to divide its
communications business into two segments _ one catering to
consumers, and the other focusing on corporate, internal and
network clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few days we will announce a more collaborative and
market-focused Communications Enterprise that links together all of
Motorola's communications businesses so they can easily share
resources and cooperate on key business and technology issues,''
Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, analysts have not been impressed with Motorola's
restructuring efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors want to see concrete evidence'' of a turnaround,
said Rick Berry, an analyst at JP Turner. ``The investor community
is getting a little anxious with Motorola's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's semiconductor business posted an operating loss in
the quarter, compared with a profit a year ago. Sales dropped 11
percent in the quarter to $1.81 billion _ from $2.03 billion for
the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Hurst, a Motorola spokesman in Austin, said the company
would continue to offer its severance package through July, then
continue looking at cuts and consolidation as it has for the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to determine the operations we're going to phase
out. We're going to take a look at every operation and every piece
of every operation. We're not just looking at this as 'let's get
rid of bodies.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Motorola was once Austin's largest private employer with about
11,000 employees here. Currently, the company has between 9,000 and
10,000 workers in the area, Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that have announced layoffs in Texas attributed
to the Asian economic crisis include Compaq, Intel and Applied
Materials, which said it would cut about 1,000 jobs in Austin and
in California over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
