<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR PLACES AN ALLY'S SON IN BUDGET POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appointed Robert Harding as
his budget director Tuesday, choosing to fill a critical position
with a lawyer who has strong political skills but little experience
in fiscal matters, and who is the son of one of Giuliani's closest
political allies.
</P>
<P>
   Harding, who has served the last four years as the
administration's chief lobbyist in Albany, succeeds Joseph Lhota,
who was promoted last week to deputy mayor for operations. Harding
will direct a staff of about 350 and oversee the city's $34 billion
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Harding, 40, has little experience with municipal budgets
compared with his predecessors, and his selection surprised many
fiscal experts, government officials and government watchdog
groups. Several critics dismissed the appointment as a payoff to
Harding's father, Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding, who has
supported and advised Giuliani since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor defended his decision as being based on pure merit,
arguing that Harding possessed other strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a mayor and a deputy mayor for operations who have
great detailed knowledge of the budget after five years in
government,'' Giuliani said. ``And frankly, we needed to add to the
team someone who has a really sophisticated knowledge of
government. I think it's the best balanced team you can put
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made the announcement at a news conference in City
Hall, sharing the lectern with Harding. The room was filled with
many of the mayor's top aides and commissioners. Harding's wife and
their two daughters sat near the stage, but his parents _ Raymond
and Elizabeth Harding _ chose to sit in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of you know my mother, Liz, and next to her is her
husband, Ray,'' the new budget director said as he pointed them
out, clearly anticipating the inevitable questions about his
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared remarks, Harding talked little about the
direction of the city's budget. But two props given to him made
clear that he was expected to pursue the Republican mayor's fiscal
policies: a black binder with a single sheet of paper that read
``Just say no,'' and an oversized pair of scissors that the mayor
handed him.
</P>
<P>
   Harding takes over the city's budget in a period of
unprecedented plenty _ fueled by Wall Street's boom, the city ended
the fiscal year in June with a record surplus of at least $2
billion _ as well as unusual political hostility inside City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the city's budget for the new fiscal year
collapsed this spring after City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, a
candidate for the Democratic nomination for governor, proposed a
referendum that would ask city voters whether public funds should
be used to help pay for a new Yankee Stadium on Manhattan's West
Side. The move enraged the mayor, who accused Vallone of raising
the issue only to further his gubernatorial ambitions. Amid
recriminations, the council adopted its own budget over the mayor's
veto for the first time, and the battle is expected to go on over
the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised Harding's knowledge of government and called
him ``one of the most talented people'' he had worked with. But
critics said that whatever Harding's skills, the overriding reason
for his appointment was his father.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff, a lawyer for the New York Public Interest
Research Group, a good-government organization, said Giuliani, who
has often accused former mayors of cronyism, was being
hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mayor who excoriated his predecessors for political
patronage,'' Russianoff said, ``and now he behaves the same way by
putting his allies in top posts.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding had been director of New York City's Office of State
Legislative Affairs since 1994. After getting his law degree from
Brooklyn Law School in 1982, he worked as counsel to Assemblyman
William Passannante from 1983 to 1990. From 1991 to 1993, he was
general counsel to the New York State Science and Technology
Foundation, and in 1993, he was counsel to the New York State
Facilities Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's appointment came a few weeks after Giuliani promoted
Russell Harding, 34, another son of the Liberal Party leader, to
run the city's Housing Development Corp., a public authority that
issues bonds for housing projects. That selection also raised
eyebrows because Russell Harding, a college dropout, had no
experience in housing finance.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Giuliani has faced criticism because Raymond
Harding built a prosperous business lobbying city agencies
controlled by the mayor, though he held back from the practice last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Harding said his relationship with the mayor was not a
factor in his son's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody thinks Rudy Giuliani would turn over the management
of a $34 billion budget for political considerations, they don't
know Rudy Giuliani,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
