u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DESIGN-DISPUTE-935     07-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DESIGN-DISPUTE-935(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS IN HOME DESIGN CLASH OVER STREET SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just before an annual design and furnishings trade
show in Manhattan last fall, a block of East 58th Street sprouted a
new, chintz-draped street sign proclaiming it ``Designers Way,''
and East 59th Street was transformed into ``Decorators Way.''
</P>
<P>
   The new look was temporary, but now the managers of the
Decoration and Design Building at 979 Third Ave., home to 130
showrooms serving the high-end interior-design business, have asked
the city to make the designation permanent. They say signs flanking
the building would be a fitting recognition of a swatch of the East
Side that is the heart of their industry _ really the only place to
turn if you need $4,000 worth of suede to cover a client's sofa,
say, or some very nice hand-embroidered silk for $2,000 a yard.
</P>
<P>
   And who could object to such a harmless bit of industry
boosterism? Well, the management of a competing design building,
for starters. The owners of the New York Design Center, located at
200 Lexington Ave. at 32nd Street, say the designation would give
an unfair advantage to the Upper East Side building, and have
enlisted the aid of a city councilman who vows to block the new
names.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the rival buildings, known in the industry
as the D and D Building and 200 Lex, has led to some nasty
exchanges, with designers and wholesalers taking sides and
questioning the motives _ or worse, the taste _ of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm looking for things, it would never enter my mind to
go to 200 Lex,'' said Robert Bray, a Manhattan interior designer.
``It's so middle-class to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed, retorted another Manhattan designer, Adam
Dolle. ``Decorating was an Upper East Side kind of phenomenon,'' he
said. ``But that's not true anymore. Everyone goes everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The street-sign debate is one small indication of broader
changes roiling the world of interior design. Once almost entirely
concentrated on the Upper East Side, showrooms sporting a ``to the
trade'' sign _ the signal that, in theory at least, a customer must
be accompanied by a decorator _ have migrated to neighborhoods like
Chelsea, SoHo and the Flatiron District.
</P>
<P>
   And the D and D Building's effort to market itself and other
nearby establishments as the center of the design universe comes as
the industry is trying to broaden its reach. The showrooms are
seeking to draw a new class of customers who can afford fine
furnishings but may have found the idea of hiring a decorator
intimidating or simply unnecessary, given the growing number of
high-end furniture stores that sell directly to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The D and D Building and 200 Lex, for example, both offer
referral services for customers without a decorator in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that a lot of people have good taste, but they
don't know how to put it all together,'' said Michael Love,
president of Interior Options, the referral service at 200 Lex.
``We want to make them feel comfortable about using professional
help.''
</P>
<P>
   In another break with the industry's fustier traditions, a major
fabric house with a showroom at the D and D Building, Brunschwig &AMP;
Fils, began accepting credit cards, mainly from decorators who in
turn bill their clients, a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Paying with plastic is still unheard of at most showrooms, which
have traditionally demanded payment in advance by check, an
arrangement that offers less protection for dissatisfied customers.
``We decided to do it because more and more clients of ours were
asking for it,'' said Hans Denbroeder, showroom manager at
Brunschwig.
</P>
<P>
   James Druckman, president of the New York Design Center,
contended that the changes in the industry rendered the notion of a
designated design corridor obsolete. ``I think the story is that
New York itself is a design center,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Steven Cohen, president of Cohen Brothers Realty
Corp., which owns the D and D Building, professed astonishment at
the reception his proposal had received. ``I never in a million
years suspected that 200 Lex would take umbrage,'' he said. ``We
are the center of the design industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Buatta, a New York decorator whose clients have included
Barbara Walters and Malcolm Forbes, agreed with Cohen that there
really was no room for debate. ``The D and D Building is
perfection,'' he declared. ``I'm not going to mention names, but if
it's not in the D and D Building, you never remember to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckman has found an unlikely ally in Councilman Andrew
Eristoff, a Republican whose district includes the D and D Building
but not 200 Lex. Eristoff said he moved to block the name change _
which requires council approval _ when he concluded that the D and
D Building was trying to gain an unfair advantage over its
long-standing competitor. ``This is an attempt to trump a rival in
a highly commercial dispute,'' said Eristoff, who added that he had
received complaints about the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The more D and D officials have pressed for the signs, the more
they have antagonized Eristoff. He said he was outraged when Cohen
asked state Sen. Roy Goodman, another East Side Republican, to
intervene. Now Eristoff said he would oppose even another temporary
renaming for this fall's design show, which D and D has sought from
the city Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a number of prominent designers agree with Cohen that the
neighborhood surrounding the D and D Building is the focal point of
their industry, and they credit the booming economy and the current
management for the building's success after several lean years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since Cohen Bros. Realty bought 979 Third for
$67 million from Travelers Group, which had acquired it in a
foreclosure, occupancy has risen from 70 percent to 100 percent,
with a waiting list of about 50 companies, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many designers looked down on 200 Lex, saying it
catered mainly to the lower end of the market. Built in 1926 as the
New York Furniture Exchange, the building was converted in 1981
from a marketplace for retail stores into showrooms for decorators
and designers. It includes a number of office furniture showrooms,
some of them refugees from the ill-fated International Design
Center in Long Island City, Queens, which emptied out after the
stock-market crash of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But 200 Lex, which has 87 showrooms, is taking steps to burnish
its image. Druckman, whose family has been involved with the
building since it opened, has attracted new, prestigious tenants
like Wood &AMP; Hogan, which sells English period furniture and
reproductions. Other longtime high-end tenants include Odegard,
which carries hand-woven Tibetan rugs and Venetian lamps with
hand-painted silk shades inspired by turbans, shields and pagodas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more user-friendly than any other design building in
town, because we were built just to display furniture,'' Druckman
said _ a pointed reminder that the D and D Building was built in
1964 as an apartment house, although it was never inhabited. From
the outset, it has been used as a design house, and tenants and
decorators constantly complain that the elevators are inadequate
for heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Since plans for redoing the living room are often the first
thing to be jettisoned when the economy sours, the D and D's
fortunes have usually depended on the stock market. Robert Lee
Tinker, a former leasing director at 979 Third who now holds the
same position at 200 Lexington, said about a dozen companies were
behind in their rent when Cohen Bros. bought the building and took
over its management from the Merchandise Mart of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those tenants are gone now, and a number of
well-established companies, like Stark, Donghia and Brunschwig &AMP;
Fils, have enlarged their showrooms. Although they also carry
furniture, they specialize in products like carpets and fabrics
that are less vulnerable to swings in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be able to accommodate the expansion of the brand
names and improve the credit-worthiness of the tenants,'' Cohen
said. ``The mom-and-pop showrooms gave way to larger vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has added Astra Cafe, an upscale restaurant managed by
Charlie Palmer, the owner of Aureole, and begun sprucing up the
corridors and the lobby (a perilous undertaking, given that his
tenants tend to have very definite ideas when it comes to
interiors). Not to be outdone, Druckman plans to convert the cafe
in his building into a more elegant restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Druckman, who provides bus service between 200 Lex and the D and
D Building to make it easier for decorators to get to his
showrooms, said he had tried in vain to get Cohen to cooperate with
him by, for example, holding a joint trade fair. ``It would create
a broader market week for the city,'' he said, ``but they want to
do their own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he did not see the value of joining forces on a trade
fair, but he did not rule out other ventures with Druckman. &UR;  &LR; ``I've
tried to work with him,'' he said, ``but he's very interested in
his own personal ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
