<SLUG> BC-NY-ASIAN-GANG-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
28 ACCUSED OF RACKETEERING AS MEMBERS OF ASIAN GANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a case that shows how organized crime continues to
prey on Chinatown, 28 people were accused Tuesday of being members
of a violent Asian gang called Tung On, which federal prosecutors
said had carried out kidnappings, robbery, extortion and other
crimes since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the government charged, the defendants kidnapped
illegal immigrants from China shortly after their arrival in the
United States, and held them for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants described as members and associates of a faction
of the Tung On led by Chen Kevin, 31, who was one of those charged
in the 51-page racketeering indictment unsealed in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Chen and 12 of the defendants remained at large Tuesday,
according to a statement issued by the office of Mary Jo White, the
U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York. Fifteen other
defendants are already in custody, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges are the latest in a two-year investigation of the
gang in which other accused members have been charged with
kidnapping a 12-year-old boy from his home in Meriden, Conn., on
Nov. 27, 1996, and the murder of a rival gang member at the Hong
Kong Supermarket on East Broadway in Chinatown that same month.
</P>
<P>
   In the kidnapping, the boy was held for six days and was
released unharmed in Queens after his father paid his abductors
$88,000.
</P>
<P>
   The charges announced Tuesday are the broadest filed by federal
prosecutors in Manhattan against a Chinatown gang since 1996, when
Ms. White's office charged 64 people of being members of a gang
called the Fukienese Flying Dragons.
</P>
<P>
   Those defendants were accused of robbery and other violent
crimes, including smuggling illegal Chinese immigrants into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The charges announced Tuesday do not include smuggling
immigrants, but in some cases, the defendants were accused of
carrying out kidnappings of immigrants shortly after they were
smuggled in to the United States by others.
</P>
<P>
   Some abductions took place at Kennedy International Airport,
court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Ko-lin Chin, a professor at Rutgers University in Newark, N.J.,
who has written two books on Chinese gangs, said Tuesday that the
Tung On is one of four well-established gangs in Chinatown.
Although the new charges may briefly slow the pace of organized
criminal activity, he said, they are unlikely to eradicate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later new members will be recruited,'' Chin said,
``and the younger members will be promoted, simply because the
political economy of Chinatown remains the same.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There are still a lot of businesses to be extorted.
There are still a lot of people being smuggled into the United
States. And when you have a lot of illegal immigrants living in a
community that's small, congested, isolated, it gives the gangs
additional opportunities to victimize the illegal immigrants. They
are more vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges were the result of a joint investigation by the FBI,
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service and the New York
City Police Department, Ms. White's office said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
