<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOMB-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TRIAL IN BOMB PLOT, OFFICER RECOUNTS RAID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Testifying Tuesday in the trial of two men accused of
plotting to bomb a subway station last year, a police officer who
took part in the violent predawn raid that led to their arrests
said he fired at the two defendants after one of them tried to take
his gun and the other lunged toward a bag he believed contained a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stand on the trial's second day in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn, Officer David Martinez, a member of the New York
Police Department's Emergency Services Unit, described to rapt
jurors how he stormed into a bedroom in a apartment in Park Slope,
Brooklyn, just after 4:30 a.m. last July 31 after the police
received a tip of a bomb plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I entered the room and the individual to the right lunged at
me to the right, which is where I hold my gun,'' Martinez said. ``A
struggle ensued, and I fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he fired a total of six shots at the two
defendants, Ghazi Ibrahim Abu Maizar, who is now 24, and Lafi
Khalil, now 23, both of whom face up to life in prison if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have contended that neither defendant moved when
the police rushed into the bedroom. Instead, they say the officers,
nervous after being told that two Arab men were in the bedroom with
a bomb, entered the room firing.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by one of the defense lawyers, Michael
Padden, Martinez said he fired only after one of the defendants
tried to grab his weapon and that he felt no unusual amount of fear
before the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that just as the raid began, his partner
accidentally locked the apartment's front door instead of opening
it with a key given to them by Abdel Rahman Mosabbah, the roommate
who flagged down police officers in the street and reported the
bomb plot.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he did not fear that the brief conversation after
the gaffe alerted the men inside. ``I actually thought it relieved
some of the tension,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Martinez's testimony, prosecutors told the judge that
Mosabbah complained that Abu Maizar made a threatening gesture
toward him. Throughout the court proceedings, Abu Maizar has
grinned during hearings. He also made two crude escape attempts
that have drawn angry criticism from Judge Reena Raggi.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, during a conference between lawyers and
Judge Raggi, the judge told defense lawyers that several court
staffers had told her that Abu Maizar tried to make faces in court
Tuesday at Mosabbah. And an assistant U.S. attorney, Bernadette
Miragliotta, said that Mosabbah complained to prosecutors that Abu
Maizar raised his finger at him. ``In the Middle East, raising your
finger is viewed as a threat.'' Ms. Miragliotta said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Maizar's lawyer, Jan Rostal, said her client has been
animated while in court, but she did not see him make faces or
raise his finger at Mosabbah.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Maizar's behavior inside and outside the courtroom was also
an issue during pretrial hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials confirmed that Abu Maizar has made two crude
escape attempts within the last month. In one, first reported in
Newsday, he jumped onto a courtroom table in the midst of a
pretrial hearing in an apparent attempt to make a run for the
courtroom door.
</P>
<P>
   In the other attempted escape, reported in The New York Post on
Tuesday, Abu Maizar tore a section of ceiling down in a court
building holding cell in an apparent effort to find a crawl space
or air duct. He found no escape route and stopped when a court
officer confronted him.
</P>
<P>
   While Abu Maizar, who refuses to stand when the jury enters the
courtroom, appears to mock the court at times, his co-defendant
seems dejected. Khalil has appeared morose during court
proceedings. He rarely speaks to his lawyer and frequently stares
at the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-98 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
