u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GRAVEYARD-RESTORE-     07-07 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAVEYARD-RESTORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR AFTER VANDALISM, REPAIRS BEGIN IN HISTORIC BLACK CEMETERY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A year after vandals destroyed a historic black
graveyard on Staten Island, church members Tuesday began restoring
26 marble and granite stones that were toppled like dominoes and
smashed to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were from the Rossville AME Zion Church, whose
cemetery was established in the early 1800s by free black oystermen
who moved to Staten Island from the Eastern Shore of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The community, known as Sandy Ground, and the cemetery, which
has long been renowned as the United States' most significant black
burial ground, were both Underground Railroad stops in the 1800s
and have since been symbols of strength for many blacks. Among
those who have made pilgrimages there are poet Maya Angelou, writer
Alex Haley and civil rights activist Julian Bond, now chairman of
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   The vandalism was discovered Aug. 23, 1997, after what the
police said was a night of drinking by local youths, who
neighborhood residents have said often take over the cemetery on
summer nights. Two teen-age boys were charged with criminal
mischief, trespassing and aggravated harassment. While a judge
instructed one of the boys to research the history of Sandy Ground,
the boys' cases are pending in juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very upset when this happened, both as the
congregation and those who had loved ones there,'' said Yvonne
Taylor, the chairwoman of the church's board of trustees. ``And we
are certainly glad that these repairs are happening. It has made us
content.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining descendants still living in Sandy Ground expressed
grief about the vandalism. ``Wouldn't you be upset if you spent
$2,000 on a headstone, only to see in toppled over?'' said
Christopher A. Moody, who is a descendant of the Dutch, Indians and
free blacks from New Jersey, New York and Maryland who lived on
Staten Island. ``The kids go up there on weekends and are drinking
and fill up on dope, and they cause senseless damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody, 83, said his grandparents, parents, sister and brother
are all buried in the cemetery. ``Why can't they just let them rest
in peace?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration was made possible by a $4,000 grant from the
Sacred Sites fund of the New York Landmarks Conservancy, a group
dedicated to the preservation of historic landmarks throughout the
state. The grant pays for all but $1,200 of the repairs to the
stones, which have to be cleaned, pieced back together with steel
rods and, in some cases, planted back into the ground. The church
is raising the $1,200 on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a critical part of Staten Island's history,'' said Peg
Breen, the president of the New York Landmarks Conservancy. ``And
from the preservationist point of view, cemeteries are very
important and are often overlooked in the scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Ground was founded in the 1830s by oystermen from Maryland
fleeing laws that forbade freed slaves from congregating and
required all oyster boats to have a white navigator. At its peak in
the mid-1880s, the settlement had about 150 families. The community
had been slowly shrinking for many decades, but developers began
buying the available land and houses in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now fewer than 10 original Sandy Grove families remain, their
wooden homes like driftwood in a sea of recently built town houses.
Older residents say newcomers have shown little respect for
history.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Moody Lewis, the president of the Sandy Ground Historical
Society, said that some good had come out of the vandalism. She
noted that the cemetery had been long overdue for a cleaning and
that one of young men accused of the destruction had stopped by _
on a court order _ to learn more about the neighborhood's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes negatives can become positives,'' Ms. Lewis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
