<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 IN L.A. TENTATIVELY LINKED TO N.Y. WOMAN'S DISAPPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (expands 18th graf to refer to fugitive warrant; changes Ms.
Silverman to Mrs. throughout)  (also see sidebar, ny-missing-woman) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officially, the disappearance of Irene Silverman, an
82-year-old Upper East Side socialite, was still listed on Tuesday
as a missing-persons case, an incident without motive, witness, or
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an elderly female who has disappeared very
mysteriously,'' said Police Inspector Joseph Reznick.
</P>
<P>
   But as a team of detectives fanned out across the city, seeking
traces of Mrs. Silverman, they also sought clues about two people
already in custody _ an unlikely mother-son team of con artists who
have been convicted of crimes as varied as stealing fur coats and
enslaving Mexican immigrants and who are wanted for questioning in
a Los Angeles murder.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman, whose home decor was inspired in part by the
palace of Versailles, was last seen walking through her town house
in a nightgown on Sunday morning and was reported missing by her
housekeeping staff on Sunday night. On Monday evening, after
finding blood outside Mrs. Silverman's apartment, police released a
sketch of a tenant who was wanted for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City detective who happened to see the sketch on
television immediately alerted Manhattan investigators to a
fortunate coincidence: the man, known to Mrs. Silverman as Manny
Guerin and to investigators as Kenneth Kimes, was already behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes, 23, had been arrested along with his 63-year-old mother,
Sante Kimes, on an unrelated federal warrant on Sunday evening that
accused him of passing a bad $14,000 check in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   That discovery led to more intriguing clues. The Kimeses were
carrying Mrs. Silverman's identification at the time of their
arrest, said an investigator who spoke on condition of anonymity,
and detectives said that their curiosity was further piqued by a
call from Los Angeles police, who want to question the Kimeses in
connection with the murder of a man whose body was found in a
garbage bin in Venice on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Los Angeles Police Department declined to
identify the victim or discuss the case. But another law
enforcement official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
that the victim was a Granada Hills, Calif., man whose home was
sold after his death and the proceeds apparently stolen.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Los Angeles Police Department, Officer
Eduardo Funes, said that police were investigating the death of the
man, David Kazdin, 63, but said that there were no suspects and
declined to discuss details of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Another law enforcement official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that Kazdin's home was sold after his death and the
proceeds were apparently stolen; detectives want to question the
Kimeses to determine whether they have information about the case.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan on East 65th Street on Tuesday, neighbors,
employees, and acquaintances said that they were worried for Mrs.
Silverman's safety, and they related incidents and anecdotes from a
unique and intriguing life.
</P>
<P>
   Professor James Schenton, who befriended Mrs. Silverman 20 years
ago when she took his history course at Columbia University,
described her as a sprightly octogenarian with a storied past and
passionate interest in the arts and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   She was a former dancer with the corps de ballet at Radio City
Music Hall in the early 1930s, who gave up the stage for society
and later married. Her husband Samuel died in 1973, and friends
said that in her later years, Mrs. Silverman had channeled her
enthusiasm toward her multimillion-dollar limestone home, half a
block from Central Park, which she had divided into lavish
apartments and operated as a sort of boarding house for the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a woman who has a fascinating propensity to become
involved in all kinds of things,'' Schenton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after Mrs. Silverman's disappearance, police
immediately grew concerned, because it was unheard of for her to
leave the home unaccompanied by a member of her domestic staff,
Reznick said. A search of the property brought another chilling
discovery, an investigator said _ a trail of blood on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator said that one servant had told detectives that
Mrs. Silverman recently argued with Kimes and had threatened to
evict him from his $6,000-a-month apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He apparently kept watching her, and that rubbed her the wrong
way,'' said an investigator. ``She had very high standards and
occasionally threw people out if they weren't up to snuff. And the
thought of a guest keeping her under surveillance, that was just
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kimes, an Oklahoma native who has used eight aliases, has a
handful of arrests for theft, using forged credentials and fraud,
according to police records. She once sued a San Diego doctor for
malpractice, but according to court documents, she herself was
forced to pay damages because the charges were untrue.
</P>
<P>
   She was found guilty of stealing a $6,500 mink coat from the
Mayflower Hotel in Washington in 1985, court records show. In 1986,
Ms. Kimes was convicted of enticing young women from Mexico across
the border to her home in La Jolla, California, then preventing
them from leaving and forcing them to work in virtual slavery. Ms.
Kimes served a five-year sentence in federal prison, according to
law enforcement records.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Ms. Kimes had apparently begun
operating with her son Kenneth, who had robbery and assault
convictions in Florida, police said. The pair had lived together
briefly in California and have been sought by federal officials
since April, when they allegedly used a bad check to purchase a
Lincoln Town car.
</P>
<P>
   Although some investigators held out hope that Mrs. Silverman
would be found alive, the grim reality of police work forced them
to explore the worst possibilities. Officers searched Central Park
early on Tuesday but found no signs of Mrs. Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   On two separate occasions they were also called to a recycling
center in the Hunt's Point section of the Bronx, where human body
parts were discovered. After conferring with the city medical
examiner, detectives determined that neither the human arm nor the
human leg discovered there could have belonged to Mrs. Silverman,
though it was not clear whose they were.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
