<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALNOURISHED BOY ALSO HAD BROKEN RIBS, DOCTORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 2-year-old malnourished boy who was taken from a
Staten Island foster home over the weekend also had seven fractured
ribs, a hospital doctor who examined him said Tuesday. And
officials familiar with the investigation say doctors have also
found scars and scabs all over his body.
</P>
<P>
   Leonora Wiener, a spokeswoman for the Administration for
Children's Services, declined to comment on the injuries, but said
the agency was investigating whether the boy had been physically
abused by his foster mother or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we're gathering all the medical evidence,'' Ms.
Wiener said.
</P>
<P>
   His foster mother, Deanna Allston, was arrested on Sunday and
charged with neglecting the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Teresa Lemma, a pediatrician at St. Vincent's Medical Center
in Staten Island, said doctors were trying to determine when the
boy broke his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was taken from his biological mother and placed in Ms.
Allston's home when he was 4 months old, in January 1996, officials
say. His mother, who was accused of abusing drugs, lost her rights
to the boy in May. Ms. Allston agreed to adopt the child, a
decision approved by lawyers for the child, city officials and the
foster care agency, Catholic Home Bureau. Ms. Allston had no record
of abusing or neglecting children in her care, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But in May and June, prosecutors say, Ms. Allston failed to seek
medical attention for the boy, who suffered from severe diarrhea
and weight loss. The boy's caseworker, who said the child seemed
healthy in May, failed to visit the child in June, as required by
state law. Another caseworker, who was visiting other children
living in the home on June 15, noticed that the boy was thin, but
did not think anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the boy was rushed to the hospital on Saturday, he
was dehydrated, ``bony, and his skin was sagging,'' Dr. Lemma said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Licitra, Ms. Allston's lawyer, declined to comment
Tuesday. A law enforcement official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said Ms. Allston has said that the boy was lactose
intolerant and suffered from stomach problems. Dr. Lemma said the
hospital had yet to determine whether that was true.
</P>
<P>
   She said lab tests showed that the boy's protein levels were
satisfactory, but he is seriously underweight. He weighed 18 pounds
when he was brought to the hospital, less than 97 percent of
children at his age, Dr. Lemma said. He also exhibits many classic
symptoms of victims of abuse and neglect, said Dr. Lemma, who heads
St. Vincent's Committee on Child Abuse and Neglect.
</P>
<P>
   When the boy arrived at the hospital, he refused to walk or
speak and avoided eye contact. He started walking on his own on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly been neglected,'' Dr. Lemma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
