u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-WOMAN-NYT &LR;      07-07 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-WOMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE OF GRAND ADVENTURE IN A BELOVED TOWN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with NY-MISSING)  
 (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Irene Zambelli Silverman once airily described the
unconventional setup at her Upper East Side town house, where she
rented luxuriously decorated apartments to wealthy strangers, as
``something between posh hotel and grand boardinghouse.''
</P>
<P>
   To the elderly widow, it was a grand adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting tenants _ short term,'' she explained in a 1990
letter to Christopher Gray, a New York architectural historian and
contributor to The New York Times, who wrote about Mrs. Silverman's
home.
</P>
<P>
   When she disappeared from her home at 20 E. 65th St. last
Sunday, Mrs. Silverman was 82 years old and still the energetic
landlady to an ever-changing galaxy of tenants who rented her
furnished suites and office space _ maid service included _ for
thousands of dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a funny environment, kind of catch as catch can,'' said
Alan Alpern, an entrepreneur who rented part of the ground floor
about 12 years ago as an office for himself and for the consulting
business of his then-wife, Marife Hernandez. ``There were always
strange people going and coming and staying over.''
</P>
<P>
   During his three or four years as a tenant, Alpern said, he
twice visited Mrs. Silverman for tea in her duplex apartment in the
building. ``She was a very nice lady,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman had divided the stately mansion into
self-contained apartments, some with kitchens, about 15 years ago.
Once she set it up, friends said, she ran the rental business with
the same meticulous attention to detail that she devoted to the
upkeep of her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always did credit references and would check people up and
down,'' said Harry Papaioannou, 39, a carpenter who said he has
known Mrs. Silverman for more than 10 years. ``She helped
everybody. She was a very nice lady _ maybe too nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they were tenants, Mrs. Silverman's renters also
thought of her as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Sinkel, who rented an apartment with a marble fireplace and
large armoires for 18 months, described the atmosphere as somewhere
between that of a friendly Parisian hotel and a salon, with Mrs.
Silverman sometimes lending her antique silver for a dinner party
and slipping a bottle of champagne into his dining room before an
important date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irene had interesting people _ business people, people in the
arts,'' said Sinkel, who stayed in touch after moving out six years
ago. ``I think she just liked having people she liked around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman also was a font of amusing stories about her
years in New York City, regaling acquaintances about her
experiences living in a walkup apartment with an active brothel on
the floor above.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, she and her husband, who was active in the real estate
business, purchased the East 65th Street house. Years later, she
once said, she became fascinated by its history and found it had
once been the home of the Sherrill family, socially prominent in
the golden age of the East Side, at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   An avid gardener who kept the roof terrace of her limestone
mansion planted with lush foliage and lighted up at night, Mrs.
Silverman spoke with passion about her home, with its garden and
its memories and its first-class address. She once said she knew
its ``every screw and nail'' and kept the interior of the
four-story building buffed and polished.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband hated the idea of this house. He said it's a big
white elephant _ it will just weigh us down,'' she recalled in a
letter to Gray a few years ago. She said she even briefly
considered selling it in 1968 but found she couldn't do it.
``Fortunately,'' Mrs. Silverman wrote, ``I chickened out!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
